Name: Inguinal hernia
Desc: Protrusion of the contents of the abdominal cavity through the inguinal canal.

Name: Azoospermia
Desc: Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen.

Name: Cryptorchidism
Desc: Testis in inguinal canal. That is, absence of one or both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.

Name: Tall stature
Desc: A height above that which is expected according to age and gender norms.

Name: Cleft palate
Desc: Cleft palate is a developmental defect of the palate resulting from a failure of fusion of the palatine processes and manifesting as a separation of the roof of the mouth (soft and hard palate).
Synonyms: Cleft of hard and soft palate

Name: Thick lower lip vermilion
Desc: Increased thickness of the lower lip, leading to a prominent appearance of the lower lip. The height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the midline is more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Synonyms: Increased height of lower lip vermilion
Increased volume of lower lip vermilion
Thick red part of the lower lip
Thick vermilion border of lower lip

Name: Long face
Desc: Facial height (length) is more than 2 standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, an apparent increase in the height (length) of the face (subjective).

Name: Epicanthus
Desc: A fold of skin starting above the medial aspect of the upper eyelid and arching downward to cover, pass in front of and lateral to the medial canthus.

Name: Hypertelorism
Desc: Interpupillary distance more than 2 SD above the mean (alternatively, the appearance of an increased interpupillary distance or widely spaced eyes).

Name: Facial asymmetry
Desc: An abnormal difference between the left and right sides of the face.
Synonyms: Asymmetry of right and left side of face

Name: Chronic otitis media
Desc: Chronic otitis media refers to fluid, swelling, or infection of the middle ear that does not heal and may cause permanent damage to the ear.
Synonyms: Chronic infections of the middle ear

Name: Strabismus
Desc: A misalignment of the eyes so that the visual axes deviate from bifoveal fixation. The classification of strabismus may be based on a number of features including the relative position of the eyes, whether the deviation is latent or manifest, intermittent or constant, concomitant or otherwise and according to the age of onset and the relevance of any associated refractive error.

Name: Blepharophimosis
Desc: A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures.

Name: Upslanted palpebral fissure
Desc: The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, the inclination of the palpebral fissure is greater than typical for age.
Synonyms: Upward slanting of the opening between the eyelids

Name: Nystagmus
Desc: Rhythmic, involuntary oscillations of one or both eyes related to abnormality in fixation, conjugate gaze, or vestibular mechanisms.

Name: Carious teeth
Desc: Caries is a multifactorial bacterial infection affecting the structure of the tooth. This term has been used to describe the presence of more than expected dental caries.

Name: Taurodontia
Desc: Increased volume of dental pulp of permanent molar characterized by a crown body-root ratio equal or larger than 1:1 or an elongated pulp chambers and apical displacement of the bifurcation or trifurcation of the roots.

Name: Abnormal dental enamel morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the dental enamel.

Name: Delayed eruption of teeth
Desc: Delayed tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD beyond the mean eruption age.

Name: Psychosis
Desc: A condition characterized by changes of personality and thought patterns often accompanied by hallucinations and delusional beliefs.

Name: Depression
Desc: Frequent feelings of being down, miserable, and/or hopeless; difficulty recovering from such moods; pessimism about the future; pervasive shame; feeling of inferior self-worth; thoughts of suicide and suicidal behavior.

Name: Autism
Desc: Autism is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by impaired social interaction and communication, and by restricted and repetitive behavior. Autism begins in childhood. It is marked by the presence of markedly abnormal or impaired development in social interaction and communication and a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest. Manifestations of the disorder vary greatly depending on the developmental level and chronological age of the individual (DSM-IV).

Name: Stereotypy
Desc: A stereotypy is a repetitive, simple movement that can be voluntarily suppressed. Stereotypies are typically simple back-and-forth movements such as waving of flapping the hands or arms, and they do not involve complex sequences or movement fragments. Movement is often but not always rhythmic and may involve fingers, wrists, or more proximal portions of the upper extremity. The lower extremity is not typically involved. Stereotypies are more commonly bilateral than unilateral.

Name: Anxiety
Desc: Intense feelings of nervousness, tenseness, or panic, often in reaction to interpersonal stresses; worry about the negative effects of past unpleasant experiences and future negative possibilities; feeling fearful, apprehensive, or threatened by uncertainty; fears of falling apart or losing control.

Name: Gynecomastia
Desc: Abnormal development of large mammary glands in males resulting in breast enlargement.

Name: Hypergonadotropic hypogonadism
Desc: Reduced function of the gonads (testes in males or ovaries in females) associated with excess pituitary gonadotropin secretion and resulting in delayed sexual development and growth delay.

Name: Intellectual disability
Desc: Subnormal intellectual functioning which originates during the developmental period. Intellectual disability, previously referred to as mental retardation, has been defined as an IQ score below 70.

Name: Seizure
Desc: A seizure is an intermittent abnormality of nervous system physiology characterised by a transient occurrence of signs and/or symptoms due to abnormal excessive or synchronous neuronal activity in the brain.

Name: Ataxia
Desc: Cerebellar ataxia refers to ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum. This causes a variety of elementary neurological deficits including asynergy (lack of coordination between muscles, limbs and joints), dysmetria (lack of ability to judge distances that can lead to under- or overshoot in grasping movements), and dysdiadochokinesia (inability to perform rapid movements requiring antagonizing muscle groups to be switched on and off repeatedly).

Name: Hypotonia
Desc: Hypotonia is an abnormally low muscle tone (the amount of tension or resistance to movement in a muscle). Even when relaxed, muscles have a continuous and passive partial contraction which provides some resistance to passive stretching. Hypotonia thus manifests as diminished resistance to passive stretching. Hypotonia is not the same as muscle weakness, although the two conditions can co-exist.

Name: Dysarthria
Desc: Dysarthric speech is a general description referring to a neurological speech disorder characterized by poor articulation. Depending on the involved neurological structures, dysarthria may be further classified as spastic, flaccid, ataxic, hyperkinetic and hypokinetic, or mixed.

Name: Global developmental delay
Desc: A delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child, including motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and emotional skills. This term should only be used to describe children younger than five years of age.

Name: Tremor
Desc: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement about a joint axis.

Name: Hip dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the hip.

Name: Obesity
Desc: Accumulation of substantial excess body fat.

Name: Pes planus
Desc: A foot where the longitudinal arch of the foot is in contact with the ground or floor when the individual is standing; or, in a patient lying supine, a foot where the arch is in contact with the surface of a flat board pressed against the sole of the foot by the examiner with a pressure similar to that expected from weight bearing; or, the height of the arch is reduced.

Name: Talipes
Desc: A deformity of foot and ankle that has different subtypes that are talipes equinovarus, talipes equinovalgus, talipes calcaneovarus and talipes calcaneovalgus.

Name: Constipation
Desc: Infrequent or difficult evacuation of feces.

Name: Gastroesophageal reflux
Desc: A condition in which the stomach contents leak backwards from the stomach into the esophagus through the lower esophageal sphincter.

Name: Asthma
Desc: Asthma is characterized by increased responsiveness of the tracheobronchial tree to multiple stimuli, leading to narrowing of the air passages with resultant dyspnea, cough, and wheezing.

Name: Apnea
Desc: Lack of breathing with no movement of the respiratory muscles and no exchange of air in the lungs. This term refers to a disposition to have recurrent episodes of apnea rather than to a single event.

Name: Ventriculomegaly
Desc: An increase in size of the ventricular system of the brain.

Name: Recurrent respiratory infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to respiratory infections as manifested by a history of recurrent respiratory infections.

Name: Abnormality of cardiovascular system morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the heart and great vessels.

Name: Scoliosis
Desc: The presence of an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine.

Name: Lymphoma
Desc: A cancer originating in lymphocytes and presenting as a solid tumor of lymhpoid cells.

Name: Radioulnar synostosis
Desc: An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the radius and the ulna.

Name: Elbow dislocation
Desc: Dislocation of the distal humerus out of the elbow joint, where the radius, ulna, and humerus meet.

Name: Abnormal shoulder morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the shoulder, which is defined as the structures surrounding the shoulder joint where the humerus attaches to the scapula.

Name: Clinodactyly of the 5th finger
Desc: Clinodactyly refers to a bending or curvature of the fifth finger in the radial direction (i.e., towards the 4th finger).
Synonyms: Permanent curving of the pinkie finger

Name: Flat occiput
Desc: Reduced convexity of the occiput (posterior part of skull).

Name: Joint hyperflexibility
Desc: Increased mobility and flexibility in the joint due to the tension in tissues such as ligaments and muscles.
Synonyms: Joints move beyond expected range of motion

Name: Type II diabetes mellitus
Desc: A type of diabetes mellitus initially characterized by insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia and subsequently by glucose interolerance and hyperglycemia.

Name: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder
Desc: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) manifests at age 2-3 years or by first grade at the latest. The main symptoms are distractibility, impulsivity, hyperactivity, and often trouble organizing tasks and projects, difficulty going to sleep, and social problems from being aggressive, loud, or impatient.

Name: Decreased testicular size
Desc: Reduced volume of the testicle (the male gonad).

Name: Feeding difficulties in infancy
Desc: Impaired feeding performance of an infant as manifested by difficulties such as weak and ineffective sucking, brief bursts of sucking, and falling asleep during sucking. There may be difficulties with chewing or maintaining attention.

Name: Open bite
Desc: Visible space between the dental arches in occlusion.
Synonyms: Absence of overlap of upper and lower teeth
Open bite between upper and lower teeth

Name: Broad jaw
Desc: Bigonial distance (lower facial width) more than 2 SD above the mean (objective); or an apparently increased width of the lower jaw (mandible) when viewed from the front (subjective).

Name: Abnormal testis morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the testicle (the male gonad).

Name: Abnormality of eye movement
Desc: An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eye movements or their control.
Synonyms: Abnormal motility of the globe of the eye
Abnormal movement of the globe of the eye

Name: Diabetes mellitus
Desc: A group of abnormalities characterized by hyperglycemia and glucose intolerance.

Name: Delayed puberty
Desc: Passing the age when puberty normally occurs with no physical or hormonal signs of the onset of puberty.

Name: Spasticity
Desc: A motor disorder characterized by a velocity-dependent increase in tonic stretch reflexes with increased muscle tone, exaggerated (hyperexcitable) tendon reflexes.
Synonyms: Involuntary muscle stiffness, contraction, or spasm

Name: Gait disturbance
Desc: The term gait disturbance can refer to any disruption of the ability to walk. In general, this can refer to neurological diseases but also fractures or other sources of pain that is triggered upon walking. However, in the current context gait disturbance refers to difficulty walking on the basis of a neurological or muscular disease.

Name: Failure to thrive
Desc: Failure to thrive (FTT) refers to a child whose physical growth is substantially below the norm.

Name: Lymphopenia
Desc: A reduced number of lymphocytes in the blood.

Name: Premature graying of hair
Desc: Development of gray hair at a younger than normal age.

Name: Neoplasm
Desc: An organ or organ-system abnormality that consists of uncontrolled autonomous cell-proliferation which can occur in any part of the body as a benign or malignant neoplasm (tumour).

Name: Abnormality of the immune system
Desc: An abnormality of the immune system.

Name: Immunodeficiency
Desc: Failure of the immune system to protect the body adequately from infection, due to the absence or insufficiency of some component process or substance.

Name: Elevated hepatic transaminase
Desc: Elevations of the levels of SGOT and SGPT in the serum. SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) are transaminases primarily found in the liver and heart and are released into the bloodstream as the result of liver or heart damage. SGOT and SGPT are used clinically mainly as markers of liver damage.

Name: Skeletal muscle atrophy
Desc: The presence of skeletal muscular atrophy (which is also known as amyotrophy).
Synonyms: Neurogenic muscle atrophy, especially in the lower limbs

Name: Abnormality of chromosome stability
Desc: A type of chromosomal aberration characterised by reduced resistance of chromosomes to change or deterioration.

Name: Decreased circulating antibody level
Desc: An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin in blood.

Name: Short stature
Desc: A height below that which is expected according to age and gender norms. Although there is no universally accepted definition of short stature, many refer to "short stature" as height more than 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender (or below the 3rd percentile for age and gender dependent norms).

Name: Cellular immunodeficiency
Desc: An immunodeficiency characterized by defective cell-mediated immunity or humoral immunity.

Name: Multiple cafe-au-lait spots
Desc: The presence of six or more cafe-au-lait spots.
Synonyms: Multiple flat light-brown marks on skin

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the thymus
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the thymus.

Name: Abnormality of movement
Desc: An abnormality of movement with a neurological basis characterized by changes in coordination and speed of voluntary movements.

Name: Cognitive impairment
Desc: Abnormal cognition with deficits in thinking, reasoning, or remembering.

Name: Mucosal telangiectasiae
Desc: Telangiectasia of the mucosa, the mucous membranes which are involved in absorption and secretion that line cavities that are exposed to the external environment and internal organs.

Name: Telangiectasia of the skin
Desc: Presence of small, permanently dilated blood vessels near the surface of the skin, visible as small focal red lesions.

Name: Sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A type of hearing impairment in one or both ears related to an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve.

Name: Visual impairment
Desc: Visual impairment (or vision impairment) is vision loss (of a person) to such a degree as to qualify as an additional support need through a significant limitation of visual capability resulting from either disease, trauma, or congenital or degenerative conditions that cannot be corrected by conventional means, such as refractive correction, medication, or surgery.

Name: Photophobia
Desc: Excessive sensitivity to light with the sensation of discomfort or pain in the eyes due to exposure to bright light.
Synonyms: Extreme sensitivity of the eyes to light

Name: Ocular albinism
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of the iris and retina.

Name: Behavioral abnormality
Desc: An abnormality of mental functioning including various affective, behavioural, cognitive and perceptual abnormalities.

Name: Dementia
Desc: A loss of global cognitive ability of sufficient amount to interfere with normal social or occupational function. Dementia represents a loss of previously present cognitive abilities, generally in adults, and can affect memory, thinking, language, judgment, and behavior.

Name: Mental deterioration
Desc: Loss of previously present mental abilities, generally in adults.

Name: Stroke
Desc: Sudden impairment of blood flow to a part of the brain due to occlusion or rupture of an artery to the brain.

Name: Cerebral hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage into the parenchyma of the brain.

Name: Headache
Desc: Cephalgia, or pain sensed in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.

Name: Cerebral calcification
Desc: The presence of calcium deposition within brain structures.
Synonyms: Abnormal deposits of calcium in the brain

Name: Cerebral amyloid angiopathy
Desc: Amyloid deposition in the walls of leptomeningeal and cortical arteries, arterioles, and less often capillaries and veins of the central nervous system.

Name: Death in early adulthood
Desc: Death between the age of 16 and 40 years.

Name: Amyloidosis
Desc: The presence of amyloid deposition in one or more tissues. Amyloidosis may be defined as the extracellular deposition of amyloid in one or more sites of the body.

Name: Nephropathy
Desc: A nonspecific term referring to disease or damage of the kidneys.

Name: Osteoporosis
Desc: Osteoporosis is a systemic skeletal disease characterized by low bone density and microarchitectural deterioration of bone tissue with a consequent increase in bone fragility. According to the WHO criteria, osteoporosis is defined as a BMD that lies 2.5 standard deviations or more below the average value for young healthy adults (a T-score below -2.5 SD).

Name: Splenomegaly
Desc: Abnormal increased size of the spleen.

Name: Weight loss
Desc: Reduction of total body weight.

Name: Anemia
Desc: A reduction in erythrocytes volume or hemoglobin concentration.
Synonyms: Low number of red blood cells or haemoglobin
Low number of red blood cells or hemoglobin

Name: Fever
Desc: Body temperature elevated above the normal range.

Name: Hepatomegaly
Desc: Abnormally increased size of the liver.

Name: Lymphadenopathy
Desc: Enlargment (swelling) of a lymph node.

Name: Osteolysis
Desc: Osteolysis refers to the destruction of bone through bone resorption with removal or loss of calcium.

Name: Abnormality of bone marrow cell morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the form or number of cells in the bone marrow.
Synonyms: Anomaly of the bone marrow cells

Name: Increased circulating antibody level
Desc: An increased level of gamma globulin (immunoglobulin) in the blood.

Name: Abnormal B cell count
Desc: A deviation from the normal count of B cells, i.e., the cells that are formed in the bone marrow, migrate to the peripheral lymphatic system, and mature into plasma cells or memory cells.

Name: Bence Jones Proteinuria
Desc: The presence of free monoclonal immunoglobulin light chains in the urine.

Name: Growth delay
Desc: A deficiency or slowing down of growth pre- and postnatally.

Name: Ascites
Desc: Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity.
Synonyms: Accumulation of fluid in the abdomen

Name: Alopecia
Desc: A noncongenital process of hair loss, which may progress to partial or complete baldness.

Name: Malabsorption
Desc: Impaired ability to absorb one or more nutrients from the intestine.

Name: Abdominal pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) and perceived to originate in the abdomen.

Name: Abnormality of the small intestine
Desc: An abnormality of the small intestine.

Name: Hypocalcemia
Desc: An abnormally decreased calcium concentration in the blood.

Name: Dysgammaglobulinemia
Desc: Selective deficiency of one or more, but not all, classes of immunoglobulins.

Name: Premature ovarian insufficiency
Desc: Amenorrhea due to loss of ovarian function before the age of 40. Primary ovarian inssuficiency (POI) is a state of female hypergonadotropic hypogonadism. It can manifest as primary amenorrhea with onset before menarche or secondary amenorrhea.

Name: Abnormal palate morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the palate, i.e., of roof of the mouth.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the roof of the mouth

Name: Skin rash
Desc: A red eruption of the skin.

Name: Rheumatoid arthritis
Desc: Inflammatory changes in the synovial membranes and articular structures with widespread fibrinoid degeneration of the collagen fibers in mesenchymal tissues, as well as atrophy and rarefaction of bony structures.

Name: Thrombocytopenia
Desc: A reduction in the number of circulating thrombocytes.

Name: Autoimmune hemolytic anemia
Desc: An autoimmune form of hemolytic anemia.

Name: Autoimmune thrombocytopenia
Desc: The presence of thrombocytopenia in combination with detection of antiplatelet antibodies.

Name: Dysphagia
Desc: Difficulty in swallowing.

Name: Autoimmunity
Desc: The occurrence of an immune reaction against the organism's own cells or tissues.

Name: Abnormal lymphocyte morphology
Desc: An abnormality of lymphocytes.
Synonyms: Abnormality of cells of the lymphoid lineage

Name: Peripheral neuropathy
Desc: Peripheral neuropathy is a general term for any disorder of the peripheral nervous system. The main clinical features used to classify peripheral neuropathy are distribution, type (mainly demyelinating versus mainly axonal), duration, and course.

Name: Fatigue
Desc: A subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation.

Name: Neoplasm of the tongue
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the tongue.

Name: Urticaria
Desc: Raised, well-circumscribed areas of erythema and edema involving the dermis and epidermis. Urticaria is intensely pruritic, and blanches completely with pressure.

Name: Paresthesia
Desc: Abnormal sensations such as tingling, pricking, or numbness of the skin with no apparent physical cause.

Name: Intestinal edema
Desc: Accumulation of cell free, noninflammatony fluid within the wall of the intestinal tract producing uniform thickening of the mucosal folds.

Name: Edema of the dorsum of hands
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the back of the hands.
Synonyms: Oedema of the dorsum of hands

Name: Dermatographic urticaria
Desc: An exaggerated whealing tendency when the skin is stroked, that is, formation of red, itchy bumps and lines on the skin as a result of pressure on the skin (for instance, stroking the skin with a pen or tongue depressor).

Name: Laryngeal edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid and swelling in the tissues of the larynx.

Name: Abnormal respiratory system morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the respiratory system.

Name: Limbal edema
Desc: Swelling of the margin of the cornea overlapped by the sclera.

Name: Tongue edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid and swelling in the tongue.

Name: Vomiting
Desc: Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth by means of a series of involuntary spasmic contractions.

Name: Diarrhea
Desc: Abnormally increased frequency of loose or watery bowel movements.

Name: Nausea
Desc: A sensation of unease in the stomach together with an urge to vomit.

Name: Dyspnea
Desc: Difficult or labored breathing. Dyspnea is a subjective feeling only the patient can rate, e.g., on a Borg scale.

Name: Abnormal uvula morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the uvula, the conic projection from the posterior edge of the middle of the soft palate.

Name: Hoarse voice
Desc: Hoarseness refers to a change in the pitch or quality of the voice, with the voice sounding weak, very breathy, scratchy, or husky.

Name: Respiratory distress
Desc: Respiratory distress is objectively observable as the physical or emotional consequences from the experience of dyspnea. The physical presentation of respiratory distress is generally referred to as labored breathing, while the sensation of respiratory distress is called shortness of breath or dyspnea.

Name: Hypotension
Desc: Low Blood Pressure, vascular hypotension.

Name: Inspiratory stridor
Desc: Inspiratory stridor is a high pitched sound upon inspiration that is generally related to laryngeal abnormalities.

Name: Abnormal epiglottis morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the epiglottis.

Name: Pharyngeal edema
Desc: Abnormal accumulation of fluid leading to swelling of the pharynx.

Name: Abnormal soft palate morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the soft palate.

Name: Aphasia
Desc: An acquired language impairment of some or all of the abilities to produce or comprehend speech and to read or write.

Name: Brain atrophy
Desc: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of brain tissue that was once present.

Name: Visual agnosia
Desc: Difficulty in recognizing objects by visual input in absence of sensorial visual impairment.

Name: Anomic aphasia
Desc: An inability to name people and objects that are correctly perceived. The individual is able to describe the object in question, but cannot provide the name.

Name: Phenotypic abnormality
Desc: A phenotypic abnormality.

Name: Dyslexia
Desc: A learning disorder characterized primarily by difficulties in learning to read and spell. Dyslectic children also exhibit a tendency to read words from right to left and to confuse letters such as b and d whose orientation is important for their identification. Children with dyslexia appear to be impaired in phonemic skills (the ability to associate visual symbols with the sounds they represent).

Name: Alexia
Desc: An acquired type of sensory aphasia where damage to the brain leads to the loss of the ability to read.

Name: Dysgraphia
Desc: A writing disability in the absence of motor or sensory deficits of the upper extremities, resulting in an impairment in the ability to write regardless of the ability to read and not due to intellectual impairment.

Name: Abulia
Desc: Poverty of behavior and speech output, lack of initiative, loss of emotional responses, psychomotor slowing, and prolonged speech latency.

Name: Thickened nuchal skin fold
Desc: A thickening of the skin thickness in the posterior aspect of the fetal neck. A nuchal fold measurement is obtained in a transverse section of the fetal head at the level of the cavum septum pellucidum and thalami, angled posteriorly to include the cerebellum. The measurement is taken from the outer edge of the occiput bone to the outer skin limit directly in the midline. A measurement 6 mm or more is considered significant between 18 and 24 weeks and a measurement of 5 mm or more is considered significant at 16 to 18 weeks (PMID:16100637).

Name: Restlessness
Desc: A state of unease characterized by diffuse motor activity or motion subject to limited control, nonproductive or disorganized behavior, and subjective distress.

Name: Personality changes
Desc: An abnormal shift in patterns of thinking, acting, or feeling.

Name: Parkinsonism
Desc: Characteristic neurologic anomaly resulting from degeneration of dopamine-generating cells in the substantia nigra, a region of the midbrain, characterized clinically by shaking, rigidity, slowness of movement and difficulty with walking and gait.

Name: Abnormality of extrapyramidal motor function
Desc: A neurological condition related to lesions of the basal ganglia leading to typical abnormalities including akinesia (inability to initiate changes in activity and perform volitional movements rapidly and easily), muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement), chorea (widespread arrhythmic movements of a forcible, rapid, jerky, and restless nature), athetosis (inability to sustain the muscles of the fingers, toes, or other group of muscles in a fixed position), and akathisia (inability to remain motionless).

Name: Frontotemporal dementia
Desc: A dementia associated with degeneration of the frontotemporal lobe and clinically associated with personality and behavioral changes such as disinhibition, apathy, and lack of insight. The hallmark feature of frontotemporal dementia is the presentation with focal syndromes such as progressive language dysfunction, or aphasia, or behavioral changes characteristic of frontal lobe disorders.

Name: Neurofibrillary tangles
Desc: Pathological protein aggregates formed by hyperphosphorylation of a microtubule-associated protein known as tau, causing it to aggregate in an insoluble form.
Synonyms: Neurofibrillary tangles composed of disordered microtubules in neurons

Name: Apraxia
Desc: A defect in the understanding of complex motor commands and in the execution of certain learned movements, i.e., deficits in the cognitive components of learned movements.

Name: Memory impairment
Desc: An impairment of memory as manifested by a reduced ability to remember things such as dates and names, and increased forgetfulness.

Name: Abnormal lower motor neuron morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the lower motor neuron.

Name: Expressive aphasia
Desc: Impairment of expressive language and relative preservation of receptive language abilities. That is, the patient understands language (speech, writing) but cannot express it.

Name: Astrocytosis
Desc: Proliferation of astrocytes in the area of a lesion of the central nervous system.

Name: Abnormal cerebral white matter morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the cerebral white matter.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the cerebral white matter
Cortical white matter abnormalities seen on MRI

Name: Frontotemporal cerebral atrophy
Desc: Atrophy (wasting, decrease in size of cells or tissue) affecting the frontotemporal cerebrum.

Name: Temporal cortical atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the temporal cortex.

Name: EEG with continuous slow activity
Desc: EEG showing diffuse slowing without interruption.

Name: Perseveration
Desc: Perseveration can be defined as the contextually inappropriate and unintentional repetition of a response or behavioral unit. In other words, the observed repetitiveness does not meet the demands of the situation, is not the product of deliberation, and may even unfold despite counterintention. Perseveration can therefore be differentiated from goal-directed and intentional forms of repetition, such as linguistic redundancies designed to enhance communicative or poetic impact.

Name: Abnormal brain FDG positron emission tomography
Desc: An anomaly detectable in [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET) brain scans. Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity.

Name: Spoken word recognition deficit
Desc: Reduced ability of lexical discrimination, which refers to the process of distinguishing a stimulus word from other phonologically similar words. Lexical discrimination can be defined as the process of correctly identifying words in the mental lexicon to match the phonological input of a stimulus.

Name: Brain neoplasm
Desc: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from or metastasizes to the brain.

Name: Senile plaques
Desc: Senile plaques are extracellular deposits of amyloid in the gray matter of the brain.

Name: Sensory neuropathy
Desc: Peripheral neuropathy affecting the sensory nerves.
Synonyms: Damage to nerves that sense feeling

Name: Abnormality of the ribs
Desc: An anomaly of the rib.

Name: Muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of muscles.

Name: Arthralgia
Desc: Joint pain.

Name: Myalgia
Desc: Pain in muscle.

Name: EMG abnormality
Desc: Abnormal results of investigations using electromyography (EMG).

Name: Dysesthesia
Desc: Painful sensations elicited by a nonpainful cutaneous stimulus such as a light touch or gentle stroking over affected areas of the body. Sometimes referred to as hyperpathia or hyperalgesia. Often perceived as an intense burning, dyesthesias may outlast the stimulus by several seconds.

Name: Carcinoid tumor
Desc: A tumor formed from the endocrine (argentaffin) cells of the mucosal lining of a variety of organs including the stomach and intestine. These cells are from neuroectodermal origin.

Name: Nausea and vomiting
Desc: Nausea is a commonly encountered symptom that has been defined as an unpleasant painless subjective feeling that one will imminently vomit. Vomiting has been defined as the forceful expulsion of the contents of the stomach, duodenum, or jejunum through the oral cavity. While nausea and vomiting are often thought to exist on a temporal continuum, this is not always the case. There are situations when severe nausea may be present without emesis and less frequently, when emesis may be present without preceding nausea.

Name: Anorexia
Desc: A lack or loss of appetite for food (as a medical condition).

Name: Intermittent diarrhea
Desc: Repeated episodes of diarrhea separated by periods without diarrhea.

Name: Episodic abdominal pain
Desc: An intermittent form of abdominal pain.

Name: Poor appetite
Desc: A reduced desire to eat.

Name: Zollinger-Ellison syndrome
Desc: A condition in which there is increased production of gastrin by a gastrin-secreting tumor (usually located in the pancreas, duodenum, or abdominal lymph nodes) that stimulates the gastric mucosa to maximal activity, with consequent gastrointestinal mucosal ulceration.

Name: Hematemesis
Desc: The vomiting of blood.

Name: Melena
Desc: The passage of blackish, tarry feces associated with gastrointestinal hemorrhage. Melena occurs if the blood remains in the colon long enough for it to be broken down by colonic bacteria. One degradation product, hematin, imbues the stool with a blackish color. Thus, melena generally occurs with bleeding from the upper gastrointestinal tract (e.g., stomach ulcers or duodenal ulcers), since the blood usually remains in the gut for a longer period of time than with lower gastrointestinal bleeding.

Name: Chronic noninfectious lymphadenopathy
Desc: A chronic form of lymphadenopathy that is not related to infection.

Name: Bloody diarrhea
Desc: Passage of many stools containing blood.

Name: Lack of bowel sounds
Desc: Complete lack of abdominal sounds as assayed by examination of the abdomen with a stethoscope.

Name: Right ventricular failure
Desc: Reduced ability of the right ventricle to perform its function (to receive blood from the right atrium and to eject blood into the pulmonary artery), often leading to pitting peripheral edema, ascites, and hepatomegaly.

Name: Palpitations
Desc: A sensation that the heart is pounding or racing, which is a non-specific sign but may be a manifestation of arrhythmia.

Name: Paraganglioma
Desc: A carotid body tumor (also called paraganglionoma or chemodectoma) is a tumor found in the upper neck at the branching of the carotid artery. They arise from the chemoreceptor organ (paraganglion) located in the adventitia of the carotid artery bifurcation.

Name: Increased serum serotonin
Desc: A increased concentration of serotonin in the blood.

Name: Increased circulating ACTH level
Desc: An abnormal increased in the concentration of corticotropin, also known as adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), in the blood.

Name: Tricuspid regurgitation
Desc: Failure of the tricuspid valve to close sufficiently upon contraction of the right ventricle, causing blood to regurgitate (flow backward) into the right atrium.

Name: Facial telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin of the face.

Name: Bowel urgency
Desc: A sudden, irresistible need to have a bowel movement.

Name: Bronchospasm
Desc: A spasm (sudden, involuntary constriction) of the bronchioles.

Name: Cardiogenic shock
Desc: Severely decreased cardiac output with evidence of inadequate end-organ perfusion (i.e., tissue hypoxia) in the presence of adequate intravascular volume.

Name: Abnormal pulmonary valve cusp morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the pulmonary valve leaflets.

Name: Episodic vomiting
Desc: Paroxysmal, recurrent episodes of vomiting.

Name: Extrahepatic cholestasis
Desc: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in large bile ducts outside the liver.

Name: Intestinal fistula
Desc: An abnormal connection between the gut and another hollow organ, such as the bladder, urethra, vagina, or other regions of the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Hydronephrosis
Desc: Severe distention of the kidney with dilation of the renal pelvis and calices.

Name: Elevated circulating growth hormone concentration
Desc: Acromegaly is a condition resulting from overproduction of growth hormone by the pituitary gland in persons with closed epiphyses, and consists chiefly in the enlargement of the distal parts of the body. The circumference of the skull increases, the nose becomes broad, the tongue becomes enlarged, the facial features become coarsened, the mandible grows excessively, and the teeth become separated. The fingers and toes grow chiefly in thickness.

Name: Edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body.

Name: Pulmonic stenosis
Desc: A narrowing of the right ventricular outflow tract that can occur at the pulmonary valve (valvular stenosis) or just below the pulmonary valve (infundibular stenosis).

Name: Increased hematocrit
Desc: An elevation above the normal ratio of the volume of red blood cells to the total volume of blood.

Name: Tricuspid stenosis
Desc: A narrowing of the orifice of the tricuspid valve of the heart.

Name: Arrhythmia
Desc: Any cardiac rhythm other than the normal sinus rhythm. Such a rhythm may be either of sinus or ectopic origin and either regular or irregular. An arrhythmia may be due to a disturbance in impulse formation or conduction or both.

Name: Insulinoma
Desc: A type of tumor of the pancreatic beta cells that secretes excess insulin and can result in hypoglycemia.

Name: Glucagonoma
Desc: An endocrine tumor of the pancreas that secretes excessive amounts of glucagon.

Name: Chronic fatigue
Desc: Subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation that persists for six months or longer.

Name: Arterial occlusion
Desc: Blockage of blood flow through an artery.

Name: Abnormal bowel sounds
Desc: An anomaly of the amount or nature of abdominal sounds. Abdominal sounds (bowel sounds) are made by the movement of the intestines as they promote passage of abdominal contents by peristalsis.

Name: Abnormal bronchus morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the bronchi, i.e., of the airways leading from the trachea to the lungs.

Name: Abdominal colic
Desc: A type of abdominal pain that comes and goes in waves, most often starting and ending suddenly and being of severe intensity.

Name: Hypoactive bowel sounds
Desc: An decreased amount of bowel sounds.

Name: Ileal adenocarcinoma
Desc: A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the ileum.

Name: Primary hypercortisolism
Desc: Hypercortisolemia associated with a primary defect of the adrenal gland leading to overproduction of cortisol.

Name: Adrenocorticotropic hormone excess
Desc: Overproduction of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), which generally leads secondarily to overproduction of cortisol by the adrenal cortex.

Name: Heart murmur
Desc: An extra or unusual sound heard during a heartbeat caused vibrations resulting from the flow of blood through the heart.

Name: Appendiceal mucinous neoplasm
Desc: An epithelial neoplasm originating in the appendix and often associated with cystic dilation of the appendix due to accumulation of gelatinous material, morphologically referred to as mucoceles.

Name: Ovarian neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the ovary.

Name: Hematochezia
Desc: The passage of fresh (red) blood per anus, usually in or with stools. Most rectal bleeding comes from the colon, rectum, or anus.

Name: Tenesmus
Desc: A repeated, painful urge to defecate without excreting stool.

Name: Neuroendocrine neoplasm
Desc: A tumor that originates from a neuroendocrine cell.

Name: Dysphonia
Desc: An impairment in the ability to produce voice sounds.

Name: Exertional dyspnea
Desc: Perceived difficulty to breathe that occurs with exercise or exertion and improves with rest.
Synonyms: Shortness of breathing upon physical activity

Name: Elevated carcinoembryonic antigen level
Desc: An increased blood concentration of the carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA). CEA is a member of the immunoglobulin supergene family. The human CEA gene family is clustered on chromosome 19q and comprises 29 genes. CEA is highly expressed in embryonic tissue and in some cancers, and is a widely used tumor marker.

Name: Inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion
Desc: A state of increased circulating antidiuretic hormone despite hyponatremia and hypo-osmolality with normal or increased plasma volume.
Synonyms: Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion

Name: Abnormality of the tympanic membrane
Desc: An abnormality of the tympanic membrane

Name: Tinnitus
Desc: Tinnitus is an auditory perception that can be described as the experience of sound, in the ear or in the head, in the absence of external acoustic stimulation.

Name: Abnormality of the auditory canal
Desc: An abnormality of the External acoustic tube (also known as the auditory canal).

Name: Chronic diarrhea
Desc: The presence of chronic diarrhea, which is usually taken to mean diarrhea that has persisted for over 4 weeks.

Name: Facial palsy
Desc: Facial nerve palsy is a dysfunction of cranial nerve VII (the facial nerve) that results in inability to control facial muscles on the affected side with weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure. This can either be present in unilateral or bilateral form.
Synonyms: Facial muscle weakness of muscles innervated by CN VII

Name: Ptosis
Desc: The upper eyelid margin is positioned 3 mm or more lower than usual and covers the superior portion of the iris (objective); or, the upper lid margin obscures at least part of the pupil (subjective).

Name: Intermittent jaundice
Desc: Jaundice that is sometimes present, sometimes not.

Name: Neoplasm of the nervous system
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the nervous system.

Name: Biliary tract obstruction
Desc: Obstruction affecting the biliary tree.

Name: Neoplasm of the liver
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the liver.

Name: Abdominal distention
Desc: Distention of the abdomen.

Name: Hepatic encephalopathy
Desc: Central nervous system dysfunction in association with liver failure and characterized clinically (depending on degree of severity) by lethargy, confusion, nystagmus, decorticate posturing, spasticity, and bilateral Babinski reflexes.

Name: Erythematous plaque
Desc: A plaque (a solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter) with a red or reddish color often associated with inflammation or irritation.

Name: Night sweats
Desc: Occurrence of excessive sweating during sleep.

Name: Elevated alkaline phosphatase of hepatic origin
Desc: An abnormally increased level of liver isoforms of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.

Name: Elevated gamma-glutamyltransferase level
Desc: Increased level of the enzyme gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT). GGT is mainly present in kidney, liver, and pancreatic cells, but small amounts are present in other tissues.

Name: Neoplasm of the eye
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the eye.

Name: Neoplasm of the lung
Desc: Tumor of the lung.

Name: Elevated alpha-fetoprotein
Desc: An increased concentration of alpha-fetoprotein.

Name: Biliary tract neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the biliary system.

Name: Cholecystitis
Desc: The presence of inflammatory changes in the gallbladder.

Name: Epiphora
Desc: Abnormally increased lacrimation, that is, excessive tearing (watering eye).

Name: Pulmonary carcinoid tumor
Desc: A malignant neuroendocrine tumor of the lung. According to histopathologic criteria (WHO 2004), carcinoids are divided into four groups i.e. typical and atypical carcinoids, large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma and small cell lung carcinoma.

Name: Abnormal B-type natriuretic peptide level
Desc: A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP).

Name: Rhinorrhea
Desc: Increased discharge of mucus from the nose.

Name: Hepatic necrosis
Desc: The presence of cell death (necrosis) affecting the liver.

Name: Myopathy
Desc: A disorder of muscle unrelated to impairment of innervation or neuromuscular junction.

Name: Multicystic kidney dysplasia
Desc: Multicystic dysplasia of the kidney is characterized by multiple cysts of varying size in the kidney and the absence of a normal pelvicaliceal system. The condition is associated with ureteral or ureteropelvic atresia, and the affected kidney is nonfunctional.

Name: Thin vermilion border
Desc: Height of the vermilion of the medial part of the lip more than 2 SD below the mean, or apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the lip in the frontal view. The vermilion is the red part of the lips (and confusingly, the vermilion itself is also often referred to as being equivalent the lips).

Name: Microcephaly
Desc: Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender.

Name: Macrocephaly
Desc: Occipitofrontal (head) circumference greater than 97th centile compared to appropriate, age matched, sex-matched normal standards. Alternatively, a apparently increased size of the cranium.

Name: Round face
Desc: The facial appearance is more circular than usual as viewed from the front.

Name: Conductive hearing impairment
Desc: An abnormality of vibrational conductance of sound to the inner ear leading to impairment of sensory perception of sound.

Name: Underdeveloped nasal alae
Desc: Thinned, deficient, or excessively arched ala nasi.

Name: Anteverted nares
Desc: Anteriorly-facing nostrils viewed with the head in the Frankfurt horizontal and the eyes of the observer level with the eyes of the subject. This gives the appearance of an upturned nose (upturned nasal tip).

Name: Short neck
Desc: Diminished length of the neck.

Name: Deeply set eye
Desc: An eye that is more deeply recessed into the plane of the face than is typical.

Name: Sparse and thin eyebrow
Desc: Decreased density/number and/or decreased diameter of eyebrow hairs.

Name: Obsessive-compulsive behavior
Desc: Recurrent obsessions or compulsions that are severe enough to be time consuming (i.e., they take more than 1 hour a day) or cause marked distress or significant impairment (DSM-IV).

Name: Congenital diaphragmatic hernia
Desc: The presence of a hernia of the diaphragm present at birth.

Name: Eczema
Desc: Eczema is a form of dermatitis. The term eczema is broadly applied to a range of persistent skin conditions and can be related to a number of underlying conditions. Manifestations of eczema can include dryness and recurring skin rashes with redness, skin edema, itching and dryness, crusting, flaking, blistering, cracking, oozing, or bleeding.

Name: Brachydactyly
Desc: Digits that appear disproportionately short compared to the hand/foot. The word brachydactyly is used here to describe a series distinct patterns of shortened digits (brachydactyly types A-E). This is the sense used here.

Name: Umbilical hernia
Desc: Protrusion of abdominal contents through a defect in the abdominal wall musculature around the umbilicus. Skin and subcutaneous tissue overlie the defect.

Name: Laryngomalacia
Desc: Laryngomalacia is a congenital abnormality of the laryngeal cartilage in which the cartilage is floppy and prolapses over the larynx during inspiration.

Name: Abnormal aortic morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the aorta.

Name: Toe syndactyly
Desc: Webbing or fusion of the toes, involving soft parts only or including bone structure. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the toes in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "Symphalangism".

Name: Short foot
Desc: A measured foot length that is more than 2 SD below the mean for a newborn of 27 - 41 weeks gestation, or foot that is less than the 3rd centile for individuals from birth to 16 years of age (objective). Alternatively, a foot that appears disproportionately short (subjective).

Name: Frontal bossing
Desc: Bilateral bulging of the lateral frontal bone prominences with relative sparing of the midline.

Name: Pyloric stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the pylorus.

Name: Sparse scalp hair
Desc: Decreased number of hairs per unit area of skin of the scalp.
Synonyms: Reduction in the number of scalp follicles

Name: Sleep disturbance
Desc: An abnormality of sleep including such phenomena as 1) insomnia/hypersomnia, 2) non-restorative sleep, 3) sleep schedule disorder, 4) excessive daytime somnolence, 5) sleep apnea, and 6) restlessness.

Name: Highly arched eyebrow
Desc: Increased height of the central portion of the eyebrow, forming a crescent, semicircular, or inverted U shape.

Name: Supernumerary nipple
Desc: Presence of more than two nipples.

Name: Nephroblastoma
Desc: The presence of a nephroblastoma, which is a neoplasm of the kidney that primarily affects children.

Name: Downturned corners of mouth
Desc: A morphological abnormality of the mouth in which the angle of the mouth is downturned. The oral commissures are positioned inferior to the midline labial fissure.

Name: Short palm
Desc: Short palm.

Name: Depressed nasal bridge
Desc: Posterior positioning of the nasal root in relation to the overall facial profile for age.

Name: Finger syndactyly
Desc: Webbing or fusion of the fingers, involving soft parts only or including bone structure. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "Symphalangism".

Name: Wide intermamillary distance
Desc: A larger than usual distance between the left and right nipple.

Name: Bilateral single transverse palmar creases
Desc: The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease on both hands.

Name: Short metacarpal
Desc: Diminished length of one or more metacarpal bones in relation to the others of the same hand or to the contralateral metacarpal.

Name: Broad columella
Desc: Increased width of the columella.

Name: Midface retrusion
Desc: Posterior positions and/or vertical shortening of the infraorbital and perialar regions, or increased concavity of the face and/or reduced nasolabial angle.

Name: Small hand
Desc: Disproportionately small hand.

Name: Cardiac arrest
Desc: An abrupt loss of heart function.

Name: Pericarditis
Desc: Inflammation of the sac-like covering around the heart (pericardium).
Synonyms: Swelling or irritation of membrane around heart

Name: Abnormal bleeding
Desc: An abnormal susceptibility to bleeding, often referred to as a bleeding diathesis. A bleeding diathesis may be related to vascular, platelet and coagulation defects.

Name: Language impairment
Desc: Language impairment is a deficit in comprehension or production of language that includes reduced vocabulary, limited sentence structure or impairments in written or spoken communication. Language abilities are substantially and quantifiably below age expectations.

Name: Increased intracranial pressure
Desc: An increase of the pressure inside the cranium (skull) and thereby in the brain tissue and cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Fatigable weakness
Desc: A type of weakness that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.
Synonyms: Generalised muscle weakness due to defect at the neuromuscular junction
Generalized muscle weakness due to defect at the neuromuscular junction
Proximal muscle weakness due to defect at the neuromuscular junction

Name: Diaphragmatic paralysis
Desc: The presence of a paralyzed diaphragm.

Name: Cough
Desc: A sudden, audible expulsion of air from the lungs through a partially closed glottis, preceded by inhalation.

Name: Neoplasm of the thymus
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the thymus.

Name: Palpebral edema
Desc: Edema in the region of the eyelids.

Name: Mediastinal lymphadenopathy
Desc: Swelling of lymph nodes within the mediastinum, the central compartment of the thoracic cavities that contains the heart and the great vessels, the esophagus, and trachea and other structures including lymph nodes.
Synonyms: Swollen lymph nodes in center of chest
Swollen lymph nodes in centre of chest

Name: Chest pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the chest.

Name: Calvarial skull defect
Desc: A localized defect in the bone of the skull resulting from abnormal embryological development. The defect is covered by normal skin. In some cases, skull x-rays have shown underlying lytic bone lesions which have closed before the age of one year.

Name: Encephalocele
Desc: A neural tube defect characterized by sac-like protrusions of the brain and the membranes that cover it through openings in the skull.

Name: Postaxial polydactyly type A
Desc: Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand with a complete extra finger and extra metacarpal.

Name: Turricephaly
Desc: Tall head relative to width and length.

Name: Low-set, posteriorly rotated ears
Desc: Ears that are low-set (HP:0000369) and posteriorly rotated (HP:0000358).

Name: Macrotia
Desc: Median longitudinal ear length greater than two standard deviations above the mean and median ear width greater than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, apparent increase in length and width of the pinna (subjective).

Name: Prominent nose
Desc: Distance between subnasale and pronasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased anterior protrusion of the nasal tip.

Name: Myopia
Desc: An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects nearby clearly, while objects in the distance appear blurry.

Name: Abnormality of the skeletal system
Desc: An abnormality of the skeletal system.

Name: Hyperkeratosis
Desc: Hyperkeratosis is thickening of the outer layer of the skin, the stratum corneum, which is composed of large, polyhedral, plate-like envelopes filled with keratin which are the dead cells that have migrated up from the stratum granulosum.

Name: Hypohidrosis
Desc: Abnormally diminished capacity to sweat.

Name: Joint stiffness
Desc: Joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in a joint or joints when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity. Joint stiffness typically subsides over time.

Name: Intrauterine growth retardation
Desc: An abnormal restriction of fetal growth with fetal weight below the tenth percentile for gestational age.

Name: Kyphosis
Desc: Exaggerated anterior convexity of the thoracic vertebral column.

Name: Hip dislocation
Desc: Displacement of the femur from its normal location in the hip joint.

Name: Vertebral segmentation defect
Desc: An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation during development.

Name: Severe short stature
Desc: A severe degree of short stature, more than -4 SD from the mean corrected for age and sex.

Name: Biparietal narrowing
Desc: A narrowing of the biparietal diameter (i.e., of the transverse distance between the protuberances of the two parietal bones of the skull).

Name: Short middle phalanx of finger
Desc: Short (hypoplastic) middle phalanx of finger, affecting one or more fingers.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia of the middle phalanges of the hand

Name: Intellectual disability, progressive
Desc: The term progressive intellectual disability should be used if intelligence decreases/deteriorates over time.

Name: Ichthyosis
Desc: An abnormality of the skin characterized the presence of excessive amounts of dry surface scales on the skin resulting from an abnormality of keratinization.

Name: Sparse hair
Desc: Reduced density of hairs.

Name: Abnormal toenail morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the toenail.

Name: Moderate postnatal growth retardation
Desc: A moderate degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between three and four standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms.

Name: Abnormality of the antihelix
Desc: An abnormality of the antihelix.

Name: Abnormality of the elbow
Desc: An anomaly of the joint that connects the upper and the lower arm.

Name: Abnormality of the helix
Desc: An abnormality of the helix. The helix is the outer rim of the ear that extends from the insertion of the ear on the scalp (root) to the termination of the cartilage at the earlobe.

Name: Abnormal eyelash morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the eyelashes.

Name: Sparse body hair
Desc: Sparseness of the body hair.

Name: Abnormality of dental color
Desc: A developmental defect of tooth color.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the eyebrow
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the eyebrow.

Name: Abnormality of the dentition
Desc: Any abnormality of the teeth.

Name: Gingivitis
Desc: Inflammation of the gingiva.

Name: Hydrocephalus
Desc: Hydrocephalus is an active distension of the ventricular system of the brain resulting from inadequate passage of CSF from its point of production within the cerebral ventricles to its point of absorption into the systemic circulation.
Synonyms: Too much cerebrospinal fluid in the brain

Name: Hearing impairment
Desc: A decreased magnitude of the sensory perception of sound.

Name: Periodontitis
Desc: Inflammation of the periodontium.

Name: Melanocytic nevus
Desc: A oval and round, colored (usually medium-to dark brown, reddish brown, or flesh colored) lesion. Typically, a melanocytic nevus is less than 6 mm in diameter, but may be much smaller or larger.

Name: Intellectual disability, mild
Desc: Mild intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 50-69.

Name: Alopecia universalis
Desc: Loss of all hair on the entire body.

Name: EEG abnormality
Desc: Abnormality observed by electroencephalogram (EEG), which is used to record of the brain's spontaneous electrical activity from multiple electrodes placed on the scalp.

Name: Hemiparesis
Desc: Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.
Synonyms: Weakness of one side of body

Name: Polyneuropathy
Desc: A generalized disorder of peripheral nerves.

Name: Motor axonal neuropathy
Desc: Progressive impairment of function of motor axons with muscle weakness, atrophy, and cramps. The deficits are length-dependent, meaning that muscles innervated by the longest nerves are affected first, so that for instance the arms are affected at a later age than the onset of deficits involving the lower leg.

Name: Agitation
Desc: A state of exceeding restlessness and excessive motor activity associated with mental distress or a feeling of inner tension.

Name: Aggressive behavior
Desc: Aggressive behavior can denote verbal aggression, physical aggression against objects, physical aggression against people, and may also include aggression towards oneself.

Name: Autistic behavior
Desc: Persistent deficits in social interaction and communication and interaction as well as a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest as well as repetitive patterns of behavior.

Name: Delayed speech and language development
Desc: A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age.

Name: Hyperactivity
Desc: Hyperactivity is a state of constantly being unusually or abnormally active, including in situations in which it is not appropriate.

Name: Specific learning disability
Desc: Impairment of certain skills such as reading or writing, coordination, self-control, or attention that interfere with the ability to learn. The impairment is not related to a global deficiency of intelligence.

Name: Clumsiness
Desc: Lack of physical coordination resulting in an abnormal tendency to drop items or bump into objects.

Name: Prominent ear helix
Desc: Abnormally prominent ear helix.

Name: Thick vermilion border
Desc: Increased width of the skin of vermilion border region of upper lip.

Name: Recurrent hand flapping
Desc: A type of stereotypic behavior in which the affected individual repeatedly waves the hands up and down.

Name: Impulsivity
Desc: Acting on the spur of the moment in response to immediate stimuli; acting on a momentary basis without a plan or consideration of outcomes; difficulty establishing or following plans; a sense of urgency and self-harming behavior under emotional distress.

Name: Stereotypical body rocking
Desc: Habitual repetitive movement of the body.

Name: Prominent nasal bridge
Desc: Anterior positioning of the nasal root in comparison to the usual positioning for age.

Name: Thickened skin
Desc: Laminar thickening of skin.

Name: Epidermal acanthosis
Desc: Diffuse hypertrophy or thickening of the stratum spinosum of the epidermis (prickle cell layer of the skin).
Synonyms: Thickening of upper layer of skin

Name: Scaling skin
Desc: Refers to the loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes.

Name: Ectropion
Desc: An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin.

Name: Erythroderma
Desc: An inflammatory exfoliative dermatosis involving nearly all of the surface of the skin. Erythroderma develops suddenly. A patchy erythema may generalize and spread to affect most of the skin. Scaling may appear in 2-6 days and be accompanied by hot, red, dry skin, malaise, and fever.
Synonyms: Red scaly skin caused by inflammatory skin disease

Name: Parakeratosis
Desc: Abnormal formation of the keratinocytes of the epidermis characterized by persistence of nuclei, incomplete formation of keratin, and moistness and swelling of the keratinocytes.

Name: Congenital nonbullous ichthyosiform erythroderma
Desc: The term collodion baby applies to newborns who appear to have an extra layer of skin (known as a collodion membrane) that has a collodion-like quality. It is a descriptive term, not a specific diagnosis or disorder (as such, it is a syndrome). Affected babies are born in a collodion membrane, a shiny waxy outer layer to the skin. This is shed 10-14 days after birth, revealing the main symptom of the disease, extensive scaling of the skin caused by hyperkeratosis. With increasing age, the scaling tends to be concentrated around joints in areas such as the groin, the armpits, the inside of the elbow and the neck. The scales often tile the skin and may resemble fish scales.

Name: Impaired temperature sensation
Desc: A reduced ability to discriminate between different temperatures.

Name: Eclabion
Desc: A turning outward of the lip or lips, that is, eversion of the lips.

Name: Palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
Desc: Abnormal thickening of the skin localized to the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.
Synonyms: Hyperkeratosis of the palms and soles
Thickening of the outer layer of the skin of the palms and soles

Name: Nail dystrophy
Desc: Onychodystrophy (nail dystrophy) refers to nail changes apart from changes of the color (nail dyschromia) and involves partial or complete disruption of the various keratinous layers of the nail plate.

Name: Palmoplantar scaling skin
Desc: Loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes localized to the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.

Name: Lower limb spasticity
Desc: Spasticity (velocity-dependent increase in tonic stretch reflexes with increased muscle tone and hyperexcitable tendon reflexes) in the muscles of the lower limbs, hips, and pelvis

Name: Lower limb hyperreflexia
Synonyms: Increased deep tendon reflexes in the lower limbs

Name: Babinski sign
Desc: Upturning of the big toe (and sometimes fanning of the other toes) in response to stimulation of the sole of the foot. If the Babinski sign is present it can indicate damage to the corticospinal tract.

Name: Distal lower limb muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the legs.
Synonyms: Distal muscle weakness in lower limbs

Name: Spastic gait
Desc: Spasticity is manifested by increased stretch reflex which is intensified with movement velocity. This results in excessive and inappropriate muscle activation which can contribute to muscle hypertonia. Spastic gait is characterized by manifestations such as muscle hypertonia, stiff knee, and circumduction of the leg.

Name: Distal lower limb amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy of distal leg muscles.

Name: Ankle clonus
Desc: Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Ankle clonus is tested by rapidly flexing the foot upward.

Name: Urinary urgency
Desc: Urge incontinence is the strong, sudden need to urinate.

Name: Motor delay
Desc: A type of Developmental delay characterized by a delay in acquiring motor skills.

Name: Impaired vibratory sensation
Desc: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to bony prominences such as the malleoli at the ankles or the metacarpal-phalangeal joints. There is a slow decay of vibration from the tuning fork. The degree of vibratory sense loss can be crudely estimated by counting the number of seconds that the examiner can perceive the vibration longer than the patient.

Name: Rigidity
Desc: Continuous involuntary sustained muscle contraction. When an affected muscle is passively stretched, the degree of resistance remains constant regardless of the rate at which the muscle is stretched. This feature helps to distinguish rigidity from muscle spasticity.

Name: Bradykinesia
Desc: Bradykinesia literally means slow movement, and is used clinically to denote a slowness in the execution of movement (in contrast to hypokinesia, which is used to refer to slowness in the initiation of movement).

Name: Hyperesthesia
Desc: Increased sensitivity to stimulation, excluding the special senses, which may refer to various modes of cutaneous sensibility including touch and thermal sensation without pain, as well as to pain.

Name: Brisk reflexes
Desc: Tendon reflexes that are noticeably more active than usual (conventionally denoted 3+ on clinical examination). Brisk reflexes may or may not indicate a neurological lesion. They are distinguished from hyperreflexia by the fact that hyerreflexia is characterized by hyperactive repeating (clonic) reflexes, which are considered to be always abnormal.

Name: Impaired vibration sensation at ankles
Desc: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration at the ankles. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to the malleoli of the ankles.

Name: Lower limb muscle weakness
Desc: Weakness of the muscles of the legs.

Name: Pes cavus
Desc: The presence of an unusually high plantar arch. Also called high instep, pes cavus refers to a distinctly hollow form of the sole of the foot when it is bearing weight.

Name: Urinary bladder sphincter dysfunction
Desc: Abnormal function of a sphincter of the urinary bladder.

Name: Distal amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy affecting muscles in the distal portions of the extremities.
Synonyms: Distal amyotrophy, especially of the hands and feet
Distal muscle atrophy, upper and lower limbs

Name: Spastic paraplegia
Desc: Spasticity and weakness of the leg and hip muscles.

Name: Abnormality of the urinary system
Desc: An abnormality of the urinary system.

Name: Abnormal cerebellum morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the cerebellum.

Name: Lower limb amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy affecting the lower limb.

Name: Limb ataxia
Desc: A kind of ataxia that affects movements of the extremities.

Name: Truncal ataxia
Desc: Truncal ataxia is a sign of ataxia characterized by instability of the trunk. It usually occurs during sitting.
Synonyms: Instability or lack of coordination of central trunk muscles

Name: Cataract
Desc: A cataract is an opacity or clouding that develops in the crystalline lens of the eye or in its capsule.
Synonyms: Clouding of the lens of the eye

Name: Upper limb muscle weakness
Desc: Weakness of the muscles of the arms.

Name: Upper limb amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy involving the muscles of the upper limbs.

Name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure
Desc: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure is a seizure defined by a tonic (bilateral increased tone, lasting seconds to minutes) and then a clonic (bilateral sustained rhythmic jerking) phase.
Synonyms: Generalised tonic-clonic seizure (without specification of onset)
Generalized tonic-clonic seizure (without specification of onset)

Name: Limited hip movement
Desc: A decreased ability to move the femur at the hip joint associated with a decreased range of motion of the hip.

Name: Limitation of movement at ankles
Desc: An abnormal limitation of the mobility of the ankle joint.

Name: Urinary incontinence
Desc: Loss of the ability to control the urinary bladder leading to involuntary urination.

Name: Postural tremor
Desc: A type of tremors that is triggered by holding a limb in a fixed position.

Name: Hyperreflexia
Desc: Hyperreflexia is the presence of hyperactive stretch reflexes of the muscles.

Name: Degeneration of the lateral corticospinal tracts
Desc: Deterioration of the tissues of the lateral corticospinal tracts.

Name: Difficulty walking
Desc: Reduced ability to walk (ambulate).

Name: Impaired vibration sensation in the lower limbs
Desc: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the legs.
Synonyms: Decreased vibratory sense in lower limbs
Decreased vibratory sense in the lower extremities
Decreased vibratory sense in the lower limbs
Diminished vibratory sensation in the legs
Distal sensory loss, especially vibratory sense
Distal vibratory impairment of the lower limbs
Impaired vibration sensation in the lower limbs

Name: Limb dysmetria
Desc: A type of dysmetria involving the limbs.

Name: Muscle spasm
Desc: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles.

Name: Progressive pes cavus
Desc: The development of Pes cavus that is progressive with age.

Name: Peroneal muscle atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the peroneous muscles, peroneus longus (also known as Fibularis longus), Peroneus brevis (also known as fibularis brevis, and Peroneus tertius (also known as fibularis tertius).

Name: Clonus
Desc: A series of rhythmic and involuntary muscle contractions (at a frequency of about 5 to 7 Hz) that occur in response to an abruptly applied and sustained stretch.
Synonyms: Involuntary rhythmic muscular contractions and relaxations

Name: Abnormality of the cerebrospinal fluid
Desc: An abnormality of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Name: Abnormal lower-limb motor evoked potentials
Desc: An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs) in the leg.
Synonyms: Abnormal motor evoked potentials in the lower limb

Name: Sensorimotor neuropathy
Synonyms: Nerve damage causing decreased feeling and movement

Name: Intellectual disability, moderate
Desc: Moderate mental retardation is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 35-49.

Name: Rod-cone dystrophy
Desc: An inherited retinal disease subtype in which the rod photoreceptors appear to be more severely affected than the cone photoreceptors. Typical presentation is with nyctalopia (due to rod dysfunction) followed by loss of mid-peripheral field of vision, which gradually extends and leaves many patients with a small central island of vision due to the preservation of macular cones.

Name: Distal sensory impairment
Desc: An abnormal reduction in sensation in the distal portions of the extremities.
Synonyms: Distal sensory impairment in lower limbs
Distal sensory impairment of the lower extremities
Distal sensory loss, upper and lower limbs

Name: Peripheral axonal neuropathy
Desc: An abnormality characterized by disruption of the normal functioning of peripheral axons.

Name: Spastic paraparetic gait
Desc: A type of spastic gait in which the legs are usually slightly bent at the hip and in an adducted position. The knees are extended or slightly bent and the feet are in a plantar flexion position. This posture requires circumduction of the legs during walking. The gait may appear stiff (spastic gait disorder) or stiff as well as insecure (spastic ataxic gait disorder). In spastic paraparetic gait, each leg appears to be dragged forward. If the muscle tone in the adductors is marked, the resulting gait disorder is referred to as scissor gait.

Name: Upper motor neuron dysfunction
Desc: A functional anomaly of the upper motor neuron. The upper motor neurons are neurons of the primary motor cortex which project to the brainstem and spinal chord via the corticonuclear, corticobulbar and corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts. They are involved in control of voluntary movements. Dysfunction leads to weakness, impairment of fine motor movements, spasticity, hyperreflexia and abnormal pyramidal signs.

Name: Impaired distal vibration sensation
Desc: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the distal portions of the limbs.

Name: Varicose veins
Desc: Enlarged and tortuous veins.

Name: Dupuytren contracture
Desc: An abnormality of the hand resulting from contracture of the palmar fascia with a fixed flexion deformity of the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints and the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints.

Name: Impaired proprioception
Desc: A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position.

Name: Female sexual dysfunction
Desc: A problem occurring during any phase of the female sexual response cycle that prevents the individual from experiencing satisfaction from the sexual activity

Name: Male sexual dysfunction
Desc: A problem occurring during any phase of the male sexual response cycle that prevents the individual from experiencing satisfaction from the sexual activity

Name: Bowel incontinence
Desc: Involuntary fecal soiling in adults and children who have usually already been toilet trained.

Name: Abnormal pyramidal sign
Desc: Functional neurological abnormalities related to dysfunction of the pyramidal tract.

Name: Hypoplasia of the corpus callosum
Desc: Underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
Synonyms: Underdevelopment of part of brain called corpus callosum

Name: Functional abnormality of the bladder
Desc: Dysfunction of the urinary bladder.

Name: Pigmentary retinopathy
Desc: An abnormality of the retina characterized by pigment deposition. It is typically associated with migration and proliferation of macrophages or retinal pigment epithelial cells into the retina; melanin from these cells causes the pigmentary changes. Pigmentary retinopathy is a common final pathway of many retinal conditions and is often associated with visual loss.

Name: Pseudobulbar paralysis
Desc: Bilateral impairment of the function of the cranial nerves 9-12, which control musculature involved in eating, swallowing, and speech. Pseudobulbar paralysis is characterized clinically by dysarthria, dysphonia, and dysphagia with bifacial paralysis, and may be accompanied by Pseudobulbar behavioral symptoms such as enforced crying and laughing.

Name: Demyelinating peripheral neuropathy
Desc: Demyelinating neuropathy is characterized by slow nerve conduction velocities with reduced amplitudes of sensory/motor nerve conduction and prolonged distal latencies.

Name: Retinal flecks
Desc: Presence of multiple yellowish-white lesions of various size and configuration on the retina not related to vascular lesions.

Name: Deep cerebral white matter hyperdensities
Desc: Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from locations distant from the ventricular system.

Name: Saccadic smooth pursuit
Desc: An abnormality of tracking eye movements in which smooth pursuit is interrupted by an abnormally high number of saccadic movements.

Name: Hand tremor
Desc: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the hand.

Name: Visual loss
Desc: Loss of visual acuity (implying that vision was better at a certain time point in life). Otherwise the term reduced visual acuity should be used (or a subclass of that).

Name: Abnormality of the hallux
Desc: This term applies for all abnormalities of the big toe, also called hallux.

Name: Tetraplegia
Desc: Paralysis of all four limbs, and trunk of the body below the level of an associated injury to the spinal cord. The etiology of quadriplegia is similar to that of paraplegia except that the lesion is in the cervical spinal cord rather than in the thoracic or lumbar segments of the spinal cord.

Name: Functional abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract
Desc: Abnormal functionality of the gastrointestinal tract.
Synonyms: Functional abnormality of the GI tract

Name: Abnormality of the foot musculature
Desc: An anomaly of the musculature of foot.

Name: Foot dorsiflexor weakness
Desc: Weakness of the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot, that is, of the movement of the toes towards the shin. The foot dorsiflexors include the tibialis anterior, the extensor hallucis longus, the extensor digitorum longus, and the peroneus tertius muscles.

Name: Hand muscle atrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy involving the muscles of the hand.
Synonyms: Amyotrophy involving the musculature of the hand

Name: Split hand
Desc: A condition in which middle parts of the hand (fingers and metacarpals) are missing giving a cleft appearance. The severity is very variable ranging from slightly hypoplastic middle fingers over absent middel fingers as far as oligo- or monodactyl hands.

Name: Hand muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the musculature of the hand.

Name: Hip pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the hip.

Name: Knee pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the knee.

Name: Ankle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the muscles that lift or otherwise move the foot at the ankle.

Name: Dysdiadochokinesis
