Desc: A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to perform rapidly alternating movements, such as pronating and supinating his or her hand on the dorsum of the other hand as rapidly as possible.
Synonyms: Difficulty performing quick and alternating movements

Name: Ophthalmoparesis
Desc: Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement.
Synonyms: Weakness of muscles controlling eye movement

Name: Hyporeflexia
Desc: Reduction of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.

Name: Choreoathetosis
Desc: Involuntary movements characterized by both athetosis (inability to sustain muscles in a fixed position) and chorea (widespread jerky arrhythmic movements).

Name: Dysmetria
Desc: A type of ataxia characterized by the inability to carry out movements with the correct range and motion across the plane of more than one joint related to incorrect estimation of the distances required for targeted movements.

Name: Myoclonus
Desc: Very brief, involuntary random muscular contractions occurring at rest, in response to sensory stimuli, or accompanying voluntary movements.

Name: Gait ataxia
Desc: A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to coordinate the movements required for normal walking. Gait ataxia is characteirzed by a wide-based staggering gait with a tendency to fall.
Synonyms: Inability to coordinate movements when walking

Name: Action tremor
Desc: A tremor present when the limbs are active, either when outstretched in a certain position or throughout a voluntary movement.

Name: Involuntary movements
Desc: Involuntary contractions of muscle leading to involuntary movements of extremities, neck, trunk, or face.

Name: Dyssynergia
Desc: A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to smoothly perform the elements of a voluntary movement in the appropriate order and speed. With dyssynergia, a voluntary movement appears broken down into its component parts.

Name: Hyperintensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
Desc: A brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.

Name: Blepharospasm
Desc: A focal dystonia that affects the muscles of the eyelids and brow, associated with involuntary recurrent spasm of both eyelids.

Name: Oromandibular dystonia
Desc: A kind of focal dystonia characterized by forceful contractions of the face, jaw, and/or tongue causing difficulty in opening and closing the mouth and often affecting chewing and speech.

Name: Palmoplantar keratoderma
Desc: Abnormal thickening of the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.

Name: Congenital alopecia totalis
Desc: Loss of all scalp hair with congenital onset.

Name: Fingernail dysplasia
Desc: An abnormality of the development of the fingernails.

Name: Abnormality of the hand
Desc: An abnormality affecting one or both hands.

Name: Generalized hypotonia
Desc: Generalized muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone).

Name: Slurred speech
Desc: Abnormal coordination of muscles involved in speech.

Name: Joint hypermobility
Desc: The ability of a joint to move beyond its normal range of motion.

Name: Abnormal foot morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the skeleton of foot.

Name: Spastic dysarthria
Desc: A type of dysarthria related to bilateral damage of the upper motor neuron tracts of the pyramidal and extra- pyramidal tracts. Speech of affected individuals is slow, effortful, and has a harsh vocal quality.

Name: Abnormal hand morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the hand.

Name: Increased overbite
Desc: Maxillary teeth cover the mandibular teeth when biting to an increased degree. The feature is defined as a vertical overlap of the maxillary incisors over the mandibular incisors that exceeds 2 mm.
Synonyms: Increased overlap of upper and lower incisors

Name: Abnormality of brain morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the brain, which has as its parts the forebrain, midbrain, and hindbrain.

Name: Dysuria
Desc: Painful or difficult urination.

Name: Low-set ears
Desc: Upper insertion of the ear to the scalp below an imaginary horizontal line drawn between the inner canthi of the eye and extending posteriorly to the ear.

Name: Downslanted palpebral fissures
Desc: The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations below the mean.
Synonyms: Downward slanting of the opening between the eyelids

Name: Emotional lability
Desc: Unstable emotional experiences and frequent mood changes; emotions that are easily aroused, intense, and/or out of proportion to events and circumstances.

Name: Hallucinations
Desc: Perceptions in a conscious and awake state in the absence of external stimuli which have qualities of real perception, in that they are vivid, substantial, and located in external objective space.

Name: Abnormal thumb morphology
Desc: An abnormal structure of the first digit of the hand.

Name: Genu valgum
Desc: The legs angle inward, such that the knees are close together and the ankles far apart.

Name: Abnormality of the nares
Desc: Abnormality of the nostril.

Name: Speech apraxia
Desc: A type of apraxia that is characterized by difficulty or inability to execute speech movements because of problems with coordination and motor problems, leading to incorrect articulation. An increase of errors with increasing word and phrase length may occur.

Name: Panic attack
Desc: A sudden episode of intense fear in a situation in which there is no danger or apparent cause.

Name: Clinodactyly
Desc: An angulation of a digit at an interphalangeal joint in the plane of the palm (finger) or sole (toe).

Name: Primitive reflex
Desc: The primitive reflexes are a group of behavioural motor responses which are found in normal early development, are subsequently inhibited, but may be released from inhibition by cerebral, usually frontal, damage. They are thus part of a broader group of reflexes which reflect release phenomena, such as exaggerated stretch reflexes and extensor plantars. They do however involve more complex motor responses than such simple stretch reflexes, and are often a normal feature in the neonate or infant.

Name: Abnormality of peripheral nerve conduction
Desc: An abnormality of the conduction of electrical impulses by peripheral (motor or sensory) nerves. This finding is elicited by a nerve conduction study (NCS).
Synonyms: Sensory and motor nerve conduction abnormalities

Name: Personality disorder
Desc: An abnormality of mental functioning affecting the personality and behavioural tendencies of an individual and characterized by a rigid and unhealthy pattern of thinking and behavior. The definition of a personal disorder implies that the abnormality is not the result of damage or insult to the brain or from another psychiatric disorder.

Name: Multiple lentigines
Desc: Presence of an unusually high number of lentigines (singular: lentigo), which are flat, tan to brown oval spots.

Name: Waddling gait
Desc: Weakness of the hip girdle and upper thigh muscles, for instance in myopathies, leads to an instability of the pelvis on standing and walking. If the muscles extending the hip joint are affected, the posture in that joint becomes flexed and lumbar lordosis increases. The patients usually have difficulties standing up from a sitting position. Due to weakness in the gluteus medius muscle, the hip on the side of the swinging leg drops with each step (referred to as Trendelenburg sign). The gait appears waddling. The patients frequently attempt to counteract the dropping of the hip on the swinging side by bending the trunk towards the side which is in the stance phase (in the German language literature this is referred to as Duchenne sign). Similar gait patterns can be caused by orthopedic conditions when the origin and the insertion site of the gluteus medius muscle are closer to each other than normal, for instance due to a posttraumatic elevation of the trochanter or pseudarthrosis of the femoral neck.

Name: Kyphoscoliosis
Desc: An abnormal curvature of the spine in both a coronal (lateral) and sagittal (back-to-front) plane.

Name: Horseshoe kidney
Desc: A connection of the right and left kidney by an isthmus of functioning renal parenchyma or fibrous tissue that crosses the midline.

Name: Silver-gray hair
Desc: Hypopigmented hair that appears silver-gray.

Name: Scissor gait
Desc: A type of spastic paraparetic gait in which the muscle tone in the adductors is marked. It is characterized by hypertonia and flexion in the legs, hips and pelvis accompanied by extreme adduction leading to the knees and thighs hitting, or sometimes even crossing, in a scissors-like movement. The opposing muscles (abductors) become comparatively weak from lack of use.

Name: Tip-toe gait
Desc: An abnormal gait pattern characterized by the failure of the heel to contact the floor at the onset of stance during gait.

Name: Paraparesis
Desc: Weakness or partial paralysis in the lower limbs.

Name: Herniation of intervertebral nuclei
Desc: The presence of one or more herniated nucleus pulposus of intervertebral disk.

Name: Lower limb pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the leg.

Name: Neck pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the neck.

Name: Developmental cataract
Desc: A cataract that occurs congenitally as the result of a developmental defect, in contrast to the majority of cataracts that occur in adulthood as the result of degenerative changes of the lens.
Synonyms: Clouding of the lens of the eye at birth

Name: Developmental glaucoma
Desc: Glaucoma which forms during the early years of a child's life is called developmental or congenital glaucoma.

Name: Cervical spondylosis
Desc: The presence of arthrosis, i.e., of degenerative joint disease, affecting the cervical vertebral column.

Name: Upper limb pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the arm.

Name: Abnormal lumbar spine morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the lumbar vertebral column.

Name: Cerebral cortical atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the cortex of the cerebrum.
Synonyms: Decrease in size of the outer layer of the brain due to loss of brain cells

Name: Dystonia
Desc: An abnormally increased muscular tone that causes fixed abnormal postures. There is a slow, intermittent twisting motion that leads to exaggerated turning and posture of the extremities and trunk.

Name: Dyskinesia
Desc: A movement disorder which consists of effects including diminished voluntary movements and the presence of involuntary movements.

Name: Abnormality of somatosensory evoked potentials
Desc: An abnormality of somatosensory evoked potentials (SSEP), i.e., of the electrical signals of sensation going from the body to the brain in response to a defined stimulus. Recording electrodes are placed over the scalp, spine, and peripheral nerves proximal to the stimulation site. Clinical studies generally use electrical stimulation of peripheral nerves to elicit potentials. SSEP testing determines whether peripheral sensory nerves are able to transmit sensory information like pain, temperature, and touch to the brain. Abnormal SSEPs can result from dysfunction at the level of the peripheral nerve, plexus, spinal root, spinal cord, brain stem, thalamocortical projections, or primary somatosensory cortex.

Name: Postural instability
Desc: A tendency to fall or the inability to keep oneself from falling; imbalance. The retropulsion test is widely regarded as the gold standard to evaluate postural instability, Use of the retropulsion test includes a rapid balance perturbation in the backward direction, and the number of balance correcting steps (or total absence thereof) is used to rate the degree of postural instability. Healthy subjects correct such perturbations with either one or two large steps, or without taking any steps, hinging rapidly at the hips while swinging the arms forward as a counterweight. In patients with balance impairment, balance correcting steps are often too small, forcing patients to take more than two steps. Taking three or more steps is generally considered to be abnormal, and taking more than five steps is regarded as being clearly abnormal. Markedly affected patients continue to step backward without ever regaining their balance and must be caught by the examiner (this would be called true retropulsion). Even more severely affected patients fail to correct entirely, and fall backward like a pushed toy soldier, without taking any corrective steps.

Name: Abolished vibration sense
Desc: A complete loss of the ability to perceive vibration.

Name: Pain insensitivity
Desc: Inability to perceive painful stimuli.

Name: Impaired tactile sensation
Desc: A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation). This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.

Name: Hiatus hernia
Desc: The presence of a hernia in which the upper part of the stomach, i.e., mainly the gastric cardia protrudes through the diaphragmatic esophageal hiatus.

Name: Hyperbilirubinemia
Desc: An increased amount of bilirubin in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of the lower urinary tract
Desc: An abnormality of the lower urinary tract.

Name: Abnormal rectum morphology
Desc: An abnormaltiy of the rectum, the final segment of the large intestine that stores solid waste until it passes through the anus.

Name: Abnormal saccadic eye movements
Desc: An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impairment of fast (saccadic) eye movements.

Name: Somatic sensory dysfunction
Desc: An abnormality of the primary sensation that is mediated by peripheral nerves (pain, temperature, touch, vibration, joint position). The word hypoesthesia (or hypesthesia) refers to a reduction in cutaneous sensation to a specific type of testing.

Name: Diffuse cerebellar atrophy
Desc: Diffuse unlocalised atrophy affecting the cerebellum.

Name: Spastic tetraparesis
Desc: Spastic weakness affecting all four limbs.

Name: Proximal muscle weakness in lower limbs
Desc: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the legs.

Name: Hypertonia
Desc: A condition in which there is increased muscle tone so that arms or legs, for example, are stiff and difficult to move.

Name: Proximal lower limb amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the legs, i.e., of the thigh.

Name: Difficulty running
Desc: Reduced ability to run.

Name: Prolonged QTc interval
Desc: A longer than normal interval (corrected for heart rate) between the Q and T waves in the heart's cycle. Prolonged QTc can cause premature action potentials during late phase depolarizations thereby leading to ventricular arrhythmias and ventricular fibrillations.

Name: Syncope
Desc: Syncope refers to a generalized weakness of muscles with loss of postural tone, inability to stand upright, and loss of consciousness. Once the patient is in a horizontal position, blood flow to the brain is no longer hindered by gravitation and consciousness is regained. Unconsciousness usually lasts for seconds to minutes. Headache and drowsiness (which usually follow seizures) do not follow a syncopal attack. Syncope results from a sudden impairment of brain metabolism usually due to a reduction in cerebral blood flow.

Name: Sinus bradycardia
Desc: Bradycardia related to a mean resting sinus rate of less than 50 beats per minute.

Name: Abnormal T-wave
Desc: An abnormality of the T wave on the electrocardiogram, which mainly represents the repolarization of the ventricles.

Name: Sudden cardiac death
Desc: The heart suddenly and unexpectedly stops beating resulting in death within a short time period (generally within 1 h of symptom onset).

Name: Torsade de pointes
Desc: A type of ventricular tachycardia characterized by polymorphioc QRS complexes that change in amplitue and cycle length, and thus have the appearance of oscillating around the baseline in the EKG.

Name: Abnormal autonomic nervous system physiology
Desc: A functional abnormality of the autonomic nervous system.

Name: Abnormal cardiac exercise stress test
Desc: Abnormal results of exercise on heart function.

Name: Abnormality of prenatal development or birth
Desc: An abnormality of the fetus or the birth of the fetus, excluding structural abnormalities.
Synonyms: Abnormality of prenatal development or birth

Name: Hypokalemia
Desc: An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood.

Name: Cirrhosis
Desc: A chronic disorder of the liver in which liver tissue becomes scarred and is partially replaced by regenerative nodules and fibrotic tissue resulting in loss of liver function.
Synonyms: Scar tissue replaces healthy tissue in the liver

Name: Hepatosplenomegaly
Desc: Simultaneous enlargement of the liver and spleen.

Name: Abnormal circulating glutamine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamine in the blood circulation.

Name: Increased serum bile acid concentration
Desc: An increase in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of the clitoris
Desc: An abnormality of the clitoris.

Name: Abnormality of the kidney
Desc: An abnormality of the kidney.

Name: Telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectasias refer to small dilated blood vessels located near the surface of the skin or mucous membranes, measuring between 0.5 and 1 millimeter in diameter. Telangiectasia are located especially on the tongue, lips, palate, fingers, face, conjunctiva, trunk, nail beds, and fingertips.

Name: Hydrops fetalis
Desc: The abnormal accumulation of fluid in two or more fetal compartments, including ascites, pleural effusion, pericardial effusion, and skin edema.

Name: Abnormal facial shape
Desc: An abnormal morphology (form) of the face or its components.

Name: Premature skin wrinkling
Desc: The presence of an increased degree of wrinkling (irregular folds and indentations) of the skin as compared with age-related norms.

Name: Atrial septal defect
Desc: Atrial septal defect (ASD) is a congenital abnormality of the interatrial septum that enables blood flow between the left and right atria via the interatrial septum.
Synonyms: An opening in the wall separating the top two chambers of the heart
Hole in heart wall separating two upper heart chambers

Name: Coarctation of aorta
Desc: Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a segment of the aorta.

Name: Biventricular hypertrophy
Desc: Thickening of the heart walls in both ventricles.

Name: Abnormality of neuronal migration
Desc: An abnormality resulting from an anomaly of neuronal migration, i.e., of the process by which neurons travel from their origin to their final position in the brain.

Name: Abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the cerebral cortex.

Name: Subcortical heterotopia
Desc: A form of heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is located deep within the white matter.

Name: Polymicrogyria
Desc: Polymicrogyria is a congenital malformation of the cerebral cortex characterized by abnormal cortical layering (lamination) and an excessive number of small gyri (folds).

Name: Abnormal foramen magnum morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the foramen magnum.

Name: EEG with focal slow activity
Desc: Focal (localized) slow activity reflects focal dysfunction, not diffuse dysfunction (i.e., encephalopathy).

Name: EEG with focal spikes
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.

Name: Agenesis of corpus callosum
Desc: Absence of the corpus callosum as a result of the failure of the corpus callosum to develop, which can be the result of a failure in any one of the multiple steps of callosal development including cellular proliferation and migration, axonal growth or glial patterning at the midline.

Name: Abnormality of the basal ganglia
Desc: Abnormality of the basal ganglia.

Name: Occipital encephalocele
Desc: A type of encephalocele (that is, a a protrusion of part of the cranial contents including brain tissue through a congenital opening in the cranium, typically covered with skin or mucous membrane) in the occipital region of the skull. Occipital encephalocele presents as a midline swelling over the occipital bone. It is usually covered with normal full-thickness scalp.
Synonyms: Brain tissue sticks out through back of skull

Name: Gray matter heterotopia
Desc: Heterotopia or neuronal heterotopia are macroscopic clusters of misplaced neurons (gray matter), most often situated along the ventricular walls or within the subcortical white matter.

Name: Focal aware seizure
Desc: A type of focal-onset seizure in which awareness is preserved. Awareness during a seizure is defined as the patient being fully aware of themself and their environment throughout the seizure, even if immobile.
Synonyms: Focal seizure without impairment of awareness
Focal seizure without impairment of consciousness or awareness
Focal seizures without impairment of consciousness or awareness
Partial seizure without impairment of awareness

Name: Abnormal bone structure
Desc: Any anomaly in the composite material or the layered arrangement of the bony skeleton.

Name: Focal-onset seizure
Desc: A focal-onset seizure is a type of seizure originating within networks limited to one hemisphere. They may be discretely localized or more widely distributed, and may originate in subcortical structures.
Synonyms: Seizure affecting one half of brain

Name: Focal cortical dysplasia
Desc: A type of malformation of cortical development that primarily affects areas of neocortex. It can be identified on conventional magnetic resonance imaging as focal cortical thickening, abnormal gyration, and blurring between gray and white matter, often associated with clusters of heterotopic neurons.

Name: Abnormality of ethmoid bone
Desc: An abnormality of the ethmoid bone

Name: Abnormality of the forehead
Desc: An anomaly of the forehead.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the frontal region of the face

Name: Partial agenesis of the corpus callosum
Desc: A partial failure of the development of the corpus callosum.
Synonyms: Partial or complete agenesis of corpus callosum
Partial or complete agenesis of the corpus callosum
Partial to complete agenesis of corpus callosum

Name: Prominent glabella
Desc: Forward protrusion of the glabella.

Name: Visual hallucinations
Desc: Visual perceptions that are not elicited by a corresponding stimulus from the outside world.

Name: Meningocele
Desc: Protrusion of the meninges through a defect of the vertebral column.

Name: Myelomeningocele
Desc: Protrusion of the meninges and portions of the spinal cord through a defect of the vertebral column.

Name: EEG with focal sharp slow waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: EEG with temporal focal spike waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the temporal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: Interictal EEG abnormality
Desc: Interictal refers to a period of time between epileptic seizures. Electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns are important in the differential diagnosis of epilepsy, and the EEG is almost always abnormal during a seizure. Some persons with seizures may show EEG abnormalities between seizures, while others do not. In some cases, multiple interictal EEGs must be recorded before an abnormality is observed. In most cases the electrographic pattern of seizure onset is completely different from the activity recorded during interictal discharge.

Name: Acroparesthesia
Desc: A type of paresthesia (tingling, pins-and-needles, burning or numbness or stiffness) that occurs in the hands and feet and particularly in the fingers and toes.

Name: Febrile seizure (within the age range of 3 months to 6 years)
Desc: A febrile seizure is any type of seizure (most often a generalized tonic-clonic seizure) occurring with fever (at least 38 degrees Celsius) but in the absence of central nervous system infection, severe metabolic disturbance or other alternative precipitant in children between the ages of 3 months and 6 years.

Name: Status epilepticus
Desc: Status epilepticus is a type of prolonged seizure resulting either from the failure of the mechanisms responsible for seizure termination or from the initiation of mechanisms which lead to abnormally prolonged seizures (after time point t1). It is a condition that can have long-term consequences (after time point t2), including neuronal death, neuronal injury, and alteration of neuronal networks, depending on the type and duration of seizures.
Synonyms: Repeated seizures without recovery between them

Name: Generalized tonic seizure
Desc: A generalized tonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterised by bilateral limb stiffening or elevation, often with neck stiffening without a subsequent clonic phase. The tonic activity can be a sustained abnormal posture, either in extension or flexion, sometimes accompanied by tremor of the extremities.

Name: Generalized clonic seizure
Desc: Generalized clonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterised by sustained bilateral jerking, either symmetric or asymmetric, that is regularly repetitive and involves the same muscle groups.

Name: Abnormal social behavior
Desc: An abnormality of actions or reactions of a person taking place during interactions with others.

Name: Generalized non-motor (absence) seizure
Desc: A generalized non-motor (absence) seizure is a type of a type of dialeptic seizure that is of electrographically generalized onset. It is a generalized seizure characterised by an interruption of activities, a blank stare, and usually the person will be unresponsive when spoken to. Any ictal motor phenomena are minor in comparison to these non-motor features.

Name: Generalized myoclonic seizure
Desc: A generalized myoclonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterised by bilateral, sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction of muscles or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal). Myoclonus is less regularly repetitive and less sustained than is clonus.

Name: Intellectual disability, profound
Desc: Profound mental retardation is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) below 20.

Name: Atypical absence seizure
Desc: An atypical absence seizure is a type of generalised non-motor (absence) seizure characterised by interruption of ongoing activities and reduced responsiveness. In comparison to a typical absence seizure, changes in tone may be more pronounced, onset and/or cessation may be less abrupt, and the duration of the ictus and post-ictal recovery may be longer. Although not always available, an EEG often demonstrates slow (<3 Hz), irregular, generalized spike-wave activity.

Name: Atonic seizure
Desc: Atonic seizure is a type of motor seizure characterized by a sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone without apparent preceding myoclonic or tonic event lasting about 1 to 2 seconds, involving head, trunk, jaw, or limb musculature.

Name: Intellectual disability, severe
Desc: Severe mental retardation is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 20-34.

Name: Complex febrile seizure
Desc: A febrile seizure that has any of the following features: focal semiology (or associated with post-ictal neurologic abnormalities beyond drowsiness, such as a Todd's paresis), prolonged seizure beyond 15 minutes, or recurring (occurring more than once) in a 24 hour period.

Name: Abnormal eating behavior
Desc: Abnormal eating habit with excessive or insufficient consumption of food or any other abnormal pattern of food consumption.

Name: Gingival bleeding
Desc: Hemorrhage affecting the gingiva.

Name: Epistaxis
Desc: Epistaxis, or nosebleed, refers to a hemorrhage localized in the nose.

Name: Gastrointestinal hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage affecting the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Cortical dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the cerebral cortex.

Name: Cerebellar dysplasia
Desc: Cerebellar dysplasia (abnormal growth or development) is defined by abnormal cerebellar foliation, white matter arborization, and gray-white matter junction. Cerebellar dysplasia is a neuroimaging finding that describes abnormalities of both the cerebellar cortex and white matter and is associated with variable neurodevelopmental outcome. Dysplasia may globally involve the cerebellum or affect only one cerebellar hemisphere. In addition, cerebellar dysplasia may be associated with cortical/subcortical cysts.

Name: Cerebral dysmyelination
Desc: Defective structure and function of myelin sheaths of the white matter of the brain.

Name: Esotropia
Desc: A form of strabismus with one or both eyes turned inward ('crossed') to a relatively severe degree, usually defined as 10 diopters or more.

Name: Cerebellar vermis hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Hypoplasia of the pons
Desc: Underdevelopment of the pons.

Name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with generalized onset
Desc: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with generalized onset is a type of bilateral tonic-clonic seizure characterised by generalized onset; these seizures rapidly engage networks in both hemispheres at the start of the seizure.
Synonyms: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with generalised onset
Generalised tonic-clonic seizure without focal onset
Generalised tonic-clonic seizure without partial onset
Generalised tonic-clonic seizures without focal onset
Generalized tonic-clonic seizure without focal onset
Generalized tonic-clonic seizure without partial onset
Generalized tonic-clonic seizures without focal onset

Name: Hypoplasia of the brainstem
Desc: Underdevelopment of the brainstem.

Name: Typical absence seizure
Desc: A typical absence seizure is a type of generalised non-motor (absence) seizure characterised by its sudden onset, interruption of ongoing activities, a blank stare, possibly a brief upward deviation of the eyes. Usually the patient will be unresponsive when spoken to. Duration is a few seconds to half a minute with very rapid recovery. Although not always available, an EEG would usually show 3 Hz generalized epileptiform discharges during the event.

Name: Increased head circumference
Desc: An abnormally increased head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart.

Name: Cerebral hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the cerebrum.

Name: EEG with focal epileptiform discharges
Desc: EEG discharges recorded in particular areas of a localized (focal) abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Widened subarachnoid space
Desc: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater.

Name: Infantile spasms
Desc: Infantile spasms represent a subset of "epileptic spasms". Infantile Spasms are epileptic spasms starting in the first year of life (infancy).

Name: Focal atonic seizure
Desc: A focal seizure characterized at onset by sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone without apparent preceding myoclonic or tonic activity, typically lasting more than 500 ms but less than 2 seconds. It may involve the head, trunk, jaw or limb musculature.

Name: Areflexia
Desc: Absence of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.

Name: Distal upper limb amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy of distal arm muscles.

Name: Impaired pain sensation
Desc: Reduced ability to perceive painful stimuli.

Name: Excessive daytime somnolence
Desc: A state of abnormally strong desire for sleep during the daytime.
Synonyms: More than typical sleepiness during day

Name: Sensory axonal neuropathy
Desc: An axonal neuropathy of peripheral sensory nerves.

Name: Decreased nerve conduction velocity
Desc: A reduction in the speed at which electrical signals propagate along the axon of a neuron.

Name: Distal muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the musculature of the distal extremities.
Synonyms: Distal limb muscle weakness due to peripheral neuropathy
Muscle weakness, distal limbs, due to neuronopathy

Name: Decreased motor nerve conduction velocity
Desc: A type of decreased nerve conduction velocity that affects the motor neuron.

Name: Decreased sensory nerve conduction velocity
Desc: Reduced speed of conduction of the action potential along a sensory nerve.

Name: Sensory ataxia
Desc: Incoordination of movement caused by a deficit in the sensory nervous system. Sensory ataxia can be distinguished from cerebellar ataxia by asking the patient to close his or her eyes. Persons with cerebellar ataxia show only a minimal worsening of symptoms, whereas persons with sensory ataxia show a marked worsening of symptoms.

Name: Acute demyelinating polyneuropathy
Desc: Acute progressive areflexic weakness and mild sensory changes resulting from myelin breakdown and axonal degeneration.

Name: Calf muscle hypertrophy
Desc: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the calf muscles.
Synonyms: Muscular hypertrophy of the calf muscles

Name: Diaphragmatic weakness
Desc: A decrease in the strength of the diaphragm.

Name: Spontaneous pain sensation
Desc: Spontaneous pain is a kind of neuropathic pain which occurs without an identifiable trigger.

Name: Shoulder pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the shoulder.

Name: Abnormal pupil morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the pupil.

Name: Increased CSF protein
Desc: Increased concentration of protein in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Elevated circulating creatine kinase concentration
Desc: An elevation of the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase, CPK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood. CPK levels can be elevated in a number of clinical disorders such as myocardial infarction, rhabdomyolysis, and muscular dystrophy.

Name: Peripheral dysmyelination
Desc: Defective structure and function of myelin sheaths. Dysmyelination is distinguished from demyleination where there is destruction or damage of previously normal myelination.

Name: Skeletal muscle hypertrophy
Desc: Hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells (as opposed to hyperplasia, which refers to an increase in the number of muscle cells).

Name: Pallor
Desc: Abnormally pale skin.

Name: Reticulocytopenia
Desc: A reduced number of reticulocytes in the peripheral blood.

Name: Bone marrow hypocellularity
Desc: A reduced number of hematopoietic cells present in the bone marrow relative to marrow fat.

Name: Bruising susceptibility
Desc: An ecchymosis (bruise) refers to the skin discoloration caused by the escape of blood into the tissues from ruptured blood vessels. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to bruising. The corresponding phenotypic abnormality is generally elicited on medical history as a report of frequent ecchymoses or bruising without adequate trauma.

Name: Abnormality of the cardiovascular system
Desc: Any abnormality of the cardiovascular system.

Name: Neutropenia
Desc: An abnormally low number of neutrophils in the peripheral blood.

Name: Pancytopenia
Desc: An abnormal reduction in numbers of all blood cell types (red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets).

Name: Decreased proportion of CD4-positive helper T cells
Desc: A decreased proportion of circulating CD4-positive helper T cells relative to total T cell count.

Name: Abnormality of immune system physiology
Desc: A functional abnormality of the immune system.

Name: Abnormality of interleukin secretion
Desc: An abnormality in the production or cellular release of interleukins (a class of cytokines).

Name: Erythroid hypoplasia
Desc: Decreased count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
Synonyms: Erythroid hypoplasia in the bone marrow

Name: Fatigable weakness of skeletal muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of skeletal muscle that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Abnormal proportion of CD8-positive T cells
Desc: Any abnormality in the proportion of CD8 T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Abnormal proportion of CD8+ T cells
Abnormal proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells

Name: Slow saccadic eye movements
Desc: An abnormally slow velocity of the saccadic eye movements.

Name: Kinetic tremor
Desc: Tremor that occurs during any voluntary movement. It may include visually or non-visually guided movements. Tremor during target directed movement is called intention tremor.

Name: Head tremor
Desc: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting head movement.

Name: Limb dystonia
Desc: A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the limbs.

Name: Cerebellar atrophy
Desc: Cerebellar atrophy is defined as a cerebellum with initially normal structures, in a posterior fossa with normal size, which displays enlarged fissures (interfolial spaces) in comparison to the foliae secondary to loss of tissue. Cerebellar atrophy implies irreversible loss of tissue and result from an ongoing progressive disease until a final stage is reached or a single injury, e.g. an intoxication or infectious event.

Name: Hypermetric saccades
Desc: A saccade that overshoots the target with the dynamic saccade.

Name: Laryngeal dystonia
Desc: A form of focal dystonia that affects the vocal cords, associated with involuntary contractions of the vocal cords causing interruptions of speech and affecting the voice quality and often leading to patterned, repeated breaks in speech.

Name: Tremor by anatomical site
Desc: Tremor classified by the affected body part.

Name: Gaze-evoked nystagmus
Desc: Nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.

Name: Vertigo
Desc: An abnormal sensation of spinning while the body is actually stationary.

Name: Upper limb postural tremor
Desc: A type of tremors that is triggered by holding an arm in a fixed position.

Name: Downbeat nystagmus
Desc: Downbeat nystagmus is a type of fixation nystagmus with the fast phase beating in a downward direction. It generally increases when looking to the side and down and when lying prone.

Name: Isometric tremor
Desc: An isometric tremor occurs with muscle contraction against a rigid stationary object (e.g., when making a fist).

Name: Intention tremor
Desc: A type of kinetic tremor that occurs during target directed movement is called intention tremor. That is, an oscillatory cerebellar ataxia that tends to be absent when the limbs are inactive and during the first part of voluntary movement but worsening as the movement continues and greater precision is required (e.g., in touching a target such as the patient's nose or a physician's finger).

Name: Facial tics
Desc: Sudden, repetitive, nonrhythmic motor movements (spasms), involving the eyes and muscles of the face.

Name: Abnormal cerebellar cortex morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the cortex of the cerebellum.
Synonyms: Abnormal morphology of the cerebellar cortex

Name: Facial myokymia
Desc: Facial myokymia is a fine fibrillary activity of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

Name: Areflexia of lower limbs
Desc: Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the lower limbs.

Name: Decreased number of large peripheral myelinated nerve fibers
Desc: A reduced number of large myelinated nerve fibers.
Synonyms: Decreased number of large peripheral myelinated nerve fibres
Loss of larger myelinated nerve fibers
Loss of larger myelinated nerve fibres

Name: EMG: neuropathic changes
Desc: The presence of characteristic findings of denervation on electromyography (fibrillations, positive sharp waves, and giant motor unit potentials).

Name: Impaired distal tactile sensation
Desc: A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation) on the skin of the distal limbs. This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.

Name: Impaired horizontal smooth pursuit
Desc: An abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit characterized by an impairment of the ability to track horizontally moving objects.

Name: Progressive gait ataxia
Desc: A type of gait ataxia displaying progression of clinical severity.

Name: Dysmetric saccades
Desc: The controller signal for saccadic eye movements has two components: the pulse that moves the eye rapidly from one point to the next, and the step that holds the eye in the new position. When both the pulse and the step are not the correct size, a dysmetric refixation eye movement results.

Name: Fasciculations
Desc: Fasciculations are observed as small, local, involuntary muscle contractions (twitching) visible under the skin. Fasciculations result from increased irritability of an axon (which in turn is often a manifestation of disease of a motor neuron). This leads to sporadic discharges of all the muscle fibers controlled by the axon in isolation from other motor units.

Name: Paralysis
Desc: Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Motor paralysis results from deficits of the upper motor neurons (corticospinal, corticobulbar, or subcorticospinal). Motor paralysis is often accompanied by an impairment in the facility of movement.

Name: Irritability
Desc: A proneness to anger, i.e., a condition of being easily bothered or annoyed.

Name: Lethargy
Desc: A state of disinterestedness, listlessness, and indifference, resulting in difficulty performing simple tasks or concentrating.

Name: Talipes equinovarus
Desc: Talipes equinovarus (also called clubfoot) typically has four main components: inversion and adduction of the forefoot; inversion of the heel and hindfoot; equinus (limitation of extension) of the ankle and subtalar joint; and internal rotation of the leg.

Name: Hypokinesia
Desc: Abnormally diminished motor activity. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.

Name: Excessive salivation
Desc: Excessive production of saliva.

Name: Decreased CSF homovanillic acid
Desc: Decreased concentration of homovanillic acid (HVA) in the cerebrospinal fluid. HVA is a metabolite of dopamine.

Name: Focal dystonia
Desc: A type of dystonia that is localized to a specific part of the body.

Name: Oculogyric crisis
Desc: An acute dystonic reaction with blepharospasm, periorbital twitches, and protracted fixed staring episodes. There may be a maximal upward deviation of the eyes in the sustained fashion. Oculogyric crisis can be triggered by a number of factors including neuroleptic medications.

Name: Feeding difficulties
Desc: Impaired ability to eat related to problems gathering food and getting ready to suck, chew, or swallow it.

Name: Generalized dystonia
Desc: A type of dystonia that affects all or most of the body.

Name: Hyperpigmentation of the skin
Desc: A darkening of the skin related to an increase in melanin production and deposition.

Name: Thin skin
Desc: Reduction in thickness of the skin, generally associated with a loss of suppleness and elasticity of the skin.

Name: Atypical scarring of skin
Desc: Atypically scarred skin .

Name: Cutaneous photosensitivity
Desc: An increased sensitivity of the skin to light. Photosensitivity may result in a rash upon exposure to the sun (which is known as photodermatosis). Photosensitivity can be diagnosed by phototests in which light is shone on small areas of skin.

Name: Hepatic steatosis
Desc: Steatosis is a term used to denote lipid accumulation within hepatocytes.

Name: Hepatocellular carcinoma
Desc: A kind of neoplasm of the liver that originates in hepatocytes and presents macroscopically as a soft and hemorrhagic tan mass in the liver.

Name: Generalized hirsutism
Desc: Abnormally increased hair growth over much of the entire body.

Name: Abnormal blistering of the skin
Desc: The presence of one or more bullae on the skin, defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls.

Name: Erythema
Desc: Redness of the skin, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.
Synonyms: Redness of skin or mucous membrane

Name: Cerebral palsy
Desc: Cerebral palsy describes a group of permanent disorders of the development of movement and posture, causing activity limitation, that are attributed to nonprogressive disturbances that occurred in the developing fetal or infant brain. The motor disorders of cerebral palsy are often accompanied by disturbances of sensation, perception, cognition, communication, and behaviour, by epilepsy, and by secondary musculoskeletal problems.

Name: Skin vesicle
Desc: A circumscribed, fluid-containing, epidermal elevation generally considered less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point.

Name: Alopecia totalis
Desc: Loss of all scalp hair.

Name: Absent septum pellucidum
Desc: Absence of the septum pellucidum.

Name: Cerebral atrophy
Desc: Atrophy (wasting, decrease in size of cells or tissue) affecting the cerebrum.

Name: Dysgenesis of the basal ganglia
Desc: Structural abnormality of the basal ganglia related to defective development.

Name: Hypoplastic hippocampus
Desc: Underdevelopment of the hippocampus.

Name: Cerebral visual impairment
Desc: A form of loss of vision caused by damage to the visual cortex rather than a defect in the eye.

Name: Abnormal esophagus morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the esophagus.

Name: Morphological abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract
Desc: Abnormal structure of the gastrointestinal tract.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of the digestive system
Morphological abnormality of the GI tract
Morphological anomaly of the digestive system

Name: Esophageal neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the esophagus.

Name: Proteinuria
Desc: Increased levels of protein in the urine.

Name: Abnormality of the eye
Desc: Any abnormality of the eye, including location, spacing, and intraocular abnormalities.

Name: Hematuria
Desc: The presence of blood in the urine. Hematuria may be gross hematuria (visible to the naked eye) or microscopic hematuria (detected by dipstick or microscopic examination of the urine).

Name: Achalasia
Desc: A disorder of esophageal motility characterized by the inability of the lower esophageal sphincter to relax during swallowing and by inadequate or lacking peristalsis in the lower half of the body of the esophagus.

Name: Smooth muscle antibody positivity
Desc: The presence in serum of antibodies against smooth muscle.

Name: Abnormality of the female genitalia
Desc: Abnormality of the female genital system.

Name: Chronic kidney disease
Desc: Functional anomaly of the kidney persisting for at least three months.

Name: Hypoperistalsis
Desc: Reduced or inadequate peristalsis, with resultant slow passage of contents through the digestive tract.

Name: Dyspepsia
Desc: A heterogeneous group of symptoms that are localized in the epigastric region. Typical dyspeptic symptoms include postprandial fullness, early satiation, epigastric pain and epigastric burning, but other upper gastrointestinal symptoms such as nausea, belching or abdominal bloating often occur.

Name: Keratitis
Desc: Inflammation of the cornea.

Name: Stage 5 chronic kidney disease
Desc: A degree of kidney failure severe enough to require dialysis or kidney transplantation for survival characterized by a severe reduction in glomerular filtration rate (less than 15 ml/min/1.73 m2) and other manifestations including increased serum creatinine.

Name: Esophageal stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the lumen of the esophagus.

Name: Fibroma
Desc: Benign tumors that are composed of fibrous or connective tissue. They can grow in all organs, arising from mesenchyme tissue. The term "fibroblastic" or "fibromatous" is used to describe tumors of the fibrous connective tissue. When the term fibroma is used without modifier, it is usually considered benign, with the term fibrosarcoma reserved for malignant tumors.

Name: Uterine neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterus.

Name: Anterior lenticonus
Desc: A conical projection of the anterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.

Name: Aspiration pneumonia
Desc: Pneumonia due to the aspiration (breathing in) of food, liquid, or gastric contents into the upper respiratory tract.

Name: Vulvar neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the female external genital tract (vulva).

Name: Precordial pain
Desc: A type of chest pain that arises in the or under the left breast and often described as throbbing, stabbing, or burning, and lasting hours or longer. The pain may arise with or after effort, and may spread to the left arm or left side of the neck.

Name: Nasogastric tube feeding
Desc: The condition of inability to eat normally treated by placement of a thin tube through the nose into the stomach that is then used to carry food.

Name: Vaginal neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the vagina.

Name: Resting tremor
Desc: A resting tremor occurs when muscles are at rest and becomes less noticeable or disappears when the affected muscles are moved. Resting tremors are often slow and coarse.

Name: Abnormal rapid eye movement sleep
Desc: Abnormality of REM sleep. Phases of REM sleep are characterized by desynchronized EEG patterns, increases in heart rate and blood pressure, sympathetic activation, and a profound loss of muscle tonus except for the eye and middle-ear muscles. There are then phases of rapid eye movements.

Name: Axial dystonia
Desc: A type of dystonia that affects the midline muscles, i.e., the chest, abdominal, and back muscles.

Name: Orthostatic hypotension due to autonomic dysfunction
Autonomic bladder dysfunction
Desc: Abnormal bladder function (increased urge or frequency of urination or urge incontinence) resulting from abnormal functioning of the autonomic nervous system.

Name: Autonomic erectile dysfunction
Desc: Impotence (inability to develop or maintain an erection) resulting from abnormal functioning of the autonomic nervous system.

Name: Stridor
Desc: Stridor is a high pitched sound resulting from turbulent air flow in the upper airway.

Name: Central sleep apnea
Desc: Sleep apnea resulting from a transient abolition of the central drive to the ventilatory muscles.

Name: Orthostatic syncope
Desc: Syncope following a quick change in position from lying down to standing.

Name: Female anorgasmia
Desc: The persistent of recurrent difficulty, delay in, or absence of attaining orgasm following sufficient sexual stimulation and arousal.

Name: Camptocormia
Desc: An abnormal forward-flexed posture e.g. forward flexion of the spine, which is noticeable when standing or walking but disappears when lying down. It is becoming an increasingly recognized feature of Parkinson's disease and dystonic disorders.

Name: Confusion
Desc: Lack of clarity and coherence of thought, perception, understanding, or action.

Name: Neurodevelopmental abnormality
Desc: A deviation from normal of the neurological development of a child, which may include any or all of the aspects of the development of personal, social, gross or fine motor, and cognitive abilities.

Name: Disinhibition
Desc: A lack of restraint manifested in several ways, including disregard for social conventions, impulsivity, and poor risk assessment.

Name: Abnormality of vision
Desc: Abnormality of eyesight (visual perception).

Name: Oculomotor apraxia
Desc: Ocular motor apraxia is a deficiency in voluntary, horizontal, lateral, fast eye movements (saccades) with retention of slow pursuit movements. The inability to follow objects visually is often compensated by head movements. There may be decreased smooth pursuit, and cancellation of the vestibulo-ocular reflex.
Synonyms: Defective or absent horizontal voluntary eye movements

Name: Finger agnosia
Desc: An inability or difficulty differentiating among the fingers of either hand as well as the hands of others.

Name: Abnormality of higher mental function
Desc: Cognitive, psychiatric or memory anomaly.

Name: Semantic dementia
Desc: A progressive loss of the ability to remember the meaning of words, faces and objects.

Name: Retinal dystrophy
Desc: Retinal dystrophy is an abnormality of the retina associated with a hereditary process. Retinal dystrophies are defined by their predominantly monogenic inheritance and they are frequently associated with loss or dysfunction of photoreceptor cells as a primary or secondary event.
Synonyms: Breakdown of light-sensitive cells in back of eye

Name: Thick eyebrow
Desc: Increased density/number and/or increased diameter of eyebrow hairs.

Name: Optic atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the optic nerve. Optic atrophy results from the death of the retinal ganglion cell axons that comprise the optic nerve and manifesting as a pale optic nerve on fundoscopy.

Name: Synophrys
Desc: Meeting of the medial eyebrows in the midline.

Name: Coarse hair
Desc: Hair shafts are rough in texture.

Name: High hypermetropia
Desc: A severe form of hypermetropia with over +5.00 diopters.

Name: Scrotal hypoplasia
Synonyms: Smaller than typical growth of scrotum

Name: Oral cleft
Desc: The presence of a cleft in the oral cavity, the two main types of which are cleft lip and cleft palate. In cleft lip, there is the congenital failure of the maxillary and median nasal processes to fuse, forming a groove or fissure in the lip. In cleft palate, there is a congenital failure of the palate to fuse properly, forming a grooved depression or fissure in the roof of the mouth. Clefts of the lip and palate can occur individually or together. It is preferable to code each defect separately.

Name: Full cheeks
Desc: Increased prominence or roundness of soft tissues between zygomata and mandible.

Name: Micrognathia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the mandible.

Name: Polyhydramnios
Desc: The presence of excess amniotic fluid in the uterus during pregnancy.

Name: Abnormal cardiac septum morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the intra-atrial or intraventricular septum.

Name: Amelia involving the upper limbs
Desc: Amelia of one or both upper limbs.

Name: Amelia
Desc: Congenital absence (aplasia) of one or more limbs.

Name: Acromelia of the lower limbs
Desc: Shortening of the legs predominantly affecting terminal parts of the leg in relation to the upper and middle arm segments.

Name: Non-midline cleft lip
Desc: Clefting of the upper lip affecting the lateral portions of the upper lip rather than the midline/median region.
Synonyms: Non-midline cleft of the upper lip
Paramedian cleft of the upper lip

Name: Everted lower lip vermilion
Desc: An abnormal configuration of the lower lip such that it is turned outward i.e., everted, with the Inner aspect of the lower lip vermilion (normally opposing the teeth) being visible in a frontal view.

Name: Dry skin
Desc: Skin characterized by the lack of natural or normal moisture.

Name: Abnormal fingernail morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the fingernails.

Name: Hypoplastic toenails
Desc: Underdevelopment of the toenail.

Name: Onycholysis
Desc: Detachment of the nail from the nail bed.

Name: Fine hair
Desc: Hair that is fine or thin to the touch.

Name: Advanced eruption of teeth
Desc: Premature tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD earlier than the mean eruption age.

Name: Abnormality of dental morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the morphology of the tooth.

Name: Tooth agenesis
Desc: The absence of one or more teeth from the normal series by a failurento develop
Synonyms: Failure of development of some teeth

Name: Nephrocalcinosis
Desc: Nephrocalcinosis is the deposition of calcium salts in renal parenchyma.
Synonyms: Too much calcium deposited in kidneys

Name: Gingival overgrowth
Desc: Hyperplasia of the gingiva (that is, a thickening of the soft tissue overlying the alveolar ridge. The degree of thickening ranges from involvement of the interdental papillae alone to gingival overgrowth covering the entire tooth crown.

Name: Amelogenesis imperfecta
Desc: A developmental dysplasia of the dental enamel.

Name: Increased circulating osteocalcin level
Desc: An elevated level of osteocalcin in the blood.

Name: Abnormal calcium-phosphate regulating hormone level
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a hormone that is involved in the regulation of phosphate and calcium.
Synonyms: Abnormal Ca2+ PO4 regulating hormone level

Name: Renal insufficiency
Desc: A reduction in the level of performance of the kidneys in areas of function comprising the concentration of urine, removal of wastes, the maintenance of electrolyte balance, homeostasis of blood pressure, and calcium metabolism.

Name: Enuresis
Desc: Lack of the ability to control the urinary bladder leading to involuntary urination at an age where control of the bladder should already be possible.

Name: Hypocalciuria
Desc: An abnormally decreased calcium concentration in the urine.

Name: Impaired renal concentrating ability
Desc: A defect in the ability to concentrate the urine.

Name: Hypophosphaturia
Desc: An abnormally decreased phosphate concentration in the urine.

Name: Abnormality of the ureter
Desc: An abnormality of the ureter. The ureter is the duct by which urine passes from the kidney to the bladder.

Name: High palate
Desc: Height of the palate more than 2 SD above the mean (objective) or palatal height at the level of the first permanent molar more than twice the height of the teeth (subjective).

Name: High forehead
Desc: An abnormally increased height of the forehead.

Name: Convex nasal ridge
Desc: Nasal ridge curving anteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip. The nose appears often also prominent, and the columella low.

Name: Arachnodactyly
Desc: Abnormally long and slender fingers ("spider fingers").

Name: Sandal gap
Desc: A widely spaced gap between the first toe (the great toe) and the second toe.
Synonyms: Gap between first and second toe
Increased space between first and second toes
Sandal gap between first and second toes
Space between great toe and second toe
Wide space between first and second toes
Widely spaced first and second toes
Widened gap first and second toe

Name: Micromelia
Desc: The presence of abnormally small extremities.
Synonyms: Smaller or shorter than typical limbs

Name: Depressed nasal ridge
Desc: Lack of prominence of the nose resulting from a posteriorly-placed nasal ridge.

Name: Lymphedema
Desc: Localized fluid retention and tissue swelling caused by a compromised lymphatic system.
Synonyms: Swelling caused by excess lymph fluid under skin

Name: Gastroschisis
Desc: A type of congenital ventral incomplete closure of the abdominal wall in which the intestines and sometimes other organs extend freely into the amniotic fluid space through a small opening in the abdomen, usually to the right of the umbilicus.

Name: Abnormal pleura morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the pulmonary pleura, the thin, transparent membrane which covers the lungs and lines the inside of the chest walls.

Name: Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita
Desc: Multiple congenital contractures in different body areas.

Name: Abnormality of the wrist
Desc: Abnormality of the wrist, the structure connecting the hand and the forearm.

Name: Abnormality of the gastric mucosa
Desc: An abnormality of the gastric mucous membrane.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the mucous membrane layer of stomach

Name: Ulnar deviation of finger
Desc: Bending or curvature of a finger toward the ulnar side (i.e., away from the thumb). The deviation is at the metacarpal-phalangeal joint, and this finding is distinct from clinodactyly.

Name: Protein-losing enteropathy
Desc: Abnormal loss of protein from the digestive tract related to excessive leakage of plasma proteins into the lumen of the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Hypoalbuminemia
Desc: Reduction in the concentration of albumin in the blood.

Name: Abnormal circulating polysaccharide concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of a polysaccharide in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal circulating protein concentration
Desc: An abnormal level of a circulating protein in the blood.

Name: Retinal telangiectasia
Desc: Dilatation of small blood vessels of the retina.

Name: Blurred vision
Desc: Lack of sharpness of vision resulting in the inability to see fine detail.

Name: Slow decrease in visual acuity
Synonyms: Slow decrease in sharpness of vision

Name: Centrocecal scotoma
Desc: A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) located between the central point of fixation and the blind spot with a roughly horizontal oval shape.

Name: Central scotoma
Desc: An area of depressed vision located at the point of fixation and that interferes with central vision.
Synonyms: Blind spot located at fixation point

Name: Retinal vascular tortuosity
Desc: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal blood vessels.

Name: Ventricular preexcitation
Desc: An abnormality in which the cardiac ventricles depolarize too early as a result of an abnormality of cardiac conduction pathways such as an accessory pathway.

Name: Abnormality of the metaphysis
Desc: An abnormality of one or more metaphysis, i.e., of the somewhat wider portion of a long bone that is adjacent to the epiphyseal growth plate and grows during childhood.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the wide portion of a long bone

Name: Abnormality of the lower limb
Desc: An abnormality of the leg.

Name: Abnormality of the ulna
Desc: An abnormality of the ulna bone of the forearm.

Name: Abnormality of epiphysis morphology
Desc: An anomaly of epiphysis, which is the expanded articular end of a long bone that developes from a secondary ossification center, and which during the period of growth is either entirely cartilaginous or is separated from the shaft by a cartilaginous disk.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of end part of bone

Name: Bowing of the long bones
Desc: A bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the radius
Desc: A small/hypoplastic or absent/aplastic radius.
Synonyms: Absence or underdevelopment of the radius bone of the arm

Name: Hypospadias
Desc: Abnormal position of urethral meatus on the ventral penile shaft (underside) characterized by displacement of the urethral meatus from the tip of the glans penis to the ventral surface of the penis, scrotum, or perineum.

Name: Narrow mouth
Desc: Distance between the commissures of the mouth more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased width of the oral aperture (subjective).

Name: Abnormal skull morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the skull, the bony framework of the head which is comprised of eight cranial and fourteen facial bones.

Name: Oligohydramnios
Desc: Diminished amniotic fluid volume in pregnancy.

Name: Abnormality of coagulation
Desc: An abnormality of the process of blood coagulation. That is, altered ability or inability of the blood to clot.

Name: Renal hypoplasia/aplasia
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the kidney.

Name: Anencephaly
Desc: Anencephaly is a developmental anomaly characterized by a fetus that has no calvarium, with a lack of most or all of the fetus' brain tissue. Anencephaly belongs to a collective group known as neural tube defects (NTD) and is a result of the neural tube failing to close in its rostral end during fetal development.

Name: Primary adrenal insufficiency
Desc: Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands as a result of a primary defect in the glands themselves.

Name: Abnormality of the midface
Desc: An anomaly of the midface, which is a region and not an anatomical term. It extends, superiorly, from the inferior orbital margin to, inferiorly, the level of nasal base. It is formed by the maxilla (upper jaw) and zygoma and cheeks and malar region. Traditionally, the nose and premaxilla are not included in the midface.

Name: Decreased corneal sensation
Desc: Reduced ability of the cornea to respond to stimulation.

Name: Broad face
Desc: Bizygomatic (upper face) and bigonial (lower face) width greater than 2 standard deviations above the mean (objective); or an apparent increase in the width of the face (subjective).

Name: Nasolacrimal duct obstruction
Desc: Blockage of the lacrimal duct.

Name: Patent ductus arteriosus
Desc: In utero, the ductus arteriosus (DA) serves to divert ventricular output away from the lungs and toward the placenta by connecting the main pulmonary artery to the descending aorta. A patent ductus arteriosus (PDA) in the first 3 days of life is a physiologic shunt in healthy term and preterm newborn infants, and normally is substantially closed within about 24 hours after bith and completely closed after about three weeks. Failure of physiologcal closure is referred to a persistent or patent ductus arteriosus (PDA). Depending on the degree of left-to-right shunting, PDA can have clinical consequences.

Name: Delayed gross motor development
Desc: A type of motor delay characterized by a delay in acquiring the ability to control the large muscles of the body for walking, running, sitting, and crawling.

Name: Aganglionic megacolon
Desc: An abnormality resulting from a lack of intestinal ganglion cells (i.e., an aganglionic section of bowel) that results in bowel obstruction with enlargement of the colon.

Name: Decreased body weight
Desc: Abnormally low body weight.

Name: Bilateral sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A bilateral form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

Name: Concave nasal ridge
Desc: Nasal ridge curving posteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip.

Name: Prominent forehead
Desc: Forward prominence of the entire forehead, due to protrusion of the frontal bone.

Name: Choriocapillaris atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the capillary lamina of choroid.

Name: Xerostomia
Desc: Dryness of the mouth due to salivary gland dysfunction.

Name: Long philtrum
Desc: Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.

Name: Choanal stenosis
Desc: Abnormal narrowing of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
Synonyms: Narrowing of the rear opening of the nasal cavity

Name: Chorioretinal atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the choroid and retinal layers of the fundus.

Name: Dacryocystitis
Desc: Inflammation of the nasolacrimal sac.

Name: Deviated nasal septum
Desc: Positioning of the nasal septum to the right or left in contrast to the normal midline position of the nasal septum.

Name: Sleep-wake cycle disturbance
Desc: Any abnormal alteration of an individual's circadian rhythm that affects the timing of sleeping and being awake.

Name: High anterior hairline
Desc: Distance between the hairline (trichion) and the glabella (the most prominent point on the frontal bone above the root of the nose), in the midline, more than two SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between the hairline and the glabella.

Name: Smooth tongue
Desc: Glossy appearance of the entire tongue surface.

Name: Shoulder dimple
Desc: A subtype of skin dimples occurring in the shoulder region.

Name: Primary microcephaly
Desc: Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender at birth.
Synonyms: Decreased head circumference present at birth
Head circumference small for gestational age
Small head circumference present at birth

Name: Chronic constipation
Desc: Constipation for longer than three months with fewer than 3 bowel movements per week, straining, lumpy or hard stools, and a sensation of anorectal obstruction or incomplete defecation.

Name: Food intolerance
Desc: A detrimental reaction to a food, beverage, food additive, or compound found in foods that produces symptoms in one or more body organs and systems that is not mediated by an immune reaction.

Name: Corneal ulceration
Desc: Disruption of the epithelial layer of the cornea with involvement of the underlying stroma.

Name: Narrow palpebral fissure
Desc: Reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids.

Name: Ambiguous genitalia
Desc: A genital phenotype that is not clearly assignable to a single gender. Ambiguous genitalia can be evaluated using the Prader scale: Prader 0: Normal female external genitalia. Prader 1: Female external genitalia with clitoromegaly. Prader 2: Clitoromegaly with partial labial fusion forming a funnel-shaped urogenital sinus. Prader 3: Increased phallic enlargement. Complete labioscrotal fusion forming a urogenital sinus with a single opening. Prader 4: Complete scrotal fusion with urogenital opening at the base or on the shaft of the phallus. Prader 5: Normal male external genitalia. The diagnosis of ambiguous genitalia is made for Prader 1-4.

Name: Triangular face
Desc: Facial contour, as viewed from the front, triangular in shape, with breadth at the temples and tapering to a narrow chin.
Synonyms: Face with broad temples and narrow chin

Name: Sloping forehead
Desc: Inclination of the anterior surface of the forehead from the vertical more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or apparently excessive posterior sloping of the forehead in a lateral view.

Name: Wide nose
Desc: Interalar distance more than two standard deviations above the mean for age, i.e., an apparently increased width of the nasal base and alae.

Name: Glaucoma
Desc: Glaucoma refers loss of retinal ganglion cells in a characteristic pattern of optic neuropathy usually associated with increased intraocular pressure.

Name: Microphthalmia
Desc: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of one or both eyes.
Synonyms: Decreased size of globe of eye

Name: Hypothyroidism
Desc: Deficiency of thyroid hormone.

Name: Abnormality of skin pigmentation
Desc: An abnormality of the pigmentation of the skin.

Name: Dandy-Walker malformation
Desc: A congenital brain malformation typically characterized by incomplete formation of the cerebellar vermis, dilation of the fourth ventricle, and enlargement of the posterior fossa. In layman's terms, Dandy Walker malformation is a cyst in the cerebellum (typically symmetrical) that is involved with the fourth ventricle. This may interfere with the ability to drain cerebrospinal fluid from the brain, resulting in hydrocephalus. Dandy Walker cysts are formed during early embryonic development, while the brain forms. The cyst in the cerebellum typically has several blood vessels running through it connecting to the brain, thereby prohibiting surgical removal.

Name: Holoprosencephaly
Desc: Holoprosencephaly is a structural anomaly of the brain in which the developing forebrain fails to divide into two separate hemispheres and ventricles.

Name: Aortic regurgitation
Desc: An insufficiency of the aortic valve, leading to regurgitation (backward flow) of blood from the aorta into the left ventricle.

Name: Subvalvular aortic stenosis
Desc: A fixed form of obstruction to blood flow across the left-ventricular outflow tract related to stenosis (narrowing) below the level of the aortic valve.
Synonyms: Narrowing of blood vessel below aortic heart valve

Name: Abnormal lung lobation
Desc: A developmental defect in the formation of pulmonary lobes.

Name: Duodenal atresia
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the duodenal lumen, that is, an abnormal closure of the duodenum.
Synonyms: Absence or narrowing of first part of small bowel

Name: Abnormality of the upper limb
Desc: An abnormality of the arm.

Name: Myelodysplasia
Desc: Clonal hematopoietic stem cell disorders characterized by dysplasia (ineffective production) in one or more hematopoietic cell lineages, leading to anemia and cytopenia.

Name: Muscular dystrophy
Desc: The term dystrophy means abnormal growth. However, muscular dystrophy is used to describe primary myopathies with a genetic basis and a progressive course characterized by progressive skeletal muscle weakness and wasting, defects in muscle proteins, and histological features of muscle fiber degeneration (necrosis) and regeneration. If possible, it is preferred to use other HPO terms to describe the precise phenotypic abnormalities.

Name: Acute lymphoblastic leukemia
Desc: A form of acute leukemia characterized by excess lympoblasts.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the corpus callosum
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
Synonyms: Complete or partial absence of the corpus callosum
Hypoplasia or absence of the corpus callosum

Name: Corneal opacity
Desc: A reduction of corneal clarity.
Synonyms: Scarring or clouding of the cornea of the eye

Name: Increased nuchal translucency
Desc: The presence of an abnormally large hypoechoic space in the posterior fetal neck (usually detected on prenatal ultrasound examination).

Name: Stomach cancer
Desc: A cancer arising in any part of the stomach.

Name: Intestinal polyposis
Desc: The presence of multiple polyps in the intestine.
Synonyms: Growths in inner lining of intestine

Name: Vascular dilatation
Desc: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of an atery, vein or the heart.
Synonyms: Wider than typical opening or gap

Name: Abnormal cerebral vascular morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the cerebral blood vessels.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the cerebral blood vessels

Name: Dilatation of the sinus of Valsalva
Desc: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation of one of the anatomic dilations of the ascending aorta, which occurs just above the aortic valve.

Name: Congestive heart failure
Desc: The presence of an abnormality of cardiac function that is responsible for the failure of the heart to pump blood at a rate that is commensurate with the needs of the tissues or a state in which abnormally elevated filling pressures are required for the heart to do so. Heart failure is frequently related to a defect in myocardial contraction.

Name: Bacterial endocarditis
Desc: A bacterial infection of the endocardium, the inner layer of the heart, which usually involves the heart valves.

Name: Oliguria
Desc: Low output of urine, clinically classified as an output below 300-500ml/day.

Name: Abnormal left ventricle morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the left ventricle of the heart.

Name: Abnormal ST segment
Desc: An electrocardiographic anomaly of the ST segment, which is the segment that connects the QRS complex and the T wave. The ST segment normally has a duration of 80 to 120 ms, is flat and at the same level (isoelectric) as the PR and TP segment.

Name: Cavernous hemangioma
Desc: The presence of a cavernous hemangioma. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma.
Synonyms: Collection of dilated blood vessels that forms mass

Name: Subcutaneous nodule
Desc: Slightly elevated lesions on or in the skin with a diameter of over 5 mm.
Synonyms: Growth of abnormal tissue under the skin

Name: Microcytic anemia
Desc: A kind of anemia in which the volume of the red blood cells is reduced.

Name: Volvulus
Desc: Abnormal twisting of a portion of intestine around itself or around a stalk of mesentery tissue.

Name: Intestinal bleeding
Desc: Bleeding from the intestines.

Name: Abnormality of the vasculature
Desc: An abnormality of the vasculature.

Name: Bone pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to bone.

Name: Prolonged bleeding time
Desc: Prolongation of the time taken for a standardized skin cut of fixed depth and length to stop bleeding.

Name: Gastrointestinal infarctions
Synonyms: Death of digestive organ tissue due to poor blood supply

Name: Arteriovenous malformation
Desc: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries.

Name: Abnormality of the nervous system
Desc: An abnormality of the nervous system.

Name: Hemangioma
Desc: A hemangioma is a benign tumor characterized by blood-filled spaces lined by benign endothelial cells. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma (in contrast to a hemangioma with small endothelial spaces, which is called capillary hemangioma).

Name: Horner syndrome
Desc: An abnormality resulting from a lesion of the sympathetic nervous system characterized by a combination of unilateral ptosis, miosis, and often ipsilateral hypohidrosis and conjunctival injection.

Name: Hyperhidrosis
Desc: Abnormal excessive perspiration (sweating) despite the lack of appropriate stimuli like hot and humid weather.

Name: Localized skin lesion
Desc: A lesion of the skin that is located in a specific region rather than being generalized.

Name: Facial hemangioma
Desc: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, occurring in the face.

Name: Petechiae
Desc: Petechiae are pinpoint-sized reddish/purple spots, resembling a rash, that appear just under the skin or a mucous membrane when capillaries have ruptured and some superficial bleeding into the skin has happened. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to developing petechiae.

Name: Purpura
Desc: Purpura (from Latin: purpura, meaning "purple") is the appearance of red or purple discolorations on the skin that do not blanch on applying pressure. They are caused by bleeding underneath the skin. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to developing purpura. Purpura are larger than petechiae.
Synonyms: Red or purple spots on the skin

Name: Hypertrichosis
Desc: Hypertrichosis is increased hair growth that is abnormal in quantity or location.

Name: Megakaryocytopenia
Desc: A reduced count of megakaryocytes.

Name: Neoplasm of the skin
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the skin.

Name: Abnormality of the common coagulation pathway
Desc: An abnormality of blood coagulation, common pathway.

Name: Hypofibrinogenemia
Desc: Decreased concentration of fibrinogen in the blood.

Name: Pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with actual or potential tissue damage, or described in terms of such damage.

Name: Hemangioma of the lip
Desc: A vascular malformation located in the lip that is related to vascular endothelial cell hyperplasia.

Name: Unilateral renal agenesis
Desc: A unilateral form of agenesis of the kidney.

Name: Telecanthus
