Desc: Distance between the inner canthi more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, apparently increased distance between the inner canthi.

Name: Communicating hydrocephalus
Desc: A form of hydrocephalus in which there is no visible obstruction to the flow of the cerebrospinal fluid between the ventricles and subarachnoid space.

Name: Craniosynostosis
Desc: Craniosynostosis refers to the premature closure of the cranial sutures. Primary craniosynostosis refers to the closure of one or more sutures due to abnormalities in skull development, and secondary craniosynostosis results from failure of brain growth.

Name: Mild global developmental delay
Desc: A mild delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

Name: Aniridia
Desc: Abnormality of the iris characterized by, typically bilateral, complete or partial iris hypoplasia. The phenotype ranges from mild defects of anterior iris stroma only to almost complete absence of the iris.

Name: Mask-like facies
Desc: A lack of facial expression often with staring eyes and a slightly open mouth.

Name: Hearing abnormality
Desc: An abnormality of the sensory perception of sound.

Name: Scanning speech
Desc: An abnormal pattern of speech in which the words are as if measured or scanned; there is a pause after every syllable, and the syllables themselves are pronounced slowly.

Name: Abnormality of the pulmonary artery
Desc: An abnormality of the pulmonary artery.

Name: Abnormal heart morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the heart.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the iris
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the iris.

Name: Persistent pupillary membrane
Desc: The presence of remnants of a fetal membrane that persist as strands of tissue crossing the pupil.

Name: Optic nerve hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the optic nerve.

Name: Ectopia lentis
Desc: Dislocation or malposition of the crystalline lens of the eye. A partial displacement (or dislocation) of the lens is described as a subluxation of the lens, while a complete displacement is termed luxation of the lens. A complete displacement occurs if the lens is completely outside the patellar fossa of the lens, either in the anterior chamber, in the vitreous, or directly on the retina. If the lens is partially displaced but still contained within the lens space, then it is termed subluxation.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the patella
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the patella.

Name: Ureteropelvic junction obstruction
Desc: Blockage of urine flow from the renal pelvis to the proximal ureter.

Name: Retrognathia
Desc: An abnormality in which the mandible is mislocalised posteriorly.

Name: Preauricular skin tag
Desc: A rudimentary tag of skin often containing ear tissue including a core of cartilage and located just anterior to the auricle (outer part of the ear).
Synonyms: Skin tag in front of the ear
Skin tag on the posterior cheek

Name: External ear malformation
Desc: A malformation of the auricle of the ear.

Name: Enlarged cochlear aqueduct
Desc: Increased size of the cochlear duct, i.e., of a duct that communicates between the perilymphatic space and the subarachnoid space, and transmits a vein from the cochlea to join the internal jugular.

Name: Vesicoureteral reflux
Desc: Abnormal (retrograde) movement of urine from the bladder into ureters or kidneys related to inadequacy of the valvular mechanism at the ureterovesicular junction or other causes.

Name: Stenosis of the external auditory canal
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the external auditory canal.
Synonyms: Narrowing of passageway from outer ear to middle ear

Name: Atresia of the external auditory canal
Desc: Absence or failure to form of the external auditory canal.
Synonyms: Atresia of the external auditory canals

Name: Abnormality of the middle ear ossicles
Desc: An abnormality of the middle-ear ossicles (three small bones called malleus, incus, and stapes) that are contained within the middle ear and serve to transmit sounds from the air to the fluid-filled labyrinth (cochlea).

Name: Hypoplasia of the cochlea
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the cochlea.

Name: Branchial cyst
Desc: A branchial cyst is a remnant of embryonic development resulting from a failure of obliteration of a branchial cleft and consists of a subcutaneous cystic mass. Cysts are located anterior or posterior to the ear or in the submandibular region.

Name: Abnormal lacrimal duct morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the lacrimal duct, a duct that drain tears from the conjunctiva, via the lacrimal puncta, into the lacrimal sac.

Name: Submucous cleft hard palate
Desc: Hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the bony palate that are covered by the mucous membrane of the roof of the mouth. It may be possible to detect a submucous cleft hard palate upon palpation as a notch in the bony palate.

Name: Protruding ear
Desc: Angle formed by the plane of the ear and the mastoid bone greater than the 97th centile for age (objective); or, outer edge of the helix more than 2 cm from the mastoid at the point of maximum distance (objective).

Name: Wide nasal bridge
Desc: Increased breadth of the nasal bridge (and with it, the nasal root).
Synonyms: Increased breadth of bridge of nose
Increased width of bridge of nose

Name: Sparse eyelashes
Desc: Decreased density/number of eyelashes.

Name: Hypodontia
Desc: The absence of five or less teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop.
Synonyms: Failure of development of between one and six teeth
Missing between one and six teeth

Name: Widely spaced teeth
Desc: Increased spaces (diastemata) between most of the teeth in the same dental arch.

Name: Conical tooth
Desc: An abnormal conical form of the teeth, that is, a tooth whose sides converge or taper together incisally.

Name: Absent lacrimal punctum
Desc: No identifiable superior and/or inferior lacrimal punctum.

Name: Ventricular septal defect
Desc: A hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum.
Synonyms: Hole in heart wall separating two lower heart chambers

Name: Hyperconvex nail
Desc: When viewed on end (with the digit tip pointing toward the examiner's eye) the curve of the nail forms a tighter curve of convexity.

Name: Dystrophic toenail
Desc: Toenail changes apart from changes of the color of the toenail (nail dyschromia) that involve partial or complete disruption of the various keratinous layers of the nail plate.

Name: Hyperconvex fingernails
Desc: When viewed on end (with the finger tip pointing toward the examiner's eye) the curve of the fingernail forms a tighter curve of convexity.

Name: Dystrophic fingernails
Desc: The presence of misshapen or partially destroyed nail plates, often with accumulation of soft, yellow keratin between the dystrophic nail plate and nail bed, resulting in elevation of the nail plate.

Name: Ankyloblepharon
Desc: Partial fusion of the upper and lower eyelid margins by single or multiple bands of tissue.

Name: Submucous cleft soft palate
Desc: A cleft of the muscular (soft) portion of the palate that is covered by mucous membrane. Soft-palate submucous clefts are characterized by a midline deficiency or lack of muscle tissue.

Name: Amniotic constriction ring
Desc: Annular constrictions around the digits, limbs, or trunk, occurring congenitally (sometimes causing intrauterine autoamputation) and also associated with a wide variety of disorders. Constrictive amniotic bands are the result of primary amniotic rupture, which can lead to entanglement of fetal tissue (especially limbs) in fibrous amniotic strands.

Name: Lip pit
Desc: A depression located on a lip.

Name: Mandibular prognathia
Desc: Abnormal prominence of the chin related to increased length of the mandible.

Name: Abnormality of the metacarpal bones
Desc: An abnormality of the metacarpal bones.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the long bone of hand

Name: Jaundice
Desc: Yellow pigmentation of the skin due to bilirubin, which in turn is the result of increased bilirubin concentration in the bloodstream.

Name: Coma
Desc: Complete absence of wakefulness and content of conscience, which manifests itself as a lack of response to any kind of external stimuli.

Name: Limitation of joint mobility
Desc: A reduction in the freedom of movement of one or more joints.

Name: Myocardial infarction
Desc: Necrosis of the myocardium caused by an obstruction of the blood supply to the heart and often associated with chest pain, shortness of breath, palpitations, and anxiety as well as characteristic EKG findings and elevation of serum markers including creatine kinase-MB fraction and troponin.

Name: Clinodactyly of the 5th toe
Desc: Bending or curvature of a fifth toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

Name: Hemolytic anemia
Desc: A type of anemia caused by premature destruction of red blood cells (hemolysis).

Name: Leukopenia
Desc: An abnormal decreased number of leukocytes in the blood.

Name: Recurrent infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to infections.

Name: Venous thrombosis
Desc: Formation of a blood clot (thrombus) inside a vein, causing the obstruction of blood flow.

Name: Disseminated intravascular coagulation
Desc: Disseminated intravascular coagulation is characterized by the widespread activation of coagulation, which results in the intravascular formation of fibrin and ultimately thrombotic occlusion of small and midsize vessels.

Name: Hypercoagulability
Desc: An abnormality of coagulation associated with an increased risk of thrombosis.

Name: Recurrent pharyngitis
Desc: An increased susceptibility to pharyngitis as manifested by a history of recurrent pharyngitis.

Name: Pachygyria
Desc: Pachygyria is a malformation of cortical development with abnormally wide gyri with sulci 1,5-3 cm apart and abnormally thick cortex measuring more than 5 mm (radiological definition). See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.
Synonyms: Fewer and broader ridges in brain

Name: Neonatal hypotonia
Desc: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period.
Synonyms: Low muscle tone, in neonatal onset

Name: Hypsarrhythmia
Desc: Hypsarrhythmia is abnormal interictal high amplitude waves and a background of irregular spikes. There is continuous (during wakefulness), high-amplitude (>200 Hz), generalized polymorphic slowing with no organized background and multifocal spikes demonstrated by electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Muscular hypotonia of the trunk
Desc: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk.

Name: EEG with changes in voltage
Desc: EEG with abnormal amplitude.

Name: Motor seizure
Desc: A motor seizure is a type of seizure that is characterized at onset by involvement of the skeletal musculature. The motor event could consist of an increase (positive) or decrease (negative) in muscle contraction to produce a movement.

Name: Agyria
Desc: A congenital abnormality of the cerebral hemisphere characterized by lack of gyrations (convolutions) of the cerebral cortex. Agyria is defined as cortical regions lacking gyration with sulci great than 3 cm apart and cerebral cortex thicker than 5 mm.

Name: Enlarged sylvian cistern
Desc: An increase in size of the subarachnoid space associated with the lateral cerebral sulcus (Sylvian fissure).

Name: Narrow palate
Desc: Width of the palate more than 2 SD below the mean (objective) or apparently decreased palatal width (subjective).

Name: Dolichocephaly
Desc: An abnormality of skull shape characterized by a increased anterior-posterior diameter, i.e., an increased antero-posterior dimension of the skull. Cephalic index less than 76%. Alternatively, an apparently increased antero-posterior length of the head compared to width. Often due to premature closure of the sagittal suture.

Name: Abnormality of the optic nerve
Desc: Abnormality of the optic nerve.

Name: Pectus excavatum
Desc: A defect of the chest wall characterized by a depression of the sternum, giving the chest ("pectus") a caved-in ("excavatum") appearance.

Name: Hashimoto thyroiditis
Desc: A chronic, autoimmune type of thyroiditis associated with hypothyroidism.

Name: Cutis marmorata
Desc: A reticular discoloration of the skin with cyanotic (reddish-blue appearing) areas surrounding pale central areas due to dilation of capillary blood vessels and stagnation of blood within the vessels. Cutis marmorata generally occurs on the legs, arms and trunk and is often more severe in cold weather.

Name: Angina pectoris
Desc: Paroxysmal chest pain that occurs with exertion or stress and is related to myocardial ischemia.

Name: Aortic aneurysm
Desc: Aortic dilatation refers to a dimension that is greater than the 95th percentile for the normal person age, sex and body size. In contrast, an aneurysm is defined as a localized dilation of the aorta that is more than 150 percent of predicted (ratio of observed to expected diameter 1.5 or more). Aneurysm should be distinguished from ectasia, which represents a diffuse dilation of the aorta less than 50 percent of normal aorta diameter.
Synonyms: Bulge in wall of large artery that carries blood away from heart

Name: Subcutaneous hemorrhage
Desc: This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to bruising (purpura, petechiae, or ecchymoses).

Name: Hypoglycemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.

Name: Intracranial hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage occurring within the skull.

Name: Abnormal large intestine morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the large intestine.

Name: Delayed skeletal maturation
Desc: A decreased rate of skeletal maturation. Delayed skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.

Name: Meningioma
Desc: The presence of a meningioma, i.e., a benign tumor originating from the dura mater or arachnoid mater.
Synonyms: Noncancerous growth of membranes covering brain

Name: Thyroid carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a carcinoma of the thyroid gland.

Name: Short nose
Desc: Distance from nasion to subnasale more than two standard deviations below the mean, or alternatively, an apparently decreased length from the nasal root to the nasal tip.

Name: Nevus
Desc: A nevus is a type of hamartoma that is a circumscribed stable malformation of the skin.

Name: Cachexia
Desc: Severe weight loss, wasting of muscle, loss of appetite, and general debility related to a chronic disease.

Name: Hamartomatous polyposis
Desc: Polyp-like protrusions which are histologically hamartomas. These can occur throughout the gastrointestinal tract. Hamartomatous polyps are composed of the normal cellular elements of the gastrointestinal tract, but have a markedly distorted architecture.

Name: Capillary hemangioma
Desc: The presence of a capillary hemangioma, which are hemangiomas with small endothelial spaces.

Name: Abdominal wall muscle weakness
Desc: Decreased strength of the abdominal musculature.

Name: Broad thumb
Desc: Increased thumb width without increased dorso-ventral dimension.

Name: Lipoma
Desc: Benign neoplasia derived from lipoblasts or lipocytes of white or brown fat. May be angiomatous or hibernomatous.

Name: Neoplasm of the breast
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the breast.

Name: Neoplasm of the adrenal cortex
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the adrenal cortex.

Name: Anonychia
Desc: Aplasia of the nail.

Name: Aplastic/hypoplastic toenail
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the toenail.

Name: Plagiocephaly
Desc: Asymmetric head shape, which is usually a combination of unilateral occipital flattening with ipsilateral frontal prominence, leading to rhomboid cranial shape.

Name: Camptodactyly of finger
Desc: The distal interphalangeal joint and/or the proximal interphalangeal joint of the fingers cannot be extended to 180 degrees by either active or passive extension.
Synonyms: Contractures of the proximal interphalangeal joints of the fingers
Flexion contractures of proximal interphalangeal joints

Name: Nephrotic syndrome
Desc: Nephrotic syndrome is a collection of findings resulting from glomerular dysfunction with an increase in glomerular capillary wall permeability associated with pronounced proteinuria. Nephrotic syndrome refers to the constellation of clinical findings that result from severe renal loss of protein, with Proteinuria and hypoalbuminemia, edema, and hyperlipidemia.

Name: Hypogonadism
Desc: A decreased functionality of the gonad.

Name: Abnormal electroretinogram
Desc: Any abnormality of the electrical responses of various cell types in the retina as measured by electroretinography.

Name: Hypertension
Desc: The presence of chronic increased pressure in the systemic arterial system.

Name: Postaxial hand polydactyly
Desc: Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand (that is, on the side with the fifth finger).

Name: Hepatic fibrosis
Desc: The presence of excessive fibrous connective tissue in the liver. Fibrosis is a reparative or reactive process.

Name: Hypoplasia of the ovary
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the ovary.

Name: Medial flaring of the eyebrow
Desc: An abnormal distribution of eyebrow hair growth in the medial direction.

Name: Hypoplasia of the maxilla
Desc: Abnormally small dimension of the Maxilla. Usually creating a malocclusion or malalignment between the upper and lower teeth or resulting in a deficient amount of projection of the base of the nose and lower midface region.

Name: Megalocornea
Desc: An enlargement of the cornea with normal clarity and function. Megalocornea is diagnosed with a horizontal corneal diameter of 12 mm or more at birth or 13 mm or more after two years of age.

Name: Anophthalmia
Desc: Absence of the globe or eyeball.

Name: Abnormality of the ear
Desc: An abnormality of the ear.

Name: Corneal dystrophy
Desc: An abnormality of the cornea that is characterized by opacity of one or parts of the cornea.

Name: Mitral regurgitation
Desc: An abnormality of the mitral valve characterized by insufficiency or incompetence of the mitral valve resulting in retrograde leaking of blood through the mitral valve upon ventricular contraction.

Name: Tricuspid valve prolapse
Desc: One or more of the leaflets (cusps) of the tricuspid valve bulges back into the right atrium upon contraction of the right ventricle.

Name: High, narrow palate
Desc: The presence of a high and narrow palate.
Synonyms: Narrow, highly arched roof of mouth

Name: Abnormal vitreous humor morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the vitreous body.

Name: Hypoplasia of the musculature
Desc: Underdevelopment of the musculature.

Name: Abnormal size of the palpebral fissures
Desc: An abnormal size of the palpebral fissures for example unusually long or short palpebral fissures.
Synonyms: Abnormal size of the opening between the eyelids

Name: Choanal atresia
Desc: Absence or abnormal closure of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
Synonyms: Blockage of the rear opening of the nasal cavity
Obstruction of the rear opening of the nasal cavity

Name: Iris coloboma
Desc: A coloboma of the iris.

Name: Eyelid coloboma
Desc: A short discontinuity of the margin of the lower or upper eyelid.
Synonyms: Full thickness defect of the eyelid

Name: Facial cleft
Desc: A congenital malformation with a cleft (gap or opening) in the face.

Name: Spina bifida
Desc: Incomplete closure of the embryonic neural tube, whereby some vertebral arches remain unfused and open. The mildest form is spina bifida occulta, followed by meningocele and meningomyelocele.

Name: Bilateral cleft lip and palate
Desc: Cleft lip and cleft palate affecting both sides of the face.
Synonyms: Bilateral cleft lip and cleft palate
Right and left cleft lip and palate

Name: Deviation of finger
Desc: Deviated fingers is a term that should be used if one or more fingers of the hand are deviated from their normal position, either to the radial or ulnar side. A deviation of a finger can be caused by an abnormal form of one or more of the phalanges of the affected finger, or by a deviation or displacement of one or more phalanges.
Synonyms: Finger pointing in a different direction than usual

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the earlobes
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the ear lobes.

Name: Cleft upper lip
Desc: A gap in the upper lip. This is a congenital defect resulting from nonfusion of tissues of the lip during embryonal development.

Name: Abnormal eyebrow morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the eyebrow.

Name: Hand oligodactyly
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in the presence of fewer than the normal number of fingers.

Name: Camptodactyly of 2nd-5th fingers
Desc: The distal interphalangeal joint and/or the proximal interphalangeal joint of the second to fifth fingers cannot be extended to 180 degrees by either active or passive extension.

Name: Death in infancy
Desc: Death within the first 24 months of life.

Name: Macrodontia
Desc: Increased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD above mean for age. Alternatively, an apparently increased maximum width of the tooth.

Name: Postaxial foot polydactyly
Desc: Polydactyly of the foot most commonly refers to the presence of six toes on one foot. Postaxial polydactyly affects the lateral ray and the duplication may range from a well-formed articulated digit to a rudimentary digit.
Synonyms: Extra toe attached near the little toe

Name: Foot oligodactyly
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in the presence of fewer than the normal number of toes.

Name: Tibial bowing
Desc: A bending or abnormal curvature of the tibia.

Name: Short long bone
Desc: One or more abnormally short long bone.

Name: Fibular hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the fibula.

Name: Abnormal form of the vertebral bodies
Desc: Abnormal morphology of vertebral body.

Name: Short tibia
Desc: Underdevelopment (reduced size) of the tibia.

Name: Tarsal synostosis
Desc: Synostosis (bony fusion) involving one or more bones of the tarsus (calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, cuneiiform bones).

Name: Large earlobe
Desc: Increased volume of the earlobe, that is, abnormally prominent ear lobules.

Name: Hypoplasia of the premaxilla
Desc: An abnormality of the premaxilla (the embryonic structure that forms the anterior part of the maxilla) causing it to appear relatively small in size compared to the other parts of the maxilla or other facial structures.
Synonyms: Decreased size of the primary palate bone
Hypoplasia of the primary palate bone
Underdevelopment of the primary palate bone

Name: True anophthalmia
Desc: Absence of globe, optic nerve, chiasm and optic tracts. No evidence of ocular tissue on MRI scan or examination.

Name: Synostosis of joints
Desc: The abnormal fusion of neighboring bones across a joint.

Name: Dilated cardiomyopathy
Desc: Dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) is defined by the presence of left ventricular dilatation and left ventricular systolic dysfunction in the absence of abnormal loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) or coronary artery disease sufficient to cause global systolic impairment. Right ventricular dilation and dysfunction may be present but are not necessary for the diagnosis.

Name: Endocardial fibroelastosis
Desc: Diffuse thickening of the ventricular endocardium and by associated myocardial dysfunction

Name: Abnormality of neutrophils
Desc: A neutrophil abnormality.

Name: Abnormal mitochondrial morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the mitochondria.

Name: Broad forehead
Desc: Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or apparently increased distance between the two sides of the forehead.

Name: Overriding aorta
Desc: An overriding aorta is a congenital heart defect where the aorta is positioned directly over a ventricular septal defect, instead of over the left ventricle. The result is that the aorta receives some blood from the right ventricle, which reduces the amount of oxygen in the blood. It is one of the four conditions of the Tetralogy of Fallot. The aortic root can be displaced toward the front (anteriorly) or directly above the septal defect, but it is always abnormally located to the right of the root of the pulmonary artery. The degree of override is quite variable, with 5-95% of the valve being connected to the right ventricle.

Name: Genu varum
Desc: A positional abnormality marked by outward bowing of the legs in which the knees stay wide apart when a person stands with the feet and ankles together.

Name: Abnormal hip bone morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the hip bone.

Name: Hypoplasia of the zygomatic bone
Desc: Underdevelopment of the zygomatic bone. That is, a reduction in size of the zygomatic bone, including the zygomatic process of the temporal bone of the skull, which forms part of the zygomatic arch.

Name: Abnormal aortic arch morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the arch of aorta.

Name: Abnormality of female external genitalia
Desc: An abnormality of the female external genitalia.

Name: Asymmetry of the thorax
Desc: Lack of symmetry between the left and right halves of the thorax.

Name: Split foot
Desc: A condition in which middle parts of the foot (toes and metatarsals) are missing giving a cleft appearance. The severity is very variable ranging from slightly hypoplastic 3rd toe over absent 2nd or 3rd toes as far as oligo- or monodactyl feet.

Name: Abnormality of pelvic girdle bone morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the bony pelvic girdle, which is a ring of bones connecting the vertebral column to the femurs.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of pelvic girdle bone

Name: Hemivertebrae
Desc: Absence of one half of the vertebral body.

Name: Vaginal fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula of the vagina.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the hand
Desc: Small or missing phalangeal bones of the fingers of the hand.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the toes
Persistent cloaca
Desc: Developmental anomaly in which the vagina, bladder, and rectum fuse resulting in a common channel.

Name: Absent toenail
Desc: Congenital absence of the toenail.

Name: Hypoplastic fingernail
Desc: Underdevelopment of a fingernail.

Name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the hand
Desc: Fusion of two or more phalangeal bones of the hand.
Synonyms: Fused finger bones of the hand
Synostosis involving phalanges of the hand

Name: Short distal phalanx of finger
Desc: Short distance from the end of the finger to the most distal interphalangeal crease or the distal interphalangeal joint flexion point. That is, hypoplasia of one or more of the distal phalanx of finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the hand

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the toes
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the distal phalanges of the toes.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia/agenesis of distal phalanges of toes

Name: Aplasia cutis congenita over the scalp vertex
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp vertex, often just lateral to the midline.

Name: Spinal dysraphism
Desc: A heterogeneous group of congenital spinal anomalies that result from defective closure of the neural tube early in fetal life.
Synonyms: Incomplete closure of the vertebral arch

Name: Skin ulcer
Desc: A discontinuity of the skin exhibiting complete loss of the epidermis and often portions of the dermis and even subcutaneous fat.

Name: Abnormality of bone mineral density
Desc: This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone. Changes may affect all bones of the organism, just certain bones or only parts of bones and include decreased mineralisation as may be seen in osteoporosis or increased mineralisation and or ossification as in osteopetrosis, exostoses or any kind of atopic calicfications of different origin and distribution. The overall amount of mineralization of the bone-organ can be measured as the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones, usually measured by densitometry of the lumbar spine or hip. The measurements are usually reported as g/cm3 or as a Z-score (the number of standard deviations above or below the mean for the patient's age and sex). Note that measurement with this method does not reflect local changes in other bones, and as such might not be correct with regard the hole bone-organ.
Synonyms: Abnormality of bone mineralisation and ossification

Name: Chorioretinal coloboma
Desc: Absence of a region of the retina, retinal pigment epithelium, and choroid.
Synonyms: Birth defect that causes a hole in the innermost layer at the back of the eye

Name: Hypoproteinemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of protein in the blood.

Name: Abnormal hair quantity
Desc: An abnormal amount of hair.

Name: Aplasia cutis congenita
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin in multiple or solitary non-inflammatory, well-demarcated, oval or circular ulcers with a diameter of about 1 to 2 cm. Aplasia cutis congenita most commonly occurs on the scalp, but may present in the face, trunk, or limbs.
Synonyms: Absence of part of skin at birth

Name: Meningitis
Desc: Inflammation of the meninges.

Name: Congenital nystagmus
Desc: Nystagmus dating from or present at birth.

Name: Abnormality of retinal pigmentation
Synonyms: Abnormality of the retinal pigment epithelium

Name: High myopia
Desc: A severe form of myopia with greater than -6.00 diopters.

Name: Abnormal nervous system morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the nervous system.

Name: Premature birth
Desc: The birth of a baby of less than 37 weeks of gestational age.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the fibula
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the fibula.

Name: Preaxial hand polydactyly
Desc: Supernumerary digits located at the radial side of the hand. Polydactyly (supernumerary digits) involving the thumb occurs in many distinct forms of high variability and severity. Ranging from fleshy nubbins over varying degrees of partial duplication/splitting to completely duplicated or even triplicated thumbs or preaxial (on the radial side of the hand) supernumerary digits.

Name: Triphalangeal thumb
Desc: A thumb with three phalanges in a single, proximo-distal axis. Thus, this term applies if the thumb has an accessory phalanx, leading to a digit like appearance of the thumb.

Name: Abnormal aortic valve morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the aortic valve.

Name: Bicuspid aortic valve
Desc: The presence of an aortic valve with two instead of the normal three cusps (flaps). Bicuspid aortic valvue is a malformation of a commissure (small space between the attachment of each cusp to the aortic wall) and the adjacent parts of the two corresponding cusps forming a raphe (the fused area of the two underdeveloped cusps turning into a malformed commissure between both cusps; the raphe is a fibrous ridge that extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps).
Synonyms: Aortic valve has two leaflets rather than three

Name: Talipes equinovalgus
Desc: A deformity of foot and ankle in which the foot is bent down and outwards.

Name: Atrioventricular canal defect
Desc: A defect of the atrioventricular septum of the heart.

Name: Proximal placement of thumb
Desc: Proximal mislocalization of the thumb.
Synonyms: Attachment of thumb close to wrist

Name: Short thumb
Desc: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the thumb.

Name: Anomalous pulmonary venous return
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by abnormal connection of one or more pulmonary veins to the superior or inferior vena cava, the right atrium, or the coronary sinus, resulting in a left-to-right shunt of oxygenated blood.

Name: Hypoplasia of the ulna
Desc: Underdevelopment of the ulna.

Name: Caudal appendage
Desc: The presence of a tail-like skin appendage located adjacent to the sacrum.

Name: Infantile sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with infantile onset.

Name: Abnormal digit morphology
Desc: A morphological abnormality of a digit, i.e., of a finger or toe.

Name: Delayed cranial suture closure
Desc: Infants normally have two fontanels at birth, the diamond-shaped anterior fontanelle at the junction of the coronal and sagittal sutures, and the posterior fontanelle at the intersection of the occipital and parietal bones. The posterior fontanelle usually closes by the 8th week of life, and the anterior fontanel closes by the 18th month of life on average. This term applies if there is delay of closure of the fontanelles beyond the normal age.

Name: Shallow orbits
Desc: Reduced depth of the orbits associated with prominent-appearing ocular globes.

Name: Infantile muscular hypotonia
Desc: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in infancy.

Name: Thin calvarium
Desc: The presence of an abnormally thin calvarium.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the Epiglottis
Desc: This term applies if the Epiglottis is absent or hypoplastic.

Name: Milia
Desc: Presence of multiple small cysts containing keratin (skin protein) and presenting as tiny pearly-white bumps just under the surface of the skin.

Name: Basal cell carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a basal cell carcinoma of the skin.

Name: Pili torti
Desc: Pili (from Latin pilus, hair) torti (from Latin tortus, twisted) refers to short and brittle hairs that appear flattened and twisted when viewed through a microscope.

Name: Trichorrhexis nodosa
Desc: Trichorrhexis nodosa is the formation of nodes along the hair shaft through which breakage readily occurs. It is thus a focal defect in the hair fiber that is characterized by thickening or weak points (nodes) that cause the hair to break off easily. The result is defective, abnormally fragile hair.

Name: Sparse or absent eyelashes
Synonyms: Partial to total absence of eyelashes

Name: Abnormal clavicle morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the clavicles (collar bones).

Name: Abnormality of finger
Desc: An anomaly of a finger.

Name: Exostoses
Desc: An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage, and arises from a bone that develops from cartilage.
Synonyms: Formation of new noncancerous bone on top of existing bone

Name: Webbed neck
Desc: Pterygium colli is a congenital skin fold that runs along the sides of the neck down to the shoulders. It involves an ectopic fibrotic facial band superficial to the trapezius muscle. Excess hair-bearing skin is also present and extends down the cervical region well beyond the normal hairline.

Name: Abnormal mitral valve morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the mitral valve.

Name: Branchial anomaly
Desc: Congenital developmental defect arising from the primitive branchial apparatus.

Name: Asymmetric growth
Desc: A growth pattern that displays an abnormal difference between the left and the right side.
Synonyms: Uneven or disproportionate growth of one body part compared to another

Name: Smooth philtrum
Desc: Flat skin surface, with no ridge formation in the central region of the upper lip between the nasal base and upper vermilion border.

Name: Craniofacial hyperostosis
Desc: Excessive growth of the craniofacial bones.
Synonyms: Excessive bone growth of the skull and face

Name: Refractory anemia with ringed sideroblasts
Desc: A type of myelodysplastic syndrome characterized by less than 5% myeloblasts in the bone marrow, but with 15% or greater red cell precursors in the marrow being abnormal iron-stuffed cells called ringed sideroblasts.

Name: Abnormality of the tragus
Desc: An abnormality of the tragus.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the breasts
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the breasts.

Name: Lipoatrophy
Desc: Localized loss of fat tissue.
Synonyms: Loss of fat tissue in localised area
Loss of fat tissue in localized area

Name: Type I diabetes mellitus
Desc: A chronic condition in which the pancreas produces little or no insulin. Type I diabetes mellitus is manifested by the sudden onset of severe hyperglycemia with rapid progression to diabetic ketoacidosis unless treated with insulin.

Name: Midline defect of the nose
Desc: This term groups together three conditions that presumably represent different degrees of severity of a midline defect of the nose or nasal tip.

Name: Hypoplasia of the nasal bone
Desc: Underdevelopment of the nasal bone.

Name: Absent nasal septal cartilage
Desc: Lack of the cartilage of the nasal septum.
Synonyms: Failure of development of nasal septal cartilage

Name: Microtia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the external ear.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nasal septum
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the nasal septum.
Synonyms: Failure of development of nasal septum

Name: Aplasia of the nose
Desc: Complete absence of all nasal structures.

Name: Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism
Desc: Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is characterized by reduced function of the gonads (testes in males or ovaries in females) and results from the absence of the gonadal stimulating pituitary hormones: follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).

Name: Lacrimation abnormality
Desc: Abnormality of tear production.

Name: Abnormality of the sense of smell
Desc: An anomaly in the ability to perceive and distinguish scents (odors).
Synonyms: Abnormality of the sense of smell

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the nose
Desc: Underdevelopment or absence of the nose or parts thereof.

Name: Attached earlobe
Desc: Attachment of the lobe to the side of the face at the lowest point of the lobe without curving upward.

Name: Gastric ulcer
Desc: An ulcer, that is, an erosion of an area of the gastric mucous membrane.

Name: Abnormality of calvarial morphology
Desc: The presence of an abnormal shape of the calvaria (skullcap), that is, of that part of the skull that is made up of the superior portions of the frontal bone, occipital bone, and parietal bones and covers the cranial cavity that contains the brain.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the shape of calvarium
Abnormality of the shape of cranium
Abnormality of the shape of skull bones

Name: Hemiplegia/hemiparesis
Desc: Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.
Synonyms: Paralysis or weakness of one side of body

Name: Congenital muscular torticollis
Desc: A congenital form of torticollis resulting from shortening of the sternocleidomastoid muscle and leading to a limited range of motion in both rotation and lateral bending.

Name: Maternal diabetes
Desc: Maternal diabetes can either be a gestational, mostly type 2 diabetes, or a type 1 diabetes. Essential is the resulting maternal hyperglycemia as a non-specific teratogen, imposing the same risk of congenital malformations to pregnant women with both type 1 and type2 diabetes.

Name: Skin dimple
Desc: Skin dimples are cutaneous indentations that are the result of tethering of the skin to underlying structures (bone) causing an indentation.

Name: Intestinal atresia
Desc: An abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the intestine.

Name: Abnormality of mesentery morphology
Desc: Folds of membranous tissue (peritoneum, mesothelium) attached to the wall of the abdomen and enclosing viscera. Examples include the mesentery for the small intestine; the transverse mesocolon, which attaches the transverse portion of the colon to the back wall of the abdomen; and the mesosigmoid, which enfolds the sigmoid portion of the colon. Cells of the same embryologic origin also surround the other organs of the body such as the lungs (pleura) or the heart (pericardium).

Name: Open mouth
Desc: A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth.

Name: Narrow chest
Desc: Reduced width of the chest from side to side, associated with a reduced distance from the sternal notch to the tip of the shoulder.

Name: Adducted thumb
Desc: In the resting position, the tip of the thumb is on, or near, the palm, close to the base of the fourth or fifth finger.

Name: Failure to thrive in infancy
Synonyms: Failure to thrive in first year of life

Name: Rocker bottom foot
Desc: The presence of both a prominent heel and a convex contour of the sole.

Name: Overlapping fingers
Desc: A finger resting on the dorsal surface of an adjacent digit when the hand is at rest.

Name: Narrow face
Desc: Bizygomatic (upper face) and bigonial (lower face) width are both more than 2 standard deviations below the mean (objective); or, an apparent reduction in the width of the upper and lower face (subjective).

Name: Reduced tendon reflexes
Desc: Diminution of tendon reflexes, which is an invariable sign of peripheral nerve disease.
Synonyms: Absent or decreased deep tendon reflexes
Decreased to absent deep tendon reflexes
Diminished or absent deep tendon reflexes
Hypoactive to absent deep tendon reflexes
Weak or absent deep tendon reflexes

Name: Flexion contracture
Desc: A flexion contracture is a bent (flexed) joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement of joints.
Synonyms: Flexed joint that cannot be straightened

Name: Disproportionate tall stature
Desc: A tall and slim body build with increased arm span to height ratio (>1.05) and a reduced upper-to-lower segment ratio (<0.85), i.e., unusually long arms and legs. The extremities as well as the hands and feet are unusually slim.

Name: Slender build
Desc: Asthenic habitus refers to a slender build with long limbs, an angular profile, and prominent muscles or bones.

Name: Mitral valve prolapse
Desc: One or both of the leaflets (cusps) of the mitral valve bulges back into the left atrium upon contraction of the left ventricle.

Name: Intestinal malrotation
Desc: An abnormality of the intestinal rotation and fixation that normally occurs during the development of the gut. This can lead to volvulus, or twisting of the intestine that causes obstruction and necrosis.

Name: Tracheoesophageal fistula
Desc: An abnormal connection (fistula) between the esophagus and the trachea.
Synonyms: Abnormal connection between trachea and esophagus
Abnormal connection between trachea and oesophagus

Name: Congenital contracture
Desc: One or more flexion contractures (a bent joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively) that are present at birth.

Name: Abnormality of the musculature
Desc: Abnormality originating in one or more muscles, i.e., of the set of muscles of body.

Name: Crumpled ear
Desc: Distortion of the course of the normal folds of the ear and the appearance of supernumerary crura and folds.

Name: Pierre-Robin sequence
Desc: Pierre Robin malformation is a sequence of developmental malformations characterized by micrognathia (mandibular hypoplasia), glossoptosis and cleft palate.

Name: Whistling appearance
Desc: An abnormality of facial morphology characterized by a small mouth opening and constant contraction of the lips as if the patient were whistling.

Name: Abnormality of the nose
Desc: An abnormality of the nose.

Name: Dimple chin
Desc: A persistent midline depression of the skin over the fat pad of the chin.

Name: Severe global developmental delay
Desc: A severe delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

Name: Ophthalmoplegia
Desc: Paralysis of one or more extraocular muscles that are responsible for eye movements.

Name: Bilateral talipes equinovarus
Desc: Bilateral clubfoot deformity (see HP:0001762).

Name: Congenital finger flexion contractures
Desc: Multiple bent (flexed) finger joints that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

Name: Absent palmar crease
Desc: The absence of the major creases of the palm (distal transverse crease, proximal transverse crease, or thenar crease).

Name: Osteoarthritis
Desc: Degeneration (wear and tear) of articular cartilage, i.e., of the joint surface. Joint degeneration may be accompanied by osteophytes (bone overgrowth), narrowing of the joint space, regions of sclerosis at the joint surface, or joint deformity.

Name: Abnormality of the knee
Desc: An abnormality of the knee joint or surrounding structures.

Name: Methylmalonic acidemia
Desc: Increased concentration of methylmalonic acid in the blood.

Name: Flattened epiphysis
Desc: Abnormal flatness (decreased height) of epiphyses.

Name: Sclerotic vertebral endplates
Desc: Sclerosis (increased density) affecting vertebral end plates.

Name: Large for gestational age
Desc: The term large for gestational age applies to babies whose birth weight lies above the 90th percentile for that gestational age.

Name: Enlarged kidney
Desc: An abnormal increase in the size of the kidney.

Name: Wide mouth
Desc: Distance between the oral commissures more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased width of the oral aperture (subjective).

Name: Macroglossia
Desc: Increased length and width of the tongue.

Name: Prominent occiput
Desc: Increased convexity of the occiput (posterior part of the skull).

Name: Coarse facial features
Desc: Absence of fine and sharp appearance of brows, nose, lips, mouth, and chin, usually because of rounded and heavy features or thickened skin with or without thickening of subcutaneous and bony tissues.
Synonyms: Thickened facial skin with coarse facial features

Name: Abnormality of earlobe
Desc: An abnormality of the lobule of pinna.

Name: Proptosis
Desc: An eye that is protruding anterior to the plane of the face to a greater extent than is typical.
Synonyms: Anterior bulging of the globe of eye

Name: Nevus flammeus
Desc: A congenital vascular malformation consisting of superficial and deep dilated capillaries in the skin which produce a reddish to purplish discolouration of the skin.

Name: Hemihypertrophy
Desc: Overgrowth of only one side of the body.

Name: Omphalocele
Desc: A midline anterior incomplete closure of the abdominal wall in which there is herniation of the abdominal viscera into the base of the abdominal cord.

Name: Redundant skin
Desc: Loose and sagging skin often associated with loss of skin elasticity.

Name: Exocrine pancreatic insufficiency
Desc: Impaired function of the exocrine pancreas associated with a reduced ability to digest foods because of lack of digestive enzymes.
Synonyms: Inability to properly digest food due to lack of pancreatic digestive enzymes

Name: Visceromegaly
Desc: Abnormal increased size of the viscera of the abdomen.

Name: Accelerated skeletal maturation
Desc: An abnormally increased rate of skeletal maturation. Accelerated skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.

Name: Large placenta
Desc: Increased size of the placenta.

Name: Posterior helix pit
Desc: Permanent indentation on the posteromedial aspect of the helix that may be sharply or indistinctly delineated.
Synonyms: Indentation in back of outer ear
Pits in posterior aspect of ear helices

Name: Anterior creases of earlobe
Desc: Sharply demarcated, typically linear and approximately horizontal, indentations in the outer surface of the ear lobe.

Name: Subchorionic septal cyst
Desc: Cyst on the surface of the placenta consisting of amnion and chorion.

Name: Infra-orbital crease
Desc: Skin crease extending from below the inner canthus laterally along the malar process of the maxilla and zygoma.
Synonyms: Crease in skin under the eye
Groove in skin under the eye

Name: Abnormality of the shape of the midface
Desc: An abnormal morphology (form) of the midface or its components, the cheeks, maxilla, zygomatic bone, malar region, and infraorbital rims.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the shape of the midface

Name: Ureteral duplication
Desc: A developmental anomaly characterized by the presence of two, instead of one, ureter connecting a kidney to the bladder.

Name: Gonadoblastoma
Desc: The presence of a gonadoblastoma, a neoplasm of a gonad that consists of aggregates of germ cells and sex cord elements.

Name: Large fontanelles
Desc: In newborns, the two frontal bones, two parietal bones, and one occipital bone are joined by fibrous sutures, which form a small posterior fontanelle, and a larger, diamond-shaped anterior fontanelle. These regions allow for the skull to pass the birth canal and for later growth. The fontanelles gradually ossify, whereby the posterior fontanelle usually closes by eight weeks and the anterior fontanelle by the 9th to 16th month of age. Large fontanelles are diagnosed if the fontanelles are larger than age-dependent norms.

Name: Wide anterior fontanel
Desc: Enlargement of the anterior fontanelle with respect to age-dependent norms.

Name: Otosclerosis
Desc: In otosclerosis, a callus of bone accumulates on the stapes creating a partial fixation. This limits the movement of the stapes bone, which results in hearing loss.

Name: Nephrolithiasis
Desc: The presence of calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

Name: Diastasis recti
Desc: A separation of the rectus abdominis muscle into right and left halves (which are normally joined at the midline at the linea alba).
Synonyms: Gap between large left and right abdominal muscles

Name: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
Desc: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is defined by the presence of increased ventricular wall thickness or mass in the absence of loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) sufficient to cause the observed abnormality.

Name: Cardiomegaly
Desc: Increased size of the heart, clinically defined as an increased transverse diameter of the cardiac silhouette that is greater than or equal to 50% of the transverse diameter of the chest (increased cardiothoracic ratio) on a posterior-anterior projection of a chest radiograph or a computed tomography.

Name: Polycythemia
Desc: Polycythemia is diagnosed if the red blood cell count, the hemoglobin level, and the red blood cell volume all exceed the upper limits of normal.

Name: Hepatoblastoma
Desc: A kind of neoplasm of the liver that originates from immature liver precursor cells and macroscopically is composed of tissue resembling fetal or mature liver cells or bile ducts.

Name: Neuroblastoma
Desc: Neuroblastoma is a solid tumor that originate in neural crest cells of the sympathetic nervous system. Most neuroblastomas originate in the abdomen, and most abdominal neuroblastomas originate in the adrenal gland. Neuroblastomas can also originate in the thorax, usually in the posterior mediastinum.

Name: Prominent metopic ridge
Desc: Vertical bony ridge positioned in the midline of the forehead.

Name: Multiple renal cysts
Desc: The presence of many cysts in the kidney.

Name: Adrenocortical carcinoma
Desc: A malignant neoplasm of the adrenal cortex that may produce hormones such as cortisol, aldosterone, estrogen, or testosterone.

Name: Adrenocortical cytomegaly
Desc: The presence of large polyhedral cells with eosinophilic granular cytoplasm and enlarged nuclei in the adrenal cortex.

Name: Congenital megaureter
Desc: A developmental disturbance with extreme ureteral dilatation.

Name: Sleep apnea
Desc: An intermittent cessation of airflow at the mouth and nose during sleep. Apneas of at least 10 seconds are considered important, but persons with sleep apnea may have apneas of 20 seconds to up to 2 or 3 minutes. Patients may have up to 15 events per hour of sleep.

Name: Large intestinal polyposis
Desc: The presence of multiple polyps in the large intestine.

Name: Leiomyosarcoma
Desc: A smooth muscle connective tissue tumor, which is rare type of cancer that is a malignant neoplasm of smooth muscle. When such a neoplasm is benign, it is called a leiomyoma.

Name: Urogenital fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula affecting the genitourinary system.

Name: Pseudohypoparathyroidism
Desc: A condition characterized by resistance to the action of parathyroid hormone, in which there is hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, and (appropriately) high levels of parathyroid hormone.

Name: Arnold-Chiari malformation
Desc: Arnold-Chiari malformation consists of a downward displacement of the cerebellar tonsils and the medulla through the foramen magnum, sometimes causing hydrocephalus as a result of obstruction of CSF outflow.

Name: Pancreatitis
Desc: The presence of inflammation in the pancreas.

Name: Abnormal intestine morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the intestine. The closely related term enteropathy is used to refer to any disease of the intestine.

Name: Positive blood 1,3 beta glucan test
Desc: Beta-1,3-glucan is a major constituent of all of the characterized fungal cell walls, making up between 30-80 percent of the mass of the wall. It is a biomarker of fungal infections such as invasive pulmonary aspergillosis.

Name: Eosinophilia
Desc: Increased count of eosinophils in the blood.

Name: Hemoptysis
Desc: Coughing up (expectoration) of blood or blood-streaked sputum from the larynx, trachea, bronchi, or lungs.
Synonyms: Coughing up blood or blood-stained mucus

Name: Chronic lung disease
Desc: According to the definitions of the American and British Thoracic Societies, including pulmonary functional tests, X-rays, and CT scans for items such as fibrosis, bronchiectasis, bullae, emphysema, nodular or lymphomatous abnormalities.

Name: Ground-glass opacification
Desc: On chest radiographs, ground-glass opacity appears as an area of hazy increased lung opacity, usually extensive, within whichnmargins of pulmonary vessels may be indistinct. On CT scans, it appears as hazy increased opacity of lung, with preservation of bronchial and vascular margins. It is caused by partial filling of airspaces, interstitial thickening (due to fluid, cells, and/or fibrosis), partial collapse of alveoli, increased capillary blood volume, or a combination of these, the common factor being the partial displacement of air. Ground-glass opacity is less opaque than consolidation, in which bronchovascular margins are obscured.

Name: Abnormality on pulmonary function testing
Desc: Any anomaly measure by pulmonary function testing, which includes spirometry, measures of diffusing capacity, and plethysmography.

Name: Abnormal sputum
Desc: Abnormal appearance of material expectorated (coughed up) from the respiratory system and that is composed of mucus but may contain other substances such as pus, blood, microorganisms, and fibrin.

Name: Parenchymal consolidation
Desc: Consolidation refers to an exudate or other product of disease that replaces alveolar air, rendering the lung solid (as in infective pneumonia).

Name: Sinusitis
Desc: Inflammation of the paranasal sinuses owing to a viral, bacterial, or fungal infection, allergy, or an autoimmune reaction.

Name: Nasal congestion
Desc: Reduced ability to pass air through the nasal cavity often leading to mouth breathing.

Name: Pneumonia
Desc: Inflammation of any part of the lung parenchyma.

Name: Pleuritis
Desc: Inflammation of the pleura.
Synonyms: Inflammation of tissues lining lungs and chest

Name: Pulmonary fibrosis
Desc: Replacement of normal lung tissues by fibroblasts and collagen.

Name: Diffuse reticular or finely nodular infiltrations
Increased circulating IgE level
Desc: An abnormally increased overall level of immunoglobulin E in blood.

Name: Hematological neoplasm
Desc: Neoplasms located in the blood and blood-forming tissue (the bone marrow and lymphatic tissue).

Name: Chronic pulmonary obstruction
Desc: An anomaly that is characterized progressive airflow obstruction that is only partly reversible, inflammation in the airways, and systemic effects or comorbities.

Name: Hypersensitivity pneumonitis
Desc: Hypersensitivity pneumonitis involves inhalation of an antigen. This leads to an exaggerated immune response and a following inflammation of the alveoli within the lungs. The main feature of chronic hypersensitivity pneumonitis on lung biopsies is expansion of the interstitium by lymphocytes accompanied by an occasional multinucleated giant cell or loose granuloma. After exposure to the provoking antigen, following symptoms can be seen: fever, chills, malaise, cough, hemoptysis, chest tightness, dyspnea, rash, swelling and headache and can be completely reversible, based on the duration of the illness, categorized as acute (HP:0011009), subacute (HP:0011011), and chronic (HP:0011010).

Name: Hepatitis
Desc: Inflammation of the liver.

Name: Invasive pulmonary aspergillosis
Desc: Infection of the lungs with aspergillus. In the respiratory mucosa, the spores may germinate into hyphae, which in turn can invade the mucosa leading to invasive pulmonary aspergillosis.

Name: Immunologic hypersensitivity
Desc: Immunological states where the immune system produces harmful responses upon reexposure to sensitising antigens.

Name: Ocular pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eye.

Name: Periorbital fullness
Desc: Increase in periorbital soft tissue.

Name: Abnormality of the vertebral column
Desc: Any abnormality of the vertebral column.

Name: Bronchiectasis
Desc: Persistent abnormal dilatation of the bronchi owing to localized and irreversible destruction and widening of the large airways.
Synonyms: Permanent enlargement of the airways of the lungs

Name: Pleural effusion
Desc: The presence of an excessive amount of fluid in the pleural cavity.

Name: Abnormality of the skull base
Desc: An abnormality of the base of the skull, which forms the floor of the cranial cavity and separates the brain from other facial structures. The skull base is made up of five bones: the ethmoid, sphenoid, occipital, paired frontal, and paired parietal bones, and is subdivided into 3 regions: the anterior, middle, and posterior cranial fossae. The petro-occipital fissure subdivides the middle cranial fossa into 1 central component and 2 lateral components.

Name: Osteomyelitis
Desc: Osteomyelitis is an inflammatory process accompanied by bone destruction and caused by an infecting microorganism.

Name: Abnormality of long bone morphology
Desc: An abnormality of size or shape of the long bones.

Name: Unusual CNS infection
Desc: A type of infection of the central nervous system that can be regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection.

Name: Vitritis
Desc: Inflammation of the vitreous body, characterized by the presence of inflammatory cells and protein exudate in the vitreous cavity.

Name: Abnormal eosinophil morphology
Desc: An abnormal count or structure of eosinophils.

Name: Pulmonary arterial hypertension
Desc: Pulmonary hypertension is defined mean pulmonary artery pressure of 25mmHg or more and pulmonary capillary wedge pressure of 15mmHg or less when measured by right heart catheterisation at rest and in a supine position.
Synonyms: Increased blood pressure in blood vessels of lungs

Name: Low-grade fever
Desc: Mild fever that does not exceed 38.5 degrees centigrade.

Name: Abnormality of lower lip
Desc: An abnormality of the lower lip.

Name: Tetralogy of Fallot
Desc: A congenital cardiac malformation comprising pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy. The diagnosis of TOF is made if at least three of the four above mentioned features are present.

Name: Abnormality of the respiratory system
Desc: An abnormality of the respiratory system, which include the airways, lungs, and the respiratory muscles.

Name: Asymmetric crying face
Desc: Asymmetry observed in the face of a neonate or infant whose face appears symmetric at rest and asymmetric during crying as the mouth is pulled downward on one side while not moving on the other side.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia of depressor angula oris muscle

Name: Oral ulcer
Desc: Erosion of the mucous mebrane of the mouth with local excavation of the surface, resulting from the sloughing of inflammatory necrotic tissue.

Name: Retinopathy
Desc: Any noninflammatory disease of the retina. This nonspecific term is retained here because of its wide use in the literature, but if possible new annotations should indicate the precise type of retinal abnormality.

Name: Acne
Desc: A skin condition in which there is an increase in sebum secretion by the pilosebaceous apparatus associated with open comedones (blackheads), closed comedones (whiteheads), and pustular nodules (papules, pustules, and cysts).

Name: Keratoconjunctivitis sicca
Desc: Dryness of the eye related to deficiency of the tear film components (aqueous, mucin, or lipid), lid surface abnormalities, or epithelial abnormalities. Keratoconjunctivitis sicca often results in a scratchy or sandy sensation (foreign body sensation) in the eyes, and may also be associated with itching, inability to produce tears, photosensitivity, redness, pain, and difficulty in moving the eyelids.

Name: Arthritis
Desc: Inflammation of a joint.

Name: Abnormal myocardium morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the muscle layer of the heart wall.

Name: Migraine
Desc: Migraine is a chronic neurological disorder characterized by episodic attacks of headache and associated symptoms.

Name: Vasculitis
Desc: Inflammation of blood vessel.

Name: Avascular necrosis
Desc: A disease where there is cellular death (necrosis) of bone components due to interruption of the blood supply.
Synonyms: Death of bone due to decreased blood supply

Name: Recurrent aphthous stomatitis
Desc: Recurrent episodes of ulceration of the oral mucosa, typically presenting as painful, sharply circumscribed fibrin-covered mucosal defects with a hyperemic border.

Name: Increased inflammatory response
Desc: A abnormal increase in the inflammatory response to injury or infection.

Name: Myositis
Desc: A general term for inflammation of the muscles without respect to the underlying cause.

Name: Optic neuritis
Desc: Inflammation of the optic nerve.

Name: Retrobulbar optic neuritis
Desc: Optic neuritis that occurs in the section of the optic nerve located behind the eyeball.

Name: Gangrene
Desc: A serious and potentially life-threatening condition that arises when a considerable mass of body tissue dies (necrosis).
Synonyms: Death of body tissue due to lack of blood flow or infection

Name: Glomerulopathy
Desc: Inflammatory or noninflammatory diseases affecting the glomeruli of the nephron.

Name: Blindness
Desc: Blindness is the condition of lacking visual perception defined as visual perception below 3/60 and/or a visual field of no greater than 10 degrees in radius around central fixation.

Name: Pulmonary embolism
Desc: An embolus (that is, an abnormal particle circulating in the blood) located in the pulmonary artery and thereby blocking blood circulation to the lung. Usually the embolus is a blood clot that has developed in an extremity (for instance, a deep venous thrombosis), detached, and traveled through the circulation before becoming trapped in the pulmonary artery.
Synonyms: Blood clot in artery of lung

Name: Developmental regression
Desc: Loss of developmental skills, as manifested by loss of developmental milestones.

Name: Cerebral ischemia
Synonyms: Disruption of blood oxygen supply to brain

Name: Arterial thrombosis
Desc: The formation of a blood clot inside an artery.

Name: Endocarditis
Desc: An inflammation of the endocardium, the inner layer of the heart, which usually involves the heart valves.

Name: Orchitis
Desc: Testicular inflammation.

Name: Papule
Desc: A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point.

Name: Delayed ability to walk
Desc: A failure to achieve the ability to walk at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children learn to walk in a series of stages, and learn to walk short distances independently between 12 and 15 months.

Name: Diffuse cerebral atrophy
Desc: Diffuse unlocalised atrophy affecting the cerebrum.

Name: Cerebellar vermis atrophy
Desc: Wasting (atrophy) of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Dilated fourth ventricle
Desc: An abnormal dilatation of the fourth cerebral ventricle.

Name: Enlarged cisterna magna
Desc: Increase in size of the cisterna magna, one of three principal openings in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid and pia mater, located between the cerebellum and the dorsal surface of the medulla oblongata.

Name: Lactic acidosis
Desc: An abnormal buildup of lactic acid in the body, leading to acidification of the blood and other bodily fluids.

Name: Impaired visuospatial constructive cognition
Desc: Reduced ability affecting mainly visuospatial cognition which may be tested using pattern construction (for example by Differential Ability Scales, which test a person's strengths and weaknesses across a range of intellectual abilities).

Name: Encephalopathy
Desc: Encephalopathy is a term that means brain disease, damage, or malfunction. In general, encephalopathy is manifested by an altered mental state.

Name: Brachycephaly
Desc: An abnormality of skull shape characterized by a decreased anterior-posterior diameter. That is, a cephalic index greater than 81%. Alternatively, an apparently shortened anteroposterior dimension (length) of the head compared to width.

Name: Abnormality of the hypothalamus-pituitary axis
Desc: Abnormality of the pituitary gland (also known as hypophysis), which is an endocrine gland that protrudes from the bottom of the hypothalamus at the base of the brain. The pituitary gland secretes the hormones ACTH, TSH, PRL, GH, endorphins, FSH, LH, oxytocin, and antidiuretic hormone. The secretion of hormones from the anterior pituitary is under the strict control of hypothalamic hormones, and the posterior pituitary is essentially an extension of the hypothalamus, so that hypothalamus and pituitary gland may be regarded as a functional unit.

Name: Microdontia
Desc: Decreased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD below mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased maximum width of tooth.

Name: Axonal loss
Desc: A reduction in the number of axons in the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Abnormal EKG
Desc: Abnormal rhythm of the heart.

Name: Generalized amyotrophy
Desc: Generalized (diffuse, unlocalized) amyotrophy (muscle atrophy) affecting multiple muscles.

Name: Cardiomyopathy
Desc: A myocardial disorder in which the heart muscle is structurally and functionally abnormal, in the absence of coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular disease and congenital heart disease sufficient to cause the observed myocardial abnormality.

Name: Episodic ataxia
Desc: Periodic spells of incoordination and imbalance, that is, episodes of ataxia typically lasting from 10 minutes to several hours or days.n

Name: Hypoplasia of the abdominal wall musculature
Desc: Underdevelopment of the abdominal musculature.

Name: Congenital miosis
Desc: Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil of congenital onset.

Name: Cubitus valgus
Desc: Abnormal positioning in which the elbows are turned out.

Name: Hyperextensible skin
Desc: A condition in which the skin can be stretched beyond normal, and then returns to its initial position.

Name: Genu recurvatum
Desc: An abnormally increased extension of the knee joint, so that the knee can bend backwards.

Name: Slender long bone
Desc: Reduced diameter of a long bone.

Name: Spina bifida occulta
Desc: The closed form of spina bifida with incomplete closure of a vertebral body with intact overlying skin.

Name: Reduced bone mineral density
Desc: A reduction of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones.
Synonyms: Decreased bone mineral density Z score
Low solidness and mass of the bones

Name: Abnormality of the autonomic nervous system
Desc: An abnormality of the autonomic nervous system.

Name: Recurrent upper respiratory tract infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to upper respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent upper respiratory tract infections (running ears - otitis, sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis).
Synonyms: Recurrent upper respiratory and lower respiratory infections

Name: EMG: chronic denervation signs
Desc: Evidence of chronic denervation on electromyography.

Name: Severe demyelination of the white matter
Desc: A severe loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

Name: Congenital sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A type of hearing impairment caused by an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve with congenital onset.

Name: Abnormal erythrocyte enzyme level
Desc: An altered level of any enzyme to act as catalysts within erythrocytes. This term includes changes due to altered activity of an enzyme.

Name: Severe infection
Desc: A type of infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection because of unusual severity or intensity of the infection.

Name: Neck muscle weakness
Desc: Decreased strength of the neck musculature.

Name: Hypouricemia
Desc: An abnormally low level of uric acid in the blood.

Name: Respiratory failure requiring assisted ventilation
Desc: A state of respiratory distress that requires a life saving intervention in the form of gaining airway access and instituting positive pressure ventilation.

Name: Spinal cord posterior columns myelin loss
Profound sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: Complete loss of hearing related to a sensorineural defect.

Name: Appendicular hypotonia
Desc: Muscular hypotonia of one or more limbs.

Name: Myopathic facies
Desc: A facial appearance characteristic of myopathic conditions. The face appears expressionless with sunken cheeks, bilateral ptosis, and inability to elevate the corners of the mouth, due to muscle weakness.

Name: Broad-based gait
Desc: An abnormal gait pattern in which persons stand and walk with their feet spaced widely apart. This is often a component of cerebellar ataxia.

Name: Gowers sign
Desc: A phenomenon whereby patients are not able to stand up without the use of the hands owing to weakness of the proximal muscles of the lower limbs.

Name: Increased variability in muscle fiber diameter
Desc: An abnormally high degree of muscle fiber size variation. This phenotypic feature can be observed upon muscle biopsy.
Synonyms: Increased variability in muscle fiber size
Increased variability in muscle fibre diameter
Increased variability in muscle fibre size
Increased variation in muscle fiber size
Increased variation in muscle fibre size

Name: Pelvic girdle muscle weakness
Desc: Weakness of the muscles of the pelvic girdle (also known as the hip girdle), that is, lack of strength of the muscles around the pelvis.

Name: Myoglobinuria
Desc: Presence of myoglobin in the urine.

Name: Abnormality of fibula morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the calf bone (fibula), one of the two bones of the calf.

Name: Short femur
Desc: An abnormal shortening of the femur.

Name: Coronal cleft vertebrae
Desc: Frontal schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.

Name: Absent or minimally ossified vertebral bodies
Rhizomelia
Desc: Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of limbs (i.e. the femur and humerus).
Synonyms: Disproportionately short upper portion of limb

Name: Abnormal ossification involving the femoral head and neck
Synonyms: Abnormal maturation of thigh bone head and neck

Name: Limb undergrowth
Desc: Limb shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the extremities.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia involving bones of the extremities

Name: Platyspondyly
Desc: A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance between the vertebral endplates.

Name: Joint dislocation
Desc: Displacement or malalignment of joints.

Name: Laryngeal stenosis
Desc: Stricture or narrowing of the larynx that may be associated with symptoms of respiratory difficulty depending on the degree of laryngeal narrowing.

Name: Malrotation of colon
Desc: An anatomical anomaly that results from an abnormal rotation of the gut as it returns to the abdominal cavity during embryogenesis.

Name: Retinal dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the retina.

Name: Neonatal short-trunk short stature
Desc: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with congenital onset recognizable at birth.

Name: Abnormal pancreatic duct morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the pancreatic duct, which is the tubular structure that collects exocrine pancreatic secretions and transports them to the duodenum.

Name: Photosensitive myoclonic seizure
Desc: Generalised myoclonic seizure provoked by flashing or flickering light.

Name: Abnormality of mitochondrial metabolism
Desc: A functional anomaly of mitochondria.

Name: Hyperlordosis
Desc: Abnormally increased cuvature (anterior concavity) of the lumbar or cervical spine.

Name: Coronary artery atherosclerosis
Desc: Reduction of the diameter of the coronary arteries as the result of an accumulation of atheromatous plaques within the walls of the coronary arteries, which increases the risk of myocardial ischemia.
Synonyms: Plaque build-up in arteries supplying blood to heart

Name: Cerebral artery atherosclerosis
Desc: Atherosclerosis (HP:0002621) of a cerebral artery.

Name: Arterial stenosis
Desc: Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of an artery.

Name: Macroorchidism
Desc: The presence of abnormally large testes.

Name: Prominent supraorbital ridges
Desc: Greater than average forward and/or lateral protrusion of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.

Name: Broad nasal tip
Desc: Increase in width of the nasal tip.
Synonyms: Increased breadth of tip of nose
Increased width of tip of nose

Name: Maxillary lateral incisor microdontia
Desc: Decreased size of the maxillary permanent incisor.
Synonyms: Decreased size of maxillary lateral incisor
Decreased size of upper lateral incisor
Decreased width of upper lateral incisor

Name: Short philtrum
Desc: Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.

Name: Abnormal pulmonary valve morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the pulmonary valve.

Name: Hyperammonemia
Desc: An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood.

Name: Respiratory failure
Desc: A severe form of respiratory insufficiency characterized by inadequate gas exchange such that the levels of oxygen or carbon dioxide cannot be maintained within normal limits.

Name: 3-Methylglutaconic aciduria
Desc: An increased amount of 3-methylglutaconic acid in the urine.

Name: Moderate global developmental delay
Desc: A moderate delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

Name: Abnormality of the pancreas
Desc: An abnormality of the pancreas.

Name: Abdominal situs inversus
Desc: A left-right reversal (or "mirror reflection") of the anatomical location of the viscera of the abdomen.

Name: Peptic ulcer
Desc: An ulcer of the gastrointestinal tract.
Synonyms: Sore in the lining of gastrointestinal tract

Name: Colonic atresia
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the colon. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the colon.

Name: Duodenal stenosis
Desc: The narrowing or partial blockage of a portion of the duodenum.

Name: Restrictive ventilatory defect
Desc: A functional defect characterized by reduced total lung capacity (TLC) not associated with abnormalities of expiratory airflow or airway resistance. Spirometrically, a restrictive defect is defined as FEV1 (forced expiratory volume in 1 second) and FVC (forced vital capacity) less than 80 per cent. Restrictive lung disease may be caused by alterations in lung parenchyma or because of a disease of the pleura, chest wall, or neuromuscular apparatus.
Synonyms: Restrictive deficit on pulmonary function testing
Restrictive deficit on pulmonary function tests
Stiff lung or chest wall causing decreased lung volume

Name: Gastrointestinal dysmotility
Desc: Abnormal intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis, related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.

Name: Absence of stomach bubble on fetal sonography
Desc: By the 14th week of gestation it is nearly always possible to visualized the fluid-filled fetal stomach bubble on prenatal sonography. This term refers to the absence of a normal fetal stomach bubble on fetal ultrasonography performed at around 16 to 20 weeks' gestation.
Synonyms: Absence of stomach bubble on foetal sonography

Name: Bronchitis
Desc: Inflammation of the large airways in the lung including any part of the bronchi from the primary bronchi to the tertiary bronchi.

Name: Oral aversion
Desc: Reluctance or refusal of a child to be breastfed or eat, manifested as gagging, vomiting, turning head away from food, or avoidance of sensation in or around the mouth (i.e. toothbrushing or face-washing).

Name: Esophagitis
Desc: Inflammation of the esophagus.

Name: Abnormality of the genitourinary system
Desc: The presence of any abnormality of the genitourinary system.

Name: Cyanosis
Desc: Bluish discoloration of the skin and mucosa due to poor circulation or inadequate oxygenation of arterial or capillary blood.

Name: Small for gestational age
Desc: Smaller than normal size according to sex and gestational age related norms, defined as a weight below the 10th percentile for the gestational age.

Name: Vocal cord paresis
Desc: Decreased strength of the vocal folds.
Synonyms: Hoarse voice due to vocal cord paresis
Vocal cord paresis in severe cases

Name: Aspiration
Desc: Inspiration of a foreign object into the airway.

Name: Abnormal vertebral morphology
Desc: An abnormality of one or more of the vertebrae.

Name: Anorectal anomaly
Desc: An abnormality of the anus or rectum.

Name: Renal agenesis
Desc: Agenesis, that is, failure of the kidney to develop during embryogenesis and development.

Name: Coloboma
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by a cleft of some portion of the eye or ocular adnexa.

Name: Laryngeal cleft
Desc: Presence of a gap in the posterior laryngotracheal wall with a continuity between the larynx and the esopahagus.

Name: Barrett esophagus
Desc: An abnormal change (metaplasia) in the cells of the inferior portion of the esophagus. The normal squamous epithelium lining of the esophagus is replaced by metaplastic columnar epithelium. Columnar epithelium refers to a cell type that is typically found in more distal parts of the gastrointestinal system.

Name: Cleft lip
Desc: A gap in the lip or lips.

Name: Bilateral choanal atresia
Desc: Bilateral absence (atresia) of the posterior nasal aperture (choana).
Synonyms: Bilateral blockage of the rear opening of the nasal cavity
Bilateral obstruction of the rear opening of the nasal cavity

Name: Short palpebral fissure
Desc: Distance between the medial and lateral canthi is more than 2 SD below the mean for age (objective); or, apparently reduced length of the palpebral fissures.

Name: Jejunal atresia
