Desc: A developmental defect resulting in abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the jejunum.

Name: Intestinal hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the intestine.

Name: Annular pancreas
Desc: A congenital anomaly in which the pancreas completely (or sometimes incompletely) encircles the second portion of duodenum and occasionally obstructs the more proximal duodenum.

Name: Abnormal tricuspid valve morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the tricuspid valve.

Name: Pulmonary artery atresia
Desc: A congenital anomaly with a narrowing or complete absence of the opening between the right ventricle and the pulmonary artery.

Name: Tricuspid atresia
Desc: Failure to develop of the tricuspid valve and thus lack of the normal connection between the right atrium and the right ventricle.

Name: Patent foramen ovale
Desc: Failure of the foramen ovale to seal postnatally, leaving a potential conduit between the left and right cardiac atria.

Name: Transposition of the great arteries
Desc: A complex congenital heart defect in which the aorta arises from the morphologic right ventricle and the pulmonary artery arises from the morphologic left ventricle.

Name: Hypoplasia of right ventricle
Desc: Underdevelopment or reduced size of the heart right ventricle, often due to a reduced number of cells.

Name: Persistent left superior vena cava
Desc: A rare congenital vascular anomaly that results when the left superior cardinal vein caudal to the innominate vein fails to regress.

Name: Abnormality of the mandible
Desc: Any abnormality of the mandible, the bone of the lower jaw.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the lower jaw bone
Deformity of the lower jaw bone
Malformation of the lower jaw bone

Name: Heterochromia iridis
Desc: Heterochromia iridis is a difference in the color of the iris in the two eyes.

Name: Color vision defect
Desc: An anomaly in the ability to discriminate between or recognize colors.

Name: Abnormality of visual evoked potentials
Desc: An anomaly of visually evoked potentials (VEP), which are electrical potentials, initiated by brief visual stimuli, which are recorded from the scalp overlying the visual cortex.

Name: Nonprogressive muscular atrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy that does not display a progression in severity with time.

Name: Multiple lipomas
Desc: The presence of multiple lipomas (a type of benign tissue made of fatty tissue).

Name: Pneumothorax
Desc: Accumulation of air in the pleural cavity leading to a partially or completely collapsed lung.

Name: Medullary thyroid carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a medullary carcinoma of the thyroid gland.

Name: Parathyroid adenoma
Desc: A benign tumor of the parathyroid gland that can cause hyperparathyroidism.

Name: Renal cell carcinoma
Desc: A type of carcinoma of the kidney with origin in the epithelium of the proximal convoluted renal tubule.
Synonyms: Cancer starting in small tubes in kidneys

Name: Skin tags
Desc: Cutaneous skin tags also known as acrochorda or fibroepithelial polyps are small benign tumours that may either form secondarily over time primarily in areas where the skin forms creases, such as the neck, armpit or groin or may also be present at birth, in which case they usually occur in the periauricular region.

Name: Pulmonary sequestration
Desc: The presence of a piece lung tissue which is not attached to the pulmonary blood supply and does not communicate with the other lung tissue (not connected to the standard bronchial airways and not performing a function in respiration).

Name: Squamous cell carcinoma
Desc: The presence of squamous cell carcinoma of the skin.

Name: Abnormal salivary gland morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the salivary glands, the exocrine glands that produce saliva.

Name: Brachyturricephaly
Desc: Abnormal vertical height of the skull and a shortening of its anterior-posterior length, frequently combined with malformations of the occipital region.

Name: Narrow nasal bridge
Desc: Decreased width of the bony bridge of the nose.

Name: Hypotelorism
Desc: Interpupillary distance less than 2 SD below the mean (alternatively, the appearance of an decreased interpupillary distance or closely spaced eyes).

Name: Poikiloderma
Desc: Poikiloderma refers to a patch of skin with (1) reticulated hypopigmentation and hyperpigmentation, (2) wrinkling secondary to epidermal atrophy, and (3) telangiectasias.

Name: Abnormality of the carpal bones
Desc: An abnormality affecting the carpal bones of the wrist (scaphoid, lunate, triquetral, pisiform, trapezium, trapezoid, capitate, hamate).

Name: Anteriorly placed anus
Desc: Anterior malposition of the anus.

Name: Anal atresia
Desc: Congenital absence of the anus, i.e., the opening at the bottom end of the intestinal tract.

Name: Osteosarcoma
Desc: A malignant bone tumor that usually develops during adolescence and usually affects the long bones including the tibia, femur, and humerus. The typical symptoms of osteosarcoma comprise bone pain, fracture, limitation of motion, and tenderness or swelling at the site of the tumor.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the thumb
Desc: Hypoplastic/small or absent thumb.

Name: Abnormal localization of kidney
Desc: An abnormal site of the kidney.

Name: Congenital hypothyroidism
Desc: A type of hypothyroidism with congenital onset.

Name: Thyroid agenesis
Desc: The congenital absence of the thyroid gland.

Name: Abnormality of the parathyroid gland
Desc: An abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

Name: Hyperinsulinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of insulin in the blood.

Name: Increased circulating cortisol level
Desc: Overproduction of the hormone of cortisol by the adrenal cortex, resulting in a characteristic combination of clinical symptoms termed Cushing syndrome, with truncal obesity, a round, full face, striae atrophicae and acne, muscle weakness, and other features.

Name: Brittle hair
Desc: Fragile, easily breakable hair, i.e., with reduced tensile strength.

Name: Shawl scrotum
Desc: Superior margin of the scrotum superior to the base of the penis.

Name: Abnormality of the face
Desc: An abnormality of the face.

Name: Abnormality of the pinna
Desc: An abnormality of the pinna, which is also referred to as the auricle or external ear.

Name: Bulbous nose
Desc: Increased volume and globular shape of the anteroinferior aspect of the nose.

Name: Hypoplastic nipples
Desc: Underdevelopment of the nipple.

Name: Ablepharon
Desc: Absent eyelids.

Name: Breast aplasia
Desc: Failure to develop and congenital absence of the breast.

Name: Hypoplastic male external genitalia
Desc: Underdevelopment of part or all of the male external reproductive organs (which include the penis, the scrotum and the urethra).

Name: Median cleft lip
Desc: A type of cleft lip presenting as a midline (median) gap in the upper lip.

Name: Popliteal pterygium
Desc: A pterygium (or pterygia) occurring in the popliteal region (the back of the knee).

Name: Absent thumb
Desc: Absent thumb, i.e., the absence of both phalanges of a thumb and the associated soft tissues.

Name: Blue sclerae
Desc: An abnormal bluish coloration of the sclera.
Synonyms: Blue outer white part of eyeball
Whites of eyes are a bluish-gray color
Whites of eyes are a bluish-gray colour

Name: Abnormal thorax morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the thorax (the region of the body formed by the sternum, the thoracic vertebrae and the ribs).
Synonyms: Structural abnormality of the chest wall

Name: Tapered finger
Desc: The gradual reduction in girth of the finger from proximal to distal.

Name: Abnormal dermatoglyphics
Desc: An abnormality of dermatoglyphs (fingerprints), which are present on fingers, palms, toes, and soles.

Name: Deep philtrum
Desc: Accentuated, prominent philtral ridges giving rise to an exaggerated groove in the midline between the nasal base and upper vermillion border.

Name: Increased bone mineral density
Desc: An abnormal increase of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones which is often referred to as osteosclerosis. Osteosclerosis can be detected on radiological examination as an increased whiteness (density) of affected bones.

Name: Pure red cell aplasia
Desc: A type of anemia resulting from suppression of erythropoiesis with little or no abnormality of leukocyte or platelet production. Erythroblasts are virtually absent in bone marrow; however, leukocyte and platelet production show little or no reduction.

Name: Elevated red cell adenosine deaminase level
Desc: Increase in the level of adenosine deaminase (ADA), an enzyme involved in purine metabolism, within erythrocytes. ADA is involved in the catabolism of adenosine.

Name: Abnormality of the head
Desc: An abnormality of the head.

Name: Increased mean corpuscular volume
Desc: Larger than normal size of erythrocytes.

Name: Persistence of hemoglobin F
Desc: Hemoglobin F (HbF) contains two globin alpha chains and two globin gamma chains. It is the main form of hemoglobin in the fetus during the last seven months of intrauterine development and in the half year of postnatal life. In adults it normally makes up less than one percent of all hemoglobin. This term refers to an increase in HbF above this limit. In beta thalassemia major, it may represent over 90 percent of all hemoglobin, and in beta thalassemia minor it may make up between 0.5 to 4 percent.

Name: Cleft soft palate
Desc: Cleft of the soft palate (also known as the velum, or muscular palate) as a result of a developmental defect occurring between the 7th and 12th week of pregnancy. Cleft soft palate can cause functional abnormalities of the Eustachian tube with resulting middle ear anomalies and hearing difficulties, as well as speech problems associated with hypernasal speech due to velopharyngeal insufficiency.

Name: Sprengel anomaly
Desc: A congenital skeletal deformity characterized by the elevation of one scapula (thus, one scapula is located superior to the other).
Synonyms: Congenital, upward displacement of the scapula

Name: Abnormality of the thenar eminence
Desc: An abnormality of the thenar eminence, i.e., of the muscle on the palm of the human hand just beneath the thumb.

Name: Partial duplication of thumb phalanx
Desc: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the thumb. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.
Synonyms: Partial duplication of the phalanges of the thumb
Partial duplication of the thumb bones

Name: Radial artery aplasia
Desc: Congenital absence of the radial artery.

Name: Low anterior hairline
Desc: Distance between the hairline (trichion) and the glabella (the most prominent point on the frontal bone above the root of the nose), in the midline, more than two SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between the hairline and the glabella.

Name: Nonimmune hydrops fetalis
Desc: A type of hydrops fetalis in which there is no identifiable circulating antibody to red blood cell antigens .

Name: Thrombocytosis
Desc: Increased numbers of platelets in the peripheral blood.
Synonyms: Increased number of platelets in blood

Name: Acute myeloid leukemia
Desc: A form of leukemia characterized by overproduction of an early myeloid cell.

Name: Malignant genitourinary tract tumor
Desc: The presence of a malignant neoplasm of the genital system.

Name: Abnormal diaphysis morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the structure or form of the diaphysis, i.e., of the main or mid-section (shaft) of a long bone.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of shaft of long bone
Abnormality involving the diaphyses of the limbs
Abnormality of shaft of long bone of the limbs
Anomaly of the limb diaphyses morphology

Name: Short toe
Desc: A toe that appears disproportionately short compared to the foot.

Name: Coxa valga
Desc: Coxa valga is a deformity of the hip in which the angle between the femoral shaft and the femoral neck is increased compared to age-adjusted values (about 150 degrees in newborns gradually reducing to 120-130 degrees in adults).

Name: Abnormality of femur morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of the structure of the femur.

Name: Cone-shaped metacarpal epiphyses
Desc: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the metacarpal bones, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphyses are located at the distal ends of the metacarpal bones.
Synonyms: Cone-shaped end part of long bone

Name: Cone-shaped epiphysis
Desc: Cone-shaped epiphyses (also known as coned epiphyses) are epiphyses that invaginate into cupped metaphyses. That is, the epiphysis has a cone-shaped distal extension resulting from increased growth of the central portion of the epiphysis relative to its periphery.

Name: Flat face
Desc: Absence of concavity or convexity of the face when viewed in profile.

Name: Amblyopia
Desc: Reduced visual acuity that is uncorrectable by lenses in the absence of detectable anatomic defects in the eye or visual pathways.

Name: Extension of hair growth on temples to lateral eyebrow
Desc: A pattern of hair growth in which there is hair extending from the temples to the lateral eyebrows.
Synonyms: Unusual hairline with hair growth on temples extending to lateral eyebrow

Name: Visual field defect
Synonyms: Partial loss of field of vision

Name: Cystoid macular degeneration
Desc: A form of macular degeneration characterized by the presence of multiple cysts in the macula.

Name: Metamorphopsia
Desc: A visual anomaly in which images appear distorted. A grid of straight lines appears wavy and parts of the grid may appear blank.

Name: Striae distensae
Desc: Thinned, erythematous, depressed bands of atrophic skin. Initially, striae appear as flattened and thinned, pinkish linear regions of the skin. Striae tend to enlarge in length and become reddish or purplish. Later, striae tend to appear as white, depressed bands that are parallel to the lines of skin tension. Striae distensae occur most often in areas that have been subject to distension such as the lower back, buttocks, thighs, breast, abdomen, and shoulders.

Name: Short columella
Desc: Reduced distance from the anterior border of the naris to the subnasale.

Name: Vertebral clefting
Desc: Schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.

Name: Low levels of vitamin K
Desc: A reduced concentration of vitamin K.

Name: Severe postnatal growth retardation
Desc: Severely slow or limited growth after birth, being four standard deviations or more below age- and sex-related norms.

Name: Adipose tissue loss
Desc: A loss of adipose tissue.

Name: Malar flattening
Desc: Underdevelopment of the malar prominence of the jugal bone (zygomatic bone in mammals), appreciated in profile, frontal view, and/or by palpation.

Name: Otitis media
Desc: Inflammation or infection of the middle ear.

Name: Insulin resistance
Desc: Increased resistance towards insulin, that is, diminished effectiveness of insulin in reducing blood glucose levels.
Synonyms: Body fails to respond to insulin

Name: Cafe-au-lait spot
Desc: Cafe-au-lait spots are hyperpigmented lesions that can vary in color from light brown to dark brown with smooth borders and having a size of 1.5 cm or more in adults and 0.5 cm or more in children.

Name: Hypopigmentation of the skin
Desc: A reduction of skin color related to a decrease in melanin production and deposition.

Name: Decreased circulating IgA level
Desc: Decreased levels of immunoglobulin A (IgA).

Name: Decreased circulating total IgM
Desc: An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin M (IgM) in blood.

Name: Decreased circulating IgG level
Desc: An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in blood.

Name: Decreased proportion of CD4-positive T cells
Desc: A reduction in the proportion of CD4-positive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Decreased proportion of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells

Name: Decreased head circumference
Desc: An abnormally reduced head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart. Microcephaly is defined as a head circumference (HC) that is great than two standard deviations below the mean of age- and gender-matched population based samples. Severe microcephaly is defined with an HC that is three standard deviations below the mean.

Name: Recurrent urinary tract infections
Desc: Repeated infections of the urinary tract.

Name: Uveitis
Desc: Inflammation of one or all portions of the uveal tract.

Name: Oligospermia
Desc: Reduced count of spermatozoa in the semen, defined as a sperm count below 20 million per milliliter semen.

Name: Paronychia
Desc: The nail disease paronychia is an often-tender bacterial or fungal hand infection or foot infection where the nail and skin meet at the side or the base of a finger or toenail. The infection can start suddenly (acute paronychia) or gradually (chronic paronychia).

Name: Patchy alopecia
Desc: Transient, non-scarring hair loss and preservation of the hair follicle located in in well-defined patches.

Name: Recurrent herpes
Desc: Increased susceptibility to herpesvirus, as manifested by recurrent episodes of herpesvirus.

Name: Recurrent tonsillitis
Desc: Inflammation of the tonsils that has occurred repeatedly. The definition of recurrent may vary somewhat, but the criteria used recently as a measure of severity were five or more episodes of true tonsillitis per year, symptoms recurring for at least a year, and episodes that are disabling and that prevent normal functioning. In some cases recurrent tonsillitis may be related to immunosusceptibility. Evidence exists for a genetic predisposition for recurrent tonsillitis.

Name: Gastrostomy tube feeding in infancy
Desc: Feeding problem necessitating gastrostomy tube feeding.

Name: Respiratory tract infection
Desc: An infection of the upper or lower respiratory tract.

Name: Rhinitis
Desc: Inflammation of the nasal mucosa with nasal congestion.

Name: Abdominal obesity
Desc: Excessive fat around the stomach and abdomen.

Name: Severe toxoplasmosis
Desc: Toxoplasmosis is a widespread parasitic infection that is frequently asymptomatic in immunocompetent patients. However, this obligate intracellular protozoan parasite can evade the immune system and persist for the life of its host in cyst form, predominantly in the brain, retina, and muscles. Reactivation of latent cysts may occur when the immune system fails to maintain cytokine pressure, which mainly relies on gamma interferon (IFN-gamma). Toxoplasmosis is a life-threatening infection in immunocompromised patients (ICPs).

Name: Recurrent gastroenteritis
Desc: Increased susceptibility to gastroenteritis, an infectious inflammationof the stomach and small intestines manifested by signs and symptoms such as diarheas and abdominal pain, as manifested by recurrent episodes of gastroenteritis.

Name: Severe varicella zoster infection
Desc: An unusually severe form of varicella zoster virus (VZV) infection. In the majority of the cases, especially in children, varicella is a very mild infection characterised by skin lesions, low grade fever and malaise. Severe infection is characterized by manifestions including VZV pneumonia, hepatitis, meningitis, and disseminated varicella.

Name: Cheilitis
Desc: Inflammation of the lip.

Name: Torsion dystonia
Desc: Sustained involuntary muscle contractions that produce twisting and repetitive movements of the body.

Name: Low posterior hairline
Desc: Hair on the neck extends more inferiorly than usual.
Synonyms: Low hairline at back of neck

Name: Sparse lateral eyebrow
Desc: Decreased density/number and/or decreased diameter of lateral eyebrow hairs.
Synonyms: Limited hair on end of eyebrow

Name: Abnormality of upper lip
Desc: An abnormality of the upper lip.

Name: Abnormal eyelid morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the eyelids.

Name: Goiter
Desc: An enlargement of the thyroid gland.

Name: Upper eyelid edema
Desc: Edema in the region of the upper eyelid.

Name: Decreased response to growth hormone stimuation test
Desc: Insufficient responses to growth hormone (GH) provocation tests. GH deficiency is defined as a serum peak GH concentration less than 10 ng/mL on provocation with a combination of at least two separate stimulation tests.

Name: Abnormality of the radius
Desc: An abnormality of the radius.

Name: Abnormality of tibia morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the tibia (shinbone).

Name: Abnormality of the humerus
Desc: An abnormality of the humerus (i.e., upper arm bone).

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the abdominal wall musculature
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the abdominal musculature.

Name: Abnormal bone ossification
Desc: Any anomaly in the formation of bone or of a bony substance, or the conversion of fibrous tissue or of cartilage into bone or a bony substance.

Name: Abnormally ossified vertebrae
Desc: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of one or more vertebrae.

Name: Poorly ossified vertebrae
Desc: Decreased ossification of the vertebral bodies.

Name: Oligodontia
Desc: The absence of six or more teeth from the normal series by a failurento develop.
Synonyms: Failure of development of more than six teeth
Number of teeth decreased by more than six

Name: Juvenile cataract
Desc: A type of cataract that is not apparent at birth but that arises in childhood or adolescence.

Name: Short 5th metacarpal
Desc: Short fifth metacarpal bone.

Name: Supernumerary tooth
Desc: The presence of one or more teeth additional to the normal number.

Name: Uncombable hair
Desc: Hair that is disorderly, stands out from the scalp, and cannot be combed flat.

Name: Urinary retention
Desc: Inability to completely empty the urinary bladder during the process of urination.

Name: Diplopia
Desc: Diplopia is a condition in which a single object is perceived as two images, it is also known as double vision.

Name: Muscle flaccidity
Desc: A type of paralysis in which a muscle becomes soft and yields to passive stretching, which results from loss of all or practically all peripheral motor nerves that innervated the muscle. Muscle tone is reduced and the affected muscles undergo extreme atrophy within months of the loss of innervation.

Name: Mydriasis
Desc: Abnormal dilatation of the iris.

Name: Broad foot
Desc: A foot for which the measured width is above the 95th centile for age; or, a foot that appears disproportionately wide for its length.

Name: Camptodactyly of toe
Desc: Camptodactyly is a painless flexion contracture of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint that is usually gradually progressive. This term refers to camptodactyly of one or more toes.

Name: Truncal obesity
Desc: Obesity located preferentially in the trunk of the body as opposed to the extremities.

Name: Severe intrauterine growth retardation
Desc: Intrauterine growth retardation that is 4 or more standard deviations below average, corrected for sex and gestational age.

Name: Postnatal growth retardation
Desc: Slow or limited growth after birth.

Name: Thin upper lip vermilion
Desc: Height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the midline more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Synonyms: Decreased height of upper lip vermilion
Decreased volume of upper lip vermilion
Thin red part of the upper lip
Thin vermilion border of upper lip

Name: Posteriorly rotated ears
Desc: A type of abnormal location of the ears in which the position of the ears is characterized by posterior rotation (the superior part of the ears is rotated towards the back of the head, and the inferior part of the ears towards the front).
Synonyms: Ears rotated toward back of head

Name: Arnold-Chiari type I malformation
Desc: Arnold-Chiari type I malformation refers to a relatively mild degree of herniation of the posteroinferior region of the cerebellum (the cerebellar tonsils) into the cervical canal with little or no displacement of the fourth ventricle.

Name: Camptodactyly
Desc: The distal interphalangeal joint and/or the proximal interphalangeal joint of the fingers or toes cannot be extended to 180 degrees by either active or passive extension.
Synonyms: Permanent flexion of the finger or toe

Name: Long eyelashes
Desc: Mid upper eyelash length >10 mm or increased length of the eyelashes (subjective).

Name: Pericardial effusion
Desc: Accumulation of fluid within the pericardium.

Name: J-shaped sella turcica
Desc: A deformity of the sella turcica whereby the sella extends further anterior than normal such that the anterior clinoid process appears to overhang it, giving the appearance of the letter J on imaging of the skull.

Name: Breast hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the breast.

Name: Supernumerary ribs
Desc: The presence of more than 12 rib pairs.

Name: Reduced arm span
Desc: Decreased length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle).

Name: Abnormal distal phalanx morphology of finger
Desc: Any anomaly of distal phalanx of finger.
Synonyms: Abnormal terminal phalanges of the hand
Abnormality of the distal phalanges of the hand
Abnormality of the distal phalanx of finger
Abnormality of the outermost finger bone

Name: Short phalanx of finger
Desc: Short (hypoplastic) phalanx of finger, affecting one or more phalanges.

Name: Mesomelia
Desc: Shortening of the middle parts of the limbs (forearm and lower leg) in relation to the upper and terminal segments.
Synonyms: Disproportionately short middle portion of limb

Name: Hernia of the abdominal wall
Desc: The presence of a hernia in the abdominal wall.

Name: Long thorax
Desc: Increased inferior to superior extent of the thorax.

Name: Radial club hand
Desc: Wrist is bent inward toward the thumb because of a congenital defect associated with shortening or absence of the radius.

Name: Short metatarsal
Desc: Diminished length of a metatarsal bone, with resultant proximal displacement of the associated toe.

Name: Recurrent skin infections
Desc: Infections of the skin that happen multiple times.

Name: Abnormal hair morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the hair.

Name: Abnormality of the nail
Desc: Abnormality of the nail.

Name: Lichenification
Desc: Thickening and hardening of the epidermis seen with exaggeration of normal skin lines.

Name: Pointed chin
Desc: A marked tapering of the lower face to the chin.

Name: Absent fingernail
Desc: Absence of a fingernail.

Name: Short distal phalanx of toe
Desc: Short distance from the end of the toe to the most distal interphalangeal crease or distal interphalangeal joint flexion point, i.e., abnormally short distal phalanx of toe.

Name: Hypoplastic fifth fingernail
Desc: A nail of the fifth finger that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped nail of little finger.

Name: Toenail dysplasia
Desc: An abnormality of the development of the toenails.

Name: Mild short stature
Desc: A mild degree of short stature, more than -2 SD but not more than -3 SD from mean corrected for age and sex.

Name: Short thorax
Desc: Reduced inferior to superior extent of the thorax.
Synonyms: Shorter than typical length between neck and abdomen

Name: Bifid scrotum
Desc: Midline indentation or cleft of the scrotum.

Name: Anosmia
Desc: An inability to perceive odors. This is a general term describing inability to smell arising in any part of the process of smelling from absorption of odorants into the nasal mucous overlying the olfactory epithelium, diffusion to the cilia, binding to olfactory receptor sites, generation of action potentials in olfactory neurons, and perception of a smell.

Name: Cholestasis
Desc: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts.
Synonyms: Slowed or blocked flow of bile from liver

Name: Intrahepatic biliary atresia
Desc: Atresia in the intrahepatic bile duct.

Name: Microcornea
Desc: A congenital abnormality of the cornea in which the cornea and the anterior segment of the eye are smaller than normal. The horizontal diameter of the cornea does not reach 10 mm even in adulthood.
Synonyms: Cornea of eye less than 10mm in diameter

Name: Nasal speech
Desc: A type of speech characterized by the presence of an abnormally increased nasal airflow during speech.

Name: Postauricular pit
Desc: Benign congenital lesion of the postauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.

Name: Preauricular pit
Desc: Small indentation anterior to the insertion of the ear.
Synonyms: Pit in front of the ear

Name: Supraauricular pit
Desc: Benign congenital lesion of the supraauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.

Name: Upper lip pit
Desc: Depression located on the vermilion of the upper lip, usually paramedian.

Name: Bifid uvula
Desc: Uvula separated into two parts most easily seen at the tip.

Name: Penoscrotal hypospadias
Desc: A severe form of hypospadias in which the urethral opening is located at the junction of the penis and scrotum.

Name: Abnormal sella turcica morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the sella turcica, a saddle-shaped depression in the sphenoid bone at the base of the human skull.

Name: Thickened calvaria
Desc: The presence of an abnormally thick calvaria.

Name: Abnormality of the vertebral spinous processes
Abnormal dentin morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of dentin.

Name: Advanced pneumatization of the mastoid process
Desc: An abnormally advanced degree of pneumatization (i.e., formation of air cells) in the mastoid process with respect to age-dependent norms.

Name: Blepharochalasis
Desc: Blepharochalasis is characterized by recurrent, non-painful, nonerythematous episodes of eyelid edema. It has been divided into hypertrophic and atrophic forms. In the hypertrophic form recurrent edema results in orbital fat herniation through a weakened orbital septum. Most patients who have blepharochalasis present in an atrophic condition with atrophy of redundant eyelid skin and superior nasal fat pads.

Name: Rootless teeth
Synonyms: Tooth with dentin dysplasia type i

Name: Mixed hearing impairment
Desc: A type of hearing loss resulting from a combination of conductive hearing impairment and sensorineural hearing impairment.

Name: Abnormality of the cervical spine
Desc: Any abnormality of the cervical vertebral column.

Name: Premature loss of teeth
Desc: Exfoliation of a tooth more than 2 SD earlier than the normal age for the deciduous teeth and not related to traume or neglect. Exfoliation of a permanent tooth is per se abnormal.

Name: Ureteral stenosis
Desc: The presence of a stenotic, i.e., constricted ureter.

Name: Absent external genitalia
Desc: Lack of external genitalia in a male or female individual.

Name: Absent nipple
Desc: Congenital failure to develop, and absence of, the nipple.

Name: Bladder exstrophy
Desc: Eversion of the posterior bladder wall through the congenitally absent lower anterior abdominal wall and anterior bladder wall.

Name: Upper limb peromelia
Desc: Peromelia affecting only the upper limbs. That is, the distal parts of the arm are missing leading to stump formation.

Name: Amelia involving the lower limbs
Desc: Amelia of one or both legs.

Name: Micropenis
Desc: Abnormally small penis. At birth, the normal penis is about 3 cm (stretched length from pubic tubercle to tip of penis) with micropenis less than 2.0-2.5 cm.

Name: Chorea
Desc: Chorea (Greek for 'dance') refers to widespread arrhythmic involuntary movements of a forcible, jerky and restless fashion. It is a random-appearing sequence of one or more discrete involuntary movements or movement fragments. Movements appear random because of variability in timing, duration or location. Each movement may have a distinct start and end. However, movements may be strung together and thus may appear to flow randomly from one muscle group to another. Chorea can involve the trunk, neck, face, tongue, and extremities.

Name: Drowsiness
Desc: Excessive daytime sleepiness.

Name: Poor head control
Desc: Difficulty to maintain correct position of the head while standing or sitting.

Name: Hyperkinetic movements
Desc: Motor hyperactivity with excessive movement of muscles of the body as a whole.

Name: Right bundle branch block
Desc: A conduction block of the right branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a prolongation of the QRS complex (greater than 0.12 s) with delayed activation of the right ventricle and terminal delay on the EKG.

Name: ST segment elevation
Desc: An electrocardiographic anomaly in which the ST segment is observed to be located superior to the isoelectric line.

Name: Tachycardia
Desc: A rapid heartrate that exceeds the range of the normal resting heartrate for age.

Name: Ventricular fibrillation
Desc: Uncontrolled contractions of muscles fibers in the left ventricle not producing contraction of the left ventricle. Ventricular fibrillation usually begins with a ventricular premature contraction and a short run of rapid ventricular tachycardia degenerating into uncoordinating ventricular fibrillations.

Name: Paroxysmal ventricular tachycardia
Desc: Episodes of ventricular tachycardia that have a sudden onset and ending.

Name: Supraventricular tachycardia
Desc: Supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) is an abnormally increased heart rate (over 100 beats per minute at rest) with origin above the level of the ventricles.

Name: Sick sinus syndrome
Desc: An abnormality involving the generation of the action potential by the sinus node and is characterized by an atrial rate inappropriate for physiological requirements. Manifestations include severe sinus bradycardia, sinus pauses or arrest, sinus node exit block, chronic atrial tachyarrhythmias, alternating periods of atrial bradyarrhythmias and tachyarrhythmias, and inappropriate responses of heart rate during exercise or stress.

Name: First degree atrioventricular block
Desc: Delay of conduction through the atrioventricular node, which is manifested as prolongation of the PR interval in the electrocardiogram (EKG). All atrial impulses reach the ventricles.

Name: Trifascicular block
Desc: Abnormal conduction in all three divisions of the intraventricular conducting tissue.

Name: Hypoplastic labia majora
Desc: Undergrowth of the outer labia.

Name: Fibrous syngnathia
Desc: Complete or nearly complete soft tissue fusion of the alveolar ridges.

Name: Leukocytosis
Desc: An abnormal increase in the number of leukocytes in the blood.

Name: Elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate
Desc: An increased erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). The ESR is a test that measures the distance that erythrocytes have fallen after one hour in a vertical column of anticoagulated blood under the influence of gravity. The ESR is a nonspecific finding. An elevation may indicate inflammation or may be caused by any condition that elevates fibrinogen.

Name: Neutrophilia
Desc: Increased number of neutrophils circulating in blood.

Name: Crackles
Desc: Crackles are discontinuous, explosive, and nonmusical adventitious lung sounds normally heard in inspiration and sometimes during expiration. Crackles are usually classified as fine and coarse crackles based on their duration, loudness, pitch, timing in the respiratory cycle, and relationship to coughing and changing body position.

Name: Nonproductive cough
Desc: A cough that does not produce phlegm or mucus.

Name: Elevated circulating C-reactive protein concentration
Desc: An abnormal elevation of the C-reactive protein level in the blood circulation.

Name: Wheezing
Desc: A high-pitched whistling sound associated with labored breathing.

Name: Bronchial breath sound
Desc: Bronchial breath sounds contain much higher frequency components than normal breath sounds due to alteration of the low pass filtering function of the alveoli, as occurs in consolidation. It is loud, hollow, and high pitch. Expiratory phase is longer than inspiratory phase with the inspiratory-expiratory ratio (I:E) changing from normal 3:1 to 1:2. There is distinct pause between inspiration and expiration due to absent alveolar phase. It is associated with whispering pectoriloquy.

Name: Hypoxemia
Desc: An abnormally low level of blood oxygen.

Name: Pneumomediastinum
Desc: The presence of free air in the mediastinum.

Name: Abnormality of the liver
Desc: An abnormality of the liver.

Name: Increased circulating IgG level
Desc: An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin G in blood.

Name: Abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract
Desc: An abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Abnormality of hepatobiliary system physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of the hepatobiliary system

Name: Asthenia
Desc: A state characterized by a feeling of weakness and loss of strength leading to a generalized weakness of the body.

Name: Epididymitis
Desc: The presence of inflammation of the epididymis.

Name: Glomerulonephritis
Desc: Inflammation of the renal glomeruli.

Name: Abnormality of the skin
Desc: An abnormality of the skin.

Name: Hypersplenism
Desc: A malfunctioning of the spleen in which it prematurely destroys red blood cells.

Name: Morphological central nervous system abnormality
Desc: A structural abnormality of the central nervous system.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the central nervous system
Morphological abnormality of the central nervous system

Name: Rheumatoid factor positive
Desc: The presence in the serum of an autoantibody directed against the Fc portion of IgG.

Name: Increased circulating IgM level
Desc: An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin M in blood.

Name: Spontaneous abortion
Desc: A pregnancy that ends at a stage in which the fetus is incapable of surviving on its own, defined as the spontaneous loss of a fetus before the 20th week of pregnancy.

Name: Sacroiliac arthritis
Desc: Inflammation of the sacroiliac joint, generally accompanied by lower back pain.

Name: Chills
Desc: A sudden sensation of feeling cold.

Name: Cutaneous cyst
Desc: A hollow mass located in the skin that is surrounded by an epithelium-lined wall and is well demarcated from the adjacent tissue. Cysts are often said to be sac-like and may contain serous liquid or semisolid material.

Name: Erythematous papule
Desc: A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid that is reddish (erythematous) in color.

Name: Granuloma
Desc: A compact, organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes, which may be but is not necessarily accompanied by accessory features such as necrosis.

Name: Liver abscess
Desc: The presence of an abscess of the liver.

Name: Abnormality of the peripheral nervous system
Desc: Any abnormality of the part of the nervous system that consists of the nerves and ganglia outside of the brain and spinal cord.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the peripheral nervous system

Name: Thrombophlebitis
Desc: Inflammation of a vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein).

Name: Arteritis
Desc: Arterial inflammation.

Name: Anterior uveitis
Desc: Inflammation of the uveal tract in which the primary site of inflammation is the anterior chamber.

Name: Chorioretinitis
Desc: An inflammation of the choroid and retina.

Name: Myocarditis
Desc: Inflammation of the myocardium.

Name: Lung abscess
Desc: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in lung parenchyma, which leads to a cavity, and after formation of bronchopulmonary fistula, can manifest as an air-fluid level inside the cavity.

Name: Pulmonary granulomatosis
Desc: The presence of multiple granulomata (small nodular inflammatory lesions containing grouped mononuclear phagocytes) in the lung.

Name: Abnormal cranial nerve physiology
Desc: A functional abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.

Name: Intrarenal abscess
Desc: An encapsulated collection of pus and necrotic material within the renal parenchyma. The destruction of renal parenchyma is associated with suppurative/neutrophil-rich inflammation and necrosis.

Name: Abnormality of the spleen
Desc: An abnormality of the spleen.

Name: Hallux valgus
Desc: Lateral deviation of the great toe (i.e., in the direction of the little toe).

Name: Esophageal atresia
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the esophagus such that the esophagus ends in a blind pouch rather than connecting to the stomach.
Synonyms: Birth defect in which part of esophagus did not develop
Birth defect in which part of oesophagus did not develop

Name: Deviation of the 2nd finger
Desc: Displacement of the 2nd finger from its normal position.

Name: Osteopoikilosis
Desc: Osteopoikilosis is a benign, asymptomatic sclerotic dysplasia of the bones. It affects both male and female and may be seen at any age. Radiographically sclerotic circular or ovoid lesions are usually symmetrically distributed in a periarticular location. Lesions can increase or decrease in size and number in serial radiographs or even disappear and do not have increased bone radiotracer uptake.

Name: Connective tissue nevi
Desc: Connective tissue nevi are hamartomas in which one or several components of the dermis is altered.

Name: Skeletal dysplasia
Desc: A general term describing features characterized by abnormal development of bones and connective tissues.

Name: Generalized osteosclerosis
Desc: An abnormal increase of bone mineral density with generalized involvement of the skeleton.
Synonyms: Increased bone density in skeletal bones

Name: Hyperostosis
Desc: Excessive growth or abnormal thickening of bone tissue.

Name: Scleroderma
Desc: A chronic autoimmune phenomenon characterized by fibrosis (or hardening) and vascular alterations of the skin.

Name: Recurrent fractures
Desc: The repeated occurrence of bone fractures (implying an abnormally increased tendency for fracture).

Name: Generalized limb muscle atrophy
Desc: Generalized (unlocalized) atrophy affecting muscles of the limbs in both proximal and distal locations.
Synonyms: Generalised muscle atrophy, proximal and distal
Generalized muscle atrophy, proximal and distal

Name: Abnormal axial skeleton morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum.

Name: Cutaneous finger syndactyly
Desc: A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints, or a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two fingers that lies significantly distal to the flexion crease that overlies the metacarpophalangeal joint of the adjacent fingers.

Name: Renal hypoplasia
Desc: Hypoplasia of the kidney.

Name: Microglossia
Desc: Decreased length and width of the tongue.

Name: Microretrognathia
Desc: A form of developmental hypoplasia of the mandible in which the mandible is mislocalised posteriorly.

Name: Abnormality of chromosome segregation
Desc: An abnormality of chromosome segregation.

Name: Oligodactyly
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in the presence of fewer than the normal number of digits.

Name: Accessory oral frenulum
Desc: Extra fold of tissue extending from the alveolar ridge to the inner surface of the upper or lower lip.

Name: Trigonocephaly
Desc: Wedge-shaped, or triangular head, with the apex of the triangle at the midline of the forehead and the base of the triangle at the occiput.

Name: Sacral dimple
Desc: A cutaneous indentation resulting from tethering of the skin to underlying structures (bone) of the intergluteal cleft.

Name: Hand polydactyly
Desc: A kind of polydactyly characterized by the presence of a supernumerary finger or fingers.

Name: Dislocated radial head
Desc: A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint.

Name: Abnormality of the anus
Desc: Abnormality of the anal canal.

Name: Female pseudohermaphroditism
Desc: Hermaphroditism refers to a discrepancy between the morphology of the gonads and that of the external genitalia. In female pseudohermaphroditism, the genotype is female (XX) and the gonads are ovaries, but the external genitalia are virilized.

Name: Abnormal hair pattern
Desc: An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.

Name: Distal renal tubular acidosis
Desc: A type of renal tubular acidosis characterized by a failure of acid secretion by the alpha intercalated cells of the cortical collecting duct of the distal nephron. The urine cannot be acidified below a pH of 5.3, associated with acidemia and hypokalemia.

Name: Portal hypertension
Desc: Increased pressure in the portal vein.

Name: Esophageal varix
Desc: Extreme dilation of the submucusoal veins in the lower portion of the esophagus.

Name: Peritonitis
Desc: Inflammation of the peritoneum.

Name: Intestinal obstruction
Desc: Blockage or impairment of the normal flow of the contents of the intestine towards the anal canal.

Name: Acute hepatic failure
Desc: Hepatic failure refers to the inability of the liver to perform its normal synthetic and metabolic functions, which can result in coagulopathy and alteration in the mental status of a previously healthy individual. Hepatic failure is defined as acute if there is onset of encephalopathy within 8 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a patient with a previously healthy liver.

Name: Calvarial hyperostosis
Desc: Excessive growth of the calvaria.

Name: Cortical irregularity
Desc: An abnormal irregularity of cortical bone.

Name: Cortical thickening of long bone diaphyses
Desc: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the diaphyseal region of long bones.

Name: Periosteal thickening of long tubular bones
Desc: Thickening of the periosteum of long bone.

Name: Cellulitis
Desc: A bacterial infection and inflammation of the skin und subcutaneous tissues.

Name: Cystic hygroma
Desc: A cystic lymphatic lesion of the neck.

Name: Pancreatic cysts
Desc: A cyst of the pancreas that possess a lining of mucous epithelium.

Name: Clubbing of toes
Desc: Terminal broadening of the toes (distal phalanges of the toes).

Name: Septate vagina
Desc: The presence of a vaginal septum, thereby creating a vaginal duplication. The septum is longitudinal in the majority of cases.

Name: Abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
Desc: An altered ability of any enzyme or their cofactors to act as catalysts. This term includes changes due to altered levels of an enzyme.

Name: Chronic infection
Desc: Presence of a protracted or persistent infection by a pathogen potentially related to an underlying abnormality of the immune system that is not able to clear the infection.

Name: Increased urinary taurine
Desc: Increased concentration of taurine in the urine.

Name: Aminoaciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of an amino acid in the urine.
Synonyms: Increased levels of animo acids in urine

Name: Short 2nd toe
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the second toe.

Name: Patellar hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the patella.

Name: Short 3rd toe
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the third toe.

Name: Short 5th toe
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the fifth toe.

Name: Dental malocclusion
Desc: Dental malocclusion refers to an abnormality of the occlusion, or alignment, of the teeth and the way the upper and lower teeth fit together, resulting in overcrowding of teeth or in abnormal bite patterns.
Synonyms: Incorrect relation between upper and lower dental arches
Malalignment of upper and lower dental arches
Misalignment of upper and lower dental arches

Name: Pectus carinatum
Desc: A deformity of the chest caused by overgrowth of the ribs and characterized by protrusion of the sternum.

Name: Scapular winging
Desc: Abnormal protrusion of the scapula away from the surface of the back.

Name: Abnormality of dental eruption
Desc: An abnormality of tooth eruption.

Name: Underdeveloped supraorbital ridges
Desc: Flatness of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.

Name: Craniofacial osteosclerosis
Desc: Abnormally increased density of craniofacial bone tissue.

Name: Abnormal subcutaneous fat tissue distribution
Synonyms: Abnormal fat tissue distribution below the skin

Name: Elevated aldolase level
Desc: An increased concentration of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase in the serum.

Name: Metaphyseal dysplasia
Desc: The presence of dysplastic regions in metaphyseal regions.

Name: Partial atrioventricular canal defect
Desc: A specific combination of heart defects including a primum atrial septal defect and cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet. There is not an inlet ventricular septal defect present. There are two valve annuluses and two valve orifices.

Name: Exercise-induced muscle fatigue
Desc: An abnormally increased tendency towards muscle fatigue induced by physical exercise.

Name: Aortic valve stenosis
Desc: The presence of a stenosis (narrowing) of the aortic valve.

Name: Atrial arrhythmia
Desc: A type of supraventricular tachycardia in which the atria are the principal site of electrophysiologic disturbance.

Name: Double outlet right ventricle
Desc: Double outlet right ventricle (DORV) is a type of ventriculoarterial connection in which both great vessels arise entirely or predominantly from the right ventricle.

Name: Hypoplastic left heart
Desc: Underdevelopment of the left side of the heart. May include atresia of the aortic or mitral orifice and hypoplasia of the ascending aorta.

Name: Atrial flutter
Desc: A type of atrial arrhythmia characterized by atrial rates of between 240 and 400 beats per minute and some degree of atrioventricular node conduction block. Typically, the ventricular rate is half the atrial rate. In the EKG; atrial flutter waves are observed as sawtooth-like atrial activity. Pathophysiologically, atrial flutter is a form of atrial reentry in which there is a premature electrical impulse creates a self-propagating circuit.

Name: Common atrium
Desc: Complete absence of the interatrial septum with common atrioventricular valve and two atrioventricular connections.

Name: Heterotaxy
Desc: An abnormality in which the internal thoraco-abdominal organs demonstrate abnormal arrangement across the left-right axis of the body.

Name: Coronary sinus enlargement
Desc: Abnormal increase in size of the coronary sinus.

Name: Nodular goiter
Desc: Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to one or more nodules in the thyroid gland.

Name: Pheochromocytoma
Desc: Pheochromocytomas (also known as chromaffin tumors) produce, store, and secrete catecholamines. Pheochromocytomas usually originate from the adrenal medulla but may also develop from chromaffin cells in or about sympathetic ganglia. A common symptom of pheochromocytoma is hypertension owing to release of catecholamines.

Name: Primary hyperparathyroidism
Desc: A type of hyperparathyroidism caused by a primary abnormality of the parathyroid glands (e.g., adenoma, carcinoma, hyperplasia). Primary hyperparathyroidism is associated with hyercalcemia.

Name: Neoplasm of the skeletal system
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the skeleton.

Name: Abnormal liver parenchyma morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the liver located predominantly in the hepatocytes as opposed to stromal cells.

Name: Pancreatic adenocarcinoma
Desc: The presence of an adenocarcinoma of the pancreas.

Name: Back pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the back.

Name: Intestinal pseudo-obstruction
Desc: A functional rather than mechanical obstruction of the intestines, associated with manifestations that resemble those caused by an intestinal obstruction, including distension, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, constipation or diarrhea, in an individual in whom a mechanical blockage has been excluded.

Name: Melanoma
Desc: The presence of a melanoma, a malignant cancer originating from pigment producing melanocytes. Melanoma can originate from the skin or the pigmented layers of the eye (the uvea).

Name: Breast carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a carcinoma of the breast.

Name: Ovarian carcinoma
Desc: A malignant neoplasm originating from the surface ovarian epithelium.

Name: Peritoneal abscess
Desc: The presence of an abscess of the peritoneum.

Name: Abnormal vagina morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the vagina.

Name: Abnormality of the mouth
Desc: An abnormality of the mouth.

Name: Abnormal lip morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the lip.

Name: Pruritus
Desc: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased disposition to experience pruritus.

Name: Broad nail
Desc: Increased width of nail.

Name: Abnormal endocardium morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the endocardium.

Name: Abnormality of temperature regulation
Desc: An abnormality of temperature homeostasis.

Name: Dyspareunia
Desc: Recurrent or persistent genital pain associated with sexual intercourse.

Name: Renal dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.

Name: Abnormal sternum morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the sternum, also known as the breastbone.

Name: Abnormal pericardium morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the pericardium, i.e., of the fluid filled sac that surrounds the heart and the proximal ends of the aorta, vena cava, and the pulmonary artery.

Name: Polysplenia
Desc: Polysplenia is a congenital disease manifested by multiple small accessory spleens.

Name: Absent gallbladder
Desc: A developmental defect in which the gallbladder fails to form.

Name: 2-3 finger syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers two and three.

Name: Hamartoma of tongue
Desc: A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the tongue.

Name: Benign neoplasm of the central nervous system
Acidosis
Desc: Abnormal acid accumulation or depletion of base.

Name: Metabolic acidosis
Desc: Metabolic acidosis (MA) is characterized by a fall in blood pH due to a reduction of serum bicarbonate concentration. This can occur as a result of either the accumulation of acids (high anion gap MA) or the loss of bicarbonate from the gastrointestinal tract or the kidney (hyperchloremic MA). By definition, MA is not due to a respirary cause.

Name: Hyperuricemia
Desc: An abnormally high level of uric acid in the blood.

Name: Tachypnea
Desc: Very rapid breathing.
Synonyms: Increased respiratory rate or depth of breathing

Name: Ketonuria
Desc: High levels of ketone bodies (acetoacetic acid, beta-hydroxybutyric acid, and acetone) in the urine. Ketone bodies are insignificant in the blood and urine of normal individuals in the postprandial or overnight-fasted state.

Name: Ketoacidosis
Desc: Acidosis resulting from accumulation of ketone bodies.

Name: Increased serum lactate
Desc: Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35).
Synonyms: Higher than normal levels of lactate in blood

Name: Hyperglycemia
Desc: An increased concentration of glucose in the blood.

Name: Abnormal metabolic brain imaging by MRS
Desc: An anomaly of metabolism in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

Name: Body odor
Desc: A perceived unpleasant smell given off by the body.

Name: Thickened helices
Desc: Increased thickness of the helix of the ear.

Name: Long palpebral fissure
Desc: Distance between medial and lateral canthi is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, apparently increased length of the palpebral fissures.

Name: Abnormal heart valve morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of a cardiac valve.

Name: Slow-growing hair
Desc: Hair whose growth is slower than normal.

Name: Deep palmar crease
Desc: Excessively deep creases of the palm.

Name: Bundle branch block
Desc: Block of conduction of electrical impulses along the Bundle of His or along one of its bundle branches.

Name: Abnormality of the intervertebral disk
Desc: An abnormality of the intervertebral disk.

Name: Progressive external ophthalmoplegia
Desc: Initial bilateral ptosis followed by limitation of eye movements in all directions and slowing of saccades.

Name: Ragged-red muscle fibers
Desc: An abnormal appearance of muscle fibers observed on muscle biopsy. Ragged red fibers can be visualized with Gomori trichrome staining as irregular and intensely red subsarcolemmal zones, whereas the normal myofibrils are green. The margins of affect fibers appear red and ragged. The ragged-red is due to the accumulation of abnormal mitochondria below the plasma membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to the appearance of a red rim and speckled sarcoplasm.

Name: Increased serum pyruvate
Desc: An increased concentration of pyruvate in the blood.

Name: Exercise intolerance
Desc: A functional motor deficit where individuals whose responses to the challenges of exercise fail to achieve levels considered normal for their age and gender.

Name: Increased adipose tissue
Desc: An increase in adipose tissue mass by hyperplastic growth (increase in the number of adipocytes) or by hypertrophic growth (increase in the size of adipocytes occurring primarily by lipid accumulation within the cell).

Name: Brain imaging abnormality
Desc: An anomaly of metabolism or structure of the brain identified by imaging.

Name: Spastic diplegia
Desc: Spasticity (neuromuscular hypertonia) primarily in the muscles of the legs, hips, and pelvis.

Name: Decreased fetal movement
Desc: An abnormal reduction in quantity or strength of fetal movements.
Synonyms: Less than 10 fetal movements in 12 hours
Less than 10 foetal movements in 12 hours

Name: Abnormal pons morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the pons.

Name: T2 hypointense thalamus
Desc: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting the entire thalamus.

Name: Dysgyria
Desc: An abnormal gyral pattern characterized by abnormalities of sulcal depth or orientation.

Name: Progressive macrocephaly
Desc: The progressive development of an abnormally large skull.

Name: Short 4th metacarpal
Desc: Short fourth metacarpal bone.

Name: Hemiatrophy
Desc: Undergrowth of the limbs that affects only one side.

Name: Cupped ear
Desc: Laterally protruding ear that lacks antihelical folding (including absence of inferior and superior crura).

Name: Absent radius
Desc: Missing radius bone associated with congenital failure of development.
Synonyms: Missing outer large bone of forearm

Name: Aplasia of the 1st metacarpal
Desc: Absent first metacarpal (long bone) of the hand.

Name: Disproportionate short stature
Desc: A kind of short stature in which different regions of the body are shortened to differing extents.

Name: Abnormal oral cavity morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the oral cavity, i.e., the opening or hollow part of the mouth.

Name: Glossoptosis
Desc: Posterior displacement of the tongue into the pharynx, i.e., a tongue that is mislocalised posteriorly.

Name: Impaired ocular abduction
Desc: An impaired ability of the eye to move in the outward direction (towards the side of the head).

Name: Abnormality of the larynx
Desc: An abnormality of the larynx.

Name: Aplasia of the pectoralis major muscle
Desc: Absence of the pectoralis major muscle.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tongue
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the tongue.

Name: Thyroid adenoma
Desc: The presence of a adenoma of the thyroid gland.

Name: Hirsutism
Desc: Abnormally increased hair growth referring to a male pattern of body hair (androgenic hair).

Name: Hypermelanotic macule
Desc: A hyperpigmented circumscribed area of change in normal skin color without elevation or depression of any size.

Name: Pituitary adenoma
Desc: A benign epithelial tumor derived from intrinsic cells of the adenohypophysis.

Name: Vestibular Schwannoma
Desc: A vestibular Schwannoma (also known as acoustic neuroma, acoustic neurinoma, or acoustic neurilemoma) is a benign, usually slow-growing tumor that develops from the VIIIth cranial nerve supplying the inner ear.

Name: Peripheral Schwannoma
Desc: The presence of a peripheral schwannoma.

Name: Abnormality of circulating adrenocorticotropin level
Desc: An abnormal concentration of corticotropin in the blood.
Synonyms: Abnormality of circulating adrenocorticotropic hormone level

Name: Cardiac myxoma
Desc: A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) of the heart. Cardiac myxomas consist of stellate to plump, cytologically bland mesenchymal cells set in a myxoid stroma. Cardiac myxomas are of endocardial origina and general project from the endocardium into a cardiac chamber.

Name: Pituitary growth hormone cell adenoma
Desc: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces growth hormone.

Name: Increased urinary cortisol level
Desc: Abnormally increased concentration of cortisol in the urine.

Name: Schwannoma
Desc: A benign nerve sheath tumor composed of Schwann cells.

Name: Ovarian cyst
Desc: The presence of one or more cysts of the ovary.

Name: Recurrent paroxysmal headache
Desc: Repeated episodes of headache with rapid onset, reaching a peak within minutes and of short duration (less than one hour) with pain that is throbbing, pulsating, or bursting in quality.

Name: Hypertension associated with pheochromocytoma
Desc: A type of hypertension associated with pheochromocytoma.

Name: Adrenal pheochromocytoma
Desc: Pheochromocytoma originating from the adrenal medulla.

Name: Pituitary prolactin cell adenoma
Desc: A type of pituitary adenoma originating in prolactin secreting cells. This kind of adenoma is characterized by overproduction of prolactin, and may cause loss of menstrual periods and breast milk production in women.

Name: Pigmentation of the sclera
Synonyms: Pigmentation of the outer white part of the eyeball

Name: Fibroadenoma of the breast
Desc: A benign biphasic tumor of the breast with epithelial and stromal components.

Name: Neoplasm of the pancreas
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the pancreas.

Name: Hepatocellular adenoma
Desc: A benign tumor of the liver of presumably epithelial origin.

Name: Histiocytoma
Desc: A neoplasm containing histiocytes.

Name: Osteochondroma
Desc: A cartilage capped bony outgrowth of a long bone. Osteochondroma arises on the external surface of bone containing a marrow cavity that is continuous with that of the underlying bone.

Name: Sertoli cell neoplasm
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the testis with origin in a Sertoli cell.

Name: Bronchogenic cyst
Desc: A rare congenital cystic lesion of the lungs in the mediastinum.

Name: Leukoencephalopathy
Desc: This term describes abnormality of the white matter of the cerebrum resulting from damage to the myelin sheaths of nerve cells.

Name: Lacunar stroke
Desc: A stroke related to a small infarct (2-20 mm in diameter) in the deep cerebral white matter, basal ganglia, or pons, that is presumed to result from the occlusion of a single small perforating artery supplying the subcortical areas of the brain.

Name: Multifocal hyperintensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
Desc: An abnormal area of increased brightness (hyperintensity) that occurs in several distinct areas.

Name: Migraine with aura
Desc: A type of migraine in which there is an aura characterized by focal neurological phenomena that usually proceed, but may accompany or occur in the absence of, the headache. The symptoms of an aura may include fully reversible visual, sensory, and speech symptoms but not motor weakness. Visual symptoms may include flickering lights, spots and lines and/or loss of vision and/or unilateral sensory symptoms such as paresthesias or numbness. At least one of the symptoms of an aura develops gradually over 5 or more minutes and/or different symptoms occur in succession.

Name: Ischemic stroke
Desc: Acute ischemic stroke (AIS) is defined by the sudden loss of blood flow to an area of the brain with the resulting loss of neurologic function. It is caused by thrombosis or embolism that occludes a cerebral vessel supplying a specific area of the brain. During a vessel occlusion, there is a core area where damage to the brain is irreversible and an area of penumbra where the brain has lost function owing to decreased blood flow but is not irreversibly injured.

Name: Hemiplegia
Desc: Paralysis (complete loss of muscle function) in the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.
Synonyms: Paralysis on one side of body

Name: Motor deterioration
Desc: Loss of previously present motor (i.e., movement) abilities.

Name: Stress urinary incontinence
Desc: Involuntary urine leakage synchronous with exertion, or actions such as sneezing, or coughing.

Name: Bradyphrenia
Desc: Abnormal slowness of thought processes.

Name: Carnosinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of carnosine in the urine.

Name: Adult onset sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: The presence of sensorineural deafness with late onset.

Name: Decreased liver function
Desc: Reduced ability of the liver to perform its functions.

Name: Abnormal circulating carbohydrate concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of a carbohydrate in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal fifth cranial nerve morphology
Desc: Any structural abormality of the fifth cranial nerve.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the fifth cranial nerve

Name: Astigmatism
Desc: A type of astigmatism associated with abnormal curvatures on the anterior and/or posterior surface of the cornea.
Synonyms: Abnormal curving of the cornea or lens of the eye

Name: Recurrent corneal erosions
Desc: The presence of recurrent corneal epithelial erosions. Although most corneal epithelial defects heal quickly, some may show recurrent ulcerations.
Synonyms: Recurrent breakdown of clear protective layer of eye

Name: Corneal stromal edema
Desc: Abnormal accumulation of fluid and swelling of the stroma of cornea.

Name: Allodynia
Desc: Pain due to a stimulus that does not normally provoke pain.

Name: Corneal perforation
Desc: A rupture of the cornea through which a portion of the iris protrudes.

Name: Deep anterior chamber
Desc: Increased depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is increased.

Name: Open angle glaucoma
Desc: A type of glaucoma defined by an open, normal appearing anterior chamber angle and raised intraocular pressure,

Name: Herpetiform corneal ulceration
Desc: The presence of one or more dendritic corneal epithelial ulcers characterized by a treelike branching linear pattern with feathery edges and terminal bulbs. Herpetiform corneal ulcers can be identified by fluorescein staining.

Name: Descemet Membrane Folds
Desc: Presence of folds in the Descemet membrane, which is the basement membrane of the endothelial (inner) cell layer of the cornea. Descemet membrane folds are generally a manifestation of inflammation or edema of the cornea.

Name: Hamartoma
Desc: A disordered proliferation of mature tissues that is native to the site of origin, e.g., exostoses, nevi and soft tissue hamartomas. Although most hamartomas are benign, some histologic subtypes, e.g., neuromuscular hamartoma, may proliferate aggressively such as mesenchymal cystic hamartoma, Sclerosing epithelial hamartoma, Sclerosing metanephric hamartoma.

Name: Neoplasm of the thyroid gland
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the thyroid gland.

Name: Lower limb asymmetry
Desc: A difference in length or diameter between the left and right leg.
Synonyms: Left and right leg differ in length or width

Name: Upper limb asymmetry
Desc: Difference in length or size between the right and left arm.

Name: Lymphangioma
Desc: Lymphangiomas are rare congenital malformations consisting of focal proliferations of well-differentiated lymphatic tissue in multi cystic or sponge like structures. Lymphangioma is usually asymptomatic due to its soft consistency but compression of adjacent structures can be seen due to the mass effect of a large tumor.

Name: Cranial asymmetry
Desc: Asymmetry of the bones of the skull.

Name: Overgrowth
Desc: Excessive postnatal growth which may comprise increased weight, increased length, and/or increased head circumference.

Name: Unilateral cryptorchidism
Desc: Absence of a testis from the scrotum on one side owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.

Name: Ventricular tachycardia
Desc: A tachycardia originating in the ventricles characterized by rapid heart rate (over 100 beats per minute) and broad QRS complexes (over 120 ms).

Name: Atrioventricular block
Desc: Delayed or lack of conduction of atrial depolarizations through the atrioventricular node to the ventricles.
Synonyms: Interruption of electrical communication between upper and lower chambers of heart

Name: Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome
Desc: A disorder of the cardiac conduction system of the heart characterized by ventricular preexcitation due to the presence of an abnormal accessory atrioventricular electrical conduction pathway.

Name: Stroke-like episode
Desc: No consensus exists on what a stroke-like episode is, but these episodes can be functionally defined as a new neurological deficit, occurring with or without the context of seizures, which last longer than 24 hours.

Name: Junctional ectopic tachycardia
Desc: Junctional ectopic tachycardia (JET) is a unique type of supraventricular arrhythmia defined by narrow QRS complex and atrioventricular (AV) dissociation or retrograde atrial conduction in a 1:1 pattern.

Name: Renal cyst
Desc: A fluid filled sac in the kidney.

Name: Thromboembolism
Desc: The formation of a blood clot inside a blood vessel that subsequently travels through the blood stream from the site where it formed to another location in the body, generally leading to vascular occlusion at the distant site.

Name: Atrial fibrillation
Desc: An atrial arrhythmia characterized by disorganized atrial activity without discrete P waves on the surface EKG, but instead by an undulating baseline or more sharply circumscribed atrial deflections of varying amplitude an frequency ranging from 350 to 600 per minute.
Synonyms: Quivering upper heart chambers resulting in irregular heartbeat

Name: Shortened PR interval
Desc: Reduced time for the PR interval (beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex). In adults, normal values are 120 to 200 ms long.

Name: Laryngeal web
Desc: A membrane-like structure that extends across the laryngeal lumen close to the level of the vocal cords.

Name: Congenital aphakia
Desc: Absence of the crystalline lens of the eye as a result of a developmental defect.

Name: Pulmonary edema
Desc: Fluid accumulation in the lungs.

Name: Abnormality of the menstrual cycle
Desc: An abnormality of the ovulation cycle.

Name: Oligomenorrhea
Desc: Infrequent menses (less than 6 per year or more than 35 days between cycles).

Name: Dysmenorrhea
Desc: Pain during menstruation that interferes with daily activities.

Name: Metrorrhagia
Desc: Bleeding at irregular intervals.

Name: Abnormal placenta morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the placenta, the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall to enable nutrient uptake, waste elimination, and gas exchange.

Name: Generalized muscle weakness
Desc: Generalized weakness or decreased strength of the muscles, affecting both distal and proximal musculature.

Name: Syringomyelia
Desc: Dilated, glial-lined cavity in spinal cord. This cavity does not communicate with the central canal, and usually is between the dorsal columns unilaterally or bilaterally along the side of the cord.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Anhidrosis
Desc: Inability to sweat.

Name: Cerebellar hypoplasia
Desc: Cerebellar hypoplasia is a descriptive term implying a cerebellum with a reduced volume, but a normal shape and is stable over time.

Name: Impaired social interactions
Desc: Difficulty in social interactions related to an impairment of characteristics such as eye contact, smiling, appropriate facial expressions, and body postures and characterized by difficulty in forming peer relationships and forming friendships.

Name: Poor eye contact
Desc: Difficulty in looking at another person in the eye.

Name: Focal impaired awareness seizure
Desc: Focal impaired awareness seizure (or focal seizure with impaired or lost awareness) is a type of focal-onset seizure characterized by some degree (which may be partial) of impairment of the person's awareness of themselves or their surroundings at any point during the seizure.
Synonyms: Focal seizure with impairment of awareness
Focal seizure with loss of awareness
Focal seizures with impairment of consciousness or awareness
Localised seizure with loss of awareness
Localized seizure with loss of awareness
Partial seizure with impairment of awareness
Partial seizure with loss of awareness

Name: Partial absence of cerebellar vermis
Desc: Congenital absence of a part of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Tall chin
Desc: Increased vertical distance from the vermillion border of the lower lip to the inferior-most point of the chin.

Name: Frontal cortical atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the frontal cortex.

Name: Beaking of vertebral bodies
Desc: Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies.

Name: Bulbar palsy
Desc: Bulbar weakness (or bulbar palsy) refers to bilateral impairment of function of the lower cranial nerves IX, X, XI and XII, which occurs due to lower motor neuron lesion either at nuclear or fascicular level in the medulla or from bilateral lesions of the lower cranial nerves outside the brain-stem. Bulbar weakness is often associated with difficulty in chewing, weakness of the facial muscles, dysarthria, palatal weakness and regurgitation of fluids, dysphagia, and dysphonia.

Name: Weak voice
Desc: Reduced intensity (volume) of speech.

Name: Limb fasciculations
Desc: Fasciculations affecting the musculature of the arms and legs.

Name: Schizophrenia
Desc: A mental disorder characterized by a disintegration of thought processes and of emotional responsiveness. It most commonly manifests as auditory hallucinations, paranoid or bizarre delusions, or disorganized speech and thinking, and it is accompanied by significant social or occupational dysfunction. The onset of symptoms typically occurs in young adulthood, with a global lifetime prevalence of about 0.3-0.7%.

Name: Mandibular condyle hypoplasia
Synonyms: Decreased size of condylar process of mandible
Hypoplasia of condylar head of mandible
Hypoplasia of condylar neck of mandible
Hypoplasia of condylar process of mandible
Hypoplasia of subcondylar region of mandible

Name: Cleft helix
Desc: A notched form of the helix of the ear. That is, a defect in the continuity of the helix, which may occur at any point along its length.

Name: Dental crowding
Desc: Changes in alignment of teeth in the dental arch
Synonyms: Inadequate arch length for tooth size

Name: Obstructive sleep apnea
Desc: A condition characterized by obstruction of the airway and by pauses in breathing during sleep occurring many times during the night. Obstructive sleep apnea is related to a relaxation of muscle tone (which normally occurs during sleep) leading to partial collapse of the soft tissues in the airway with resultant obstruction of the air flow.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the external ear
Desc: The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the external ear.

Name: Abnormality of the crus of the helix
Desc: An abnormality of the crus of the helix, which is the horizontal piece of cartilage located outside the ear canal that divides the upper and lower parts of the ear.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the crus of the ear

Name: Abnormality of the temporomandibular joint
Desc: An anomaly of the temporomandibular joint.

Name: Snoring
Desc: Deep, noisy breathing during sleep accompanied by hoarse or harsh sounds caused by the vibration of respiratory structures (especially the soft palate) resulting in sound due to obstructed air movement during breathing while sleeping.

Name: Question mark ear
Desc: Cleft between the helix and the lobe.

Name: Periauricular skin pits
Desc: Benign congenital lesions of the periauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.

Name: Mandibular condyle aplasia
Synonyms: Absence of the condylar head of mandible
Absence of the condylar neck of mandible
Absence of the condylar process of mandible
Agenesis of condylar head of mandible
Agenesis of condylar neck of mandible
Agenesis of condylar process of mandible
Failure of development of condylar head of mandible
Failure of development of condylar neck of mandible
Failure of development of the condylar process of mandible
Underdevelopment of condylar head of mandible
Underdevelopment of condylar neck of mandible
Underdevelopment of condylar process of mandible

Name: Vein of Galen aneurysmal malformation
Desc: Gross dilatation of the vein of Galen, being fed by large anomalous vessel or vessels arising from the carotid or basilar circulation.

Name: Abnormality of the dorsal column of the spinal cord
Desc: An abnormality of the dorsal columns, i.e., of the dorsal portion of the gray substance of the spinal cord. The dorsal column consists of the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus and itself is part of the dorsal funiculus.

Name: Progressive spasticity
Desc: Spasticity that increases in degree with time.

Name: Increased CSF lactate
Desc: Increased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Impaired distal proprioception
Desc: A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position occuring at distal joints.

Name: Poor fine motor coordination
Desc: An abnormality of the ability (skills) to perform a precise movement of small muscles with the intent to perform a specific act. Fine motor skills are required to mediate movements of the wrists, hands, fingers, feet, and toes.

Name: Absent speech
Desc: Complete lack of development of speech and language abilities.

Name: Unilateral microphthalmos
Desc: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of one eye.
Synonyms: Abnormally small eyeball on one side

Name: Pseudopapilledema
Desc: Apparent optic disc swelling in the absence of increased intracranial pressure.

Name: Optic disc hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the optic disc, that is of the optic nerve head, where ganglion cell axons exit the eye to form the optic nerve.

Name: Abnormal best corrected visual acuity test
Abnormal involuntary eye movements
Desc: Anomalous movements of the eyes that occur without the subject wanting them to happen.

Name: Chronic sinusitis
Desc: A chronic form of sinusitis.

Name: Abnormal nasal mucus secretion
Desc: Any deviation from the normal quantity of secretion of nasal mucus, a thick viscous liquid produced by the mucous membranes of the nose.

Name: Upper airway obstruction
