Desc: Increased resistance to the passage of air in the upper airway.

Name: Mandibulofacial dysostosis
Desc: A type of craniofacial dysostosis associated with abnormalities of the external ears, mirognathia, macrostomia, coloboma of the lower eyelid, and cleft palate. This is a bundled term that is left in the HPO now for convenience with legacy annotations but should not be used for new annotations.

Name: Inappropriate crying
Desc: Uncontrolled episodes of crying, without apparent motivating stimuli.

Name: Choking episodes
Desc: Incidents in which a piece of food or other objects get stuck in the upper airway and provoke coughing, gagging, inability to talk, and difficulty breathing.

Name: Polydactyly
Desc: A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of supernumerary fingers or toes.
Synonyms: More than five fingers or toes on hands or feet

Name: Intercostal retractions
Desc: A pulling inward of the soft tissues between the ribs upon inhalation. This is a sign of increased use of the chest muscles for breathing and is a manifestation of respiratory distress.

Name: Abnormality of the inner ear
Desc: An abnormality of the inner ear.

Name: Overfolded helix
Desc: A condition in which the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal. That is, excessive curling of the helix edge, whereby the free edge is parallel to the plane of the ear.

Name: Abnormal cranial nerve morphology
Desc: Structural abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.

Name: Hypoplasia of the semicircular canal
Desc: Underdevelopment of the semicircular canal.

Name: Abnormal morphology of female internal genitalia
Desc: An abnormality of the female internal genitalia.

Name: Anterior hypopituitarism
Desc: A condition of reduced function of the anterior pituitary gland characterized by decreased secretion of one or more of the pituitary hormones growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, prolactin, luteinizing hormone, and follicle-stimulating hormone.

Name: Aortic arch aneurysm
Desc: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic arch.

Name: Interrupted aortic arch
Desc: Non-continuity of the arch of aorta with an atretic point or absent segment.

Name: Abnormality of the adrenal glands
Desc: Abnormality of the adrenal glands, i.e., of the endocrine glands located at the top of the kindneys.

Name: Aqueductal stenosis
Desc: Stenosis of the cerebral aqueduct (also known as the mesencephalic duct, aqueductus mesencephali, or aqueduct of Sylvius), which connects the third cerebral ventricle in the diencephalon to the fourth ventricle, which is between the pons and cerebellum.

Name: Bifid femur
Desc: A bifid or bifurcated appearance of the femur as seen on x-rays, possible appearing as a more or less severe bowing of the upper leg. Might be associated with hip dysplasia on the affected side.

Name: Renal tubular dysfunction
Desc: Abnormal function of the renal tubule. The basic functional unit of the kidney, the nephron, consists of a renal corpuscle attached to a renal tubule, with roughly 0.8 to 1.5 nephrons per adult kidney. The functions of the renal tubule include reabsorption of water, electrolytes, glucose, and amino acids and secretion of substances such as uric acid.
Synonyms: Abnormal function of filtrating structures in kidney

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the lens
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the lens.

Name: Generalized hypertrichosis
Desc: Generalized excessive, abnormal hairiness.

Name: Furrowed tongue
Desc: Accentuation of the grooves on the dorsal surface of the tongue.

Name: Tooth malposition
Desc: Abnormal alignment, positioning, or spacing of the teeth, i.e., misaligned teeth.

Name: Radial deviation of the 2nd finger
Desc: Displacement of the 2nd finger towards the radial side.

Name: Oral synechia
Desc: Fibrous band between the mucosal surfaces of the upper and lower alveolar ridges.

Name: Metatarsus valgus
Desc: A condition in which the anterior part of the foot rotates outward away from the midline of the body and the heel remains straight.

Name: Nyctalopia
Desc: Inability to see well at night or in poor light.

Name: Abnormal retinal vascular morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of retinal vasculature.

Name: Down-sloping shoulders
Desc: Low set, steeply sloping shoulders.

Name: Bell-shaped thorax
Desc: The rib cage has the shape of a wide mouthed bell. That is, the superior portion of the rib cage is constricted, followed by a convex region, and the inferior portion of the rib cage expands again to have a large diameter.

Name: Neonatal respiratory distress
Desc: Respiratory difficulty as newborn.

Name: Posterior rib gap
Desc: Radiolucent focal defect of the posterior portion of a rib shaft. The 'gaps' may lead to flail chest.

Name: Porencephalic cyst
Desc: A cavity within the cerebral hemisphere, filled with cerebrospinal fluid, that communicates directly with the ventricular system.

Name: Hydranencephaly
Desc: A defect of development of the brain characterized by replacement of greater portions of the cerebral hemispheres and the corpus striatum by cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and glial tissue.

Name: Short hard palate
Desc: Distance between the labial point of the incisive papilla to the midline junction of the hard and soft palate more than 2 SD below the mean (objective) or apparently decreased length of the hard palate (subjective).

Name: Astereognosia
Desc: Inability to recognize the form of objects by touch without visual input. That is, an impairment in the recognition of objects based only on the texture, size, weight and three-dimensional form of the object in the absence of any major somatosensory deficit.

Name: Hoffmann sign
Desc: A Hoffman test is performed by flicking the fingernail of the long finger, from dorsal to volar, on each hand while the hand was supported by the examiner's hand. The test was done with the neck in the neutral position and then with the neck maximally forward flexed. Any flexion of the ipsilateral thumb and/or index finger was interpreted as a positive test.

Name: Inability to walk
Desc: Incapability to ambulate.

Name: Vegetative state
Desc: Absence of wakefulness and conscience, but (in contrast to coma) with involuntary opening of the eyes and movements (such as teeth grinding, yawning, or thrashing of the extremities).

Name: Abnormal periventricular white matter morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the myelinated axons (white matter) located near the cerebral ventricles.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the periventricular white matter

Name: Abnormal circulating fatty-acid concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of a fatty acid in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormality of the brainstem white matter
Desc: An anomaly of the white matter of brainstem.

Name: Male hypogonadism
Desc: Decreased functionality of the male gonad, i.e., of the testis, with reduced spermatogenesis or testosterone synthesis.

Name: Short attention span
Desc: Reduced attention span characterized by distractibility and impulsivity but not necessarily satisfying the diagnostic criteria for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder.

Name: Diffuse demyelination of the cerebral white matter
Desc: A diffuse loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

Name: CNS demyelination
Desc: A loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

Name: Decreased circulating cortisol level
Desc: Abnormally reduced concentration of cortisol in the blood.

Name: Very long chain fatty acid accumulation
Abnormality of the spinal cord
Desc: An abnormality of the spinal cord (myelon).

Name: Global brain atrophy
Desc: Unlocalized atrophy of the brain with decreased total brain matter volume and increased ventricular size.

Name: Broad philtrum
Desc: Distance between the philtral ridges, measured just above the vermilion border, more than 2 standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased distance between the ridges of the philtrum.

Name: Bifid ribs
Desc: A bifid rib refers to cleavage of the sternal end of a rib, usually unilateral. Bifid ribs are usually asymptomatic, and are often discovered incidentally by chest x-ray.

Name: Rib fusion
Desc: Complete or partial merging of adjacent ribs.

Name: Tubulointerstitial nephritis
Desc: A form of inflammation of the kidney affecting the interstitium of the kidneys surrounding the tubules.

Name: Macule
Desc: A flat, distinct, discolored area of skin less than 1 cm wide that does not involve any change in the thickness or texture of the skin.

Name: Enanthema
Desc: A sudden eruption (rash) of the surface of a mucous membrane of the mouth or pharynx.

Name: Thyroiditis
Desc: Inflammation of the thyroid gland.

Name: Angioedema
Desc: Rapid swelling (edema) of the dermis, subcutaneous tissue, mucosa and submucosal tissues of the skin of the face, normally around the mouth, and the mucosa of the mouth and/or throat, as well as the tongue during a period of minutes to several hours. The swelling can also occur elsewhere, typically in the hands. Angioedema is similar to urticaria, but the swelling is subcutaneous rather than on the epidermis.

Name: Lymphocytosis
Desc: Increase in the number or proportion of lymphocytes in the blood.

Name: Pustule
Desc: A small elevation of the skin containing cloudy or purulent material usually consisting of necrotic inflammatory cells.

Name: Adrenocortical adenoma
Desc: Adrenocortical adenomas are benign tumors of the adrenal cortex.

Name: Verrucous papule
Desc: A wartlike (with multiple small elevated projections) papule.

Name: Skin nodule
Desc: Morphologically similar to a papule, but greater than either 10mm in both width and depth, and most frequently centered in the dermis or subcutaneous fat.
Synonyms: Growth of abnormal tissue on or under the skin

Name: EEG with spike-wave complexes
Desc: Complexes of spikes (<70 ms) and sharp waves (70-200 ms), which are sharp transient waves that have a strong association with epilepsy, in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Focal seizure with eyelid myoclonia
Desc: Focal seizure with eyelid myoclonia, not eyelid myoclonias in the context of absence seizures.

Name: Chin myoclonus
Desc: Involuntary and irregular twitches of the chin.

Name: Histiocytosis
Desc: An excessive number of histiocytes (tissue macrophages).

Name: Intracranial cystic lesion
Desc: A cystic lesion originating within the brain.

Name: Infantile axial hypotonia
Desc: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk and with onset in infancy.

Name: Lacrimal duct atresia
Desc: A developmental disorder of the lacrimal drainage system that most often affects the lacrimal ostium and resulting in non-opening of the nasolacrimal duct. It usually results from a non-canalization of the nasolacrimal duct.

Name: Sex reversal
Desc: Development of the reproductive system is inconsistent with the chromosomal sex.

Name: Abnormal penis morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the male external sex organ.

Name: Malrotation of small bowel
Desc: A deviation from the normal rotation of the midgut during embryologic development with mislocalization of the small bowel.

Name: Hypoplasia of the bladder
Desc: Underdevelopment of the urinary bladder.

Name: Sclerocornea
Desc: A congenital anomaly in which a part or the whole of the cornea acquires the characteristics of sclera, resulting in clouding of the cornea.
Synonyms: Hardening of skin and connective tissue

Name: Nail dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the nail.

Name: Inferior vermis hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the inferior portion of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Enamel hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.

Name: Thick nasal alae
Desc: Increase in bulk of the ala nasi.

Name: Bifid nose
Desc: Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal bridge, ridge and tip.
Synonyms: Indentation or clefting of the nose

Name: Proximal muscle weakness
Desc: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles.
Synonyms: Weakness in muscles of upper arms and upper legs

Name: Focal T2 hypointense basal ganglia lesion
Desc: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.

Name: Congenital hepatic fibrosis
Desc: The presence of fibrosis of that part of the liver with congenital onset.
Synonyms: Excessive buildup of connective tissue and scarring of liver at birth

Name: Increased circulating ferritin concentration
Desc: Increased concentration of ferritin in the blood circulation.

Name: Hepatic periportal necrosis
Desc: A type of hepatic necrosis that is concentrated around the necrosis of hepatocytes localized around the intrahepatic branch of portal vein.

Name: Viral hepatitis
Desc: Inflammation of the liver due to infection with a virus.

Name: Elevated transferrin saturation
Desc: An above normal level of saturation of serum transferrin with iron.

Name: Elevated hepatic iron concentration
Desc: An increased level of iron in liver tissues.

Name: Abnormality of the genital system
Desc: An abnormality of the genital system.

Name: Micronodular cirrhosis
Desc: A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of small regenerative nodules.

Name: Abnormality of adrenal morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the adrenal glands.

Name: Abnormal thyroid morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the thyroid gland.

Name: Hepatic bridging fibrosis
Desc: Hepatic fibrosis that reaches from a portal area to another portal area.

Name: Low levels of vitamin C
Desc: A reduced concentration of Vitamin C.

Name: Esophageal carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a carcinoma of the esophagus.

Name: Thenar muscle atrophy
Desc: Wasting of thenar muscles, which are located on palm of the hand at the base of the thumb.

Name: Hammertoe
Desc: Hyperextension of the metatarsal-phalangeal joint with hyperflexion of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint.

Name: Pes valgus
Desc: An outward deviation of the foot at the talocalcaneal or subtalar joint.

Name: Distal sensory loss of all modalities
Acral ulceration
Desc: A type of digital ulcer that manifests as an open sore on the surface of the skin at the tip of a finger or toe.

Name: Foot osteomyelitis
Desc: An infection of bone of the foot.

Name: Cerebellar agenesis
Desc: Cerebellar agenesis is defined by the near complete absence of cerebellar tissue with only remnants of the anterior vermis, flocculus, and/or middle cerebellar peduncles.

Name: Acanthocytosis
Desc: Acanthocytosis is a type of poikilocytosis characterized by the presence of spikes on the cell surface. The cells have an irregular shape resembling many-pointed stars.

Name: Steatorrhea
Desc: Greater than normal amounts of fat in the feces. This is a result of malabsorption of lipids in the small intestine and results in frothy foul-smelling fecal matter that floats.

Name: Fat malabsorption
Desc: Abnormality of the absorption of fat from the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Abnormal circulating apolipoprotein concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration in blood of an apolipoprotein, i.e., of a protein that binds lipids to form lipoprotein and is thereby responsible for the transport of lipids in the blood and lymph circulation.

Name: Low levels of vitamin E
Desc: A reduced concentration of vitamin E in the blood circulation. Vitamin E is a lipophilic vitamin that is also known as alpha-tocopherol.

Name: Progressive visual loss
Desc: A reduction of previously attained ability to see.

Name: Reticulocytosis
Desc: An elevation in the number of reticulocytes (immature erythrocytes) in the peripheral blood circulation.
Synonyms: Increased number of immature red blood cells

Name: Hypocholesterolemia
Desc: An decreased concentration of cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Decreased HDL cholesterol concentration
Desc: An decreased concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Decreased LDL cholesterol concentration
Desc: An decreased concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Low levels of vitamin A
Desc: A reduced concentration of vitamin A.

Name: Hypotriglyceridemia
Desc: An decrease in the level of triglycerides in the blood.

Name: Low levels of vitamin D
Desc: A reduced concentration of Vitamin D.

Name: Scotoma
Desc: A regional and pathological increase of the light detection threshold in any region of the visual field surrounded by a field of normal or relatively well-preserved vision.

Name: Osteopenia
Desc: Osteopenia is a term to define bone density that is not normal but also not as low as osteoporosis. By definition from the World Health Organization osteopenia is defined by bone densitometry as a T score -1 to -2.5.

Name: Positive Romberg sign
Desc: The patient stands with the feet placed together and balance and is asked to close his or her eyes. A loss of balance upon eye closure is a positive Romberg sign and is interpreted as indicating a deficit in proprioception.

Name: Steppage gait
Desc: An abnormal gait pattern that arises from weakness of the pretibial and peroneal muscles due to a lower motor neuron lesion. Affected patients have footdrop and are unable to dorsiflex and evert the foot. The leg is lifted high on walking so that the toes clear the ground, and there may be a slapping noise when the foot strikes the ground again.

Name: Hypopigmentation of the fundus
Desc: Reduced pigmentation of the fundus, typically generalised. Fundoscopy may reveal a low level pigment in both RPE and choroid with clear visibility of choroidal vessels (pale/albinoid) or low pigment level in the RPE with deep pigment in choroid so that visible choroidal vessels are separated by deeply pigmented zones (tesselated/tigroid).

Name: Prolonged prothrombin time
Desc: Increased time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.

Name: Decreased erythrocyte sedimentation rate
Desc: A reduced erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). The ESR is a test that measures the distance that erythrocytes have fallen after one hour in a vertical column of anticoagulated blood under the influence of gravity. The ESR is a nonspecific finding. A decreased ESR may be seen in polycythemia or in certain blood diseases in which red blood cells have an irregular or smaller shape that causes slower settling.

Name: Male pseudohermaphroditism
Desc: Hermaphroditism refers to a discrepancy between the morphology of the gonads and that of the external genitalia. In male pseudohermaphroditism, the genotype is male (XY) and the external genitalia are imcompletely virilized, ambiguous, or complete female. If gonads are present, they are testes.

Name: 11 pairs of ribs
Desc: Presence of only 11 pairs of ribs.

Name: Tracheobronchomalacia
Desc: Weakness of the cartilage in the trachea and the bronchi, resulting in a floppy (non-rigid) airway. Affected persons may have difficulties to maintain patency of the airways.

Name: Femoral bowing
Desc: Bowing (abnormal curvature) of the femur.

Name: Poorly ossified cervical vertebrae
Desc: Decreased ossification of the cervical vertebral bodies, i.e., of the Cervical vertebrae set.

Name: Hydroureter
Desc: The distention of the ureter with urine.

Name: Abnormal oral frenulum morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the lingual frenulum, that is of the small fold of mucous membrane that attaches the tongue to the floor of the mouth, or the presence of accessory frenula in the oral cavity.

Name: Commissural lip pit
Desc: A depression located at an oral commissure.
Synonyms: Lip pits at corners of the mouth
Pits at the corners of the lips

Name: Agenesis of permanent teeth
Desc: A congenital defect characterized by the absence of one or more permanent teeth, including oligodontia, hypodontia, and adontia of the of permanent teeth.
Synonyms: Failure of development of permanent teeth
Failure of development of secondary teeth

Name: Bifid tongue
Desc: Tongue with a median apical indentation or fork.

Name: Imperforate hymen
Desc: A congenital disorder where the hymen (a membrane that surrounds or partially covers the external vaginal opening) does not have an opening and completely obstructs the vagina.

Name: Atelectasis
Desc: Collapse of part of a lung associated with absence of inflation (air) of that part.
Synonyms: Partial or complete collapse of part or entire lung

Name: Agenesis of maxillary incisor
Synonyms: Failure of development of maxillary incisor
Failure of development of upper incisor

Name: Short fifth metatarsal
Desc: Short (hypoplastic) fifth metatarsal bone.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia of the fifth metatarsal bone

Name: Skin erosion
Desc: A discontinuity of the skin exhibiting incomplete loss of the epidermis, a lesion that is moist, circumscribed, and usually depressed.

Name: Secondary hyperparathyroidism
Desc: Secondary hyperparathyroidism refers to the production of higher than normal levels of parathyroid hormone in the presence of hypocalcemia.

Name: Abnormal circulating calcium concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of calcium in the blood circulation.

Name: Acute infectious pneumonia
Desc: Acute inflammation of the lung due to an infection.

Name: Pharyngitis
Desc: Inflammation (due to infection or irritation) of the pharynx.

Name: Acute kidney injury
Desc: Sudden loss of renal function, as manifested by decreased urine production, and a rise in serum creatinine or blood urea nitrogen concentration (azotemia).

Name: Hypertriglyceridemia
Desc: An abnormal increase in the level of triglycerides in the blood.

Name: Increased HDL cholesterol concentration
Desc: An elevated concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL) in the blood.

Name: Eruptive xanthomas
Desc: Eruptive xanthomas are yellow-orange-to-red-brown papules that are often surrounded by an erythematous halo. They appear in crops on the buttocks, extensor surfaces of the extremities, and flexural creases. Acutely, variable amounts of pruritus and pain occur.

Name: Premature coronary artery atherosclerosis
Desc: Reduction of the diameter of the coronary arteries as the result of an accumulation of atheromatous plaques within the walls of the coronary arteries before age of 45.

Name: Inflammatory abnormality of the skin
Desc: The presence of inflammation of the skin. That is, an abnormality of the skin resulting from the local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes.
Synonyms: Abnormal tendency to infections of the skin

Name: Stiff skin
Desc: An induration (hardening) of the skin

Name: Acanthosis nigricans
Desc: A dermatosis characterized by thickened, hyperpigmented plaques, typically on the intertriginous surfaces and neck.

Name: Perioral hyperpigmentation
Desc: Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the skin surrounding the vermilion of the lips.
Synonyms: Darkening of skin around the mouth

Name: Exotropia
Desc: A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward.

Name: High pitched voice
Desc: An abnormal increase in the pitch (frequency) of the voice.

Name: Absent lower eyelashes
Desc: Lack of eyelashes on the lower lid.
Synonyms: Failure of development of lower eyelashes

Name: Yellow nails
Desc: Yellowish discoloration of the nails.

Name: Decreased serum insulin-like growth factor 1
Desc: A reduced level of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF1) in the blood circulation.

Name: Clitoral hypertrophy
Desc: Hypertrophy of the clitoris.

Name: Ectopic kidney
Desc: A developmental defect in which a kidney is located in an abnormal anatomic position.

Name: Lop ear
Desc: Anterior and inferior folding of the upper portion of the ear that obliterates triangular fossa and scapha.

Name: Bicornuate uterus
Desc: The presence of a bicornuate uterus.

Name: Hypoplasia of the radius
Desc: Underdevelopment of the radius.

Name: Pulmonary artery stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

Name: Macular dystrophy
Desc: Macular dystrophy is a nonspecific term for premature retinal cell aging and cell death, generally confied to the macula in which no clear extrinsic cause is evident.

Name: Mitral atresia
Desc: A congenital defect with failure to open of the mitral valve orifice.

Name: Nephronophthisis
Desc: Presence of cysts at the corticomedullary junction of the kidney in combination with tubulointerstitial fibrosis.

Name: Abnormality of body height
Desc: Deviation from the norm of height with respect to that which is expected according to age and gender norms.

Name: Hypoplastic ilia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the ilium.
Synonyms: Small wings of the pelvic girdle

Name: Abnormal acetabulum morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the acetabulum, i.e., the Acetabular part of hip bone, which together with the head of the femur forms the hip joint.

Name: Abducens palsy
Desc: Malfunction of the abducens nerve as manifested by impairment of the ability of the affected eye to be moved outward. Patients who develop abducens nerve palsy often present with binocular horizontal diplopia, which is a double vision when looking at objects side by side. There will be a notable weakness of the ipsilateral lateral rectus muscle leading to a deficit in of eye abduction on the affected side. Some patients may present with a constant head turning movement to maintain binocular fusion and to lessen the degree of diplopia.

Name: Small epiphyses
Desc: Reduction in the size or volume of epiphyses.

Name: Cerebral vasculitis
Desc: Inflammation of the blood vessels within the brain.

Name: CSF pleocytosis
Desc: An increased white blood cell count in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Abnormal CSF protein level
Desc: Any deviation from the normal range of a protein concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Tetraparesis
Desc: Weakness of all four limbs.

Name: Transient global amnesia
Desc: A paroxysmal, transient loss of memory function with preservation of immediate recall and remote memory but with a severe impairment of memory for recent events and ability to retain new information.

Name: Abnormal visual field test
Desc: Abnormal result of a test designed to test an individual's central and peripheral vision by determining the ability of the individual to perceive objects at differing locations of the visual field.

Name: Constitutional symptom
Desc: A symptom or manifestation indicating a systemic or general effect of a disease and that may affect the general well-being or status of an individual.

Name: Amaurosis fugax
Desc: A transient visual disturbance that is typically caused by a circulatory, ocular or neurological underlying condition.

Name: Woolly hair
Desc: The term woolly hair refers to an abnormal variant of hair that is fine, with tightly coiled curls, and often hypopigmented. Optical microscopy may reveal the presence of tight spirals and a clear diameter reduction as compared with normal hair. Electron microscopy may show flat, oval hair shafts with reduced transversal diameter.

Name: Trichodysplasia
Desc: Developmental dysplasia of the hair.

Name: White hair
Desc: Hypopigmented hair that appears white.

Name: Supernumerary naris
Desc: The presence of more than two nostrils.

Name: Abnormality of ethmoid sinus
Desc: An abnormality of an ethmoid sinus.

Name: Abnormal trachea morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the trachea.

Name: Anomalous origin of left pulmonary artery from ascending aorta
Desc: The left pulmonary artery originates from the ascending aorta in the presence of a pulmonary valve and main pulmonary artery.

Name: Fetal ascites
Desc: Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity during the fetal period.

Name: Abnormal lung morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the lung.

Name: Meckel diverticulum
Desc: Meckel's diverticulum is a congenital diverticulum located in the distal ileum.

Name: Abnormal stomach morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the stomach.

Name: Preductal coarctation of the aorta
Desc: Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized proximal to the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the preductal region of aortic arch.

Name: Neonatal asphyxia
Desc: Respiratory failure in the newborn.

Name: Ascending aorta hypoplasia
Desc: Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of or the entire ascending aorta.

Name: Subcutaneous calcification
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in subcutaneous tissue (i.e., the the lowermost layer of the integument).

Name: Perineal hemangioma
Desc: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, located in the perineal region, i.e., the region between the anus and the genitals.

Name: Prominent superficial veins
Desc: A condition in which superficial veins (i.e., veins just under the skin) are more conspicuous or noticable than normal.

Name: Hepatic hemangioma
Desc: A congenital vascular malformation in the liver composed of masses of blood vessels that are atypical or irregular in arrangement and size.

Name: Visceral hemangioma
Desc: A hemangioma arising from within visceral structures, the internal organs of the body.

Name: Tufted angioma
Desc: A vascular tumor of the skin and subcutaneous tissues and characterized by slow angiomatous proliferation.

Name: Abnormal pattern of respiration
Desc: An anomaly of the rhythm or depth of breathing.

Name: Impaired mastication
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the ability to masticate (chew), i.e., in the ability to crush and ground food in preparation for swallowing.

Name: Disturbance of facial expression
Desc: An abnormality of the gestures or movements executed with the facial muscles with which emotions such as fear, joy, sadness, surprise, and disgust can be expressed.

Name: Speech articulation difficulties
Desc: Impairment in the physical production of speech sounds.

Name: Abnormality of masticatory muscle
Desc: Any abnormality of the masticatory muscle.

Name: Abnormality of the nasal septum
Desc: An abnormality of the nasal septum.

Name: Preaxial polydactyly
Desc: A form of polydactyly in which the extra digit or digits are localized on the side of the thumb or great toe.

Name: Biliary tract abnormality
Desc: An abnormality of the biliary tree.

Name: Hyperlipidemia
Desc: An elevated lipid concentration in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of urine homeostasis
Desc: An abnormality of the composition of urine or the levels of its components.

Name: Acholic stools
Desc: Clay colored stools lacking bile pigment.

Name: Abnormality of the lymphatic system
Desc: An anomaly of the lymphatic system, a network of lymphatic vessels that carry a clear fluid called lymph unidirectionally towards either the right lymphatic duct or the thoracic duct, which in turn drain into the right and left subclavian veins respectively.

Name: Chondrocalcinosis
Desc: Radiographic evidence of articular calcification that represent calcium pyrophosphate depositions in soft tissue surrounding joints and at the insertions of tendons near joints (Entheses/Sharpey fibers) .

Name: Broad neck
Desc: Increased side-to-side width of the neck.

Name: Vocal cord paralysis
Desc: A loss of the ability to move the vocal folds.

Name: Abnormal skeletal muscle morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of a skeletal muscle.

Name: Malignant neoplasm of the central nervous system
Desc: A tumor that originates in the pineal gland, has moderate cellularity and tends to form rosette patterns.

Name: Miosis
Desc: Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil.

Name: Increased skull ossification
Desc: An increase in the magnitude or amount of ossification of the skull.

Name: Broad long bones
Desc: Increased cross-section (diameter) of the long bones. Note that widening may primarily affect specific regions of long bones (e.g., diaphysis or metaphysis), but this should be coded separately.

Name: Hypoplasia of the iris
Desc: Congenital underdevelopment of the iris.

Name: Flared elbow metaphyses
Synonyms: Flared wide portion of elbow bone

Name: Coxa vara
Desc: Coxa vara includes all forms of decrease of the femoral neck shaft angle (the angle between the neck and the shaft of the femur) to less than 120 degrees.

Name: Patellar dislocation
Desc: The kneecap normally is located within the groove termed trochlea on the distal femur and can slide up and down in it. Patellar dislocation occurs if the patella fully dislocates out of the groove.

Name: Abnormal femoral neck/head morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal neck or head of thigh bone
Abnormality of the femoral neck or head region

Name: Disproportionate short-limb short stature
Desc: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short limbs but an average-sized trunk.

Name: Abnormal leukocyte morphology
Desc: An abnormality of leukocytes.

Name: Decreased skull ossification
Desc: A reduction in the magnitude or amount of ossification of the skull.

Name: Anterior rib punctate calcifications
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in point-like foci within the anterior portion of one or more ribs.

Name: Abnormal pelvis bone ossification
Desc: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of any bone of the bony pelvis.
Synonyms: Abnormal maturation of the pelvis bone
Abnormal ossification involving the bones of the pelvis

Name: Preeclampsia
Desc: Pregnancy-induced hypertension in association with significant amounts of protein in the urine.

Name: Recurrent pneumonia
Desc: An increased susceptibility to pneumonia as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of pneumonia.

Name: Hypercalcemia
Desc: An abnormally increased calcium concentration in the blood.

Name: Parathyroid carcinoma
Desc: A malignancy of the parathyroid glands. Parathyroid carcinoma usually secretes parathyroid hormone, leading to hyperparathyroidism.

Name: Hypophosphatemia
Desc: An abnormally decreased phosphate concentration in the blood.

Name: Elevated circulating parathyroid hormone level
Desc: An abnormal increased concentration of parathyroid hormone.

Name: Abnormality of the parathyroid morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

Name: Uterine leiomyoma
Desc: The presence of a leiomyoma of the uterus.

Name: Polydipsia
Desc: Excessive thirst manifested by excessive fluid intake.

Name: Shortened QT interval
Desc: Decreased time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).

Name: Renal hamartoma
Desc: A disordered proliferation of mature tissues that are native to the kidneys.

Name: Mandibular pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the mandible.

Name: Testicular neoplasm
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the testis.

Name: Ungual fibroma
Desc: Flesh-colored papule in or around the nail bed. Ungual fibromas may be periungual (arising under the proximal nail fold) or subungual (originating under the nail plate).

Name: Abnormal chorioretinal morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the choroid and retina.

Name: Abnormal cochlea morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the cochlea.

Name: Stapes ankylosis
Desc: Stapes ankylosis refers to congenital or acquired fixation of the stapes (the stirrup-shaped small bone or ossicle in the middle ear), which is associated with conductive hearing resulting from impairment of the sound-conduction mechanism (the external auditory canal, tympanic membrane, and/or middle-ear ossicles).

Name: Dilatated internal auditory canal
Desc: The presence of a dilated inner part of external acoustic meatus.

Name: Abnormality of the Achilles tendon
Desc: An abnormality of the Achilles tendon.

Name: Reticular pigmentary degeneration
Desc: A type of retinal reticular pigmentation that forms a polygonal, netlike arrangement of hyperpigmented lines forming geometric patterns in the fundus.

Name: Peripheral visual field loss
Desc: Loss of peripheral vision with retention of central vision, resulting in a constricted circular tunnel-like field of vision.

Name: Pituitary hypothyroidism
Desc: A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in thyroid-stimulating hormone secretion.
Synonyms: Low thyroid gland function due to abnormal pituitary gland

Name: Renal artery stenosis
Desc: The presence of stenosis of the renal artery.

Name: Central diabetes insipidus
Desc: A form of diabetes insipidus related to a failure of vasopressin (AVP) release from the hypothalamus.

Name: Anterior pituitary dysgenesis
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior pituitary gland, also known as the adenohypophysis.

Name: Adrenocorticotropic hormone deficiency
Desc: A reduced ability to secrete adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), a hormone that stimulates the adrenal cortex to secrete of glucocorticoids such as cortisol.

Name: Fused cervical vertebrae
Desc: A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more cervical vertebral bodies with one another.

Name: Abnormal sacrum morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the sacral bone.

Name: Thoracic hemivertebrae
Desc: Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the thoracic spine.

Name: Syndactyly
Desc: Webbing or fusion of the fingers or toes, involving soft parts only or including bone structure. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers or toes in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "symphalangism".

Name: Secundum atrial septal defect
Desc: A kind of atrial septum defect arising from an enlarged foramen ovale, inadequate growth of the septum secundum, or excessive absorption of the septum primum.
Synonyms: Atrial septal defect, ostium secundum type

Name: Lumbar hyperlordosis
Desc: An abnormal accentuation of the inward curvature of the spine in the lumbar region.
Synonyms: Excessive inward curvature of lower spine

Name: Abnormal 5th finger morphology
Desc: An abnormality affecting one or both 5th fingers.

Name: Symphalangism of the thumb
Desc: Congenital fusion (ankylosis) of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb.
Synonyms: Symphalangism of the distal and proximal phalanges of the thumb

Name: Glioblastoma multiforme
Desc: A tumor arising from glia in the central nervous system with macroscopic regions of necrosis and hemorrhage. Microscopically, glioblastoma multiforme is characterized by regions of pseudopalisading necrosis, pleomorphic nuclei and cells, and microvascular proliferation.

Name: Agnosia
Desc: Inability to recognize objects not because of sensory deficit but because of the inability to combine components of sensory impressions into a complete pattern. Thus, agnosia is a neurological condition which results in an inability to know, to name, to identify, and to extract meaning from visual, auditory, or tactile impressions.

Name: Urinary tract neoplasm
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary system.

Name: Cardiac diverticulum
Desc: A cardiac diverticulum is a rare congenital malformation which is either fibrous or muscular.

Name: Amenorrhea
Desc: Absence of menses for an interval of time equivalent to a total of more than (or equal to) 3 previous cycles or 6 months.

Name: Diabetes insipidus
Desc: A state of excessive water intake and hypotonic (dilute) polyuria. Diabetes insipidus may be due to failure of vasopressin (AVP) release (central or neurogenic diabetes insipidus) or to a failure of the kidney to respond to AVP (nephrogenic diabetes insipidus).

Name: Narrow palm
Desc: For children from birth to 4 years of age, the palm width is more than 2 SD below the mean; for children from 4 to 16 years of age the palm width is below the 5th centile; or, the width of the palm appears disproportionately narrow for its length.

Name: Simple febrile seizure
Desc: A short generalized seizure, of a duration of <15 min, not recurring within 24 h, occurring during a febrile episode not caused by an acute disease of the nervous system intracranial infection or severe metabolic disturbance.

Name: Fused thoracic vertebrae
Desc: A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more thoracic vertebral bodies with one another.

Name: Neurofibromas
Desc: The presence of multiple cutaneous neurofibromas.

Name: 2-3 toe syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of toes two and three.
Synonyms: Syndactyly of second and third toes

Name: Protruding tongue
Desc: Tongue extending beyond the alveolar ridges or teeth at rest.

Name: Wide nasal base
Desc: Increased distance between the attachments of the alae nasi to the face.
Synonyms: Increased width of base of nose

Name: Small earlobe
Desc: Reduced volume of the earlobe.

Name: Abnormal posterior cranial fossa morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the fossa cranii posterior (the posterior fossa), which is made up primarily of the occipital bone and which surrounds to the foramen magnum.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the posterior cranial fossa

Name: Flat forehead
Desc: A forehead with abnormal flatness.

Name: Unilateral ptosis
Desc: A unilateral form of ptosis.

Name: Prominent crus of helix
Desc: The presence of an abnormally prominent of the crus of the helix. That is, development of the crus helix to the same degree as an average antihelix stem or helix.
Synonyms: Abnormal prominence of the crus of the ear

Name: Slender finger
Desc: Fingers that are disproportionately narrow (reduced girth) for the hand/foot size or build of the individual.

Name: Narrow naris
Desc: Slender, slit-like aperture of the nostril.

Name: Hydrocele testis
Desc: Accumulation of clear fluid in the between the layers of membrane (tunica vaginalis) surrounding the testis.

Name: Single transverse palmar crease
Desc: The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease.

Name: Situs inversus totalis
Desc: A left-right reversal (or "mirror reflection") of the anatomical location of the major thoracic and abdominal organs.
Synonyms: All organs on wrong side of body

Name: Median cleft palate
Desc: Cleft palate of the midline of the palate.

Name: Short 5th finger
Desc: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the fifth finger, also known as the little finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic phalanges of the little finger
Short phalanges of the little finger

Name: 3-4 toe syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of toes three and four.

Name: Abnormal fallopian tube morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the fallopian tube.

Name: Primary peritoneal carcinoma
Desc: A type of cancer that originates in the peritoneum. It is to be distinguished from metastatic cancer of the peritoneum. Peritoneal cancer can occur anywhere in the abdominal space, and affects the surface of organs contained inside the peritoneum.

Name: Prostate cancer
Desc: A cancer of the prostate.

Name: Abnormal joint morphology
Desc: An abnormal structure or form of the joints, i.e., one or more of the articulations where two bones join.

Name: Delayed closure of the anterior fontanelle
Desc: A delay in closure (ossification) of the anterior fontanelle, which generally undergoes closure around the 18th month of life.
Synonyms: Delayed closure of the bregma sutures
Delayed closure of the soft spot on the skull
Late closure of large anterior fontanel
Late closure of soft spot on the skull
Late closure of the bregma sutures
Later than typical closing of soft spot of skull

Name: Abnormal thrombocyte morphology
Desc: An abnormality of platelets.

Name: Abnormal granulocyte morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality or abnormal count of granulocytes.

Name: Inflammatory abnormality of the eye
Desc: Inflammation of the eye, parts of the eye or the periorbital region.

Name: Hypoplastic scapulae
Desc: Underdeveloped scapula.

Name: Short clavicles
Desc: Reduced length of the clavicles.

Name: Wormian bones
Desc: The presence of extra bones within a cranial suture. Wormian bones are irregular isolated bones which appear in addition to the usual centers of ossification of the cranium.
Synonyms: Islands of bone within cranial sutures

Name: Short face
Desc: Facial height (length) is more than two standard deviations below the mean (objective); or an apparent decrease in the height (length) of the face (subjective).

Name: Short middle phalanx of the 5th finger
Desc: Hypoplastic/small middle phalanx of the fifth finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic middle phalanx of the 5th finger
Hypoplastic/small middle phalanx of the 5th finger
Hypoplastic/small middle phalanx of the little finger
Short middle bone of the little finger
Short middle bone of the pinkie finger
Short middle bone of the pinky finger
Short middle phalanx of the little finger

Name: Diaphyseal thickening
Synonyms: Thickening of shaft or central part of long bones

Name: Optic nerve coloboma
Desc: A cleft of the optic nerve that extends inferiorly.

Name: Coarctation of the descending aortic arch
Desc: Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized to the region of the descending trunk of arch of aorta.

Name: Abnormal left ventricular outflow tract morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the outflow tract of the left ventricle.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the left ventricular outflow tract

Name: Perimembranous ventricular septal defect
Desc: A ventricular septal defect that is confluent with and involves the membranous septum and is bordered by an atrioventricular valve, not including the type 3 VSDs.

Name: Hypoplastic aortic arch
Desc: Underdevelopment of the arch of aorta.

Name: Aortic valve atresia
Desc: A congenital disorder of the aortic valve in which the orifice of the valve fails to develop.

Name: Pseudocoarctation of the aorta
Desc: Pseudocoarctation is a congenital anomaly of kinking, or buckling, of the aorta without a pressure gradient across the lesion. It is characterized by elongation and kinking of the aorta at the level of the ligamentum arteriosum.

Name: Extrahepatic biliary duct atresia
Desc: Atresia in the extrahepatic bile duct.

Name: Mitral stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the orifice of the mitral valve.

Name: Supravalvular aortic stenosis
Desc: A pathological narrowing in the region above the aortic valve associated with restricted left ventricular outflow.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
Synonyms: Absent/small outermost bone of little finger
Absent/small outermost bone of pinkie finger
Absent/small outermost bone of pinky finger
Absent/underdeveloped outermost bone of pinky finger

Name: Hypoplastic fifth toenail
Desc: Underdeveloped nails of the fifth toes.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 5th toe
Vestibular dysfunction
Desc: An abnormality of the functioning of the vestibular apparatus.

Name: Conjunctivitis
Desc: Inflammation of the conjunctiva.

Name: Large vessel vasculitis
Desc: A type of vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessel walls) affecting large arteries such as the aorta and branches of the aorta.

Name: Scleritis
Desc: Inflammation of the sclera.
Synonyms: Inflammation of the outer white part of the eye

Name: Episcleritis
Desc: Inflammation of the episclera, a thin layer of tissue covering the white part (sclera) of the eye.
Synonyms: Inflammation of the thin layer on top of the white part of eye

Name: Hypoargininemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of arginine in the blood.

Name: Retinal detachment
Desc: Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium.

Name: Posterior embryotoxon
Desc: A posterior embryotoxon is the presence of a prominent and anteriorly displaced line of Schwalbe.

Name: Retinal coloboma
Desc: A notch or cleft of the retina.
Synonyms: Hole in the back of the eye

Name: Optic nerve dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the optic nerve.

Name: Abnormal cortical bone morphology
Desc: An abnormality of compact bone (also known as cortical bone), which forms the dense surface of bones.

Name: Abnormality of the middle ear
Desc: An abnormality of the middle ear.

Name: Missing ribs
Desc: A developmental anomaly with absence of one or more ribs.

Name: Depressed nasal tip
Desc: Decreased distance from the nasal tip to the nasal base.

Name: Abnormal macular morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the macula lutea, which is an oval-shaped highly pigmented yellow spot near the center of the retina.

Name: Renal tubular acidosis
Desc: Acidosis owing to malfunction of the kidney tubules with accumulation of metabolic acids and hyperchloremia, potentially leading to complications including hypokalemia, hypercalcinuria, nephrolithiasis and nephrocalcinosis.
Synonyms: Accumulation of acid in body due to kidney problem

Name: Ureteral atresia
Desc: A developmental defect defined by the failure of the formation of the lumen (tube) of the ureter.

Name: Decreased circulating IgG2 level
Desc: A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG2 subclass in the blood circulation.

Name: Flat acetabular roof
Desc: Flattening of the superior part of the acetabulum, which is a cup-shaped cavity at the base of the hipbone into which the ball-shaped head of the femur fits. The acetabular roof thereby appears horizontal rather than arched, as it normally does.

Name: Narrow greater sciatic notch
Desc: A narrowing of the sacrosciatic notch, i.e., the deep indentation in the posterior border of the hip bone at the point of union of the ilium and ischium.

Name: Abnormal iliac wing morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the ilium ala. This is the large expanded portion of the ilum which bounds the greater pelvis laterally.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the wing of the ilium

Name: Bowing of the legs
Desc: A bending or abnormal curvature affecting a long bone of the leg.

Name: Thoracolumbar kyphosis
Desc: Hyperconvexity of the thoracolumbar spine producing a rounded or humped appearance.

Name: Parietal bossing
Desc: Parietal bossing is a marked prominence in the parietal region.

Name: Limited elbow extension
Desc: Limited ability to straighten the arm at the elbow joint.

Name: Short nasal bridge
Desc: Decreased superior-inferior length of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose.
Synonyms: Decreased length of bridge of nose

Name: Spinal canal stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the spinal canal.

Name: Trident hand
Desc: A hand in which the fingers are of nearly equal length and deflected at the first interphalangeal joint, so as to give a forklike shape consisting of separation of the first and second as well as the third and fourth digits.

Name: Cervical spinal canal stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the cervical spinal canal.

Name: Short proximal phalanx of finger
Desc: Congenital hypoplasia of one or more proximal phalanx of finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanges of the hand

Name: Functional abnormality of the middle ear
Desc: An abnormality of the function of the middle ear.
Synonyms: Functional abnormality of the middle ear

Name: Knee joint hypermobility
Desc: The ability of the knee to move past its normal range of motion, (knee hyperextension is greater than 10 degrees).

Name: Abnormality of reproductive system physiology
Desc: An abnormal functionality of the genital system.

Name: Hyperaldosteronism
Desc: Overproduction of the mineralocorticoid aldosterone by the adrenal cortex.

Name: Paradoxical increased cortisol secretion on dexamethasone suppression test
Increased body weight
Desc: Abnormally increased body weight.

Name: Increased serum estradiol
Desc: An elevation above normal limits of the concentration of estradiol in the circulation.

Name: Increased circulating androstenedione concentration
Desc: Increased concentration of androstenedione in the blood circulation.

Name: Elevated serum 11-deoxycortisol
Desc: Increased concentration of 11-deoxycortisol in the circulation. 11-deoxycorticosterone, which is also known as simply deoxycorticosterone and 21-hydroxyprogesterone, is a steroid hormore that is produces in the adrenals and is a precursor to aldosterone.

Name: Increased circulating androgen concentration
Desc: An elevation of the blood concentration of an androgen, that is, of a steroid hormone that controls development and maintenance of masculine characteristics. The androgens include testosterone and Dehydroepiandrosterone.

Name: Abnormal circulating dehydroepiandrosterone concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone in the circulation.

Name: Displacement of the urethral meatus
Desc: A displacement of the external urethral orifice from its normal position (in males normally placed at the tip of glans penis, in females normally placed about 2.5 cm behind the glans clitoridis and immediately in front of that of the vagina).
Synonyms: Displacement of the external urethral orifice
Displacement of the male external urethral orifice

Name: Exaggerated cupid's bow
Desc: More pronounced paramedian peaks and median notch of the Cupid's bow.

Name: Ectopic anus
Desc: Abnormal displacement or malposition of the anus.

Name: Broad hallux phalanx
Desc: An increase in width in one or more phalanges of the big toe.

Name: Ankyloglossia
Desc: Short or anteriorly attached lingual frenulum, associated with limited mobility of the tongue.

Name: Tented upper lip vermilion
Desc: Triangular appearance of the oral aperture with the apex in the midpoint of the upper vermilion and the lower vermilion forming the base.

Name: Hypoplastic female external genitalia
Desc: Underdevelopment of part or all of the female external reproductive organs (which include the mons pubis, labia majora, labia minora, Bartholin glands, and clitoris).

Name: Aplastic clavicle
Desc: Absence of the clavicles as a developmental defect.

Name: Thick hair
Desc: Increased density of hairs, i.e., and elevated number of hairs per unit area.

Name: Broad ribs
Desc: Increased width of ribs

Name: Deep plantar creases
Desc: The presence of unusually deep creases (ridges/wrinkles) on the skin of sole of foot.
Synonyms: Deep wrinkles in soles of feet

Name: Ovoid vertebral bodies
Desc: When viewed in lateral radiographs, vertebral bodies have a roughly rectangular configuration. This term applies if the vertebral body appears rounded or oval.

Name: Curly eyelashes
Desc: Abnormally curly or curved eyelashes.

Name: Short hallux
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the big toe.

Name: Widow's peak
Desc: Frontal hairline with bilateral arcs to a low point in the midline of the forehead.
Synonyms: Pointed hairline at front of head

Name: Congenital pseudoarthrosis of the clavicle
Desc: The two portions of the clavicle (corresponding to the two primary ossification centers of the clavicle) are connected by a fibrous bridge that is contiguous with the periosteum, and a synovial membrane develops, resulting in a clavicle with a bipartite appearance radiographically. Congenital pseudarthrosis of the clavicle generally presents as a painless mass or swelling over the clavicle.

Name: Ridged fingernail
Desc: Longitudinal, linear prominences in the fingernail plate.

Name: Abnormality of hair texture
Desc: An abnormality of the texture of the hair.

Name: Midline nasal groove
Desc: An abnormal groove on the midline of the nose that may extend to the nasal tip.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the skull
Bifid uterus
Desc: The presence of a bifid uterus.

Name: Short lingual frenulum
Desc: The presence of an abnormally short lingual frenulum.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the shoulder musculature
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the muscles of the shoulder.

Name: Asymmetry of the nares
Desc: Asymmetry or size difference between the left and right nostril.

Name: Unilateral hypoplasia of pectoralis major muscle
Desc: Hypoplasia (underdevelopment) of the pectoralis minor on only one side of the chest.
Synonyms: Small pec muscle on one side
Underdeveloped pec muscle on one side

Name: Abnormal reproductive system morphology
Desc: A structural or developmental anomaly of any of the tissues involved in the genital system.

Name: Vertical orbital dystopia
Desc: The orbits do not lie on the same horizontal plane, that is, one eye is lower than the other.

Name: Sparse eyebrow
Desc: Decreased density/number of eyebrow hairs.

Name: Osteopetrosis
Desc: Abnormally increased formation of dense trabecular bone tissue. Despite the increased density of bone tissue, osteopetrotic bones tend to be more fracture-prone than normal.

Name: Mottled pigmentation
Desc: Patchy and irregular skin pigmentation.

Name: Lissencephaly
Desc: A spectrum of malformations of cortical development caused by insufficient neuronal migration that subsumes the terms agyria, pachygyria and subcortical band heterotopia. See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.
Synonyms: Fewer or absent grooves in brain

Name: Septo-optic dysplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the optic nerve and absence of the septum pellucidum.

Name: Abnormal brainstem morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the brainstem.

Name: Fibular aplasia
Desc: Absence of the fibula.

Name: Broad metatarsal
Desc: Increased side-to-side width of a metatarsal bone.

Name: Preaxial foot polydactyly
Desc: Duplication of all or part of the first ray.
Synonyms: Partial/complete duplication of the phalanges of the big toe

Name: Malignant hyperthermia
Desc: Malignant hyperthermia is characterized by a rapid increase in temperature to 39-42 degrees C in response to inhalational anesthetics such as halothane or to muscle relaxants such as succinylcholine.

Name: Nodular pattern on pulmonary HRCT
Desc: A nodular pattern is characterised on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography by the presence of numerous rounded opacities that range from 2 mm to 1 cm in diameter, with micronodules defined as smaller than 3 mm in diameter.

Name: Systemic lupus erythematosus
Desc: A chronic, relapsing, inflammatory, and often febrile multisystemic disorder of connective tissue, characterized principally by involvement of the skin, joints, kidneys, and serosal membranes.

Name: Limb muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength and weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.

Name: Nuchal rigidity
Desc: Resistance of the extensor muscles of the neck to being bent forwards (i.e., impaired neck flexion) as a result of muscle spasm of the extensor muscles of the neck. Nuchal rigidity is not a fixed rigidity. Nuchal rigidity has been used as a bedside test for meningism, although its sensitivity for this purpose has been debated.

Name: Prostatitis
Desc: The presence of inflammation of the prostate.

Name: Abnormality of the outer ear
Desc: An abnormality of the external ear.

Name: Abnormal retinal morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the retina.

Name: Cerebral edema
Desc: Abnormal accumulation of fluid in the brain.

Name: Lymphoid leukemia
Desc: A malignant lymphocytic neoplasm of B-cell or T-cell lineage involving primarily the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. This category includes precursor or acute lymphoblastic leukemias and chronic leukemias.

Name: Sepsis
Desc: Systemic inflammatory response to infection.

Name: Freckling
Desc: The presence of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.

Name: Brachytelomesophalangy
Desc: Disproportionately short middle and distal phalanges compared to the hand/foot.
Synonyms: Progressive brachydactyly of middle and distal phalanges
Short middle and distal phalanges of digits ii through v

Name: Abnormal T cell count
Desc: A deviation from the normal count of T cells.

Name: Cholangitis
Desc: Inflammation of the biliary ductal system, affecting the intrahepatic or extrahepatic portions, or both.

Name: Early balding
Desc: Loss of scalp hair at an earlier than normal age.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the fovea
Desc: Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.

Name: Decreased circulating copper concentration
Desc: A reduced concentration of copper in the blood.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the sacrum
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the sacral bone.

Name: Sacrococcygeal teratoma
Desc: A teratoma arising in the sacro-coccygeal region.

Name: Foot polydactyly
Desc: A kind of polydactyly characterized by the presence of a supernumerary toe or toes.
Synonyms: Duplication of bones of the toes

Name: Abnormality of thumb phalanx
Desc: A structural anomaly of one or more phalanges of the thumb.

Name: Cloverleaf skull
Desc: Trilobar skull configuration when viewed from the front or behind.

Name: Prominent scrotal raphe
Desc: Increased size of the ridge of tissue that extends along the midline of the scrotum.

Name: Preauricular skin furrow
Desc: A groove of the skin immediately in front of the ear.
Synonyms: Skin groove in front of the ear
Skin sulcus in front of the ear

Name: Palmoplantar cutis gyrata
Desc: Cutis gyrata of palms and soles.
Synonyms: Cutis gyrata of palms and soles

Name: Leukocoria
Desc: An abnormal white reflection from the pupil rather than the usual black reflection.

Name: Short lower limbs
Desc: Shortening of the legs related to developmental hypoplasia of the bones of the leg.

Name: Abnormal meningeal morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the Meninges, including any abnormality of the Dura mater, the Arachnoid mater, and the Pia mater.

Name: Abnormal subarachnoid space morphology
Desc: Abnormality in the space in the meninges beneath the arachnoid membrane and above the pia mater that contains the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Arachnoid cyst
Desc: An extra-parenchymal and intra-arachnoidal collection of fluid with a composition similar to that of cerebrospinal fluid.
Synonyms: Fluid-filled sac located in membrane surrounding brain or spinal cord

Name: CSF lymphocytic pleiocytosis
Desc: An increased lymphocyte count in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Posterior fossa cyst at the fourth ventricle
Generalized-onset seizure
Desc: A generalized-onset seizure is a type of seizure originating at some point within, and rapidly engaging, bilaterally distributed networks. The networks may include cortical and subcortical structures but not necessarily the entire cortex.

Name: Spinal arachnoid cyst
Desc: Presence of arachnoid cysts of the spinal canal extradurally in the epidural space.
Synonyms: Epidural arachnoid cysts of the spinal canal

Name: Abnormal eye morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the globe of the eye, or bulbus oculi.

Name: Stiff neck
Desc: A sensation of tightness in the neck when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity. Neck stiffness often involves soreness and difficulty moving the neck, especially when trying to turn the head to the side.

Name: Calcification of muscles
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in muscle tissue.

Name: Iridocyclitis
Desc: A type of anterior uveitis, in which there is Inflammation of the iris and the ciliary body.

Name: Abnormality of optic chiasm morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the optic chiasm.The optic chiasm, located below the hypothalamus, is a partial crossing of the optic nerves.

Name: Iris hypopigmentation
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation of the iris.

Name: Cerebellar cortical atrophy
Desc: Atrophy (wasting) of the cerebellar cortex.

Name: Hyperacusis
Desc: Over-sensitivity to certain frequency ranges of sound.

Name: Abnormal cardiovascular system physiology
Desc: Abnormal functionality of the cardiovascular system.

Name: Hypoparathyroidism
Desc: A condition caused by a deficiency of parathyroid hormone characterized by hypocalcemia and hyperphosphatemia.

Name: Enlarged joints
Desc: Increase in size of one or more joints.

Name: Reduced carnitine O-palmitoyltransferase level
Desc: Reduced carnitine O-palmitoyltransferase level, leading to a reduced activity of the reaction: palmitoyl-CoA + L-carnitine = CoA + L-palmitoylcarnitine.

Name: Exercise-induced myalgia
Desc: The occurrence of an unusually high amount of muscle pain following exercise.

Name: Decreased plasma free carnitine
Desc: A decreased concentration of free (unbound) carnitine in the blood.

Name: Decreased plasma total carnitine
Desc: A decreased concentration of total carnitine in the blood.

Name: Red-brown urine
Desc: An abnormal red-brown color of the urine.

Name: Elevated circulating acylcarnitine concentration
Desc: An abnormally increased concentration in the blood circulation of acylcarnitine, which is produced by reversible esterification of the 3-hydroxyl group of carnitine.

Name: Rhabdomyolysis
Desc: Breakdown of muscle fibers that leads to the release of muscle fiber contents (myoglobin) into the bloodstream.

Name: Cold-induced muscle cramps
Desc: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles brought on by exposure to cold temperatures.

Name: Exercise-induced muscle cramps
Desc: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles brought on by physical exertion.

Name: Renal tubular epithelial necrosis
Desc: Coagulative necrosis of tubular epithelial cells, defined as cells with increased cytoplasmic eosinophilia and nucleus that has a condensed chromatin pattern with fuzzy nuclear contour or has barely visible nuclear basophilic staining. The extent of cortical tubular necrosis is scoredsemiquantitatively as none, mild (less than 25% tubules with necrosis), moderate (25-50 percent), and severe (over 50%).

Name: Intermittent painful muscle spasms
Desc: History of repeated intermittent involuntary muscle contractions that were painful.

Name: Polycystic kidney dysplasia
Desc: The presence of multiple cysts in both kidneys.

Name: Hypoketotic hypoglycemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of glucose in the blood associated with a reduced concentration of ketone bodies.

Name: Hepatic calcification
Desc: The presence of abnormal calcium deposition in the liver.

Name: Abnormality of the humeroulnar joint
Desc: An anomaly of the joint between the trochlear notch of ulna and the trochlea of humerus, which is part of the elbow joint.

Name: Macular degeneration
Desc: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells of the macula lutea.

Name: Vitreoretinopathy
Desc: Ocular abnormality characterised by premature degeneration of the vitreous and the retina that may be associated with increased risk of retinal detachment.

Name: Dextrocardia
Desc: The heart is located in the right hand sided hemithorax. That is, there is a left-right reversal (or "mirror reflection") of the anatomical location of the heart in which the heart is locate on the right side instead of the left.
Synonyms: Heart tip and four chambers point towards right side of body

Name: Bifid ureter
Desc: Incomplete duplication of the ureter.

Name: Recurrent bronchitis
Desc: An increased susceptibility to bronchitis as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchitis.

Name: Rickets
Desc: Rickets is divided into two major categories including calcipenic and phosphopenic. Hypophosphatemia is described as a common manifestation of both categories. Hypophosphatemic rickets is the most common type of rickets that is characterized by low levels of serum phosphate, resistance to ultraviolet radiation or vitamin D intake. There are several issues involved in hypophosphatemic rickets such as calcium, vitamin D, phosphorus deficiencies. Moreover, other disorder can be associated with its occurrence such as absorption defects due to pancreatic, intestinal, gastric, and renal disorders and hepatobiliary disease. Symptoms are usually seen in childhood and can be varied in severity. Severe forms may be linked to bowing of the legs, poor bone growth, and short stature as well as joint and bone pain. Hypophosphatemic rickets are associated with renal excretion of phosphate, hypophosphatemia, and mineral defects in bones. The familial type of the disease is the most common type of rickets.

Name: Osteomalacia
Desc: Osteomalacia is a general term for bone weakness owing to a defect in mineralization of the protein framework known as osteoid. This defective mineralization is mainly caused by lack in vitamin D. Osteomalacia in children is known as rickets.

Name: Abnormality of limb bone morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of bones of the arms or legs.

Name: Abnormality of macular pigmentation
Desc: Abnormality of macular or foveal pigmentation.

Name: Hyperplastic colonic polyposis
Desc: Presence of multiple hyperplastic polyps in the colon. Hyperplastic polyps are generally about 5 mm in size and show hyperplastic mucosal proliferation.

Name: Adenomatous colonic polyposis
Desc: Presence of multiple adenomatous polyps in the colon.

Name: Neoplasm of the gastrointestinal tract
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Juvenile colonic polyposis
Desc: The presence of more than 5 juvenile polyps of the colon. The term juvenile polyps refer to a special histopathology and not the age of onset as the polyp might be diagnosed at all ages. The juvenile polyp has a spherical appearance and is microscopically characterized by overgrowth of an oedematous lamina propria with inflammatory cells and cystic glands.

Name: Rectal polyposis
Desc: The presence of multiple rectal hyperplastic/adenomatous polyps.

Name: Colorectal polyposis
Desc: Multiple abnormal growths that arise from the lining of the large intestine (colon or rectum) and protrude into the intestinal lumen.

Name: Intussusception
Desc: An abnormality of the intestine in which part of the intestine invaginates (telescopes) into another part of the intestine.

Name: Duodenal adenocarcinoma
Desc: A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the duodenum.

Name: Endometrial carcinoma
Desc: A carcinoma of the endometrium, the mucous lining of the uterus.

Name: Desmoid tumors
Desc: Benign, slow-growing tumors without any metastatic potential. Despite their benign nature, they can damage nearby structures causing organ dysfunction. Histologically they resemble low-grade fibrosarcomas, but they are very locally aggressive and tend to recur even after complete resection. There is a tendency for recurrence in the setting of prior surgery and the most common localisation of these tumors is intraabdominal from smooth muscle cells of the instestine.

Name: Gastric diverticulum
Desc: An outpouching of the gastric wall.

Name: Neoplasm of the large intestine
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the large intestine.

Name: Bladder carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a carcinoma of the urinary bladder.

Name: Hodgkin lymphoma
Desc: A type of lymphoma characterized microscopically by multinucleated Reed-Sternberg cells.

Name: Hyperphenylalaninemia
Desc: An increased concentration of L-phenylalanine in the blood.

Name: Abnormal circulating biopterin concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of biopterin in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal circulating neopterin concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of neopterin in the blood circulation.

Name: Hypomagnesemia
Desc: An abnormally decreased magnesium concentration in the blood.

Name: Maturity-onset diabetes of the young
Desc: The term Maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY) was initially used for patients diagnosed with fasting hyperglycemia that could be treated without insulin for more than two years, where the initial diagnosis was made at a young age (under 25 years). Thus, MODY combines characteristics of type 1 diabetes (young age at diagnosis) and type 2 diabetes (less insulin dependence than type 1 diabetes). The term MODY is now most often used to refer to a group of monogenic diseases with these characteristics. Here, the term is used to describe hyperglycemia diagnosed at a young age with no or minor insulin dependency, no evidence of insulin resistence, and lack of evidence of autoimmune destruction of the beta cells.
Synonyms: Maturity onset diabetes of the young

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the hallux
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the big toe.

Name: Metacarpal synostosis
Desc: Fusion involving two or more metacarpal bones (A synostosis of the first metacarpal and the proximal phalanx of the thumb can also be observed, note that the first metacarpal bone corresponds to a proximal phalanx).

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanges of the hand
Synonyms: Absent/small middle finger bone of the hand
Absent/underdeveloped middle finger bone of the hand

Name: Phonophobia
Desc: An abnormally heightened sensitivity to loud sounds.

Name: Conjunctival hyperemia
Desc: Dilatation of the blood vessels of the conjunctiva leading to a red appearance of the sclera.

Name: Flushing
Desc: Recurrent episodes of redness of the skin together with a sensation of warmth or burning of the affected areas of skin.

Name: Focal sensory seizure with olfactory features
Desc: Seizures characterized by olfactory phenomena as its first clinical manifestation.

Name: Restless legs
Desc: A feeling of uneasiness and restlessness in the legs after going to bed (sometimes causing insomnia).

Name: Cluster headache
Desc: A type of headache characterized by repeated attacks of unilateral pain lasting 15 to 180 minutes and associated with local autonomic signs.

Name: Trigeminal neuralgia
Desc: A neuropathic disorder characterized by episodes of intense pain in the face, originating from the trigeminal nerve. One, two, or all three branches of the nerve may be affected.

Name: Decreased circulating ferritin concentration
Desc: Abnormally reduced concentration of ferritin, a ubiquitous intracellular protein that stores iron, in the blood.

Name: Iron accumulation in brain
Desc: An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in brain tissue.

Name: Hypomimic face
Desc: A reduced degree of motion of the muscles beneath the skin of the face, often associated with reduced facial crease formation.

Name: Abnormal caudate nucleus morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the caudate nucleus.

Name: Iron accumulation in globus pallidus
Desc: An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in the globus pallidus.

Name: Iron accumulation in substantia nigra
Desc: An anomalous build up of iron (Fe) in the substantia nigra.

Name: Abnormal thalamic MRI signal intensity
Desc: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus.

Name: Leg dystonia
Desc: A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the legs.

Name: Abnormal putamen morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the putamen, a brain nucleus which together with the caudate nucleus and fundus striati makes up the striatum.

Name: Abnormal dentate nucleus morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the dentate nucleus.

Name: Writer's cramp
Desc: A focal dystonia of the fingers, hand, and/or forearm that appears when the affected person attempts to do a task that requires fine motor movements such as writing or playing a musical instrument.

Name: Impaired smooth pursuit
Desc: An impairment of the ability to track objects with the ocular smooth pursuit system, a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion.

Name: Palatal myoclonus
Desc: Palatal myoclonus is characterized by myoclonic (rhythmic involuntary jerky) movements of the soft palate.

Name: Arm dystonia
Desc: A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the arms.

Name: Subcortical dementia
Desc: A particular type of dementia characterized by a pattern of mental defects consisting prominently of forgetfulness, slowness of thought processes, and personality or mood change.

Name: Upgaze palsy
Desc: A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze above the horizontal meridian.

Name: Akinesia
Desc: Inability to initiate changes in activity or movement and to perform ordinary volitional movements rapidly and easily.

Name: Obsessive-compulsive trait
Desc: The presence of one or more obsessive-compulsive personality traits. Obsessions refer to persistent intrusive thoughts, and compulsions to intrusive behaviors, which the affected person experiences as involuntary, senseless, or repugnant.

Name: Delusions
Desc: A false belief that is held despite evidence to the contrary.

Name: Abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit
Desc: An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impaired smooth-pursuit eye movements.

Name: Gliosis
Desc: Gliosis is the focal proliferation of glial cells in the central nervous system.

Name: Abnormal posturing
Desc: Involuntary flexion or extension of the arms and legs.

Name: Simultanapraxia
Desc: A subset of motor impersistence, defined as the inability to perform more than two of the simple voluntary acts simultaneously, such as closing the eyes and protruding the tongue.

Name: Psychomotor deterioration
Desc: Loss of previously present mental and motor abilities.

Name: Extrapyramidal muscular rigidity
Desc: Muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement).

Name: Motor neuron atrophy
Desc: Wasting involving the motor neuron.

Name: Ulnar deviation of the hand
Desc: Divergence of the longitudinal axis of the hand at the wrist in a posterior (ulnar) direction (i.e., towards the little finger).

Name: Anterior pituitary hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the anterior pituitary gland.

Name: Adrenocorticotropin deficient adrenal insufficiency
Desc: Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in ACTH production.

Name: Abnormal response to ACTH stimulation test
Desc: An anomolous response to stimulation by adminstration of the adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH). ACTH stimulation normally stimulates the adrenal glands to release cortisol and adrenaline.
Synonyms: Abnormal response to adrenocorticotropic-hormone stimulation test
Abnormal response to corticotropin stimulation test

Name: Reduced circulating prolactin concentration
Desc: A reduced level of prolactin in the blood circulation. Prolactin is a protein hormone that is secreted by lactotrophs in the anterior pituitary and that stimulates mammary gland development and milk production.

Name: Flat capital femoral epiphysis
Desc: An abnormal flattening of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Synonyms: Flat end part of innermost thighbone

Name: Broad femoral neck
Desc: An abnormally wide femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).

Name: Moderately short stature
Desc: A moderate degree of short stature, more than -3 SD but not more than -4 SD from mean corrected for age and sex.

Name: Short femoral neck
Desc: An abnormally short femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).

Name: Spinal rigidity
Desc: Reduced ability to move the vertebral column with a resulting limitation of neck and trunk flexion.

Name: Axial muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the axial musculature (i.e., of the muscles of the head and neck, spine, and ribs).

Name: Erythematous macule
