Desc: A macule (flat, distinct, discolored area of skin less than 1 cm wide that does not involve any change in the thickness or texture of the skin) with a red or reddish color often associated with inflammation or irritation.

Name: Maculopapular exanthema
Desc: A skin rash that is characterized by diffuse cutaneous erythema with areas of skin elevation. It may evolve to vesicles or papules as part of a more severe clinical entity. Different degrees of angioedema with involvement of subcutaneous tissue may also appear.

Name: Elevated total serum tryptase
Desc: An abnormally elevated concentration of total tryptase (alpha and beta tryptase) in the blood circulation.

Name: Hypereosinophilia
Desc: A severely increased count of eosinophils in the blood defined as a blood eosinophil count of 1.5 × 10e9/L or greater (one and a half billion cells per liter).

Name: Abnormal vitamin B12 level
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of cobalamin (vitamin B12) in the blood. Vitamin B12 is one of the eight B vitamins.

Name: Leukemia
Desc: A cancer of the blood and bone marrow characterized by an abnormal proliferation of leukocytes.

Name: Abnormal Langerhans cell morphology
Desc: Any functional anomaly of Langerhans cells, which are dendritic cells in the epidermis and some other locations. Langerhans cells play roles in immune surveillance and homeostasis.

Name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with focal onset
Desc: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with focal onset is a focal-onset seizure which progresses into a bilateral tonic-clonic phase.
Synonyms: Generalised tonic-clonic seizures with focal onset
Generalized tonic-clonic seizures with focal onset

Name: Blepharitis
Desc: Inflammation of the eyelids.

Name: Iritis
Desc: Inflammation of the iris.

Name: Myeloproliferative disorder
Desc: Proliferation (excess production) of hemopoietically active tissue or of tissue which has embryonic hemopoietic potential.

Name: Abnormal oral mucosa morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the oral mucosa.

Name: Hyphema
Desc: Bleeding in the anterior chamber of the eye.

Name: Asymmetry of iris pigmentation
Desc: Asymmetry between the two irides or asymmetry between different parts of one iris.

Name: Abnormality of the pharynx
Desc: An anomaly of the pharynx, i.e., of the tubular structure extending from the base of the skull superiorly to the esophageal inlet inferiorly.

Name: Skin plaque
Desc: A plaque is a solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter.

Name: Paraplegia
Desc: Severe or complete weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities.

Name: Mucinous histiocytosis
Desc: Multiple subcutaneous non-fragile and skin-coloured papules characterized by interstitial infiltrate of spindle and epithelioid histiocytes, and mucin. There are well circumscribed aggregates of epithelioid histiocytes and mucin in the upper and middle dermis,with the histiocytes arranged between collagen bundles and separated from the epidermis by a Grenz zone.

Name: Sea-blue histiocytosis
Desc: An abnormality of histiocytes, in which the cells take on a sea blue appearance due to abnormally increased lipid content. Histiocytes are a type of macrophage. Sea-blue histiocytes are typically large macrophages from 20 to 60 micrometers in diameter with a single eccentric nucleus whose cytoplasm if packed with sea-blue or blue-green granules when stained with Wright-Giemsa.

Name: Absent eyelashes
Desc: Lack of eyelashes.

Name: Fragile skin
Desc: Skin that splits easily with minimal injury.

Name: Esophageal stricture
Desc: A pathological narrowing of the esophagus that is caused by the development of a ring of scar tissue that constricts the esophageal lumen.
Synonyms: Narrowing of esophagus due to inflammation and scar tissue
Narrowing of oesophagus due to inflammation and scar tissue

Name: Dermal atrophy
Desc: Partial or complete wasting (atrophy) of the skin.

Name: Palmoplantar keratosis with erythema and scale
Acral blistering
Desc: Bullae (defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls) of the skin with an acral distribution (affecting peripheral regions such as hands and feet).

Name: Recurrent loss of toenails and fingernails
Desc: Recurrent loss, or shedding, of the nails of the fingers and toes.
Synonyms: Recurrent loss of toenails and fingernails
Recurrent shedding of toenails and fingernails

Name: Onychogryposis
Desc: Nail that appears thick when viewed on end.

Name: Fragile nails
Desc: Nails that easily break.

Name: Onychogryposis of toenails
Desc: Thickened toenails.

Name: Onychogryposis of fingernail
Desc: Thickened fingernails.

Name: Abnormality of skin morphology
Desc: Any morphological abnormality of the skin.

Name: Ureterocele
Desc: A ureterocele is a congenital saccular dilatation of the distal segment of the ureter.

Name: Glomerular sclerosis
Desc: Accumulation of scar tissue within the glomerulus.

Name: Aplasia of the bladder
Desc: Aplasia (absence) of the urinary bladder.

Name: Oral mucosal blisters
Desc: Blisters arising in the mouth.

Name: Natal tooth
Desc: A tooth present at birth or erupting within the first month of life.

Name: Esophageal ulceration
Desc: Defect in the epithelium of the esophagus, essentially an open sore in the lining of the esophagus.

Name: Retinoblastoma
Desc: A tumor of the eye originating from cells of the retina.

Name: Dicarboxylic aciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of dicarboxylic acid in the urine.

Name: Decreased plasma carnitine
Desc: A decreased concentration of carnitine in the blood.

Name: Hypothermia
Desc: Reduced body temperature due to failed thermoregulation.

Name: Sudden episodic apnea
Desc: Recurrent bouts of sudden, severe apnea that may be life-threatening.

Name: Small nail
Desc: A nail that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped nail.

Name: Generalized joint laxity
Desc: Joint hypermobility (ability of a joint to move beyond its normal range of motion) affecting many or all joints of the body.

Name: 2-3 toe cutaneous syndactyly
Synonyms: Complete cutaneous syndactyly of second and third toes
Cutaneous syndactyly of second and third toes

Name: Short finger
Desc: Abnormally short finger associated with developmental hypoplasia.

Name: Single umbilical artery
Desc: Single umbilical artery (SUA) is the absence of one of the two umbilical arteries surrounding the fetal bladder and in the fetal umbilical cord.
Synonyms: Only one artery in umbilical cord instead of two

Name: Double outlet right ventricle with doubly committed ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
Desc: A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Synonyms: DORV with doubly committed VSD and pulmonary stenosis

Name: Abnormality of the philtrum
Desc: An abnormality of the philtrum.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the uvula
Desc: Underdevelopment or absence of the uvula.

Name: Blue cone monochromacy
Desc: A form of monochromacy in which vision is derived from the remaining preserved blue (S) cones and rod photoreceptors.

Name: Follicular hyperplasia
Desc: Lymphadenopathy (enlargement of lymph nodes) owing to hyperplasia of follicular (germinal) centers.

Name: Increased circulating interleukin 6
Desc: An increased concentration of interleukin-6 in the circulation.

Name: Generalized lymphadenopathy
Desc: A generalized form of lymphadenopathy.
Synonyms: Swollen lymph nodes affecting all regions of the body

Name: Decreased mean corpuscular volume
Desc: A reduction from normal of the mean corpuscular volume, or mean cell volume (MCV) of red blood cells (usually defined as an MCV below 80 femtoliters).

Name: Flank pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) and perceived to originate in the flank.

Name: Abdominal mass
Desc: An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the abdomen.

Name: Restrictive cardiomyopathy
Desc: Restrictive left ventricular physiology is characterized by a pattern of ventricular filling in which increased stiffness of the myocardium causes ventricular pressure to rise precipitously with only small increases in volume, defined as restrictive ventricular physiology in the presence of normal or reduced diastolic volumes (of one or both ventricles), normal or reduced systolic volumes, and normal ventricular wall thickness.

Name: Ureteral obstruction
Desc: Obstruction of the flow of urine through the ureter.

Name: Myelofibrosis
Desc: Replacement of bone marrow by fibrous tissue.

Name: Anasarca
Desc: An extreme form of generalized edema with widespread and massive edema due to effusion of fluid into the extracellular space.

Name: Pulmonary valve defects
Desc: Any defect in the valve connecting the heart and the pulmonary artery.

Name: Bilateral conductive hearing impairment
Desc: A bilateral type of conductive hearing impairment.

Name: Bilateral cryptorchidism
Desc: Absence of both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.

Name: Abnormal myelination
Desc: Any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons.

Name: Absence of the pulmonary valve
Desc: Refers to the specific combination of defects with a severely dysplastic pulmonary valve and massively dilated branch pulmonary arteries.

Name: Dysplastic pulmonary valve
Desc: A congenital malformation of the pulmonary valve characterized by leaflet deformation.

Name: Left aortic arch with right descending aorta and right ductus arteriosus
Desc: The ring may be completed by the ductal ligament.

Name: Left-to-right shunt
Desc: Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system from the left side of the heart to the right.

Name: Atlantoaxial abnormality
Desc: An anomaly of the atlantoaxial joint, i.e., of the joint between the first (atlas) and second (axis) cervical vertebrae.

Name: Astrocytoma
Desc: Astrocytoma is a neoplasm of the central nervous system derived from astrocytes. Astrocytes are a type of glial cell, and thus astrocytoma is a subtype of glioma.

Name: Abnormal palmar dermatoglyphics
Desc: An abnormality of the dermatoglyphs, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of palm of hand.

Name: Chronic atrophic gastritis
Desc: A form of chronic gastritis associated with atrophic gastric mucous membrane.

Name: Abnormality of the neck
Desc: An abnormality of the neck.

Name: Polyphagia
Desc: A neurological anomaly with gross overeating associated with an abnormally strong desire or need to eat.

Name: Horizontal eyebrow
Desc: An eyebrow that extends straight across the brow, without curve.

Name: Self-injurious behavior
Desc: Aggression towards oneself.

Name: Small face
Desc: A face that is short (HP:0011219) and narrow (HP:0000275).

Name: Abnormality iris morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the iris, which is the pigmented muscular tissue between the cornea and the lens, that is perforated by an opening called the pupil.

Name: Hand clenching
Desc: An abnormal hand posture in which the hands are clenched to fists. All digits held completely flexed at the metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints.

Name: Central apnea
Desc: Apnea resulting from depression of the respiratory centers in the medulla oblongata. There is a lack of respiratory effort rather than obstruction of airflow.

Name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanx of the hallux
Desc: An abnormal morphology of the distal phalanx of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Synonyms: Bullet-shaped outermost bone of big toe

Name: Long fingers
Desc: The middle finger is more than 2 SD above the mean for newborns 27 to 41 weeks EGA or above the 97th centile for children from birth to 16 years of age AND the five digits retain their normal length proportions relative to each other (i.e., it is not the case that the middle finger is the only lengthened digit), or, Fingers that appear disproportionately long compared to the palm of the hand.

Name: Abnormal vestibulo-ocular reflex
Desc: An abnormality of the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR). The VOR attempts to keep the image stable on the retina. Ideally passive or active head movements in one direction are compensated for by eye movements of equal magnitude.

Name: Abnormality of the fontanelles or cranial sutures
Desc: Any abnormality of the fontanelles (the regions covered by a thick membrane that normally ossify in the first two years of life) or the cranial sutures (the fibrous joints in which the articulating bones or cartilages of the skull are connected by sutural ligaments).

Name: Abnormal hemoglobin
Desc: Anomaly in the level or the function of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying protein of erythrocytes.

Name: Intellectual disability, borderline
Desc: Borderline intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 70-85.

Name: Chondrosarcoma
Desc: A slowly growing malignant neoplasm derived from cartilage cells.

Name: Sarcoma
Desc: A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells. Bone and soft tissue sarcomas are the main types of sarcoma. Sarcoma is usually highly malignant.

Name: Neoplasm of the parathyroid gland
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the parathyroid gland.

Name: Thoracic kyphosis
Desc: Over curvature of the thoracic region, leading to a round back or if sever to a hump.

Name: Delayed patellar ossification
Desc: Formation of bone in the patella later than normal.
Synonyms: Delayed bone maturation of the knee cap

Name: Wide proximal femoral metaphysis
Desc: Increased width of the proximal part of the shaft (metaphysis) of the femur.

Name: Anterior plagiocephaly
Desc: Asymmetry of the anterior part of the skull.

Name: Abnormality of cranial sutures
Desc: Any anomaly of a cranial suture, that is one of the six membrane-covered openings in the incompletely ossified skull of the fetus or newborn infant.

Name: Hemiatrophy of upper limb
Desc: Unilateral atrophy (reduction in size) of an arm.

Name: Anisospondyly
Desc: Abnormally increased variability of the size of the vertebral bodies.

Name: Oligosacchariduria
Desc: Increased urinary excretion of oligosaccharides (low molecular weight carbohydrate chains composed of at least three monosaccharide subunits), derived from a partial degradation of glycoproteins.

Name: Thick upper lip vermilion
Desc: Height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the midline more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Synonyms: Increased height of upper lip vermilion
Increased volume of upper lip vermilion
Thick red part of the upper lip
Thick vermilion border of upper lip

Name: Abnormality of the chin
Desc: An abnormality of the chin, i.e., of the inferior portion of the face lying inferior to the lower lip and including the central prominence of the lower jaw.

Name: Abnormal metatarsal morphology
Desc: Abnormalities of the metatarsal bones (i.e. of five tubular bones located between the tarsal bones of the hind- and mid-foot and the phalanges of the toes).
Synonyms: Abnormality of the long bone of foot

Name: Limited pronation/supination of forearm
Desc: A limitation of the ability to place the forearm in a position such that the palm faces anteriorly (supination) and to place the forearm in a position such that the palm faces posteriorly (pronation).

Name: Hypoplastic pelvis
Desc: Underdevelopment of the bony pelvis.

Name: Facial hirsutism
Desc: Excess facial hair.

Name: Narrow philtrum
Desc: Distance between the philtral ridges, measured just above the vermilion border, more than 2 standard deviations below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between the ridges of the philtrum.

Name: Abnormal ilium morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the ilium, the largest and uppermost bone of the pelvis.

Name: Disproportionate short-trunk short stature
Desc: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs.

Name: Bilateral coxa valga
Desc: The presence of bilateral coxa valga.

Name: Cystinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of cystine in the urine.

Name: Sudden death
Desc: Rapid and unexpected death.

Name: Drooling
Desc: Habitual flow of saliva out of the mouth.

Name: EEG with focal sharp waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

Name: EEG with generalized epileptiform discharges
Desc: EEG discharges recorded on the entire scalp typically seen in persons with epilepsy.

Name: Continuous spike and waves during slow sleep
Desc: Diffuse, bilateral and recently also unilateral or focal localization spike-wave occurring in slow sleep or non-rapid eye movement sleep.

Name: Abnormally low-pitched voice
Desc: An abnormally low-pitched voice.

Name: Abnormal speech prosody
Desc: An anomaly of the expressive patterns of speech that involve intonation, stress pattern, loudness variations, pausing, articulatory force, and rhythm.

Name: Horizontal nystagmus
Desc: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements.

Name: Paroxysmal dystonia
Desc: A form of dystonia characterized by episodes of dystonia (often hemidystonia or generalized) lasting from minutes to hours. There are no dystonic symptoms between episodes.

Name: Focal hemifacial clonic seizure
Desc: Focal seizure characterized at onset by clonic movements affecting half of the face.

Name: EEG with parietal sharp waves
Desc: EEG with sharp waves in the parietal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

Name: EEG with parietal focal spike waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the parietal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: Decreased lacrimation
Desc: Abnormally decreased lacrimation, that is, reduced ability to produce tears.

Name: Ileus
Desc: Acute obstruction of the intestines preventing passage of the contents of the intestines.

Name: Microcolon
Desc: A colon of abnormally small caliber.

Name: Loss of eyelashes
Desc: This term refers to the loss of eyelashes that were previously present.

Name: Corneal neovascularization
Desc: Ingrowth of new blood vessels into the cornea.
Synonyms: New blood vessel formation in cornea

Name: Chemosis
Desc: Edema (swelling) of the bulbar conjunctiva.

Name: Low hanging columella
Desc: Columella extending inferior to the level of the nasal base, when viewed from the side.
Synonyms: Columella extends below the ala nasi
Extension of the columella below the ala nasi

Name: Neonatal hyperbilirubinemia
Desc: A type of hyperbilirubinemia with neonatal onset.
Synonyms: High blood bilirubin levels in neonate

Name: Hypointensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
Desc: A darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.

Name: Echolalia
Desc: The tendency to repeat vocalizations made by another person.

Name: Overlapping toe
Desc: Describes a foot digit resting on the dorsal surface of an adjacent digit when the foot is at rest.

Name: Peripheral pulmonary artery stenosis
Desc: Stenosis of a peripheral branch of the pulmonary artery.

Name: Abnormal vena cava morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the structure of the veins that return deoxygenated blood from the body into the heart, i.e., the superior vena cava and the inferior vena cava.

Name: Abnormal hair whorl
Desc: An abnormal hair whorl (that is, a patch of hair growing in the opposite direction of the rest of the hair).

Name: Lumbar hypertrichosis
Desc: Excessive, increased hair growth located in the lumbar region.

Name: Lower extremity joint dislocation
Desc: Displacement or malalignment of one or more joints in the lower extremity (leg).

Name: Recurrent cutaneous abscess formation
Desc: An increased susceptibility to cutaneous abscess formation, as manifested by a medical history of recurrent cutaneous abscesses.

Name: Recurrent ear infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to ear infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of ear infections.

Name: Episodic tachypnea
Desc: Episodes of very rapid breathing.

Name: Apneic episodes in infancy
Desc: Recurrent episodes of apnea occurring during infancy.

Name: Poor suck
Desc: An inadequate sucking reflex, resulting in the difficult of newborns to be breast-fed.

Name: Agenesis of cerebellar vermis
Desc: Congenital absence of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Thin ribs
Desc: Ribs with a reduced diameter.

Name: Hypoplastic iliac wing
Desc: Underdevelopment of the ilium ala.

Name: Metaphyseal chondrodysplasia
Desc: An abnormality of skeletal development characterized by a disturbance of the metaphysis and its histological structure with relatively normal epiphyses and vertebrae.

Name: Metaphyseal cupping of metacarpals
Desc: Metaphyseal cupping affecting the metacarpal bones.
Synonyms: Cupping of wide portion of long bone of hand

Name: Abnormality of the calcaneus
Desc: An abnormality of the calcaneus, also known as the heel bone, one of the or heel bone, one of the components of the tarsus of the foot which make up the heel.

Name: Increased circulating gonadotropin level
Desc: Overproduction of gonadotropins (FSH, LH) by the anterior pituitary gland.

Name: Absence of secondary sex characteristics
Desc: No secondary sexual characteristics are present at puberty.
Synonyms: No secondary sexual characteristics at puberty

Name: Coronal craniosynostosis
Desc: Premature closure of the coronal suture of skull.

Name: Paranoia
Desc: A persecutory delusion of supposed hostility of others.

Name: Retractile testis
Desc: A testis that is located at the upper scrotum or lower inguinal canal and that can be made to descend completely into the scrotum without resistance by manual reduction but returns to its original position by the cremasteric reflex.

Name: Short chin
Desc: Decreased vertical distance from the vermilion border of the lower lip to the inferior-most point of the chin.

Name: Toe clinodactyly
Desc: Bending or curvature of a toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

Name: Overhanging nasal tip
Desc: Positioning of the nasal tip inferior to the nasal base.

Name: Hyperextensibility of the finger joints
Desc: The ability of the finger joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

Name: Bulbous tips of toes
Desc: An abnormality of the morphology of the toes, such that the tips of the toes are prominent and bulbous.

Name: Broad skull
Desc: Increased width of the skull.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nails
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the nail.

Name: Long toe
Desc: Toes that appear disproportionately long compared to the foot.

Name: Exaggerated startle response
Desc: An exaggerated startle reaction in response to a sudden unexpected visual or acoustic stimulus, or a quick movement near the face.

Name: Hypoplasia of the frontal lobes
Desc: Underdevelopment of the frontal lobe of the cerebrum.

Name: EEG with temporal focal spikes
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the temporal region.

Name: Epileptic encephalopathy
Desc: A condition in which epileptiform abnormalities are believed to contribute to the progressive disturbance in cerebral function. Epileptic encephalaopathy is characterized by (1) electrographic EEG paroxysmal activity that is often aggressive, (2) seizures that are usually multiform and intractable, (3) cognitive, behavioral and neurological deficits that may be relentless, and (4) sometimes early death.

Name: Opacification of the corneal stroma
Desc: Reduced transparency of the stroma of cornea.

Name: Abnormal spermatogenesis
Desc: Incomplete maturation or aberrant formation of the male gametes.

Name: Non-obstructive azoospermia
Desc: Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, resulting from a defect in the production of spermatozoa in the testes. This can be differentiated from obstructive azoospermia on the basis of testicular biopsy.

Name: Abnormal cerebellar vermis morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Renal tubular atrophy
Desc: The presence of renal tubules with thick redundant basement membranes, or a reduction of greater than 50% in tubular diameter compared to surrounding non-atrophic tubules.

Name: Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis
Desc: Segmental accumulation of scar tissue in individual (but not all) glomeruli.

Name: Proximal tubulopathy
Desc: Dysfunction of the proximal tubule, which is the portion of the duct system of the nephron of the kidney which leads from Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle.

Name: Renal phosphate wasting
Desc: High urine phosphate in the presence of hypophosphatemia.
Synonyms: Decreased tubular maximum for phosphate reabsorption per glomerular filtration rate

Name: Delayed epiphyseal ossification
Synonyms: Delayed maturation of end part of long bone

Name: Thin bony cortex
Desc: Abnormal thinning of the cortical region of bones.

Name: Bulging epiphyses
Desc: A morphological abnormality of epiphyses whereby they are abnormally outwardly curving (protuberant).

Name: Enlarged epiphyses
Desc: Increased size of epiphyses.

Name: Metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the metaphyses.
Synonyms: Irregular wide portion of a long bone

Name: Glycosuria
Desc: An increased concentration of glucose in the urine.

Name: Hyperphosphaturia
Desc: An increased excretion of phosphates in the urine.

Name: Low-molecular-weight proteinuria
Desc: Excretion in urine of proteins of a size smaller than albumin (molecular weight 69 kD).

Name: Hyperuricosuria
Desc: An abnormally high level of uric acid in the urine.

Name: High serum calcitriol
Desc: An increased concentration of calcitriol in the blood. Calcitriol is also known as 1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol or 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.

Name: Tubulointerstitial fibrosis
Desc: A progressive detrimental connective tissue deposition (fibrosis) on the kidney parenchyma involving the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney. Tubulointerstitial injury in the kidney is complex, involving a number of independent and overlapping cellular and molecular pathways, with renal interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy (IF/TA) as the final common pathway. However, IF and TA are separable, as shown by the profound TA in renal artery stenosis, which characteristically has little or no fibrosis (or inflammation). For new annotations it is preferable to annotate to the specific HPO terms for Renal interstitial lfibrosis and/or Renal tubular atrophy.

Name: Non-acidotic proximal tubulopathy
Desc: A type of proximal renal tubulopathy characterized by resorption defects leading to glycosuria, aminoaciduria, tubular proteinuria, renal hypophosphatemia, and urate tubular hyporeabsorption without bicarbonate loss.

Name: Renal hypophosphatemia
Desc: Renal hypophosphatemia is defined as reduced serum phosphate (e.g., below 0.70 mmol/l) and an inappropriately high renal phosphate excretion.

Name: Abnormality of the uterus
Desc: An abnormality of the uterus.

Name: Vaginal atresia
Desc: Congenital occlusion of the vagina or adhesion of the walls of the vagina causing occlusion.

Name: Abnormally large globe
Desc: Diffusely large eye (with megalocornea) without glaucoma.

Name: Redundant neck skin
Desc: Excess skin around the neck, often lying in horizontal folds.

Name: Pancreatic lymphangiectasis
Desc: The presence of lymphangiectasis in the pancreas.

Name: Pulmonary lymphangiectasia
Desc: Abnormal dilatation of the pulmonary lymphatic vessels. Lymphatic fluid in the lung is derived from normal leakage of fluid out of the blood capillaries in the lung. In pulmonary lymphangiectasia, the pulmonary lymphatics are not properly connected and become dilated with fluid.

Name: Alveolar ridge overgrowth
Desc: Increased width of the alveolar ridges.
Synonyms: Hyperplasia of alveolar process of jaw

Name: Abnormal renal morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the kidney.
Synonyms: Structural anomalies of the renal tract

Name: Ectodermal dysplasia
Desc: Ectodermal dysplasia is a group of conditions in which there is abnormal development of the skin, hair, nails, teeth, or sweat glands.

Name: Arthralgia of the hip
Desc: Joint pain affecting the hip.

Name: Postexertional malaise
Desc: A subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation and that is induced by exertion or exercise.

Name: Abnormal patella morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the patella (knee cap).

Name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the elbow
Synonyms: Abnormality of end part of the elbow bone

Name: Fragmentation of the metacarpal epiphyses
Desc: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the metacarpals.
Synonyms: Fragmentation of end part of the long bone of hand

Name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the feet
Desc: Any abnormality of the epiphyses of the feet.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the end part of the foot bone

Name: Epiphyseal dysplasia
Synonyms: Abnormal development of end part of bone
Abnormal development of the ends of long bones in arms and legs

Name: Retinal degeneration
Desc: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells.

Name: Abnormality of the endocrine system
Desc: An abnormality of the endocrine system.

Name: Absent eyebrow
Desc: Absence of the eyebrow.

Name: Abnormality of pattern visual evoked potentials
Olivopontocerebellar hypoplasia
Desc: Hypoplasia of the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus.

Name: Abnormal metacarpal morphology
Desc: Irregularly shaped metacarpal bones of varying degree.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of long bones of hand

Name: Narrow forehead
Desc: Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations below the mean (objective); or apparently narrow intertemporal region (subjective).

Name: Incisor macrodontia
Desc: Increased size of the incisor tooth.

Name: Fatiguable weakness of proximal limb muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of a skeletal muscle of proximal part of a limb that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Tongue fasciculations
Desc: Fasciculations or fibrillation affecting the tongue muscle.

Name: Spinal muscular atrophy
Desc: Muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.

Name: Contractures involving the joints of the feet
Liposarcoma
Desc: Malignant neoplasms which probably originate in primitive mesenchymal stem cell populations differentiating down a lipomatous pathway.

Name: Lip hyperpigmentation
Synonyms: Darkening of skin of the lips

Name: Entropion
Desc: An abnormal inversion (turning inward) of the eyelid (usually the lower) towards the globe. Entropion is usually acquired as a result of involutional or cicatricial processes but may occasionally be congenital.

Name: Short umbilical cord
Desc: Decreased length of the umbilical cord.

Name: Widely patent fontanelles and sutures
Desc: An abnormally increased width of the cranial fontanelles and sutures.

Name: Premature delivery because of cervical insufficiency or membrane fragility
Small placenta
Desc: Reduced size of the placenta.

Name: Thin clavicles
Desc: Abnormally reduced diameter (cross section) of the clavicles.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the clavicles
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the clavicles (collar bones).

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplastia of the eccrine sweat glands
Desc: Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the eccrine sweat glands.

Name: Structural foot deformity
Desc: A foot deformity resulting due to an abnormality affecting the bones of the foot (as well as muscle and soft tissue). In contrast if only the muscle and soft tissue are affected the term positional foot deformity applies.

Name: Dermal translucency
Desc: An abnormally increased ability of the skin to permit light to pass through (translucency) such that subcutaneous structures such as veins display an increased degree of visibility.

Name: Temporomandibular joint ankylosis
Desc: Bony fusion of the mandibular condyle to the base of the skull, resulting in limitation of jaw opening.

Name: Abnormal cellular phenotype
Desc: An anomaly of cellular morphology or physiology.

Name: Short nail
Desc: Decreased length of nail.

Name: Ascending tubular aorta aneurysm
Desc: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the tubular part of the ascending aorta.
Synonyms: Aneurysm of the ascending tubular aorta
Bulging of wall of large artery located above heart

Name: Congenital adrenal hypoplasia
Desc: A type of adrenal hypoplasia with congenital onset.

Name: Dentinogenesis imperfecta
Desc: Developmental dysplasia of dentin.

Name: Square pelvis bone
Desc: An abnormally squared appearance of the bony pelvis, a normally rounded or basin-shaped structure.

Name: Pathologic fracture
Desc: A pathologic fracture occurs when a bone breaks in an area that is weakened secondarily to another disease process such as tumor, infection, and certain inherited bone disorders. A pathologic fracture can occur without a degree of trauma required to cause fracture in healthy bone.

Name: Upper limb undergrowth
Desc: Arm shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the upper extremity.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia involving bones of the upper limbs

Name: T-wave inversion
Desc: An inversion of the T-wave (which is normally positive).

Name: Congenital malformation of the great arteries
Desc: Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the aorta and pulmonary arteries.

Name: Abnormal pulmonary situs morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, which is defined by characteristics such as the number of lobes per lung and the relationship of the pulmonary arteries to their bronchi.

Name: Abnormality of abdominal situs
Desc: An abnormality of the abdominal situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the abdomen and its organs.

Name: Pancreatic hypoplasia
Desc: Hypoplasia of the pancreas.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the ear
Desc: The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the ear.

Name: Hypermetropia
Desc: An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects in the distance clearly, while objects nearby appear blurry.

Name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
Desc: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the fingers of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.
Synonyms: Cone-shaped end part of finger bones

Name: Narrow iliac wing
Desc: Decreased width of the wing (or ala) of the ilium (which is the large expanded portion which bounds the greater pelvis laterally).

Name: Intracerebral periventricular calcifications
Desc: The presence of calcium deposition in the cerebral white matter surrounding the cerebral ventricles.

Name: Reduced pancreatic beta cells
Desc: Reduced number of beta cells in the pancreatic islets of Langerhans.

Name: Vacuolated lymphocytes
Desc: The presence of clear, sharply defined vacuoles in the lymphocyte cytoplasm.

Name: Recurrent bacterial infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of bacterial infection.

Name: Abnormality of multiple cell lineages in the bone marrow
Hemophagocytosis
Desc: Phagocytosis by macrophages of erythrocytes, leukocytes, platelets, and their precursors in bone marrow and other tissues.

Name: Increased proportion of CD25+ mast cells
Desc: An increased proportion of mast cells are positive for the cell surface marker CD25 (also called interleukin-2 receptor alpha chain).

Name: Rotary nystagmus
Desc: A form of nystagmus in which the eyeball makes rotary motions around the axis.

Name: Large clumps of pigment irregularly distributed along hair shaft
Synonyms: Large clumps of pigment irregularly distributed along hair shaft

Name: Recurrent bacterial skin infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections of the skin, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infectious dermatitis.

Name: Recurrent staphylococcal infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to staphylococcal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of staphylococcal infections.

Name: Abnormal platelet function
Desc: Any anomaly in the function of thrombocytes.

Name: Abnormality of neutrophil physiology
Desc: A functional abnormality of neutrophils.

Name: Abnormal natural killer cell morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the natural killer cell, which is a lymphocyte that can spontaneously kill a variety of target cells without prior antigenic activation via germline encoded activation receptors. It also regulates immune responses via cytokine release and direct contact with other cells.

Name: Recurrent streptococcal infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to streptococcal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of streptococcal infections.

Name: Hyponatremia
Desc: An abnormally decreased sodium concentration in the blood.

Name: Atrophy of alveolar ridges
Synonyms: Atrophy of alveolar processes of jaw
Flattening of alveolar processes of jaw
Resorption of alveolar processes of jaw

Name: Increased circulating lactate dehydrogenase concentration
Desc: An elevated level of the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase in the blood circulation.

Name: Diastomatomyelia
Desc: Coexistence of two hemicords, at variable levels, causing splaying of the posterior vertebral elements. Results in neurological deficits in lower limb or perineum.

Name: Long penis
Desc: Penile length more than 2 SD above the mean for age.

Name: Arterial dissection
Desc: A separation (dissection) of the layers of an artery.

Name: Cupped ribs
Desc: Wide, concave rib end.

Name: Proximal femoral metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the proximal metaphysis of the femur.

Name: Irregular iliac crest
Desc: Irregularity of the iliac crest, which is the superior border of the wing of the ilium.

Name: Ambiguous genitalia, male
Desc: Ambiguous genitalia in an individual with XY genetic gender.

Name: Renal salt wasting
Desc: A high concentration of one or more electrolytes in the urine in the presence of low serum concentrations of the electrolyte(s).

Name: Aplasia of the uterus
Desc: Aplasia of the uterus.

Name: Adrenal hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal glands.

Name: Increased circulating renin level
Desc: An increased level of renin in the blood.

Name: Hyperkalemia
Desc: An abnormally increased potassium concentration in the blood.

Name: Decreased circulating aldosterone level
Desc: Abnormally reduced levels of aldosterone.

Name: Abnormal circulating cholesterol concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of cholesterol in the blood circulation.

Name: Hypernatriuria
Desc: An increased concentration of sodium(1+) in the urine.

Name: Low maternal serum estriol
Desc: An abnormally high concentration of serum conjugated estriol as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

Name: Elevated circulating follicle stimulating hormone level
Desc: An elevated concentration of follicle-stimulating hormone in the blood.
Synonyms: Increased circulating follicle stimulating hormone level

Name: Female external genitalia in individual with 46,XY karyotype
Desc: The presence of female external genitalia in a person with a male karyotype.

Name: Hypovolemia
Desc: An decrease in the amount of intravascular fluid, particularly in the volume of the circulating blood.

Name: Elevated circulating luteinizing hormone level
Desc: An elevated concentration of luteinizing hormone in the blood.

Name: Abnormal sex determination
Desc: Anomaly of primary or secondary sexual development or characteristics.

Name: Abnormal urine potassium concentration
Desc: An abnormal concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.

Name: Midshaft hypospadias
Desc: Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the middle of the inferior shaft of the penis.

Name: Decreased circulating androgen concentration
Desc: A reduction in the blood concentration of an androgen, that is, of a steroid hormone that controls development and maintenance of masculine characteristics. The androgens include testosterone and Dehydroepiandrosterone.

Name: Induced vaginal delivery
Desc: Vaginal delivery following induction of labor, a procedure used to stimulate uterine contractions during pregnancy before labor begins on its own.

Name: Urogenital sinus anomaly
Desc: A rare birth defect in women where the urethra and vagina both open into a common channel.

Name: Hypoplasia of the uterus
Desc: Underdevelopment of the uterus.

Name: Abnormal peripheral myelination
Desc: An abnormality of the myelination of motor and sensory peripheral nerves. These are axons for motor nerves and dendrites for sensory nerves in the strict anatomic sense.

Name: Decreased serum estradiol
Desc: A reduction below normal concentration of estradiol in the circulation.

Name: Gonadal dysgenesis with female appearance, male
Desc: Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to a more female sex differentiation.

Name: Streak ovary
Desc: A developmental disorder characterized by the progressive loss of primordial germ cells in the developing ovaries of an embryo, leading to hypoplastic ovaries composed of wavy connective tissue with occasional clumps of granulosa cells, and frequently mesonephric or hilar cells.

Name: Corneal arcus
Desc: A hazy, grayish-white ring about 2 mm in width located close to but separated from the limbus (the corneoscleral junction). Corneal arcus generally occurs bilaterally, and is related to lipid deposition in the cornea. Corneal arcus can occur in elderly persons as a part of the aging process but may be associated with hypercholesterolemia in people under the age of 50 years.

Name: Recurrent fever
Desc: Periodic (episodic or recurrent) bouts of fever.

Name: Chronic rhinitis
Desc: Chronic inflammation of the nasal mucosa.

Name: Psoriasiform dermatitis
Desc: A skin abnormality characterized by redness and irritation, with thick, red skin that displays flaky, silver-white patches (scales).

Name: Lipodystrophy
Desc: Degenerative changes of the fat tissue.
Synonyms: Inability to make and keep healthy fat tissue

Name: Progressive congenital scoliosis
Desc: A progressive form of scoliosis with congenital onset.

Name: Abnormality of the curvature of the vertebral column
Desc: The presence of an abnormal curvature of the vertebral column.

Name: Abnormality of skeletal muscle fiber size
Desc: Any abnormality of the size of the skeletal muscle cell.
Synonyms: Abnormality of skeletal muscle fibre size

Name: Joint laxity
Desc: Lack of stability of a joint.

Name: Increased intracellular sodium
Desc: An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the cytosol.

Name: Stomatocytosis
Desc: The presence of erythrocytes with a mouth-shaped (stoma) area of central pallor on peripheral blood smear.

Name: Hypoglycorrhachia
Desc: Abnormally low glucose concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Synonyms: Low glucose levels in cerebral spinal fluid

Name: Zonular cataract
Desc: Zonular cataracts are defined to be cataracts that affect specific regions of the lens.

Name: Cerebral white matter hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the cerebral white matter.

Name: Delayed myelination
Desc: Delayed myelination.

Name: Decreased thalamic volume
Desc: A reduction in the quantity of space occupied by the thalamus.

Name: Progressive language deterioration
Desc: Progressive loss of previously present language abilities.

Name: Abnormal emotion/affect behavior
Desc: An abnormality of emotional behaviour.

Name: Supraventricular arrhythmia
Desc: A type of arrhythmia that originates above the ventricles, whereby the electrical impulse propagates down the normal His Purkinje system similar to normal sinus rhythm.

Name: Abnormal atrioventricular conduction
Desc: An impairment of the electrical continuity between the atria and ventricles.

Name: Abnormal electrophysiology of sinoatrial node origin
Desc: An abnormality of the sinoatrial (SA) node in the right atrium. THe SA node acts as the pacemaker of the heart.

Name: Pedal edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of excess fluid in the lower extremity resulting in swelling of the feet and extending upward to the lower leg.

Name: Menorrhagia
Desc: Prolonged and excessive menses at regular intervals in excess of 80 mL or lasting longer than 7 days.

Name: Capillary malformation of the lip
Desc: A vascular malformation located in the lip that is characterized bynectatic papillary dermal capillaries and postcapillary venules in the upper reticular dermis.

Name: Macrodactyly
Desc: Significant increase in the length and girth of most or all of a digit compared to its contralateral digit (if unaffected) or compared to what would be expected for age/body build. The increased girth is accompanied by an increase in the dorso-ventral dimension AND the lateral dimension of the digit.

Name: Venous malformation
Desc: A vascular malformation resulting from a developmental error of venous tissue composed of dysmorphic channels lined by flattened endothelium and exhibiting slow turnover. A venous malformation may present as a blue patch on the skin ranging to a soft blue mass. Venous malformations are easily compressible and usually swell in thewhen venous pressure increases (e.g., when held in a dependent position or when a child cries). They may be relatively localized or quite extensive within an anatomic region.

Name: Hemihypertrophy of lower limb
Desc: Overgrowth of only one leg.

Name: Hemihypertrophy of upper limb
Desc: Overgrowth of only one arm.

Name: Ganglioneuroma
Desc: A benign neoplasm that usually arises from the sympathetic trunk in the mediastinum, representing a tumor of the sympathetic nerve fibers arising from neural crest cells.

Name: Recurrent viral infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to viral infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral infection.

Name: T lymphocytopenia
Desc: An abnormally low count of T cells.
Synonyms: Decreased numbers of circulating T cells

Name: B lymphocytopenia
Desc: An abnormal decrease from the normal count of B cells.

Name: Recurrent fungal infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to fungal infections, as manifested by multiple episodes of fungal infection.

Name: Hypocalcification of dental enamel
Desc: A form of hypomineralization of enamel characterized by reduced calcification.

Name: Recurrent mycobacterial infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.

Name: Nail pits
Desc: Small (typically about 1 mm or less in size) depressions on the dorsal nail surface.

Name: Ridged nail
Desc: Longitudinal, linear prominences in the nail plate.

Name: Thymoma
Desc: A tumor originating from the epithelial cells of the thymus.

Name: Decreased proportion of CD8-positive T cells
Desc: A decreased proportion of circulating CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells relative to total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Decreased proportion of CD8+ T cells
Decreased proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells

Name: Decreased lymphocyte proliferation in response to mitogen
Desc: A decreased proliferative response of lymphocytes in vitro or in vivo, when stimulated with mitogens, such as phytohemagglutinin (PHA).

Name: Decreased proportion of CD3-positive T cells
Desc: Any abnormality in the proportion of CD3-positive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Decreased proportion of CD3+ T cells

Name: Recurrent lower respiratory tract infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to lower respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent lower respiratory tract infections.

Name: Increased circulating IgA level
Desc: An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin A in blood.

Name: Recurrent candida infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to candida infections, as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of candida infections.

Name: Psoriasiform lesion
Desc: A skin lesions that resembles the lesions observed in psoriasis, viz., an erythematous plaque covered by fine silvery scales. Psoriasiform lesions can be observed in psoriasis as well as in other conditions including allergic contact dermatitis, seborrhoeic dermatitis, Atopic dermatitis, pityriasis rubra, and lichen simplex chronicus.

Name: Neonatal sepsis
Desc: Systemic inflammatory response to infection in newborn babies.

Name: Decreased circulating total IgA
Desc: Undetectable serum immunoglobulin A level at a value < 5 mg/dL (0.05 g/L).

Name: Failure to thrive secondary to recurrent infections
Desc: Insufficient weight gain or inappropriate weight loss for a child, that is attributed to an endogenous recurrent infections.
Synonyms: Faltering weight secondary to recurrent infections
Weight faltering secondary to recurrent infections

Name: Recurrent abscess formation
Desc: An increased susceptibility to abscess formation, as manifested by a medical history of recurrent abscesses.

Name: Chronic oral candidiasis
Desc: Chronic accumulation and overgrowth of the fungus Candida albicans on the mucous membranes of the mouth, generally manifested as associated with creamy white lesions on the tongue or inner cheeks, occasionally spreading to the gums, tonsils, palate or oropharynx.

Name: Difficulty climbing stairs
Desc: Reduced ability to climb stairs.

Name: Facial diplegia
Desc: Facial diplegia refers to bilateral facial palsy (bilateral facial palsy is much rarer than unilateral facial palsy).

Name: Left ventricular hypertrophy
Desc: Enlargement or increased size of the heart left ventricle.

Name: EMG: decremental response of compound muscle action potential to repetitive nerve stimulation
Desc: A compound muscle action potential (CMAP) is a type of electromyography (EMG). CMAP refers to a group of almost simultaneous action potentials from several muscle fibers in the same area evoked by stimulation of the supplying motor nerve and are recorded as one multipeaked summated action potential. This abnormality refers to a greater than normal decrease in the amplitude during the course of the investigation.
Synonyms: EMG: decremental response of CMAP to repetitive nerve stimulation

Name: Centrally nucleated skeletal muscle fibers
Desc: An abnormality in which the nuclei of sarcomeres take on an abnormally central localization (or in which this feature is found in an increased proportion of muscle cells).

Name: Type 1 muscle fiber predominance
Desc: An abnormal predominance of type I muscle fibers (in general, this feature can only be observed on muscle biopsy).

Name: EMG: myopathic abnormalities
Desc: The presence of abnormal electromyographic patterns indicative of myopathy, such as small-short polyphasic motor unit potentials.

Name: Macrocephaly at birth
Desc: The presence of an abnormally large skull with onset at birth.
Synonyms: Head circumference large for gestational age

Name: Proximal muscle weakness in upper limbs
Desc: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the arms.

Name: Muscle fibrillation
Desc: Fine, rapid twitching of individual muscle fibers with little or no movement of the muscle as a whole. If a motor neuron or its axon is destroyed, the muscle fibers it innervates undergo denervation atrophy. This leads to hypersensitivity of individual muscle fibers to acetyl choline so that they may contract spontaneously. Isolated activity of individual muscle fibers is generally so fine it cannot be seen through the intact skin, although it can be recorded as a short-duration spike in the EMG.

Name: External ophthalmoplegia
Desc: Paralysis of the external ocular muscles.
Synonyms: Paralysis or weakness of muscles within or surrounding outer part of eye
Progressive paralysis or weakness of muscles of eye motility
Progressive paralysis or weakness of muscles of eye movement

Name: Respiratory insufficiency due to muscle weakness
Synonyms: Decreased lung function due to weak breathing muscles
Decreased respiratory function due to muscle weakness
Respiratory distress due to muscle weakness
Respiratory failure due to muscle weakness

Name: Hypoplastic thumbnail
Desc: A thumbnail that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped thumb nail.

Name: Renal cortical cysts
Desc: Cysts of the cortex of the kidney.

Name: Posterior fossa cyst
Desc: A discrete posterior fossa cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) collection that does not communicate directly with the fourth ventricle.

Name: Complete duplication of thumb phalanx
Desc: A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the thumb. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accesory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, this is actually a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.
Synonyms: Complete duplication of the phalanges of the thumb

Name: Broad 2nd toe
Desc: A broad appearance of the second toe.

Name: Broad toe
Desc: Visible increase in width of the non-hallux digit without an increase in the dorso-ventral dimension.

Name: Elbow flexion contracture
Desc: A chronic loss of elbow joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the elbow.
Synonyms: Fixed flexion at the elbow joint

Name: Penile hypospadias
Desc: Location of the urethral opening on the inferior aspect of the penis.

Name: Congenital bilateral ptosis
Synonyms: Congenital drooping of both upper eyelids

Name: Short upper lip
Desc: Decreased width of the upper lip.
Synonyms: Decreased vertical length of upper lip

Name: Absent distal interphalangeal creases
Desc: Absence of the distal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fingers.
Synonyms: Absence of skin creases over distal interphalangeal joints
Aplasia of the distal interphalangeal creases

Name: Small anterior fontanelle
Desc: Abnormally decreased size of the anterior fontanelle with respect to age-dependent norms.

Name: Hepatic agenesis
Desc: Absence of the liver owing to a failure of the liver to develop.

Name: Reduced factor VIII activity
Desc: Reduced activity of coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.

Name: Prolonged partial thromboplastin time
Desc: Increased time to coagulation in the partial thromboplastin time (PTT) test, a measure of the intrinsic and common coagulation pathways. Phospholipid, and activator, and calcium are mixed into an anticoagulated plasma sample, and the time is measured until a thrombus forms.

Name: Poor wound healing
Desc: A reduced ability to heal cutaneous wounds.

Name: Prolonged bleeding after surgery
Desc: Bleeding that persists longer than the normal time following a surgical procedure.

Name: Joint hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage occurring within a joint.

Name: Oral cavity bleeding
Desc: Recurrent or excessive bleeding from the mouth.

Name: Limb joint contracture
Desc: A contrqacture (chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin) that prevent normal movement of one or more joints of the limbs.

Name: Reduced von Willebrand factor activity
Desc: Decreased activity of von Willebrand factor. Von Willebrand factor mediates the adhesion of platelets to the collagen exposed on endothelial cell surfaces.

Name: Intramuscular hematoma
Desc: Blood clot formed within muscle tissue following leakage of blood into the tissue.

Name: Cephalohematoma
Desc: Hemorrhage between the skull and periosteum of a newborn resulting from rupture of blood vessels that cross the periosteum.

Name: Macroscopic hematuria
Desc: Hematuria that is visible upon inspection of the urine.

Name: Prolonged bleeding following circumcision
Desc: Bleeding that persists for a longer than usual time following circumcision.

Name: Subdural hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage occurring between the dura mater and the arachnoid mater.

Name: Epidural hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage occurring between the dura mater and the skull.

Name: Intraventricular hemorrhage
Desc: Bleeding into the ventricles of the brain.

Name: Bleeding with minor or no trauma
Desc: Significant bleeding or hemorrhage without significant precipitating factor.
Synonyms: Bleeding with minor or no trauma

Name: Prolonged bleeding after dental extraction
Desc: Prolonged bleeding post dental extraction sufficient to require medical intervention.

Name: Spontaneous hematomas
Desc: Spontaneous development of hematomas (hematoma) or bruises without significant trauma.

Name: Abnormality of the upper urinary tract
Desc: An abnormality of the upper urinary tract.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the upper urinary tract

Name: Abnormality of periauricular region
Synonyms: Abnormality of the region around the ear

Name: Craniofacial asymmetry
Desc: Asymmetry of the bones of the skull and the face.

Name: Short forearm
Desc: Underdevelopment of both forearm bones, the ulna and the radius, resulting in a shortened forearm.

Name: Nasogastric tube feeding in infancy
Desc: Feeding problem necessitating nasogastric tube feeding.

Name: Single coronary artery origin
Desc: The presence of a single coronary artery ostium from which both coronary arteries arise.

Name: Abnormal ear morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the ear.

Name: Abnormal biliary tract morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the biliary tree.

Name: Spider hemangioma
Desc: A form of telangiectasis characterized by a central elevated red dot the size of a pinhead, representing an arteriole, with numerous small blood vessels that radiate out thereby resembling the legs of a spider. Characteristically, compression of the central arteriole causes the entire lesion to blanch, and the lesion quickly refills once the compression is released.

Name: Abnormal large intestine physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of the large intestine.

Name: Dilated superficial abdominal veins
Desc: Increase in diameter of the veins located underneath the skin of the abdomen.
Synonyms: Dilatation of the superficial abdominal veins

Name: Ulcerative colitis
Desc: A chronic inflammatory bowel disease that includes characteristic ulcers, or open sores, in the colon. The main symptom of active disease is usually constant diarrhea mixed with blood, of gradual onset and intermittent periods of exacerbated symptoms contrasting with periods that are relatively symptom-free. In contrast to Crohn's disease this special form of colitis begins in the distal parts of the rectum, spreads continually upwards and affects only mucose and submucose tissue of the colon.

Name: Palmar telangiectasia
Desc: The presence of telangiectases on the skin of palm of hand.

Name: Cholelithiasis
Desc: Hard, pebble-like deposits that form within the gallbladder.

Name: Celiac disease
Desc: Celiac disease (CD) is an autoimmune condition affecting the small intestine, triggered by the ingestion of gluten, the protein fraction of wheat, barley, and rye. Clinical manifestations of CD are highly variable and include both gastrointestinal and non-gastrointestinal features. The hallmark of CD is an immune-mediated enteropathy. This term is included because the occurence of CD is seen as a feature of a number of other diseases.

Name: Polyclonal elevation of IgM
Desc: A heterogeneous increase in IgM immunoglobulins characterized by a diffuse band on serum electrophoresis.

Name: Cholangiocarcinoma
Desc: Cholangiocarcinoma is a primary cancer originating in the biliary epithelium i.e., the cholangiocytes, of the extrahepatic and intrahepatic biliary ducts. It is extremely invasive, develops rapidly, often metastasizes, and has a very poor prognosis. They are slow growing tumors which spread longitudinally along the bile ducts with neural, perineural and subepithelial extension.

Name: Adenocarcinoma of the large intestine
Desc: A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the large intestine.

Name: Neoplasm of the gallbladder
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the gallbladder.

Name: Recurrent systemic pyogenic infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to systemic pyogenic infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of systemic pyogenic infections.

Name: Expressive language delay
Desc: A delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

Name: Breech presentation
Desc: A position of the fetus at delivery in which the fetus enters the birth canal with the buttocks or feet first.
Synonyms: Feet or buttocks of fetus positioned near opening of uterus
Feet or buttocks of foetus positioned near opening of uterus

Name: Nemaline bodies
Desc: Nemaline rods are abnormal bodies that can occur in skeletal muscle fibers. The rods can be observed on histological analysis of muscle biopsy tissue or upon electron microscopy, where they appear either as extensions of sarcomeric Z-lines, in random array without obvious attachment to Z-lines (often in areas devoid of sarcomeres) or in large clusters localized at the sarcolemma or intermyofibrillar spaces.

Name: Multiple prenatal fractures
Desc: The presence of bone fractures in the prenatal period that are diagnosed at birth or before.
Synonyms: Numerous multiple fractures present at birth
Numerous multiple fractures that are present at birth

Name: Severe muscular hypotonia
Desc: A severe degree of muscular hypotonia characterized by markedly reduced muscle tone.

Name: Increased connective tissue
Desc: The presence of an abnormally increased amount of connective tissue.

Name: Abnormality of the diaphragm
Desc: Any abnormality of the diaphragm, the sheet of skeletal muscle that separates the thoracic cavity from the abdominal cavity.

Name: Limb-girdle muscle weakness
Desc: Weakness of the limb-girdle muscles (also known as the pelvic and shoulder girdles), that is, lack of strength of the muscles around the shoulders and the pelvis.

Name: Neck flexor weakness
Desc: Weakness of the muscles involved in neck flexion (sternocleidomastoid, longus capitus, longus colli, and scalenus anterior).

Name: Fatigable weakness of distal limb muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of a skeletal muscle of distal part of a limb that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Fatigable weakness of respiratory muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of the muscles involved in breathing (respiration) that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Fetal akinesia sequence
Desc: Decreased fetal activity associated with multiple joint contractures, facial anomalies and pulmonary hypoplasia. Ultrasound examination may reveal polyhydramnios, ankylosis, scalp edema, and decreased chest movements (reflecting pulmonary hypoplasia).

Name: Reduced vital capacity
Desc: An abnormal reduction on the vital capacity, which is defined as the total lung capacity (volume of air in the lungs at maximal inflation) less the residual volume (i.e., volume of air in the lungs following maximal exhalation) of the lung.

Name: Fatigable weakness of bulbar muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of the bulbar muscles (muscles of the mouth and throat responsible for speech and swallowing) that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Muscle stiffness
Desc: A condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm.

Name: Increased muscle lipid content
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of lipids in skeletal muscle.

Name: Paraproteinemia
Desc: An abnormal immunoglobulin or part of an Ig (light chain) in the circulation. Paraproteins are typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

Name: Progressive intervertebral space narrowing
Desc: A progressive form of decreased height of the intervertebral disk.

Name: Shuffling gait
Desc: A type of gait (walking) characterized by by dragging one's feet along or without lifting the feet fully from the ground.

Name: Amyotrophy of ankle musculature
Desc: Atrophy of the muscles of the ankle.

Name: Corpus callosum atrophy
Desc: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the corpus callosum.

Name: Peripheral demyelination
Desc: A loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Positional foot deformity
Desc: A foot deformity resulting due to an abnormality affecting the muscle and soft tissue. In contrast if the bones of the foot are affected the term structural foot deformity applies.

Name: Pontocerebellar atrophy
Desc: Atrophy affecting the pons and the cerebellum.

Name: Enuresis nocturna
Desc: Enuresis occurring during sleeping hours.

Name: Pollakisuria
Desc: Increased frequency of urination.

Name: Decreased corneal reflex
Desc: An abnormally reduced response to stimulation of the cornea (by touch, foreign body, blowing air). The corneal reflex (also known as the blink reflex, normally results in an involuntary blinking of the eyelids.

Name: Opacification of the corneal epithelium
Desc: Lack of transparency of the corneal epithelium.

Name: Generalized opacification of the cornea
Desc: Generalized reduced transparency of the stroma of the cornea.

Name: Cornea verticillata
Desc: Golden brown or gray deposits with a clockwise, whorl-like distribution in the inferior interpalpebal portion of the cornea.

Name: Neurogenic bladder
Desc: A type of bladder dysfunction caused by neurologic damage. Neurogenic bladder can be flaccid or spastic. Common manifestatios of neurogenic bladder are overflow incontinence, frequency, urgency, urge incontinence, and retention.
Synonyms: Lack of bladder control due to nervous system injury

Name: Substantia nigra gliosis
Desc: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the substantia nigra.

Name: Monotonic speech
Desc: A speech pattern characterized by abnormally reduced or lacking variability of the pitch of the voice.

Name: Almond-shaped palpebral fissure
Desc: A shape created by an acute downward arching of the upper eyelid and upward arching of the lower eyelid, toward the medial canthus, which gives the outline of the palpebral fissures the configuration of an almond. Thus, the maximum distance between the fissures is offset from, and medial to, the center point.

Name: Abnormal temper tantrums
Desc: A temper tantrum is an emotional outburst usually triggered by a sense of frustration and manifested as whining and crying, screaming, kicking, hitting, and breath holding. Temper tantrums are normal in toddlers and young children and usually happen between the ages of one to three years. Temper tantrums may be considered abnormal if they occur at an unusually high frequency, are of unusual severity, or occur at an old age than usual.

Name: Long foot
Desc: Increased back to front length of the foot.

Name: Abnormality of the septum pellucidum
Desc: An abnormality of the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain.

Name: Lens subluxation
Desc: Partial dislocation of the lens of the eye.

Name: Microphakia
Desc: Abnormal smallness of the lens.

Name: Intrahepatic cholestasis
Desc: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in the small bile ducts within the liver.
Synonyms: Impaired release of bile from liver

Name: Decreased circulating ceruloplasmin concentration
Desc: Decreased concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood.

Name: Knee flexion contracture
Desc: A bent (flexed) knee joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

Name: Barrel-shaped chest
Desc: A rounded, bulging chest that resembles the shape of a barrel. That is, there is an increased anteroposterior diameter and usually some degree of kyphosis.

Name: Relative macrocephaly
Desc: A relatively mild degree of macrocephaly in which the head circumference is not above two standard deviations from the mean, but appears dysproportionately large when other factors such as body stature are taken into account.

Name: Glucocortocoid-insensitive primary hyperaldosteronism
Desc: A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone cannot be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone or similar glucocorticoids.

Name: Hypovolemic shock
Desc: A state of shock characterized by decreased circulating blood volume in relation to total vascular capacity. This type of shock is characterized by a reduction of diastolic filling pressures.

Name: Recurrent upper and lower respiratory tract infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to upper and lower respiratory tract infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of upper and lower respiratory tract infections.

Name: Atopic dermatitis
Desc: Atopic dermatitis (AD) or atopic eczema is an itchy, inflammatory skin condition with a predilection for the skin flexures. It is characterized by poorly defined erythema with edema, vesicles, and weeping in the acute stage and skin thickening (lichenification) in the chronic stage.

Name: Proportionate short stature
Desc: A kind of short stature in which different regions of the body are shortened to a comparable extent.

Name: Abnormal muscle fiber morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the skeletal muscle cell. Muscle fibers are subdivided into two types. Type I fibers are fatigue-resistant and rich in oxidative enzymes (they stain light with the myosin ATPase reaction), and type II fibers are fast-contracting, fatigue-prone, and rich in glycolytic enzymes (these fibers stain darkly). Normal muscle tissue has a random distribution of type I and type II fibers.

Name: Aortic root aneurysm
Desc: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic root.
Synonyms: Bulge in wall of root of large artery that carries blood away from heart

Name: Easy fatigability
Desc: Increased susceptibility to fatigue.

Name: Sinus tachycardia
Desc: Heart rate of greater than 100 beats per minute.

Name: Long neck
Desc: Increased inferior-superior length of the neck.

Name: Vertebral fusion
Desc: A developmental defect leading to the union of two adjacent vertebrae.

Name: Dysplastic tricuspid valve
Desc: A congenital malformation of the tricuspid valve characterized by leaflet deformation.

Name: Urethral stenosis
Desc: Abnormal narrowing of the urethra.

Name: Abnormal blood ion concentration
Desc: Abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of a monoatomic ion.

Name: Abnormality of renal excretion
Desc: An altered ability of the kidneys to void urine and/or specific substances.

Name: Decreased urine output
Desc: A decreased rate of urine production.

Name: Hyperventilation
Desc: Hyperventilation refers to an increased pulmonary ventilation rate that is faster than necessary for the exchange of gases. Hyperventilation can result from increased frequency of breathing, an increased tidal volume, or both, and leads to an excess intake of oxygen and the blowing off of carbon dioxide.

Name: Palmoplantar cutis laxa
Desc: Loose, wrinkled skin of hands and feet.
Synonyms: Excessive wrinkled skin of palms and soles
Increased wrinkles of palms and soles
Wrinkled skin of hands and feet

Name: Abdominal cramps
Desc: A type of abdominal pain characterized by a feeling of contractions and typically fluctuating in intensity.

Name: Achlorhydria
Desc: A condition in which production of hydrochloric acid in the stomach is absent.

Name: Metaphyseal cupping
Desc: Metaphyseal cupping refers to an inward bulging of the metaphyseal profile giving the metaphysis a cup-like appearance.

Name: Proximal femoral metaphyseal abnormality
Desc: An anomaly of the metaphysis of the proximal femur (close to the hip).
Synonyms: Abnormal wide portion of innermost thighbone

Name: Thick growth plates
Desc: Increased thickness (dimension along the axis of the bone) of the growth plate.

Name: Distal femoral metaphyseal abnormality
Desc: An anomaly of the metaphysis of the distal femur (close to the knee).
Synonyms: Abnormality of wide portion of outermost thighbone

Name: Anterior rib cupping
Desc: Wide, concave anterior rib end.

Name: Short tubular bones of the hand
Desc: Decreased length of the tubular bones of the hand, that is, the phalanges and metacarpals.
Synonyms: Shortened short tubular bones of the hand

Name: Flared metaphysis
Desc: The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of one or more long bones.
Synonyms: Flared wide portion of long bone
Marked metaphyseal flaring of long bones

Name: Widened proximal tibial metaphyses
Synonyms: Wide innermost wide portion of shankbone bone
Wide innermost wide portion of shinbone bone

Name: Abnormalities of the metaphyses of the hand
Synonyms: Abnormality of the wide portion of the hand bone

Name: Metaphyseal cupping of proximal phalanges
Desc: Metaphyseal cupping affecting the proximal phalanges.

Name: Osteosclerosis of ribs
Desc: Osteosclerosis of ribs (increased density related to increased bone mass).

Name: Broad proximal phalanges of the hand
Desc: Increased width of the proximal phalanges of the finger.
Synonyms: Broad innermost finger bones of the hand
Wide innermost finger bones of the hand

Name: Distal femoral metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the distal metaphysis of the femur.

Name: Irregular vertebral endplates
Desc: An irregular surface of the vertebral end plates, which are normally relatively smooth.

Name: Radial metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the metaphysis of the radius.

Name: Ulnar metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the metaphysis of the ulna.

Name: Abnormality of the antitragus
Desc: An abnormality of the antitragus, which is a small tubercle opposite to the tragus of the ear. The antitragus and the tragus are separated by the intertragic notch.

Name: Biconvex vertebral bodies
Desc: Presence of abnormal convexity of the upper and lower end plates of the vertebrae, i.e., an exaggerated bulging out of the upper and lower vertebral end plates.

Name: Mucopolysacchariduria
Desc: Excessive amounts of mucopolysaccharide in the urine.

Name: Heart block
Desc: Impaired conduction of cardiac impulse occurring anywhere along the conduction pathway.

Name: Bone cyst
Desc: A fluid filled cavity that develops with a bone.

Name: Uterus didelphys
Desc: A malformation of the uterus in which the uterus is present as a paired organ as a result of the failure of fusion of the mullerian ducts during embryogenesis.

Name: Bifid sacrum
Desc: Presence of a bifid sacral bone.

Name: Intestinal duplication
Desc: A developmental disorder in which there is a duplication the entire intestine or of a portion of the intestine.

Name: Absent tibia
Desc: Absence of the tibia.

Name: Rounded middle phalanx of finger
Desc: An abnormally round shape of the middle phalanx of the finger.

Name: Punctate vertebral calcifications
Desc: The presence of punctiform calcification of the bone of the vertebral bodies.

Name: Epiphyseal stippling
Desc: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more epiphyses.
Synonyms: Speckled calcifications in end part of bone

Name: Alacrima
Desc: Absence of tear secretion.
Synonyms: Absence of tears in the eyes

Name: Acrocyanosis
Synonyms: Persistent blue color of hands, feet, or parts of face
Persistent blue colour of hands, feet, or parts of face

Name: Orthostatic hypotension
Desc: A form of hypotension characterized by a sudden fall in blood pressure that occurs when a person assumes a standing position.
Synonyms: Decrease in blood pressure upon standing up

Name: Abnormality of the peritoneum
Desc: An abnormality of the peritoneum.

Name: Corneal erosion
Desc: An erosion or abrasion of the cornea's outermost layer of epithelial cells.
Synonyms: Damage to outer layer of the cornea of the eye

Name: Radial bowing
Desc: A bending or abnormal curvature of the radius.
Synonyms: Bowing of outer large bone of the forearm
Bowing of radius bone of the forearm

Name: Ulnar bowing
Desc: Bending of the diaphysis (shaft) of the ulna.

Name: Madelung deformity
Desc: An anomaly related to partial closure, or failure of development of the ulnar side of the distal radial growth plate, which results in an arrest of epiphyseal growth of the medial and volar portions of the distal radius. This leads to shortening of the radius and relative overgrowth of the ulna.

Name: Mesomelic short stature
Desc: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by disproportionate shortening of the medial parts of the extremities (forearm or lower leg).

Name: Epispadias
Desc: Displacement of the urethral opening on the dorsal (superior) surface of the penis.

Name: Chordee
Desc: Ventral, lateral, or ventrolateral bowing of the shaft and glans penis of more than 30 degrees.

Name: Ambiguous genitalia, female
Desc: Ambiguous genitalia in an individual with XX genetic gender.

Name: Recurrent otitis media
Desc: Increased susceptibility to otitis media, as manifested by recurrent episodes of otitis media.

Name: Abnormal internal genitalia
Desc: An anomaly of the adnexa, uterus, and vagina (in female) or seminal tract and prostate (in male).

Name: Prolonged QT interval
Desc: Increased time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).

Name: Dyscalculia
Desc: A specific learning disability involving mathematics and arithmetic.

Name: Muscle hypertrophy of the lower extremities
Desc: Muscle hypertrophy primarily affecting the legs.

Name: Cervix cancer
Desc: A tumor of the uterine cervix.

Name: Ovotestis
Desc: A gonad that contains both ovarian follicles and testicular tubular elements.

Name: Ovarian serous cystadenoma
Desc: A cystic tumor of the ovary, containing thin, clear, yellow serous fluid and varying amounts of solid tissue.

Name: Oral leukoplakia
Desc: A thickened white patch on the oral mucosa that cannot be rubbed off.

Name: Coarse metaphyseal trabecularization
Desc: Coarse appearance of the components of the network of osseous tissue that makes up the cancellous structure of a bone, i.e., thickening of the (usually fine) white lines that are produced by trabeculae in radiograms.
