Name: Clitoral hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the clitoris.

Name: External genital hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of part or all of the external reproductive organs.

Name: Central adrenal insufficiency
Desc: A form of adrenal insufficiency related to a lack of ACTH, which leads to a decrease in the production of cortisol by the adrenal glands. Aldosterone production is not usually affected.

Name: Central hypothyroidism
Desc: A type of hypothyroidism due to an insufficient stimulation of an otherwise normal thyroid gland. Central hypothyroidism is caused by either pituitary (secondary hypothyroidism) or hypothalamic (tertiary hypothyroidism) defects.

Name: Parietal cortical atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the parietal cortex.

Name: Occipital cortical atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the occipital cortex.

Name: Skin-picking
Desc: Repetitive and compulsive picking of skin which results in tissue damage.

Name: Premature pubarche
Desc: The onset of growth of pubic hair at an earlier age than normal.

Name: Premature adrenarche
Desc: Onset of adrenarche at an earlier age than usual.

Name: Perisylvian polymicrogyria
Desc: Polymicrogyria (an excessive number of small gyri or convolutions) that is maximal in perisylvian regions (the regions that surround the Sylvian fissures), which may be symmetric or asymmetric and may extend beyond perisylvian regions. The Sylvian fissures often extend posteriorly and superiorly.

Name: Decreased circulating gonadotropin concentration
Desc: A reduction of the circulating level of a gonadotropin, that is, of a protein hormone secreted by gonadotrope cells of the anterior pituitary of vertebrates. The primary gonadotropins are luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).

Name: Decreased circulating T4 level
Desc: A reduction below the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).

Name: Bulimia
Desc: A form of anomalous eating behavior characterized by binge eating is followed by self-induced vomiting or other compensatory behavior intended to prevent weight gain (purging, fasting or exercising or a combination of these).

Name: Gastroparesis
Desc: Decreased strength of the muscle layer of stomach, which leads to a decreased ability to empty the contents of the stomach despite the absence of obstruction.

Name: Decreased inhibin B level
Desc: A reduced concentration of inhibin B in the blood.

Name: Postterm pregnancy
Desc: A pregnancy that extends to 42 weeks of gestation or beyond.

Name: Precocious puberty
Desc: The onset of secondary sexual characteristics before a normal age. Although it is difficult to define normal age ranges because of the marked variation with which puberty begins in normal children, precocious puberty can be defined as the onset of puberty before the age of 8 years in girls or 9 years in boys.

Name: Microdontia of primary teeth
Desc: Decreased size of the primary teeth.

Name: Underdeveloped nasolabial fold
Desc: Reduced bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion or commissure).

Name: Head-banging
Desc: Habitual striking of one's own head against a surface such as a mattress or wall of a crib.

Name: Stellate iris
Desc: A lacy pattern or iris pigmentation that resembles the spokes of a bicycle wheel.

Name: Happy demeanor
Desc: A conspicuously happy disposition with frequent smiling and laughing that may be context-inappropriate or unrelated to context.

Name: Triangular-shaped open mouth
Desc: A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth, in which the upper lip is tented in a way that the opened mouth has the appearance of a triangle.

Name: Prolonged bleeding following procedure
Desc: Prolonged or protracted bleeding following an invasive procedure or intervention.

Name: Post-partum hemorrhage
Desc: Significant maternal haemorrhage/blood loss following deilvery of a child.

Name: Rectovaginal fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula between the vagina and the rectum.
Synonyms: Abnormal connection between rectum and vagina

Name: Cervical C2/C3 vertebral fusion
Desc: Fusion of cervical vertebrae at C2 and C3, caused by a failure in the normal segmentation or division of the cervical vertebrae during the early weeks of fetal development, leading to a short neck with a low hairline at the back of the head, and restricted mobility of the upper spine.

Name: Nocturia
Desc: Abnormally increased production of urine during the night leading to an unusually frequent need to urinate.

Name: Distal upper limb muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the arms.

Name: Hyporeflexia of upper limbs
Desc: Reduced intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in the upper limbs. Reflexes are elicited by stretching the tendon of a muscle, e.g., by tapping.

Name: Recurrent patellar dislocation
Desc: Patellar dislocation occurring repeated times.

Name: Intrinsic hand muscle atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the intrinsic muscle groups of the hand, comprising the thenar and hypothenar muscles; the interossei muscles; and the lumbrical muscles.

Name: Minicore myopathy
Desc: Multiple small zones of sarcomeric disorganization and lack of oxidative activity (known as minicores) in muscle fibers.

Name: Abnormality of the palpebral fissures
Desc: An anomaly of the space between the medial and lateral canthi of the two open eyelids.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the opening between the eyelids

Name: Increased endomysial connective tissue
Desc: An increased volume of the endomysium, which is a connective tissue sheath that surrounds each muscule fiber. Together, bundles of muscle fibers form a fasciculus, surrounded by another layer of connective tissue called the perimysium.

Name: Underfolded helix
Desc: Underdevelopment of the helix that either affects the entire helix, or is localized.

Name: Conspicuously happy disposition
Desc: An unusually happy aspect over time which can also may be observed during inappropriate situations that should be causing for example distress, fear or anger.

Name: Abnormality of serum cytokine level
Desc: Abnormality of the cytokine levels in the blood, i.e., an abnormality of any of the non-antibody proteins made by inflammatory leukocytes and some non-leukocytic cells that affect the behavior of other cells.

Name: Increased circulating surfactant protein level
Desc: An increased concentration of a surfactant protein in the blood circulation. Pulmonary surfactant is a highly surface-active mixture of proteins and lipids that is synthesized and secreted onto the alveoli by type II epithelial cells. The protein part of surfactant constitutes of four types of surfactant proteins (SP), SP-A, SP-B, SP-C and SP-D. SP-A and SP-D are hydrophilic proteins that regulate surfactant metabolism and have immunologic functions. These two proteins are detectable in the bloodstream and an elevated level may reflect idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.

Name: Acute pancreatitis
Desc: A acute form of pancreatitis.

Name: Abnormal pulmonary interstitial morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the lung parenchyma extending to the pulmonary interstitium and leading to diffuse pulmonary fibrosis.
Synonyms: Abnormality in area between air sacs in lung

Name: Abnormality of tumor necrosis factor secretion
Desc: An abnormality in the production or cellular release of tumor necrosis factor.
Synonyms: Abnormality of tumour necrosis factor secretion

Name: Diffuse alveolar hemorrhage
Desc: A type of of pulmonary hemorrhage that originates from the pulmonary microcirculation, including the alveolar capillaries, arterioles, and venules. It presents with hemoptysis, anemia, diffuse lung infiltration, and acute respiratory failure. The diagnosis is confirmed by the observation of the accumulation of red blood cells, fibrin, or hemosiderin-laden macrophage in the alveolar space on pathologic biopsy. Hemosiderin, a product of hemoglobin degradation, appears at least 48-72 hours after bleeding and is helpful in distinguishing diffuse alveolar hemorrhage from surgical trauma. Mild interstitial thickening, organizing pneumonia, or diffuse alveolar damage can also be seen.

Name: Alcoholism
Desc: An addictive behavior defined as drinking excessive amounts of alcohol over a long period of time, having difficulty reducing the amount of alcohol consumed, strongly desiring alcohol and experiencing withdrawal symptoms when not drinking alcohol.

Name: Shock
Desc: The state in which profound and widespread reduction of effective tissue perfusion leads first to reversible, and then if prolonged, to irreversible cellular injury.

Name: Hypoplasia of the fovea
Desc: Underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.

Name: Difficulty adjusting from light to dark
Brushfield spots
Desc: The presence of whitish spots in a ring-like arrangement at the periphery of the iris.

Name: Dimple on nasal tip
Desc: An abnormal indentation of the skin in the region of the nasal tip.

Name: Absent muscle fiber dysferlin
Desc: Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of dysferlin protein in the muscle biopsy.

Name: Abnormal circulating creatine kinase concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal circulating creatine kinase concentration.
Synonyms: Abnormal levels of creatine kinase in blood

Name: Tibialis muscle weakness
Desc: Muscle weakness affecting the tibialis anterior muscle.

Name: Progressive proximal muscle weakness
Desc: Lack of strength of the proximal muscles that becomes progressively more severe.

Name: Absent Achilles reflex
Desc: Absence of the Achilles reflex (also known as the ankle jerk reflex), which can normally be elicited by tapping the tendon is tapped while the foot is dorsiflexed.

Name: Weakness of the intrinsic hand muscles
Finger flexor weakness
Desc: Reduced ability to flex (bend) the fingers. This can manifest as incomplete closure of the hand due to weakness in finger flexion.

Name: Rimmed vacuoles
Desc: Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. On histological staining with hematoxylin and eosin, rimmed vacuoles are popcorn-like clear vacuoles with a densely blue rim. The vacuoles are often associated with cytoplasmic and occasionally intranuclear eosinophilic inclusions.

Name: Muscle fiber splitting
Desc: Fiber splitting or branching is a common finding in human and rat skeletal muscle pathology. Fiber splitting refers to longitudinal halving of the complete fiber, while branching originates from a regenerating end of a necrotic fiber as invaginations of the sarcolemma. In fiber branching, one end of the fiber remains intact as a single entity, while the other end has several branches.

Name: Orthopnea
Desc: A sensation of breathlessness in the recumbent position, relieved by sitting or standing.

Name: Internally nucleated skeletal muscle fibers
Desc: An abnormality in which the nuclei of sarcomeres take on an abnormally internal localization (or in which this feature is found in an increased proportion of muscle cells).

Name: Focal emotional seizure with laughing
Desc: Focal emotional seizure with laughing (gelastic) is characterized by bursts of laughter or giggling, usually without appropriate related emotion of happiness, and described as 'mirthless'.

Name: Epileptic spasm
Desc: A sudden flexion, extension, or mixed extension-flexion of predominantly proximal and truncal muscles that is usually more sustained than a myoclonic movement but not as sustained as a tonic seizure. Limited forms may occur: Grimacing, head nodding, or subtle eye movements. Epileptic spasms frequently occur in clusters. Infantile spasms are the best known form, but spasms can occur at all ages

Name: Focal motor seizure
Desc: A type of focal-onset seizure characterized by a motor sign as its initial semiological manifestation.

Name: Eyelid myoclonus
Desc: Marked, involuntary jerking of the eyelids.

Name: Abnormal hippocampus morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the hippocampus,

Name: Bilateral generalized polymicrogyria
Desc: Symmetric generalized polymicrogyria with no obvious gradient or region of maximal severity; may have abnormal high signal in white matter.

Name: Thin eyebrow
Desc: Decreased diameter of eyebrow hairs.

Name: Unilateral cleft lip
Desc: A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on one side only.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the ulna
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the ulna.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia or unilateral/bilateral absence of ulna

Name: Attenuation of retinal blood vessels
Synonyms: Narrowing of blood vessels in back of eye

Name: Macular hole
Desc: A macular hole is a small break in the macula, located in the center of the retina.

Name: Retinal thinning
Desc: Reduced anteroposterior thickness of the retina. This phenotype can be appreciated by retinal optical coherence tomography (OCT).

Name: Epiretinal membrane
Desc: An epiretinal membrane is a thin sheet of fibrous tissue that can develop on the surface of the macular area of the retina and cause a disturbance in vision. An epiretinal membrane area can develop on the thin macular area of the retin. An epiretinal membrane is also sometimes called a macular pucker, premacular fibrosis, surface wrinkling retinopathy or cellophane maculopathy.

Name: Vitreous floaters
Desc: Deposits of various size, shape, consistency, refractive index, and motility within the eye's vitreous humour, which is normally transparent.

Name: Macular scar
Desc: Scar tissue in the macula.

Name: Choroidal neovascularization
Desc: Choroidal neovascularization (CNV) is the creation of new blood vessels in the choroid layer of the eye.

Name: Abnormal choroid morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the choroid.

Name: Ocular hypertension
Desc: Intraocular pressure that is 2 standard deviations above the population mean.

Name: Cystoid macular edema
Desc: Cystoid macular edema (CME) is any type of macular edema that involves cyst formation.

Name: Photoreceptor layer loss on macular OCT
Desc: Loss of the outer nuclear layer (photoreceptor layer) as assessed by ocular coherence tomography.

Name: Optic disc pallor
Desc: A pale yellow discoloration of the optic disk (the area of the optic nerve head in the retina). The optic disc normally has a pinkish hue with a central yellowish depression.

Name: Maxillozygomatic hypoplasia
Desc: Hypoplasia of the maxillozygomatic complex.
Synonyms: Decreased projection of zygomaticomaxillary bone complex
Decreased size of zygomaticomaxillary bone complex

Name: Laryngeal hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the larynx.

Name: Bifid nasal tip
Desc: A splitting of the nasal tip. Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal tip.

Name: Upper eyelid coloboma
Desc: A short discontinuity of the margin of the upper eyelid.
Synonyms: Full thickness defect of the upper eyelid

Name: Limbal dermoid
Desc: A benign tumor typically found at the junction of the cornea and sclera (limbal epibullar dermoid).

Name: Decreased serum leptin
Desc: A decreased concentration of leptin in the blood.

Name: Decreased T cell activation
Desc: Decreased or impaired activation of T cells in response to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

Name: Insulin-resistant diabetes mellitus
Desc: A type of diabetes mellitus related not to lack of insulin but rather to lack of response to insulin on the part of the target tissues of insulin such as muscle, fat, and liver cells. This type of diabetes is typically associated with increases both in blood glucose concentrations as will as in fasting and postprandial serum insulin levels.

Name: Posterior rib fusion
Desc: Complete or partial merging of the posterior part of adjacent ribs.

Name: Persistent open anterior fontanelle
Desc: The anterior fontanelle generally ossifies by around the 18th month of life. A persistent open anterior fontanelle is diagnosed if closure is delayed beyond this age.

Name: Massively thickened long bone cortices
Desc: Extreme thickening of the cortex of long bones.

Name: Chronic metabolic acidosis
Desc: Longstanding metabolic acidosis.

Name: Hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis
Desc: A form of metabolic acidosis with increased serum chloride levels.

Name: Hypocitraturia
Desc: A lower than normal concentration of citrate(3-) in the urine.

Name: Decreased serum bicarbonate concentration
Desc: An abnormal reduction of the concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.

Name: Renal potassium wasting
Desc: High urine potassium in the presence of hypokalemia.

Name: Hypermagnesiuria
Desc: An increased concentration of magnesium the urine.

Name: Increased susceptibility to fractures
Desc: An abnormally increased tendency to fractures of bones caused by an abnormal reduction in bone strength that is generally associated with an increased risk of fracture.

Name: Enlarged vestibular aqueduct
Desc: Increased size of the vestibular aqueduct.

Name: Decreased glomerular filtration rate
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the volume of fluid filtered out of plasma through glomerular capillary walls into Bowman's capsules per unit of time.

Name: Lateral clavicle hook
Desc: An excessive upward convexity of the lateral clavicle.

Name: Undulate ribs
Desc: An abnormally wavy surface or edge of the ribs.

Name: Gonadal neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a gonad.

Name: Neuroectodermal neoplasm
Desc: A neoplasm arising in the neuroectoderm, the portion of the ectoderm of the early embryo that gives rise to the central and peripheral nervous systems, including some glial cells.

Name: Abnormal circulating gonadotropin concentration
Desc: An anomaly of the circulating level of a gonadotropin, that is, of a protein hormone secreted by gonadotrope cells of the anterior pituitary of vertebrates. The primary gonadotropins are luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).

Name: Neoplasm of head and neck
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the head and neck region with origin in the lip, oral cavity, nasal cavity, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, or larynx.

Name: Irregular menstruation
Desc: Abnormally high variation in the amount of time between periods.

Name: Increased serum testosterone level
Desc: An elevated circulating testosterone level in the blood.

Name: Short ribs
Desc: Reduced rib length.

Name: Distichiasis
Desc: Double rows of eyelashes.

Name: Abnormal sacroiliac joint morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the sacroiliac joint, which connects the base of the spine (sacrum) to the ilium (a hip bone).

Name: Sparse axillary hair
Desc: Reduced number or density of axillary hair.
Synonyms: Sparse scalp, axillary, and pubic hair

Name: Sparse pubic hair
Desc: Reduced number or density of pubic hair.

Name: Follicular hyperkeratosis
Desc: A skin condition characterized by excessive development of keratin in hair follicles, resulting in rough, cone-shaped, elevated papules resulting from closure of hair follicles with a white plug of sebum.

Name: Everted upper lip vermilion
Desc: Inner aspect of the upper lip vermilion (normally apposing the teeth) visible in a frontal view, i.e., the presence of an everted upper lip.

Name: Premature loss of primary teeth
Desc: Loss of the primary (also known as deciduous) teeth before the usual age.

Name: Thin nail
Desc: Nail that appears thin when viewed on end.

Name: Premature eruption of permanent teeth
Desc: Premature tooth eruption of the permanent dentition.

Name: Slow-growing nails
Desc: Nails whose growth is slower than normal.

Name: Hypercholesterolemia
Desc: An increased concentration of cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Shagreen patch
Desc: A plaque representing a connective-tissue nevus. Connective tissue naevi are uncommon skin lesions that occur when the deeper layers of the skin do not develop correctly or the components of these layers occur in the wrong proportion. Shagreen patches are oval-shaped and nevoid, skin-colored or occasionally pigmented, smooth or crinkled, The word shagreen refers to a type of roughened untanned leather.

Name: Predominantly lower limb lymphedema
Desc: Localized fluid retention and tissue swelling caused by a compromised lymphatic system, affecting mainly the legs.

Name: Serpiginous cutaneous lesion
Desc: A skin lesion with a snake- or serpent-like distribution.

Name: Annular cutaneous lesion
Desc: A lesion of the skin with a ring-like distribution.

Name: Hyperparakeratosis
Desc: Abnormal keratinization of the epidermal stratum coreum (horny layer) with increased keratin formation, preservation of the nuclei in the superficial cells, and absence of the stratum granulosum.

Name: Hyperkeratotic papule
Desc: A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point that is composed of localized hyperkeratosis (the latter may be demonstrated histopathologically).

Name: Lymphangiectasis
Desc: Dilation of the lymphatic vessels, the basic process that may result in the formation of a lymphangioma.

Name: Ankylosis
Desc: A reduction of joint mobility resulting from changes involving the articular surfaces.

Name: Eyelid retraction
Desc: With the eyes in primary position, the sclera is visible above the superior corneal limbus.

Name: Congenital thrombocytopenia
Desc: Thrombocytopenia with congenital onset.

Name: Nephritis
Desc: The presence of inflammation affecting the kidney.

Name: Giant platelets
Desc: Giant platelets are larger than 7 micrometers and usually 10 to 20 micrometers. The term giant platelet is used when the platelet is larger than the size of the average red cell in the field. (Description adapted from College of American Pathologists, Hematology Manual, 1998).

Name: Presenile cataracts
Desc: Presenile cataract is a kind of cataract that occurs in early adulthood, that is, at an age that is younger than usual.

Name: Neutrophil inclusion bodies
Desc: The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neutrophils. Cytoplasmic neutrophil inclusions (oval, basophilic) are also known as Doehle bodies.

Name: Increased mean platelet volume
Desc: Average platelet volume above the upper limit of the normal reference interval.

Name: Abnormal femoral neck morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).

Name: Flattened femoral head
Desc: An abnormally flattened femoral head.

Name: Irregular epiphyses
Desc: An alteration of the normally smooth contour of the epiphysis leading to an irregular appearance.
Synonyms: Irregular end part of long bone

Name: Abnormality of nail color
Desc: An anomaly of the color of the nail.

Name: Joint contracture of the hand
Desc: Contractures of one ore more joints of the hands meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Name: Interphalangeal joint contracture of finger
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion in an interphalangeal joint of a finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Name: Wrist flexion contracture
Desc: A chronic loss of wrist joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the wrist.

Name: Sclerosis of skull base
Desc: Increased bone density of the skull base without significant changes in bony contour.

Name: Metaphyseal widening
Desc: Abnormal widening of the metaphyseal regions of long bones.
Synonyms: Broad wide portion of long bone

Name: Metacarpophalangeal joint contracture
Desc: A chronic loss of joint motion in metacarpophalangeal joints due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.

Name: Limited wrist movement
Desc: An abnormal limitation of the mobility of the wrist.

Name: Short distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Hypoplastic (short) distal phalanx of the thumb.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/small distal phalanx of the thumb
Short outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Limitation of knee mobility
Desc: An abnormal limitation of knee joint mobility.

Name: Abnormal cornea morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the cornea, which is the transparent tissue at the front of the eye that covers the iris, pupil, and anterior chamber.

Name: Hypotrophy of the small hand muscles
Progressive bowing of long bones
Desc: Progressive bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.

Name: Shoulder muscle hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of muscles of the shoulder.

Name: Abnormality of the glabella
Desc: An abnormality of the glabella.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the area between the eyebrows
Deformity of the area between the eyebrows
Malformation of the area between the eyebrows

Name: Choroid plexus cyst
Desc: A cyst occurring within the choroid plexus within a cerebral ventricle.

Name: Hypoplasia of the olfactory bulb
Desc: Underdevelopment of the olfactory bulb.

Name: Large sella turcica
Desc: An abnormal enlargement of the sella turcica.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tibia
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the tibia.

Name: Dermoid cyst
Desc: A congenital subcutaneous cyst that arises from entrapment of skin along the lines of embryonic fusion. In contrast to epidermal cysts, dermoid cysts tend to contain various adnexal structures such as hair, sebaceous, eccrine or apocrine glands. Dermoid cysts are present at birth, and are indolent, firm, deep, subcutaneous nodules. They are often located on the head and neck, and rarely in the anogenital area. Dermoid cysts arenslowly progressive and can grow to a size of 1 to 4 cm.

Name: Recurrent intrapulmonary hemorrhage
Desc: A recurrent hemorrhage occurring within the lung.

Name: Nasal polyposis
Desc: Polypoidal masses arising mainly from the mucous membranes of the nose and paranasal sinuses. They are freely movable and nontender overgrowths of the mucosa that frequently accompany allergic rhinitis.

Name: Abnormal T cell morphology
Desc: An abnormality of T cells.

Name: Median cleft lip and palate
Desc: Cleft lip or palate affecting the midline region of the palate.

Name: Gingival fibromatosis
Desc: The presence of fibrosis of the gingiva.

Name: Mandibular aplasia
Desc: Absence of the mandible.
Synonyms: Aplasia of the lower jaw bone
Failure of development of lower jaw

Name: Dumbbell-shaped humerus
Desc: The humerus is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.
Synonyms: Dumbbell-shaped long bone in upper arm

Name: Severe combined immunodeficiency
Desc: A combined immunodeficiency primary immune deficiency that is characterized by a more severe defect in both the T- and B-lymphocyte systems.

Name: Abnormality of the bladder
Desc: An abnormality of the urinary bladder.

Name: Fetal polyuria
Desc: Abnormally increased production of urine by the fetus resulting in polyhydramnios.

Name: Sirenomelia
Desc: A developmental defect in which the legs are fused together.

Name: Pulmonary artery hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the pulmonary artery.

Name: Single ventricle
Desc: The presence of only one working lower chamber in the heart, usually with a virtual absence of the ventricular septum and usually present in conjunction with double inlet left or right ventricle.

Name: Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return
Desc: A form of anomalous pulmonary venous return in which not all pulmonary veins drain abnormally. Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return frequently involves one or both of the veins from one lung.

Name: Descending aorta hypoplasia
Desc: Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of the descending aorta.

Name: Truncus arteriosus
Desc: A single arterial trunk arises from the cardiac mass. The pulmonary arteries, aorta and coronary arteries arise from this single trunk with no evidence of another outflow tract.

Name: Anomalous origin of left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
Desc: Left main coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta, above the left cusp of the aortic valve.
Synonyms: Anomalous left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery

Name: Left superior vena cava draining to coronary sinus
Desc: A persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC) that drains into the right atrium via the coronary sinus. This is the case in 80-92% of cases of PLSVC and results in no hemodynamic consequence.

Name: Interrupted inferior vena cava with azygous continuation
Desc: Interrupted inferior vena cava with azygous continuation is the result of connection failure between the right subcardinal vein and the right vitelline vein. Consequently, venous blood from the caudal part of the body reaches the heart via the azygous vein and superior vena cava.

Name: Antinuclear antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against nuclei or nuclear components.

Name: Anti-dsDNA antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against double-stranded DNA.

Name: Enchondroma
Desc: A solitary, benign, intramedullary cartilage tumor that is often found in the short tubular bones of the hands and feet, distal femur, and proximal humerus.

Name: Abnormal lateral ventricle morphology
Desc: A morphological anomaly of the lateral ventricle.

Name: Abnormal hip joint morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the hip joint.

Name: Abnormality of the vertebral endplates
Desc: Any abnormality of the vertebral end plates, which are the top and bottom portions of the vertebral bodies that interface with the vertebral discs.

Name: Type E brachydactyly
Desc: In type E brachydactyly, shortening of the fingers is mainly in the metacarpals and metatarsals.

Name: Delayed pubic bone ossification
Desc: Delayed maturation and calcification of the pubic bone.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the extremities
Broad hallux
Desc: Visible increase in width of the hallux without an increase in the dorso-ventral dimension.

Name: Abnormal circulating lipid concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a lipid in the blood circulation.

Name: Elevated circulating alkaline phosphatase concentration
Desc: Abnormally increased serum levels of alkaline phosphatase activity.

Name: Abnormality of the intrahepatic bile duct
Desc: An abnormality of the intrahepatic bile duct.

Name: Onychomycosis
Desc: A fungal infection of the toenails or fingernails that tends to cause the nails to thicken, discolor, disfigure, and split.

Name: Gastrointestinal inflammation
Desc: Inflammation of the alimentary part of the gastrointestinal system.

Name: Biliary cirrhosis
Desc: Progressive destruction of the small-to-medium bile ducts of the intrahepatic biliary tree, which leads to progressive cholestasis and often end-stage liver disease.

Name: Abnormality of the thyroid gland
Desc: An abnormality of the thyroid gland.

Name: Short greater sciatic notch
Desc: The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a reduction in the height of the notch.

Name: Abnormality of the ovary
Desc: An abnormality of the ovary.

Name: Spontaneous esophageal perforation
Desc: The occurrence of the full-thickness tear (perforation) of the wall of the esophagus.

Name: Complete duplication of the distal phalanges of the hand
Desc: A complete duplication affecting one or more of the distal phalanges of the hand.
Synonyms: Complete duplication of the outermost bones of the hand

Name: Abnormal renal tubule morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the renal tubules.
Synonyms: Morphologic abnormality of the renal tubules

Name: Multiple myeloma
Desc: A malignant plasma cell tumor growing within soft tissue or within the skeleton.

Name: Ebstein anomaly of the tricuspid valve
Desc: Ebstein's anomaly refers to an abnormally placed and deformed tricuspid valve characterized by apical displacement of the septal and posterior tricuspid valve leaflets, leading to atrialization of the right ventricle with a variable degree of malformation and displacement of the anterior leaflet.
Synonyms: Ebstein's anomaly of the tricuspid valve

Name: Imperforate tricuspid valve
Desc: A tricuspid valve that has failed to open.

Name: Ciliary dyskinesia
Desc: A deviation from the normally well coordinated pattern of intracellular and intercellular synchrony of motile cilia. Dyskinetic cilia usually beat out of synchrony relative to neighboring cilia.

Name: Joint contracture of the 5th finger
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion in the 5th finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly of the 5th finger is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

Name: Ectopia pupillae
Desc: A malposition of the pupil owing to a developmental defect of the iris.

Name: Abnormal nasolacrimal system morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the nasolacrimal drainage system, which serves as a conduit for tear flow from the external eye to the nasal cavity.

Name: Ectrodactyly
Desc: A condition in which middle parts of the hands and/or feet (digits and meta-carpals and -tarsals) are missing giving a cleft appearance. The severity is very variable ranging from slightly hypoplastic 3rd toe/fingers over absent 2nd or 3rd toes/fingers as far as oligo- or monodactyl hands and/or feet.

Name: Menometrorrhagia
Desc: Prolonged/excessive menses and bleeding at irregular intervals.

Name: Adrenal hyperplasia
Desc: Enlargement of the adrenal gland.

Name: Urethral atresia
Desc: Congenital anomaly characterized by closure or failure to develop an opening in the urethra.

Name: Hypoplasia of the thymus
Desc: Underdevelopment of the thymus.

Name: Selective tooth agenesis
Desc: Agenesis specifically affecting one of the classes incisor, premolar, or molar.
Synonyms: Failure of development of a tooth

Name: Abnormality of subcutaneous fat tissue
Synonyms: Abnormality of fatty tissue below the skin

Name: Avascular necrosis of the capital femoral epiphysis
Desc: Avascular necrosis of the proximal epiphysis of the femur occurring in growing children and caused by an interruption of the blood supply to the head of the femur close to the hip joint. The necrosis is characteristically associated with flattening of the femoral head, for which reason the term coxa plana has been used to refer to this feature in the medical literature.

Name: Femoral hernia
Desc: A hernia which occurs just below the inguinal ligament, where abdominal contents pass through a naturally occurring weakness called the femoral canal.

Name: Abnormal anterior chamber morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the anterior chamber, which is the space in the eye that is behind the cornea and in front of the iris.

Name: Atrophic scars
Desc: Scars that form a depression compared to the level of the surrounding skin because of damage to the collagen, fat or other tissues below the skin.
Synonyms: Sunken or indented skin due to damage

Name: Joint subluxation
Desc: A partial dislocation of a joint.

Name: Aortic dissection
Desc: Aortic dissection refers to a tear in the intimal layer of the aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers of the aorta.
Synonyms: Tear in inner wall of large artery that carries blood away from heart

Name: Shoulder subluxation
Desc: A partial dislocation of the shoulder joint.

Name: Distal joint laxity
Desc: Lack of stability of a distal joint (e.g., finger).

Name: Arterial rupture
Desc: Sudden breakage of an artery leading to leakage of blood from the circulation.

Name: Scleral rupture
Desc: Breakage of the sclera.

Name: Hip subluxation
Desc: A partial dislocation of the hip joint, whereby the head of the femur is partially displaced from the socket.

Name: Widened atrophic scar
Desc: An atrophic scar (fibrous connective tissue resulting from incomplete healing of a wound) that has stretched (gotten wider), a manifestation of tissue fragility.

Name: Abnormal venous morphology
Desc: An anomaly of vein.

Name: Wrist drop
Desc: A condition in which the affected individual cannot extend the wrist, which hangs flaccidly.

Name: Impaired tandem gait
Desc: Reduced ability to walk in a straight line while placing the feet heel to toe.

Name: Abnormality of the brachial nerve plexus
Desc: Any abnormality of the brachial nerve plexus.

Name: Vascular calcification
Desc: Abnormal calcification of the vasculature.

Name: Abnormal number of teeth
Desc: The presence of an altered number of of teeth.

Name: Retinal arteriolar constriction
Desc: Decreased retinal arteriolar diameters, which may decrease blood flow and slow oxygen delivery to regions of the retina.

Name: Lentiglobus
Desc: Exaggerated curvature of the lens of the eye, producing an anterior or posterior spherical bulging.

Name: Abnormal renal physiology
Desc: An abnormal functionality of the kidney.

Name: Malar rash
Desc: An erythematous (red), flat facial rash that affects the skin in the malar area (over the cheekbones) and extends over the bridge of the nose.

Name: Stooped posture
Desc: A habitual positioning of the body with the head and upper back bent forward.

Name: Retinal hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage occurring within the retina.

Name: Retinal atrophy
Desc: Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the fundus, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.

Name: Progressive microcephaly
Desc: Progressive microcephaly is diagnosed when the head circumference falls progressively behind age- and gender-dependent norms.

Name: Progressive sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A progressive form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

Name: High-frequency sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects primarily the higher frequencies.

Name: Basal ganglia calcification
Desc: The presence of calcium deposition affecting one or more structures of the basal ganglia.

Name: Dense calcifications in the cerebellar dentate nucleus
Patchy demyelination of subcortical white matter
Desc: Patchy loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

Name: Reduced subcutaneous adipose tissue
Desc: A reduced amount of fat tissue in the lowest layer of the integument. This feature can be appreciated by a reduced skinfold thickness.
Synonyms: Reduced fat tissue below the skin

Name: Dry hair
Desc: Hair that lacks the lustre (shine or gleam) of normal hair.

Name: Band keratopathy
Desc: An abnormality of the cornea characterized by the deposition of calcium in a band across the central cornea, leading to decreased vision, foreign body sensation, and ocular irritation.

Name: Delayed eruption of primary teeth
Desc: Delayed tooth eruption affecting the primary dentition.

Name: Limb hypertonia
Synonyms: Increased muscle tone of arm or leg

Name: Atherosclerosis
Desc: A condition characterized by patchy atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques which develop in the walls of medium-sized and large arteries and can lead to arterial stenosis with reduced or blocked blood flow.

Name: Thoracoabdominal eventration
Desc: Congenital protrusion of the abdominal or thoracic viscera, usually with a defect of the sternum and ribs as well as of the abdominal walls.

Name: Epididymal cyst
Desc: A smooth, extratesticular, spherical cyst in the head of the epididymis.

Name: Abnormal nasal base
Desc: An anomaly of the nasal base, which can be conceived of as an imaginary line between the most lateral points of the external inferior attachments of the alae nasi to the face.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of fingers
Desc: Small/hypoplastic or absent/aplastic fingers.

Name: Broad finger
Desc: Increased width of a non-thumb digit of the hand.

Name: Pseudoepiphyses of the metacarpals
Desc: A pseudoepiphysis is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis. The normal metacarpal epiphyses are located at the distal ends of the metacarpal bones. Accessory epiphyses (which are also known as pseudoepiphyses) can also occasionally be observed at the proximal ends of the metacarpals, usually involving the 2nd metacarpal bone.

Name: Contractures of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is also called Articulatio interphalangealis pollicis.

Name: Slender toe
Desc: Toes that are disproportionately narrow (reduced girth) for the hand/foot size or build of the individual.

Name: Cat cry
Desc: The presence of a characteristic high-pitched cry that sounds similar to the meowing of a kitten.

Name: Leukodystrophy
Desc: Leukodystrophy refers to deterioration of white matter of the brain resulting from degeneration of myelin sheaths in the CNS. Their basic defect is directly related to the synthesis and maintenance of myelin membranes. Symmetric white matter involvement at MRI is a typical finding in patients with leukodystrophies.
Synonyms: Degeneration of white matter of brain

Name: Methylmalonic aciduria
Desc: Increased concentration of methylmalonic acid in the urine.

Name: EEG with burst suppression
Desc: The burst suppression pattern in electroencephalography refers to a characteristic periodic pattern of low voltage (<10 microvolts) suppressed background and a relatively shorter pattern of higher amplitude slow, sharp, and spiking complexes.

Name: Uni- and bilateral multifocal epileptiform discharges
Desc: Epileptiform discharges identified at multiple locations temporarily in both hemispheres and temporarily in one hemisphere.

Name: Broad phalanx of the toes
Desc: Increased width of phalanx of one or more toes.

Name: Absent thumbnail
Desc: Absence of thumb nail.

Name: Focal tonic seizure
Desc: A type of focal motor seizure characterized by sustained increase in muscle contraction, lasting a few seconds to minutes.

Name: EEG with polyspike wave complexes
Desc: The presence of complexes of repetitive spikes and waves in EEG.
Synonyms: EEG: spike and multispike waves, 3-4 hz

Name: Photosensitive tonic-clonic seizure
Desc: Generalized-onset tonic-clonic seizures that are provoked by flashing or flickering light.

Name: EEG with spike-wave complexes (>3.5 Hz)
Desc: The presence of complexes of spikes and waves (>3.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Generalized myoclonic-atonic seizure
Desc: A generalized myoclonic-atonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterized by a myoclonic jerk followed by an atonic motor component.

Name: EEG with abnormally slow frequencies
Desc: EEG with abnormally slow frequencies.

Name: EEG with centrotemporal focal spike waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the centrotemporal region of the brain (also known as the central sulcus), i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: Laryngospasm
Desc: A spasm (involuntary contraction) of the vocal cords that can make it difficult to speak or breathe.

Name: EEG with irregular generalized spike and wave complexes
Desc: EEG shows spikes (<80 ms) and waves, which are recorded over the entire scalp and do not have a specific frequency.
Synonyms: EEG with irregular generalised spike and wave complexes

Name: Focal EEG discharges with secondary generalization
Desc: Focal EEG discharges that secondarily spread to both hemispheres and can then be recorded over the entire scalp.
Synonyms: Focal EEG discharges with secondary generalisation

Name: Focal clonic seizure
Desc: A focal clonic seizure is a type of focal motor seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking, that is regularly repetitive.

Name: Focal autonomic seizure
Desc: An autonomic seizure is a type of focal non-motor seizure characterized by alteration of autonomic nervous system function as the initial semiological feature.

Name: Circumoral cyanosis
Desc: Persistent blue color of the skin that surrounds the mouth.

Name: Increased theta frequency activity in EEG
Desc: Increased frequency of theta wave activity in the electroencephalogram. Theta waves have a frequency of 3.5-7.5 Hertz, and are present in very small amounts in healthy waking adult EEGs. Theta activity is normal in small very amounts in the healthy waking adult EEG in a symmetrical distribution.

Name: Conjunctival telangiectasia
Desc: The presence of small (ca. 0.5-1.0 mm) dilated blood vessels near the surface of the mucous membranes of the conjunctiva.
Synonyms: Small dilated blood vessels near membrane covering front of eye and eyelids

Name: Neutropenia in presence of anti-neutropil antibodies
Desc: A type of neutropenia that is observed in the presence of granulocyte-specific antibodies.

Name: Multiple exostoses
Desc: Presence of more than one exostosis. An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage, and arises from a bone that develops from cartilage.

Name: Ventricular extrasystoles
Desc: Premature ventricular contractions (PVC) or ventricular extrasystoles are premature contractions of the heart that arise in response to an impulse in the ventricles rather than the normal impulse from the sinoatrial (SA) node.

Name: Long nose
Desc: Distance from nasion to subnasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased length from the nasal root to the nasal base.

Name: Hyperlipoproteinemia
Desc: An abnormal increase in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of esophagus physiology
Desc: Any physiological abnormality of the esophagus.

Name: Bladder diverticulum
Desc: Diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.

Name: Abnormality of the pubic bone
Desc: An anomaly of the the pubic bone, i.e., of the ventral and anterior of the three principal components (publis, ilium, ischium) of the hip bone.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the humerus
Desc: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the humerus.
Synonyms: Absent/small long bone in upper arm
Absent/underdeveloped long bone in upper arm

Name: Large iliac wing
Desc: Increased size of the ilium ala.

Name: Phthisis bulbi
Desc: Atrophy of the eyeball with blindness and decreased intraocular pressure due to end-stage intraocular disease.

Name: Prenatal movement abnormality
Desc: An abnormality of fetal movement.

Name: Short 1st metacarpal
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by reduced length of the first metacarpal (long bone) of the hand.

Name: Submucous cleft of soft and hard palate
Desc: Soft and hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the soft and hard palate that are covered by the lining (ie mucous membrane) of the roof of the mouth.

Name: Secondary hypercortisolism
Desc: Hypercortisolemia associated with a overproduction of ACTH (often from a tumor), leading secondarily to overproduction of cortisol.

Name: Pituitary corticotropic cell adenoma
Desc: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH).

Name: Quadriceps muscle atrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy involving the quadriceps muscle.

Name: Oculomotor nerve palsy
Desc: Reduced ability to control the movement of the eye associated with damage to the third cranial nerve (the oculomotor nerve).

Name: Increased circulating prolactin concentration
Desc: The presence of abnormally increased levels of prolactin in the blood. Prolactin is a peptide hormone produced by the anterior pituitary gland that plays a role in breast development and lactation during pregnancy.

Name: Pituitary carcinoma
Desc: A pituitary tumor with subarachnoid, brain, or systemic metastasis. The diagnosis of a pituitary carcinoma requires evidence of metastatic disease, either outside the central nervous system (CNS) or as separate noncontiguous foci within the CNS.

Name: Abnormality of the sphenoid sinus
Desc: An abnormality of the sphenoid sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The sphenoid sinus is located within the sphenoid bone.

Name: Medulloblastoma
Desc: A rapidly growing embryonic tumor arising in the posterior part of the cerebellar vermis and neuroepithelial roof of the fourth ventricle in children. More rarely, medulloblastoma arises in the cerebellum in adults.

Name: Odontogenic keratocysts of the jaw
Desc: A benign uni- or multicystic, intraosseous tumor of odontogenic origin, with a characteristic lining of parakeratinized stratified squamous epithelium and potential for aggressive, infiltrative behaviour.

Name: Prolonged neonatal jaundice
Desc: Neonatal jaundice refers to a yellowing of the skin and other tissues of a newborn infant as a result of increased concentrations of bilirubin in the blood. Neonatal jaundice affects over half of all newborns to some extent in the first week of life. Prolonged neonatal jaundice is said to be present if the jaundice persists for longer than 14 days in term infants and 21 days in preterm infants.
Synonyms: Prolonged yellowing of skin in newborn

Name: Decreased circulating ACTH level
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the concentration of corticotropin, also known as adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), in the blood.

Name: Normocytic anemia
Desc: A kind of anemia in which the volume of the red blood cells is normal.

Name: Macrocytic anemia
Desc: A type of anemia characterized by increased size of erythrocytes with increased mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH).

Name: Graves disease
Desc: An autoimmune disease where the thyroid is overactive, producing an excessive amount of thyroid hormones (a serious metabolic imbalance known as hyperthyroidism and thyrotoxicosis). This is caused by autoantibodies to the TSH-receptor (TSHR-Ab) that activate that TSH-receptor (TSHR), thereby stimulating thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion, and thyroid growth (causing a diffusely enlarged goiter). The resulting state of hyperthyroidism can cause a dramatic constellation of neuropsychological and physical signs and symptoms, which can severely compromise the patients.

Name: Generalized bone demineralization
Desc: A generalized decrease in bone mineral density.

Name: Velopharyngeal insufficiency
Desc: Inability of velopharyngeal sphincter to sufficiently separate the nasal cavity from the oral cavity during speech.

Name: Supernumerary maxillary incisor
Desc: The presence of a supernumerary, i.e., extra, maxillary incisor, either the primary maxillary incisor or the permanent maxillary incisor.

Name: Maternal teratogenic exposure
Desc: A medical history of exposure of the mother of a child or fetus to a teratogenic substance during pregnancy.

Name: Low self esteem
Desc: Negative opinion about oneself characterized by low self-confidence and exaggeratedly critical feelings about oneself.

Name: Bilateral cleft lip
Desc: A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on the left and right sides.

Name: Malnutrition
Desc: A deficiency in the intake of energy and nutrients.

Name: Peg-shaped maxillary lateral incisors
Desc: A tooth crown with its mesial and distal sides converging or tapering toward the incisal edge causing severe reduction of mesiodistal diameter

Name: Palate fistula
Desc: A fistula which connects the oral cavity and the pharyngeal area via the aspects of the soft palate.

Name: Abnormal number of permanent teeth
Desc: The presence of an altered number of of permanent teeth.

Name: Bilateral cleft palate
Desc: Nonmidline cleft palate on the left and right sides.

Name: Agenesis of lateral incisor
Synonyms: Failure of development of lateral incisor

Name: Perineal hypospadias
Desc: Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the perineal region.

Name: True hermaphroditism
Desc: The presence of both ovarian and testicular tissues either in the same or in opposite gonads. Affected persons have ambiguous genitalia and may have 46,XX or 46,XY karyotypes or 46,XX/XY mosaicism.

Name: Blood group antigen abnormality
Desc: An abnormality of an erythrocyte cell surface molecule.

Name: Abnormal cellular immune system morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the morphology or counts of the cells that make up the immune system.

Name: Renal magnesium wasting
Desc: High urine magnesium in the presence of hypomagnesemia.

Name: Abnormal urinary electrolyte concentration
Desc: An abnormality in the concentration of electrolytes in the urine.

Name: Renal sodium wasting
Desc: An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the urine in the presence of hyponatremia.

Name: Salt craving
Desc: An excessive desire to eat salt (sodium chloride) or salty foods.

Name: Metabolic alkalosis
Desc: Metabolic alkalosis is defined as a disease state where the pH is elevated to greater than 7.45 secondary to some metabolic process.

Name: Peripheral hypomyelination
Desc: Reduced amount of myelin in the nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis in the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Hypometric saccades
Desc: Saccadic undershoot, i.e., a saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object.

Name: Parkinsonism with favorable response to dopaminergic medication
Desc: Parkinsonism is a clinical syndrome that is a feature of a number of different diseases, including Parkinson disease itself, other neurodegenerative diseases such as progressive supranuclear palsy, and as a side-effect of some neuroleptic medications. Some but not all individuals with Parkinsonism show responsiveness to dopaminergic medication defined as a substantial reduction of amelioration of the component signs of Parkinsonism (including mainly tremor, bradykinesia, rigidity, and postural instability) upon administration of dopaminergic medication.
Synonyms: Parkinsonism with favourable response to dopaminergic medication

Name: Generalized cerebral atrophy/hypoplasia
Desc: Generalized atrophy or hypoplasia of the cerebrum.

Name: Stiff hip
Desc: A sensation of tightness in the hip joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

Name: Supranuclear gaze palsy
Desc: A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a particular direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.

Name: Euryblepharon
Desc: Euryblepharon is a congenital eyelid anomaly characterized by horizontal enlargement of the palpebral fissure. The eyelid is shortened vertically compared with the horizontal dimension, with associated lateral canthal malpositioning and lateral ectropion abnormally wide lid opening.

Name: Epidermoid cyst
Desc: Nontender, round and firm, but slightly compressible, intradermal or subcutaneous cyst measuring 0.5-5 cm in diameter. Epidermal cysts are intradermal or subcutaneous tumors, grow slowly and occur on the face, neck, back and scrotum. They usually appear at or around puberty, and as a rule an affected individual has one solitary or a few cysts.

Name: Recurrent hypoglycemia
Desc: Recurrent episodes of decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.

Name: Reye syndrome-like episodes
Desc: Repeated occurrences of acute noninflammatory encephalopathy and fatty degenerative liver failure.

Name: Hypoglycemic coma
Synonyms: Coma caused by low blood sugar
Loss of consciousness due to hypoglycemia

Name: Spastic hemiparesis
Desc: Unilateral paresis (weakness) with spasticity of the affected muscles and increased tendon reflexes.

Name: Severe sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A severe form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

Name: Sacral lipoma
Desc: Presence of a lipoma in the region of the sacrum.

Name: Impaired oropharyngeal swallow response
Desc: Delay or absence of the swallow response, reflexes triggered by the contact the food bolus makes with the anterior faucial pillars.

Name: Cleft ala nasi
Desc: The presence of a notch in the margin of the ala nasi.

Name: Hyperthyroidism
Desc: An abnormality of thyroid physiology characterized by excessive secretion of the thyroid hormones thyroxine (i.e., T4) and/or 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine zwitterion (i.e., triiodothyronine or T3).

Name: Follicular thyroid carcinoma
Desc: The presence of an follicular adenocarcinoma of the thyroid gland.

Name: Adenoma sebaceum
Desc: The presence of a sebaceous adenoma with origin in the sebum secreting cells of the skin.

Name: Papilloma
Desc: A tumor of the skin or mucous membrane with finger-like projections.

Name: Neoplasm of the central nervous system
Desc: A neoplasm of the central nervous system.
Synonyms: Neoplasia of the central nervous system
Tumors of the central nervous system
Tumours of the central nervous system

Name: Conjunctival hamartoma
Desc: A hamartoma (disordered proliferation of mature tissues) of the conjunctiva.

Name: Carpal synostosis
Desc: Synostosis (bony fusion) involving one or more bones of the carpus (scaphoid, lunate, triquetrum, trapezium, trapezoid, capitate, hamate, pisiform).

Name: Oligodontia of primary teeth
Desc: Reduced number of primary teeth.
Synonyms: Failure of development of some deciduous teeth
Failure of development of some primary teeth

Name: Elfin facies
Desc: This is a description previously used to describe a facial form characterized by a short, upturned nose, wide mouth, widely spaced eyes, and full cheeks. Because of the imprecision in this definition it is preferable to describe these features precisely. This term is retained because it was often used in the past, but it should not be used for new annotations.

Name: Humeroradial synostosis
Desc: An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the radius and the humerus.
Synonyms: Fusion of upper and lower arm bones

Name: Short humerus
Desc: Underdevelopment of the humerus.
Synonyms: Short long bone of upper arm

Name: Ankle flexion contracture
Desc: A chronic loss of ankle joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the ankle.

Name: Type 1 muscle fiber atrophy
Desc: Atrophy (wasting) affecting primary type 1 muscle fibers. This feature in general can only be observed on muscle biopsy.

Name: Flexion contracture of finger
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion in a finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Name: Soft tissue sarcoma
Desc: A type of sarcoma (A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells) that develops from soft tissues like fat, muscle, nerves, fibrous tissues, blood vessels, or deep skin tissues.

Name: Progressive flexion contractures
Desc: Progressively worsening joint contractures.

Name: Honeycomb lung
Desc: Honeycombing represents destroyed and fibrotic lung tissue containing numerous cystic airspaces with thick fibrous walls, representing the late stage of various lung diseases, with complete loss of acinar architecture. The cysts range in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters in diameter, have variable wall thickness, and are lined by metaplastic bronchiolar epithelium. On chest radiographs, honeycombing appears as closely approximated ring shadows, typically 3-10 mm in diameter with walls 1-3 mm in thickness, that resemble a honeycomb; the finding implies end-stage lung disease. On CT scans, the appearance is of clustered cystic air spaces, typically of comparable diameters on the order of 3-10 mm but occasionally as large as 2.5 cm. Honeycombing is usually subpleural and is characterized by well-defined walls. It is a CT feature of established pulmonary fibrosis. Because honeycombing is often considered specific for pulmonary fibrosis and is an important criterion in the diagnosis of usual interstitial pneumonia, the term should be used with care, as it may directly impact patient care.

Name: Reticular pattern on pulmonary HRCT
Desc: On pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography, reticular pattern is characterised by innumerable interlacing shadows suggesting a mesh.

Name: Clubbing of fingers
Desc: Terminal broadening of the fingers (distal phalanges of the fingers).

Name: Pulmonary insufficiency
Desc: The retrograde (backwards) flow of blood through the pulmonary valve into the right ventricle during diastole.

Name: Lymphadenitis
Desc: Inflammation of a lymph node.

Name: Circulating immune complexes
Desc: Persistence of immune complexes in the blood circulation.

Name: Opportunistic infection
Desc: An infection that is caused by a pathogen that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such pathogens take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

Name: Opportunistic bacterial infection
Desc: An infection that is caused by a bacterium that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such bacteria take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

Name: Vaginal hydrocele
Desc: A type of hydrocele testis in which the processus vaginalis remains patent only around the testes, and, as fluid accumulates, it renders the testes impalpable.

Name: Urethral obstruction
Desc: Obstruction of the flow of urine through the urethra.

Name: Abnormal scalp morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of the scalp, the skin an subcutaneous tissue of the head on which head hair grows.

Name: Underdeveloped antitragus
Desc: Reduction in the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.

Name: Underdeveloped tragus
Desc: Decreased posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.

Name: Duplication of renal pelvis
Desc: A duplication of the renal pelvis.

Name: Pyelonephritis
Desc: An inflammation of the kidney involving the parenchyma of kidney, the renal pelvis and the kidney calices.

Name: Pulmonary arteriovenous fistulas
Desc: A rare vascular anomaly with a direct communication between pulmonary artery and pulmonary vein without an intervening capillary bed.

Name: Hemothorax
Desc: The presence of blood in the pleural space.

Name: Clubbing
Desc: Broadening of the soft tissues (non-edematous swelling of soft tissues) of the digital tips in all dimensions associated with an increased longitudinal and lateral curvature of the nails.

Name: Abnormal thrombosis
Desc: Venous or arterial thrombosis (formation of blood clots) of spontaneous nature and which cannot be fully explained by acquired risk (e.g. atherosclerosis).

Name: Pleural empyema
Desc: Accumulation of pus in the pleural cavity.

Name: Brain abscess
Desc: A collection of pus, immune cells, and other material in the brain.

Name: Pulmonary hemorrhage
Desc: Pulmonary hemorrhage is a bleeding within the lungs. Older children and adults may spit blood or bloody sputum. Neonates, infants and young children usually do not spit up blood. Anemia, pulmonary infiltrates, increasingling bloody return on BAL and the presence of hemosiderin-laden macrophages in broncho-alveolar lavage (BAL) fluid or lung biopsy can diagnose lung bleeding. Alveolar macrophages contain phagocytosed red blood cells and stain positive for hemosiderin, a product of hemoglobin degradation, after about 48-72 hours following pulmonary hemorraghe. Previous or recurrent bleeding can thus be distinguished from fresh events. A differentiation into local or diffuse is of importance. Also differentiate if pulmonary hemorrhage is due to a primary lung disorder or a manifestation of a systemic disease.

Name: Neuronal loss in central nervous system
Akinetic mutism
Desc: Akinetic mutism is essentially characterized by a total absence of spontaneous behavior and speech occurring in the presence of preserved visual tracking.

Name: Recurrent aspiration pneumonia
Desc: Increased susceptibility to aspiration pneumonia, defined as pneumonia due to breathing in foreign material, as manifested by a medical history of repeated episodes of aspiration pneumonia.

Name: Congenital posterior urethral valve
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in an obstructing membrane in the posterior male urethra.

Name: Crumpled long bones
Desc: An crumpled radiographic appearance of the long bones, as if the long bone had been crushed together producing irregularities. This feature is the result of multiple fractures and repeated rounds of ineffective healing, as can be seen for instance in severe forms of osteogenesis imperfecta.

Name: Cryptophthalmos
Desc: Cryptophthalmos is a condition of total absence of eyelids and the skin of forehead is continuous with that of cheek, in which the eyeball is completely concealed by the skin, which is stretched over the orbital cavity.

Name: Anal stenosis
Desc: Abnormal narrowing of the anal opening.

Name: Wide pubic symphysis
Desc: Abnormally increased width of the pubic symphysis is the midline cartilaginous joint uniting the superior rami of the left and right pubic bones.

Name: Lacrimal duct aplasia
Desc: A congenital defect resulting in absence of the lacrimal duct.

Name: Malformed lacrimal duct
Desc: Congenital malformation of the lacrimal duct associated with incomplete development of the bony nasolacrimal canal or craniofacial anomalies.

Name: Patellar aplasia
Desc: Absence of the patella.

Name: Proximal radio-ulnar synostosis
Desc: An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the proximal portions of the radius and the ulna.

Name: Multiple unerupted teeth
Desc: The presence of multiple embedded tooth germs which have failed to erupt.
Synonyms: Failure of eruption of multiple teeth

Name: Crowded maxillary incisors
Desc: A type of dental misalignment with crowded central incisors, i.e., of maxillary secondary incisor, or of maxillary central primary incisor.

Name: Posterior fusion of lumbosacral vertebrae
Desc: Bony fusion of the posterior part of the L5 vertebral body with the sacrum.

Name: Unexplained fevers
Desc: Episodes of fever for which no infectious cause can be identified.

Name: Elevated brain choline level by MRS
Desc: An increase in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

Name: Reduced brain N-acetyl aspartate level by MRS
Desc: A decrease in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Synonyms: Reduced brain N-acetyl aspartate level by magnetic resonance spectroscopy

Name: Reduced brain glutamate level by MRS
Desc: An decrease in the level of glutamate (Glu) in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

Name: Shoulder girdle muscle weakness
Desc: The shoulder, or pectoral, girdle is composed of the clavicles and the scapulae. Shoulder-girdle weakness refers to lack of strength of the muscles attaching to these bones, that is, lack of strength of the muscles around the shoulders.

Name: Temperature instability
Desc: Disordered thermoregulation characterized by an impaired ability to maintain a balance between heat production and heat loss, with resulting instability of body temperature.

Name: Decerebrate rigidity
Desc: A type of rigidity that is manifested by an exaggerated extensor posture of all extremities.

Name: Slow pupillary light response
Desc: Reduced velocity and acceleration in the pupillary light response.

Name: Abnormal heart rate variability
Desc: Any abnormality in the variability of the time interval between successive heartbeats.

Name: Cherry red spot of the macula
Desc: Pallor of the perifoveal macula of the retina with appearance of a small circular reddish choroid shape as seen through the fovea centralis due to relative transparancy of the macula.

Name: EEG with persistent abnormal rhythmic activity
Abnormal CNS myelination
Desc: An abnormality of myelination of nerves in the central nervous system.

Name: Abnormal corpus callosum morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the corpus callosum.

Name: Abnormal midbrain morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the midbrain, which has as its parts the tectum, cerebral peduncle, midbrain tegmentum and cerebral aqueduct.

Name: Morphological abnormality of the pyramidal tract
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the pyramidal tract, whose chief element, the corticospinal tract, is the only direct connection between the brain and the spinal cord. In addition to the corticospinal tract, the pyramidal system includes the corticobulbar, corticomesencephalic, and corticopontine tracts.

Name: Abnormality of the medulla oblongata
Desc: An abnormality of the medulla oblongata, the lower half of the brainstem.

Name: Morphological abnormality of the corticospinal tract
Desc: Abnormality of the corticospinal tract, which is the chief element of the pyramidal system (the principle motor tract) and is the only direct connection between the cerebrum and the spinal cord.

Name: Erectile dysfunction
Desc: A multidimensional but common male sexual dysfunction that involves an alteration in any of the components of the erectile response, including organic, relational and psychological.

Name: Ovarian gonadoblastoma
Desc: The presence of a gonadoblastoma of the ovary.

Name: Gonadal calcification
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in gonadal tissue.

Name: Dysgerminoma
Desc: The presence of a dysgerminoma, i.e., an undifferentiated germ cell tumor of the ovary.

Name: Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy
Desc: Muscular dystrophy affecting the muscles of the limb girdle (the hips and shoulders).

Name: EMG: axonal abnormality
Desc: Electromyographic (EMG) findings characteristic of axonal neuropathy, with normal or slightly decreased nerve conduction velocities, normal or slightly prolonged distal latencies, but significantly reduced motor potentials and sensory amplitudes. There may be spontaneous activity upon needle EMG studies, such as increased insertional activity, positive sharp waves, and fibrillation potentials.

Name: EMG: myotonic runs
Desc: Spontaneous, repetitive electrical activity demonstrated by electromyography (EMG).

Name: Pelvic girdle muscle atrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles that attach to the pelvic girdle (the gluteal muscles, the lateral rotators, adductor magnus, adductor brevis, adductor longus, pectineus, and gracilis muscles).

Name: Fatty replacement of skeletal muscle
Desc: Muscle fibers degeneration resulting in fatty replacement of skeletal muscle fibers

Name: Reduced muscle fiber alpha dystroglycan
Desc: Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced alpha dystroglycan protein in the muscle biopsy. Alpha-dystroglycan is a heavily glycosylated peripheral-membrane component of the dystrophin-associated glycoprotein complex (DAPC), which, in addition to laminin alpha2, binds perlecan and agrin in the extracellular matrix, whereas beta-dystroglycan, derived from the same gene, is a transmembrane protein that links to dystrophin intracellularly.

Name: Proximal amyotrophy
Desc: Amyotrophy (muscular atrophy) affecting the proximal musculature.
Synonyms: Wasting of muscles near the body

Name: Scapuloperoneal amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy in the distribution of shoulder girdle and peroneal muscles.

Name: Left ventricular systolic dysfunction
Desc: Abnormality of left ventricular contraction, often defined operationally as an ejection fraction of less than 40 percent.

Name: Keratoconus
Desc: A cone-shaped deformity of the cornea characterized by the presence of corneal distortion secondary to thinning of the apex.

Name: Multiple suture craniosynostosis
Desc: Craniosynostosis involving at least 2 cranial sutures, where the exact pattern of sutures fused has not been precisely specified.

Name: Narrow internal auditory canal
Desc: Reduction in diameter of the internal auditory canal.

Name: Allergic rhinitis
Desc: It is characterized by one or more symptoms including sneezing, itching, nasal congestion, and rhinorrhea.

Name: Aortic valve calcification
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in the aortic valve.

Name: Mitral valve calcification
Desc: Abnormal calcification of the mitral valve.

Name: Calcification of the aorta
Desc: Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the aorta.

Name: Papilledema
Desc: Papilledema refers to edema (swelling) of the optic disc secondary to any factor which increases cerebral spinal fluid pressure.

Name: Opsoclonus
Desc: Bursts of large-amplitude multidirectional saccades without intersaccadic interval

Name: Abnormal visual fixation
Desc: Any anomaly in the process of ocular fixation, which is the maintaining of the visual gaze on a single location.

Name: Ecchymosis
Desc: A purpuric lesion that is larger than 1 cm in diameter.

Name: Cataplexy
Desc: A sudden and transient episode of bilateral loss of muscle tone, often triggered by emotions.

Name: Abnormality of the gallbladder
Desc: An abnormality of the gallbladder.

Name: Gonadal dysgenesis, male
Desc: Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to an unassigned sex differentiation.

Name: Vertebral compression fracture
Synonyms: Compression fracture of a vertebral body

Name: Biconcave vertebral bodies
Desc: Exaggerated concavity of the anterior or posterior surface of the vertebral body, i.e., the upper and lower vertebral endplates are hollowed inward.

Name: Delayed fine motor development
Desc: A type of motor delay characterized by a delay in acquiring the ability to control the fingers and hands.

Name: Auditory hallucinations
Desc: The false perception of sound.

Name: Delirium
Desc: A state of sudden and severe confusion.

Name: Suicidal ideation
Desc: Frequent thinking about or preoccupation with killing oneself.

Name: Abnormal fear/anxiety-related behavior
Desc: An abnormality of fear/anxiety-related behavior, which may relate to either abnormally reduced fear/anxiety-related response or increased fear/anxiety-related response.

Name: Pseudobulbar signs
Desc: Pseudobulbar signs result from injury to an upper motor neuron lesion to the corticobulbar pathways in the pyramidal tract. Patients have difficulty chewing, swallowing and demonstrate slurred speech (often initial presentation) as well as abnormal behavioral symptoms such as inappropriate emotional outbursts of uncontrolled laughter or weeping etc.

Name: Profound global developmental delay
Desc: A profound delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

Name: Spastic tetraplegia
Desc: Spastic paralysis affecting all four limbs.

Name: Paroxysmal dyskinesia
Desc: Episodic bouts of involuntary movements with dystonic, choreic, ballistic movements, or a combination thereof. There is no loss of consciousness during the attacks.

Name: Total ophthalmoplegia
Desc: Paralysis of both the extrinsic and intrinsic ocular muscles.

Name: Delayed social development
Desc: A failure to meet one or more age-related milestones of social behavior.

Name: Visual fixation instability
Desc: A deficit in the ability to fixate eye movements in order to stabilize images on the retina

Name: Increased hepatic glycogen content
Desc: An increase in the amount of glycogen stored in hepatocytes compared to normal.

Name: Impaired glucose tolerance
Desc: An abnormal resistance to glucose, i.e., a reduction in the ability to maintain glucose levels in the blood stream within normal limits following oral or intravenous administration of glucose.

Name: Abnormal hepatic glycogen storage
Desc: Change in normal glycogen storage content.

Name: Postprandial hyperglycemia
Desc: An increased concentration of glucose in the blood following a meal.

Name: Generalized aminoaciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of all types of amino acid in the urine.

Name: Bone fracture
Desc: A partial or complete breakage of the continuity of a bone.

Name: Elevated circulating aspartate aminotransferase concentration
Desc: An abnormally high concentration in the circulation of aspartate aminotransferase (AST).

Name: Elevated circulating alanine aminotransferase concentration
Desc: An abnormally high concentration in the circulation of alanine aminotransferase (ALT).

Name: Doll-like facies
Desc: A characteristic facial appearance with a round facial form, full cheeks, a short nose, and a relatively small chin.

Name: Ketosis
Desc: Presence of elevated levels of ketone bodies in the body.

Name: Ketotic hypoglycemia
Desc: Low blood glucose is accompanied by elevated levels of ketone bodies in the body.

Name: Symmetrical progressive peripheral demyelination
Desc: A symmetric and progressive loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Demyelinating sensory neuropathy
Desc: Demyelination of peripheral sensory nerves.

Name: Demyelinating motor neuropathy
Desc: Demyelination of peripheral motor nerves.

Name: Macular coloboma
Desc: A congenital defect of the macula distinct from coloboma associated with optic fissure closure defects. Macular coloboma is characterized by a sharply defined, rather large defect in the central area of the fundus that is oval or round, and coarsely pigmented.

Name: Bowel diverticulosis
Desc: The presence of multiple diverticula of the intestine.

Name: Esophageal diverticulum
Desc: The presence of a diverticulum of the esophagus.

Name: Rieger anomaly
Desc: A congenital malformation of the anterior segment characterized by iridicorneal malformation, glaucoma, iris stroma hypoplasia, posterior embryotoxon, and corneal opacities.

Name: Chronic axonal neuropathy
Desc: An abnormality characterized by chronic impairment of the normal functioning of the axons.

Name: Monoclonal immunoglobulin M proteinemia
Desc: Presence of a monoclonal immunoglobulin M protein in the serum.

Name: Increased circulating beta-2-microglobulin level
Desc: Elevated concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.

Name: Cryoglobulinemia
Desc: Increased level of cryoglobulins in the blood. Cryoglobulins are abnormal immunoglobulins, especially IGG or IGM, that precipitate spontaneously when serum is cooled below 37 degrees Celsius.

Name: Multinodular goiter
Desc: Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to multiple nodules in the thyroid gland.

Name: Abnormality of the pulmonary vasculature
Synonyms: Abnormality of the lung blood vessels

Name: Abnormal adipose tissue morphology
Desc: An abnormality of adipose tissue, which is loose connective tissue composed of adipocytes.

Name: Giant cell tumor of bone
Desc: A bone tumor composed of cellular spindle-cell stroma containing scattered multinucleated giant cells resembling osteoclasts.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nasal bone
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the nasal bone.

Name: Skin dimple over apex of long bone angulation
Abnormality of the glenoid fossa
Desc: An anomaly of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the metacarpal bones
Desc: Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the metacarpal bones.

Name: Aplasia of the middle phalanges of the toes
Macrovesicular hepatic steatosis
Desc: A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of large, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes.

Name: Increased LDL cholesterol concentration
Desc: An elevated concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Accelerated atherosclerosis
