Desc: Atherosclerosis which occurs in a person with certain risk factors (e.g., SLE, diabetes, smoking, hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, family history of early heart disease) at an earlier age than would occur in another person without those risk factors.

Name: Acute hepatic steatosis
Desc: An acute form of hepatic steatosis.

Name: Cholesterol gallstones
Desc: Gallstones composed primarily of cholesterol, usually about 2-3 cm in length with an oval form and a yellow or green/brown color.

Name: Aortic atherosclerotic lesion
Desc: The presence of atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques in the aorta.

Name: Megacystis
Desc: Dilatation of the bladder postnatally.

Name: Cavum septum pellucidum
Desc: If the two laminae of the septum pellucidum are not fused then a fluid-filled space or cavum is present. The cavum septum pellucidum is present at birth but usually obliterates by the age of 3 to 6 months. It is up to 1cm in width and the walls are parallel. It is an enclosed space and is not part of the ventricular system or connected with the subarachnoid space.

Name: Abnormal drinking behavior
Desc: Abnormal consumption of fluids with excessive or insufficient consumption of fluid or any other abnormal pattern of fluid consumption.

Name: Elevated circulating thyroid-stimulating hormone concentration
Desc: Increased concentration of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) in the blood circulation.

Name: Compensated hypothyroidism
Desc: Condition associated with a raised serum concentration of thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) but a normal serum free thyroxine (FT4).

Name: Thyroid hemiagenesis
Desc: Absence of a lobe of the thyroid gland related to a failure of its embryologic development.

Name: Receptive language delay
Desc: A delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

Name: Poor gross motor coordination
Desc: An abnormality of the ability (skills) to perform a precise movement of large muscles with the intent to perform a specific act. Gross motor skills are required to mediate movements of the arms, legs, and other large body parts.

Name: Retinal exudate
Desc: Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina.

Name: Tractional retinal detachment
Desc: A type of retinal detachment arising due to a combination of contracting retinal membranes, abnormal vitreoretinal adhesions, and vitreous changes. It is usually seen in the context of diseases that induce a fibrovascular response, e.g. diabetes.

Name: Macular edema
Desc: Thickening of the retina that takes place due to accumulation of fluid in the macula as a nonspecific response to blood-retinal barrier breakdown. Macular edema is a common pathological response to a wide variety of ocular insults, most commonly after intraocular (e.g. cataract) surgery or in association with retinal vascular (e.g. diabetic eye disease, retinal vein occlusion) or inflammatory (e.g. uveitis) disease.

Name: Bilateral wrist flexion contracture
Desc: A chronic loss of wrist joint motion on the right and left sides.

Name: Flexion contracture of toe
Desc: One or more bent (flexed) toe joints that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

Name: Restricted neck movement due to contractures
Synonyms: Restricted neck mobility due to contractures
Restricted neck movement due to contractures

Name: Abnormal sclera morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the sclera.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the outer white part of eyeball

Name: Abnormal anterior eye segment morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the anterior segment of the eyeball (which comprises the structures in front of the vitreous humour: the cornea, iris, ciliary body, and lens).
Synonyms: Abnormality of the anterior segment of the eye
Abnormality of the anterior segment of the eyeball
Abnormality of the anterior segment of the globe

Name: Exudative retinal detachment
Desc: A type of retinal detachment arising from damage to the outer blood-retinal barrier that allows fluid to access the subretinal space and separate the neurosensory retina from the retinal pigment epithelium.

Name: Superficial episcleral hyperemia
Desc: Prominence of blood vessels of the superficial episcleral tissues.

Name: Scleral thickening
Desc: Increased dimension of the sclera in the anterior-posterior axis.

Name: Subretinal fluid
Desc: Edema/fluid accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane.

Name: Retinal fold
Desc: A wrinkle of retinal tissue projecting outward from the surface of the retina and visible as a line on fundoscopy.

Name: Abnormal intraocular pressure
Desc: An anomaly in the amount of force per unit area exerted by the intraocular fluid within the eye.

Name: Myokymia
Desc: Myokymia consists of involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions that spread across the affected striated muscle.

Name: Erlenmeyer flask deformity of the femurs
Desc: Flaring of distal femur.
Synonyms: Erlenmeyer flask deformity of distal femur

Name: Cortical sclerosis
Desc: Sclerosis (abnormal hardening) of cortical bone, characterized by increased radiodensity.

Name: Osteosclerosis of the base of the skull
Desc: An increase in bone density affecting the basicranium (base of the skull).

Name: Optic atrophy from cranial nerve compression
Asplenia
Desc: Absence (aplasia) of the spleen.

Name: Pulmonary valve atresia
Desc: A congenital disorder of the pulmonary valve in which the orifice of the valve fails to develop.

Name: Gaze-evoked horizontal nystagmus
Desc: Horizontal nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.

Name: Abnormal circulating histidine concentration
Desc: An abnormality of a histidine metabolic process.

Name: Urocanic aciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of urocanic acid in the urine.

Name: Nodular regenerative hyperplasia of liver
Desc: Diffuse benign transformation of the hepatic parenchyma into small regenerative nodules with minimal or no fibrosis.

Name: Abnormality of the hepatic vasculature
Desc: An abnormality of the hepatic vasculature.

Name: Myocardial fibrosis
Desc: Myocardial fibrosis is characterized by dysregulated collagen turnover (increased synthesis predominates over unchanged or decreased degradation) and excessive diffuse collagen accumulation in the interstitial and perivascular spaces as well as by phenotypically transformed fibroblasts, termed myofibroblasts.

Name: Abnormal breath sound
Desc: An anomalous (adventitious) sound produced by the breathing process.

Name: Torticollis
Desc: Involuntary contractions of the neck musculature resulting in an abnormal posture of or abnormal movements of the head.

Name: Abnormality of the tongue
Desc: Any abnormality of the tongue.

Name: Rib exostoses
Desc: Multiple circumscribed bony excrescences located in the ribs.

Name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the femoral head
Desc: Any abnormality of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the end part of the innermost thighbone
Abnormality of the proximal femoral epiphysis

Name: Glossitis
Desc: Inflammation of the tongue.

Name: Neutral hyperaminoaciduria
Desc: The presence of an abnormally increased concentration of neutral amino acids in the urine. The neutral amino acids are tryptophan, alanine, asparagine, glutamine, histidine, isoleucine, leucine, phenylalanine, serine, threonine, tyrosine and valine.

Name: Abnormal urinary color
Desc: An abnormal color of the urine, that is, the color of the urine appears different from the usual straw-yellow color.

Name: Lobar holoprosencephaly
Desc: A type of holoprosencephaly in which most of the right and left cerebral hemispheres and lateral ventricles are separated but the most rostral aspect of the telencephalon, the frontal lobes, are fused, especially ventrally.

Name: 4-Hydroxyphenylpyruvic aciduria
Desc: Increased concentration of pyruvic acid in the urine.

Name: 4-hydroxyphenylacetic aciduria
Desc: Increased concentration of 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid in the urine.

Name: Abnormal circulating tyrosine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of tyrosine in the blood circulation.

Name: Cystathioninuria
Desc: An elevated urinary concentration of cystathionine.

Name: Cystathioninemia
Desc: An increased concentration of cystathionine in the blood.

Name: Genital neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genital system.

Name: Soft tissue neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) that arises from the soft tissue. The most common types are lipomatous (fatty), vascular, smooth muscle, fibrous, and fibrohistiocytic neoplasms.

Name: Low back pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the lower back.

Name: Abnormal prostate morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the prostate.

Name: Reduced C-peptide level
Desc: A decreased concentration of C-peptide in the circulation. Since C-peptide is secreted in equimolar amounts to insulin, this feature correlates with reduced insulin secretion.

Name: Pelvic mass
Desc: An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the pelvic region.

Name: Hypoinsulinemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of insulin in the blood.

Name: Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus
Desc: A form of diabetes insipidus caused by failure of the kidneys to respond to vasopressin (AVP).

Name: Abnormality of blood and blood-forming tissues
Desc: An abnormality of the hematopoietic system.
Synonyms: Abnormality of blood and blood-forming tissues

Name: Abnormal lactate dehydrogenase level
Desc: A deviation from the normal serum concentration/activity of lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), which catalyzes the reduction of pyruvate to form lactate.

Name: Complement deficiency
Desc: An immunodeficiency defined by the absent or suboptimal functioning of one of the complement system proteins.

Name: Abnormality of complement system
Desc: An abnormality of the complement system.

Name: Decreased serum complement factor I
Desc: A reduced level of the complement component Factor I in circulation.

Name: Decreased serum complement factor B
Desc: A reduced level of the complement component factor B in circulation.

Name: Decreased level of thrombomodulin
Desc: Thrombomodulin is a cofactor in the thrombin induced activation of Protein C. In the case of deficiency there will be less Protein C and tendency to clot

Name: Mastocytosis
Desc: The presence of an increased number of mast cells and CD34+ mast cell precursors in the body.

Name: Mild postnatal growth retardation
Desc: A mild degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between two and three standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms.
Synonyms: Postnatal onset of mild growth retardation

Name: Erysipelas
Desc: Increased susceptibility to erysipelas, as manifested by a medical history of repeated episodes of erysipelas, which is a superficial infection of the skin, typically involving the lymphatic system.

Name: Chylothorax
Desc: Accumulation of excessive amounts of lymphatic fluid (chyle) in the pleural cavity.

Name: Antineutrophil antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against neutrophils.

Name: Liver kidney microsome type 1 antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against P450 2D6, a cytochrome P450 mono-oxygenase. Anti-LKM-1 antibodies are considered to be a diagnostic marker of autoimmune hepatitis type 2 (AIH2).

Name: Anti-liver cytosolic antigen type 1 antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against a 60-kd peptide contained in the liver cytosolic fraction.

Name: Inflammation of the large intestine
Desc: Inflammation, or an inflammatory state in the large intestine.

Name: Increased total bilirubin
Desc: Increased concentration of total (conjugated and unconjugated) bilirubin in the blood.

Name: Diffuse hepatic steatosis
Desc: A diffuse form of hepatic steatosis.

Name: Sclerosing cholangitis
Desc: Cholangitis associated with evident ductal fibrosis that develops as a consequence of long-standing bile duct inflammatory, obstruction, or ischemic injury; it can be obliterative or nonobliterative.

Name: Acute hepatitis
Desc: Acute hepatic injury resulting from inflammation typically accompanied by increased serum alanine transaminase activity. Etiologies include viral hepatitis, drugs, toxins, and autoimmune disorders.

Name: Fulminant hepatitis
Desc: Acute hepatitis complicated by acute liver failure with hepatic encephalopathy occurring less than 8 weeks after the onset of jaundice.

Name: Abnormality of male internal genitalia
Desc: An abnormality of the male internal genitalia.

Name: Abnormal scrotal rugation
Desc: Anomaly of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.

Name: Abnormality of amino acid metabolism
Desc: Abnormality of an amino acid metabolic process.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the diaphragm
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the diaphragm.

Name: Abnormal scapula morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the scapula, also known as the shoulder blade.

Name: Abnormality of the urethra
Desc: An abnormality of the urethra, i.e., of the tube which connects the urinary bladder to the outside of the body.

Name: Secondary microcephaly
Desc: Head circumference which falls below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender because of insufficient head growth after birth.
Synonyms: Development of small head that was not present at birth

Name: Perivascular spaces
Desc: Increased dimensions of the Virchow-Robin spaces (also known as perivascular spaces), which surround the walls of vessels as they course from the subarachnoid space through the brain parenchyma. Perivascular spaces are commonly microscopic, and not visible on conventional neuroimaging. This term refers to an increase of size of these spaces such that they are visible on neuroimaging (usually magnetic resonance imaging). The dilatations are regular cavities that always contain a patent artery.

Name: Cerebral white matter atrophy
Desc: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebral white matter.

Name: Congenital stationary night blindness with normal fundus
Congenital stationary night blindness with abnormal fundus
Electronegative electroretinogram
Desc: A dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram in which the b-wave that is of markedly lower amplitude than the associated a-wave (source: Holder GE., Inherited Chorioretinal Dystrophies: A Textbook and Atlas; 2014; p.17; ISBN 978-3-540-69466-3).
Synonyms: Reduced amplitude of dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram b-wave

Name: Reduced amplitude of dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram a-wave
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the amplitude of the a-wave.

Name: Compensatory head posture
Desc: A compensatory head posture occurs when the head is deviated out of the normal primary straight head position in order to compensate for an ocular problem.

Name: Short phalanx of hallux
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of a phalanx of big toe.

Name: Uplifted earlobe
Desc: An abnormal orientation of the earlobes such that they point out- and upward. That is, the lateral surface of ear lobe faces superiorly.

Name: Histidinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of histidine in the urine.

Name: Hyperhistidinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of histidine in the blood.

Name: Panhypopituitarism
Desc: A pituitary functional deficit affecting all the anterior pituitary hormones (growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, and prolactin).

Name: Hyposmia
Desc: A decreased sensitivity to odorants (that is, a decreased ability to perceive odors).

Name: Solitary median maxillary central incisor
Desc: A single maxillary central incisor positioned in the midline with morphological symmetry of the crown and bordered by lateral incisors.
Synonyms: Solitary median maxillary central incisor syndrome

Name: Cyclopia
Desc: Cyclopia is a congenital abnormality in which there is only one eye. That eye is centrally placed in the area normally occupied by the root of the nose.

Name: Spinal cord tumor
Desc: A neoplasm affecting the spinal cord.

Name: Absent nares
Desc: The nostrils (the paired channels of the nose) are not present.

Name: Abnormality of the diencephalon
Desc: An abnormality of the Diencephalon, which together with the cerebrum (telencephalon) makes up the forebrain.

Name: Thyroid hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the thyroid gland.

Name: Abnormal atrioventricular valve morphology
Desc: An abnormality of an atrioventricular valve.

Name: Discordant atrioventricular connection
Desc: Connection of the right atrium to the left ventricle and of the left atrium to the right ventricle in a biventricular heart.

Name: Bradycardia
Desc: A slower than normal heart rate (in adults, slower than 60 beats per minute).

Name: Atrial situs ambiguous
Desc: Common atrium without defining morphologic features.

Name: Ambiguous atrioventricular connection
Desc: With left or right cardiac isomerism in a biventricular, the atrioventricular connections are perforce ambiguous, in that one of the connections is concordant (e.g., right-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic right ventricle) and one of the connections is discordant (e.g., left-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic left ventricle).

Name: Cardiac conduction abnormality
Desc: Any anomaly of the progression of electrical impulses through the heart.

Name: Third degree atrioventricular block
Desc: Third-degree atrioventricular (AV) block (also referred to as complete heart block) is the complete dissociation of the atria and the ventricles. Third-degree AV block exists when more P waves than QRS complexes exist and no relationship (no conduction) exists between them.

Name: Global systolic dysfunction
Desc: A reduced ejection fraction and an enlarged left ventricle chamber, the latter by an increased resistance to filling with increased filling pressures. Systolic dysfunction is clinically associated with left ventricular failure in the presence of marked cardiomegaly.

Name: Premature atrial contractions
Desc: A type of cardiac arrhythmia with premature atrial contractions or beats caused by signals originating from ectopic atrial sites.

Name: Atrial situs inversus
Desc: Mirror image atrial arrangement, with morphologic right atrium on the left hand side and morphologic left atrium on the right hand side.

Name: Double outlet left ventricle
Desc: A congenital defect of heart development characterized by origin of both pulmonary artery and aorta from the morphological left ventricle.

Name: Double aortic arch
Desc: A conenital abnormality of the aortic arch in which the two embryonic aortc arches form a vascular ring that surrounds the trachea or esophagus and then join to form the descending aorta. Double aortic arch can cause symptoms because of compression of the esophagus (dysphagia, cyanosis while eating) or trachea (stridor).

Name: Gerbode ventricular septal defect
Desc: A type of ventricular septal defect communicating directly between the left ventricle and right atrium. This is anatomically possible because the normal tricuspid valve is more apically displaced than the mitral valve.

Name: Right ventricular cardiomyopathy
Desc: Right ventricular dysfunction (global or regional) with functional and morphological right ventricular abnormalities, with or without left ventricular disease.

Name: Bilateral superior vena cava with bridging vein
Supraventricular tachycardia with an accessory connection mediated pathway
Desc: Supraventricular tachycardia in which an accessory pathway connecting the atria and ventricles, apart from the AV node, participates as a necessary part of a reentrant mechanism.
Synonyms: Supraventricular tachycardia with an accessory connexion mediated pathway

Name: Mobitz I atrioventricular block
Desc: Progressive PR interval prolongation with the subsequent occurrence of a single nonconducted P wave that results in a pause. The pause that follows the nonconducted impulse is less than fully compensatory (less than the sum of two normal sinus intervals).

Name: Abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the aortic valve leaflets.

Name: Mesocardia
Desc: Mesocardia is an abnormal location of the heart in which the heart is in a midline position and the longitudinal axis of the heart lies in the mid-sagittal plane.

Name: Eye of the tiger anomaly of globus pallidus
Desc: The presence, on T2-weighted magnetic resonance imaging, of markedly low signal intensity if the globus pallidus that surrounds a central region of high signal intensity in the anteromedial globus pallidus, producing an eye-of-the-tiger appearance.

Name: Inertia
Desc: Reduction of goal-directed behaviors linked to the impairment in frontal executive functions (planning of an action for example).

Name: Tongue atrophy
Desc: Wasting of the tongue.

Name: Megaloblastic bone marrow
Desc: Abnormal increased number of megaloblasts in the bone marrow.

Name: Hyperhomocystinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of homocystine in the blood.

Name: Hypomethioninemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of methionine in the blood.

Name: Deep venous thrombosis
Desc: Formation of a blot clot in a deep vein. The clot often blocks blood flow, causing swelling and pain. The deep veins of the leg are most often affected.
Synonyms: Blood clot in a deep vein

Name: Hemolytic-uremic syndrome
Desc: A thrombotic microangiopathy with presence of non-immune, intravascular hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia and acute kidney injury. A vicious cycle of complement activation, endothelial cell damage, platelet activation, and thrombosis is the hallmark of the disease.

Name: Platybasia
Desc: A developmental malformation of the occipital bone and upper end of the cervical spine, in which the latter appears to have pushed the floor of the occipital bone upward such that there is an abnormal flattening of the skull base.
Synonyms: Increased basal angle of skull base
Obtuse basal angle of skull base

Name: Atretic occipital cephalocele
Desc: A congenital defect in the occipital region of the skull, covered by skin of the scalp and containing meninges or remnants of glial or neural tissues.

Name: Postauricular skin tag
Desc: A rudimentary tag of ear tissue often containing a core of cartilage and located just in back of the auricle (outer part of the ear).

Name: Peripheral arterial stenosis
Desc: Narrowing of peripheral arteries with reduction of blood flow to the limbs. This feature may be quantified as an ankle-brachial index of less than 0.9, and may be manifested clinically as claudication.

Name: Constrictive median neuropathy
Desc: Injury to the median nerve caused by its entrapment at the wrist as it traverses through the carpal tunnel. Clinically, constrictive median neuropathy is characterized by pain, paresthesia, and weakness in the median nerve distribution of the hand.

Name: Heparan sulfate excretion in urine
Desc: An increased concentration of heparan sulfates in the urine.

Name: Dermatan sulfate excretion in urine
Desc: An increased concentration of dermatan sulfate in the urine.

Name: Enlarged tonsils
Desc: Increase in size of the tonsils, small collections of lymphoid tissue facing into the aerodigestive tract on either side of the back part of the throat.

Name: Increased size of nasopharyngeal adenoids
Desc: An abnormal increase in the size of nasopharyngeal adenoids.

Name: Abnormal foveal morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the fovea centralis, the central area of the macula that mediates central, high resolution vision and contains the largest concentration of cone cells in the retina.

Name: Abnormal uvea morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the uvea, the vascular layer of the eyeball.

Name: Decreased light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram amplitude
Desc: Descreased amplitude of eletrical response upon electroretinography.
Synonyms: Decreased amplitudes on flash visual electroretinogram

Name: Thickened ribs
Desc: Increased thickness (diameter) of ribs.

Name: Spinal cord compression
Desc: External mechanical compression of the spinal cord.

Name: Abnormal proportion of CD4-positive T cells
Desc: Any abnormality in the proportion of CD4-positive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Abnormal proportion of CD4+ T cells
Abnormal proportion of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells

Name: Abnormal oligodendroglia morphology
Desc: One of the three types of glia cells that, with the nerve cells, compose the central nervous system and are characterized by sheetlike processes that wrap around individual axons to form the myelin sheath of nerve fibers.

Name: Abnormal astrocyte morphology
Desc: An abnormality of astrocytes.

Name: Weakness due to upper motor neuron dysfunction
Desc: Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Paralysis due to lesions of the principle motor tracts is related to a lesion in the corticospinal, corticobulbar or brainstem descending (subcorticospinal) neurons.
Synonyms: Paralysis due to lesions of the principle motor tracts

Name: Self-neglect
Desc: Neglecting one's own needs and well-being.

Name: Abnormality of the 5th toe
Desc: An anomaly of the little toe.

Name: Infra-orbital fold
Desc: Elevated ridge(s) of skin starting well below the medial aspect of the lower lid that curves gradually upward toward and/or across the nasal bridge.

Name: Recurrent sinusitis
Desc: A recurrent form of sinusitis.

Name: Verrucae
Desc: Warts, benign growths on the skin or mucous membranes that cause cosmetic problems as well as pain and discomfort. Warts most often occur on the hands, feet, and genital areas.

Name: Squamous cell carcinoma of the vulva
Desc: A cancer that originates in the squamous cells that line the surface of the vulva.

Name: Intraalveolar phospholipid accumulation
Desc: Accumulation of amorphous PAS-positive material in the space betweem alveolar macrophages, sometimes as condensed form (oval bodies) are typically found in alveolar proteinosis.
Synonyms: Detection of PAS-positive extracellular material in broncho-alveolar lavage

Name: Pulmonary opacity
Desc: Opacity refers to any area that preferentially attenuates the x-ray beam and therefore appears more opaque than the surrounding area. It is a nonspecific term that does not indicate the size or pathologic nature of the abnormality.

Name: Right ventricular hypertrophy
Desc: In this case the right ventricle is more muscular than normal, causing a characteristic boot-shaped (coeur-en-sabot) appearance as seen on anterior- posterior chest x-rays. Right ventricular hypertrophy is commonly associated with any form of right ventricular outflow obstruction or pulmonary hypertension, which may in turn owe its origin to left-sided disease. The echocardiographic signs are thickening of the anterior right ventricular wall and the septum. Cavity size is usually normal, or slightly enlarged. In many cases there is associated volume overload present due to tricuspid regurgitation, in the absence of this, septal motion is normal.

Name: Spontaneous neonatal pneumothorax
Desc: Pneumothorax occurring neonatally without traumatic injury to the chest or lung.

Name: Right ventricular dilatation
Desc: Enlargement of the chamber of the right ventricle.

Name: Reduced ejection fraction
Desc: A diminution of the volumetric fraction of blood pumped out of the ventricle with each cardiac cycle.

Name: Elevated pulmonary artery pressure
Desc: An abnormally elevated blood pressure in the circulation of the pulmonary artery.

Name: Left bundle branch block
Desc: A conduction block of the left branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a generalized disturbance of QRS morphology on EKG.

Name: Abnormal cardiac ventricular function
Desc: An abnormality of the cardiac ventricular function.

Name: Recurrent infections of the middle ear
Desc: Increased susceptibility to middle ear infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of middle ear infections

Name: Abnormal corpus striatum morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the striatum, which is the largest nucleus of the basal ganglia, comprising the caudate, putamen and ventral striatum, including the nucleus accumbens.

Name: Dilatation of the ventricular cavity
Desc: A localized outpouching of ventricular cavity that is generally associated with dyskinesia and paradoxical expansion during systole.

Name: Antenatal intracerebral hemorrhage
Desc: Cerebral hemorrhage that occurs before birth.

Name: Abnormal cerebral artery morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of a cerebral artery. The cerebral arteries comprise three main pairs of arteries and their branches, which supply the cerebrum of the brain. These are the anterior cerebral artery, the middle cerebral artery, and the posterior cerebral artery.

Name: Abnormal dura mater morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the Dura mater.

Name: Abnormality of fontanelles
Desc: An abnormality of the fontanelle.

Name: Thalamic edema
Desc: Swelling within the thalamus due to the accumulation of fluid.

Name: Dysgenesis of the thalamus
Desc: Structural abnormality of the thalamus related to defective development.

Name: Atrophic pituitary gland
Desc: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of the pituitary gland.

Name: Abnormal internal carotid artery morphology
Desc: An abnormality of an internal carotid artery.

Name: Abnormality of the falx cerebri
Desc: An abnormality of the Falx cerebri.

Name: Anal mucosal leukoplakia
Desc: Leukoplakia is a precancerous dermatosis of mucous membranes analogous Leukoplakia is basically a chronic inflammatory hypertrophy in which anaplasia and malignant dyskeratosis may develop and subsequently advance to an invasive squamous cell cancer. The clinical diagnosis of primary anal leukoplakia is indicated by single or multiple slightly raised,irregular, marginated, grayish-white keratinized' patches in the anal canal. Tissue biopsy is necessary for confirmation.

Name: Plantar pits
Desc: The presence of multiple pits (small, pinpoint-large indentations on the surface of the skin) located on the skin of sole of foot.

Name: Acrokeratosis
Desc: Overgrowth of the stratum corneum characterized by flesh-coloured or slightly pigmented smooth or warty papules on the upper surface of hands and feet.

Name: Shoulder dislocation
Desc: A displacement or misalignment of the humerus with respect to the other bones of the should joint. Note that a subluxation is a partial dislocation.

Name: Absent facial hair
Desc: Absence of facial hair.

Name: Sparse facial hair
Desc: Reduced number or density of facial hair.

Name: Small cerebral cortex
Desc: Reduced size of the cerebral cortex.

Name: Abnormal cortical gyration
Desc: An abnormality of the gyri (i.e., the ridges) of the cerebral cortex of the brain.

Name: Colpocephaly
Desc: Colpocephaly is an anatomic finding in the brain manifested by occipital horns that are disproportionately enlarged in comparison with other parts of the lateral ventricles.

Name: Macular hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the macula lutea.

Name: Gingival cleft
Desc: A fissure in the gingiva (gums), i.e., the mucosal tissue that lies over the mandible and maxilla.

Name: Tracheal atresia
Desc: A congenital absence or considerable underdevelopment of the trachea such that communication between the larynx proximally and the alveoli of the lungs distally is lacking.

Name: Proximal upper limb amyotrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the arms.
Synonyms: Proximal muscle atrophy in upper limbs

Name: Renal calcium wasting
Desc: High urine calcium in the presence of hypocalcemia.

Name: Calcium oxalate nephrolithiasis
Desc: The presence of calcium- and oxalate-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

Name: Parathormone-independent increased renal tubular calcium reabsorption
Desc: An increase in the reabsorption of calcium by the renal tubulus that is not associated with increased parathormone levels.
Synonyms: Parathormone-independent increased renal tubular Ca reabsorption
Parathormone-independent increased renal tubular Ca2+ reabsorption

Name: Gingival hyperkeratosis
Desc: Hyperkeratosis of the gingiva.

Name: Focal friction-related palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
Desc: Hyperkeratosis affecting the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot in areas exposed to friction.

Name: Subungual hyperkeratosis
Desc: A thickening of the stratum corneum in the region beneath the nails.

Name: Circumungual hyperkeratosis
Desc: A thickening of the stratum corneum, the outer layer of the skin, in the region surrounding the nails.

Name: Arteriosclerosis
Desc: Sclerosis (hardening) of the arteries with increased thickness of the wall of arteries as well as increased stiffness and a loss of elasticity.

Name: Squamous cell carcinoma of the skin
Desc: Squamous cell carcinoma of the skin is a malignant tumor of squamous epithelium.

Name: Aplasia of the falx cerebri
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by aplasia of the Falx cerebri.

Name: Abnormal central motor function
Desc: An anomaly of the control or production of movement in the central nervous system.

Name: Abnormal hypothalamus physiology
Desc: An abnormal functionality of the hypothalamus.

Name: Abnormal morphology of the olfactory bulb
Desc: An abnormal morphology of the olfactory bulb (bulbus olfactorius), which is involved in olfaction, i.e. the sense of smell.

Name: Neural tube defect
Desc: A neural tube defect arises when the neural tube, the embryonic precursor of the brain and spinal cord, fails to close during neurulation. The cranial region (anencephaly) or the low spine (open spina bifida; myelomeningocele) are most commonly affected although, in the severe NTD craniorachischisis, almost the entire neural tube remains open, from midbrain to low spine.

Name: Single naris
Desc: The presence of only a single nostril.

Name: Proboscis
Desc: A fleshy, tube-like structure usually located in the midline of the face or just to one side of the midline.

Name: Narrow foramen obturatorium
Desc: Decreased width of the foramen obturatorium. The foramen obturatorium (also known as the obturator foramen) is a hole located between the ischium and pubis bones of the pelvis.

Name: Duodenal polyposis
Desc: Presence of multiple polyps in the duodenum.

Name: Neoplasm of the stomach
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the stomach.

Name: Congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium
Desc: Sharply demarcated, congenital hyperpigmentation of the retinal pigment epithelium.

Name: Molar tooth sign on MRI
Desc: An abnormal appearance of the midbrain in axial magnetic resonance imaging in which the elongated superior cerebellar peduncles give the midbrain an appearance reminiscent of a molar or wisdom tooth.

Name: Hypoplastic helices
Desc: Underdevelopment of the helix, i.e., of the outer rim of the pinna.

Name: Bifid distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx) to a partially fused appearance of the two bones.
Synonyms: Notched outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Inflammatory myopathy
Desc: Chronic muscle inflammation accompanied by muscle weakness.

Name: Periorbital edema
Desc: Edema affecting the region situated around the orbit of the eye.

Name: Facial erythema
Desc: Redness of the skin of the face, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.

Name: Plantar hyperkeratosis
Desc: Hyperkeratosis affecting the sole of the foot.

Name: Metaphyseal striations
Desc: Longitudinal densities on radiographs located in a metaphysis (the narrow region of a long bone between the epiphysis and the diaphysis).

Name: Abnormal trabecular bone morphology
Desc: Abnormal structure or form of trabecular bone.

Name: Aplastic anemia
Desc: Aplastic anemia is defined as pancytopenia with a hypocellular marrow.

Name: Calcinosis
Desc: Formation of calcium deposits in any soft tissue.
Synonyms: Calcium buildup in soft tissues of body

Name: Metaphyseal sclerosis
Desc: Abnormally increased density of metaphyseal bone.
Synonyms: Increased bone density in wide portion of long bone

Name: Finger symphalangism
Desc: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the fingers. The synonymous term "symphalangism of the hand" may be translated as fusions of bones of varying digree, that involve at least one phalangeal bone of the hand. If bony fusions are referred to as "Symphalangism" the fusion occurs in a proximo-distal axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a radio-ulnar axis are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly.
Synonyms: Synostosis involving bones of the fingers

Name: Porokeratosis
Desc: A clonal disorder of keratinization with one or multiple atrophic patches surrounded by a clinically and histologically distinctive hyperkeratotic ridgelike border called the cornoid lamella.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the upper limbs
Desc: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the upper limbs.
Synonyms: Absent/small bones of the upper limbs
Absent/underdeveloped bones of the upper limbs

Name: Synostosis involving bones of the upper limbs
Desc: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the upper limbs.
Synonyms: Fusion involving bones of the upper limbs

Name: Oxycephaly
Desc: Oxycephaly (from Greek oxus, sharp, and kephalos, head) refers to a conical or pointed shape of the skull.

Name: Protuberant abdomen
Desc: A thrusting or bulging out of the abdomen.

Name: Premature closure of fontanelles
Desc: Normally, the posterior and lateral fontanelles are obliterated by about six months after birth, the anterior fontanelle closes by about the middle of the second year. This term refers to the situation in which the fontanelles close at an inappropriately early time point.
Synonyms: Early closure of the bregma sutures
Early closure of the cranial sutures
Premature closure of the bregma sutures
Premature closure of the cranial sutures

Name: Focal T2 hyperintense brainstem lesion
Desc: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.

Name: Focal T2 hypointense brainstem lesion
Desc: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.

Name: Neuroma
Desc: A tumor made up of nerve cells and nerve fibers.

Name: Choroidal hemangioma
Desc: The presence of multiple hemangiomas in the choroid. These are generally reddish or orange or can have increased pigmentation maiking them difficult to distinguish from choroidal melanomas.

Name: Retinal cavernous angioma
Desc: A benign tumor of the retina that appears as a grouping of blood-filled saccules within the inner retinal layers or on the surface of the optic disc. Retinal cavernous angioma are described as having a 'cluster of grapes' appearance.

Name: Episodic paroxysmal anxiety
Desc: Recurrent attacks of severe anxiety, whose occurence is not restricted to any particular situation or set of circumstances and is therefore unpredictable.

Name: Vascular tortuosity
Desc: Abnormal twisting of arteries or veins.

Name: Macrogyria
Desc: Increased size of cerebral gyri, often associated with a moderate reduction in the number of sulci of the cerebrum.

Name: Exencephaly
Desc: A malformation of the neural tube with a large amount of protruding brain tissue and absence of calvarium.

Name: Frontal upsweep of hair
Desc: Upward and/or sideward growth of anterior hair.

Name: Abnormal temporal bone morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the temporal bone of the skull, which is situated at the sides and base of the skull roughly underlying the region of the face known as the temple.

Name: Patchy reduction of bone mineral density
Desc: Patchy (irregular) reduction in bone density. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

Name: Absent earlobe
Desc: Absence of fleshy non-cartilaginous tissue inferior to the tragus and incisura.

Name: Inverted nipples
Desc: The presence of nipples that instead of pointing outward are retracted inwards.

Name: Sagittal craniosynostosis
Desc: A kind of craniosynostosis affecting the sagittal suture.
Synonyms: Early closure of midline skull joint

Name: Talipes valgus
Desc: Outward turning of the heel, resulting in clubfoot with the person walking on the inner part of the foot.

Name: Mild conductive hearing impairment
Desc: A mild form of conductive hearing impairment.

Name: Hypoplasia of the antihelix
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the antihelix.

Name: Sacrococcygeal pilonidal abnormality
Desc: The presence of a cyst, fistula, or abscess in the sacrococcygeal region (gluteal crease) characteristically accompanied by hair and skin folds.

Name: Posterolateral diaphragmatic hernia
Desc: A posterolateral defect in the diaphragm, commonly referred to as a Bochdalek hernia, which is often accompanied by herniation of the stomach, intestines, liver, and/or spleen into the chest cavity.

Name: Postaxial polydactyly
Desc: A form of polydactyly in which the extra digit or digits are localized on the side of the fifth finger or fifth toe.

Name: Combined immunodeficiency
Desc: A group of phenotypically heterogeneous genetic disorders characterized by profound deficiencies of T- and B-cell function, which predispose the patients to both infectious and noninfectious complications.

Name: Lacrimal duct stenosis
Desc: Narrowing of a tear duct (lacrimal duct).

Name: Broad middle phalanx of finger
Desc: Increased width of the middle phalanx of finger.
Synonyms: Broad middle phalanges of the hand

Name: Thin lower lip vermilion
Desc: Height of the vermilion of the medial part of the lower lip more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Synonyms: Decreased height of lower lip vermilion
Decreased volume of lower lip vermilion
Thin red part of the lower lip
Thin vermilion border of lower lip

Name: Dermatochalasis
Desc: Loss of elasticity of the upper and lower eyelids causing the skin to sag and bulge.

Name: Abnormal T cell subset distribution
Desc: Any abnormality in the proportion T cells subsets relative to the total number of T cells.

Name: Arteria lusoria
Desc: Usually, three large arteries arise from the arch of the aorta: the brachiocephalic trunk (divided into the right common carotid artery and the right subclavian artery), the left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery. However, when aberrant right subclavian artery variant is present, the brachiocephalic trunk is absent and four large arteries arise from the arch of the aorta: the right common carotid artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery, and the final one with the most distal left sided origin, the right subclavian artery, also called the arteria lusoria.

Name: Decreased lymphocyte proliferation in response to anti-CD3
Desc: A decreased proliferative response of lymphocytes in vitro or in vivo, when stimulated with an anti-CD3 antibody against the T-cell co-receptor, CD3.
Synonyms: Defective proliferation of lymphocytes following anti-CD3 stimulation

Name: Decreased circulating total IgG
Desc: A reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.

Name: Decreased specific antibody response to vaccination
Desc: A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against toxoids and polysaccharides in vaccines, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.

Name: Reduced natural killer cell count
Desc: Less than normal number of natural killer cells, a type of lymphocyte in the innate immune system with an ability to mediate cytotoxicity and produce cytokines after the ligation of a germline-encoded activation receptor.

Name: Crossed fused renal ectopia
Desc: A developmental anomaly in which the kidneys are fused and localized on the same side of the midline. This anomaly is thought to result from disruption of the normal embryologic migration of the kidneys.

Name: Metatarsus adductus
Desc: The metatarsals are deviated medially (tibially), that is, the bones in the front half of the foot bend or turn in toward the body.
Synonyms: Front half of foot turns inward

Name: Long palm
Desc: For children from birth to 16 years of age the length of the palm is more than the 97th centile; or, the length of the palm appears relatively long compared to the finger length or the limb length.

Name: Prominence of the zygomatic bone
Desc: Large or prominent malar surface of the zygomatic bone of the skull, which is convex and forms the prominence of the 'cheek bones'.

Name: Abnormal aldolase level
Desc: An abnormal concentration of aldolase in the serum. Aldolase is an enzyme responsible for converting fructose 1,6-bisphosphate into the triose phosphates dihydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.

Name: Naevus flammeus of the eyelid
Desc: Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the eyelid.

Name: Periostitis
Desc: Inflammation of the periosteum

Name: Scarring alopecia of scalp
Synonyms: Hair loss on scalp from scarring condition

Name: Neoplasm of the respiratory system
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the respiratory system.

Name: Thin toenail
Desc: Toenail that appears thin when viewed on end.

Name: Aplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd toe
Synonyms: Absent digital bone of the 3rd toe

Name: Hyposthenuria
Desc: An abnormally low urinary specific gravity, i.e., reduced concentration of solutes in the urine.

Name: Hypernatremia
Desc: An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the blood.

Name: Impotence
Desc: Inability to develop or maintain an erection of the penis.

Name: Agonadism
Desc: Absence of sex glands (gonads are the organs that produce gametes; testis in males and ovary in females).

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the uterus
Desc: Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the uterus.

Name: Aplasia of the ovary
Desc: Aplasia, that is failure to develop, of the ovary.

Name: Decreased palmar creases
Desc: Poorly defined or shallow palmar creases.

Name: Contracture of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 5th finger
Desc: Proximal interphalangeal (PIP) flexion deformity of the little finger. That is, the PIP joint of a little finger is bent (flexed) and cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.

Name: Small hypothenar eminence
Desc: Reduced muscle mass on the ulnar side of the palm, that is, reduction in size of the hypothenar eminence.

Name: Small pituitary gland
Desc: An abnormally decreased size of the pituitary gland.

Name: Eunuchoid habitus
Desc: A body habitus that is tall, slim and underweight, with long legs and long arms (i.e., arm span exceeds height by 5 cm or more).

Name: Parathyroid hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the parathyroid gland.

Name: Abnormality of T cell physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of T cells.

Name: Congenital hypoparathyroidism
Desc: Deficiency of parathyroid hormone with congenital onset.

Name: Parathyroid agenesis
Desc: Aplasia of the parathyroid gland.

Name: Hyperphosphatemia
Desc: An abnormally increased phosphate concentration in the blood.

Name: Neoplasm of the heart
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the heart.

Name: Failure of eruption of permanent teeth
Desc: Lack of tooth eruption of the secondary dentition.
Synonyms: Failure of eruption of adult teeth

Name: Recurrent streptococcus pneumoniae infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to streptococcus pneumoniae infections as manifested by a history of recurrent infections by streptococcus pneumoniae.

Name: Progressive extrapyramidal muscular rigidity
Desc: A progressive degree of muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement).

Name: Atypical absence status epilepticus
Desc: Atypical absence status epilepticus is a type of generalized non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma that is semiologically a prolonged atypical absence seizure.

Name: Titubation
Desc: Nodding movement of the head or body.

Name: Basal ganglia gliosis
Desc: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the basal ganglia.

Name: Horizontal pendular nystagmus
Desc: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements of equal velocity.

Name: Cogwheel rigidity
Desc: A type of rigidity in which a muscle responds with cogwheellike jerks to the use of constant force in bending the limb (i.e., it gives way in little, repeated jerks when the muscle is passively stretched).

Name: Basal ganglia cysts
Synonyms: Cystic lesions in the basal ganglia

Name: Undetectable light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram
Desc: Absence of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.
Synonyms: Absent cone and rod functions by electroretinogram
Absent rod-and cone-mediated responses on ERG

Name: Small basal ganglia
Desc: Decreased size of the basal ganglia.

Name: Nonopposable triphalangeal thumb
Desc: A form of triphalangeal thumb that cannot be placed opposite the fingers of the same hand.

Name: Pancreatic aplasia
Desc: Aplasia of the pancreas.

Name: Hypoplastic tricuspid valve
Desc: Congenital defect characterized by underdevelopment of the tricuspid valve.

Name: Biliary atresia
Desc: Atresia of the biliary tree.

Name: Anterior pituitary agenesis
Desc: Absence of the anterior pituitary gland resulting from a developmental defect.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the gallbladder
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the gallbladder.

Name: Congenital defect of the pericardium
Desc: A developmental defect of the pericardium with congenital onset.

Name: Mild microcephaly
Desc: Decreased occipito-frontal (head) circumference (OFC). For the microcephaly OFC must be between -3 SD and -2 SD compared to appropriate, age matched, normal standards (i.e. -3 SD <= OFC < -2 SD).

Name: Aplasia of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Abnormal pulmonary artery morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the structure of the pulmonary artery.

Name: Congenital malformation of the left heart
Desc: Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the left heart identifiable at birth.

Name: Primary hypothyroidism
Desc: A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in the thyroid gland.

Name: Decreased T3/T4 ratio
Desc: A ratio of serum triiodothyronine (T3) to thyroxine (T4) in the blood that is lower than normal.

Name: Absent axillary hair
Desc: Absence of axillary hair.

Name: Absent pubic hair
Desc: Absence of pubic hair.

Name: Cutis laxa
Desc: Wrinkled, redundant, inelastic and sagging skin.

Name: Tetraplegia/tetraparesis
Desc: Loss of strength in all four limbs. Tetraplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas Tetraparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.

Name: Bifid penis
Desc: Two penile structures, separated from the tip to the base of the shaft.

Name: Ectopic scrotum
Desc: Scrotum in a position other than the usual position inferior to the base of the penis.

Name: Penoscrotal transposition
Desc: A partial or complete positional exchange between the penis and the scrotum, with positioning of the scrotum superior to the penis.

Name: Renal duplication
Desc: A congenital anomaly of the urinary tract, in which the kidney is duplicated and is drained via two separate renal pelves and ureters.

Name: Renal malrotation
Desc: An abnormality of the normal developmental rotation of the kidney leading to an abnormal orientation of the kidney.

Name: Cloacal exstrophy
Desc: Cloacal exstrophy is a severe anterior abdominal wall defect in which the two hemibladders are visible and are separated by a midline intestinal plate, an omphalocele, and an imperforate anus.

Name: Gastrointestinal duplication
Desc: A spherical hollow structure with a smooth muscle coat, lined by a mucous membrane, and attached to any part of the gastrointestinal tract, from the base of the tongue to the anus.

Name: Butterfly vertebrae
Desc: A butterfly vertebra (sagittal cleft vertebra or anterior rachischisis) is a sagittal defect in the vertebral body caused by failure of fusion of the two lateral chondrification centers during embryogenesis. The name is based on the appearance of the two hemivertebrae emerging as butterfly wings from the central cleft on x-ray.

Name: Rectoperineal fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula between the perineum and the rectum.

Name: Heat intolerance
Desc: The inability to maintain a comfortable body temperature in warm or hot weather.

Name: Thin fingernail
Desc: Fingernail that appears thin when viewed on end.

Name: Subcortical cerebral atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the cerebral subcortical white and gray matter, termed subcortical atrophy, reflects loss of nerve cells in the basal ganglia or fibers in the deep white matter.

Name: Cerebral cortical hemiatrophy
Desc: Atrophy of one side of the brain, characterized by findings including thinning of the cerebral cortex, reduced volume of the cerebral white matter with abnormal myelination, and enlargement of the ispilateral fourth ventricle.

Name: Autoimmune antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against the organism's own cells or tissues.

Name: Antiphospholipid antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of circulating autoantibodies to phospholipids.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the spleen
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the spleen.

Name: Autoimmune hypoparathyroidism
Desc: A type of hypoparathyroidism with circulating antiparathyroid or anti-calcium sensing receptor antibodies indicative of autoimmunity.

Name: Non-caseating epithelioid cell granulomatosis
Desc: The presence of multiple epithelioid cell granulomas consist of highly differentiated mononuclear phagocytes (epithelioid cells and giant cells) and lymphocytes, not exhibiting caseation (a form of necrosis in which the tissue changes into a dry, amorphous mass said to resemble cheese).

Name: Chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis
Desc: Recurrent or persistent superficial Candida infections of the skin, mucous membranes, and nails.
Synonyms: Chronic candidiasis of mucosa, skin and nails

Name: Pulmonary artery aneurysm
Desc: An aneurysm (severe localized balloon-like outward bulging) in the pulmonary artery.

Name: Regional abnormality of skin
Desc: An abnormality of the skin that is restricted to a particular body region.

Name: Invasive fungal infection
Desc: Fungal infection characterized by invasion of host tissues.

Name: Productive cough
Desc: A cough that produces phlegm or mucus.

Name: Panniculitis
Desc: Inflammation of adipose tissue.

Name: Skin detachment
Desc: Loss of sections of skin either spontaneously or after gentle handling.

Name: Air crescent sign
Desc: A crescent of air surrounding a soft-tissue mass in a pulmonary cavity and can be seen in both plain X-ray and CT scan.

Name: Fasciitis
Desc: Inflammation of fascia, the tissue under the skin and over the muscle.

Name: Otitis externa
Desc: Inflammation or infection of the external auditory canal (EAC), the auricle, or both.

Name: Exudative pleural effusion
Desc: A type of pleural effusion with a exudate (extravascular fluid that has exuded out of a tissue or its capillaries due to injury or inflammation). Pleural effusions can be classified as transudates or exudates based on Light's criteria, which classify an effusion as exudate if one or more of the following are present: (1) the ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is greater than 0.5, (2) the ratio of pleural fluid lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) to serum LDH is greater than 0.6, or (3) the pleural fluid LDH level is greater than two thirds of the upper limit of normal for serum LDH.

Name: Erythema nodosum
Desc: An erythematous eruption commonly associated with drug reactions or infection and characterized by inflammatory nodules that are usually tender, multiple, and bilateral.

Name: Morbilliform rash
Desc: An exanthema consisting of widespread pink-to-red macules (flat spots of 2-10 mm in diameter) or papules (red bumps) that blanch with pressure. The macules and papules may cluster and merge to form sheets over several days.

Name: Folliculitis
Desc: Inflammatory cells within the wall and ostia of the hair follicle, creating a follicular-based pustule.

Name: Urticarial plaque
Desc: A well-circumscribed, intensely pruritic, raised wheal (edema of the superficial skin) typically 1 to 2 cm in diameter.

Name: Indurated nodule
Desc: A skin nodule that is unusually hard (indurated).

Name: Abnormality of the male genitalia
Desc: Abnormality of the male genital system.

Name: Abnormal sperm morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of sperm.

Name: Vasospasm
Desc: Narrowing of an artery due to constriction of the blood vessels.

Name: Coccidioidal meningitis
Desc: A type of fungal meningitis caused by dissemination of coccidioides to basilar meninges.

Name: Short digit
Desc: One or more digit that appears disproportionately short compared to the hand/foot, whereby either the entire digit or a specific phalanx is shortened.

Name: Elevated circulating long chain fatty acid concentration
Desc: Increased concentration of long-chain fatty acids in the blood circulation.

Name: Hypoglycemic encephalopathy
Desc: Brain damage related to a lowering of blood glucose below a critical level (around 30 mg/dl), which may lead to confusion, lethargy and delirium followed by seizures and coma. Prolonged hypoglycemia may lead to irreversible brain damage.

Name: Ventricular hypertrophy
Desc: Enlargement of the cardiac ventricular muscle tissue with increase in the width of the wall of the ventricle and loss of elasticity. Ventricular hypertrophy is clinically differentiated into left and right ventricular hypertrophy.

Name: Duane anomaly
Desc: A condition associated with a limitation of the horizontal ocular movement with retraction of the globe and narrowing of the palpebral fissure on adduction
Synonyms: Globe retraction and deviation on adduction
Limited eye motility from Duane anomaly
Limited eye movement from Duane anomaly

Name: Anti-thyroid peroxidase antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against thyroid peroxidase.

Name: Anti-glutamic acid decarboxylase antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against glutamic acid decarboxylase.

Name: Insulin receptor antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the insulin receptor.

Name: Basilar impression
Desc: Abnormal elevation of the floor of the posterior fossa including occipital condyles and foramen magnum.

Name: Ascending aortic dissection
Desc: A separation of the layers within the wall of the ascending aorta. Tears in the intimal layer result in the propagation of dissection (proximally or distally) secondary to blood entering the intima-media space.

Name: Dilatation of the cerebral artery
Desc: The presence of a localized dilatation or ballooning of a cerebral artery.

Name: Descending thoracic aorta aneurysm
Desc: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the descending thoracic aorta.
Synonyms: Dilatation of the descending thoracic aorta

Name: Abnormal left ventricular function
Desc: Inability of the left ventricle to perform its normal physiologic function. Failure is either due to an inability to contract the left ventricle or the inability to relax completely and fill with blood during diastole.

Name: Carotid artery dilatation
Desc: A dilatation (balooning or bulging out of the vessel wall) of a carotid artery.

Name: Descending aortic dissection
Desc: A separation of the layers within the wall of the descending aorta. Tears in the intimal layer result in the propagation of dissection (proximally or distally) secondary to blood entering the intima-media space.

Name: Paroxysmal dyspnea
Desc: A sudden attack of dyspnea that occurs while the affected person is at rest.

Name: Mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation
Desc: An increase of medial mucoid extracellular matrix creating translamellar and/or intralamellar expansions including extracellular pools as noted on an H&E stain and/or a stain to highlight extracellular matrix material (Movat's pentachrome, Alcian blue, etc.).
Synonyms: Cystic medial necrosis of the aorta

Name: Abnormality of small intestinal villus morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of small intestinal villus

Name: Villous atrophy
Desc: The enteric villi are atrophic or absent.
Synonyms: Small intestine biopsy shows villous atrophy

Name: Abnormality of the tonsils
Desc: An abnormality of the tonsils.

Name: Hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia
Desc: An increased concentration of insulin combined with a decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.

Name: Glucose intolerance
Desc: Glucose intolerance (GI) can be defined as dysglycemia that comprises both prediabetes and diabetes. It includes the conditions of impaired fasting glucose (IFG) and impaired glucose tolerance (IGT) and diabetes mellitus (DM).

Name: Diabetic ketoacidosis
Desc: A type of diabetic metabolic abnormality with an accumulation of ketone bodies.

Name: Abnormality of body weight
Desc: An abnormal increase or decrease of weight or an abnormal distribution of mass in the body.

Name: Abnormality of circulating leptin level
Desc: An abnormal concentration of leptin in the blood.

Name: Abnormal oral glucose tolerance
Desc: An abnormal resistance to glucose, i.e., a reduction in the ability to maintain glucose levels in the blood stream within normal limits following oral administration of glucose.

Name: Fasting hyperinsulinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of insulin in the blood in the fasting state, i.e., not as the response to food intake.
Synonyms: High blood insulin levels while fasting

Name: Hyperglutaminemia
Desc: An increased concentration of glutamine in the blood.

Name: Oroticaciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of orotic acid in the urine.

Name: Elevated urinary dopamine
Desc: An increased concentration of dopamine in the urine.

Name: Increased blood urea nitrogen
Desc: An increased amount of nitrogen in the form of urea in the blood.

Name: Elevated circulating creatinine concentration
Desc: An increased amount of creatinine in the blood.

Name: Retrograde ejaculation
Desc: The emission of semen and seminal fluid into the bladder instead of through the penis during orgasm.

Name: Oxygen desaturation on exertion
Desc: Oxygen saturation less than 95% on exertion or arterial partial pressure of oxygen falling by more than 1kPa.

Name: Subpleural honeycombing
Desc: So-called honeycombs (variably sized cysts in a background of densely scarred tissue) located in the subpleural space.

Name: Pleural thickening
Desc: An increase in the thickness of the pleura, generally related to scarring of the pleural tissue.

Name: Late inspiratory crackles
Desc: Crackles that appear any time after the beginning of inspiration and last till the end of inspiration.

Name: Reduced forced vital capacity
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal inspiration.

Name: Decreased DLCO
Desc: Reduced ability of the lungs to transfer gas from inspired air to the bloodstream as measured by the diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide (DLCO) test.

Name: Cor pulmonale
Desc: Right-sided heart failure resulting from chronic hypertension in the pulmonary arteries and right ventricle.

Name: Hepatojugular reflux
Desc: The examiner applies firm but persistent pressure over the liver for 10 seconds while observing the mean jugular venous pressure. Normally there is either no rise or only a transient (i.e., 2 to 3 sec) rise in mean jugular venous pressure. A sustained increase in the mean venous pressure until abdominal compression is released is abnormal and indicates impaired right heart function. This abnormal response is called hepatojugular reflux.

Name: Interlobular septal thickening
Desc: Presence of thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a CT scan.
Synonyms: Interlobular septal thickening on pulmonary HRCT

Name: Chest tightness
Desc: An unpleasant sensation of tightness or pressure in the chest.

Name: Malignant mesothelioma
Desc: Malignant mesothelioma is a form of cancer that originates from the cells of the mesothelium, a thin tissue layer surrounding the body's internal organs. Malignant mesothelioma is almost exclusively caused by asbestos exposure, pleural mesothelioma beeing the most common form, affecting the lining of the lungs called the pleura. Other forms such as perioneal-, percardial- or testicular- mesothelioma are much rarer.

Name: Conotruncal defect
Desc: A congenital malformation of the outflow tract of the heart. Conotruncal defects are thought to result from a disturbance of the outflow tract of the embryonic heart, and comprise truncus arteriosus, tetralogy of Fallot, interrupted aortic arch, transposition of the great arteries, and double outlet right ventricle.

Name: Abnormal cardiac ventricle morphology
Desc: An abnormality of a cardiac ventricle.

Name: Abnormal cardiac atrium morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of a cardiac atrium.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the inner ear
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the inner ear.

Name: Abnormality of the pulmonary veins
Desc: An abnormality of the pulmonary veins.

Name: Anotia
Desc: Complete absence of any auricular structures.

Name: Long hallux
Desc: Increased length of the big toe.

Name: Soft, doughy skin
Desc: A skin texture that is unusually soft (and may feel silky), and has a malleable consistency resembling that of dough.

Name: Absent phalangeal crease
Desc: Absence of one or more interphalangeal creases (i.e., of the transverse lines in the skin between the phalanges of the fingers).

Name: Hypermobility of distal interphalangeal joints
Synonyms: Increased mobility of outermost hinge joint

Name: Calcaneovalgus deformity
Desc: This is a postural deformity in which the foot is positioned up against the tibia. The heel (calcaneus) is positioned downward (that is, the ankle is flexed upward), and the heel is turned outward (valgus).
Synonyms: Foot and ankle bend up toward shin of leg

Name: Severe conductive hearing impairment
Desc: A severe form of conductive hearing impairment.

Name: Recurrent shoulder dislocation
Desc: Shoulder dislocation occurring repeated times.

Name: Tendon rupture
Desc: Breakage (tear) of a tendon.

Name: Myopic astigmatism
Desc: A condition where one or both of the two principal meridians focus in the front of the retina when the eye is at rest.

Name: Palmoplantar blistering
Desc: A type of blistering that affects the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.

Name: Hyperplastic callus formation
Desc: Increased growth of callus, the bony and cartilaginous material that forms a connecting bridge across a bone fracture during fracture healing.

Name: Palmoplantar hyperhidrosis
Desc: An abnormally increased perspiration on palms and soles.
Synonyms: Excessive sweating of palms and soles

Name: Linear arrays of macular hyperkeratoses in flexural areas
Palmar hyperkeratosis
Desc: Abnormal thickening of the skin localized to the palm of the hand.

Name: Steatocystoma multiplex
Desc: Multiple, localized or widespread, asymptomatic or inflammatory dermal cysts involving the pilosebaceous units. Lesions can appear anywhere on the body, but steatocystoma multiplex is more commonly involved with those areas of the skin with a high density of developed pilosebaceous units (e.g., the axilla, groin, neck, and proximal extremities).

Name: Eruptive vellus hair cyst
Desc: A cutaneous cyst that is small (one or two millimeters in diameter) and painless, presenting as a follicular papule that usually is skin colored but may have a reddish or brownish tinge.

Name: Ear pain
Desc: Pain in the ear can be a consequence of otologic disease (primary or otogenic otalgia), or can arise from pathologic processes and structures other than the ear (secondary or referred otalgia).

Name: Angular cheilitis
Desc: A type of inflammation of the lips involving one or both of the corners of the mouth.
Synonyms: Inflammation of corners of the mouth
Red and sore corners of the mouth

Name: Lower limb undergrowth
Desc: Leg shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the lower extremity.
Synonyms: Hypoplasia involving bones of the lower limbs

Name: Decreased serum complement C3
Desc: A reduced level of the complement component C3 in circulation.

Name: Lupus anticoagulant
Desc: Presence of lupus anticoagulant (LA) autoantibodies. LA represent a heterogeneous group of autoantibodies, IgG, IgM, or a mixture of both classes, that interfere with standard phospholipid-based coagulant tests (this is only an in vitro phenomenon, LA do not cause reduction of coagulation in vivo). The antibodies are directed against plasma proteins which also bind to phospholipid surfaces.

Name: Decreased serum complement C4
Desc: A reduced level of the complement component C4 in the circulation.

Name: Serositis
Desc: Inflammation in any serous cavity.

Name: Narrow nose
Desc: Interalar distance more than 2 SD below the mean for age, or alternatively, an apparently decreased width of the nasal base and alae.

Name: Prominent fingertip pads
Desc: A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips. The term "persistent fetal fingertip pads" is often used as a synonym, but should better not be used because it implies knowledge of history of the patient which often does not exist.

Name: Narrow foot
Desc: A foot for which the measured width is below the 5th centile for age; or, a foot that appears disproportionately narrow for its length.

Name: Gastrojejunal tube feeding in infancy
Desc: Feeding problem necessitating gastrojejunal tube feeding.

Name: Cerebral berry aneurysm
Desc: A small, sac-like aneurysm (outpouching) of a cerebral blood vessel.

Name: Abnormal circle of Willis morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the circle of Willis, also known as the cerebral arterial circle.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the cerebral arterial circle

Name: Subarachnoid hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage occurring between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater.

Name: Encephalomalacia
Desc: Encephalomalacia is the softening or loss of brain tissue after cerebral infarction, cerebral ischemia, infection, craniocerebral trauma, or other injury.

Name: Vestibular hypofunction
Desc: Reduced functioning of the vestibular apparatus.

Name: Hemianopia
Desc: Partial or complete loss of vision in one half of the visual field of one or both eyes.

Name: Anisopoikilocytosis
Desc: A type of poikilocytosis characterized by the presence in the blood of erythrocytes of varying sizes and abnormal shapes.

Name: Hypochromic microcytic anemia
Desc: A type of anemia characterized by an abnormally low concentration of hemoglobin in the erythrocytes and lower than normal size of the erythrocytes.

Name: Anemia of inadequate production
Desc: A kind of anemia characterized by inadequate production of erythrocytes.

Name: Reduced hemoglobin A
Desc: Hemoglobin A (HbA) contains two globin alpha chains and two globin beta chains. HbA is normally the main adult hemoglobin, representing about 96-98 percent of all hemoglobin. This term represents a decreased in the proportion of HbA below this limit, and can be seen in various forms of thalassemia.

Name: Decreased mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration
Desc: A reduction from the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell). A reduced mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) may indicate a hypochromic anemia, but the MCH may be normal if both the total hemoglobin and the red blood cell count are reduced.

Name: Extramedullary hematopoiesis
Desc: The process of hematopoiesis occurring outside of the bone marrow (in the liver, thymus, and spleen) in the postnatal organisms.

Name: Abnormality of iron homeostasis
Desc: An abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of iron cation.

Name: Abnormality of skeletal morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the form, structure, or size of the skeletal system.

Name: High-output congestive heart failure
Desc: A form of heart failure characterized by elevated cardiac output. This may be seen in patients with heart failure and hyperthyroidism, anemia, pregnancy, arteriovenous fistulae, and others.

Name: Malar prominence
Desc: Prominence of the malar process of the maxilla and infraorbital area appreciated in profile and from in front of the face.

Name: Hyperplasia of the maxilla
Desc: Abnormally increased dimension of the maxilla, especially relative to the mandible, resulting in a malocclusion or malalignment between the upper and lower teeth or in anterior positioning of the nasal base, increased convexity of the face, increased nasolabial angle, or increased width (transverse dimension of the maxilla.

Name: Adrenal insufficiency
Desc: Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands.

Name: Erythroid hyperplasia
Desc: Increased count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
Synonyms: Bone marrow biopsy shows erythroid hyperplasia
Bone marrow smear shows erythroid hyperplasia

Name: Increased HbA2 hemoglobin
Desc: An elevated concentration in the blood of hemoglobin A2 (HbA2), which is a normal variant of hemoglobin A that consists of two alpha and two delta chains and is normally present at low levels in adults but may be increased in beta thalassemia.

Name: Anisocytosis
Desc: Abnormally increased variability in the size of erythrocytes.
Synonyms: Unequal size of red blood cells

Name: Chronic hepatitis
Desc: Hepatitis that lasts for more than six months.

Name: Generalized abnormality of skin
Desc: An abnormality of the skin that is not localized to any one particular region.

Name: Acute leukemia
Desc: A clonal (malignant) hematopoietic disorder with an acute onset, affecting the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. The malignant cells show minimal differentiation and are called blasts, either myeloid blasts (myeloblasts) or lymphoid blasts (lymphoblasts).

Name: HbH hemoglobin
Desc: Hemoglobin H (HbH) contains four beta-globin chains. It is normally not present at all in blood, but may make up about 1-40 percent of all hemoglobin in HbH disease, a subform of alpha thalassemia.

Name: Sciatica
Desc: Pain in the lower back and hip radiating in the distribution of the sciatic nerve.

Name: Increased CSF/serum albumin ratio
Desc: An increase above normal limits of the ratio of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) albumin concentration to serum albumin concentration.

Name: Recurrent acute respiratory tract infection
Desc: A history of repeated acute infections of the upper or lower respiratory tract.

Name: Erosion of oral mucosa
Desc: Loss of the superficial layer of the oral mucosa usually resulting in a shallow or crusted lesion.

Name: Decreased circulating renin level
Desc: An decreased level of renin in the blood.

Name: Increased urinary potassium
Desc: An increased concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.

Name: Neoplasm of the adrenal gland
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adrenal gland.

Name: Renal cortical adenoma
Desc: The presence of an adenoma in the cortex of the kidney.

Name: Gonadotropin deficiency
Desc: A reduced ability to secrete gonadotropins, which are protein hormones secreted by gonadotrope cells of the anterior pituitary gland, including the hormones follitropin (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).

Name: Hypothalamic luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone deficiency
Desc: Decreased secretion of luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone by the hypothalamus.

Name: Remnants of the hyaloid vascular system
Desc: Persistence of the hyaloid artery, which is the embryonic artery that runs from the optic disk to the posterior lens capsule may persist; the site of attachment may form an opacity. The hyaloid artery is a branch of the ophthalmic artery, and usually regresses completely before birth. This features results from a failure of regression of the hyaloid vessel, which supplies the primary vitreous during embryogenesis and normally regresses in the third trimester of pregnancy, leading to a particular form of posterior cataract.
Synonyms: Persistent posterior fetal fibrovascular sheath of the lens
Persistent posterior foetal fibrovascular sheath of the lens

Name: Posterior lenticonus
Desc: A conical projection of the posterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.

Name: Chronic hemolytic anemia
Desc: An chronic form of hemolytic anemia.

Name: Pigment gallstones
Desc: Gallstones composed primarily of bilirubin and calcium salts (calcium bilirubinate) with a low cholesterol concentration.

Name: Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia
Desc: An increased amount of unconjugated (indirect) bilurubin in the blood.

Name: Hypochromic anemia
Desc: A type of anemia characterized by an abnormally low concentration of hemoglobin in the erythrocytes.

Name: Duplicated collecting system
Desc: A duplication of the collecting system of the kidney, defined as a kidney with two (instead of, normally, one) pyelocaliceal systems. The pyelocaliceal system is comprised of the renal pelvis and calices. The duplicated renal collecting system can be associated with a single ureter or with double ureters. In the latter case, the two ureters empty separately into the bladder or fuse to form a single ureteral orifice.
Synonyms: Double urinary collecting systems on intravenous pyelography

Name: Eversion of lateral third of lower eyelids
Patchy osteosclerosis
Desc: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
Synonyms: Patchy increase of bone mineral density

Name: Total anosmia
Desc: Inability to detect any qualitative olfactory sensation.

Name: Partial anosmia
Desc: Inability to perceive certain odorants (implies that the sense of smell is maintained for other classes of odorants).

Name: Right aortic arch
Desc: Aorta descends on right instead of on the left.

Name: Dysplastic corpus callosum
Desc: Dysplasia and dysgenesis of the corpus callosum are nonspecific descriptions that imply defective development of the corpus callosum. The term dysplasia is applied when the morphology of the corpus callosum is altered as a congenital trait. For instance, the corpus callosum may be hump-shaped, kinked, or a striped corpus callosum that lacks an anatomically distinct genu and splenium.

Name: Central heterochromia
