Desc: The presence of distinct colors in the central (pupillary) zone of the iris than in the mid-peripheral (ciliary) zone.

Name: Hypoplastic iris stroma
Desc: Underdevelopment of the stroma of iris.

Name: Patchy hypopigmentation of hair
Desc: Reduced pigmentation of hair in patches.

Name: Chronic disseminated intravascular coagulation
Desc: A chronic form of disseminated intravascular coagulation in which a persistent weak or intermittent activating stimulus is present and destruction and production of coagulation factors and platelets are balanced.

Name: Abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the vessel that contains or conveys lymph fluid.

Name: Hypopnea
Desc: Hypopnea is referring to breathing that is abnormally shallow.

Name: Cervical lymphadenopathy
Desc: Enlarged lymph nodes in the neck.
Synonyms: Swollen lymph nodes in the neck

Name: Palmoplantar erythema
Desc: Redness of the skin of the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.

Name: Double outlet right ventricle with subpulmonary ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
Desc: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Synonyms: DORV with subpulmonary VSD without pulmonary stenosis

Name: Sterile pyuria
Desc: Patients who routinely have greater than 20 leukocytes per microliter, but have abacterial urine, are said to have sterile pyuria.

Name: Widely-spaced maxillary central incisors
Desc: Increased distance between the maxillary central permanent incisor tooth.
Synonyms: Wide gap between upper central incisors

Name: Cutaneous syndactyly
Desc: A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints, or a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits that lies significantly distal to the flexion crease that overlies the metacarpophalangeal or metatarsophalangeal joint of the adjacent digits.

Name: Diffuse palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
Desc: Diffuse abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles.

Name: Abnormal cartilage morphology
Desc: Any morphological abnormality of cartilage.

Name: Abnormality of the ischium
Desc: An anomaly of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

Name: Xanthomatosis
Desc: The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin.
Synonyms: Yellow bumps of fatty deposits on skin

Name: Loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue in limbs
Desc: Loss (disappearance) of previously present subcutaneous fat tissue in arm or leg.
Synonyms: Loss of fat tissue below the skin in limbs
Loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue from extremities

Name: Eclampsia
Desc: An acute and life-threatening complication of pregnancy, which is characterized by the appearance of tonic-clonic seizures, usually in a patient who had developed pre-eclampsia. Eclampsia includes seizures and coma that happen during pregnancy but are not due to preexisting or organic brain disorders.

Name: Rectal prolapse
Desc: Protrusion of the rectal mucous membrane through the anus.

Name: Impacted tooth
Desc: A tooth that has not erupted because of local impediments (overcrowding or fibrous gum overgrowth).

Name: Abdominal wall defect
Desc: An incomplete closure of the abdominal wall.

Name: Ectopia cordis
Desc: Congenital malformation of the ventral wall with partial or total evisceration of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and through the defect in the ventral wall.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the thorax
Ventral hernia
Desc: Ventral hernia refers to a condition in which abdominal contents protrude through a weakened portion of the abdominal wall.

Name: Aplasia cutis congenita of scalp
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp.

Name: Cutis gyrata of scalp
Desc: The presence of convoluted folds and furrows formed from thickened skin of the scalp, resembling cerebriform pattern. The scalp has convoluted and elevated folds, 1 to 2 cm in thickness. The convolutions generally cannot be flattened by traction.
Synonyms: Furrows in thickened skin on top of scalp
Thickened folds on top of scalp

Name: Thoracoabdominal wall defect
Desc: Failure to close of the chest and abdominal wall likely caused by the failure of the ventral wall to close during week 4 of development.

Name: Fibular duplication
Desc: Duplication of the fibula. This may occur as a part of diplopodia (accessory tarsal or metatarsal bone). Diplopodia with double fibula is an extremely rare condition.

Name: Mirror image polydactyly
Desc: A hand or foot with more than five digits that has a recognizable A/P axis of symmetry. The axis can lie within a normally formed or partially duplicated digit resembling a middle finger, index finger, thumb, toe, or hallux. Alternatively, the axis can be in an interdigital space with a flanking pair of digits that resemble a middle finger, index finger, thumb, toe or hallux. The most lateral digits on each side of the hand typically resemble fifth fingers/toes.

Name: Limb duplication
Desc: Congenital duplication of all or part of a limb.

Name: Abnormal circulating carboxylic acid concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carboxylic acid in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal platelet granules
Desc: An anomaly of alpha or dense granules or platelet lysosomes.

Name: Abnormal megakaryocyte morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of megakaryocytes. Mature blood platelets are released from the cytoplasm of megakaryocytes, which are bone-marrow resident cells.
Synonyms: Abnormality of cells of the megakaryocyte lineage

Name: Abnormality of the abdominal wall
Desc: The presence of any abnormality affecting the abdominal wall.
Synonyms: Abnormality of external features of the abdomen

Name: Generalized hypopigmentation of hair
Desc: Reduced pigmentation of hair diffusely.

Name: EEG with generalized slow activity
Desc: Diffuse slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Decreased number of peripheral myelinated nerve fibers
Desc: A loss of myelinated nerve fibers in the peripheral nervous system (in general, this finding can be observed on nerve biopsy).
Synonyms: Decreased number of large and small myelinated fibers
Decreased number of large and small myelinated fibres
Decreased number of peripheral myelinated nerve fibres

Name: Allergy
Desc: An allergy is an immune response or reaction to substances that are usually not harmful.

Name: Scintillating scotoma
Desc: A scintillating scotoma is a common visual aura that can preced a migraine, whereby a spot of flickering light near the center of the visual fields occurs. The spot prevents vision, and is thus termed scotoma. The scotoma can extend into one or more shimmering arcs of white or colored flashing lights.

Name: Pulsatile tinnitus
Desc: Pulsatile tinnitus is generally classified a kind of objective tinnitus, meaning that it is not only audible to the patient but also to the examiner on auscultation of the auditory canal and/or of surrounding structures with use of an auscultation tube or stethoscope. Usually, pulsatile tinnitus is heard as a lower pitched thumping or booming, a rougher blowing sound which is coincidental with respiration, or as a clicking, higher pitched rhythmic sensation.

Name: Bimanual synkinesia
Desc: Involuntary movements of one hand that accompany and mirror intentional movements of the opposite hand.

Name: Dysgenesis of the hippocampus
Desc: Structural abnormality of the hippocampus related to defective development.

Name: Decreased amplitude of sensory action potentials
Desc: A reduction in the amplitude of sensory nerve action potential. This feature is measured by nerve conduction studies.

Name: Square-wave jerks
Desc: Square wave jerks are saccadic eye movements which, when recorded with open eyes are considered to be a pathological sign, caused by fixation instability, and pointing to a central neurological lesion.

Name: Motor tics
Desc: Movement-based tics affecting discrete muscle groups.

Name: Phonic tics
Desc: Involuntary sounds produced by moving air through the nose, mouth, or throat. The vocal cords are not involved in all tics that produce sound.

Name: Head titubation
Desc: A head tremor of moderate speed (3 to 4 Hz) in the anterior-posterior direction.

Name: Bruxism
Desc: Bruxism is characterized by the grinding of the teeth including the clenching of the jaw and typically occur during sleep.

Name: Self-mutilation of tongue and lips due to involuntary movements
Synonyms: Self-mutilation of tongue and lips due to involuntary movements

Name: Hair-pulling
Desc: A phenomenon in which persons repetitively pull out their own hair, resulting in noticeable hair loss.

Name: Temporomandibular joint crepitus
Desc: Noises from the temporomandibular joint during mandibular movement (e.g., chewing). Temporomandibular joint crepitus is often described as a clicking, popping, grating sound.

Name: Socially inappropriate behavior
Desc: Behavior that is not in line with social norms.

Name: Lingual dystonia
Desc: Involuntary protrusions, movements, spams and contortions of the tongue.

Name: Micrographia
Desc: Abnormally small sized handwriting defined formally as an impairment of a fine motor skill manifesting mainly as a progressive or stable reduction in amplitude during a writing task.

Name: Hypoplasia of the odontoid process
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the dens of the axis.

Name: Elevated plasma branched chain amino acids
Desc: An increased concentration of a branched chain amino acid in the blood.

Name: Increased urine alpha-ketoglutarate concentration
Desc: A greater than normal concentration of 2-oxoglutaric acid in the urine.

Name: Hyperisoleucinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of isoleucine in the blood.

Name: Osteochondrosis
Desc: Abnormal growth ossification centers in children. Initially a degeneration/ necrosis followed by regeneration or recalcification.

Name: Lacrimal punctal atresia
Desc: Congenital absence or closure of the opening of the lacrimal punctum.

Name: Hamartoma of the orbital region
Desc: A hamartoma (disordered proliferation of mature tissues) which can originate from any tissue of the orbital region.

Name: Cutaneous hamartoma
Desc: A hamartoma (tissue malformation consisting of an abnormal mixture of constitutive components) originating in the skin.

Name: Lipomas of eyelids
Desc: Fatty tumors on the eyelids.

Name: Bilateral microphthalmos
Desc: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of both eyes.
Synonyms: Abnormally small eyeball on both sides
Decreased size of globes of eyes

Name: Abnormality of cartilage of external ear
Desc: An abnormality of a cartilage of external ear.

Name: Dorsal subluxation of ulna
Desc: Partial dislocation of the ulna in the dorsal direction.

Name: Axial muscle stiffness
Desc: Stiffness (a condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) of the axial musculature.

Name: Vertical supranuclear gaze palsy
Desc: A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a vertical direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.

Name: Freezing of gait
Desc: Freezing of gait is defined as a brief, episodic absence or marked reduction of forward progression of the feet despite the intention to walk.

Name: Palilalia
Desc: Repetition of one's own words or phrases.

Name: Tachylalia
Desc: Extreme rapidity of speech.

Name: Frontal release signs
Desc: Primitive reflexes traditionally held to be a sign of disorders that affect the frontal lobes.

Name: Limb apraxia
Desc: Difficulty in performing the correct execution of limbs movements in absence of motor impairment.

Name: Slowed horizontal saccades
Desc: An abnormally slow velocity of horizontal saccadic eye movements.

Name: Deficit in phonologic short-term memory
Desc: Impaired ability to repeat non-word sounds. The test for nonword repetition involves the repetition of nonsensical words of increasing length and complexity and is regarded as a measure of phonological (speech sound) processing and short-term memory

Name: Stuttering
Desc: Disruptions in the production of speech sounds, with involuntary repetitions of words or parts of words, prolongations of speech sounds, or complete blockage of speech production for several seconds.

Name: Anarthria
Desc: A defect in the motor ability that enables speech.

Name: Abnormality of the abdominal organs
Desc: An abnormality of the viscera of the abdomen.

Name: Craniofacial dysostosis
Desc: A characteristic appearance resulting from defective ossification of craniofacial bones.

Name: Widely patent coronal suture
Desc: The presence of a coronal suture (the cranial suture that separates the frontal and parietal bones) that is not ossified but rather wide open at an age when it is normally closed.

Name: Talon cusp
Desc: Talon cusp is an accessory cusp located near the cingulum (the portion of the lingual or palatal aspect of the tooth that forms a convex protuberance at the cervical third of the anatomic crown).
Synonyms: Extra cusp on inside of front tooth

Name: Abnormality of the supraorbital ridges
Desc: An anomaly of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the brow of the face

Name: Prominence of the premaxilla
Desc: Prominent positioning of the premaxilla in relation to the rest of the maxilla, the facial skeleton, or mandible. Not necessarily caused by an increase in size (hypertrophy of) the premaxilla.
Synonyms: Anterior position of the primary palate bone
Prominence of the primary palate bone

Name: Chylopericardium
Desc: Accumulation of chyle (the whitish fluid taken up by the lacteals in the intestine, consisting of an emulsion of lymph and triglyceride fat thatpasses into the veins by the thoracic duct) in the pericardium. Chylopericardium is generally caused by obstruction of or trauma to the thoracic duct.

Name: Abnormality of secondary sexual hair
Desc: Abnormality of the growth of secondary sexual hair, which normally ensues during puberty. In males, secondary sexual hair usually comprises body hair, including underarm, abdominal, chest, and pubic hair. In females, secondary sexual hair usually comprises a lesser degree of body hair, most prominently underarm and pubic hair.

Name: Osteoporosis of vertebrae
Desc: Osteoporosis affecting predominantly the vertebrae.

Name: Increased muscle fatiguability
Desc: An abnormal, increased fatiguability of the musculature.

Name: Fish odor
Desc: Body odor characterized by an offensive body odor and the smell of rotting fish due to the excessive excretion of trimethylamine (TMA) in the urine, sweat, and breath of affected individuals.

Name: Ureteral agenesis
Desc: Failure of the ureter to undergo development.

Name: 3-4 finger syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers three and four.

Name: Prominent antitragus
Desc: Increased anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.

Name: Aplasia of the left hemidiaphragm
Desc: Congenital absence of the left half of the diaphragm.

Name: 1-2 finger syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one and two.

Name: Shortening of all middle phalanges of the fingers
Desc: Short, hypoplastic middle phalanx of finger, affecting all fingers.

Name: Hallux varus
Desc: Medial deviation of the great toe owing to a deformity of the great toe joint causing the hallux to deviate medially.

Name: Short first metatarsal
Desc: Short first metatarsal bone.

Name: Recurrent sinopulmonary infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to infections involving both the paranasal sinuses and the lungs, as manifested by a history of recurrent sinopulmonary infections.

Name: Abnormal sperm motility
Desc: An anomaly of the mobility of ejaculated sperm.

Name: Airway obstruction
Desc: Obstruction of conducting airways of the lung.

Name: Pulmonary situs ambiguus
Desc: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which the morphology of both left and right lungs is the same.

Name: Peribronchovascular interstitial thickening
Desc: Thickening of the peribronchovascular interstitium, a connective tissue sheath that surrounds the central bronchi and pulmonary arteries. The peribronchovascular interstitium extends from the level of the pulmonary hila into the peripheral lung. This feature may be ascertained on high-resolution computer tomography.

Name: Ectopic pregnancy
Desc: A pregnancy in which the fertilized egg inserts in a location outside of the main cavity of the uterus (usually in the Fallopian tube).

Name: Lithoptysis
Desc: Expectoration (coughing up) of a broncholith. Broncholithiasis is defined as the presence of calculi in the tracheobronchial tree. It is a rare disease but can be characterized by clinical and radiological findings of a calcified lymph node eroding bronchial wall and opening into the bronchial lumen.

Name: Abnormal atrial arrangement
Desc: Abnormality of the spatial relationship of the atria to other components of the heart.

Name: Abnormal inferior vena cava morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the lower portion of the body.

Name: Absent hand
Desc: The total absence of the hand, with no bony elements distal to the radius or ulna.

Name: Generalized edema
Desc: Generalized abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body.

Name: Maternal hypertension
Desc: Increased blood pressure during a pregnancy.

Name: Hemoglobinuria
Desc: The presence of free hemoglobin in the urine.

Name: Placental abruption
Desc: Separation of the placenta from the uterus wall before delivery.

Name: Epigastric pain
Desc: Pain that is localized to the region of the upper abdomen immediately below the ribs.

Name: Internal hemorrhage
Desc: The presence of hemorrhage within the body.

Name: Lower eyelid coloboma
Desc: A short discontinuity of the margin of the lower eyelid.
Synonyms: Full thickness defect of the lower eyelid

Name: Phocomelia
Desc: Missing or malformed long bones of the extremities with the distal parts (such as hands and/or feet) connected to the variably shortened or even absent extremity, leading to a flipper-like appearance, as opposed to other forms of limb malformations were either the hole limb is missing (such as amelia), or the distal part of a limb is absent (peromelia).

Name: Increased adipose tissue around the neck
Desc: An increased amount of subcutaneous fat tissue around the neck.

Name: Hypoplasia of teeth
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of teeth.

Name: Acroosteolysis of distal phalanges (feet)
Synonyms: Acroosteolysis of distal phalanges of feet

Name: Reduced intrathoracic adipose tissue
Desc: An abnormally reduced amount of adipose tissue in the thoracic cavity.

Name: Increased intraabdominal fat
Desc: An abnormal increase in the amount of intraabdominal fat tissue.

Name: Increased subcutaneous truncal adipose tissue
Desc: The presence of an abnormally increased amount of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the trunk of the body.
Synonyms: Increased fat below the skin in trunk

Name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanges of the hand
Synonyms: Osteolytic defects of the outermost finger bone of the hand

Name: Increased circulating free fatty acid level
Desc: A higher than normal levels of the fatty acids which can occur in plasma as a result of lipolysis in adipose tissue or when plasma triacyglycerols are taken into tissues.

Name: Abnormal tongue morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the tongue.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the skeletal musculature
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the musculature.

Name: Abnormal anatomic location of the heart
Desc: Thickening of the left ventricle wall with congenital onset.

Name: Abnormality of the columella
Desc: An abnormality of the columella.

Name: Broad chin
Desc: Increased width of the midpoint of the mandible (mental protuberance) and overlying soft tissue.

Name: Increased arm span
Desc: Increased length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle).

Name: Abnormality of the thymus
Desc: Abnormality of the thymus, an organ located in the upper anterior portion of the chest cavity just behind the sternum and whose main function is to provide an environment for T lymphocyte maturation.

Name: Lumbar hemivertebrae
Desc: Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the lumbar spine.

Name: Loss of truncal subcutaneous adipose tissue
Desc: Loss (reduction of previously present) of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the region of the trunk.
Synonyms: Loss of fat tissue in trunk
Loss of subcutaneous truncal adipose tissue

Name: Chronic leukemia
Desc: A slowly progressing leukemia characterized by a clonal (malignant) proliferation of maturing and mature myeloid cells or mature lymphocytes. When the clonal cellular population is composed of myeloid cells, the process is called chronic myelogenous leukemia. When the clonal cellular population is composed of lymphocytes, it is classified as chronic lymphocytic leukemia, hairy cell leukemia, or T-cell large granular lymphocyte leukemia.

Name: Abnormal spleen morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of the structure of the spleen.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the pancreas
Desc: A congenital underdevelopment (aplasia or hypoplasia) of the pancreas.

Name: Abnormal sweat gland morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the sweat gland.

Name: Focal autonomic seizure with epigastric sensation/nausea/vomiting/other gastrointestinal phenomena
Desc: A type of focal autonomic seizure characterised by symptoms or signs pertaining to the gastrointestinal system as the initial semiological feature.

Name: Shortening of all distal phalanges of the fingers
Desc: Hypoplasia of all of the distal phalanx of finger.
Synonyms: Shortening of all outermost bones of the fingers

Name: Shallow anterior chamber
Desc: Reduced depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is decreased.

Name: Abnormal parietal bone morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the parietal bone of the skull.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the parietal bone of skull

Name: Cerebral hypomyelination
Desc: Reduced amount of myelin in the nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis in the white matter of the central nervous system.

Name: Urethral stricture
Desc: Narrowing of the urethra associated with inflammation or scar tissue.

Name: Hydrometrocolpos
Desc: Hydrometrocolpos is an accumulation of uterine and vaginal secretions as well as menstrual blood in the uterus and vagina.

Name: White forelock
Desc: A triangular depigmented region of white hairs located in the anterior midline of the scalp.
Synonyms: White part of hair above forehead

Name: Elevated plasma citrulline
Desc: An increased concentration of citrulline in the blood.

Name: Respiratory alkalosis
Desc: Alkalosis due to excess loss of carbon dioxide from the body.

Name: Acute hyperammonemia
Desc: An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood with sudden onset.

Name: Decreased body mass index
Desc: Abnormally decreased weight-to-height squared ratio, calculated by dividing the individual's weight in kilograms by the square of the individual's height in meters and used as an indicator of underweight compared to averages.

Name: Asterixis
Desc: A clinical sign indicating a lapse of posture and is usually manifest by a bilateral flapping tremor at the wrist, metacarpophalangeal, and hip joints.

Name: Sleep terror
Desc: Episodes of intense fear, screaming and flailing although affected individuals are still asleep.

Name: Delayed menarche
Desc: First period after the age of 15 years.

Name: Mania
Desc: A state of abnormally elevated or irritable mood, arousal, and or energy levels.

Name: Insomnia
Desc: Persistent difficulty initiating or maintaining sleep.

Name: Hypergalactosemia
Desc: Elevated concentration of galactose in the blood.

Name: Hyperlysinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of lysine in the blood.

Name: Hypertyrosinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.

Name: Abnormal circulating arginine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of arginine in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal circulating alanine concentration
Desc: An abnormality of an alanine metabolic process.

Name: Hypermethioninemia
Desc: An increased concentration of methionine in the blood.

Name: Hyperthreoninemia
Desc: An increased concentration of threonine in the blood.

Name: Abnormal circulating serine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of serine in the blood circulation.

Name: Increased urinary glycerol
Desc: An increased concentration of glycerol in the urine.

Name: Abnormal upper motor neuron morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly that affects the upper motor neuron.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of upper motor neuron

Name: Pseudobulbar behavioral symptoms
Desc: Individuals with Pseudobulbar signs often also demonstrate abnormal behavioral symptoms such as inappropriate emotional outbursts of uncontrolled laughter or weeping etc.

Name: Migraine without aura
Desc: Repeated headache attacks lasting 4-72 h fulfilling at least two of the following criteria: 1) unilateral location, 2) pulsating quality, 3) moderate or severe pain intensity, and 4) aggravation by or causing avoidance of routine physical activity such as climbing stairs. Headache attacks are commonly accompanied by nausea, vomiting, photophobia, or phonophobia.

Name: Focal sensory seizure with somatosensory features
Desc: A seizure characterized by sensory phenomena including tingling, numbness, electric-shock like sensation, pain, sense of movement, or desire to move as its first clinical manifestation.

Name: Weakness of facial musculature
Desc: Reduced strength of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

Name: Retinal neovascularization
Desc: In wound repair, neovascularization (NV) involves the sprouting of new vessels from pre-existent vessels to repair or replace damaged vessels. In the retina, NV is a response to ischemia. The NV adheres to the inner surface of the retina and outer surface of the vitreous. NV are deficient in tight junctions and hence leak plasma into surrounding tissue including the vitreous. Plasma causes the vitreous gel to degenerate, contract, and eventually collapse which pulls on the retina. Since retinal NV is adherent to both retina and vitreous, as the vitreous contracts the NV may be sheared resulting in vitreous hemorrhage or the NV may remain intact and pull the retina with the vitreous resulting in retinal elevation referred to as traction retinal detachment.

Name: Retinal cotton wool spot
Desc: Fluffy white patch on the retina, representing localized areas of dense white swelling of the retinal nerve fibre layer. They often have a zigzag internal structure, a feathered edge but an otherwise well-delineated form and an approximately 1 mm dimension; they project slightly into the vitreous and sometimes deflect retinal vessels.

Name: Focal hyperintensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
Desc: An abnormal area of increased brightness (hyperintensity) that is limited to one particular area.

Name: Focal hypointensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
Shield chest
Desc: A broad chest.

Name: Frontal balding
Desc: Absence of hair in the anterior midline and/or parietal areas.

Name: Papillary thyroid carcinoma
Desc: The presence of a papillary adenocarcinoma of the thyroid gland.

Name: Odontoma
Desc: The presence of an odontoma.

Name: Thyroid nodule
Desc: A nodular lesion that develops in the thyroid gland. The term "thyroid nodule" refers to any abnormal growth that forms a lump in the thyroid gland.

Name: Pilomatrixoma
Desc: Pilomatricoma is an asymptomatic slowly growing benign cutaneous tumor, differentiating towards the hair matrix of the hair follicle. It is covered by normal or hyperemic skin, and usually varies in size from 0.5 to 3 cm.

Name: Fibrosarcoma
Desc: A fibroblastic sarcoma is a malignant tumor derived from fibrous connective tissue and characterized by immature proliferating fibroblasts or undifferentiated anaplastic spindle cells.

Name: Osteoma
Desc: Osteomas are bony growths found most commonly on the skull and mandible; however, they may occur in any bone of the body. Osteomas do not usually cause clinical problems and do not become malignant.

Name: Abnormal circulating phytanic acid concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of phytanic acid in the blood circulation.

Name: Iridodonesis
Desc: Tremulousness of the iris on movement of the eye, occurring in subluxation of the lens.

Name: Oral motor hypotonia
Desc: Reduced muscle tone of oral musculature. In infants, this feature may be associated with difficulties in breast feeding, and may affect the latch, jaw motions, tongue placement, lip seal, suck/swallow/breathe pattern and overall feeding behavior.

Name: Neuronal loss in basal ganglia
Desc: A reduction in the number of nerve cells in the basal ganglia.

Name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the hand
Desc: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the hand.
Synonyms: Breakdown of small bones of fingers

Name: Ectopic ossification in muscle tissue
Desc: Formation of abnormal bony tissue within muscle tissue.

Name: Giant hypertrophic gastritis
Desc: A type of gastritis characterized by excessive proliferation of the gastric mucosa and diffuse thickening of the gastric mucosal folds.

Name: Helicobacter pylori infection
Desc: A recurrent infection of the GI tract with helicobacter pylori, a gram-negative, microaerophilic bacterium usually found in the stomach.

Name: Peripheral edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of interstitial fluid in the soft tissues of the limbs.

Name: Chromosomal breakage induced by ionizing radiation
Desc: Increased amount of chromosomal breaks in cultured blood lymphocytes or other cells induced by treatment with ionizing radiation.
Synonyms: Chromosomal breakage induced by ionising radiation

Name: Increased sensitivity to ionizing radiation
Desc: An abnormally increased sensitivity to the effects of ionizing radiation.

Name: Focal T2 hypointense thalamic lesion
Desc: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the thalamus.

Name: Decreased circulating follicle stimulating hormone concentration
Desc: A reduction of the circulating level of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).
Synonyms: Decreased circulating follicle stimulating hormone level

Name: Decreased circulating luteinizing hormone level
Desc: A reduction in the circulating level of luteinizing hormone (LH).

Name: Hypothalamic hypothyroidism
Desc: A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in thyrotropin-releasing hormone activity.

Name: Abnormal central sensory function
Desc: An abnormality of sensation related to CNS function. Assuming the primary sensory modalities are intact and the patient is alert and cooperative, the presence of an abnormality of sensory function may indicate a lesion of a parietal cortex, the thalamocortical projections to the parietal cortex, or the spinal cord.

Name: Neoplasm of the anterior pituitary
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

Name: Enlarged pituitary gland
Desc: An abnormally increased size of the pituitary gland.

Name: Hemifacial spasm
Desc: Intermittent clonic or tonic contraction of muscles supplied by facial nerve. Muscles are relaxed in between contractions.
Synonyms: Spasms on one side of the face

Name: Neoplasm of the posterior pituitary
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm (tumour) in the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.

Name: Metatarsal synostosis
Synonyms: Fusion of the long bones of the feet

Name: Glutaric aciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of glutaric acid in the urine.

Name: Athetosis
Desc: A slow, continuous, involuntary writhing movement that prevents maintenance of a stable posture. Athetosis involves continuous smooth movements that appear random and are not composed of recognizable sub-movements or movement fragments. In contrast to chorea, in athetosis, the same regions of the body are repeatedly involved. Athetosis may worsen with attempts at movement of posture, but athetosis can also occur at rest.
Synonyms: Involuntary writhing movements in fingers, hands, toes, and feet

Name: Pallidal degeneration
Desc: Neurodegeneration involving the globus pallidus,a part of the basal ganglia that is involved in the regulation of voluntary movement.

Name: Subependymal nodules
Desc: Small nodular masses which originate in the subependymal region of the lateral ventricles and protrude into the ventricular cavity. They may represent subependymal hamartomas of tuberous sclerosis.

Name: T2 hypointense basal ganglia
Desc: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting all of the basal ganglia.

Name: Open operculum
Desc: Underdevelopment of the operculum.

Name: Basal encephalocele
Desc: Basal encephalocele is an encephalocele that occurs along the cribriform plate or through the sphenoid bone. The mass may appear in the nasal cavity, nasopharynx, epipharynx, sphenoid sinus, posterior orbit, or pterygopalatine fossa. The important distinction from other types is that no external tumor is visible except in those rare instances of herniations so large that they protrude through the mouth or nares.

Name: Progressive leg bowing
Desc: Progressive bending or abnormal curvature of the leg.

Name: Metaphyseal dysostosis
Desc: Abnormal mineralization of the metaphyseal area of bones.

Name: Broad palm
Desc: For children from birth to 4 years of age the palm width is more than 2 SD above the mean; for children from 4 to 16 years of age the palm width is above the 95th centile; or, the width of the palm appears disproportionately wide for the length.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of metatarsal bones
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the metatarsal bones.

Name: Long fibula
Desc: Disproportionately long fibulae.

Name: Broad phalanx
Desc: Increased side-to-side width of one or more phalanges of the fingers or toes.

Name: Broad femoral metaphyses
Synonyms: Broad wide portion of thigh bone

Name: Antecubital pterygium
Desc: Pterygium affecting the elbow. This is a cutaneous web that can lead to severe flexion contracture of the elbow joint. Antecubital pterygium can be unilateral, bilateral, symmetric, or asysmmetric.

Name: Peters anomaly
Desc: A form of anterior segment dysgenesis in which abnormal cleavage of the anterior chamber occurs. Peters anomaly is characterized by central, paracentral, or complete corneal opacity.

Name: Fused labia minora
Desc: Fusion of the labia minora as a result of labial adhesions resulting in vaginal obstruction.

Name: Congenital blindness
Desc: Blindness with onset at birth.

Name: Hyposegmentation of neutrophil nuclei
Desc: Hyposegmented (hypolobulated) or bilobed neutrophil nuclei.
Synonyms: Hyposegmentation of neutrophil nuclei in peripheral blood

Name: Abnormality of the tarsal bones
Desc: An abnormality of the tarsus are the cluster of seven bones in the foot between the tibia and fibula and the metatarsus, including the calcaneus (heel) bone and the talus (ankle) bone.

Name: Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis
Desc: A type of glomerulonephritis characterized by diffuse mesangial cell proliferation and the thickening of capillary walls due to subendothelial extension of the mesangium. The term membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis is often employed to denote a general pattern of glomerular injury seen in a variety of disease processes that share a common pathogenetic mechanism, rather than to describe a single disease entity

Name: Episodic hemolytic anemia
Desc: A form of hemolytic anemia that occurs in repeated episodes.

Name: Dyschromatopsia
Desc: A form of colorblindness in which only two of the three fundamental colors can be distinguished due to a lack of one of the retinal cone pigments.

Name: Abnormal retinal morphology on macular OCT
Panhypogammaglobulinemia
Desc: A reduction in the circulating levels of all the major classes of immunoglobulin. is characterized by profound decreases in all classes of immunoglobulin with an absence of circulating B lymphocytes.

Name: Abnormality of upper lip vermillion
Desc: An abnormality of the vermilion border, the sharp demarcation between the lip (red colored) and the adjacent normal skin.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the red part of the upper lip
Anomaly of the upper lip vermillion
Deformity of the upper lip vermillion
Malformation of the upper lip vermillion

Name: Prominent calcaneus
Desc: Protruding heel bone, or calcaneus.

Name: Esodeviation
Desc: A manifest or latent ocular deviation in which one or both eyes tends to deviate nasally.

Name: Spherocytosis
Desc: The presence of erythrocytes that are sphere-shaped.

Name: Abnormality of the zygomatic bone
Desc: An abnormality of the zygomatic bone.

Name: Abnormal circulating renin
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of renin in the blood, a central hormone in the control of blood pressure and various other physiological functions.

Name: Dexamethasone-suppressible primary hyperaldosteronism
Desc: A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone can be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone.

Name: Vertical nystagmus
Desc: Vertical nystagmus may present with either up-beating or down-beating eye movements or both. When present in the straight-ahead position of gaze it is referred to as upbeat nystagmus or downbeat nystagmus.

Name: Dental enamel pits
Desc: The presence of small depressions in the dental enamel.

Name: Mitten deformity
Desc: Fusion of the hands and feet by a thin membrane of skin (scarring) seen in forms of dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa and leading to a "mitten" hand deformity.

Name: Alternating esotropia
Desc: Esotropia in which either eye may be used for fixation.

Name: Abnormal labia morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the labia, the externally visible portions of the vulva.

Name: Hypoplasia of the vagina
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.

Name: Vanishing testis
Desc: A condition which is considered to be due to the subsequent atrophy and disappearance in fetal life of an initially normal testis. In the presence of spermatic cord structures is evidence of the presence of the testis in early intrauterine life. When associated with a blind-ending spermatic cord, this entity is named as his absence of a testis in an otherwise normal 46XY male is usually unilateral and is assumed to be a consequence of intrauterine or perinatal torsion or infarction.

Name: Testicular gonadoblastoma
Desc: The presence of a gonadoblastoma of the testis.

Name: Pituicytoma
Desc: A solid, low grade, spindle cell, glial neoplasm of adults that originates in the neurohypophysis or infundibulum. Clinical signs and symptoms include visual disturbance, headache and features of hypopituitarism. Pituicytomas are well-circumscribed, solid masses that can measure up to several centimeters. Histologically, they show a compact architecture consisting of elongate, bipolar spindle cells arranged in interlacing fascicles or assuming a storiform pattern.

Name: Abnormality of the pituitary gland
Desc: An anomaly of the pituitary gland.

Name: Decreased female libido
Desc: Dminished sexual desire in female.

Name: Galactorrhea
Desc: Spontaneous flow of milk from the breast, unassociated with childbirth or nursing.

Name: Ependymoma
Desc: The presence of an ependymoma of the central nervous system.

Name: Abnormal cell morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of cell structure.

Name: Supratentorial neoplasm
Desc: A benign or malignant neoplasm that occurs within the intracranial cavity above the tentorium cerebelli.

Name: Abnormal conus terminalis morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the conus terminalis, which is the distal bulbous part of the spinal cord at the location where the spinal cord tapers and ends (usually between the L1 and L2 lumbar vertebrae).

Name: Pinealoma
Desc: A neoplasm of the pineal gland.

Name: Impaired convergence
Desc: Reduced ability to turn the eyes inward in order to focus on a nearby object.

Name: Pituitary null cell adenoma
Desc: A type of pituitary adenoma that is of unknown cellular origin and that lacks immunocytochemical or fine structural markers. Null cell adenomas are not associated with hormone excess.

Name: Abnormality of the orbital region
Synonyms: Abnormality of the region around the eyes
Anomaly of the orbital region of the face
Deformity of the orbital region of the face
Malformation of the orbital region of the face

Name: Hemangioblastoma
Desc: A hemangioblastoma is a benign vascular neoplasm that arises almost exclusively in the central nervous system. Hemangioblastomas consist of a tightly packed cluster of small blood vessels forming a mass of up to 1 or 2 cm in diameter.

Name: Cerebellar hemangioblastoma
Desc: A hemangioblastoma of the cerebellum.

Name: Retinal capillary hemangioma
Desc: A benign vascular tumor of the retina without any neoplastic characteristics.

Name: Cerebellar edema
Desc: Swelling from fluid accumulation (serous fluid infiltration into the interstitial space) in the cerebellum.

Name: Spinal hemangioblastoma
Desc: A hemangioblastoma of the spinal cord.

Name: Abnormal parotid gland morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the parotid glands, which are the salivary glands that are located in the subcutaneous tissues of the face overlying the mandibular ramus and anterior and inferior to the external ear.

Name: Abnormality of the breast
Desc: An abnormality of the breast.

Name: Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve
Desc: Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve.

Name: Abnormality of peripheral nervous system electrophysiology
Desc: An abnormality of the function of the electrical signals with which peripheral nerve cells communicate with each other or with muscles.

Name: Neurofibrosarcoma
Desc: A form of malignant cancer of the connective tissue surrounding nerves. Given its origin and behavior, it is classified as a sarcoma.

Name: Periarticular subcutaneous nodules
Desc: Subcutaneous nodules that are located in the vicinity of joints.

Name: Plexiform neurofibroma
Desc: A neurofibroma in which Schwann cells proliferate inside the nerve sheath, producing an irregularly thickened, distorted, tortuous structure.

Name: Enlarged peripheral nerve
Desc: Increase in size of a peripheral nerve. This finding can be appreciated by palpation along the axis of the nerve.

Name: Subcutaneous neurofibromas
Desc: The presence of Neurofibromas in the subcutis.

Name: Symmetric spinal nerve root neurofibromas
Desc: Multiple neurofibromas of the spinal nerve roots with a symmetric distribution.
Synonyms: Spinal nerve root neurofibromas, symmetric, multiple

Name: Spinal neurofibromas
Desc: Neurofibromas originating in the spine.

Name: Enlargement of parotid gland
Desc: Increased size of the parotid gland.

Name: Facial neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the face.

Name: Neoplasm of the trachea
Desc: A neoplasm of the trachea.

Name: Abnormal reticulocyte morphology
Desc: A reticulocyte abnormality.

Name: Hyperplasia of midface
Desc: Abnormally anterior positioning of the infraorbital and perialar regions, or increased convexity of the face, or increased nasolabial angle. The midface includes the maxilla, the cheeks, the zygomas, and the infraorbital and perialar regions of the face

Name: Hypoplasia of the ventral pons
Desc: Underdevelopment of the ventral portion of the pons.

Name: Viral infection-induced rhabdomyolysis
Desc: Rhabdomyolysis induced by a viral infection.

Name: Widened cerebellar subarachnoid space
Desc: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebellum.

Name: Chorioretinal dysplasia
Desc: Abnormal development of the choroid and retina.

Name: Leukonychia
Desc: White discoloration of the nails.

Name: Melanonychia
Desc: Brown or black discoloration of the nails.

Name: Absent frontal sinuses
Desc: Aplasia of frontal sinus.

Name: Torus palatinus
Desc: A bony protrusion present on the midline of the hard palate.

Name: Microgastria
Desc: A developmental anomaly wtih a small tubular or saccular midline stomach.

Name: Perineal fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula between the bowel and the perineum.

Name: Rectal atresia
Desc: A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the rectum. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the rectum.

Name: Achilles tendon contracture
Desc: A contracture of the Achilles tendon.

Name: Bilateral facial palsy
Desc: Two-sided or bilateral weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure.
Synonyms: Paralysis of both sides of the face
Weakness of both sides of the face

Name: Decreased cervical spine flexion due to contractures of posterior cervical muscles
Synonyms: Inability to touch chin to chest

Name: Bronchiolitis
Desc: Inflammation of the bronchioles.

Name: Acetylcholine receptor antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the acetylcholine receptor.

Name: Few cafe-au-lait spots
Desc: The presence of two to five cafe-au-lait macules.

Name: Coat hanger sign of ribs
Desc: An abnormal morphology of the ribs consisting of shorted, abnormally curved ribs. On posteroanterior chest radiography, the ribs show a curvature resembling that of a coat hanger (clothes hanger).

Name: Delayed ability to sit
Desc: A failure to achieve the ability to sit at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children sit with support at 6 months of age and sit steadily without support at 9 months of age.

Name: Pursed lips
Desc: An abnormality of the appearance of the face caused by constant contraction of the lips leading to a puckered or pursed appearance.

Name: Frontal hirsutism
Desc: Excessive amount of hair growth on forehead.

Name: Acromicria
Desc: Small hands and feet in proportion to the rest of the body.

Name: Decreased facial expression
Desc: A reduced degree of voluntary and involuntary facial movements involved in responded to others or expressing emotions.

Name: Abnormal transferrin saturation
Desc: Any abnormality in the serum transferrin saturation, which is calculated by dividing the serum iron level by total iron-binding capacity.

Name: Hyporeflexia of lower limbs
Desc: Reduced intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in the lower limbs. Reflexes are elicited by stretching the tendon of a muscle, e.g., by tapping.

Name: Fatigable weakness of neck muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of a skeletal muscle in the neck that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Quadriceps muscle weakness
Desc: Weakness of the quadriceps muscle (that is, of the muscle fasciculus of quadriceps femoris).

Name: Fatigable weakness of swallowing muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of the muscles involved in swallowing that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Recurrent myoglobinuria
Desc: Recurring episodes of myoglobinuria, i.e., of the presence of myoglobin in the urine. This is usually a consequence of rhabdomyolysis, i.e., of the destruction of muscle tissue.

Name: Severe lactic acidosis
Desc: A severe form of lactic acidemia.

Name: Generalized neonatal hypotonia
Desc: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period and affecting the entire musculature.
Synonyms: Generalised low muscle tone in neonate
Generalized low muscle tone in neonate

Name: Cytochrome C oxidase-negative muscle fibers
Desc: An abnormally reduced activity of the enzyme cytochrome C oxidase in muscle tissue.
Synonyms: Cytochrome c oxidase deficiency in skeletal muscle
Decreased activity of cytochrome C oxidase in muscle tissue
Decreased skeletal muscle cytochrome c oxidase activity

Name: Increased muscle glycogen content
Desc: An increased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.

Name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex I
Desc: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex I, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

Name: Ventilator dependence with inability to wean
Infantile encephalopathy
Desc: Encephalopathy with onset in the infantile period.

Name: Mitochondrial myopathy
Desc: A type of myopathy associated with mitochondrial disease and characterized by findings on biopsy such as ragged red muscle fibers.

Name: Abnormality of the mitochondrion
Desc: An anomaly of the mitochondrion, the membranous cytoplasmic organelle the interior of which is subdivided by cristae. The mitochondrion is a self replicating organelle that is the site of tissue respiration.

Name: Short mandibular rami
Synonyms: Short body and ramus of mandible

Name: Laryngeal stridor
Desc: An abnormal high-pitched noisy sound, occurring during inhalation or exhalation caused by the incomplete obstruction in the throat.

Name: Elevated brain lactate level by MRS
Desc: An increase in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

Name: Abnormal brainstem MRI signal intensity
Desc: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem.

Name: Exodeviation
Desc: A manifest or latent ocular deviation in which one or both eyes tends to deviate temporally.

Name: Decreased activity of the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex
Synonyms: Decreased activity of the PDH complex

Name: Periventricular heterotopia
Desc: A form of gray matter heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is typically located periventricularly, also sometimes called subependymal heterotopia. Periventricular means beside the ventricles. This is by far the most common location for heterotopia. Subependymal heterotopia present in a wide array of variations. There can be a small single node or a large number of nodes, can exist on either or both sides of the brain at any point along the higher ventricle margins, can be small or large, single or multiple, and can form a small node or a large wavy or curved mass.

Name: Abnormal CSF pyruvate family amino acid concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of pyruvate-family amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Synonyms: Abnormal pyruvate-family amino acid levels in cerebrospinal fluid

Name: Abnormal circulating pyruvate family amino acid concentration
Desc: An abnormality of a pyruvate family amino acid metabolic process.
Synonyms: Abnormality of pyruvate family amino acid metabolism

Name: Abnormality of the urinary system physiology
Keratoconjunctivitis
Desc: Inflammation of the cornea and conjunctiva.

Name: Abnormal vocal cord morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the vocal cord.

Name: Abnormality of the endometrium
Desc: An anomaly of the inner mucous membrane of the uterus.

Name: Urethritis
Desc: Inflammation of the urethra.

Name: Hyperalaninemia
Desc: An increased concentration of alanine in the blood.

Name: Segmental peripheral demyelination/remyelination
Desc: A segmental pattern of demyelination and regeneration (remyelination) affecting peripheral nerves.

Name: Multiple glomerular cysts
Desc: The presence of many cysts in the glomerulus of the kidney related to dilatation of the Bowman's capsule.

Name: Low plasma citrulline
Desc: A decreased concentration of citrulline in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of Krebs cycle metabolism
Desc: An abnormality of the tricarboxylic acid cycle.

Name: Lacticaciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of lactic acid in the urine.

Name: Focal T2 hyperintense basal ganglia lesion
Desc: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.
Synonyms: Hyperintense lesions in the basal ganglia on MRI

Name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
Desc: Decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.
Synonyms: Decreased activities of mitochondrial-encoded respiratory chain complexes
Decreased activity of mitochondrial respiratory complexes

Name: Heavy proteinuria
Desc: Severely increased levels of protein in the urine (1000-3000 mg per day in adults).

Name: Microtia, third degree
Desc: Presence of some auricular structures, but none of these structures conform to recognized ear components.

Name: Cleft earlobe
Desc: Discontinuity in the convexity of the inferior margin of the lobe.

Name: Facial paralysis
Desc: Complete loss of ability to move facial muscles innervated by the facial nerve (i.e., the seventh cranial nerve).

Name: Short sternum
Desc: Decreased inferosuperior length of the sternum.

Name: Sound sensitivity
Desc: Decreased tolerance to sound.

Name: Abnormal nervous system physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of the nervous system.

Name: Abnormal erythrocyte morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of erythrocytes (red-blood cells).

Name: Megaloblastic anemia
Desc: Anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal (megaloblasts).

Name: Folate-unresponsive megaloblastic anemia
Desc: A type of megaloblastic anemia that does not improve upon administration of folate. Since vitamin B12 acts by promoting recycling of folate, administration of vitamin B12 also does not improve this type of anemia.

Name: Gastritis
Desc: The presence of inflammation of the gastric mucous membrane.

Name: Absent muscle fiber merosin
Desc: Lack of merosin protein in the muscle biopsy.
Synonyms: Absent merosin staining in muscle biopsy

Name: Highly elevated creatine kinase
Desc: An increased CPK level between 4X and 50X above the upper normal level.

Name: Hypoventilation
Desc: A reduction in the amount of air transported into the pulmonary alveoli by breathing, leading to hypercapnia (increase in the partial pressure of carbon dioxide).

Name: Intercostal muscle weakness
Desc: Lack of strength of the intercostal muscles, i.e., of the muscle groups running along the ribs that create and move the chest wall.

Name: Cobblestone-like hyperkeratosis
Desc: The presence of verrucous, cobblestone-like papules and nodules in a region of skin that is said to have an appearance like that of cobblestones.

Name: Abnormal appendicular skeleton morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the appendicular skeletal system, consisting of the of the limbs, shoulder and pelvic girdles.

Name: Abnormality of head or neck
Desc: An abnormality of head and neck.

Name: Painless fractures due to injury
Desc: An increased tendency to fractures following trauma, with fractures occurring without pain.

Name: Scalp tenderness
Desc: Pain or discomfort of the scalp elicited by palpation.

Name: Cutaneous T-cell lymphoma
Desc: A type of T-cell lymphoma that exhibits malignant infiltration of the skin.

Name: Hypoplastic anemia
Desc: Anemia with varying degrees of erythrocytic hypoplasia without leukopenia or thrombocytopenia.

Name: Abnormal macrophage morphology
Desc: An abnormality of macrophages.

Name: Acute myelomonocytic leukemia
Desc: An acute leukemia characterized by the proliferation of both neutrophil and monocyte precursors.

Name: Myoclonic status epilepticus
Desc: A type of motor status epilepticus with repeating bilateral sudden brief (less than 100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction of muscles or muscle groups of variable topography.

Name: Muscle fiber tubular inclusions
Desc: Unusual regions of densely packed membranous tubules known as tubular aggregates which present as membranous inclusions, derived from membranes of sarcoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria, containing miscellaneous proteins with a variety of enzymatic activities.

Name: Type 2 muscle fiber atrophy
Desc: Atrophy (wasting) affecting primary type 2 muscle fibers. This feature in general can only be observed on muscle biopsy.

Name: Sternocleidomastoid amyotrophy
Desc: Wasting of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, the muscle in the anterior part of the neck that acts to flex and rotate the head.

Name: Weakness of orbicularis oculi muscle
Desc: Reduced strength of the orbicularis oculi, the circumorbital muscle in the face that closes the eyelid.

Name: EEG with occipital focal spike waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the occipital region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: Visual gaze preference
Desc: An abnormality of gaze that can be observed following an acute supranuclear cerebral lesion (e.g., stroke) that is characterized by an acute inability to direct gaze contralateral to the side of the lesion and is accompanied by a tendency for tonic deviation of the eyes toward the side of the lesion.

Name: Hyperparathyroidism
Desc: Excessive production of parathyroid hormone (PTH) by the parathyroid glands.

Name: T-cell lymphoma/leukemia
Desc: A type of T-cell lymphoma in which cancerous T-cells may present in the blood (leukemia), lymph nodes (lymphoma), skin or in multiple areas.

Name: Paroxysmal involuntary eye movements
Desc: Sudden-onset episode of abnormal, involuntary eye movements.

Name: Abnormal mitochondria in muscle tissue
Desc: An abnormality of the mitochondria in muscle tissue.

Name: Fetal distress
Desc: An intrauterine state characterized by suboptimal values in the fetal heart rate, oxygenation of fetal blood, or other parameters indicative of compromise of the fetus. Signs of fetal distress include repetitive variable decelerations, fetal tachycardia or bradycardia, late decelerations, or low biophysical profile.

Name: Myotonia
Desc: An involuntary and painless delay in the relaxation of skeletal muscle following contraction or electrical stimulation.
Synonyms: Delayed relaxation of muscle fibers after contraction
Delayed relaxation of muscle fibres after contraction

Name: Absent muscle fiber emerin
Desc: Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of emerin protein in the muscle biopsy.

Name: Ventricular escape rhythm
Desc: A ventircular escape rhythm occurs whenever higher-lever pacemakers in AV junction or sinus node fail to control ventricular activation. Escape rate is usually 20-40 bpm, often associated with broad QRS complexes (at least 120 ms).

Name: Tics
Desc: Repeated, individually recognizable, intermittent movements or movement fragments that are almost always briefly suppresable and are usually associated with awareness of an urge to perform the movement.

Name: Oval face
Desc: A face with a rounded and slightly elongated outline.

Name: Moderate receptive language delay
Desc: A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

Name: Coxa magna
Desc: Widening of the femoral head and neck.

Name: Urethral valve
Desc: The presence of an abnormal membrane obstructing the urethra.

Name: Broad eyebrow
Desc: Regional increase in the width (height) of the eyebrow.

Name: Microscopic hematuria
Desc: Microscopic hematuria detected by dipstick or microscopic examination of the urine.
Synonyms: Small amount of blood in urine

Name: Facial hypotonia
Desc: Reduced muscle tone of a muscle that is innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

Name: Delayed CNS myelination
Desc: Delayed myelination in the central nervous system.
Synonyms: Delay in central nervous system myelination

Name: Decreased scrotal rugation
Desc: Decreased number or density of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.

Name: Periorbital hyperpigmentation
Desc: Increased pigmentation of the skin in the region surrounding the orbit of the eye.
Synonyms: Idiopathic cutaneous hyperchromia at the orbital region

Name: Acromesomelia
Desc: Small hands and feet.

Name: Short proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
Desc: Hypoplastic/small proximal phalanx of the fifth finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/small proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
Short proximal phalanx of the fifth finger

Name: Short proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
Desc: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the proximal phalanx of the second finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/small proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
Short proximal phalanx of the second finger

Name: Scaphocephaly
Desc: Scaphocephaly is a subtype of dolichocephaly where the anterior and posterior aspects of the cranial vault are pointed (boat-shaped). Scaphocephaly is caused by a precocious fusion of sagittal suture without other associated synostosis.

Name: Branchial fistula
Desc: A congenital fistula in the neck resulting from incomplete closure of a branchial cleft.

Name: Concave nail
Desc: The natural longitudinal (posterodistal) convex arch is not present or is inverted.

Name: Thickening of the lateral border of the scapula
Synonyms: Thickening of the lateral border of the shoulder blade

Name: Iliac horns
Desc: Horn-like malformations of the iliac crests with symmetrical bilateral central posterior iliac processes. A characteristic finding in the Nail-Patella syndrome. Iliac horns are visible on X-ray and may be palpable, but are asymptomatic.

Name: Gonadal tissue inappropriate for external genitalia or chromosomal sex
Hypoplastic areola
Desc: Underdevelopment of the areola, the circular area of pigmented skin surrounding the nipple.

Name: Low frustration tolerance
Desc: The feeling of frustration can be defined as an emotional reaction that occurs if a desired goal is not achieved. Frustration intolerance is defined as an age-inappropriate response to frustration characterized by crying or temper tantrums (in children) or aggressive or other undesirable behaviors.

Name: Abnormal plantar dermatoglyphics
Desc: An abnormality of dermatoglyphs on the toes and soles, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of sole of foot.

Name: Abnormality of the testis size
Desc: An anomaly of the size of the testicle (the male gonad).

Name: Large basal ganglia
Desc: Increased size of the basal ganglia.

Name: Pulmonary artery sling
Desc: An anomalous origin of the left pulmonary artery, such that it arises from the posterior aspect of the right pulmonary artery and passes between the trachea and esophagus to reach the left hilum.

Name: Right unicoronal synostosis
Desc: Unicoronal synostosis affecting only the right coronal suture.

Name: Enlarged cerebellum
Desc: An abnormally increased size of the cerebellum compared to other brain structures.

Name: Webbed penis
Desc: Ventral skinfold extending from penis to scrotum.

Name: Pelvic kidney
Desc: A developmental defect in which a kidney is located in an abnormal anatomic position within the pelvis.

Name: Axenfeld anomaly
Desc: Axenfeld's anomaly is a bilateral disorder characterized by a prominent, anteriorly displaced Schwalbe's line (posterior embryotoxon) and peripheral iris strands which span the anterior chamber angle to attach to Schwalbe's line.

Name: Abnormality of refraction
Desc: An abnormality in the process of focusing of light by the eye in order to produce a sharp image on the retina.

Name: Iris atrophy
Desc: Loss of iris tissue (atrophy)

Name: Abnormal jaw morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the jaw, the bony structure of the mouth that consists of the mandible and the maxilla.

Name: Hypoplastic anterior commissure
Desc: Underdevelopment of the anterior commissure.

Name: Abnormality of canine
Desc: An abnormality of canine tooth.

Name: Posterior polar cataract
Desc: A polar cataract that affects the posterior pole of the lens.

Name: Horizontal ribs
Desc: A horizontal (flat) conformation of the ribs, the long curved bones that form the rib cage and normally progressively oblique (slanted) from ribs 1 through 9, then less slanted through rib 12.

Name: Hypoplastic pubic bone
Desc: Underdevelopment of the pubis, which together with the ilium and the ischium, is one of the three bones that make up the hip bone.

Name: Hypoplastic ischia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

Name: Increased vertebral height
Desc: Increased top to bottom height of vertebral bodies.

Name: Severe expressive language delay
Desc: A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

Name: Abnormal shape of the palpebral fissure
Desc: The presence of an abnormal shape of the palpebral fissure.
Synonyms: Abnormal morphology of the palpebral fissure
Abnormal shape of the opening between the eyelids

Name: Congenital pyloric atresia
Desc: Congenital atresia of the pylorus.

Name: Shortening of all distal phalanges of the toes
Desc: Abnormally short distal phalanx of toe of all toes.
Synonyms: Shortening of all outermost bone of the toes

Name: Submucous cleft lip
Desc: A cleft of the lip with overlying mucous membrane.

Name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
Desc: Absence of the distal phalanx of the little (5th) finger.

Name: Small toe
Desc: Significant reduction in both length and girth of the toe compared to the contralateral toe, or alternatively, compared to a typical toe size for an age-matched individual.

Name: Small forehead
Desc: The presence of a forehead that is abnormally small.
Synonyms: Decreased size of frontal region of face

Name: Abnormality of the frontal hairline
Desc: An anomaly in the placement or shape of the hairline (trichion) on the forehead, that is, the border between skin on the forehead that has head hair and that does not.
Synonyms: Abnormality of hairline at front of head

Name: Flexion contracture of thumb
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion in the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

Name: Patent ductus arteriosus after birth at term
Desc: Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus in postnatal life when birth was at 37 completed weeks of gestation or greater.

Name: Ventricular septal hypertrophy
Desc: The dividing wall between left and right sides of the heart, thickens and bulges into the left ventricle.

Name: Decreased muscle glycogen content
Desc: A decreased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.

Name: Cardiomyocyte hypertrophy
Desc: An abnormal increase in the volume of cardiac myocytes.

Name: Radial head subluxation
Desc: Partial dislocation of the head of the radius.

Name: Renal Fanconi syndrome
Desc: An inability of the tubules in the kidney to reabsorb small molecules, causing increased urinary loss of electrolytes (sodium, potassium, bicarbonate), minerals, glucose, amino acids, and water.

Name: Pancreatic islet-cell hyperplasia
Desc: Hyperplasia of the islets of Langerhans, i.e., of the regions of the pancreas that contain its endocrine cells.

Name: Metabolic ketoacidosis
Desc: A metabolic acidosis due to accumulation of ketone bodies generally observed in the setting of poor nutritional intake.

Name: Abnormal C-peptide level
Desc: An anomolous circulating concentration of the connecting (C) peptide, which links the insulin A and B chains in proinsulin, providing thereby a means to promote their efficient folding and assembly in the endoplasmic reticulum during insulin biosynthesis. After cleavage of proinsulin, C-peptide is stored with insulin in the soluble phase of the secretory granules and is subsequently released in equimolar amounts with insulin, providing a useful independent indicator of insulin secretion.

Name: Intervertebral space narrowing
Desc: Decreased height of the intervertebral disk.

Name: Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin
Desc: Glycosylated transferrin concentrations can be measured in serum as a marker of N-linked glycosylation fidelity. In the traditional nomenclature for congenital disorders of glycosylation, absence of entire glycans was designated type I, and loss of one or more monosaccharides as type II. These terms are retained for historical reasons but for new annotations the precise glycosylation defect should be recorded.
Synonyms: Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin

Name: Decreased sialylation of O-linked protein glycosylation
Desc: An reduced addition of sialic acids to O-linked glycans.

Name: Halberd-shaped pelvis
Desc: An anomalous radiographic appearance of the developing pelvis, in which the greater ischiadic noth (incisura ischiadica major) is shallow and the pelvis takes on the appearance said to resemble a halberd (a weapon especially of the 15th and 16th centuries consisting typically of a battle-ax and pike mounted on a handle).

Name: Abnormal enchondral ossification
Desc: An abnormality of the process of endochondral ossification, which is a type of replacement ossification in which bone tissue replaces cartilage.

Name: Abnormal protein N-linked glycosylation
Desc: An anomaly of protein N-linked glycosylation, i.e., an abnormality of the protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via a nitrogen atom in an amino acid residue in a protein.

Name: Abnormal protein O-linked glycosylation
Desc: An anomaly of protein O-linked glycosylation, i.e., of the process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via the hydroxyl group of a serine or threonine residue.

Name: Abnormality of the coagulation cascade
Desc: An abnormality of the coagulation cascade, which is comprised of the contact activation pathway (also known as the intrinsic pathway) and the tissue factor pathway (also known as the extrinsic pathway) as well as cofactors and regulators.

Name: Type II transferrin isoform profile
Desc: Abnormal transferrin isoform profile consistent with a type II congenital disorder of glycosylation.
Synonyms: Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin, type 2 pattern
Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin, type II pattern
Isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin consistent with CDG type II

Name: Recurrent infection of the gastrointestinal tract
Desc: Recurrent infection of the gastrointestinal tract.
Synonyms: Recurrent infection of the gastrointestinal tract
Recurrent infection of the GI tract

Name: Atrial septal dilatation
Desc: A bulging of the interatrial septum towards one side. In adults, atrial septal aneurysm can be defined as a protrusion of the aneurysm of >10 mm beyond the plane of the atrial septum as measured by transesophageal echocardiography.

Name: Focal myoclonic seizure
Desc: A type of focal motor seizure characterized by sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction(s) of muscles(s) or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal). Myoclonus is less regularly repetitive and less sustained than is clonus.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the femur
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the femur.

Name: Broad distal phalanx of finger
Desc: Abnormally wide (broad) distal phalanx of finger.
Synonyms: Broad distal phalanges of the hand
Broad, square ends of distal phalanges

Name: Increased T cell count
Desc: An abnormal increase in the total number of T cells detected in the blood.

Name: Colonic diverticula
Desc: The presence of multiple diverticula of the colon.

Name: Duodenal ulcer
Desc: An erosion of the mucous membrane in a portion of the duodenum.

Name: Intestinal polyp
Desc: A discrete abnormal tissue mass that protrudes into the lumen of the intestine and is attached to the intestinal wall either by a stalk, pedunculus, or a broad base.

Name: Stercoral ulcer
Desc: An ulcer of the colon due to pressure and irritation from retained fecal masses.

Name: Narrow pelvis bone
Desc: Reduced side to side width of the pelvis.

Name: Optic nerve aplasia
Desc: Congenital absence of the optic nerve.

Name: Short fourth metatarsal
Desc: Short fourth metatarsal bone.

Name: Metopic suture patent to nasal root
Desc: The frontal suture divides the two halves of the frontal bone in infants and usually fuses by the age of six years. The suture runs from the bregma (the point on the skull at which the coronal suture is intersected perpendicularly by the sagittal suture) to the nasion or nasal root. This term applies if the suture is widely patent from bregma to nasal root.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tragus
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the tragus.

Name: Fetal pyelectasis
Desc: Mild pyelectasis is defined as a hypoechoic spherical or elliptical space within the renal pelvis that measures at least 5mm and not more than 10 mm. The measurement is taken on a transverse section through the fetal renal pelvis using the maximum anterior-to-posterior measurement.

Name: Clinodactyly of the 4th toe
Desc: Bending or curvature of a fourth toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

Name: Dysplastic aortic valve
Desc: A congenital malformation of the aortic valve characterized by leaflet deformation.

Name: Morphological abnormality of the middle ear
Desc: An abnormality of the morphology or structure of the middle ear.
Synonyms: Morphological abnormality of the middle ear

Name: Abnormal atrioventricular connection
Desc: An abnormality of the circulatory connection between atria and ventricles.

Name: 3-4 finger cutaneous syndactyly
Desc: A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between fingers 3 and 4.

Name: Crazy paving pattern
Desc: The so-called crazy paving pattern is characterised on HRCT by the presence of thickened interlobular septae and intralobular lines superimposed on a background of ground-glass opacity, resembling irregularly shaped paving stones.
Synonyms: Crazy paving pattern on pulmonary HRCT

Name: Foam cells
Desc: The presence of foam cells, a type of macrophage that localizes to fatty deposits on blood vessel walls, where they ingest low-density lipoproteins and become laden with lipids, giving them a foamy appearance.

Name: Cranial hyperostosis
Desc: Excessive growth of the bones of cranium, i.e., of the skull.

Name: Facial hyperostosis
Desc: Excessive growth (overgrowth) of the facial bones, that is of the facial skeleton.
Synonyms: Increase in size of the facial bones

Name: Autophagic vacuoles
Desc: The lysosomal-vacuolar pathway has a role in the controlled intracellular digestion of macromolecules such as protein complexes and organelles. This feature refers to the presence of an abnormally increased number of autophagic vacuoles in muscle tissue.

Name: Limited knee flexion/extension
Desc: A limited ability of the knee joint to perform extension and flexion.

Name: Hip flexor weakness
Desc: Reduced ability to flex the femur, that is, to pull the knee upward.

Name: Reduced maximal inspiratory pressure
Desc: A decrease in the maximum amount of negative pressure a person can generate during an inhalation.

Name: Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the hallux
Synonyms: Notched outermost bone of big toe
Partial duplication of the outermost bone of big toe

Name: Pelvic girdle amyotrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the muscles of the pelvic girdle (also known as hip girdle), i.e., the gluteal muscles, the lateral rotators, the adductors, the psoas major and the iliacus muscle.

Name: Scapular muscle atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the muscles that are responsible for moving the scapula, which are the levator scapulae, the infraspinatus muscle, the teres major, the teres minor, and the supraspinatus muscle.

Name: Pectoralis amyotrophy
Desc: Wasting of the pectoral muscles, i.e., of the pectoralis major and pectoralis minor.

Name: Trismus
Desc: Limitation in the ability to open the mouth.

Name: Pterygium
Desc: Pterygia are 'winglike' triangular membranes occurring in the neck, eyes, knees, elbows, ankles or digits.

Name: Ethylmalonic aciduria
Desc: An increased concentration of ethylmalonic acid in the urine.

Name: Increased intramyocellular lipid droplets
Desc: An abnormal increase in intracellular lipid droplets In a muscle. The number and size of these drops can increase with somd disorders of lipid metabolism affecting muscle. See PMID 20691590 for histological images.

Name: Exercise-induced rhabdomyolysis
Desc: Rhabdomyolysis induced by exercise.

Name: Overweight
Desc: Increased body weight with a body mass index of 25-29.9 kg per square meter.

Name: Abnormality of toe
Desc: An anomaly of a toe.

Name: CNS hypomyelination
Desc: Reduced amount of myelin in the central nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis.

Name: 2-4 toe cutaneous syndactyly
Desc: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the toes 2, 3, and 4.
Synonyms: Soft tissue syndactyly of toes 2, 3, and 4
Webbed second, third and fourth toes

Name: Posterior pituitary hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the neurohypophysis.

Name: Dilatation of the renal pelvis
Desc: The presence of dilatation of the renal pelvis.

Name: Stereotypical hand wringing
Desc: Habitual clasping and squeezing of the hands.

Name: Premature thelarche
Desc: Premature development of the breasts.

Name: Cyclic neutropenia
Desc: Recurrent episodes of abnormally low levels of neutrophils in the body (neutropenia).

Name: Tooth abscess
Desc: A pocket of pus located within a region of a tooth.

Name: Periodic fever
Desc: Episodic fever that recurs at regular intervals.

Name: Premature loss of permanent teeth
Desc: Premature loss of the permanent teeth.

Name: Perianal abscess
Desc: The presence of an abscess located around the anus.

Name: Decreased eosinophil count
Desc: Abnormal reduction in the count of eosinophils in the blood per volume.

Name: Enterocolitis
Desc: An inflammation of the colon and small intestine. However, most conditions are either categorized as Enteritis (inflammation of the small intestine) or Colitis (inflammation of the large intestine).

Name: Bacteremia
Desc: Presence of viable bacteria in the blood.

Name: Granulocytic hypoplasia
Desc: Decreased number of granulocyte precursors in the bone marrow.

Name: Monocytopenia
Desc: An decreased number of circulating monocytes.

Name: Bone marrow hypercellularity
Desc: A larger than normal amount or percentage of hematopoietic cells relative to marrow fat.

Name: Monocytosis
Desc: An increased number of circulating monocytes.

Name: Abnormal neutrophil count
Desc: A deviation from the normal range of neutrophil cell counts in the circulation.

Name: Tethered cord
