Desc: During normal embryological development, the spinal cord first occupies the entire length of the vertebral column but goes on to assume a position at the level of L1 due to differential growth of the conus medullaris and the vertebral column. The filum terminale is a slender, threadlike structure that remains after the normal regression of the distal embryonic spinal cord and attaches the spinal cord to the coccyx. A tethered cord results if there is a thickened rope-like filum terminale which anchors the cord at the level of L2 or below, potentially causing neurologic signs owing to abnormal tension on the spinal cord.

Name: Occipital meningocele
Desc: A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull in the occipital region.

Name: Lipomyelomeningocele
Desc: A type of spinal dysraphism presenting as a subcutaneous fatty mass, that is, a spinal defect associated with lipomatous tissue, and covered by skin. The most usual location for lipomyelomeningocele is at the gluteal cleft.

Name: Hydromyelia
Desc: Dilation of central canal from incomplete fusion of the posterior columns or persistence of the primitive large canal of the embryo.

Name: Anteriorly placed odontoid process
Desc: Anterior mislocalization of the dens of the axis.

Name: Distal peripheral sensory neuropathy
Desc: Peripheral sensory neuropathy affecting primarily distal sensation.

Name: Abnormality of the vestibulocochlear nerve
Desc: Abnormality of the vestibulocochlear nerve, the eighth cranial nerve, which is involved in transmitting sound and equilibrium information from the inner ear to the brain.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the eighth cranial nerve
Abnormality of the VIIIth cranial nerve

Name: Abnormality of the clivus
Desc: An abnormality of the clivus, which is the inclined bony region of the posterior cranial fossa located between the sella turcica and the foramen magnum.

Name: Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve
Desc: Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve.

Name: Functional abnormality of the inner ear
Desc: An abnormality of the function of the inner ear.
Synonyms: Functional abnormality of the inner ear

Name: Areflexia of upper limbs
Desc: Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the upper limbs.

Name: Abnormality of the musculature of the lower limbs
Basilar invagination
Desc: Projection of the tip of the dens more than 5 mm above a line joining the hard palate to the posterior lip of the foramen magnum (Chamberlain's line) or the tip of the dens is greater than 7 mm above McGregor's line (the back of the hard palate to the lowest point of the occipital squama).

Name: Cerebellar ataxia associated with quadrupedal gait
Desc: The presence of cerebellar signs and symptoms such as lack of balance associated with quadrupedal gait (locomotion on all four extremities with a 'bear-like' gait with the legs held straight).

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cerebral white matter
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the cerebral white matter.

Name: 4-layered lissencephaly
Desc: A form of lissencephaly in which the cortex is thickened and has four more or less disorganized layers rather than six normal layers resulting from incomplete neuronal migration during brain development. At neuropathological examination, a 4-layered cortex consists of an upper molecular layer, a second thin cellular layer containing pyramidal neurons usually observed in layer V, a third pale poorly cellular layer and a fourth thick deep layer made up of neurons which had failed to migrate. Radiologocally would manifest as agyria or pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm.

Name: Abnormal glossopharyngeal nerve morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the glossopharyngeal nerve, the ninth paired cranial nerve (CN IX).

Name: Giant somatosensory evoked potentials
Desc: An abnormal enlargement (i.e. increase in measured voltage) of somatosensory evoked potentials.

Name: Pulmonary arteriovenous malformation
Desc: Pulmonary arteriovenous malformation, a condition most commonly associated with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia, is an abnormal communication between the pulmonary artery and pulmonary vein without an intervening capillary communication. HRCT images usually show a coarse spidery appearance of the peripheral vascular markings in the lungs. More specific findings are obtained in the pulmonary angiogram where the normally invisible capillary phase is replaced by irregular vascular channels bridging the peripheral branches of pulmonary arteries and veins.

Name: EEG with frontal focal spikes
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the frontal region.

Name: Impaired use of nonverbal behaviors
Desc: Reduced ability to use nonverbal behavior for communication, such as eye-to-eye gaze, facial expression, body posture, and gestures.

Name: EEG with central focal spikes
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the central region.

Name: EEG with occipital focal spikes
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the occipital region.

Name: EEG with parietal focal spikes
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the parietal region.

Name: Spondylolisthesis
Desc: Complete bilateral fractures of the pars interarticularis resulting in the anterior slippage of the vertebra.
Synonyms: Displacement of one backbone compared to another

Name: Enlarged fetal cisterna magna
Desc: The cisterna magna is measured on a transaxial view of the fetal head angled 15 degrees caudal to the canthomeatal line. The anterior/posterior diameter is taken between the inferior/posterior surface of the vermis of the cerebellum to the inner surface of the cranium. An enlarged cisternal magna is defined by an anterior/posterior diameter of 10 mm or more (PMID:16100637).

Name: Flexion contracture of the 2nd toe
Desc: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the second toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

Name: Flexion contracture of the 4th toe
Desc: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the fourth toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

Name: Fused teeth
Desc: The union of two separately developing tooth germs typically leading to one less tooth than normal in the affected dental arch.

Name: Type II lissencephaly
Desc: A form of lissencephaly characterized by an uneven cortical surface with a so called 'cobblestone' appearace. There are no distinguishable cortical layers.

Name: Hypoglycosylation of alpha-dystroglycan
Desc: A reduction in the degree of glycosylation of alpha-dystroglycan in muscle tissue.

Name: Multiple bladder diverticula
Desc: Presence of a many diverticula (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.

Name: Facial hypertrichosis
Desc: Excessive, increased hair growth located in the facial region.

Name: Primum atrial septal defect
Desc: An ostium primum atrial septal defect is located in the most anterior and inferior aspect of the atrial septum. The ostium primum refers to an anterior and inferior opening (ostium) within the septum primum, which divides the rudimentary atrium during fetal development. The ostium primum is normally sealed by fusion of the superior and inferior endocardial cushions around 5 weeks' gestation. Ostium primum defects result from a failure of the fusion of the embryologic endocardial cushion and septum primum.

Name: Unilateral renal hypoplasia
Desc: One sided hypoplasia of the kidney.

Name: Exaggerated median tongue furrow
Desc: Increased depth of the median tongue furrow.

Name: Myotonia with warm-up phenomenon
Desc: Myotonia that occurs after a period of rest and decreases with continuing exercise.

Name: Posterior subcapsular cataract
Desc: A type of cataract affecting the posterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the Lens capsule.
Synonyms: Posterior subcapsular opacities of the lens

Name: EMG: myotonic discharges
Desc: High frequency discharges in electromyography (EMG) that vary in amplitude and frequency, waxing and waning continuously with firing frequencies ranging from 150/second down to 20/second and producing a sound that has been referred to as a dive bomber sound.

Name: Prolonged QRS complex
Desc: Increased time for the complex comprised of the Q wave, R wave, and S wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).. In adults, normal values are 0.06 - 0.10 sec.

Name: Prolonged PR interval
Desc: Increased time for the PR interval (beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex).

Name: Impairment in personality functioning
Desc: A maladaptive personality trait characterized by moderate or greater impairment in personality (self /interpersonal) functioning.

Name: Testicular atrophy
Desc: Wasting (atrophy) of the testicle (the male gonad) manifested by a decrease in size and potentially by a loss of fertility.

Name: Abnormality of thyroid physiology
Desc: An abnormal functionality of the thyroid gland.

Name: Mild fetal ventriculomegaly
Desc: A kind of ventriculomegaly occurring in the fetal period and usually diagnosed by prenatal ultrasound. Cerebral ventriculomegaly is defined by atrial measurements 10 mm or more. Mild ventriculomegaly (MVM) is defined as measurements between 10 and 15 mm. Measurements are obtained from an axial plane at the level of the thalamic nuclei just below the standard image to measure the BPD (PMID:16100637).

Name: Handgrip myotonia
Desc: Difficulty releasing one's grip associated with prolonged first handgrip relaxation times.

Name: Myotonia of the jaw
Desc: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the jaw.

Name: Myotonia of the upper limb
Desc: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the arm.

Name: Choroidal melanoma
Desc: Malignant tumor of melanocytes of the choroid. The classic appearance of choroidal melanoma is a pigmented dome-shaped or collar button-shaped tumor with an associated exudative retinal detachment. Choroidal melanoma is usually pigmented, but can be variably pigmented and even amelanotic (non-pigmented).

Name: Olivopontocerebellar atrophy
Desc: Neuronal degeneration in the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus.

Name: Impaired ristocetin-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal response to ristocetin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ristocetin.

Name: Decreased platelet glycoprotein Ib-IX-V
Desc: Decreased cell membrane concentration of the glycoprotein complex Ib-IX-V.

Name: Partially duplicated kidney
Desc: The presence of a partially duplicated kidney.

Name: Obtuse angle of mandible
Desc: Abnormally flat (obtuse) angle of the mandible. The angle of the mandibular, located at the junction between the body and the ramus of the mandible, is normally close to being a right angle. This terms describes an abnormal increase of this angle such that the mandible appears flatter than normal.

Name: Horizontal supranuclear gaze palsy
Desc: A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a horizontal direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.

Name: Squared iliac bones
Desc: A shift from the normally round (convex) appearance of the iliac wing towards a square-like appearance.

Name: Abnormality of the gingiva
Desc: Any abnormality of the gingiva (also known as gums).

Name: Recurrent opportunistic infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to opportunistic infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection by opportunistic agents, i.e., by microorganisms that do not usually cause disease in a healthy host, but are able to infect a host with a compromised immune system.

Name: Lobulated tongue
Desc: Multiple indentations and/or elevations on the edge and/or surface of the tongue producing an irregular surface contour.

Name: Odontogenic neoplasm
Desc: Neoplasm involving odontogenic cells, an odontogenic tumor.

Name: Mesomelic leg shortening
Desc: Shortening of the middle parts of the leg in relation to the upper and terminal segments.

Name: Hypoplasia of the epiglottis
Desc: Hypoplasia of the epiglottis.

Name: Polysyndactyly of hallux
Desc: Combined syndactyly and polydactyly of the great toe.

Name: Central retinal vessel vascular tortuosity
Desc: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of retinal blood vessels (arteries, arterioles, veins, venules).

Name: Unilateral alveolar cleft of maxilla
Desc: One sided alveolar cleft of the maxilla.

Name: Adactyly
Desc: The absence of all phalanges of all the digits of a limb and the associated soft tissues.

Name: Y-shaped metacarpals
Desc: Y-shaped metacarpals are the result of a partial fusion of two metacarpal bones, with the two arms of the Y pointing in the distal direction. Y-shaped metacarpals may be seen in combination with polydactyly.

Name: Agenesis of central incisor
Desc: Agenesis of one or more central incisors, i.e., of lower secondary incisor, lower primary incisor, upper secondary incisor, or of upper central primary incisor.
Synonyms: Failure of development of central incisor

Name: Broad first metatarsal
Desc: Increased side-to-side width of the first metatarsal bone.

Name: Complete duplication of hallux phalanx
Desc: Complete duplication of one or more phalanx of big toe.
Synonyms: Complete duplication of big toe bones
Complete duplication of the phalanges of the hallux

Name: Suprasellar arachnoid cyst
Desc: An arachnoid cyst that progressively enlarges from an abnormality in the membrane of Liliequist or in the interpeduncular cistern, and typically, expands from the prepontine space, displacing the floor of the third ventricle upwards, the pituitary stalk and optic chiasm upwards and forwards, and the mammillary bodies upwards and backwards.

Name: Seesaw nystagmus
Desc: Seesaw nystagmus is a type of pendular nystagmus where a half cycle consists of the elevation and intorsion of one eye, concurrently with the depression and extortion of the fellow eye. In the other half cycle, there is an inversion of the ocular movements.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the mandible
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the mandible.

Name: Absent testis
Desc: Testis not palpable in the scrotum or inguinal canal.

Name: Monorchism
Desc: Having only one testis in the scrotum.

Name: Bilateral lung agenesis
Desc: Bilateral lack of development of the lungs.

Name: Absent crus of helix
Desc: Continuum between the tragus and ascending helix, without any evidence of a posterior extension (crus) towards the concha.

Name: Hypothalamic hamartoma
Desc: The presence of a hamartoma of the hypothalamus.

Name: Central Y-shaped metacarpal
Desc: A central Y-shaped metacarpal is the result of a partial fusion of two central metacarpals (i.e., metacarpals 2-4) of the hand, with the two arms of the Y pointing in the distal direction. Central Y-shaped metacarpals may be seen as a result of a central polydactyly with partial fusion of the duplicated metacarpal.
Synonyms: Y-shaped central long bones of hand

Name: Midline notch of upper alveolar ridge
Synonyms: Midline cleft of maxillary alveolar process
Midline cleft of upper alveolar ridge
Midline notch of maxillary alveolar process
Midline notch of maxillary alveolar ridge
Midline notch of upper gum ridge

Name: Mesoaxial polydactyly
Desc: The presence of a supernumerary finger or toe (not a thumb or hallux) involving the third or fourth metacarpal/tarsal with associated osseous syndactyly.

Name: Elevated systolic blood pressure
Desc: Abnormal increase in systolic blood pressure.

Name: Elevated diastolic blood pressure
Desc: Abnormal increase in diastolic blood pressure.

Name: Increased body mass index
Desc: Abnormally increased weight-to-height squared ratio, calculated by dividing the individual's weight in kilograms by the square of the individual's height in meters and used as an indicator of overweight compared to averages.

Name: Mesomelic arm shortening
Desc: Shortening of the middle parts of the arm in relation to the upper and terminal segments.

Name: Multiple palmar creases
Desc: The presence of multiple creases on the palm of the hand (more than the normal three major creases (distal transverse crease, proximal transverse crease, and thenar crease).

Name: Hypoplasia of proximal radius
Desc: Proximal radial shortening owing to a congenital defect of development.

Name: Short 4th finger
Desc: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the fourth finger, also known as the ring finger.

Name: Radial deviation of the hand
Desc: An abnormal position of the hand in which the wrist is bent toward the radius (i.e., toward the thumb).

Name: Duplication of thumb phalanx
Desc: Complete or partial duplication of the phalanges of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones (bifid), two separate bones appearing side to side, or completely duplicated phalanges (proximal and distal phalanx of the thumb and/or 1st metacarpal). In contrast to the phalanges of the digits 2-5 (proximal, middle and distal), the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Synonyms: Complete/partial duplication of phalanges of the thumb

Name: Xanthelasma
Desc: The presence of xanthomata in the skin of the eyelid.
Synonyms: Fatty deposits in skin around the eyes

Name: Microvesicular hepatic steatosis
Desc: A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of small, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes.

Name: Bone-marrow foam cells
Desc: The presence of foam cells in the bone marrow, generally demonstrated by bone-marrow aspiration or biopsy. Foam cells have a vacuolated appearance due to the presence of complex lipid deposits, giving them a foamy or soap-suds appearance.
Synonyms: Large vacuolated foam cells ('NP cells') on bone marrow biopsy
Large vacuolated foam cells on bone marrow biopsy

Name: Adrenal calcification
Desc: Calcification within the adrenal glands.

Name: Increased pulmonary vascular resistance
Desc: Pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) more than 3 wood units, as defined by the current definition of pulmonary hypertension. 95% of individuals have a PVR of less than 2.4 wood units.

Name: Abnormal jugular vein morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of a jugular vein.

Name: Edema of the dorsum of feet
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the back of the feet.
Synonyms: Oedema of the dorsum of feet

Name: Abnormality of connective tissue
Desc: Any abnormality of the soft tissues, including both connective tissue (tendons, ligaments, fascia, fibrous tissues, and fat).

Name: Hyperorality
Desc: A tendency or compulsion to examine objects by mouth.

Name: Restrictive behavior
Desc: Behavior characterized by an abnormal limitation to few interests and activities.

Name: Collectionism
Desc: Excessive or pathological tendency to save and collect possessions.

Name: Emotional blunting
Desc: Lack of emotional reactivity and empathy for situations or persons, sometime also for family members.

Name: Neuronal loss in the cerebral cortex
Abnormal immunoglobulin level
Desc: An abnormal deviation from normal levels of immunoglobulins in blood.

Name: Decreased proportion of naive T cells
Desc: An abnormally decreased proportion of naive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Decreased proportion of naive thymus-derived, alpha-beta T cells
Reduced proportion of naive T cells

Name: Abnormally low T cell receptor excision circle level
Desc: Reduced level of T cell receptor excision circle (TRECs) as measured by the TREC assay. Late in maturation, 70% of thymocytes that will ultimately express alpha/beta-T cell receptors form a circular DNA TREC from the excised TCRdelta gene that lies within the TCRalpha genetic locus. The circles are stable but do not increase following cell division and, therefore, become diluted as T cells proliferate. A quantitative polymerase chain reaction (PCR) reaction across the joint of the circular DNA provides the TREC copy number, a marker of newly-formed, antigenically-naïve thymic emigrant T cells.

Name: Lymph node hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the lymph nodes.

Name: Recurrent Haemophilus influenzae infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to Haemophilus influenzae infections as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection by Haemophilus influenzae.

Name: Recurrent cutaneous fungal infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to cutaneous fungal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of cutaneous fungal infections.

Name: Absent tonsils
Desc: Lack of observable tonsillar tissue.

Name: Parathyroid hyperplasia
Desc: Hyperplasia of the parathyroid gland.

Name: Subcutaneous lipoma
Desc: The presence of subcutaneous lipoma.

Name: Renal angiomyolipoma
Desc: A benign renal neoplasm composed of fat, vascular, and smooth muscle elements.

Name: Angiofibromas
Desc: Angiofibroma consist of many often dilated vessels.

Name: Abnormality of pancreas physiology
Desc: An anomaly of the function of the pancreas.

Name: Increased glucagon level
Desc: An elevated concentration of glucagon in the blood circulation.

Name: Loss of Purkinje cells in the cerebellar vermis
Ectopic calcification
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in a tissue or location in which calcification does not normally occur.

Name: Supranuclear ophthalmoplegia
Desc: A vertical gaze palsy with inability to direct the gaze of the eyes downwards.

Name: Facial-lingual fasciculations
Desc: Fasciculations affecting the tongue muscle and the musculature of the face.

Name: Degeneration of anterior horn cells
Synonyms: Degeneration of alpha-motor neurons in anterior horn cells of the spinal cord
Degeneration of spinal cord anterior horn cells
Loss of spinal cord anterior horn cells
Progressive loss of anterior horn cells
Spinal cord anterior horn cell degeneration

Name: Seborrheic dermatitis
Desc: Seborrheic dermatitis is a form of eczema which is closely related to dandruff. It causes dry or greasy peeling of the scalp, eyebrows, and face, and sometimes trunk.

Name: 2-4 toe syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to four.

Name: Pleuropulmonary blastoma
Desc: A rare cancer originating in the lung or pleural cavity that occurs most often in infants and young children but also has been reported in adults. Pleuropulmonary blastoma is regarded as malignant.

Name: Testicular seminoma
Desc: The presence of a seminoma, an undifferentiated germ cell tumor of the testis.

Name: Medulloepithelioma
Desc: A primitive neuroectodermal tumor that originates from the cells of the embryonic medullary canal.

Name: Decreased hip abduction
Desc: Reduced ability to move the femur outward to the side.

Name: Abnormality of musculoskeletal physiology
Desc: An abnormality of the function of the skeletal system.

Name: Curved middle phalanx of the 4th toe
Desc: A deviation from the normal straight form of the middle phalanx of the fourth toe.

Name: Enlarged naris
Desc: Increased aperture of the nostril.

Name: Capillary malformation
Desc: A capillary malformation is a flat, sharply defined vascular stain of the skin. It may cover a large surface area or it may be scattered and appear as little islands of color. In a capillary maformation, the predominant vessels are small, slow-flow vessels (i.e., arterioles and postcapillary venules).

Name: Low levels of vitamin B1
Desc: A reduced concentration of vitamin B1.

Name: Reactive hypoglycemia
Desc: Hypoglycermia following a meal (or more generally, after intake of glucose).
Synonyms: Low blood sugar after a meal

Name: Extraadrenal pheochromocytoma
Desc: Pheochromocytoma not originating from the adrenal medulla but from another source such as from chromaffin cells in or about sympathetic ganglia.

Name: Episodic hyperhidrosis
Desc: Intermittent episodes of abnormally increased perspiration.

Name: Elevated urinary norepinephrine
Desc: An increased concentration of noradrenaline in the urine.

Name: Positive regitine blocking test
Desc: A positive response to the regitine blocking test consisting of a substantial reduction in blood pressure following administration of regitine, indicative of the presence of increased levels of epinephrine and norepinephrine in the circulation, which is seen in pheochromocytoma-associated hypertension.

Name: Elevated urinary epinephrine
Desc: An increased concentration of adrenaline in the urine.

Name: Paroxysmal vertigo
Desc: Paroxysmal episodes of vertigo.

Name: Anodontia
Desc: The absence of all teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop.
Synonyms: Failure of development of all teeth

Name: Abnormality of the tibial metaphysis
Synonyms: Abnormality of the wide portion of shankbone
Abnormality of the wide portion of shinbone

Name: Abnormality of the proximal tibial epiphysis
Desc: Any abnormality of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the end part of innermost shankbone
Abnormality of the end part of innermost shinbone

Name: Absence of lymph node germinal center
Desc: Absence of germinal centers in lymph nodes. Germinal centers are the parts of lymph nodes in which B lymphocytes proliferate, differentiate, mutate through somatic hypermutation and class switch during antibody responses.
Synonyms: Absence of lymph node germinal centre

Name: Lack of T cell function
Desc: Complete inability of T cells to perform their functions in cell-mediated immunity.

Name: Abnormality of humoral immunity
Desc: An abnormality of the humoral immune system, which comprises antibodies produced by B cells as well as the complement system.

Name: Decreased calvarial ossification
Desc: Abnormal reduction in ossification of the calvaria (roof of the skull consisting of the frontal bone, parietal bones, temporal bones, and occipital bone).

Name: Carpal osteolysis
Desc: Osteolysis affecting carpal bones.

Name: Sclerotic vertebral body
Desc: Increase in bone density of the vertebral body.

Name: Osteopathia striata
Desc: A lamellar pattern visible on radiographs and mainly localized at the metaphyses of the long tubular bones. Pathologic-anatomical studies revealed that these benign signs on x-rays are the result of a juvenile metaphyseal bone necrosis. Calcifications in the necrotic marrow lead to this lamellar or lattice-like appearance.

Name: High iliac wing
Desc: Increased height of the wing (or ala) of the ilium (which is the large expanded portion which bounds the greater pelvis laterally).

Name: Persistence of primary teeth
Desc: Persistence of the primary teeth beyond the age by which they normally are shed and replaced by the permanent teeth.

Name: Abnormality of vertebral epiphysis morphology
Desc: An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of one or more vertebrae.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of the end part of the vertebra bone

Name: Albinism
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of skin, hair and eye (iris and retina).

Name: Severely reduced visual acuity
Desc: Severe reduction of the ability to see defined as visual acuity less than 6/60 (20/200 in US notation; 0.1 in decimal notation) but at least 3/60 (20/400 in US notation; 0.05 in decimal notation).

Name: Low serum calcitriol
Desc: A reduced concentration of calcitriol in the blood. Calcitriol is also known as 1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol or 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.

Name: Angle closure glaucoma
Desc: A type of glaucomatous optic neuropathy in an eye that has evidence of angle closure (i.e. significant iridotrabecular contact).

Name: Abnormal lower limb bone morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal morphology of bones of the lower limbs
Abnormal shape of bones of the lower limbs

Name: Visual acuity light perception with projection
Moderately reduced visual acuity
Desc: Moderate reduction of the ability to see defined as visual acuity less than 6/18 (20/60 in US notation; 0.5 in decimal notation) but at least 6/60 (20/200 in US notation; 0.1 in decimal notation).

Name: Dural ectasia
Desc: A widening or ballooning of the dural sac surrounding the spinal cord usually at the lumbosacral level.

Name: Clavicular sclerosis
Desc: An increase in bone density within the clavicle.

Name: Abnormal dental pulp morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the dental pulp.

Name: Abnormal molar morphology
Desc: An abnormality of morphology of molar tooth.

Name: Abnormality of the maxilla
Desc: An abnormality of the Maxilla (upper jaw bone).
Synonyms: Abnormality of the upper jaw bone
Abnormality of the upper jaw bones
Deformity of the upper jaw bones
Malformation of the upper jaw bones

Name: Pulp calcification
Desc: Pulp calcifications may appear as punctate calcifications, irregular, roughly spherical mineralized masses in any part of the pulp. It may occur isolated or associated to calcifications elsewhere such as the carotid arteries and kidneys. The diagnosis pulp calcifications can be established using radiological studies.

Name: Agenesis of premolar
Desc: Agenesis of premolar tooth.

Name: Otitis media with effusion
Desc: Otitis media characterized by thick or sticky fluid behind the tympanic membrane.

Name: Lens coloboma
Desc: A sectoral indentation of the crystalline lens, usually due to zonular weakness or absence.

Name: Posterior synechiae of the anterior chamber
Desc: Adhesions between the iris and the lens.

Name: Vitreous haze
Desc: Vitreous haze is the obscuration of fundus details by vitreous cells and protein exudation.

Name: Vitreous snowballs
Desc: Yellow-white inflammatory aggregates in the vitreous that are found in the midvitreous and inferior periphery.

Name: Arterial calcification
Desc: Pathological deposition of calcium salts in one or more arteries.

Name: Abnormality of skin physiology
Desc: Any abnormality of the physiological function of the skin.

Name: Ectopic ossification
Desc: Formation of abnormal, extraskeletal bony tissue, i.e., the presence of bone in soft tissue where bone normally does not exist.

Name: Type I transferrin isoform profile
Desc: Abnormal transferrin isoform profile consistent with a type I congenital disorder of glycosylation. In the traditional nomenclature for congenital disorders of glycosylation, absence of entire glycans was designated type I, and loss of one or more monosaccharides as type II.
Synonyms: Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin, type I pattern
Isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin consistent with CDG type I

Name: Megalencephaly
Desc: Diffuse enlargement of the entire cerebral hemispheres leading to macrocephaly (with or without overlying cortical dysplasia).

Name: Rhombencephalosynapsis
Desc: Rhombencephalosynapsis is a rare brain malformation defined by midline fusion of the cerebellar hemispheres with partial or complete loss of the intervening vermis.

Name: Midnasal stenosis
Desc: Abnormal narrowing (stenosis) of the midnasal cavity, i.e., of the middle nasal meatus, which in neonates can cause respiratory distress.

Name: Pendular nystagmus
Desc: Rhythmic, involuntary sinusoidal oscillations of one or both eyes. The waveform of pendular nystagmus may occur in any direction.

Name: Dystonic gait
Desc: Dystonic gait disorders frequently appear bizarre, particularly because activity increases dystonic tonus and posture. The abnormal posture of the foot in dystonic gait typically involves inversion, plantar flexion and tonic extension of the big toe. In many patients complex types of walking, such as walking backwards and running are paradoxically less impaired than walking forward and may seem completely unaffected. Sensory tricks, for instance, if the affected individual rests a hand on his or her neck, may improve or even normalize dystonic gait in some patients.

Name: Confluent hyperintensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
Desc: Areas of brighter than expected MRI signal in the white matter of the brain whereby individual patches run together.

Name: Abnormal morphology of musculature of pharynx
Desc: An abnormality of any of the muscles of the pharynx.
Synonyms: Abnormality of muscles of the pharynx

Name: Nevus flammeus of the forehead
Desc: Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the forehead.

Name: Decreased vigilance
Desc: A reduction in the ability to maintain sustained attention characterized by reduced alertness.

Name: Hand apraxia
Desc: Inability to perform purposeful (learned) movements with the hand upon command, even though the command is understood and there is a willingness to perform the movement. Hand apraxia includes the inability to grasp, pick up, and hold large and small objects.

Name: Calf muscle pseudohypertrophy
Desc: Enlargement of the muscles of the calf due to their replacement by connective tissue or fat.

Name: Loss of gluteal subcutaneous adipose tissue
Desc: Loss (reduction of previously present) of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the gluteal region.
Synonyms: Loss of fat tissue below the skin in gluts

Name: Abnormal circulating hormone concentration
Desc: An abnormal concentration of a hormone in the blood.

Name: Narrow nasal ridge
Desc: Decreased width of the nasal ridge.
Synonyms: Decreased width of dorsum of nose

Name: Progeroid facial appearance
Desc: A degree of wrinkling of the facial skin that is more than expected for the age of the individual, leading to a prematurely aged appearance.

Name: Increased facial adipose tissue
Desc: An increased amount of subcutaneous fat tissue in the face.
Synonyms: Increased amount of facial adipose tissue
Increased volume of facial adipose tissue

Name: Decreased adiponectin level
Desc: A reduced circulating concentration of adiponectin, a 30-kDa complement C1-related protein that is the most abundant secreted protein expressed in adipose tissue.

Name: Abdominal symptom
Desc: A subjective manifestation of disease localized to the abdomen.

Name: Jaw pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the jaw.

Name: Agenesis of maxillary central incisor
Desc: Agenesis of upper secondary incisor or of upper central primary incisor.
Synonyms: Failure of development of maxillary central incisor

Name: Broad uvula
Desc: Increased width of the uvula (subjective finding).

Name: Abnormality of the scalp hair
Desc: An abnormality of the hair of head.

Name: Prominent palatine ridges
Desc: Increased size and/or number of soft tissue folds on the palatal side of the maxillary alveolar ridge.

Name: Prominent superior crus of antihelix
Desc: Increased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.

Name: Fair hair
Desc: A lesser degree of hair pigmentation than would otherwise be expected.

Name: Deep longitudinal plantar crease
Desc: Narrow, paramedian longitudinal depressions in the plantar skin of the forefoot.

Name: Abnormal renal collecting system morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the renal collecting system.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the renal collecting system

Name: Hypertrophy of the urinary bladder
Desc: Abnormal enlargement of the urinary bladder.

Name: Unilateral renal dysplasia
Desc: A unilateral form of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.

Name: Prominent tragus
Desc: Increase posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.

Name: Rectovestibular fistula
Desc: A congenital malformation characterized by an abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the vulval vestibule, at the lower aspect of the vaginal opening.

Name: Cerebral venous thrombosis
Desc: Formation of a blood clot (thrombus) inside a cerebral vein, causing the obstruction of blood flow.

Name: Absent/hypoplastic paranasal sinuses
Desc: Aplasia or hypoplasia of the paranasal sinuses.

Name: Narrow vertebral interpedicular distance
Desc: A reduction of the distance between vertebral pedicles, which are the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the vertebral body, at the junction of its posterior and lateral surfaces.

Name: Blue irides
Desc: A markedly blue coloration of the iris.

Name: Low urinary cyclic AMP response to PTH administration
Moyamoya phenomenon
Desc: A noninflammatory, progressive occlusion of the intracranial carotid arteries owing to the formation of netlike collateral arteries arising from the circle of Willis.

Name: Choroid plexus papilloma
Desc: Choroid plexus papilloma is a histologically benign neoplasm located in the ventricular system of the choroid plexus.

Name: Acetabular dysplasia
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the acetabular part of hip bone.

Name: Diffuse telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) with a diffuse localization.

Name: Cutaneous mastocytosis
Desc: Multifocal dense infiltrates of mast cells in cutaneous tissue.

Name: Red eye
Desc: A reddish appearance over the white part (sclera) of the eye ranging from a few enlarged blood vessels appearing as wiggly lines over the sclera to a bright red color completely covering to sclera.

Name: Nuclear cataract
Desc: A nuclear cataract is an opacity or clouding that develops in the lens nucleus. That is, a nuclear cataract is one that is located in the center of the lens. The nucleus tends to darken changing from clear to yellow and sometimes brown.

Name: Increased cup-to-disc ratio
Desc: An elevation in the ratio of the diameter of the cup of the optic disc to the total diameter of the disc. The optic disc has an orange-pink rim with a pale centre (the cup) that does not contain neuroretinal tissue. An increase in this ratio therefore may indicate a decrease in the quantity of healthy neuroretinal cells.

Name: Basal lamina onion bulb formation
Desc: A type of onion bulb formation prominently affecting the area of the basal lamina.
Synonyms: Basal lamina 'onion bulb' formations on nerve biopsy

Name: Poor visual behavior for age
Desc: Lack of visual responsiveness or decrease in visual capabilities suggesting a lack of visual responsiveness or decrease in visual capabilities in an infant or young child in which visual behavior fails to meet normal developmental milestones.

Name: Abnormal pupillary function
Desc: A functional abnormality of the pupil.

Name: Vestibular nystagmus
Desc: Nystagmus due to disturbance of the vestibular system; eye movements are rhythmic, with slow and fast components.

Name: Amyloidosis of peripheral nerves
Desc: The presence of amyloid deposition in the nerves of the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Precocious puberty in males
Desc: The onset of puberty before the age of 9 years in boys.
Synonyms: Early onset of puberty in males

Name: Hyperplasia of the Leydig cells
Desc: Hypertrophy or overdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.

Name: Deformed humeral heads
Synonyms: Deformed head of long bone in upper arm

Name: Excessive skin wrinkling on dorsum of hands and fingers
Synonyms: Excessive skin wrinkling on back of hands and fingers

Name: Premature rupture of membranes
Desc: Premature rupture of membranes (PROM) is a condition which occurs in pregnancy when the amniotic sac ruptures more than an hour before the onset of labor.

Name: Abnormality of the cheek
Desc: An abnormality of the cheek- one of two bilateral soft tissue facial structures in the region of the face inferior to the eyes and between the nose and the ear. "Buccal" means relating to the cheek. The cheek is part of the midface

Name: Slender long bones with narrow diaphyses
Desc: Reduced diameter of a long bone with a more pronounced reduction of the diameter of the diaphysis of the long bones.
Synonyms: Slender long bones with narrow shaft

Name: Prominent nasolabial fold
Desc: Exaggerated bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion, or commissure).

Name: Prominent veins on trunk
Desc: Prominent thoracic and abdominal veins.

Name: High nonceruloplasmin-bound serum copper
Desc: An increased concentration of non ceruloplasmin bound copper in the blood.

Name: Fragmented elastic fibers in the dermis
Desc: Elastic fibers in the dermis exhibit an increased number of breaks associated with disorganization of the structure of the elastic fibers.
Synonyms: Fragmented elastic fibres in the dermis

Name: Abnormality of the intrinsic pathway
Desc: An abnormality of the intrinsic pathway (also known as the contact activation pathway) of the coagulation cascade.

Name: Long clavicles
Desc: Increased length of the clavicles.

Name: Fifth finger distal phalanx clinodactyly
Desc: Bending or curvature of the distal phalanx of little finger in the radial direction (i.e., towards the 4th finger).
Synonyms: Curvature of outermost bone of little finger
Curvature of outermost bone of pinkie finger
Curvature of outermost bone of pinky finger

Name: Absent proximal finger flexion creases
Desc: Absence of the proximal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fingers.

Name: Thick anterior alveolar ridges
Synonyms: Thick anterior alveolar process of jaw

Name: Cutaneous abscess
Desc: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the skin.

Name: Pulmonary cyst
Desc: A round circumscribed space within a lung that is surrounded by an epithelial or fibrous wall of variable thickness. A cyst usually has a thin and regular wall (less than 2 mm) and contains air, although some may contain fluid.

Name: Budd-Chiari syndrome
Desc: Budd-Chiari syndrome (BCS) is caused by obstruction of hepatic venous outflow at any level from the small hepatic veins to the junction of the inferior vena cava (IVC) with the right atrium, 1 and occurs in 1/100,000 of the general population worldwide. The most common presentation is with ascites, but can range from fulminant hepatic failure (FHF) to asymptomatic forms. Obstruction of hepatic venous outflow is mainly caused by primary intravascular thrombosis, which can occur suddenly or be repeated over time, accompanied by some revascularization, accounting for the variable parenchymal hepatic damage and histologic presentation. Budd-Chiari syndrome is thus a disease, but since it occurs as a manifestation of several other diseases, this term is kept for the present for convenience.

Name: Abnormality of bladder morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the bladder.

Name: Acantholysis
Desc: The loss of intercellular connections, such as desmosomes, resulting in loss of cohesion between keratinocytes.

Name: Absent cupid's bow
Desc: Lack of paramedian peaks and median notch of the upper lip vermilion.
Synonyms: Failure of development of cupid's bow

Name: Transudative pleural effusion
Desc: A type of pleural effusion with a transudate (extravascular fluid with low protein content and a low specific gravity). Pleural effusions can be classified as transudates or exudates based on Light's criteria, which classify an effusion as exudate if one or more of the following are present: (1) the ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is greater than 0.5, (2) the ratio of pleural fluid lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) to serum LDH is greater than 0.6, or (3) the pleural fluid LDH level is greater than two thirds of the upper limit of normal for serum LDH.

Name: Tortuosity of conjunctival vessels
Desc: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the conjunctival blood vessels.

Name: Abnormal urine carbohydrate level
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carbohydrate in the urine.

Name: Abnormal cerebral morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the telencephalon, which is also known as the cerebrum.

Name: Microphallus
Desc: Length of penis more than 2 SD below the mean for age accompanied by hypospadias.

Name: Absent penis
Desc: Lack of recognizable penile structures.

Name: Bladder neoplasm
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary bladder.

Name: Hyperglycinemia
Desc: An elevated concentration of glycine in the blood.

Name: Hyposerinemia
Desc: Reduced concentration of serine in the blood.

Name: Simplified gyral pattern
Desc: An abnormality of the cerebral cortex with fewer gyri but with normal cortical thickness. This pattern is usually often associated with congenital microcephaly.

Name: Partial diaphragmatic absence of pericardium
Desc: Lack of a part of the pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.

Name: Abnormal echocardiogram
Desc: An abnormality detectable by sonography of the heart (echocardiography).

Name: Talipes calcaneovarus
Desc: A congenital deformity characterized by a dorsiflexed, inverted, and adducted foot, i.e., a combination of talipes calcaneus and talipes varus.

Name: Uterine prolapse
Desc: The presence of prolapse of the uterus.

Name: Protrusio acetabuli
Desc: Intrapelvic bulging of the medial acetabular wall.

Name: Osteoarthritis of the small joints of the hand
Arterial tortuosity
Desc: Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of arteries.

Name: Abdominal aortic aneurysm
Desc: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta.

Name: Intervertebral disc degeneration
Desc: The presence of degenerative changes of intervertebral disk.

Name: Osteochondritis Dissecans
Desc: A joint disorder caused by blood deprivation in the subchondral bone causing the subchondral bone to die in a process called avascular necrosis. The bone is then reabsorbed by the body, leaving the articular cartilage it supported prone to damage. The result is fragmentation (dissection) of both cartilage and bone, and the free movement of these osteochondral fragments within the joint space, causing pain and further damage.

Name: Soft skin
Desc: Subjective impression of increased softness upon palpitation of the skin.

Name: Cystocele
Desc: Anterior vaginal wall prolapse with bulging of the bladder into the vagina.

Name: Cigarette-paper scars
Desc: Thin (atrophic) and wide scars.

Name: Arteriovenous fistulas of celiac and mesenteric vessels
Synonyms: Arteriovenous fistulas of coeliac and mesenteric vessels

Name: Arteriovenous fistula
Desc: An abnormal connection between an artery and vein.

Name: Renovascular hypertension
Desc: The presence of hypertension related to stenosis of the renal artery.
Synonyms: Hypertension due to renal artery hyperplasia

Name: Neoplasm of the nose
Desc: Tumor (An abnormal mass of tissue resulting from abnormally dividing cells) of the nasal cavity.

Name: Abnormal pigmentation of the oral mucosa
Desc: An abnormality of the pigmentation of the mucosa of the mouth.
Synonyms: Abnormal color of the oral mucosa
Abnormal colour of the oral mucosa
Abnormal pigmentation of oral mucous membrane
Abnormal pigmentation of the oral mucosa/gingivae

Name: Neoplasm of the small intestine
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the small intestine.

Name: Molluscoid pseudotumors
Desc: Bluish-grey, spongy nodules associated with scars over pressure points and easily traumatized areas like the elbows and knees.

Name: Incisional hernia
Desc: An abdominal hernia that occurs at a site of weakness in the abdominal wall resulting from an incompletely-healed surgical wound.

Name: Limb pain
Desc: Chronic pain in the limbs with no clear focal etiology.

Name: Subcutaneous spheroids
Desc: Small, hard cyst-like nodules, freely moveable in the subcutis over the bony prominences of the legs and arms, which have an outer calcified layer with a translucent core on x-ray.

Name: Piezogenic pedal papules
Desc: Flesh-colored or yellowish papules, 2 mm or larger, that are responses to internal mechanical pressure and weakness in the connective tissue in the dermis, appear commonly over the medial aspect of the heel, but in some cases on the wrists. They are thought to represent herniations of adipose tissue through the plantar fascia retinaculum.

Name: Cervical insufficiency
Desc: A cervix that shows a painless dilation and shortening during the second trimester of pregnancy with resultant recurrent pregnancy loss or delivery is considered incompetent

Name: Abnormal heart valve physiology
Desc: Any functional abnormality of a cardiac valve.

Name: Contracture of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd finger
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Name: Cutaneous syndactyly of toes
Desc: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between adjacent foot digits that involves at least half of the proximodistal length of one of the two involved digits; or, a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits of the foot that does not meet the prior objective criteria.

Name: Asymmetric radial dysplasia
Desc: The presence of asymmetric developmental dysplasia of the radius.

Name: Upper limb phocomelia
Desc: Missing or malformed long bones of the upper limbs with the distal parts (the hands) connected to the variably shortened or even absent upper extremity, leading to a flipper-like appearance, as opposed to other forms of limb malformations were either the whole limb is missing (such as amelia), or the distal part of a limb is absent (peromelia).

Name: Short 2nd metacarpal
Desc: Short second metacarpal bone because of developmental hypoplasia.

Name: Aplasia of the ulna
Desc: Missing ulna bone associated with congenital failure of development.

Name: Elliptocytosis
Desc: The presence of elliptical, cigar-shaped erythrocytes on peripheral blood smear.

Name: Poikilocytosis
Desc: The presence of abnormally shaped erythrocytes.

Name: Congenital hemolytic anemia
Desc: A form of hemolytic anemia with congenital onset.

Name: Piebaldism
Desc: Piebaldism is characterized by stable and persistent, well-circumscribed depigmented patches present at birth affecting the skin of the face, trunk, and extremities in a symmetrical distribution.

Name: White eyebrow
Desc: White color (lack of pigmentation) of the eyebrow.

Name: White eyelashes
Desc: White color (lack of pigmentation) of the eyelashes.

Name: Prominent antihelix
Desc: The presence of an abnormally prominent antihelix.

Name: Abnormal duodenum morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the duodenum, i.e., the first section of the small intestine.

Name: Athetoid cerebral palsy
Desc: A type of cerebral palsy characterized by slow, involuntary muscle movement and mixed muscle tone.

Name: Neonatal short-limb short stature
Desc: A type of short-limbed dwarfism that is manifest beginning in the neonatal period.
Synonyms: Short limb dwarfism recognisable at birth
Short limb dwarfism recognizable at birth

Name: Conical incisor
Desc: An abnormal conical morphology of the incisor tooth.

Name: Deformed rib cage
Desc: Malformation of the rib cage.

Name: Rachitic rosary
Desc: A row of beadlike prominences at the junction of a rib and its cartilage (i.e., enlarged costochondral joints), resembling a rosary.

Name: Enlargement of the costochondral junction
Desc: Abnormally increased size of the costochondral junctions, which are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.

Name: Tetany
Desc: A condition characterized by intermittent involuntary contraction of muscles (spasms) related to hypocalcemia or occasionally magnesium deficiency.

Name: Subperiosteal bone resorption
Desc: Loss of bone mass occurring beneath the periosteum (the periosteum is the connective-tissue membrane that surrounds all bones except at the articular surfaces). This process may create a serrated and lace-like appearance in periosteal cortical bone.

Name: Wide cranial sutures
Desc: An abnormally increased width of the cranial sutures for age-related norms (generally resulting from delayed closure).

Name: Elevated alkaline phosphatase of bone origin
Desc: An abnormally increased level of bone isoforms of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.
Synonyms: Elevated alkaline phosphatase of bone origin

Name: Distal femoral bowing
Desc: A bending or abnormal curvature of the distal portion of the femur.

Name: Pseudo-fractures
Desc: A band of bone material of decreased density forming alongside the surface of the cortical bone with thickening of the periosteum. Callus formation in the affected area is common and gives the appearance of a false fracture.

Name: Hypocalcemic tetany
Desc: Hyperexcitability of the neuromuscular system related to abnormally low level of calcium in the blood, resulting in carpopedal or generalized spasms.

Name: EEG with multifocal slow activity
Desc: Multifocal slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Parotitis
Desc: Inflammation of the parotid gland.

Name: Chronic pain
Desc: Persistent pain, usually defined as pain that has lasted longer than 3 to 6 months.

Name: Usual interstitial pneumonia
Desc: Temporal and spatial heterogeneity in lungs based on presence of fibrosis and honeycombing.

Name: Lymphocytic interstitial pneumonia
Desc: Lymphocytic interstitial pneumonitis is a benign lymphoproliferative disorder of the lung that is characterized by the presence of a dense, predominantly lymphocytic interstitial infiltrate (lymphocytes, plasma cells, other elements of the lymphoreticular system) that expands the alveolar septa.

Name: Vaginal dryness
Desc: Persistent vaginal dryness.

Name: Lichenoid skin lesion
Desc: Mutliple skin lesions resembling those characteristic of the disease lichen planus. These lesions are violaceous (reddish-purple), shiny, isolated, flat-topped papules and plaques.

Name: Abnormal pulmonary thoracic imaging finding
Desc: This term groups terms representing abnormal findings derived from chest X-ray investigation of the lung. In general, lung abnormalities can manifest as opacities (areas of increased density) or as regions with decreased density.

Name: Multiple mononeuropathy
Desc: A type of peripheral neuropathy that happens when there is damage to two or more different nerve areas characterized by peripheral neuropathy of both the motor and sensory nerves of at least two different nerve trunks. Different nerves are affected either simultaneously or sequentially.

Name: Chronic active hepatitis
Desc: Chronic hepatitis associated with recurrent clinical exacerbations, extrahepatic manifestations, and progression to cirrhosis.

Name: Anisocoria
Desc: Anisocoria, or unequal pupil size, may represent a benign physiologic variant or a manifestation of disease.

Name: Impaired continence
Desc: Partial or total incontinence of bowel or bladder.

Name: Irregularly spaced teeth
Desc: Irregular distribution of the teeth along the dental arch, i.e., and irregular spatial pattern of teeth.

Name: Abnormal globus pallidus morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the globus pallidus.

Name: Abnormal substantia nigra morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the substantia nigra, which is a midbrain dopaminergic nucleus which has a critical role in modulating motor movement and reward functions as part of the basal ganglia circuitry.

Name: Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma
Desc: A benign but highly vascular nasopharyngeal neoplasm. The tumor originates from the sphenopalatine foramen and involves both the pterygopalatine fossa and the posterior nasal cavity.

Name: Broad fingertip
Desc: Increased width of the distal segment of a finger.

Name: Decreased serum creatinine
Desc: An abnormally reduced amount of creatinine in the blood.

Name: Coronary artery calcification
Desc: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in a coronary artery.

Name: Developmental stagnation
Desc: A cessation of the development of a child in the areas of motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and/or emotional skills.

Name: Abnormally straight spine
Desc: The absence of the normal curvature of the vertebral column.

Name: Sclerosis of hand bone
Desc: Osteosclerosis affecting one or more bones of the hand.
Synonyms: Increased bone density in hand bone
Increased bone density in hand bones

Name: Sclerosis of foot bone
Desc: An elevation in bone density in one or more foot bones. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Synonyms: Increased bone density in foot bone
Sclerosis of bones of the feet

Name: Transitional cell carcinoma of the bladder
Desc: The presence of a carcinoma of the urinary bladder with origin in a transitional epithelial cell.

Name: Abnormal preputium morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the retractable fold of skin that covers the tip of the penis.

Name: Arachnoid hemangiomatosis
Desc: The presence of multiple hemangiomas in the arachnoid.

Name: Hyperproteinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of proteins in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of vitamin B12 metabolism
Synonyms: Abnormality of the vitamin B12 metabolism

Name: Phimosis
Desc: The male foreskin cannot be fully retracted from the head of the penis.

Name: Colitis
Desc: Colitis refers to an inflammation of the colon and is often used to describe an inflammation of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum). Colitides may be acute and self-limited or chronic, and broadly fit into the category of digestive diseases.

Name: Neoplasm of the urethra
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the urethra.

Name: Reticular hyperpigmentation
Desc: Increased pigmentation of the skin with a netlike (reticular) pattern.

Name: Broad ulna
Desc: Increased width of the ulna.

Name: Absence of subcutaneous fat
Desc: Lack of subcutaneous adipose tissue.
Synonyms: Lack of fatty tissue below the skin

Name: Retinal hamartoma
Desc: A hamartoma (a benign, focal malformation consisting of a disorganized mixture of cells and tissues) of the retina.

Name: Myelitis
Desc: Inflammation of the spinal cord.

Name: Impairment of activities of daily living
Desc: Difficulty in performing one or more activities normally performed every day, such as eating, bathing, dressing, grooming, work, homemaking, and leisure.

Name: Vaginal hernia
Desc: The presence of a hernia of the vagina.

Name: Postaxial polysyndactyly of foot
Desc: Combined syndactyly and polydactyly of the foot on the lateral side (i.e., on the side of the little toe).

Name: Ectopic accessory finger-like appendage
Desc: In contrast to forms of polydactyly where the supernumerary digit (this can either be a rudimentary or a completely 'normal' digit) is either located postaxial (on the ulnar side of the hand, next to the little finger), preaxial (on the radial side of the hand, next to the thumb) or mesoaxial (somewhere central, between thumb and little finger), a supernumerary digit may also be placed ectopically, meaning anywhere else except post-,meso- or preaxial. In the literature this is sometimes referred to as Disorganisation-like Syndrome (OMIM223200).

Name: Agenesis of canine
Desc: Agenesis of canine tooth.
Synonyms: Failure of development of eye tooth

Name: Juvenile gastrointestinal polyposis
Desc: The presence of multiple juvenile polyps in the stomach and intestine. The term juvenile polyps refer to a special histopathology and not the age of onset as the polyp might be diagnosed at all ages. The juvenile polyp has a spherical appearance and is microscopically characterized by overgrowth of an oedematous lamina propria with inflammatory cells and cystic glands. Juvenile polyps are a specific type of hamartomatous polyps.

Name: Hamartomatous stomach polyps
Desc: Polyp-like protrusions which are histologically hamartomas located in the stomach.

Name: Rectocele
Desc: A Rectocele results from a tear in the rectovaginal septum (which is normally a tough, fibrous, sheet-like divider between the rectum and vagina). Rectal tissue bulges through this tear and into the vagina as a hernia. There are two main causes of this tear: childbirth, and hysterectomy.

Name: Large forehead
Synonyms: Increased size of frontal region of face

Name: Extrahepatic portal hypertension
Desc: Increased pressure in the pre-hepatic portal vein.

Name: Small intestinal polyposis
Desc: The presence of multiple polyps in the small intestine.

Name: Cerebral arteriovenous malformation
Desc: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the brain.

Name: Hypogeusia
Desc: A decreased ability to perceive flavor.

Name: Motor conduction block
Desc: Blockade of impulses at a focal site along the course of a motor axon.

Name: Abnormal corneal endothelium morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the corneal endothelium, that is, the single layer of cells on the inner surface of the cornea.

Name: Epicanthus inversus
Desc: A fold of skin starting at or just below the medial aspect of the lower lid and arching upward to cover, extend in front of and lateral to the medial canthus.

Name: Absent antihelix
Desc: No discernible ridge between concha and triangular fossa and helix.

Name: Self-biting
Desc: Habitual biting of one's own body.

Name: Long ear
Desc: Median longitudinal ear length greater than two SD above the mean determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear.

Name: Abnormal circulating insulin level
Desc: An abnormal concentration of insulin in the blood.

Name: Hypoplasia of the tooth germ
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the tooth germ, i.e., of the structure that forms in odontogenesis that will develop into a tooth.

Name: Congenital stationary night blindness
Desc: A nonprogressive (i.e., stationary) form of difficulties with night blindness with congenital onset.

Name: Underdeveloped superior crus of antihelix
Desc: Decreased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.

Name: Moderate intrauterine growth retardation
Desc: Intrauterine growth retardation that is at least 3 standard deviations (SD) below average, but not as low as 4 SD, corrected for sex and gestational age.

Name: Abnormality of the optic disc
Desc: A morphological abnormality of the optic disc, i.e., of the portion of the optic nerve clinically visible on fundoscopic examination.

Name: Decreased corneal thickness
Desc: A decreased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.

Name: Severe B lymphocytopenia
Desc: A severe form of B lymphocytopenia in which the count of B cells is very low or absent.

Name: Abnormal size of pituitary gland
Desc: A deviation from the normal size of the pituitary gland.

Name: Abnormality of the periungual region
Desc: An abnormality of the region around the nails of the fingers or toes.

Name: Abnormal pupillary light reflex
Desc: An abnormality of the reflex that controls the diameter of the pupil, in response to the intensity of light that falls on the retina of the eye.

Name: Narcolepsy
Desc: An abnormal phenomenon characterized by a classic tetrad of excessive daytime sleepiness with irresistible sleep attacks, cataplexy (sudden bilateral loss of muscle tone), hypnagogic hallucination, and sleep paralysis.

Name: Chronic monilial nail infection
Desc: Chronic infection of the nails by Candida species.

Name: Perianal rash
Desc: The presence of a rash (change of color and texture) of the perianal skin.

Name: Anal fissure
Desc: A small tear in the thin, moist tissue (mucosa) that lines the anus. It appears as a crack or slit in the mucous membrane of the anus.

Name: Chapped lip
Desc: Cracking, fissuring, and peeling of the skin of the lips.

Name: Slow-growing scalp hair
Desc: Scalp hair whose growth is slower than normal.

Name: Limited knee extension
Desc: Reduced ability to extend (straighten) the knee joint.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the quadriceps
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the quadriceps muscle.

Name: Recurrent joint dislocation
Desc: Dislocation of a given joint repeated times.

Name: Cervical kyphosis
Desc: Exaggerated convexity of the cervical vertebral column, causing the cervical spine to bow outwards and take on a rounded appearance.

Name: Atlantoaxial dislocation
Desc: Partial dislocation of the atlantoaxial joint.

Name: Abnormal fundus morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the fundus of the eye.

Name: Patellar subluxation
Desc: The kneecap normally is located within the groove termed trochlea on the distal femur and can slide up and down in it. Patellar subluxation refers to an unstable kneecap that does not slide centrally within its groove, i.e., a partial dislocation of the patella.

Name: Abnormal number of incisors
Desc: The presence of an altered number of the incisor teeth.

Name: Lack of facial subcutaneous fat
Synonyms: Lack of facial fat below the skin

Name: Abnormality of thalamus morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the thalamus.

Name: Fragile teeth
Desc: A tendency of teeth to fracture as manifested by a history of repeated fracture of the dental enamel without adequate trauma.

Name: Talipes calcaneovalgus
Desc: Talipes calcaneovalgus is a flexible foot deformity (as opposed to a rigid congenital vertical talus foot deformity) that can either present as a positional or structural foot deformity depending on severity and/or causality. The axis of calcaneovalgus deformity is in the tibiotalar joint, where the foot is positioned in extreme hyperextension. On inspection, the foot has an "up and out" appearance, with the dorsal forefoot practically touching the anterior aspect of the ankle and lower leg.

Name: Abnormal fundus fluorescein angiography
Desc: An abnormality observed by retinal fluorescein angiography, which involves the intravenous injection of fluorescein dye followed by fluorescent imaging of the fundus immediately after injection and for up to ten minutes thereafter. It can be used to study various retinal abnormalities including especially anomalies of the choroidal and retinal circulation.

Name: Female hypogonadism
Desc: Decreased functionality of the female gonads, i.e., of the ovary.

Name: Sudden loss of visual acuity
Desc: Severe loss of visual acuity within hours or days. This is characteristic of Leber hereditary optic neuropathy.

Name: Fourth cranial nerve palsy
Desc: Paralysis of the fourth cranial (trochlear) nerve manifested as weakness of the superior oblique muscle which causes vertical diplopia that is maximal when the affected eye is adducted and directed inferiorly.

Name: Internal ophthalmoplegia
Desc: Paralysis of the iris and ciliary apparatus.

Name: Impaired neutrophil chemotaxis
Desc: An impairment of the migration of neutrophils towards chemoattractants as part of the innate immune response

Name: Severe periodontitis
Desc: A severe form of periodontitis.

Name: Impaired platelet aggregation
Desc: An impairment in the rate and degree to which platelets aggregate after the addition of an agonist that stimulates platelet clumping. Platelet aggregation is measured using aggregometer to measure the optical density of platelet-rich plasma, whereby platelet aggregation causes the plasma to become more transparent.

Name: Pyoderma gangrenosum
Desc: A deep skin ulcer with a well defined border, which is usually violet or blue. The ulcer edge is often undermined (worn and damaged) and the surrounding skin is erythematous and indurated. The ulcer often starts as a small papule or collection of papules, which break down to form small ulcers with a so called cat's paw appearance. These coalesce and the central area then undergoes necrosis to form a single ulcer.

Name: Vaginitis
Desc: Inflammation of the vagina that can result from a spectrum of conditions that cause vaginal and sometimes vulvar symptoms, such as itching, burning, irritation, odor, and vaginal discharge.

Name: BCGosis
Desc: Distant, or disseminated infection with Bacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination associated with failure to contain thebacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination leading to spread of BCG to many sites in the body. The tuberculosis vaccine BCG contains live attenuated Mycobacterium bovis.

Name: Nasolacrimal sac granuloma
Desc: A mass of granulation tissue in response to chronic dacryocystitis as polypoid formations or they follow accidental injury, from probing and as a reaction to retained foreign bodies in the sac.

Name: Thymus hyperplasia
Desc: Enlargement of the thymus.

Name: Epidermal nevus
Desc: Epidermal naevi are due to an overgrowth of the epidermis and may be present at birth (50%) or develop during childhood.

Name: Viremia
Desc: The presence of virus in the blood.

Name: Diminished ability to concentrate
Desc: Being unable to focus one's attention or mental effort on a particular object or activity.

Name: Polyneuritis
Desc: Simulataneous inflammation of multiple nerves.

Name: Aplasia of the abdominal wall musculature
Desc: Absence of the abdominal musculature.

Name: Alveolar process hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the alveolar process (also known as alveolar bone).
Synonyms: Decreased size of alveolar process of jaw
Deficiency of alveolar process of jaw
Underdevelopment of alveolar process of jaw

Name: Deformed humerus
Synonyms: Deformed long bone in upper arm

Name: Abnormality of the odontoid process
Desc: Abnormality of the dens of the axis, which is also known as the odontoid process.

Name: Abnormality of limb epiphysis morphology
Desc: An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of a limb.
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of end part of limb bones
Abnormality involving the epiphyses of the limbs

Name: Abnormal placental size
Desc: A deviation from normal size of the placenta.

Name: Abnormal mandible condylar process morphology
Desc: An abnormality of a mandible condylar process.

Name: Abnormal platelet morphology
Desc: An anomaly in platelet form, ultrastructure, or intracellular organelles.

Name: Small intestinal dysmotility
Desc: Abnormal small intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.

Name: Atrophic muscularis propria
Desc: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of muscularois propria tissue that was once present. The atrophy may involve a marked vacuolar degeneration of myocytes, loss of muscle fibers and some cases a highly characteristic honeycomb fibrosis.

Name: Abnormality of the extraocular muscles
Desc: An abnormality of an extraocular muscle.

Name: Abnormality of facial musculature
Desc: An anomaly of a muscle that is innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

Name: Grayish enamel
Desc: A grey discoloration of the dental enamel.

Name: Small thenar eminence
Desc: Underdevelopment of the thenar eminence with reduced palmar soft tissue mass surrounding the base of the thumb.

Name: Narrow nasal tip
Desc: Decrease in width of the nasal tip.

Name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb. This epiphysis is located on the proximal end of the phalanx.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the end part of the outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Plantar edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on sole of the foot.

Name: Palmar edema
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the palm of the hand.

Name: Axillary pterygium
Desc: Presence of a cutaneous membrane (flap) in the armpit.

Name: Retinoschisis
Desc: Splitting of the neuroretinal layers of the retina.

Name: Orotic acid crystalluria
Desc: Formation of crystals owing to an increased concentration of orotic acid in the urine.

Name: Impaired T cell function
Desc: Abnormally reduced ability of T cells to perform their functions in cell-mediated immunity.

Name: Decreased transferrin saturation
Desc: A below normal level of saturation of serum transferrin with iron.

Name: Abnormality of mouth shape
Desc: An abnormality of the outline, configuration, or contour of the mouth.

Name: Abnormal intramembranous ossification
Desc: An anomaly in the process of intramembranous ossification by which flat bones (cranial bones of the skull, i.e., the frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal bones, and the clavicles) are formed.

Name: Unossified sacrum
Desc: Lack of ossification of the sacrum.

Name: Short iliac bones
Desc: Underdevelopment of the iliac bones.

Name: Increased serum insulin-like growth factor 1
Desc: An elevated level of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF1) in the blood circulation.

Name: Decreased thyroid-stimulating hormone level
Desc: Reduced amount of the thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), which is produced by the anterior pituitary gland and stimulates the function of the thyroid gland.

Name: Diastema
Desc: Increased space between two adjacent teeth in the same dental arch.

Name: Hyperpituitarism
Desc: Hypersecretion of one or more pituitary hormones. This can occur in conditions in which deficiency in the target organ leads to decreased hormonal feedback, or as a primary condition most usually in connection with a pituitary adenoma.

Name: Pituitary gonadotropic cell adenoma
Desc: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces gonadotropins.

Name: Pituitary thyrotropic cell adenoma
Desc: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH).

Name: Aplasia of the thymus
Desc: Absence of the thymus. This feature may be appreciated by the lack of a thymic shadow upon radiographic examination.

Name: High-frequency hearing impairment
Desc: A type of hearing impairment affecting primarily the higher frequencies of sound (3,000 to 6,000 Hz).

Name: Mouth neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the mouth.

Name: Nephrotic range proteinuria
Desc: Severely increased amount of excretion of protein in the urine, defined as 3.5 grams per day or more in adults and 40 mg per meter-squared body surface area per hour in children.

Name: Congenital fibrosis of extraocular muscles
Desc: Congenital non-progressive ophthalmoplegia with multiple extraocular muscle restrictions. Typically, there is ptosis and variable degrees of restriction of horizontal and vertical eye movements.
Synonyms: Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles

Name: Normal pressure hydrocephalus
Desc: A form of hydrocephalus characterized by enlarged cerebral ventricles and normal cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) pressure upon lumbar puncture.

Name: Agenesis of the anterior commissure
Desc: Absence of the anterior commissure.

Name: Grasp reflex
Desc: A type of primitive reflex that can be elicated when the hand of the examiner is gently inserted into the palm of the patient's hand. The palmar surface is stroked or simply touched. The flexor surfaces of the fingers may be stimulated also by the examiner's fingers. The stimulus should be in a distal direction. With a positive response, the patient grasps the examiner's hand with variable strength and continues to grasp as the examiner's hand is moved. Ability to release the grip voluntarily depends on the activity of the reflex; some patients can do so readily, while others can even be lifted off the bed, since the grasp has such power [NCBI Books:NBK395].

Name: Schizencephaly
Desc: The presence of a cleft in the cerebral cortex unilaterally or bilaterally, usually located in the frontal area.

Name: Contractures of the joints of the lower limbs
Contractures of the joints of the upper limbs
Retrocollis
Desc: A form of torticollis in which the head is drawn back, either due to a permanent contractures of neck extensor muscles, or to a spasmodic contracture.

Name: Sinoatrial block
Desc: Disturbance in the atrial activation that is caused by transient failure of impulse conduction from the sinoatrial node to the cardiac atria.

Name: Abnormal lymphocyte physiology
Desc: Any anomaly of lymphocyte function.

Name: Delayed ossification of carpal bones
Desc: Ossification of carpal bones occurs later than age-adjusted norms.

Name: Dysharmonic bone age
Desc: Different levels of maturation of different bones.

Name: Acute constipation
Desc: Constipation of sudden onset and lasting for less than three months.

Name: Renotubular dysgenesis
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by absence or poor development of proximal renal tubules.

Name: Unilateral narrow palpebral fissure
Desc: A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures on one side only.
Synonyms: Unequal size of opening between the eyelids

Name: Atretic gallbladder
Desc: Failure of formation of the lumen of the gallbladder, often associated with gallbladder hypoplasia.

Name: Dark yellow urine
Desc: An abnormal dark-yellow color of the urine.

Name: Periportal fibrosis
Desc: The presence of fibrosis affecting the interlobular stroma of liver.

Name: Bile duct proliferation
Desc: Proliferative changes of the bile ducts.

Name: 4-5 toe syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of toes four and five.

Name: Flexion contracture of digit
Desc: A bent (flexed) finger or toe joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement of joints.

Name: Calcification of the auricular cartilage
Desc: Ossification affecting the external ear cartilage.

Name: Posterior scalloping of vertebral bodies
Desc: An excessive concavity of the posterior surface of one or more vertebral bodies.

Name: Narrow nasal base
Desc: Decreased distance between the attachments of the alae nasi to the face.
Synonyms: Decreased width of base of nose

Name: Ectopic thyroid
Desc: Mislocalised thyroid gland.

Name: Increased serum iduronate sulfatase level
Desc: An increased level of iduronate-2-sulfatase activity in the blood.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the testes
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the testes.

Name: Normal interictal EEG
Desc: Lack of observable abnormal electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns in an individual with a history of seizures. About half of individuals with epilepsy show interictal epileptiform discharges upon the first investigation. The yield can be increased by repeated studies, sleep studies, or by ambulatory EEG recordings over 24 hours. Normal interictal EEG is a sign that can be useful in the differential diagnosis.

Name: Interictal epileptiform activity
Desc: Epileptiform activity refers to distinctive EEG waves or complexes distinguished from background activity found in in a proportion of human subjects with epilepsy, but which can also be found in subjects without seizures. Interictal epileptiform activity refers to such activity that occurs in the absence of a clinical or subclinical seizure.

Name: Asymmetry of the ears
Desc: An asymmetriy, i.e., difference in size, shape or position between the left and right ear.

Name: Multiple trichilemmomata
Desc: Presence of multiple trichilemmomata, a benign tumour originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.

Name: Abnormal cerebral vein morphology
Desc: An anomaly of cerebral veins.

Name: Hypoplasia of the frontal bone
Desc: Underdevelopment of the frontal bone.
Synonyms: Decreased size of bone of forehead

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the frontal sinuses
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of frontal sinus.

Name: Hemifacial atrophy
