Desc: Unilateral atrophy of facial tissues, including muscles, bones and skin.
Synonyms: Atrophy of one side of the face

Name: Increased reactive oxygen species production
Desc: An accumulation of free radical groups in the body inadequately neutralized by antioxidants, which creates a potentially unstable and damaging cellular environment linked to tissue damage.

Name: Decreased male libido
Desc: Reduced desire for sexual activity on the part of a male.

Name: Hypersexuality
Desc: Pathological persistent sexual disinhibiting behavior, directed at oneself or to others.

Name: Hypometric horizontal saccades
Desc: Saccadic undershoot of horizontal saccadic eye movements, i.e., a horizontal saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object.

Name: Hemiballismus
Desc: Hemiballismus is a rare movement disorder that is caused primarily by damage to various areas in the basal ganglia. Hemiballismus is usually characterized by involuntary flinging motions of the extremities. The movements are often violent and have wide amplitudes of motion. They are continuous and random and can involve proximal and/or distal muscles on one side of the body, while some cases even include the facial muscles. The more a patient is active, the more the movements increase. With relaxation comes a decrease in movements.

Name: Abnormal basal ganglia MRI signal intensity
Desc: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia.

Name: Abnormal delivery
Desc: An abnormality of the birth process.

Name: Abnormal paranasal sinus morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the paranasal (cranial) sinuses, which are air-filled spaces that are located within the bones of the skull and face and communicate with the nasal cavity. They comprise the maxillary sinuses, the frontal sinuses, the ethmoid sinuses, and the sphenoid sinuses.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the sinuses of the head

Name: Dense calvaria
Desc: An abnormal increase of density of the bones making up the calvaria.

Name: Advanced pneumatization of cranial sinuses
Desc: A degree of pneumatization that is increased compared to age-related norms.

Name: Rhizomelic leg shortening
Desc: Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of the leg (i.e. the femur).

Name: Deep-set nails
Desc: Deeply placed nails.

Name: Thickened Achilles tendon
Desc: An abnormal thickening of the Achilles tendon.

Name: Abnormal aggressive, impulsive or violent behavior
Synonyms: Abnormal aggressive, impulsive or violent behaviour

Name: Profound hearing impairment
Desc: A profound (essentially complete) form of hearing impairment.

Name: Small fontanelle
Desc: A fontanelle that is small for age.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of toe
Desc: Absence or hypoplasia of toes.

Name: Delayed ability to stand
Desc: A failure to achieve the ability to stand up at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children begin to walk alone at 11 to 15 months of age. On average, children can stand while holding on at the age of 9 to 10 months, can pull up to stand and walk with one hand being held at 12 months, and can stand alone and walk well at 18 months.

Name: Left ventricular outflow tract obstruction
Desc: Left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) obstruction can occur at the valvular, subvalvular, or supravalvular level. In general, there is an obstruction to forward flow which increases afterload, and if untreated, can result in hypertrophy, dilatation, and eventual failure of the left ventricle.

Name: Low-output congestive heart failure
Desc: A form of heart failure characterized by reduced cardiac output. This may be seen in patients with heart failure owing to ischemic heart disease, hypertension, cardiomyopathy, and other causes.

Name: Hemeralopia
Desc: A visual defect characterized by the inability to see as clearly in bright light as in dim light. The word hemeralopia literally means day blindness.

Name: Neurodegeneration
Desc: Progressive loss of neural cells and tissue.

Name: Glabellar reflex
Desc: A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by repetitive tapping on the forehead. Normal subjects usually blink in response to the first several taps, but if blinking persists, the response is abnormal and considered to be a sign of frontal release. Persistent blinking is also known as Myerson's sign.

Name: Punctate periventricular T2 hyperintense foci
Desc: Multiple pointlike areas of high T2 signal observed upon magnetic resonance imaging of the periventricular cerebral white matter.

Name: Abnormal glycosphingolipid metabolism
Desc: An abnormality of glycosphingolipid metabolism.

Name: Increased QRS voltage
Desc: Elevation of the voltage (height) of the QRS complex. There are several criteria in use, but the most common is the Sokolov-Lyon criterion (S wave depth in V1 + tallest R wave height in V5-V6 greater than 35 mm).

Name: Abnormal pulse pressure
Desc: An anomaly of the pulse pressure, which is defined as the systolic pressured minus the diastolic pressure.

Name: Thoracic aortic aneurysm
Desc: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the thoracic aorta.

Name: Pill-rolling tremor
Desc: A type of resting tremor characterized by simultaneous rubbing movements of thumb and index fingers against each other.

Name: Abnormal blood inorganic cation concentration
Desc: An abnormality of divalent inorganic cation homeostasis.
Synonyms: Abnormality of divalent inorganic cation homeostasis

Name: Increased total iron binding capacity
Desc: An elevation in the total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added. A high TIBC corresponds to a high transferrin concentration. The latent (or free) iron binding capacity is the difference between the TIBC and the measured serum iron, corresponding to the transferrin not bound to iron, i.e., free iron binding capacity.

Name: Copper accumulation in liver
Desc: An anomalous build up of copper (Cu) in the liver.

Name: Abnormal urine alpha-ketoglutarate concentration
Desc: A deviation from normal of the concentration of 2-oxoglutaric acid in the urine.
Synonyms: Abnormality of urine alpha ketoglutarate concentration

Name: Decreased anterioposterior diameter of lumbar vertebral bodies
Vertebral wedging
Desc: An abnormal shape of the vertebral bodies whereby the vertebral bodies are thick on one side and taper to a thin edge at the other.

Name: EMG: myokymic discharges
Desc: The presence of spontaneous bursts of rapidly firing potentials that recur at regular intervals of 2-10 per second and are unaffected by voluntary effort. This is an electromyographic (EMG) finding.

Name: Asymmetric limb muscle stiffness
Desc: Stiffness of the limbs (a condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) occurring in an asymmetric pattern.

Name: Radial deviation of finger
Desc: Bending or curvature of a finger toward the radial side (i.e., towards the thumb). The deviation is at the metacarpal-phalangeal joint, and this finding is distinct from clinodactyly.

Name: Porphyrinuria
Desc: Abnormally increased excretion of porphyrins in the urine.

Name: Bilirubinuria
Desc: Presence of conjugated bilirubin in the urine.

Name: Conjunctival icterus
Desc: Conjunctival icterus is a condition where there is yellowing of the whites of the eyes. This is most commonly seen in patients who have liver disease.
Synonyms: Yellowing of the whites of the eyes

Name: Storage in hepatocytes
Desc: Hepatocytes (liver parenchymal cells) exhibit a bloated appearance because of expansion of the cytoplasm by accumulated material.

Name: Coronary artery stenosis
Desc: Abnormal narrowing of the coronary artery.

Name: Orange discolored tonsils
Desc: A phenomenon of orange colored oral tonsils. This feature is characteristic of Tangier disease and illustrated will by Figure 1 of PMID:19470903.

Name: Carotid artery stenosis
Desc: Narrowing of the carotid arteries.

Name: Congenital bullous ichthyosiform erythroderma
Desc: An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin that presents at birth or shortly thereafter with generalized erythema, blistering, erosions, and peeling. In the subsequent months, erythema and blistering improves but patients go on to develop hyperkeratotic scaling that is especially prominent along the joint flexures, neck, hands and feet.

Name: Splenic abscess
Desc: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the parenchyma of the spleen.

Name: Unusual skin infection
Desc: A type of infection of the skin that can be regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection.

Name: Rigors
Desc: Severe chills with violent shivering. A rigor is an episode of shaking or exaggerated shivering which can occur with a high fever.

Name: Oligoarthritis
Desc: A type of arthritis that affects up to four joints in the first six months of disease.

Name: Abdominal aseptic abscess
Desc: An abscess-like lesion located within the abdomen. The lesions are localized in the spleen, liver, abdominal lymph nodes. The lesions represent visceral sterile collections of mature neutrophils that do not respond to antibiotics but regress quickly when treated with corticosteroids, but relapses occur frequently.

Name: Tendonitis
Desc: Inflammation of a tendon.

Name: Hypersarcosinemia
Desc: An elevated plasma concentration of sarcosine.

Name: Hypersarcosinuria
Desc: An elevated urinary concentration of sarcosine.

Name: Peroneal muscle weakness
Desc: Weakness of the peroneal muscles.

Name: Transient hypogammaglobulinemia of infancy
Desc: At birth, newborns are endowed with maternal antibodies. IgG production normally begins at the age of two months. A delay in recovery from this physiological hypogammaglobulinemia between the 3rd and the 6th month of life, and of recovery period between 18 and 36 months defines transient newborn hypogammaglobulinemia.

Name: Ulnar deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand
Abnormality of the hairline
Desc: The hairline refers to the outline of hair of the head. An abnormality of the hairline can refer to an unusually low or high border between areas of the scalp with and without hair or to abnormal projections of scalp hair.

Name: Fetal fifth finger clinodactyly
Desc: Fifth finger clinodactyly is defined by a hypoplastic or absent mid-phalanx of the fifth digit. Ultrasound identification of the fetal hand must first be undertaken and then appropriate magnification accomplished. The evaluation requires stretching of the 5 fingers. The diagnosis is established when the middle phalanx of the fifth finger is markedly smaller than normal or absent, which often causes the finger to be curved inward (PMID:16100637).

Name: Overfolding of the superior helices
Desc: A condition in which the superior portion of the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal.

Name: Steep acetabular roof
Desc: An exaggeration of the normal arched form of the acetabular roof such that it takes on a steep appearance.

Name: Metopic depression
Desc: Linear vertical groove in the midline of the forehead, extending from hairline to glabella.

Name: Incomplete ossification of pubis
Desc: Failure to complete ossification (maturation and calcification) of the pubic bone.
Synonyms: Incomplete maturation of the pubic bone

Name: Low alkaline phosphatase
Desc: Abnormally reduced serum levels of alkaline phosphatase.

Name: Dumbbell-shaped long bone
Desc: An abnormal appearance of the long bones with resemblance to a dumbbell, a short bar with a weight at each end. That is, the long bone is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.
Synonyms: Dumbbell widening of long bone metaphyses

Name: Advanced tarsal ossification
Desc: Precocious (accelerated) maturation and calcification of any of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.

Name: Increased fibular diameter
Desc: Increased width of the cross sectional diameter of the fibula.

Name: Dilated third ventricle
Desc: An increase in size of the third ventricle.

Name: Ovarian fibroma
Desc: The presence of a fibroma of the ovary.

Name: Mesenteric cyst
Desc: A closed fluid filled sac originating from the mesentary.

Name: Abnormal coccyx morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the coccyx.

Name: Abnormality of the incisor
Desc: An abnormality of the Incisor tooth.

Name: Contracture of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Name: Teratoma
Desc: The presence of a teratoma.

Name: Abnormality of the plantar skin of foot
Desc: An abnormality of the plantar part of foot, that is of the soles of the feet.

Name: Abnormality of joint mobility
Desc: An abnormality in the range and ease of motion of joints across their normal range.

Name: Abnormal hypothalamus morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the hypothalamus.

Name: Abnormality of masseter muscle
Desc: An abnormality of a masseter muscle.

Name: Mesiodens
Desc: A supernumerary tooth in the midline between the maxillary central incisors.

Name: Short ear
Desc: Median longitudinal ear length less than two SD above the mean determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear.

Name: Cortical diaphyseal thickening of the upper limbs
Forearm undergrowth
Desc: Forearm shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the forearm.

Name: Ulnar radial head dislocation
Desc: A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint in an ulnar direction.

Name: Episodic ketoacidosis
Desc: Intermittent episodes of ketoacidosis.

Name: Elevated brain N-acetyl aspartate level by MRS
Desc: An increase in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Synonyms: Elevated brain N-acetyl aspartate level by magnetic resonance spectroscopy

Name: Curved distal phalanges of the hand
Synonyms: Curved outermost finger bone of the hand

Name: Anteroposteriorly shortened larynx
Desc: Abnormal shortening of the larynx in the anteroposterior (front to back) axis.

Name: Hypoplasia of the pharynx
Desc: Underdevelopment of the pharynx.

Name: Abnormal proximal phalanx morphology of the hand
Synonyms: Abnormality of the innermost finger bones of the hand
Abnormality of the proximal phalanges of the hand

Name: Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
Desc: An abnormal shape or form of the proximal phalanx of the big toe.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

Name: Aplasia of the middle phalanx of the hand
Desc: Absence of one or more middle phalanx of a finger.

Name: Chess-pawn distal phalanges
Desc: A morphological abnormality of distal phalanges such that they have the appearance of chess pawns.

Name: Absence of the sacrum
Desc: Absence (aplasia) of the sacrum.

Name: Patchy palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
Desc: A focal type of palmoplantar keratoderma in which only certain areas of the palms and soles are affected.

Name: Experiential epileptic aura
Desc: Affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual auras with subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognized by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.

Name: Abnormal proerythroblast morphology
Desc: Anomalous form of the proerythroblast, i.e., the immature, nucleated erythrocyte occupying the stage of erythropoeisis that follows formation of erythroid progenitor cells. This cell is CD71-positive, has both a nucleus and a nucleolus, and lacks hematopoeitic lineage markers.

Name: Abnormality of the shoulder girdle musculature
Abnormality of acid-base homeostasis
Desc: An abnormality of the balance or maintenance of the balance of acids and bases in bodily fluids, resulting in an abnormal pH.

Name: Basal ganglia necrosis
Desc: Death of cells in the basal ganglia.

Name: Permanent atrial fibrillation
Desc: AF that cannot be successfully terminated by cardioversion, and longstanding (more than 1 year) AF, where cardioversion is not indicated or has not been attempted, is termed permanent.

Name: Euphoria
Desc: A sense of intense joy or happiness that is beyond what would be expected under the given circumstances.

Name: Elevated serum anion gap
Desc: An abnormally high value of the serum anion gap (the sum of serum chloride and bicarbonate concentrations subtracted from the serum sodium concentration).

Name: Membranous subvalvular aortic stenosis
Desc: Subvalvular stenosis is caused by a diaphragm-like membrane. The stenosis is clinically manifested like any other form of aortic stenosis but is often associated with some aortic insufficiency.

Name: Unilateral polymicrogyria
Desc: Excessive number of small gyri (convolutions) on the surface of one side of the brain.

Name: Hyperextensibility at elbow
Desc: The ability of the elbow joint to move beyond its normal range of motion.

Name: Dilatation of renal calices
Desc: An abnormal enlargement of the renal calices, the system of ducts of the kidney that collect urine.

Name: Congenital, generalized hypertrichosis
Desc: A confluent, generalized overgrowth of silvery blonde to gray lanugo hair at birth.

Name: Fractures of the long bones
Desc: An increased tendency to fractures of the long bones (Mainly, the femur, tibia, fibula, humerus, radius, and ulna).

Name: Wide humerus
Synonyms: Wide long bone of upper arm

Name: Onychauxis
Desc: Thickened nails without deformity.

Name: Hyperconvex toenail
Desc: When viewed on end (with the tip of the toe pointing toward the examiner's eye) the curve of the toenail forms a tighter curve of convexity.

Name: Abnormality of the lymph nodes
Desc: A lymph node abnormality.

Name: Papillary renal cell carcinoma
Desc: The presence of renal cell carcinoma in the renal papilla.

Name: Abnormality of neck blood vessel
Desc: An abnormality of a blood vessel of the neck, including branches of the arterial and venous systems of the neck.
Synonyms: Abnormality of blood vessel of neck
Abnormality of the cervical blood vessels
Abnormality of the vasculature of the neck

Name: Subsarcolemmal accumulations of abnormally shaped mitochondria
Desc: An abnormally increased number of mitochondria in the cytoplasma adjacent to the sarcolemma (muscle cell membrane), whereby the mitochondria also possess an abnormal morphology.

Name: Elevated CSF neopterin level
Desc: Increased concentration of neopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Name: Bilateral breast hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the breast on both sides.

Name: Agoraphobia
Desc: A type of anxiety disorder characterized by avoidance of public places, especially where crowds gather.

Name: Paraspinal muscle hypertrophy
Desc: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the paraspinal muscles.

Name: Reduced glutathione synthetase level
Desc: Reduced level of the enzyme glutathione synthetase, which catalyzes the last step in the synthesis of glutathione and a deficiency results in low levels of glutathione. Acidosis is due to reduced feedback inhibition of gamma-glutamyl cysteine synthetase in the gamma-glutamyl cycle, which ultimately leads to overproduction and accumulation of 5-oxoproline.

Name: Abnormality of circulating cortisol level
Desc: An abnormality of the concentration of cortisol in the blood.

Name: Abnormal urine sodium concentration
Desc: An abnormal concentration of sodium in the urine.

Name: Schistocytosis
Desc: The presence of an abnormal number of fragmented red blood cells (schistocytes) in the blood.

Name: Abnormal blood potassium concentration
Desc: An abnormal concentration of potassium.

Name: Episodic fatigue
Desc: Intermittent and recurrent bouts of a subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation.

Name: Increased hemoglobin concentration
Desc: An abnormal elevation above normal hemoglobin concentration in the circulation.

Name: Increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration
Desc: An elevation over the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell).

Name: Portal vein thrombosis
Desc: Thrombosis of the portal vein and/or its tributaries, which include the splenic vein and the superior and inferior mesenteric veins.

Name: Pulmonary venous hypertension
Desc: An abnormal increase in pressure in the pulmonary veins, usually as a result of left atrial hypertension.

Name: Abnormal mean corpuscular volume
Desc: A deviation from normal of the mean corpuscular volume, or mean cell volume (MCV) of red blood cells, usually taken to be 80 to 100 femtoliters.

Name: Onion bulb formation
Desc: Repeated episodes of segmental demyelination and remyelination lead to the accumulation of supernumerary Schwann cells around axons, which is referred to as onion bulb formation. This finding affects peripheral nerves.

Name: Periventricular white matter hyperdensities
Desc: Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.

Name: Reduced sperm motility
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the mobility of ejaculated sperm.

Name: Abnormal sperm head morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the sperm head.

Name: Abnormal tendon morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the structure or form of the tendons, also often called sinews.

Name: Abnormal auditory evoked potentials
Desc: An abnormality of the auditory evoked potentials, which are used to trace the signal generated by a sound, from the cochlear nerve, through the lateral lemniscus, to the medial geniculate nucleus, and to the cortex.

Name: Abnormal motor evoked potentials
Desc: An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs). MEPs are measured following single-pulse or repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation and can be used for the assessment of the excitability of the motor cortex and the integrity of conduction along the central and peripheral motor pathways.

Name: Thickened cortex of long bones
Desc: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of long bones.
Synonyms: Cortical thickening of the long bones

Name: Absent patellar reflexes
Desc: Absence of the knee jerk reflex, which can normally be elicited by tapping the patellar tendon with a reflex hammer just below the patella.

Name: Noncompaction cardiomyopathy
Desc: A type of cardiomyopathy characterized anatomically by deep trabeculations in the ventricular wall, which define recesses communicating with the main ventricular chamber.

Name: Pelvic bone exostoses
Desc: A benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface of the pelvis. Exostoses are capped by cartilage, and arise from a bone that develops from cartilage.

Name: Anterior synechiae of the anterior chamber
Desc: Adhesions between the iris and the cornea.

Name: Abnormality of femoral epiphysis
Desc: An anomaly of a growth plate of a femur.

Name: Abnormality of the stapes
Desc: An abnormality of the stapes, a stirrup-shaped ossicle in the middle ear.

Name: Cochlear degeneration
Desc: Deterioration or loss of the tissues of the cochlea.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle ear
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the middle ear.

Name: Angiokeratoma
Desc: A vascular lesion defined histologically as one or more dilated blood vessels lying directly subepidermal and showing an epidermal proliferative reaction. Clinically, angiokeratoma presents as a small, raised, dark-red spot.

Name: Absent brainstem auditory responses
Desc: Lack of measurable response to stimulation of auditory evoked potentials.

Name: Vestibular areflexia
Desc: Vestibular areflexia can be measured as the absence of the caloric nystagmus response in electronystagmography.

Name: Temporal hypotrichosis
Desc: Reduced or lacking hair growth in the temporal region (i.e., around the temples on the side of the skull).
Synonyms: Reduced hair growth in temporal region

Name: Abnormality of ocular abduction
Desc: An abnormality involving the movement of the eye outwards.

Name: Lafora bodies
Desc: An intraneuronal inclusion body composed of acid mucopolysaccharides.

Name: Abnormal serum interleukin level
Desc: An abnormal amount of any of the interleukins, a class of cytokines, in the circulation.

Name: Predominantly dermal neutrophilic infiltrate
Desc: Collection of neutrophils in the dermis.

Name: Small vessel vasculitis
Desc: A type of vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessel walls) that affects blood vessels that are smaller than arteries, i.e., arterioles, venules, and capilllaries.

Name: Sterile abscess
Desc: An abscess not caused by infection with pyogenic bacteria. Operationally, a sterile abscess is inferred if investigations of an abscess fail to reveal evidence of pathogenic organisms.

Name: Non-periodic recurrent fever
Desc: Episodic fever that recurs at irregular intervals.

Name: Abnormal drug response
Desc: An anomlous response to a medication related to individual variation in metabolic or immune response to drugs varying from potentially from potentially life-threatening adverse drug reactions to alteration of therapeutic efficacy.

Name: Acne inversa
Desc: A chronic skin condition involving the inflammation of the apocrine sweat glands, forming pimple-like bumps known as abscesses.

Name: Chronic lymphatic leukemia
Desc: A chronic lymphocytic/lymphatic/lymphoblastic leukemia (CLL) is a neoplastic disease characterized by proliferation and accumulation (blood, marrow and lymphoid organs) of morphologically mature but immunologically dysfunctional lymphocytes. A CLL is always a B-cell lymphocytic leukemia as there are no reports of cases of T-cell lymphocytic leukemias.

Name: Metopic synostosis
Desc: Premature fusion of the metopic suture.

Name: Ocular anterior segment dysgenesis
Desc: Abnormal development (dysgenesis) of the anterior segment of the eye globe. These structures are mainly of mesenchymal origin.

Name: Distal sensory impairment of all modalities
Synonyms: Distal sensory loss to all modalities

Name: Percussion-induced rapid rolling muscle contractions
Desc: Mechanical percussion (i.e., striking a muscle with a reflex hammer) leads to spreading waves of muscle contractions that begin proximally and spread laterally across the muscle.

Name: Exercise-induced leg cramps
Desc: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles of the leg brought on by physical exertion.

Name: Weakness of long finger extensor muscles
Short third metatarsal
Desc: Underdevelopment of the Third metatarsal bone leading to a short (hypoplastic) third metatarsal bone.

Name: Unilateral vocal cord paralysis
Desc: A loss of the ability to move the vocal fold on one side.
Synonyms: Unilateral paralysis of the vocal cord

Name: Flexion contracture of the 2nd finger
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion in the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly of the 2nd finger is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

Name: Duplication of phalanx of hallux
Desc: Partial or complete duplication of one or more phalanx of big toe.
Synonyms: Duplication of phalanx of big toe
Partial/complete duplication of the phalanges of the hallux

Name: Duplication of distal phalanx of toe
Desc: A partial or complete duplication of one or more distal phalanx of toe.
Synonyms: Duplication of outermost bone of toe
Partial/complete duplication of the distal phalanges of the toes

Name: Small scrotum
Desc: Apparently small scrotum for age.

Name: Frog-leg posture
Desc: A type of rest posture in an infant that indicated a generalized reduction in muscle tone. The hips are flexed and the legs are abducted to an extent that causes the lateral thigh to rest upon the supporting surface. This posture is said to resemble the legs of a frog.

Name: Symphalangism of the 4th finger
Desc: Fusion of two or more bones of the 4th finger.

Name: Symphalangism of the 5th finger
Desc: Fusion of two or more bones of the 5th finger.

Name: Absent distal phalanges
Desc: Aplasia (absence) of the distal phalanges.

Name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the toes
Abnormality of the distal phalanges of the toes
Synonyms: Abnormality of the outermost bone of the toes

Name: Cutaneous syndactyly between fingers 2 and 5
Desc: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the second to the fifth fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

Name: Short distal phalanx of hallux
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the distal phalanx of big toe.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/small distal phalanx of the hallux
Small distal phalanx of big toe
Small outermost bone of big toe

Name: Intermittent episodes of respiratory insufficiency due to muscle weakness
Limited neck flexion
Desc: Reduced abilty to lower the chin towards the chest by bending the neck.

Name: Diminished motivation
Desc: A reduction in goal-directed behavior, that is, motivation, the determinant of behavior and adaptation that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action.

Name: Stiff interphalangeal joints
Desc: Interphalangeal joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in the interphalangeal joints when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity.

Name: Bursitis
Desc: Inflammation of a synovial bursa.

Name: Ankle joint effusion
Desc: Abnormal accumulation of fluid in or around the ankle joint.

Name: Neuritis
Desc: Inflammation of a nerve.

Name: Reduced antithrombin III activity
Desc: An abnormality of coagulation related to a decreased concentration of antithrombin-III.

Name: Palmoplantar pustulosis
Desc: A chronic, relapsing, pustular eruption that is localized to the palms and soles.

Name: Abnormal umbilical stump bleeding
Desc: Abnormal bleeding of the umbilical stump following separation of the cord at approximately 7-10 days after birth.

Name: Excessive bleeding from superficial cuts
Desc: An abnormally increased degree of bleeding following a superfical injury to the surface of the skin.

Name: Reduced prothrombin antigen
Desc: Reduced prothrombin antigen as measured by ELISA assay. Prothrombin is a vitamin K-dependent coagulation factor that is proteolytically cleaved to form thrombin.

Name: Metacarpophalangeal synostosis
Desc: Fusion of a metacarpal bone with the proximal phalanx of the finger distal to it across the corresponding metacarpophalangeal joint.
Synonyms: Fused long bone of hand with innermost finger bone

Name: Urethrovaginal fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula between the vagina and the urethra.

Name: Abnormal vas deferens morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the secretory duct of the testicle that carries spermatozoa from the epididymis to the prostatic urethra where it terminates to form ejaculatory duct.

Name: Hyperpigmented genitalia
Desc: Localized or generalized increased genital pigmentation.

Name: Myocardial eosinophilic infiltration
Desc: An increase in the number of eosinophils in myocardial tissue.

Name: Thromboembolic stroke
Desc: A cerebrovascular accident (stroke) that occurs because of thromboembolism.

Name: Portal fibrosis
Desc: Fibroblast proliferation and fiber expansion from the portal areas to the lobule.

Name: Elevated proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative, alpha-beta regulatory T cells
Desc: An abnormally increased proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative (double negative or DN) alpha-beta regulatory T cells (Tregs) as compared to total number of T cells.
Synonyms: Increased number of CD4-/CD8- T cells expressing alpha/beta T-cell receptors

Name: Increased B cell count
Desc: An abnormal increase from the normal count of B cells.

Name: Decreased specific anti-polysaccharide antibody level
Desc: The presence of normal overall immunoglobulin levels with deficiency of specific immunoglobulins directed against bacterial polysaccharides.
Synonyms: Depressed antibody response to polysaccharide antigens

Name: Coombs-positive hemolytic anemia
Desc: A type of hemolytic anemia in which the Coombs test is positive.

Name: T-cell lymphoma
Desc: A type of lymphoma that originates in T-cells.

Name: B-cell lymphoma
Desc: A type of lymphoma that originates in B-cells.

Name: Non-Hodgkin lymphoma
Desc: A type of lymphoma characterized microscopically by the absence of multinucleated Reed-Sternberg cells.

Name: Burkitt lymphoma
Desc: A form of undifferentiated malignant lymphoma commonly manifested as a large osteolytic lesion in the jaw or as an abdominal mass.

Name: Abnormality of the musculature of the upper arm
Wrist pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the wrist.

Name: Abnormality of the umbilical cord
Desc: An abnormality of the umbilical cord, which is the cord connecting the developing embryo or fetus to the placenta.

Name: Reduced factor X activity
Desc: Reduced activity of coagulation factor X. The extrinsic and intrinsic pathways converge at factor X (fX). The extrinsic pathway activates fX by means of d factor VII with its cofactor, tissue factor. The intrinsic pathway activates fX by means of the tenase complex (Ca2+ and factors VIIIa, IXa and X) on the surface of activated platelets. Factor Xa in turn activates prothrombin (factor II) to thrombin (factor IIa).

Name: Antepartum hemorrhage
Desc: Significant maternal hemorrhage/bleed in the second half of pregnancy and prior to the birth of the baby.

Name: Hemoperitoneum
Desc: Accumulation of blood in the peritoneal cavity owing to internal hemorrhage.

Name: Reduced factor XI activity
Desc: Decreased activity of coagulation factor XI. Factor XI, also known as plasma thromboplastin antecedent, is a serine proteinase that activates factor IX.

Name: Absent smooth pursuit
Desc: A complete lack of the ability to track objects with the ocular smooth pursuit system, a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion.

Name: Abnormal neuron morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of a neuron.

Name: Swan neck-like deformities of the fingers
Desc: A swan neck deformity describes a finger with a hyperextended PIP joint and a flexed DIP joint. The most common cause for a swan neck-like deformity is a disruption of the end of the extensor tendon. Conditions that loosen the PIP joint and allow it to hyperextend, for example conditions that weaken the volar plate, can produce a swan neck deformity of the finger. One example is rheumatoid arthritis. Another cause are conditions that tighten up the small (intrinsic) muscles of the hand and fingers, for example hand trauma or nerve disorders, such as cerebral palsy, Parkinson's disease, or stroke.

Name: Limb-girdle muscle atrophy
Desc: Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles of the limb girdle.

Name: Abnormality of the spinocerebellar tracts
Desc: An abnormality of the spinocerebellar tracts, a set of axonal fibers originating in the spinal cord and terminating in the ipsilateral cerebellum. The spinocerebellar tract convey information to the cerebellum about limb and joint position (proprioception). They comprise the ventral spinocerebellar tract, the anterior spinocerebellar tract, and the posterior spinocerebellar tract.

Name: Craniofacial dystonia
Desc: A form of focal dystonia affecting the face and especially the jaw that is induced by the act of speaking. It is an involuntary contraction of the masticatory muscles, resulting in dysarthria or dysphagia.

Name: Increased spinal bone density
Desc: Increased bone density affecting the bones of the spine (vertebral column).

Name: Risus sardonicus
Desc: Fixed sarcastic grimace and anxious expression. Caused by spasms of the masseter and other facial muscles.

Name: Humoral immunodeficiency
Desc: A general term referring to a defect in immunity resulting from impaired antibody production.

Name: Mesangial hypercellularity
Desc: Increased numbers of mesangial cells per glomerulus, defined as more than 3 nuclei fully surrounded by matrix in one or more mesangial areas, not including perihilar region, on a standard 3-micron-thick tissue section, best evaluated on periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) stain.

Name: Glomerular extracapillary hypercellularity
Desc: Hypercellularity (increased number of cells) in the renal glomerulus but external to the glomerular capillaries, i.e., in the Bowman space or more than one layer of parietal or visceral epithelial cells.

Name: C3 nephritic factor positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against C3 convertase (C3bBb).

Name: Drusen
Desc: Drusen (singular, 'druse') are tiny yellow or white accumulations of extracellular material (lipofuscin) that build up in Bruch's membrane of the eye.

Name: Central serous chorioretinopathy
Desc: An anomaly of the retina with serous detachment of the neurosensory retina secondary to one or more focal lesions of the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE), and associated with blurred vision, usually in one eye only and perceived typically by the patient as a dark spot in the centre of the visual field with associated micropsia and metamorphopsia. Normal vision often recurs spontaneously within a few months.

Name: Anemic pallor
Desc: A type of pallor that is secondary to the presence of anemia.

Name: Imbalanced hemoglobin synthesis
Desc: Normal hemoglobin synthesis is characterized by production of equal amounts of alpha and beta globins. This term refers to a deviation from this pattern and is the main characteristic of the various forms of thalassemia.

Name: Decreased circulating osteocalcin level
Desc: A reduced level of osteocalcin in the blood.

Name: Abnormal muscle fiber protein expression
Desc: An anomalous amount of protein present in or on the surface of muscle fibers. This feature may be appreciate upon immunohistochemical investigation of muscle biopsy tissue.

Name: Late onset atopic dermatitis
Desc: A form of atopic dermatitis with onset in adulthood characterized by atopic red face, chronic lichenified eczema on the trunk, subacute or psoriasiform dermatitis.

Name: Actinic keratosis
Desc: A scaly, crusty lesion caused by damage from the ultraviolet radiation of the sun, with typical location on sun-exposed areas of the skin. Actinic keratosis lesions are often elevated, rough, and wartlike, and may be red, or occasionally tan, pink, or flesh-toned in color.

Name: Tetraamelia
Desc: Amelia of all four limbs.

Name: Hypoplastic nasal tip
Synonyms: Decreased size of tip of nose

Name: Severe receptive language delay
Desc: A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

Name: Focal hemiclonic seizure
Desc: A type of focal clonic seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking rapidly involves one side of the body at seizure onset.

Name: Multifocal epileptiform discharges
Desc: An abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG) and being identified at multiple locations (foci).

Name: Epilepsia partialis continua
Desc: Epilepsia partialis continua (also called Kojevnikov's or Kozhevnikov's epilepsia) is a type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by repeated stereotyped simple motor manifestations such as jerks, typically of a limb or the face, recurring every few seconds or minutes for extended periods (days or years).

Name: Status epilepticus without prominent motor symptoms
Desc: There is inconclusive evidence to precisely define the duration of the seizure; however, based on current evidence an operational threshold of 10 minutes is appropriate as beyond this a seizure is likely to be more prolonged. The individual may or may not be aware or in coma.

Name: Tibial torsion
Desc: Tibial torsion is inward twisting (medial rotation) (PATO:0002155) of the tibia.

Name: Reduced factor XIII activity
Desc: Decreased activity of coagulation factor XIII (also known as fibrin stabilizing factor). Activated Factor XIII cross-links fibrin polymers solidifying the clot.

Name: Umbilical cord hematoma
Desc: Bleeding from the vessels of the cord with extravasation of blood into the Wharton jelly surrounding the umbilical cord vessels.

Name: Delayed onset bleeding
Desc: Abnormal bleeding related to a procedure or trauma which does not start at the time of the initial insult, but after delay by at least 24 hours.

Name: Recurrent spontaneous abortion
Desc: Repeated episodes of abortion (Expulsion of the product of fertilization before completing the term of gestation) without deliberate interference.

Name: Myeloid leukemia
Desc: A leukemia that originates from a myeloid cell, that is the blood forming cells of the bone marrow.

Name: Glue ear
Desc: Middle ear is filled with glue-like fluid instead of air.

Name: Juxtaductal coarctation of the aorta
Desc: Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized at the insertion of the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the juxtaductal region of aortic arch.

Name: Agammaglobulinemia
Desc: A lasting absence of total IgG and total IgA and total IgM in the blood circulation, whereby at most trace quantities can be measured.

Name: Recurrent enteroviral infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to enteroviral infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of enteroviral infection.

Name: Reduced antigen-specific T cell proliferation
Desc: Impaired proliferation and expansion of a T cell population following activation by an antigenic stimulus.

Name: Abnormal natural killer cell count
Desc: Any deviation from the normal overall count of natural killer (NK) cells in the circulation or a deviation from the normal distribution of NK cell subtypes.
Synonyms: Abnormal number of natural killer cells
Abnormality of natural killer cell count

Name: Increased megakaryocyte count
Desc: Increased megakaryocyte number, i.e., of platelet precursor cells, present in the bone marrow.

Name: Axial malrotation of the kidney
Desc: An abnormality of the normal developmental rotation of the kidney leading to an abnormal axial orientation of the kidney.

Name: Mesenteric venous thrombosis
Desc: A clot that obstructs blood flow in a mesenteric vein (the superior and the inferior mesenteric vein drain blood from the small and large intestine).

Name: Abnormality of the musculature of the limbs
Synonyms: Muscle issues in the arms and/or legs

Name: Euthyroid goiter
Desc: A goiter that is not associated with functional thyroid abnormalities.

Name: Neoplasm by anatomical site
Desc: Neoplasm categorized according to the anatomical site of origin of the neoplasm.

Name: Foam cells in visceral organs and CNS
Abnormal conjunctiva morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the conjunctiva.

Name: Abnormal larynx morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of the structure of the larynx.

Name: Split nail
Desc: A nail plate that has a longitudinal separation and the two sections of the nail share the same lateral radius of curvature.

Name: Low-set nipples
Desc: Placement of the nipples at a lower than normal location.

Name: Defective DNA repair after ultraviolet radiation damage
Recurrent bronchopulmonary infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to bronchopulmonary infections as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchopulmonary infections.
Synonyms: Recurrent infections in bronchi and lungs

Name: Paraplegia/paraparesis
Desc: Weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities. Paraplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas paraparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.

Name: Impaired social reciprocity
Desc: A reduced ability to participate in the back and forth flow of social interaction, which is normally characterized by an influence of the behavior of one person on the behavior of another person who is in conversation with the first.

Name: Tiger tail banding
Desc: An abnormal appearance of hair under polarizing microscopy (using crossed polarizers), whereby hair shafts show striking alternating bright and dark bands, often referred to as tiger tail banding.

Name: Hypoplasia of mandible relative to maxilla
Desc: Abnormally small dimension of the mandible (lower jaw) relative to the maxilla (upper jaw).
Synonyms: Disorder of mandibular and maxillary dental arch relationship

Name: Abnormal carotid artery morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the carotid arteries, including the common carotid artery and its' arterial branches.

Name: Keratoglobus
Desc: Limbus-to-limbus corneal thinning, often greatest in the periphery, with globular protrusion of the cornea.

Name: Fibular bowing
Desc: A bending or abnormal curvature of the fibula.

Name: Tracheobronchmegaly
Desc: Marked widening of the trachea and major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.

Name: Projectile vomiting
Desc: Vomiting that ejects the gastric contents with great force.

Name: Abnormality of the anterior fontanelle
Desc: An abnormality of the anterior fontanelle, i.e., the cranial fontanelle that is located at the intersection of the coronal and sagittal sutures.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the forehead soft spot

Name: Acute disseminated intravascular coagulation
Desc: An acute form of disseminated intravascular coagulation. Acute DIC can occur following sudden exposure of blood to procoagulants, with the compensatory hemostatic mechanisms becoming overwhelmed.

Name: Abnormality of the subungual region
Desc: A lesion located beneath a fingernail or toenail.

Name: Splenic rupture
Desc: A breach of the capsule of the spleen.

Name: Hemorrhagic ovarian cyst
Desc: An abdominal mass formed by bleeding into a follicular ovarian cyst or corpus luteum cyst.

Name: Anaphylactic shock
Desc: An acute hypersensitivity reaction due to exposure to a previously encountered antigen.

Name: Abnormality of the mastoid
Desc: An abnormality of the mastoid process, which is the conical prominence projecting from the undersurface of the mastoid portion of the temporal bone.
Synonyms: Abnormality of mastoid process of temporal bone

Name: Enamel hypomineralization
Desc: A decreased amount of enamel mineralization. Hypomineralized enamel has a brown discoloration and brittle aspect.
Synonyms: White spot lesions of tooth enamel

Name: Obliteration of the calvarial diploe
Desc: Absence of the spongy bone structure (or tissue) of the internal part of the skull cap (i.e., of the calvarial diploe).

Name: Periapical tooth abscess
Desc: A tooth abscess that occurs at the tip of the root (apex) of a tooth.

Name: Agenesis of incisor
Desc: Agenesis of incisor.

Name: Abnormality of the first metatarsal bone
Desc: An anomaly of the first metatarsal bone.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the 1st long bone of foot

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the hallux
Ectopic ossification in ligament tissue
Desc: Formation of abnormal bony tissue within ligament tissue.

Name: Midline facial cleft
Desc: A congenital malformation with a cleft (gap or opening) in the midline of the face.

Name: Accessory spleen
Desc: An accessory spleen is a round, iso-echogenic, homogenic and smooth structure and is seen as a normal variant mostly on the medial contour of the spleen, near the hilus or around the lower pole. This has no pathogenic relevance.

Name: Abnormality of renin-angiotensin system
Desc: An abnormality of the renin-angiotensin system.

Name: Second degree atrioventricular block
Desc: An intermittent atrioventricular block with failure of some atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles, i.e., some but not all atrial impulses are conducted through the atrioventricular node and trigger ventricular contraction.

Name: Abnormal growth hormone level
Desc: Any deviation from the normal level of growth hormone (GH) in the blood circulation. GH or somatotropin is a peptide hormone that stimulates growth, cell reproduction, and cell regeneration. Its secretion from the pituitary is regulated by the neurosecretory nuclei of the hypothalamus, which can release Growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH or somatocrinin) and Growth hormone-inhibiting hormone (GHIH or somatostatin) into the hypophyseal portal venous blood surrounding the pituitary. GH is secreted in a pulsatile manner, which is one of the reasons why an isolated measurement of its blood concentration is not meaningful.

Name: Abnormal nasopharyngeal adenoid morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of nasopharyngeal adenoids.

Name: Abnormal tubulointerstitial morphology
Desc: An abnormality that involves the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney.

Name: Subconjunctival hemorrhage
Desc: Bleeding beneath the mucous membrane that lines the inner surface of the eyelid.

Name: Aorto-ventricular tunnel
Desc: Aorto-ventricular tunnel is a congenital, extracardiac channel which connects the ascending aorta above the sinutubular junction to the cavity of the left, or (less commonly) right ventricle.

Name: Abnormal coronary artery morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of the coronary arteries.

Name: Potter facies
Desc: A facial appearance characteristic of a fetus or neonate due to oligohydramnios experienced in the womb, comprising ocular hypertelorism, low-set ears, receding chin, and flattening of the nose.

Name: Enlarged labia minora
Desc: Increase in size of the folds of skin between the outer labia.

Name: Long upper lip
Desc: Increased width of the upper lip.
Synonyms: Increased vertical length of upper lip

Name: Abnormal forearm bone morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of of forearm bone

Name: Premature epimetaphyseal fusion
Desc: Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at each end of a long bone, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.

Name: Recurrent bronchiolitis
Desc: An increased susceptibility to bronchiolitis as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchiolitis.

Name: Abnormality of the uterine cervix
Desc: An anomaly of the neck of the uterus (lower part of the uterus), called the uterine cervix.

Name: Hydrocolpos
Desc: Distention of the vagina caused by accumulation of fluid due to congenital vaginal obstruction.

Name: Unfavorable response of muscle weakness to acetylcholine esterase inhibitors
Desc: Lack of improvement of muscle strength in response to administration of an acetylcholine esterase inhibitor.
Synonyms: Unfavourable response of muscle weakness to acetylcholine esterase inhibitors

Name: Hypermobility of interphalangeal joints
Desc: The ability of the interphalangeal joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

Name: Wide nasal ridge
Desc: Increased width of the nasal ridge.
Synonyms: Increased width of dorsum of nose

Name: Poliosis
Desc: Circumscribed depigmentation of the hair of the head or the eyelashes.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the colon
Desc: Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the colon.

Name: Reduced muscle fiber merosin
Desc: A reduced amount of merosin in muscle fibers. This feature is usually assessed by immunohistochemical examination of muscle biopsy tissue.

Name: Myofibrillar myopathy
Desc: Myofibrillar structural changes characterized by abnormal intracellular accumulation of the intermediate filament desmin and other proteins.

Name: Skeletal muscle fibrosis
Desc: Excessive formation of fibrous bands of scar tissue in between muscle fibers.

Name: Percussion myotonia
Desc: A localized myotonic contraction in a muscle in reaction to percussion (tapping with the examiner's finger, a rubber percussion hammer, or a similar object).
Synonyms: Transient swelling of muscle induced by percussion

Name: Loss of facial adipose tissue
Desc: Loss of normal subcutaneous fat tissue in the face.
Synonyms: Decreased amount of facial adipose tissue
Decreased volume of facial adipose tissue
Loss of facial subcutaneous adipose tissue
Loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue from face

Name: Thin long bone diaphyses
Desc: Decreased width of the diaphysis of long bones.

Name: Caesarian section
Desc: Delivery of a fetus through surgical incisions made through the abdominal wall (laparotomy) and the uterine wall (hysterotomy).

Name: Cervical vertebral dysplasia
Desc: Dysplasia of the cervical vertebral column.

Name: Wide penis
Desc: Distance between left and right side of the flaccid penis at the attachment to the skin above the pubic symphysis more than 2 standard deviations above the mean for age.

Name: Lagopthalmos
Desc: A condition in which the eyelids do not close to cover the eye completely.

Name: Hypoplasia of the fallopian tube
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.

Name: Decreased urinary urate
Desc: Decreased concentration of urate in the urine.

Name: Uric acid nephrolithiasis
Desc: The presence of uric acid-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

Name: Xanthine nephrolithiasis
Desc: The presence of xanthine-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

Name: Aldehyde oxidase deficiency
Desc: A reduction in aldehyde oxidase level.

Name: Reduced xanthine dehydrogenase level
Desc: An abnormal reduction in xanthine dehydrogenase level.

Name: Sulfite oxidase deficiency
Desc: Abnormally reduced sulfite oxidase level.

Name: Hyperxanthinemia
Desc: An increased level of xanthine in the blood circulation.

Name: Xanthinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of xanthine in the urine.

Name: Increased urinary hypoxanthine
Desc: An increased level of hypoxanthine in the urine.

Name: Crystalluria
Desc: The presence of crystals in the urine.

Name: Gout
Desc: Recurrent attacks of acute inflammatory arthritis of a joint or set of joints caused by elevated levels of uric acid in the blood which crystallize and are deposited in joints, tendons, and surrounding tissues.

Name: Obstructive azoospermia
Desc: Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, resulting from post-testicular obstruction or retrograde ejaculation. This can be differentiated from obstructive azoospermia on the basis of testicular biopsy.

Name: Aplasia of the distal phalanges of the hand
Synonyms: Absent distal phalanges of the hand

Name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the hallux
Synonyms: Absent outermost bone of big toe

Name: Short proximal phalanx of hallux
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the proximal phalanx of big toe.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic proximal phalanx of the hallux
Small proximal phalanx of big toe

Name: Absent sternal ossification
Desc: Lack of formation of mineralized bony tissue of the sternum.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the 1st metatarsal
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the first metatarsal bone.

Name: Abnormality of dental structure
Desc: An abnormality of the structure or composition of the teeth.

Name: Abnormal occipital bone morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the occipital bone of the skull.

Name: Gingival recession
Desc: The loss of gum tissue. The result is that gum tissue is recessed and its position on the tooth is lowered, exposing the roots of the teeth.

Name: Anterior open-bite malocclusion
Desc: Anterior open bite is a malocclusion characterized by a gap between the anterior teeth (incisors), that is, by a deficiency in the normal vertical overlap between antagonist incisal edges when the posterior teeth are in occlusion.
Synonyms: Absence of overlap of anterior upper and lower teeth
Anterior open bite between upper and lower teeth
Gap between upper and lower front teeth when biting

Name: Thickened ears
Desc: Increased thickness of the external ear.

Name: Overtubulated long bones
Desc: Overconstriction, or narrowness of the diaphysis and metaphysis of long bones.

Name: Intermittent lactic acidemia
Desc: An intermittent (discontinuous) form of lactic acidemia.

Name: Intermittent hyperventilation
Desc: Episodic hyperventilation.

Name: Anterior beaking of lumbar vertebrae
Desc: Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies of the lumbar spine.
Synonyms: Anterior tongue-like protrusion of lumbar vertebral bodies

Name: Organic aciduria
Desc: Excretion of non-amino organic acids in urine.

Name: Propionyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency
Desc: An abnormality of amino acid metabolism characterized by a decreased level of propionyl-CoA carboxylase.

Name: Impaired lymphocyte transformation with phytohemagglutinin
Desc: Normal peripheral blood lymphocytes, when stimulated by phytohemagglutinin (PHA) are cytotoxic for homologous and heterologous cells but not for autologous cells in monolayer culture. The cytotoxic effect is thought to be indicative of the immunological competence of the lymphocytes.

Name: Absent natural killer cells
Desc: Lack of natural killer cells, a type of lymphocyte in the innate immune system that contains cytoplasmic granzymes, i.e., small granules with perforin and proteases that allow natural killer cells to form pores in the cell membrane of the target cell through which the granzymes and associated molecules can enter, inducing apoptosis.

Name: Acute otitis media
Desc: Acute otitis media is a short and generally painful infection of the middle ear.

Name: Partial IgA deficiency
Desc: Detectable but decreased IgA levels that are more than 2 standard deviations below normal age-adjusted means.

Name: Congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma
Desc: An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin with congenital onset.

Name: Exercise-induced myoglobinuria
Desc: Presence of myoglobin in the urine following exercise.

Name: EEG with focal spike waves
Desc: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: Periventricular nodular heterotopia
Desc: Nodules of heterotopia along the ventricular walls. There can be a single nodule or a large number of nodules, they can exist on either or both sides of the brain at any point along the higher ventricle margins, they can be small or large, single or multiple.

Name: Lambdoidal craniosynostosis
Desc: A kind of craniosynostosis affecting the lambdoidal suture.

Name: Abnormality of primary teeth
Desc: Any abnormality of the primary tooth.

Name: Iris transillumination defect
Desc: Transmission of light through the iris as visualized upon slit lamp examination or infrared iris transillumination videography. The light passes through defects in the pigmentation of the iris.

Name: Optic nerve misrouting
Desc: Abnormal decussation of the visual pathways, typically identified using visual evoked potentials (VEP) (asymmetrical distribution of the VEP over the posterior scalp).

Name: Abnormal morphology of the choroidal vasculature
EMG: positive sharp waves
Desc: These are spontaneous firing action potentials stimulated by needle movement of an injured muscle fiber. There is propagation to, but not past, the needle tip. This inhibits the display of the negative deflection of the waveform.

Name: Laryngeal cartilage malformation
Desc: A malformation of the laryngeal cartilage.
Synonyms: Vocal impairment, severe, due to laryngeal cartilage abnormalities

Name: Trichiasis
Desc: Inversion and rubbing of the eyelashes against the globe of the eye.

Name: Deviation of the hallux
Desc: Displacement of the big toe from its normal position.

Name: Abnormal subclavian artery morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of a subclavian artery.

Name: Cervical cord compression
Desc: Compression of the spinal cord in the cervical region, generally manifested by paresthesias and numbness, weakness, difficulty walking, abnormalities of coordination, and neck pain or stiffness.

Name: Vascular ring
Desc: A developmental defect of the aortic arch system in which the trachea and esophagus are completely encircled by connected segments of the aortic arch and its branches. This occurs if the normal process of regression and persistence of the bilateral embryonic aortic arches fails.

Name: Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia
Desc: A disorder of bone growth affecting the vertebrae and the ends of the long bones (epiphyses).

Name: Irregular capital femoral epiphysis
Desc: Irregular surface of the normally relatively smooth capital femoral epiphysis.
Synonyms: Irregular end part of innermost thighbone

Name: Broad femoral head
Desc: Increased width of the femoral head.

Name: Delayed proximal femoral epiphyseal ossification
Desc: Developmental delay of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Synonyms: Delayed ossification of the proximal femoral epiphysis

Name: Prominent eyelashes
Desc: Eyelashes that draw the attention of the viewer due to increased density and/or length and/or curl without meeting the criteria of trichomegaly.

Name: Hippocampal atrophy
Desc: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of hippocampus tissue that was once present.

Name: Abnormal peripheral nervous system synaptic transmission
Desc: An anomaly in the communication from a neuron to a target across a synapse in the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Favorable response of weakness to acetylcholine esterase inhibitors
Desc: Improvement of muscle strength in response to administration of an acetylcholine esterase inhibitor.
Synonyms: Favourable response of weakness to acetylcholine esterase inhibitors

Name: Increased jitter at single fiber EMG
Desc: The variation in the time interval between the two action potentials of the same motor unit is called jitter. This term therefore applies to increased variability in the interval between successive action potentials of the same motor unit, which is measured by electromyography (EMG).
Synonyms: Increased jitter at single fibre electromyography
Increased jitter at single fibre EMG

Name: Generalized weakness of limb muscles
Desc: Generalized weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.

Name: Ganglioside accumulation
Desc: Defects in the lysosomal glycosidases or specific co-activators, result in accumulation of the substrates, such as glycosphingolipids, including gangliosides in GM1 gangliosidosis (Tay-Sachs disease) and GM2 gangliosidosis (Sandhoff disease).

Name: Decreased beta-galactosidase activity
Desc: Abnormally decreased rate of beta-galactosidase activity. Beta-galactosidase activity can be measured in leukocyte, fibroblast, or plasma.
Synonyms: Beta-galactosidase deficiency in fibroblasts and white blood cells

Name: Retinopathy of prematurity
Desc: An avascular or abnormally vascularized retina that occurs in premature infants and can lead to blindness.

Name: Cervical spinal cord atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the cervical segment of the spinal cord.

Name: Abnormal glycosylation
Desc: An anomaly of a glycosylation process, i.e., a process involved in the covalent attachment of a glycosyl residue to a substrate molecule.

Name: Decreased galactosylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
Desc: A reduction in the amount of galactose residues of N-glycans.

Name: Anisometropia
Desc: Inequality of refractive power of the two eyes.

Name: Increased circulating thyroglobulin level
Desc: An abnormal elevation of the concentration of thyroglobulin, a protein produced in the thyroid gland that acts as a precursor to thyrroid hormones.

Name: Abnormal cutaneous elastic fiber morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the elastic fibers of the skin. Elastic fibers are the essential extracellular matrix macromolecules comprising an elastin core surrounded by a mantle of fibrillin-rich microfibrils.

Name: Enlarged posterior fossa
Desc: Abnormal increased size of the posterior cranial fossa.

Name: Subretinal pigment epithelium hemorrhage
Desc: An accumulation of blood located between the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) and Bruch's membrane.

Name: Oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma
Desc: A squamous cell carcinoma that originates in the oropharnyx.

Name: Hypermagnesemia
Desc: An abnormally increased magnesium concentration in the blood.

Name: Primary hyperaldosteronism
Desc: A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by a defect within the adrenal gland.

Name: ST segment depression
Desc: An electrocardiographic anomaly in which the ST segment is observed to be located inferior to the isoelectric line.

Name: Decreased urinary potassium
Desc: A decreased concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.

Name: Prominent U wave
Desc: Increased amplitude of the U wave, defined as an amplitude grerater than 1-2mm or 25 percent of the height of the T wave.

Name: Asymptomatic hyperammonemia
Desc: An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood not associated with symptoms such as encephalopathy.

Name: Reduced coagulation factor V activity
Desc: Decreased activity of coagulation factor V.

Name: Testicular adrenal rest tumor
Desc: Testicular adrenal rest tumor (TART) is a abenign tumor of the testis. TART generally occurs multiply and bilaterally within the rete testis. Histologically, TART resemble adrenocortical tissue, which led to the name. The tumous are not encapsulated and consist of sheets or confluent cords of large polygonal cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm.

Name: Leydig cell neoplasia
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the testis with origin in a Leydig cell.

Name: Impaired cortisol response to insulin stimulation test
Desc: Failure of cortisol levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the insulin tolerance test (ITT).

Name: Constrictive pericarditis
Desc: Presence of a thickened, fibrotic pericardium that forms a non-compliant shell around the heart, and resulting from chronic inflammation of the pericardium.

Name: Capillary leak
Desc: An acute phenomenon characterized by hypotension and anasarca due to the loss of plasma volume into peripheral tissues, with evidence of decreased plasma volume (hemoconcentration) and protein loss from the intravascular space (hypoalbuminemia) during acute episodes.

Name: Severe viral infection
Desc: An unusually severe viral infection.

Name: Increased circulating myelocyte count
Desc: An abnormally increased number of myelocytes in the peripheral blood circulation. Myelocytes are immature neutrophils with a size of 12-18 micrometers, a round or oval nucleus with no nucleoli, bluish-pink staining cytoplasm with primary and seconday granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 2:1.

Name: Increased circulating metamyelocyte count
Desc: An abnormally increased number of metamyelocytes in the peripheral blood circulation. Metamyelocytes are immature neutrophils with a size of 10-18 micrometers, an indented or kidney-shaped nucleus, pinkish-blue staining cytoplasm with seconday granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 1.5:1.

Name: Acute cutaneous wound
Desc: A cutaneous wound that is proceeding through an orderly and timely reparative process that results in sustained restoration of the anatomic and functional integrity of the skin.

Name: Increased circulating procalcitonin concentration
Desc: An elevated concentration of procalcitonin in the blood circulation.

Name: Shivering
Desc: Involuntary contraction or twitching of the muscles.

Name: Pulmonary pneumatocele
Desc: A pneumatocele is a thin walled, gas-filled space in the lung. It is most frequently caused by acute pneumonia, trauma, or aspiration of hydrocarbon fluid and is usually transient. The mechanism is believed to be a combination of parenchymal necrosis and check-valve airway obstruction. A pneumatocele appears as an approximately round, thin-walled airspace in the lung.

Name: Generalized lipodystrophy
Desc: Generalized degenerative changes of the fat tissue.

Name: Reduced intraabdominal adipose tissue
Desc: An abnormally reduced amount of adipose tissue in the abdominal cavity.

Name: Proximal symphalangism of hands
Desc: The term proximal symphalangism refers to a bony fusion of the middle and proximal phalanges of the digits of the hand, in other words the proximal interphalangeal joint (PIJ) is missing which can be seen either on x-rays or as an absence of the proximal interphalangeal finger creases.

Name: Complete duplication of proximal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. On x-ray two separate bones appear side to side. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Synonyms: Complete duplication of the innermost bone of the thumb

Name: Complete duplication of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
Desc: Complete duplication of the middle phalanx of middle finger.
Synonyms: Complete duplication of the middle bone of the middle finger

Name: Partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
Desc: Partial duplication of the third proximal phalanx of hand, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
Synonyms: Partial duplication of the proximal bone of the middle finger

Name: Synostosis of carpals/tarsals
Desc: The carpus consists of the scaphoid, lunate, triquetal, pisiform, captitate, hamate, trapezoid, and trapezium bones. The tarsus consists of the talus, calcaneus, navicular, cuboid, cuneiform, and navicular bones. This term applies if there is any fusion among the bones of the carpus or tarsus.
Synonyms: Coalescence of carpal and tarsal bones
Fusion of carpal and tarsal bones

Name: Abnormality of the lens
Desc: An abnormality of the lens.

Name: Abnormal spaced incisors
Synonyms: Abnormality of spacing of front teeth

Name: Muscular ventricular septal defect
Desc: The trabecular septum is the largest part of the interventricular septum. It extends from the membranous septum to the apex and superiorly to the infundibular septum. A defect in the trabecular septum is called muscular VSD if the defect is completely rimmed by muscle.

Name: Endometriosis
Desc: The growth of endometrial tissue outside the uterus.

Name: Medullary nephrocalcinosis
Desc: The deposition of calcium salts in the parenchyma of the renal medulla (innermost part of the kidney).

Name: Macrodontia of permanent maxillary central incisor
Desc: Increased size of the maxillary central secondary incisor tooth.
Synonyms: Hyperplasia of permanent maxillary central incisor
Hypertrophy of permanent maxillary central incisor
Increased size of permanent maxillary central incisor
Increased size of permanent upper central incisor
Increased width of permanent maxillary central incisor
Increased width of permanent upper central incisor

Name: Tented philtrum
Desc: Prominence of a triangular soft tissue area of the philtrum with the apex to the columella.

Name: Abnormal nasal bridge morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose. It lies between the glabella and the inferior boundary of the nasal bone, and extends laterally to the inner canthi.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the bridge of the nose
Deformity of the bridge of the nose
Malformation of the bridge of the nose

Name: Hyperopic astigmatism
Desc: A form of astigmatism in which one meridian is hyperopic while the one at a right angle to it has no refractive error.

Name: Axillary freckling
Desc: The presence in the axillary region (armpit) of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.

Name: Lisch nodules
Desc: The presence of pigmented, oval and dome-shaped raised hamartomatous nevi of the iris..

Name: Inguinal freckling
Desc: The presence in the inguinal region (groin) of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.

Name: Optic nerve glioma
Desc: A glioma originating in the optic nerve or optic chiasm.

Name: Lower limb dysmetria
Desc: A lack of coordination of leg movement manifested by undershoot or overshoot of the intended position of the leg.

Name: Ossifying fibroma
Desc: A benign central bone tumor composed of fibrous connective tissue within which bone is formed.

Name: Abnormal conjugate eye movement
Desc: Any deviation from the normal motor coordination of the eyes that allows for bilateral fixation on a single object.

Name: Recurrent cerebral hemorrhage
Desc: Recurrent bleeding into the parenchyma of the brain.

Name: Carotid artery tortuosity
Desc: Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the carotid arteries.

Name: Arterial fibromuscular dysplasia
Desc: An arterial lesion that is characterized by either intimal fibroplasia, with neointimal lesions of cells and matrix deposition, or medial fibroplasia, in which there is loss of smooth muscle cells and increased deposition of collagen and proteoglycans in the medial layer.

Name: Carotid artery dissection
Desc: A separation (dissection) of the layers of the carotid artery wall.

Name: Overfriendliness
Desc: A form of hypersociability that presents as mostly inappropriate people-orientation and friendliness towards others on an inadequate level which might go as far as being dangerous considering for example young children following strangers without restriction.

Name: Pineal cyst
Desc: A glial uniloculated or multiloculated fluid-filled sac that either reside within or completely replace the pineal gland.

Name: Anomaly of lower limb diaphyses
Desc: A structural abnormality of a diaphysis of the leg.
Synonyms: Anomaly of shaft of long bone of lower limb

Name: Abnormality of muscle size
Desc: Abnormalities of the overall muscle bulk based on clinical observation.

Name: Facial capillary hemangioma
Desc: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells with small endothelial spaces, occurring in the face.

Name: Cleft mandible
Desc: Midline deficiency of the mandible and some or all overlying tissues.

Name: Delayed peripheral myelination
Desc: Delayed myelination in the peripheral nervous system.

Name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the 5th toe
Synonyms: Absent outermost bone of the little toe
Absent outermost bone of the pinkie toe
Absent outermost bone of the pinky toe

Name: Glycogen accumulation in muscle fiber lysosomes
Desc: An increased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue found specifically in lysosomes.
Synonyms: Glycogen accumulation in muscle fibre lysosomes

Name: Basilar artery calcification
Desc: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the basilar artery.

Name: Abnormal muscle glycogen content
Desc: Any anomaly in the amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.

Name: Abnormal cardiomyocyte morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of cardiomyocytes, which are terminally differentiated muscle cells in the heart that are interconnected end to end by gap junctions, which allows coordinated contraction of heart tissue.

Name: Abnormal neuron branching
Desc: Abnormality of the structure and branching of the dendrites of a neuron.

Name: Dark urine
Desc: An abnormal dark color of the urine.

Name: Exercise-induced muscle stiffness
Desc: A type of muscle stiffness that occurs following physical exertion.

Name: Spinal myoclonus
Desc: Spinal myoclonus is generally due to a tumor, infection, injury, or degenerative process of the spinal cord, and is characterized by involuntary rhythmic muscle contractions, usually at a rate of more than one per second. Myoclonus occurs synchronously in several muscles and can be increased in severity and frequency by fatigue or stress, but is usually unaffected by sensory stimuli. Spinal myoclonus ceases during sleep or anesthesia.

Name: Postprandial hyperlactemia
Desc: Abnormally increased level of blood lactate following a meal.

Name: Calcium nephrolithiasis
Desc: The presence of calcium-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

Name: Abnormal eye physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of the eye.

Name: EEG with generalized sharp slow waves
Desc: EEG with generalized sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Synonyms: EEG with generalised sharp slow waves

Name: Downgaze palsy
Desc: A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze below the horizontal meridian.

Name: Posterior staphyloma
Desc: A localized defect in the posterior eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.

Name: Exophoria
Desc: A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward to a milder degree than with exotropia.

Name: Increased resting energy expenditure
Desc: An increase in the number of calories used per unit time.

Name: EMG: impaired neuromuscular transmission
Desc: An electromyographic finding associated with erratic or absent neuromuscular transmission with erratic, moment-to-moment changes in the shape of the motor unit potential (MUP).

Name: Abnormality of the pineal gland
Desc: An anomaly of the pineal gland,a small endocrine gland in the brain that produces melatonin.

Name: Curved distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: A deviation from the normal straight shape of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
Synonyms: Curved outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the thumb. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Synonyms: Triangular shaped outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Short 3rd metacarpal
Desc: Short third metacarpal bone.

Name: Osseous finger syndactyly
Desc: Webbing or fusion of the fingers, involving soft parts and including fusion of individual finger bones. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "Symphalangism".

Name: Moderate hearing impairment
Desc: The presence of a moderate form of hearing impairment.

Name: Elongated superior cerebellar peduncle
Desc: Increased length of the superior cerebellar peduncle.

Name: Abnormal visual accommodation
Desc: An anomaly in the process of visual accommodation, which is the process of adjustment of the eye to enable sharp vision of objects at different distances. Accommodation is mediated by contraction of the ciliary muscles, which alter the convexity of the lens and, consequently, its refractive power.

Name: Abnormal iris pigmentation
Desc: Abnormal pigmentation of the iris.

Name: Abnormal foveal morphology on macular OCT
Peripheral primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm
Desc: A primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm that occurs extracranially in soft tissue and bone.

Name: Elevated carcinoma antigen 125 level
Desc: An increased blood concentration of carcinoma antigen 125 (CA-125). CA-125, also known as mucin 16, can exhibit increased blood levels in certain types of cancer.

Name: Abnormal thoracic spine morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the thoracic vertebral column.

Name: Abnormal superior cerebellar peduncle morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the superior cerebellar peduncle

Name: Neoplasm of the scrotum
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the scrotum.

Name: Secretory diarrhea
Desc: Watery voluminous diarrhea resulting from an imbalance between ion and water secretion and absorption.

Name: Reduced proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative, alpha-beta regulatory T cells
Desc: An abnormally decreased proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative (double negative or DN) alpha-beta regulatory T cells (Tregs) as compared to total number of T cells.

Name: Membranous nephropathy
Desc: A type of glomerulonephropathy characterized by thickening of the basement membrane and deposition of immune complexes in the subepithelial space.

Name: Decreased prealbumin level
