Desc: A reduced concentration of prealbumin in the blood. Prealbumin, also known as transthyretin, has a half-life in plasma of about 2 days, much shorter than that of albumin. Prealbumin is therefore more sensitive to changes in protein-energy status than albumin, and its concentration closely reflects recent dietary intake rather than overall nutritional status.

Name: Dependency on intravenous nutrition
Desc: Inability to be weaned from intravenous (parenteral) nutrition, as judged by the hydration status (urine output, blood urea nitrogen, creatinine, urine sodium concentration), ability to maintain weight, stool output, and serum electrolyte status.

Name: Moon facies
Desc: A rounded, puffy face with fat deposits in the temporal fossa and cheeks, a double chin.

Name: Buphthalmos
Desc: Diffusely large eye (with megalocornea) associated with glaucoma.

Name: Tapered distal phalanges of finger
Desc: A reduction in diameter of the distal phalanx of finger towards the distal end.
Synonyms: Tapered distal phalanges of the hand

Name: Osteolysis involving tarsal bones
Desc: An increased resorption of bone matrix by osteoclasts leading to bony defects involving the tarsal bones.

Name: Osteolysis involving bones of the lower limbs
Osteolysis involving bones of the upper limbs
Broad clavicles
Desc: Increased width (cross-sectional diameter) of the clavicles.

Name: Broad metacarpals
Desc: Abnormally broad metacarpal bones.

Name: Sclerotic cranial sutures
Desc: An increased density in the cranial sutures following obliteration.

Name: Urinary bladder inflammation
Desc: Inflammation of the urinary bladder.

Name: Short 2nd finger
Desc: Hypoplasia of the second finger, also known as the index finger.

Name: Sclerodactyly
Desc: Localized thickening and tightness of the skin of the fingers or toes.

Name: Desquamation of skin soon after birth
Iris melanoma
Desc: Malignant tumor of melanocytes affecting the iris.

Name: Ciliary body melanoma
Desc: Malignant tumor of melanocytes of the ciliary body.

Name: Vitreous hemorrhage
Desc: Bleeding within the vitreous compartment of the eye.

Name: Inferior lens subluxation
Desc: Partial displacement of the lens in the inferior direction.

Name: Photopsia
Desc: Perceived flashes of light.

Name: Chin with horizontal crease
Desc: Horizontal crease or fold situated below the vermilion border of the lower lip and above the fatty pad of the chin, with the face at rest.

Name: Dorsocervical fat pad
Desc: An area of fat accumulation at the back of the neck in the form of a hump.

Name: Abnormal urinary acylglycine profile
Desc: An abnormal distribution of N-acylglycines in the urine. There are numerous different N-acylglycines, and this term refers to pathological alterations in their level or distribution.

Name: Elevated urinary 3-hydroxybutyric acid
Desc: An increased amount of 3-hydroxybutyric acid in the urine.

Name: Chronic lactic acidosis
Desc: A chronic form of lactic acidemia.

Name: Abnormal concentration of acylcarnitine in the urine
Desc: An abnormal amount of acylcarnitine in the urine.

Name: Hypoplastic frontal sinuses
Desc: Underdevelopment of frontal sinus.

Name: Congenital conductive hearing impairment
Desc: A type of conductive deafness with congenital onset.

Name: Immune dysregulation
Desc: Altered immune function characterized by lymphoid proliferation, immune activation, and excessive autoreactivity often leading to autoimmune/inflammatory complications.

Name: Recurrent Aspergillus infections
Desc: An increased susceptibility to Aspergillus infections, as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of Aspergillus infections.

Name: Medial calcification of large arteries
Desc: Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of large (conduit) arteries.

Name: Abnormal serum interferon-gamma level
Desc: Abnormal levels of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.

Name: Short middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
Desc: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the middle phalanx of the second finger, also known as the index finger.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/small middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
Short middle bone of index finger

Name: Multiple muscular ventricular septal defects
Desc: A type of muscular ventricular septal defect characterized by the presence of multiple small defects in the ventricular septum.

Name: Premature arteriosclerosis
Desc: Arteriosclerosis occurring at an age that is younger than usual.

Name: Myocardial steatosis
Desc: Steatosis in the myocardium.

Name: Renal steatosis
Desc: Abnormal fat accumulation in the kidneys.

Name: Tendon xanthomatosis
Desc: The presence of xanthomas (intra-and extra-cellular accumulations of cholesterol) extensor tendons (typically over knuckles, Achilles tendon, knee, and elbows).

Name: Coronary artery aneurysm
Desc: Enlargement of the diameter (cross-section) of a coronary artery as defined by a focal dilation of a segment at least 1.5 times larger than the reference vessel.

Name: Abnormal glucose homeostasis
Desc: Abnormality of glucose homeostasis.

Name: Paroxysmal atrial fibrillation
Desc: Episodes of atrial fibrillation that typically last for several hours up to one day and terminate spontaneously.

Name: Homocystinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of homocystine in the urine.

Name: Recurrent singultus
Desc: A contraction of the diaphragm that repeats several times per minute. In humans, the abrupt rush of air into the lungs causes the epiglottis to close, creating a hic sound. Also known as synchronous diaphragmatic flutter (SDF), or singultus, from the Latin singult, the act of catching one's breath while sobbing. The hiccup is an involuntary action involving a reflex arc.

Name: Abnormal speech discrimination
Desc: A type of hearing impairment prominently characterized by a difficulty in understanding speech, rather than an inability to hear speech. Poor speech discrimination is a very common symptom of high frequency hearing loss.

Name: Thick corpus callosum
Desc: Increased vertical dimension of the corpus callosum. This feature can be visualized by sagittal sections on magnetic resonance tomography imaging of the brain.

Name: Hyperechogenic kidneys
Desc: An increase in amplitude of waves returned in ultrasonography of the kidney, which is generally displayed as increased brightness of the signal.
Synonyms: Increased echogenicity of the renal parenchyma

Name: Dysgenesis of the cerebellar vermis
Desc: Defective development of the vermis of cerebellum.

Name: Small cervical vertebral bodies
Desc: Reduced size of cervical vertebrae.

Name: Rhizomelic arm shortening
Desc: Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of the arm (i.e. the humerus).

Name: Early ossification of capital femoral epiphyses
Desc: Developmental acceleration of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

Name: Abnormality of the 5th metacarpal
Desc: Any abnormality of the fifth metacarpal bone.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the 5th long bone of hand

Name: Subretinal deposits
Desc: Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.

Name: Progressive distal muscle weakness
Desc: Progressively reduced strength of the distal musculature.

Name: Mitochondrial swelling
Desc: The mitochondrial matrix refers to the substance occupying the space enclosed by the inner membrane of a mitochondrion, which contains enzymes, DNA, granules, and inclusions of protein crystals, glycogen, and lipid. Mitochondrial swelling refers to an increase in size of the mitochondrial matrix. This phenomenon is thought to be related to a permeabilized inner membrane that originates a large swelling in the mitochondrial matrix. Mitochondrial swelling may distend the outer membrane until it ruptures.

Name: Long eyebrows
Desc: Increased length of the hairs of the eyebrows.

Name: Abnormal position of hair whorl
Desc: Hair growth from a single point on the scalp in any location other than lateral to the midline and close to the vertex of the skull.

Name: Erratic myoclonus
Desc: A type of myoclonus in which the myoclonias shift from body region to another in a random and asynchronous fashion. Erratic myoclonus can affect the face or limbs, are brief, single or repetitive, very frequent and nearly continuous.

Name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the toes
Synonyms: Cone-shaped end part of the toe bones

Name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 2nd toe
Synonyms: Cone-shaped end part of the 2nd toe bone

Name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 3rd toe
Synonyms: Cone-shaped end part of the 3rd toe bone

Name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 4th toe
Synonyms: Cone-shaped end part of the 4th toe bone

Name: Hyponasal speech
Desc: Hyponasal speech is when there is an abnormally reduced nasal airflow during speech often in a setting of nasal obstruction or congestion.

Name: Confusional arousal
Desc: A nocturnal episode characterized by disorientation, grogginess, and, at times, substantial agitation upon awakening from slow-wave sleep or following forced awakenings. These characteristics might present as agitation, crying or moaning, disorientation, and particularly slow mentation on arousal from sleep (i.e., sleep inertia). The duration of episodes is typically 5 to 15 min but they might last up to several hours.

Name: Stomatitis
Desc: Stomatitis is an inflammation of the mucous membranes of any of the structures in the mouth.

Name: Limited shoulder movement
Desc: A limitation of the range of movement of the shoulder joint.

Name: Cutaneous sclerotic plaque
Desc: A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter that is characterized by hardening (sclerosis) of the affected skin area (related to collagen thickening).

Name: Curved linear dimple below the lower lip
Bitemporal forceps marks
Desc: Bilateral temporal scarlike defects, which are said to resemble forceps marks.
Synonyms: Congenital ectodermal dysplasia of the face

Name: Abnormal epidermal morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the morphology of the epidermis.

Name: Abnormal mast cell morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly of mast cells, which are found in almost all tissues and contain numerous basophilic granules and are capable of releasing large amounts of histamine and heparin upon activation.

Name: Abnormality of buccal mucosa
Desc: An abnormality of a buccal mucosa.
Synonyms: Abnormality of inside lining of cheek

Name: Staring gaze
Desc: An abnormality in which the eyes are held permanently wide open.

Name: Hostility
Desc: Persistent or frequent angry feelings; anger or irritability in response to minor slights and insults.

Name: Abnormal libido
Desc: Any deviation from the normal sexual drive or desire for sexual activity.

Name: Accumulation of muscle fiber desmin
Desc: Immunohistochemistry shows accumulation of desmin protein in the muscle biopsy.

Name: Posterior capsular cataract
Desc: A cataract which is found in the back outer layer of the lens. This type often develops more rapidly.

Name: Groin pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the groin region.

Name: Globozoospermia
Desc: Any structural anomaly of the acrosome resulting in a round sperm head.

Name: Abnormal sperm tail morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the sperm tail.

Name: Multiple pulmonary cysts
Desc: The presence of multiple lung cysts.

Name: Unusual infection
Desc: A type of infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection. There are five general subtypes. (i) Opportunistic infection, meaning infection by a pathogen that is not normally able to cause infection in a healthy host (e.g., pneumonia by Pneumocystis jirovecii or CMV); (ii) Unusual location (focus) of an infection (e.g., an aspergillus brain abscess); (iii) a protracted course or lack of adequate response to treatment (e.g., chronic rhinosinusitis); (iv) Unusual severity or intensity of an infection; and (v) unusual recurrence of infections.

Name: Splenic cyst
Desc: A closed sac located in the spleen.

Name: Abnormal subpleural morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly located between the pleura and the chest wall.

Name: Invasive parasitic infection
Desc: A parasitic infection whereby the parasite invades (migrates through) tissues of the infected host.

Name: Central core regions in muscle fibers
Desc: The presence of disorganized areas called cores in the center of muscle fibers. There is a typical appearance of the biopsy on light microscopy, where the muscle cells have cores that are devoid of mitochondria and specific enzymes. Cores are typically well demarcated and centrally located, but may occasionally be multiple and of eccentric.
Synonyms: Central core regions in muscle fibres

Name: Loss of ability to walk in early childhood
Abnormality of odontoid tissue
Desc: An abnormality of an odontoid tissue.
Synonyms: Abnormality of hard tissues of teeth

Name: Cleft lower lip
Desc: A gap in the lower lip.

Name: Fusion of gums
Desc: A congenital defect with an abnormal joining of the gums of the upper and lower jaw.
Synonyms: Upper and lower gums fused together

Name: Abnormality of orbicularis oris muscle
Desc: An abnormality of an orbicularis oris muscle.

Name: Abnormal platelet aggregation
Desc: An abnormality in the rate and degree to which platelets aggregate after the addition of an agonist that stimulates platelet clumping. Platelet aggregation is measured using aggregometer to measure the optical density of platelet-rich plasma, whereby platelet aggregation causes the plasma to become more transparent.

Name: Asymmetry of the mouth
Desc: The presence of an asymmetric mouth.

Name: Thoracic aorta calcification
Desc: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the thoracic aorta.

Name: Secretory adrenocortical adenoma
Desc: An hormonally active adrenocortical adenoma, that is, an adenoma that secretes excessive amounts of adrenal hormones.

Name: Hypoplastic nasal septum
Desc: Underdevelopment of the nasal septum.
Synonyms: Decreased size of septum of nose

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the maxilla
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the maxilla.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the lower limbs
Desc: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the lower limbs.

Name: Widely spaced toes
Desc: An overall widening of the spaces between the digits.

Name: Slanting of the palpebral fissure
Synonyms: Slanting of the opening between the eyelids

Name: Decreased CSF 5-hydroxyindolacetic acid
Desc: CSF 5-HIAA (5-hydroxyindolacetic acid) level is below the lower limit of normal.

Name: Decreased CSF protein
Desc: CSF total protein level is below the lower limit of normal.

Name: Decreased CSF albumin concentration
Desc: CSF albumin level is below the lower limit of normal.

Name: Decreased CSF biopterin level
Desc: Decreased concentration of biopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Name: Reduced protein C activity
Desc: An abnormality of coagulation related to a decreased concentration of vitamin K-dependent protein C. Protein C is activated to protein Ca by thrombin bound to thrombomodulin. Activated protein C degrades factors VIIIa and Va.

Name: Decreased resting energy expenditure
Desc: A reduction in the number of calories used per unit time.

Name: Astasia
Desc: A postural abnormality characterized by the inability to stand without external support despite having sufficient muscle strength.

Name: Fatigable weakness of speech muscles
Desc: A type of weakness of the muscles involved in speech that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

Name: Suck reflex
Desc: A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by lightly touching or tapping on the lips with an object such as a tongue blade, reflex hammer, or the examiner's finger. At times the reflex is obtained merely by approaching the lips with an object. A positive suck reflex consists of sucking movements by the lips when they are stroked or touched.

Name: Tarsal sclerosis
Desc: An elevation in bone density in one or more tarsal bones of the foot. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

Name: Impaired oral bolus formation
Desc: An abnormality of swallowing characterized by reduced tongue coordination to form bolus after chewing. Food material spreads over the oral cavity instead of being concentrated into a bolus that is easily swallowed.

Name: Sclerosis of finger phalanx
Desc: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Synonyms: Increased bone density in the finger bone
Sclerosis of the phalanges of the hand

Name: Reduced ratio of renal calcium clearance to creatinine clearance
Desc: A reduction of the ratio of renal calcium clearance to creatinine clearance to below 0.01.
Synonyms: Reduced ration of kidney calcium clearance to creatinine clearance
Reduced ration of renal Ca clearance to creatinine clearance
Reduced ration of renal Ca2+ to creatinine clearance

Name: Hypomagnesiuria
Desc: An decreased concentration of magnesium the urine.

Name: Respiratory acidosis
Desc: Acidosis because of respiratory retention of carbon dioxide.

Name: Hyperkeratosis lenticularis perstans
Desc: Hyperkeratosis lenticularis perstans (HLP), also known as Flegel disease, is a keratinization abnormality characterized by small, asymptomatic erythematous papules that leave characteristic punctate bleeding when they become detached. The lesions generally occur symmetrically along the top of the foot and on the legs, appearing more rarely on the arms, forearms, palms, and soles, and even on the oral mucosa.

Name: Macular hypopigmentation
Desc: Decreased amount of pigmentation in the macula lutea.

Name: Macular hyperpigmentation
Desc: Increased amount of pigmentation in the macula lutea.

Name: Cessation of head growth
Desc: Stagnation of head growth seen as flattening of the head circumference curve.

Name: Macular cotton wool spot
Desc: Fluffy white patch on the macula, representing localized areas of dense white swelling of the retinal nerve fibre layer. They often have a zigzag internal structure, a feathered edge but an otherwise well-delineated form and an approximately 1 mm dimension; they project slightly into the vitreous and sometimes deflect retinal vessels.

Name: Intraretinal hemorrhage
Desc: A subtype of fundus hemorrhage occurring within the neurosensory retina. Intraretinal haemorrhages may be 'dot' or' blot' shaped or flame shaped depending upon their depth within the retina.

Name: Large central visual field defect
Synonyms: Large central loss of field of vision

Name: Increased phosphoribosylpyrophosphate synthetase level
Desc: Abnormally elevated level of the enzyme phosphoribosyl pyrophosphatesynthetase, which catalyzes the synthesis of PP-ribose-P from ATP and ribose-5-phosphate.

Name: Increased urinary urate
Desc: Elevated concentration of urate in the urine.

Name: Stage 4 chronic kidney disease
Desc: A type of chronic kidney disease with severely reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 15-29 mL/min/1.73 m2).

Name: Elevated leukocyte cystine
Desc: An increased concentration of cystine within white blood cells.

Name: Mycobacterium abscessus abscessus infection
Desc: Mycobacterium abscessus complex comprises a group of rapidly growing, multidrug-resistant, nontuberculous mycobacteria that are responsible for a wide spectrum of skin and soft tissue diseases, central nervous system infections, bacteremia, and ocular and other infections.

Name: Disseminated nontuberculous mycobacterial infection
Desc: An infection with nontuberculous mycobacteria that affects multiple body sites. Such infections can occur in individuals with immune disease.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the bladder
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the urinary bladder.

Name: Bilateral renal agenesis
Desc: A bilateral form of agenesis of the kidney.

Name: Absent vas deferens
Desc: Aplasia (congenital absence) of the vas deferens.
Synonyms: Congenital absence of the vas deferens

Name: Type IV atherosclerotic lesion
Desc: In type IV atherosclerotic lesions a dense accumulation of extracellular lipid occupies an extensive but well-defined region of the intima. This type of extracellular lipid accumulation is known as the lipid core. A fibrous tissue increase is not a feature, and complications such as defects of the lesion surface and thrombosis are not present. The type IV lesion is also known as atheroma. Type IV is the first lesion considered advanced in this classification because of the severe intimal disorganization caused by the lipid core. The characteristic core appears to develop from an increase and the consequent confluence of the small isolated pools of extracellular lipid that characterize type III lesions. The increase in lipid is believed to result from continued insudation from the plasma. Type IV lesions, when they first appear in younger people, are found in the same locations as adaptive intimal thickenings of the eccentric type. Thus, atheroma is, at least initially, an eccentric lesion.

Name: Low insertion of columella
Desc: Insertion of the posterior columella below the nasal base.

Name: Hemihypotrophy of lower limb
Desc: Shortening of a leg affecting only one side.

Name: Upbeat nystagmus
Desc: In primary position, the eyes drift slowly downward and then spontaneously beat upward. Upward gaze accentuates the nystagmus. The associated oscillopsias are often very irritating, but the symptoms are usually transient.

Name: Mild myopia
Desc: A mild form of myopia with up to -3.00 diopters.

Name: Abnormal mitochondrial shape
Desc: An anomaly in the surface contour of mitochondria.

Name: Abnormal urinary odor
Desc: A deviation from the normal odor of the urine.

Name: Hyperornithinemia
Desc: Increased concentration of ornithine in the blood.

Name: Subcapsular cataract
Desc: A cataract that affects the region of the lens directly beneath the capsule of the lens.

Name: Constriction of peripheral visual field
Desc: An absolute or relative decrease in retinal sensitivity extending from edge (periphery) of the visual field in a concentric pattern. The visual field is the area that is perceived simultaneously by a fixating eye.

Name: Abnormal circulating citrulline concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of citrulline in the blood circulation.

Name: Hyperoxaluria
Desc: Increased excretion of oxalates in the urine.
Synonyms: Increased level of oxalate in urine

Name: Intermittent claudication
Desc: Intermittent claudication is a symptom of peripheral arterial occlusive disease. After having walked over a distance which is individually characteristic, the patients experience pain or cramps in the calves, feet or thighs which typically subsides on standing still.

Name: Aciduria
Desc: Excretion of urine with an acid pH, i.e., having an increased hydrogen ion concentration.

Name: Elevated urine glycolate
Desc: An increased concentration of glycolate in the urine.

Name: Calcinosis cutis
Desc: Deposition of calcium in the skin.

Name: Prolinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of proline in the urine.

Name: Hyperprolinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of proline in the blood.

Name: Distal arthrogryposis
Desc: An inherited primary limb malformation disorder characterized by congenital contractures of two or more different body areas and without primary neurologic and/or muscle disease that affects limb function.

Name: Vocal tremor
Desc: A wavering, unsteady voice that reflects involuntary and approximately sinusoidal oscillation of motor unit firings of laryngeal muscles. Vocal tremor results in low frequency modulations of voice frequency or amplitude and intermittent voice instability.

Name: Neck muscle hypertrophy
Desc: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the muscles of the neck.

Name: Absent nail of hallux
Desc: Absent nail of big toe.

Name: Delayed phalangeal epiphyseal ossification
Desc: Delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more phalanx.
Synonyms: Delayed bone maturation of end part of digital bone

Name: Short phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Hypoplastic (short) thumb phalanx.

Name: Hydroxyprolinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of 4-hydroxy-L-proline in the urine.

Name: Hyperglycinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of glycine in the urine.

Name: Hydroxyprolinemia
Desc: An increased concentration of hydroxyproline in the blood.

Name: Short 4th toe
Desc: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the fourth toe.

Name: Elevated jugular venous pressure
Desc: Increased jugular venous pressure.

Name: Hypercapnia
Desc: Abnormally elevated blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level.

Name: Cardiomyocyte mitochondrial proliferation
Desc: An abnormal increase in the number of mitochondria per cardiac myocyte.

Name: Acute rhabdomyolysis
Desc: An acute form of rhabdomyolysis.

Name: Elevated amniotic fluid alpha-fetoprotein
Desc: An elevation of alpha-feto protein measured in the amniotic fluid.
Synonyms: Elevated amniotic fluid alpha fetal protein
Elevated amniotic fluid alpha foetal protein

Name: Activating thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor defect
Desc: Gain-of-function thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) defect.

Name: Thyroid hyperplasia
Desc: Hyperplasia of the thyroid gland.

Name: Anal canal adenocarcinoma
Desc: An adenoma carcinoma that originates in the anal canal.

Name: Anal canal squamous cell carcinoma
Desc: A squamous cell carcinoma that originates in the anal canal.

Name: Rectus femoris muscle atrophy
Synonyms: Atrophy of the rectus femoris muscles

Name: Proximal renal tubular acidosis
Desc: A type of renal tubular acidosis characterized by a failure of the proximal tubular cells to reabsorb bicarbonate, leading to urinary bicarbonate wasting and subsequent acidemia.

Name: Cortical myoclonus
Desc: Cortical myoclonus mainly affects the distal upper limbs and face, which reflects the largest cortical representations of these body areas. It is often focal, but may be multifocal, bilateral or generalized, as a consequence of intracortical and transcallosal spreading of abnormal activity. It typically occurs on voluntary action and may affect speech and gait. Cortical myoclonic jerks are stimulus sensitive, typically to touch, but sensitivity to visual stimuli is also described. Most patients with cortical myoclonus have both positive myoclonus and NM, occurring either independently or together as a complex of the two kinds of myoclonus. If cortical myoclonus is prolonged and lasts for hours, days or weeks, it is called epilepsia partials continua and is considered to be a rare form of focal epileptic status. Focal cortical myoclonus almost always points to an underlining lesion of the sensori-motor cortex, which produces hyperexcitability (e.g. vascular, inflammatory or neoplastic).

Name: Progressive hearing impairment
Desc: A progressive form of hearing impairment.

Name: Abnormality of adrenal physiology
Desc: A functional abnormality of the adrenal glands.

Name: Stress/infection-induced lactic acidosis
Desc: A form of lactic acidemia that occurs in relation to stress or infection.

Name: Abnormal circulating carnitine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of carnitine in the blood circulation.

Name: Increased female libido
Desc: Elevated sexual desire in female

Name: EMG: repetitive nerve stimulation abnormality
Desc: Abnormality observed upon electromyography when nerve studied is electrically stimulated six to ten times at 2 or 3 Hertz.

Name: Calcium channel antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against voltage-gated calcium channels.

Name: Small cell lung carcinoma
Desc: Small cell lung cancer (SCLC) is a type of highly malignant lung cancer that is composed of small ovoid cells. In the past, SCLC was called oat cell carcinoma because the microscopic appearance of the cells was felt to resemble oats. SLCLC usually originates near the bronchi and in many cases may grow and metastasize quickly.

Name: Aplasia of the epiglottis
Desc: Absence of the epiglottis.

Name: Marked muscular hypertrophy
Desc: Severe hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells.

Name: Abnormal labia majora morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the outer labia.

Name: Abnormality of frontal sinus
Desc: An abnormality of the frontal sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The frontal sinus is located within the frontal bone.

Name: Prelingual sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A form of sensorineural deafness with either congenital onset or infantile onset, i.e., before the acquisition of speech.

Name: Patchy atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium
Desc: Wasting (atrophy) of the retinal pigment epithelium present in small, isolated areas.

Name: Rectal abscess
Desc: A collection of pus in the area of the rectum.

Name: Abnormality of the ductus choledochus
Desc: An abnormality of the Common bile duct, a tube-like anatomic structure in the human gastrointestinal tract, formed by the union of the Common hepatic duct and the Cystic duct from the gall bladder.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the common bile duct

Name: Congenital cystic adenomatoid malformation of the lung
Desc: Congenital cystic adenomatoid malformation (CCAM) can be diagnosed prenatally if ultrasound shows a cystic or solid lung tumor. A CCAM does not have systemic arterial blood supply (in contrast to bronchopulmonary sequenstration). It is a cystic area within the lung that originates from abnormal embryogenesis.
Synonyms: Congenital cystic disease of the lung

Name: Progressive leukoencephalopathy
Desc: Leukoencephalopathy that gets more severe with time.

Name: Odontodysplasia
Desc: The diagnosis odontodysplasia requires clinical and radiological exams, in which unusually large pulp chambers and large pulp room chambers with thin enamel and dentin are visible. It may affect either a single tooth or several teeth. The term regional odontodysplasia is used if several teeth are affected. It affects the deciduous and permanent dentitions in the maxilla, the mandible or both, although the maxilla is more frequently involved. A type of dental dysplasia occurring in dentinogenesis imperfecta in which the pulp chambers are enlarged and there is a reduced amount of coronal dentin.
Synonyms: Teeth with thin dentin and large pulp chambers
Teeth with type iii dentinogenesis imperfecta

Name: Patchy variation in bone mineral density
Desc: Patchy (irregular) changes in bone mineral density with patches of bone showing an increased density side to side with patches that are affected by reduction of mineral density. This is sometimes referred to as a moth-eaten appearance on x-rays.
Synonyms: Patchy increased and decreased bone mineral density

Name: Fibrous dysplasia of the bones
Desc: Tumor-like growths that consist of replacement of the medullary bone with fibrous tissue, causing the expansion and weakening of the areas of bone involved. Especially when involving the skull or facial bones, the lesions can cause externally visible deformities. The skull is often, but not necessarily, affected, and any other bone or bones may be involved. Fibrous dysplasia can either effect isolated bones (Monostotic fibrous dysplasia) or also generalized all bones of the body (Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia).

Name: Shoulder girdle muscle atrophy
Desc: Amyotrophy affecting the muscles of the shoulder girdle.

Name: Decreased Achilles reflex
Desc: Decreased intensity of the Achilles reflex (also known as the ankle jerk reflex), which can be elicited by tapping the tendon is tapped while the foot is dorsiflexed.

Name: Decreased patellar reflex
Desc: Decreased intensity of the patellar reflex (also known as the knee jerk reflex).

Name: Left anterior fascicular block
Desc: Conduction block in the anterior division of the left bundle branch of the bundle of His.

Name: Beevor's sign
Desc: Weakness of the inferior portion of the rectus abdominal muscle, which is ascertained clinically as follows. When a patient sits up or raises the head from a recumbent position, the umbilicus is displaced toward the head. This is the result of paralysis of the inferior portion of the rectus abdominal muscle, so that the upper fibres predominate pulling upwards the umbilicus.

Name: Triceps weakness
Desc: A lack of strength in the triceps muscle, which normally is responsible for extending (straightening) the elbow and mediating certain shoulder movements.

Name: Absent pubertal growth spurt
Desc: The abrupt and transient increase in the annual growth rate normally observed in adolescent individuals does not occur.

Name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure on awakening
Desc: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure of either generalized or focal onset occurring on or soon after wakening (typically within 90 minutes of waking, regardless of the time of day).

Name: Brown anomaly
Desc: An ocular motility defect where the affected eye(s) does not elevate in adduction but has full depression in adduction. It can be congenital or acquired from injury to or defect of the superior oblique tendon or trochlea and has a positive forced duction test result.

Name: Abnormality of the anterior pituitary
Desc: An abnormality of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

Name: Anomalous origin of left subclavian artery
Desc: Origin of the left subclavian artery from an anomalous anatomical location.

Name: Necrolytic migratory erythema
Desc: Acral or periorificial lesions that evolve in recurrent crops, with an annular and migratory distribution.

Name: Stage 3 chronic kidney disease
Desc: A type of chronic kidney disease with moderately reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 30-59 mL/min/1.73 m2).

Name: Caudal interpedicular narrowing
Desc: Narrowing (becoming gradually narrower) of the distance between vertebral pedicles that gets progressively more severe towards to caudal (lower) end of the vertebral column. Note that normally, the interpedicular distances get progressively wider as one proceeds down the spine.

Name: Abnormal circulating creatine concentration
Desc: A deviation from the normal concentration of creatine in the blood circulation. Creatine is a derivative of glycine having methyl and amidino groups attached to the nitrogen. Creatine is naturally produced from amino acids, primarily in liver and kidney, and acts as an energy source for cells, primarly for muscle cells.

Name: Renal neoplasm
Desc: The presence of a neoplasm of the kidney.

Name: Abnormality of globe location
Desc: An abnormality in the placement of the ocular globe (eyeball).

Name: Abnormality of circulating catecholamine level
Desc: An abnormal catecholamine concentration in the blood.

Name: Large posterior fontanelle
Desc: An enlargement of the posterior fontanelle relative to age-dependent norms.

Name: Ewing sarcoma
Desc: A malignant tumor of the bone which always arises in the medullary tissue, occurring more often in cylindrical bones.

Name: Pancreatoblastoma
Desc: A rare pediatric carcinoma of the pancreas.

Name: Pancreatic squamous cell carcinoma
Desc: A subtype of ductal pancreatic carcinoma that is thought to originate from squamous metaplasia of pancreatic ductal epithelium.
Synonyms: Squamous cell carcinoma of the pancreas

Name: Lactose intolerance
Desc: An inability to digest lactose.

Name: Mild neurosensory hearing impairment
Desc: The presence of a mild form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

Name: Abnormal CD4:CD8 ratio
Desc: Any abnormality in the relative amount of CD4+ and CD8+ T lymphocytes.

Name: Epidermal thickening
Desc: Thickening of the epidermal layer of the skin.

Name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex IV
Desc: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex IV, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

Name: Severely reduced ejection fraction
Desc: A large reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at over 50 percent, and a severe reduction is defined as less than 30 percent.

Name: Brainstem dysplasia
Desc: A developmental structural anomaly of the stalk-like part of the brain that comprises the midbrain (aka mesencephalon), the pons (aka pons Varolii), and the medulla oblongata, and connects the cerebral hemispheres with the cervical spinal cord.

Name: Infancy onset short-trunk short stature
Desc: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with onset in infancy.

Name: Vertical forehead creases
Desc: Vertical soft tissue creases in the midline of the forehead, often extending from the hairline to the brow, and seen with facial expression or when the face is at rest.

Name: Increased circulating chylomicron concentration
Desc: Increased plasma concentrations of chylomicrons, the large lipid droplet (up to 100 mm in diameter) of reprocessed lipid synthesized in epithelial cells of the small intestine and containing triacylglycerols, cholesterol esters, and several apolipoproteins.

Name: Lipemia retinalis
Desc: A creamy appearance of the retinal blood vessels that occurs when the concentration of lipids in the blood are extremely increased, with pale pink to milky white retinal vessels and altered pale reflexes from choroidal vasculature.

Name: Recurrent pancreatitis
Desc: A recurrent form of pancreatitis.

Name: Infection associated neutropenia
Desc: Transient neutropenia caused by an infection, such as with a virus, bacteria or protozoan.

Name: Cerebral artery stenosis
Desc: Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of a cerebral artery.

Name: Abnormality of pain sensation
Desc: Pain is an unpleasant sensation that can range from mild, localized discomfort to agony, whereby the physical part of pain results from nerve stimulation and is often accompanied by an emotional component. This term groups abnormalities in pain sensation presumed to result from abnormalities related to the specific nerve fibers that carry the pain impulses to the brain.

Name: High myoinositol in brain by MRS
Desc: An elevated level of myoinositol in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Synonyms: High myo-inositol in brain by MRS

Name: Transient hearing impairment
Desc: Hearing loss that occurs acutely and resolves completely.

Name: Congenital intracerebral calcification
Desc: The presence of calcium deposition within brain structures that is present already at the time of birth.

Name: Macular atrophy
Desc: Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the macula, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.

Name: Retinal pigment epithelial mottling
Desc: Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium, i.e., localized or generalized fundal pigment granularity associated with processes at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium.
Synonyms: Focal hypopigmentation of the retinal pigment epithelium

Name: Absent foveal reflex
Desc: Lack of the foveal reflex, which normally occurs as a result of the reflection of light from the ophthalmoscope in the foveal pit upon examination. The foveal reflex is a bright pinpoint of light that is observed to move sideways or up and down in response to movement of the opthalmoscope.

Name: Opportunistic fungal infection
Desc: An infection that is caused by a fungus that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such fungi take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

Name: Pulmonary tuberculosis
Desc: A lung infection by Mycobacterium tuberculosis a slightly curved non-motile, aerobic, non-capsulated and non-spore forming strains of mycobacteria.

Name: Abnormal jejunum morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the jejunum, i.e., of the middle section of the small intestine.

Name: Fungal meningitis
Desc: An infection of the meninges caused by a fungus. Generally, only individuals with deficiencies of the immune system contract fungal meningitis.

Name: Apical pulmonary opacity
Desc: An apical cap is a caplike lesion at the lung apex, usually caused by intrapulmonary and pleural fibrosis pulling down extrapleural fat or possibly by chronic ischemia resulting in hyaline plaque formation on the visceral pleura. The prevalence increases with age. It can also be seen in hematoma resulting from aortic rupture or in other fluid collection associated with infection or tumor, either outside the parietal pleura or loculated within the pleural space.

Name: Muscle fiber necrosis
Desc: Abnormal cell death involving muscle fibers usually associated with break in, or absence of, muscle surface fiber membrane and resulting in irreversible damage to muscle fibers.

Name: Respiratory paralysis
Desc: Inability to move the muscles of respiration.

Name: Hypohidrosis or hyperhidrosis
Synonyms: Lack of sweating or excessive sweating

Name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Any anomaly of the distal phalanx of thumb.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the outermost bone of the thumb

Name: EMG: slow motor conduction
Desc: The presence of reduced conduction velocity of motor nerves on electromyography.

Name: Tibialis atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the tibialis muscle.

Name: Abnormal P wave
Desc: Any anomaly of the P wave of the EKG, which results from atrial depolarization. The P wave occurs when the sinoatrial node creates an action potential that depolarizes the atria.

Name: Histiocytoid cardiomyopathy
Desc: A type of cardiomyopathy characterized pathologically by hamartomatous lesions of cardiac Purkinje cells.

Name: Cardiac rhabdomyoma
Desc: A benign tumor of cardiac striated muscle.

Name: Seborrheic keratosis
Desc: A raised growth on the skin of older individuals. The lesion usually is initially light tan and may darken to dark brown or nearly black. The consistent feature of seborrheic keratoses is their waxy, pasted-on or stuck-on look.

Name: Ulnar deviation of the 3rd finger
Desc: Displacement of the 3rd finger towards the ulnar side (i.e., towards the ring finger).

Name: Ulnar deviation of the 2nd finger
Desc: Displacement of the 2nd (index) finger towards the ulnar side.
Synonyms: Ulnar angulation of the index finger

Name: Blind vagina
Desc: The vagina ends in a blind pouch or sac rather than being connected to the internal genitalia.

Name: Abnormal peripheral action potential amplitude
Desc: An anomaly in the magnitude of the action potential along a peripheral nerve, that is, of the rapid rise and fall of the electrical membrane potential of the nerve.

Name: Joint contractures involving the joints of the feet
Desc: Contractures of one ore more joints of the feet meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Name: Contracture of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 4th toe
Desc: The proximal interphalangeal joint of the 4th toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
Synonyms: Contracture of the innermost hinge joint of the 4th toe

Name: Aplasia of the vagina
Desc: Aplasia of the vagina.

Name: Upper eyelid entropion
Desc: An inward turning (inversion) of the margin of the upper eyelid.

Name: EEG with frontal sharp slow waves
Desc: EEG with sharp slow waves in the frontal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

Name: Sacral hypertrichosis
Desc: Excessive, increased hair growth located in the sacral region.

Name: Carpal bone hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of one or more carpal bones.

Name: Hyperextensible hand joints
Desc: The ability of the joints of the hand to move beyond their normal range of motion.

Name: Proximal femoral epiphysiolysis
Desc: Slipped capital femoral epiphysis is defined as a posterior and inferior slippage of the proximal epiphysis of the femur onto the metaphysis (femoral neck), occurring through the physeal plate during the early adolescent growth spurt.
Synonyms: Slipped end part of innermost thighbone

Name: Tibial metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of a metaphysis of a tibia.

Name: Fibular metaphyseal irregularity
Desc: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of a metaphysis of a fibula.
Synonyms: Irregularity of wide portion of calf bone

Name: Small foramen magnum
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the foramen magnum.

Name: Thoracic platyspondyly
Desc: A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance beween the vertebral endplates affecting the thoracic spine.

Name: Ossifying fibroma of the jaw
Desc: A benign central bone tumor of the jaw composed of fibrous connective tissue within which bone is formed.

Name: Eyelid myokymia
Desc: Involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions of the eyelid.

Name: Alzheimer disease
Desc: A degenerative disease of the brain characterized by the insidious onset of dementia. Impairment of memory, judgment, attention span, and problem solving skills are followed by severe apraxia and a global loss of cognitive abilities. The condition primarily occurs after age 60, and is marked pathologically by severe cortical atrophy and the triad of senile plaques, neurofibrillary tangles, and neuropil threads.
Synonyms: Late-onset form of familial Alzheimer disease

Name: Progressive distal muscular atrophy
Desc: Progressive muscular atrophy affecting muscles in the distal portions of the extremities.

Name: Temporal optic disc pallor
Desc: A pale yellow discoloration of the temporal (lateral) portion of the optic disc.

Name: Mild hearing impairment
Desc: The presence of a mild form of hearing impairment.

Name: Abnormal humerus morphology
Desc: Any anomaly of the structure of the humerus.

Name: Methemoglobinemia
Desc: Abnormally increased levels of methemoglobin in the blood. In this form of hemoglobin, there is an oxidized ferric iron (Fe +3) rather than the reduced ferrous form (Fe 2+) that is normally found in hemoglobin. Methemoglobin has a reduced affinity for oxygen, resulting in a reduced ability to release oxygen to tissues.

Name: Broad distal phalanx of the toes
Desc: Increased width of the distal phalanx of toe of one or more toes.
Synonyms: Broad outermost bone of the toe
Wide outermost bone of the toe

Name: Male urethral meatus stenosis
Desc: An abnormal narrowing of the urethral opening (meatus) of the penis.

Name: Abnormality of metacarpophalangeal joint
Desc: An anomaly of a metacarpophalangeal joint.

Name: Triangular mouth
Desc: The presence of a triangular form of the mouth.

Name: Mesoaxial hand polydactyly
Desc: The presence of a supernumerary finger (not a thumb) involving the third or fourth metacarpal with associated osseous syndactyly.

Name: Mesoaxial foot polydactyly
Desc: The presence of a supernumerary toe (not a hallux) involving the third or fourth metatarsal with associated osseous syndactyly.

Name: Increased circulating NT-proBNP concentration
Desc: An elevated level of circulating N-terminal part of the prohormone of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP).

Name: Increased circulating creatine kinase MB isoform
Desc: An increased concentration of the MB isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.

Name: Increased circulating troponin I concentration
Desc: An increased concentration of tropnin I in the blood, which is a cardiac regulatory protein that controls the calcium mediated interaction between actin and myosin. Raised cardiac troponin concentrations are now accepted as the standard biochemical marker for the diagnosis of myocardial infarction.
Synonyms: Increased troponin I level in blood

Name: Priapism
Desc: A painful and harmful medical condition in which the erect penis doesn't return to its flaccid state, despite the absence of both physical and psychological stimulation, within four hours.

Name: Muscle abnormality related to mitochondrial dysfunction
Detrusor sphincter dyssynergia
Desc: A urodynamic anomaly characterized by bladder outlet obstruction from detrusor muscle contraction with concomitant involuntary urethral sphincter activation.

Name: Abnormality of peripheral somatosensory evoked potentials
Decreased distal sensory nerve action potential
Desc: A reduction in the amplitude of sensory nerve action potential in distal nerve segments. This feature is measured by nerve conduction studies.

Name: Tongue tremor
Desc: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the tongue.

Name: Infantile constant exotropia
Desc: Constant exotropia occurring before 6 months of age.; often associated with a large angle of deviation and ocular/CNS abnormalities.

Name: Synostosis involving the 1st metacarpal
Desc: Fusion of the 1st metacarpal with another bone. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2 to 5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Synonyms: Fusion involving 1st long bone of hand

Name: Square face
Desc: Facial contours, as viewed from the front, show a broad upper face/cranium and lower face/mandible, creating a square appearance.

Name: Nasal flaring
Desc: Widening of the nostrils upon inhalation as a manifestation of respiratory distress.

Name: Borderline personality disorder
Desc: A personality disorder characterized by impulsive behavior and unpredictable and capricious mood. Affected individuals show a liability to outbursts of emotion and an incapacity to control the behavioural explosions.

Name: Mood swings
Desc: An exaggeration of emotional affects such as laughing crying, or yawning beyond what the person feels.

Name: Thin ear helix
Desc: Decreased thickness of the helix of the ear.

Name: 2-5 finger syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers two to five.
Synonyms: Webbed index, middle and little finger
Webbed index, middle and pinkie finger
Webbed index, middle and pinky finger

Name: 4-5 finger syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers four and five.

Name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex II
Desc: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex II, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

Name: Abnormal blood zinc concentration
Desc: An abnormality of zinc ion homeostasis.

Name: Hypomanganesemia
Desc: A reduction below the normal concentration of manganese in the blood.

Name: Decreased mitochondrial complex III activity in liver tissue
Desc: Decreased activity of complex III of the mitochondrion in the liver.

Name: Reduced aldolase level
Desc: An decreased concentration of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase in the serum.

Name: Argininuria
Desc: A increased concentration of arginine in the urine.

Name: Hyperlysinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of lysine in the urine.

Name: Renal amyloidosis
Desc: A form of amyloidosis that affects the kidney. On hematoxylin and eosin stain, amyloid is identified as extracellular amorphous material that is lightly eosinophilic. These deposits often stain weakly for periodic acid Schiff (PAS), demonstrate a blue-to-gray hue on the trichrome stain and are typically negative on the Jones methenamine silver (JMS) stain. These tinctorial properties contrast with the histologic appearance of collagen, a major component of basement membranes, mesangial matrix and areas of sclerosis, which demonstrates strong positivity for PAS and JMS (See Figure 1 of PMID:25852856).

Name: Ornithinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of ornithine in the urine.

Name: Increased serum zinc
Desc: An increased consentration of zinc in the blood.

Name: Hepatic amyloidosis
Desc: A form of amyloidosis that affects the liver.

Name: Renal fibrosis
Desc: Renal fibrosis is the consequence of an excessive accumulation of extracellular matrix that occurs in virtually every type of chronic kidney disease.

Name: Eruption failure
Desc: A tooth which does not erupt within the teeth eruption timeline and after the loss of eruption potential.

Name: Complete atrioventricular canal defect
Desc: A congenital heart defect characterized by a specific combination of heart defects with a common atrioventricular valve, primum atrial septal defect and inlet ventricular septal defect.

Name: Partial absence of thumb
Desc: The absence of a phalangeal segment of a thumb.
Synonyms: Aplasia of the phalanges of the thumb

Name: Unilateral radial aplasia
Desc: Missing radius bone on one side only associated with congenital failure of development.

Name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex III
Desc: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex III, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

Name: Multifocal seizures
Desc: Seizures that start from several different areas of the brain (i.e., with multiple ictal onset locations).

Name: EEG with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges
Desc: Periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs)are periodic, lateralized, and epileptiform. PLEDs show a relatively constant interval between discharges (0.5 to 3 seconds).

Name: Subependymal cysts
Desc: Cerebral cysts, usually located in the wall of the caudate nucleus or in the caudothalamic groove. They are found in up to 5.2% of all neonates, using transfontanellar ultrasound in the first days of life.

Name: Ovarian dermoid cyst
Desc: An cystic ovarian teratoma composed of dermal and epidermal elements and containing tissue components including hair, teeth, bone, thyroid, and others.

Name: Hyperextensible thumb
Desc: The ability of the thumb joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

Name: Abnormal thyroid hormone level
Desc: Any deviation from the normal range of the hormones produced by the thyroid gland.

Name: Abnormal periodontium morphology
Desc: Any abnormality of the periodontium.

Name: Abnormal sacral segmentation
Desc: An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation of sacral vertebrae during development.

Name: Hyperextensibility at wrists
Desc: The ability of the wrist joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

Name: Abnormal cartilage collagen
Desc: Abnormal morphology of collagen fibers in cartilage. In cartilage, collagen II, actually a collagen II:IX:XI heterofibril, is by far the most important type of collagen. A number of abnormalities may be appreciated by electron micrography or biochemical investigations, including sparse collagen fibers in the cartilage matrix.

Name: Keratan sulfate excretion in urine
Desc: An increased concentration of keratan sulfate in the urine.

Name: Enlarged metaphyses
Desc: Abnormal increase in size of one or more metaphyses.
Synonyms: Enlarged wide portion of a long bone

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the extremities
Desc: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the extremities.

Name: Cervical spine instability
Desc: An abnormal lack of stability of the cervical spine.

Name: Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment
Desc: A type of retinal detachment associated with a retinal tear, that is, with a break in the retina that allows fluid to pass from the vitreous space into the subretinal space between the sensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.

Name: Dumbbell-shaped femur
Desc: The femur is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.

Name: Lens luxation
Desc: Complete dislocation of the lens of the eye.

Name: Nail-biting
Desc: Habitual biting of one's own fingernails.

Name: Recurrent pyelonephritis
Desc: Repeated episodes of pyelonephritis.

Name: Abnormal elasticity of skin
Desc: Any abnormal increase or reduction in skin elasticity.

Name: Total anomalous pulmonary venous return
Desc: Total anomalous pulmonary venous return refers to a congenital malformation in which all four pulmonary veins do not connect normally to the left atrium, but instead drain abnormally to the right atrium.

Name: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the central nervous system
Aceruloplasminemia
Desc: Absence of ceruloplasmin in the blood.

Name: Symblepharon
Desc: A partial or complete adhesion of the palpebral conjunctiva of the eyelid to the bulbar conjunctiva of the eyeball.
Synonyms: Eyelid adhesion to globe of eye

Name: Elevated circulating ribitol concentration
Desc: An increase above the normal concentration of ribitol in the blood.
Synonyms: Increased level of ribitol in serum

Name: Increased level of ribose in urine
Desc: An increase in the level of ribose in the urine.

Name: Abnormal coronary artery course
Desc: An abnormal path of a coronary artery.

Name: Hypermobility of toe joints
Desc: An ability of the toe joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

Name: Abnormal morphology of the great vessels
Desc: A structural anomaly affecting a blood vessel involved in the circulation of the heart, i.e., the superior or inferior vena cava, the pulmonary arteries, the pulmonary veins, and the aorta.

Name: Calf muscle hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the muscuklature of the calf.

Name: Urethral atresia, male
Desc: Congenital anomaly characterized by closure or failure to develop an opening in the urethra in males.

Name: Urethral fistula
Desc: The presence of an abnormal connection between the urethra and another organ or the skin.

Name: Bilateral renal hypoplasia
Desc: Two sided hypoplasia of the kidney.

Name: Cloacal abnormality
Desc: A developmental anomaly associated with the failure of rectum, vagina, and bladder to separate.

Name: Rectal fistula
Desc: The presence of a fistula affecting the rectum.

Name: Deep dermal perivascular inflammatory infiltrate
Desc: Numerous lymphocytes surrounding blood vessels in the deep part of the dermis.

Name: Varicocele
Desc: A varicocele is a widening of the veins along the spermatic cord, leading to enlarged, twisted veins in the scrotum, and manifested clinically by a painless testicle lump, scrotal swelling, or bulge in the scrotum.

Name: Pulp obliteration
Desc: Mineralized substance filling the entire dental pulp space.
Synonyms: Narrowing of pulp chamber of tooth
Reduced size of pulp chamber of tooth

Name: Abnormal dental root morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the dental root.

Name: Generalized hypoplasia of dental enamel
Desc: A generalized form of developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.

Name: Short dental root
Desc: Tooth root length more than 2 SD below mean, or subjectively apparently decreased tooth root length.

Name: Monochromacy
Desc: Complete color blindness, a complete inability to distinguish colors. Affected persons cannot perceive colors, but only shades of gray.

Name: Undetectable light-adapted electroretinogram
Desc: No detectable response to the light-adapted 3.0 ERG (single-flash cone response). This type of ERG measures responses of the cone system; a-waves arise from cone photoreceptors and cone off-bipolar cells; the b-wave comes from On- and Off-cone bipolar cells.

Name: Inner retinal layer loss on macular OCT
Eccentric visual fixation
Desc: A uniocular condition in which there is fixation of an object by a point other than the fovea. This point adopts the principal visual direction. The degree of the eccentric fixation is defined by its distance from the fovea in degrees.

Name: Retinal pigment epithelial atrophy
Desc: Atrophy (loss or wasting) of the retinal pigment epithelium observed on fundoscopy or fundus imaging.

Name: Honeycomb palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
Desc: Abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles with an honeycomb pattern.

Name: Striatal T2 hyperintensity
Desc: Abnormally bright T2 signal from the striatum on brain magnetic resonance imaging.

Name: Reduced protein S activity
Desc: An abnormality of coagulation related to a decreased concentration of vitamin K-dependent protein S. Protein S is a cofactor of protein C.

Name: Macular purpura
Desc: Purpura that is flat (non-palpable, not raised).

Name: Absent scrotum
Desc: Congenital absence of the scrotum.

Name: Block vertebrae
Desc: Congenital synostosis between two or more adjacent vertebrae (partial or complete fusion of adjacent vertabral bodies).

Name: Chronic neutropenia
Desc: Neutropenia with an absolute neutrophil count (ANC) less than 1,500,000,000/L lasting for more than 3 months.

Name: Transient neutropenia
Desc: A transient reduction in the number of neutrophils in the peripheral blood. Transient neutropenia is most commonly associated with viral infections, but other causes include drugs and autoimmunity.

Name: Abnormal right ventricle morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the right ventricle of the heart.

Name: Abnormal femoral torsion
Desc: Femoral torsion, also known as femoral rotation or femoral version, refers to the twist between the proximal and distal parts of the femur on the transverse plane. Femoral anteversion averages between 30-40 degress at birth, and between 8-14 degrees in adults. This term applies if the amount of femoral torsion deviates from this range.

Name: Secretory IgA deficiency
Desc: Deficiency of secretory IgA (polymers of 2-4 IgA monomers are linked by two additional chains) and is the primary antibody response at the mucosal level, where it forms immune complexes with pathogens and allergens.

Name: Broad lateral eyebrow
Desc: Regional increase in the width (height) of the lateral eyebrow.

Name: Bilateral renal dysplasia
Desc: A bilateral form of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.

Name: Unilateral lung agenesis
Desc: Lack of development of one lung.

Name: Abnormal common carotid artery morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the common carotid arteries, which provide the arterial supply to the head and neck and give rise to the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the common carotid artery

Name: Mild malformation of cortical development
Desc: A malformation of cortical development characterized by mild abnormalities of the cortex: excessive heterotopic neurons in Layer 1 or microscopic neuronal clusters or excess of single neurons of normal morphology in deep white matter.

Name: Severe photosensitivity
Desc: A severe degree of photosensitivity of the skin.

Name: Focal sensory seizure with visual features
Desc: A seizure characterized by elementary visual hallucinations such as flashing or flickering lights/colours, or other shapes, simple patterns, scotomata, or amaurosis as its first clinical manifestation.

Name: Multiple long-bone exostoses
Desc: Multiple exostoses originating in long bones.
Synonyms: Multiple exostoses of long tubular bones

Name: Abnormality of globe size
Desc: An abnormality in the size of the ocular globe (eyeball).

Name: Obstruction of the superior vena cava
Desc: Blockage of blood flow through the superior vena cava (SVC). Because the venous drainage from the upper extremities, upper thorax and head is obstructed, SVC obstruction presents with symptoms related to engorgement of these areas. Both the degree of SVC compromise and the extent of collateral veins determine the varied clinical presentation, which can be as mild as slight facial and upper extremity edema or as dire as intracranial swelling, seizures, hemodynamic instability and tracheal obstruction.

Name: Accessory carpal bones
Desc: The presence of more than the normal number of carpal bones.

Name: Perifollicular hyperkeratosis
Desc: Increased amount of keratin (visible as white scales) surrounding hair follicles.

Name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial ATP synthase complex
Desc: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial proton-transporting ATP synthase complex, which makes ATP via oxidative phosphorylation, and is sometimes described as Complex V of the electron transport chain.

Name: Urinary glycosaminoglycan excretion
Desc: Excretion of glycosaminoglycan in the urine. Glycosaminoglycans are long unbranched polysaccharides consisting of a repeating disaccharide unit.

Name: Lumbar kyphosis
Desc: Over curvature of the lumbar region.

Name: Sydney crease
Desc: Extension of the proximal transverse crease (five finger crease) to the ulnar edge of the palm.

Name: Recurrent infantile hypoglycemia
Desc: Recurrent episodes of decreased concentration of glucose in the blood occurring during the infantile period.
Synonyms: Recurrent low blood sugar in infant

Name: Megarectum
Desc: An abnormal dilation of the rectum. There is a large filled rectum as a result of underlying innervation or muscular abnormalities, which remains after disimpaction of the rectum.

Name: Osteolysis of talus
Desc: Osteolysis affecting the talus.

Name: Dense metaphyseal bands
Desc: Dense radiopaque bands of bone which are thicker than the adjacent diaphyseal cortex and may form at the metaphysis of growing bones. They appear on radiographs as bone that is more radiopaque that the adjacent diaphyseal cortex.

Name: Posterior Y-sutural cataract
Desc: A type of sutural cataract in which the opacity follows the posterior Y suture.

Name: Posterior wedging of vertebral bodies
Desc: An abnormality of the shape of vertebrae, such that they are wedge-shaped (narrow towards the back).

Name: Hemifacial hypoplasia
Desc: Unilateral underdevelopment of the facial tissues, including muscles and bones.
Synonyms: Decrease in size of half of face
Decrease in size of one side of the face
Decreased size of half of the face
Decreased size of one side of the face
Shrinking of one side of the face

Name: Ectopic posterior pituitary
Desc: An abnormal anatomical location of the posterior lobe of the hypophysis, also known as the neurohypophysis. The posterior pituitary is normally present in the dorsal portion of the sella turcica, but when ectopic is usually near the median eminence. This defect is likely to be due to abnormal migration during embryogenesis.

Name: Cleft maxillary alveolus
Desc: Alveolar cleft is a tornado-shaped bone defect in the maxillary arch. Alveolar cleft occurs in response to divergence from normal development during frontonasal prominence growth, contact, and fusion. The most common alveolar portion of the cleft is located between the lateral incisor and the canine.

Name: Abnormal cricoid cartilage morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality of a cricoid cartilage, that is, of the ring-shaped cartilage of the larynx.

Name: Duplication of phalanx of hand
Desc: This term applies if one or more of the phalanges of the hand are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.

Name: Cerebellopontine angle arachnoid cyst
Desc: An arachnoid cyst located at the margin of the cerebellum and pons.

Name: Cervical hemivertebrae
Desc: Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the cervical spine.

Name: Broad phalanges of the hand
Desc: Increased width of the phalanges of the hand.
Synonyms: Widening of phalanges of the hand

Name: Increased intervertebral space
Desc: An increase in the vertical distance between adjacent vertebral bodies, observed as an increase in the intervertebral disc space.

Name: Broad ischia
Desc: Increased width of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

Name: Erythroid dysplasia
Desc: Dysplasia in the erythroid lineage, which presents with a variety of morphological changes in the bone marrow, including nuclear budding or irregular nuclear contour in erythroblasts.

Name: Megakaryocyte dysplasia
Desc: The presence of micro-megakaryocytes, hypo-lobed, or non-lobed nuclei in megakaryocytes of all sizes and multiple, widely-separated nuclei.

Name: Elevated serum transaminases during infections
Desc: Elevations of the levels of SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) that occur during infections.

Name: Cellular urinary casts
Desc: A type of urinary cast composed of cells incorporated in a protein matrix. The cells can be those found in the urinary sediment (erythrocytes, leuklocytes, renal tubular epithelial cells).

Name: Increased CSF interferon alpha
Desc: Increased concentration of interferon alpha in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Name: Chilblains
Desc: Chilblains, also called perniosis, are an inflammatory skin condition related to an abnormal vascular response to the cold. We are unaware of a reliable estimate of incidence. It typically presents as tender, pruritic red or bluish lesions located symmetrically on the dorsal aspect of the fingers, toes, ears and nose. Less commonly, reports describe involvement of the thighs and buttocks. The lesions present hours after exposure to cold and usually resolve spontaneously in one to three weeks.

Name: Increased serum interferon-gamma level
Desc: An elevation in the concentration of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.

Name: Chronic CSF lymphocytosis
Desc: Chronic cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) lymphocytosis is defined as the finding, in at least two serial CSF examinations, of more than 5 cells per cubic millimeter.

Name: Neonatal alloimmune thrombocytopenia
Desc: Low platelet count associated with maternal platelet-specific alloantibodies.

Name: Addictive behavior
Desc: A recurrent pattern of behavior that is characeterized by the failure to resist an impulse, drive, or temptation to perform an act that is harmful to the person or to others. The repetitive engagement in these behaviors ultimately interferes with functioning in other domains.

Name: Abnormal gallbladder morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the gallbladder.

Name: Hemobilia
Desc: Bleeding into the biliary tree.

Name: Increased axial length of the globe
Desc: Abnormal largeness of the eye with an axial length > 2.5 standard deviations from population mean.
Synonyms: Increased front to back length of eyeball

Name: Marcus Gunn jaw winking synkinesis
Desc: Unilateral ptosis with associated upper eyelid contraction and contraction of either the external or the internal pterygoid muscle. It is thought to occur because of congenital miswiring of a branch of the fifth cranial nerve into the branch of the third cranial nerve supplying the levator muscle. In Marcus Gunn jaw winking synkinesis, elevation and even retraction of the affected eyelid is triggered by chewing, suction, lateral mandible movement, smiling, sternocleidomastoid contraction, protruding tongue, Valsalva manoeuvre and even by breathing.

Name: Acute monocytic leukemia
Desc: The accumulation of transformed primitive hematopoietic blast cells, which lose their ability of normal differentiation and proliferation.

Name: Abnormality of neutrophil morphology
Desc: An abnormal form or size of neutrophils.

Name: Myelokathexis
Desc: Impaired egress of mature neutrophils from bone marrow causing neutropenia.

Name: Cutaneous melanoma
Desc: The presence of a melanoma of the skin.

Name: Butterfly vertebral arch
Desc: Butterfly vertebrae have a cleft through the body of the vertebrae and a funnel shape at the ends.

Name: Reduced number of intrahepatic bile ducts
Desc: The presence of reduced numbers of intrahepatic bile duct than normal.

Name: Parietal foramina
Desc: The presence of symmetrical and circular openings (foramina) in the parietal bone ranging in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters wide.
Synonyms: Persistent foramina of the parietal bones

Name: Abnormal basophil morphology
Desc: Any structural abnormality or abnormal count of basophils.

Name: Abnormality of the nasal bone
Desc: An abnormality of the nasal bone, comprising the left nasal bone and the right nasal bone.

Name: Clinodactyly of the 3rd toe
Desc: Bending or curvature of a third toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

Name: Esophoria
Desc: A form of strabismus with both eyes turned inward to a relatively mild degree, usually defined as less than 10 prism diopters.

Name: Hypermanganesemia
Desc: An elevation above the normal concentration of manganese in the blood.

Name: Abnormal circulating copper concentration
Desc: An abnormal concentration of copper.

Name: Delayed eruption of permanent teeth
Desc: Delayed tooth eruption affecting the secondary dentition.

Name: Abnormality of the palmar creases
Desc: An abnormality of the creases of the skin of palm of hand.

Name: Vertebrobasilar dolichoectasia
Desc: Elongation, dilatation, and/or tortuosity of the vertebrobasilar segment. The definition of VBD includes: (i) diameter of basilar or vertebral artery over 4.5 mm; or (ii) deviation of any portion more than 10 mm from the shortest expected course; and (iii) length of basilar artery over 29.5 mm or length of intracranial vertebral artery over 23.5 mm.

Name: Equinus calcaneus
Desc: Abnormal plantar flexion of the calcaneus relative to the longitudinal axis of the tibia. This results in the angle between the long axis of the tibia and the long axis of the heel bone (calcaneus) being greater than 90 degrees.

Name: EEG with series of focal spikes
Desc: Focal spikes occurring for several seconds.

Name: Uterine leiomyosarcoma
Desc: The presence of a leiomyosarcoma of the uterus.

Name: Papillary renal cell carcinoma type 2
Desc: A type of papillary renal cell carcinoma in which the papillae are covered by large eosinophilic cells with pleomorphic nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and nuclear pseudostratification.

Name: Multiple cutaneous leiomyomas
Desc: The presence of multiple leiomyomas of the skin.

Name: Cutaneous leiomyoma
Desc: The presence of leiomyoma of the skin.

Name: Postlingual sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with onset after the acquisition of speech.

Name: Central primitive neuroectodermal tumor
Desc: A primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm that occurs in the central nervous system.

Name: Choroid plexus carcinoma
Desc: Intraventricular papillary neoplasm derived from choroid plexus epithelium. Plexus tumors are most common in the lateral and fourth ventricles; while 80% of lateral ventricle tumors present in children, fourth ventricle tumors are evenly distributed in all age groups. Clinically, choroid plexus tumors tend to cause hydrocephalus and increased intracranial pressure. Histologically, choroid plexus papillomas correspond to WHO grade I, choroid plexus carcinomas to WHO grade III.

Name: Choriocarcinoma
Desc: A malignant, trophoblastic and aggressive cancer, usually of the placenta. It is characterized by early hematogenous spread to the lungs and belongs to the far end of the spectrum of gestational trophoblastic disease (GTD), a subset of germ cell tumors.

Name: Posterior uveitis
Desc: Inflammation of the uveal tract in which the primary site of inflammation is the retina or choroid.

Name: Abnormal light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram
Desc: An abnormality of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.

Name: Lenticonus
Desc: A conical projection of the anterior or posterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.

Name: Abnormality of fundus pigmentation
Desc: Any anomaly of the pigmentation of the fundus, the posterior part of the eye including the retina and optic nerve.

Name: Ubiquitin-positive cerebral inclusion bodies
Desc: Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates that show positive staining with antibodies against ubiquitin within cells of the brain.

Name: Abnormal motor neuron morphology
Desc: Any structural anomaly that affects the motor neuron.

Name: Weakness of muscles of respiration
Desc: Reduced function of the muscles required to generate subatmospheric pressure in the thoracic cavity during breathing: the diaphragm, the external intercostal and the interchondral part of the internal intercostal muscles.

Name: Neoplasm of the oral cavity
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the oral cavity.

Name: Increased circulating T4 level
Desc: An elevation above the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).

Name: Increased circulating free T3
Desc: An elevated concentration of free 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the blood circulation.

Name: Increased fetal movement
Desc: An abnormal increase in quantity or strength of fetal movements.

Name: Pretibial myxedema
Desc: A diffuse, non-pitting edema and thickening of the skin usually on the anterior aspect of the lower legs spreading to the dorsum of the feet.

Name: Increased C-peptide level
Desc: An elevated concentration of C-peptide in the circulation. Since C-peptide is secreted in equimolar amounts to insulin, this feature correlates with increased insulin secretion.

Name: Precocious puberty in females
Desc: The onset of puberty before the age of 8 years in girls.

Name: Pulmonary artery dilatation
Desc: An abnormal widening of the diameter of the pulmonary artery.

Name: Kernicterus
Desc: Damage to cerebral nuclei caused in infants by highly increased levels of unconjugated bilirubin. The basal ganglia and brainstem nuclei could be shown to have a yellow staining historically in infants who died of kernicterus, that is, kernicterus is strictly speaking a pathological diagnosis. The presence of kernicterus may be inferred in infants with characteristic acute or chronic bilirubin-induced neurological dysfunction.

Name: Progressive conductive hearing impairment
Desc: A progressive type of conductive deafness.

Name: Abnormal fingertip morphology
Desc: An abnormal structure of the tip (end) of a finger.

Name: Acephalic spermatozoa
Desc: Spermatozoa with very small cranial ends devoid of any nuclear material, that is, lacking a typical sperm head.

Name: Abnormal sperm mid-piece morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the sperm mid-piece.

Name: Androgen insufficiency
Desc: Insufficient amount of androgenic activity.

Name: Mandibular osteomyelitis
Desc: Osteomyelitis of the lower jaw.

Name: Hepatic granulomatosis
Desc: The presence of multiple granulomas in the liver as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.

Name: Granulomatosis
Desc: A granulomatous inflammation leading to multiple granuloma formation, which is a specific type of inflammation. A granuloma is a focal compact collection of inflammatory cells, mononuclear cells predominating, usually as a result of the persistence of a non-degradable product and of active cell mediated hypersensitivity.

Name: Hypoammonemia
Desc: A decreased concentration of ammonia in the blood.

Name: Discoid lupus rash
Desc: Cutaneous lesion that develops as a dry, scaly, red patch that evolves to an indurated and hyperpigmented plaque with adherent scale. Scarring may result in central white patches (loss of pigmentation) and skin atrophy.

Name: Nail bed telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectases in the area of the nails.

Name: Abnormal abdomen morphology
Desc: A structural abnormality of the abdomen ('belly'), that is, the part of the body between the pelvis and the thorax.

Name: Pterygium of nails
Desc: Inward advance of skin over the nail plate.

Name: Mixed hypo- and hyperpigmentation of the skin
Nail bed hemorrhage
Desc: Small areas of bleeding (hemorrhage) under the fingernail or toenail.

Name: Abnormal breast morphology
