Desc: Any anomaly of the structure of the breast.

Name: Superficial dermal perivascular inflammatory infiltrate
Desc: Numerous lymphocytes surrounding blood vessels in the superfical part of the dermis.

Name: Neutrophilic infiltration of the skin
Desc: A predominantly neutrophilic infiltrate of the dermis and or epidermis (i.e., a large number of neutrophils inferred to have migrated into the skin).

Name: Digital pitting scar
Desc: Pinhole-sized concave depressions with hyperkeratosis in the skin of a finger or toe.

Name: Abnormality of the palm
Desc: An abnormality of the palm, that is, of the front of the hand.

Name: Dysplasia of the femoral head
Desc: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the femoral head.

Name: Multiple joint dislocation
Desc: Dislocation of many joints.

Name: Peripapillary atrophy
Desc: Thinning in the layers of the retina and retinal pigment epithelium around the optic nerve.

Name: Abnormal femoral head morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the femoral head.

Name: Subluxation of the small joints of the hand
Desc: A partial dislocation of some or all of the small joints of the hand.
Synonyms: Partial dislocation of small joints of hand

Name: Agenesis of pineal gland
Desc: Failure to develop of the pineal gland, defined clinically as the absence of the pineal gland with no indication of the pineal gland even having been present.

Name: Shoulder flexion contracture
Desc: Chronic reduction in active and passive mobility of the shoulder joint due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.

Name: Keratosis pilaris
Desc: An anomaly of the hair follicles of the skin that typically presents as small, rough, brown folliculocentric papules distributed over characteristic areas of the skin, particularly the outer-upper arms and thighs.

Name: Dislocated wrist
Desc: An injury of the wrist with displacement of any of the eight carpal bones.

Name: Sunken cheeks
Desc: Lack or loss of the soft tissues between the zygomata and mandible.

Name: Long uvula
Desc: Increased length of the uvula.

Name: Spontaneous rupture of the globe
Desc: Rupture of the eyeball not due to trauma.

Name: Atlantoaxial instability
Desc: Abnormally increased movement at the junction between the first cervical (atlas) and the second cervical (axis) vertebrae as a result of either a bony or ligamentous anomaly.

Name: Intestinal perforation
Desc: A hole (perforation) in the wall of the intestine.

Name: Pulmonary lymphangiomyomatosis
Desc: Infiltration of smooth muscle-like cells in lymph vessels as well as the lung (pleura, alveolar septa, bronchi, pulmonary vessels and lymphatics as well as lymph nodes, especially in posterior mediastinum and retroperitoneum). Focal emphysema can develop because of airway narrowing, and the thoracic duct may be obliterated. Pulmonary lymphangiomyomatosis may lead to multiple small cysts with a hamartomatous proliferation of smooth muscle in their walls.

Name: Giant melanosomes in melanocytes
Desc: The presence of large spherical melanosomes (1 to 6 micrometer in diameter) in the cytoplasm of melanocytes.

Name: Esophageal web
Desc: Thin (2-3mm) membranes of normal esophageal tissue consisting of mucosa and submucosa that can be congenital or acquired. Congenital webs commonly appear in the middle and inferior third of the esophagus, and they are more likely to be circumferential with a central or eccentric orifice. Acquired webs are much more common than congenital webs and typically appear in the cervical area (postcricoid). Clinical symptoms of this condition are selective (solid more than liquids) dysphagia, thoracic pain, nasopharyngeal reflux, aspiration, perforation and food impaction (the last two are very rare).

Name: Intra-oral hyperpigmentation
Desc: Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the mucosa of the mouth.

Name: Geophagia
Desc: The practice of eating earth or soil-like substrates such as clay or chalk.

Name: Decreased serum zinc
Desc: A reduced concentration of zinc in the blood.

Name: Drumstick terminal phalanges
Desc: Rounding and broadening of the tufts of the distal phalanges.

Name: Periventricular white matter hypodensities
Desc: Multiple areas of darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.

Name: Glomerular subendothelial electron-dense deposits
Desc: Electron dense deposits at the glomerular basement membrane,

Name: Eating-induced seizure
Desc: A seizure precipitated by aspects of anticipating food, eating itself, or the post-prandial period.

Name: Myoclonic absence seizure
Desc: Myoclonic absence seizure is a type of generalized non-motor (absence) seizure characterised by an interruption of ongoing activities, a blank stare and rhythmic three-per-second myoclonic movements, causing ratcheting abduction of the upper limbs leading to progressive arm elevation, and associated with 3 Hz generalized spike-wave discharges on the electroencephalogram. Duration is typically 10-60 s. Whilst impairment of consciousness may not be obvious the ILAE classified this seizure as a generalized non-motor seizure in 2017.

Name: Abnormal tongue physiology
Desc: Any functional anomaly of the tongue.

Name: Tapered toe
Desc: The gradual reduction in girth of the toe from proximal to distal.

Name: Non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma
Desc: A type of status epilepticus without prominent motor symptoms in the absence of coma.

Name: High maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein
Desc: An abnormally high concentration of serum alpha-fetoprotein as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

Name: Abnormality of the frontal bone
Desc: An abnormality of the frontal bone.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the bone of the forehead

Name: Dissociated sensory loss
Desc: A pattern of sensory loss with selective loss of touch sensation and proprioception without loss of pain and temperature, or vice-versa.

Name: Entrapment neuropathy
Desc: Malfunction of a peripheral nerve resulting from mechanical compression of the nerve roots from internal or external causes and leading to a conduction block or axonal loss.

Name: Hypopigmented macule
Desc: A white or lighter patch of skin that may appear anywhere on the body and are caused by decreased skin pigmentation.

Name: Abnormality of the upper respiratory tract
Desc: An abnormality of the upper respiratory tract.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the upper respiratory tract

Name: Abnormality of the seventh cranial nerve
Desc: Abnormality of the seventh cranial nerve sometimes also referred to as the facial nerve.

Name: Abnormality of facial skeleton
Desc: An abnormality of one or more of the set of bones that make up the facial skeleton.

Name: Paralytic lagophthalmos
Desc: A type of lagophthalmos that occurs in association with facial nerve palsy.

Name: Testicular mass
Desc: An abnormal bulge or lump in a testis. A testicular mass has a long differential diagnosis including testicular torsion, epididymitis, acute orchitis, strangulated hernia and testicular cancer.

Name: Widened cerebral subarachnoid space
Desc: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebrum.

Name: Concentric hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
Desc: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with an symmetrical and concentric pattern of hypertrophy.

Name: Abnormal insulin level
Desc: An abnormal concentration of insulin in the body.

Name: Elevated hemoglobin A1c
Desc: An increased concentration of hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c), which is the product of nonenzymatic attachment of a hexose molecule to the N-terminal amino acid of the hemoglobin molecule. This reaction is dependent on blood glucose concentration, and therefore reflects the mean glucose concentration over the previous 8 to 12 weeks. The HbA1c level provides a better indication of long-term glycemic control than one-time blood or urinary glucose measurements.

Name: Urinary hesitancy
Desc: Difficulty in beginning the process of urination.

Name: Abnormal circulating corticosterone level
Desc: An abnormality of the concentration of corticosterone in the blood.

Name: Decreased circulating lipoprotein lipase concentration
Desc: Reduction in the level of lipoprotein lipase in the blood.

Name: Hypoamylasemia
Desc: Decreased level of amylase in the blood, an enzyme which helps digest glycogen and starch. It is produced mainly in the pancreas and salivary glands.

Name: Semilobar holoprosencephaly
Desc: A type of holoprosencephaly in which the left and right frontal and parietal lobes are fused and the interhemispheric fissure is only present posteriorly.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the thumb
Abnormality of the external nose
Desc: An abnormality of the external nose.

Name: Rectourethral fistula
Desc: An abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the urethra.

Name: Hemisacrum
Desc: A hemisacral defect involving the sacral vertebrae S2 to S5. In hemisacrum, the first sacral vertebra is intact and there is agenesis involving only S2-S5.

Name: Abnormality of mucopolysaccharide metabolism
Desc: An abnormality of the metabolism of mucopolysaccharide.

Name: Hypoplasia of the capital femoral epiphysis
Desc: Underdevelopment of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Synonyms: Underdevelopment of the innermost thighbone end part

Name: Spontaneous pneumothorax
Desc: Pneumothorax occurring without traumatic injury to the chest or lung.

Name: Abnormality of malar bones
Desc: An abnormality of the malar surface of the zygomatic bone and including the frontal process of maxilla.

Name: Dilatation of an abdominal artery
Desc: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in an artery that originates from he abdominal aorta.

Name: Aortic tortuosity
Desc: Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the aorta.

Name: Flat cornea
Desc: Cornea plana is an abnormally flat shape of the cornea such that the normal protrusion of the cornea from the sclera is missing. The reduced corneal curvature can lead to hyperopia, and a hazy corneal limbus and arcus lipoides may develop at an early age.

Name: Intervertebral disk calcification
Desc: The presence of abnormal calcium deposition of the intervertebral disk.

Name: Large cafe-au-lait macules with irregular margins
Desc: Large hypermelanotic macules with jagged borders.

Name: Abnormal endocrine physiology
Desc: Any anomaly of the function of the endocrine system.

Name: Monostotic fibrous dysplasia
Desc: Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in only one bone.

Name: Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia
Desc: Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in many bones throughout of the body. Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia is a cardinal feature of McCune-Albright syndrome.

Name: Aneurysmal bone cyst
Desc: Radiographic features include a dilated, radiolucent lesion typically located eccentrically within the metaphyseal portion of the bone, with fluid levels visible on magnetic resonance imaging.

Name: Cutaneous myxoma
Desc: A myxoma originating in the skin.

Name: Left atrial enlargement
Desc: Increase in size of the left atrium.

Name: Toxemia of pregnancy
Desc: Pregnancy-induced toxic reactions of the mother that can be as harmless as slight Maternal hypertension or as life threatening as Eclampsia.

Name: Hitchhiker thumb
Desc: With the hand relaxed and the thumb in the plane of the palm, the axis of the thumb forms an angle of at least 90 degrees with the long axis of the hand.

Name: Excessive femoral anteversion
Desc: An increased degree of femoral version, which is defined as the angular difference between axis of femoral neck and transcondylar axis of the knee. Thus, femoral anteversion is an inward twisting of the femur that causes the knees and feet to turn inward.

Name: Facial midline hemangioma
Desc: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, occurring in the midline region of the face.

Name: Distal tapering femur
Synonyms: Tapering of outermost end of thighbone

Name: Vertebral hypoplasia
Desc: Small, underdeveloped vertebral bodies.

Name: Absent humerus
Desc: Missing humerus bone associated with congenital failure of development.
Synonyms: Absent long bone in upper arm

Name: Epiphyseal stippling of the humerus
Desc: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the humeral epiphysis.
Synonyms: Stippled ossification of the humeral epiphyses

Name: Abnormal cervical curvature
Desc: The presence of an abnormal curvature of the cervical vertebral column.

Name: Club-shaped distal femur
Desc: An abnormal conformation of the femur that becomes gradually enlarged towards the distal end. This feature affects the distal femoral metaphysis and epiphysis.

Name: Maternal fever in pregnancy
Desc: The occurence of an elevated body temperature of the mother during pregnancy.

Name: Abnormality of the calvaria
Desc: Abnormality of the calvaria, which is the roof of the skull formed by the frontal bone, parietal bones, and occipital bone.

Name: Posterior pituitary agenesis
Desc: Absence of the neurohypophysis owing to a developmental defect.

Name: Episodic hypokalemia
Desc: An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood occurring periodically with a return to normal between the episodes.

Name: Deep white matter hypodensities
Desc: Multiple areas of darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the deep cerebral white matter.

Name: Retinal arteriolar tortuosity
Desc: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal arterioles.

Name: Focal sensory seizure
Desc: A focal sensory seizure is a type seizure beginning with a subjective sensation.

Name: Alien limb phenomenon
Desc: Alien limb phenomenon refers to involuntary motor activity of a limb in conjunction with the feeling of estrangement from that limb.

Name: Episodic pain
Desc: Intermittent pain, i.e., pain that occurs occasionally and at irregular intervals.

Name: Increased tear production
Desc: Increased lacrimation owing to overproduction of tears.

Name: Reduced MHC II surface expression
Desc: A reduction from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.

Name: Recurrent Staphylococcus aureus infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to Staphylococcus aureus infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Staphylococcus aureus infection.

Name: Recurrent protozoan infections
Desc: Increased susceptibility to protozoan infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of protozoan infection.

Name: Decreased circulating beta-2-microglobulin level
Desc: Reduced concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.

Name: Chronic hepatitis due to cryptosporidium infection
Desc: Chronic hepatitis associated with infection by cryptosporidia, as demonstrated (for example) by immunohistochemistry of liver tissue.
Synonyms: Hepatitis, chronic, due to cryptosporidium infection

Name: Abnormal atrioventricular valve physiology
Desc: Any functional defect of the mitral or tricuspid valve.

Name: Decreased movement range in interphalangeal joints
Synonyms: Decreased range of movement range in hinge joints

Name: Telangiectases of the cheeks
Desc: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin of the cheeks.

Name: Abnormal epiphyseal ossification
Desc: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of an epiphysis.
Synonyms: Abnormal maturation of the end part of a bone
Abnormality of the mineralisation or ossification of the epiphyses

Name: Oppositional defiant disorder
Desc: An enduring pattern of uncooperative, defiant, and hostile behavior toward authority figures that does not involve major antisocial violations, is not accounted for by the child's developmental stage, and results in significant functional impairment. A certain level of oppositional behavior is common in children and adolescents.

Name: Adenoiditis
Desc: An inflammation of the adenoid tissue.

Name: Anterior beaking of lower thoracic vertebrae
Desc: Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the lower thoracic vertebral bodies.

Name: Laryngeal carcinoma
Desc: A carcinoma of the larynx.

Name: Salivary gland neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a salivary gland.

Name: Single fiber EMG abnormality
Desc: Abnormality in single fiber EMG recording, a technique that allows identification of action potentials (APs) from individual muscle fibers.

Name: Muscle specific kinase antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against muscle specific kinase (anti-MuSK Ab).

Name: Frontalis muscle weakness
Desc: Reduced strength of the frontalis muscle (which is located on the forehead).

Name: Apneic episodes precipitated by illness, fatigue, stress
Desc: Recurrent episodes of apnea that are precipitated by factors such as illness, fatigue, or stress.
Synonyms: Episodic apnea induced by febrile illness or stress

Name: Nasal regurgitation
Desc: Regurgitation of milk through the nose.

Name: Narrow jaw
Desc: Bigonial distance (lower facial width) more than 2 standard deviations below the mean (objective); or an apparently decreased width of the lower jaw (mandible) when viewed from the front (subjective).

Name: Toe extensor amyotrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the extensor digitorum longus muscles, which mediate extension of the toes.

Name: High maternal serum chorionic gonadotropin
Desc: An abnormally high concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

Name: Fusion of the left and right thalami
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by fusion of the left and right halves of the thalamus.

Name: Abnormal circulating leucine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal circulation of leucine in the blood circulation.

Name: Bowing of the vocal cords
Desc: Bowing (abnormal curvature) of the vocal folds.

Name: Symmetrical, oval parietal bone defects
Synonyms: Symmetrical, oval defects in the parietal bone

Name: Reduced FEV1/FVC ratio
Desc: Abnormally low FEV1/FVC (FEV1 - forced expiratory volume in 1 second; FVC forced vital capacity).
Synonyms: Obstructive deficit on pulmonary function test
Obstructive deficit on pulmonary function testing

Name: Halitosis
Desc: Noticeably unpleasant odors exhaled in breathing.

Name: Scrotal pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the scrotum.

Name: Vulvodynia
Desc: Pain in the vulvar area

Name: Neoplasm of the genitourinary tract
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genitourinary system.

Name: Cerebellar hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage into the parenchyma of the cerebellum.

Name: Lip discoloration
Desc: Lightening or darkening of the lips from their usual coloring.

Name: Congenital giant melanocytic nevus
Desc: The giant congenital nevus is greater than 8 cm in size, pigmented and often hairy. A giant congenital nevus is smaller in infants and children, but it usually continues to grow with the child.

Name: Thin glomerular basement membrane
Desc: Decreased thickness of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM), measured from endothelial to visceral epithelial plasma membrane and mainly attributable to a decrease in thickness of the lamina densa, generally to an overall thickness more than 2 standard deviations less than that of the normal mean GBM thickness for health age- and sex matched individuals. May be focal or diffuse, although the term thin GBMs generally implies thinning of over 50% of GBMs.

Name: Glomerular basement membrane lamellation
Desc: Presence of abnormal additional layers of the basement membrane of the glomerulus.
Synonyms: Lamellation of the glomerular basement membrane

Name: IgA deposition in the glomerulus
Desc: The presence of immunoglobulin A deposits in the glomerulus.

Name: Thickened glomerular basement membrane
Desc: Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM), reflecting an increase in thickness (subjective estimate) of the basal lamina of the glomerulus of the kidney.

Name: Glomerular C3 deposition
Desc: The presence of complement 3 deposits in the glomerulus.

Name: Thickening of glomerular capillary wall
Desc: Widening of the wall of capillary blood vessels in the glomerulus. This feature may be produced by deposits and other changes affecting either subepithelial and subendothelial regions or the glomerular basement membrane itself.

Name: Absent vertebra
Desc: A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies.

Name: Bifid sternum
Desc: The sternal cleft is a rare congenital anomaly resulting from a fusion failure of the sternum.

Name: Limited knee flexion
Desc: Reduced ability to flex (bend) the knee joint.

Name: Hypoplastic nasal bridge
Synonyms: Decreased size of bridge of nose

Name: Flared iliac wing
Desc: Widening of the ilium ala, that is of the wing of the ilium, combined with external rotation, leading to a flared appearance of the iliac wing.

Name: Elevated urinary catecholamines
Desc: An increased concentration of catecholamine in the urine.

Name: Chronic myelogenous leukemia
Desc: A myeloproliferative disorder characterized by increased proliferation of the granulocytic cell line without the loss of their capacity to differentiate.

Name: Bilateral vestibular Schwannoma
Desc: A bilateral vestibular Schwannoma (acoustic neurinoma).

Name: Mononeuropathy
Desc: A focal lesion of a single peripheral nerve. Damage to a sensory nerve is accompanied by sensory impairment of all modalities in the affected anatomic distribution.

Name: Cortical cataract
Desc: A cataract which affects the layer of the lens surrounding the nucleus, i.e., the lens cortex. It is identified by its unique wedge or spoke appearance.

Name: Glioma
Desc: The presence of a glioma, which is a neoplasm of the central nervous system originating from a glial cell (astrocytes or oligodendrocytes).

Name: Sensorimotor polyneuropathy affecting arms more than legs
Hyperostosis frontalis interna
Desc: Bony overgrowth of the internal (endosteal) surface of the frontal bone.
Synonyms: Enlargement of the inner surface of the frontal bone
Excessive growth of inner surface of the frontal bone
Hyperostosis of the internal surface of the frontal bone
Hypertrophy of the internal surface of the frontal bone
Increased ossification of the internal surface of the frontal bone
Overgrowth of the inner surface of the frontal bone
Overgrowth of the inside of the frontal bone
Thick inner surface of the frontal bone
Thick internal surface of the frontal bone

Name: Chronic bronchitis
Desc: Chronic inflammation of the bronchi.

Name: Abnormal liver physiology
Desc: Any functional anomaly of the liver.

Name: Hyoplasia of the Leydig cells
Desc: Underdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.

Name: Recurrent cystitis
Desc: Repeated infections of the urinary bladder.

Name: Testicular fibrosis
Desc: Formation of excess connective tissue in the testicle.

Name: Abnormal coronary artery physiology
Desc: Any anomaly of the function of a coronary artery.

Name: Aplasia of the sweat glands
Desc: Absence of the sweat glands.

Name: Trophic limb changes
Desc: Trophic changes occurring in a limb.

Name: Abnormality of lower limb joint
Synonyms: Abnormality of the joints of the lower limbs

Name: Tongue pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the tongue.

Name: EEG with spike-wave complexes (2.5-3.5 Hz)
Desc: The presence of complexes of spikes and waves (2.5-3.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).

Name: Punding
Desc: Punding is a stereotypical motor behavior characterized by an intense fascination with repetitive, excessive and non-goal oriented handling, and examining of objects.

Name: Pili canaliculi
Desc: Uncombable hair.

Name: Low cholesterol esterification rate
Desc: A reduction in the rate of cholesterol esterification.

Name: Decreased number of small peripheral myelinated nerve fibers
Synonyms: Decreased number of small peripheral myelinated nerve fibres

Name: Comedo
Desc: A clogged cutaneous sebaceous follicle, which is a cutaneous gland that secretes sebum (usually into a hair follicle).

Name: Aplasia of the semicircular canal
Desc: Absence of the semicircular canal.

Name: Vascular neoplasm
Desc: A benign or malignant neoplasm (tumour) originating in the vascular system.

Name: Hypergastrinemia
Desc: An elevated amount of gastrin in the blood.

Name: Pancreatic endocrine tumor
Desc: A neuroendocrine tumor originating in a hormone-producing cell (islet cell) of the pancreas.

Name: Trichilemmoma
Desc: A benign tumour originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.

Name: Thyroid C cell hyperplasia
Desc: An abnormal growth of parafollicular (C-cells) cells.

Name: Elevated urinary vanillylmandelic acid
Desc: An increased concentration of vanillylmandelic acid in the urine.

Name: Cervical neoplasm
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterine cervix.

Name: Prominent corneal nerve fibers
Desc: Abnormal prominence of the corneal nerve fibers.

Name: Ganglioneuromatosis
Desc: Hyperplastic submucosal and myenteric plexus containing an increased number of ganglion cells, glial cells and nerve fibers.

Name: Multiple mucosal neuromas
Desc: Multiple painful, dome-shaped, translucent pink to skin-colored papules on oral mucosa. Histologically, the lesions may demonstrate dermal proliferation of well-demarcated nerve bundles associated with abundant mucin and surrounded by a distinct perineural sheath.

Name: Cutaneous lichen amyloidosis
Desc: Lichen amyloidosis presents with multiple localized or rarely generalized, hyperpigmented grouped papules with a predilection for the shins, calves, ankles, and dorsa of the feet and thighs.

Name: Skin fissure
Desc: A clearly-defined and roughly linear cleavage in the skin that usually extends to the dermis.

Name: Hypoplasia of lymphatic vessels
Desc: Congenital underdevelopment of lymph vessels.

Name: Calcification of the interosseus membrane of the forearm
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in the fibrous sheet that connects the radius and the ulna.

Name: Enlarged vertebral pedicles
Desc: Increased size of the vertebral pedicle.

Name: Multiple rib fractures
Desc: More than one fracture of the ribs.

Name: Noncommunicating hydrocephalus
Desc: A form of hydrocephalus in which the flow of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the cerebral ventricular system or in the outlets of the CSF to the arachnoid space is obstructed.

Name: Claustrophobia
Desc: An abnormal fear of being in a closed or narrow space with no escape.

Name: Separation insecurity
Desc: Fears of rejection by and/or separation from significant others, associated with fears of excessive dependency and complete loss of autonomy.

Name: U-Shaped upper lip vermilion
Desc: Gentle upward curve of the upper lip vermilion such that the center is placed well superior to the commissures.

Name: Elevated circulating glutaric acid concentration
Desc: An increased concentration of glutaric acid in the blood.

Name: Normochromic microcytic anemia
Desc: A type of anemia characterized by an normal concentration of hemoglobin in the erythrocytes and lower than normal size of the erythrocytes.

Name: Diaphragmatic eventration
Desc: A congenital failure of muscular development of part or all of one or both hemidiaphragms, resulting in superior displacement of abdominal viscera and altered lung development.

Name: Abnormality of the femoral metaphysis
Desc: An anomaly of the femoral metaphysis.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the wide portion of the femoral bone

Name: Acute colitis
Desc: An acute and self-limited inflammatory disease of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum).

Name: Posterior cortical cataract
Desc: A cataract that affects the posterior part of the cortex of the lens.

Name: Tritanomaly
Desc: Difficulty distinguishing between yellow and blue, possible related to dysfunction of the S photopigment.

Name: Red-green dyschromatopsia
Desc: Difficulty with discriminating red and green hues.

Name: Anterior cortical cataract
Desc: A cataract that affects the anterior part of the cortex of the lens.

Name: Cerulean cataract
Desc: Cerulean cataracts are a kind of congenital cataract having peripheral bluish and white opacifications in concentric layers with occasional central lesions arranged radially. Although the opacities may be observed during fetal development and childhood, usually visual acuity is only mildly reduced until adulthood, when lens extraction is generally necessary.

Name: Anterior subcapsular cataract
Desc: A type of cataract affecting the anterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the lens capsule.

Name: Punctate opacification of the cornea
Desc: Punctate opacification (reduced transparency) of the corneal stroma.

Name: Abnormal corneal epithelium morphology
Desc: Abnormality of the corneal epithelium, that is of the epithelial tissue that covers the front of the cornea.

Name: Abnormal posterior eye segment morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal morphology of the posterior segment of the globe
Abnormality of the posterior segment of the eye
Abnormality of the posterior segment of the eyeball
Abnormality of the posterior segment of the globe

Name: Bifid epiglottis
Desc: A midline anterior-posterior cleft of the epiglottis that involves at least two-thirds of the epiglottic leaf. It is a useful feature for clinical diagnosis because it appears to be very rare in syndromes other than Pallister-Hall-Syndrome and is also rare as an isolated malformation.

Name: Auricular tag
Desc: Small protrusion within the pinna.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the vagina
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.

Name: Supernumerary metacarpal bones
Desc: The presence of more than the normal number of metacarpal bones.

Name: Pancreatic calcification
Desc: The presence of abnormal calcium deposition lesions in the pancreas.

Name: Splanchnic vein thrombosis
Desc: The term splanchnic vein thrombosis encompasses Budd-Chiari syndrome (hepatic vein thrombosis), extrahepatic portal vein obstruction (EHPVO), and mesenteric vein thrombosis; the word splanchnic is used to refer to the visceral organs (of the abdominal cavity).

Name: Elevated maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein
Desc: An elevation of alpha-feto protein in the maternal serum.

Name: Chronic furunculosis
Desc: A furuncle (boil) is a skin infection involving an entire hair follicle and nearby skin tissue. Chronic furunculosis refers to recurrent episodes of furuncles, often caused by recurrent staphylococcus infection.

Name: Increased red blood cell count
Desc: An abnormal elevation above the normal number of red blood cells per volume in the circulation.

Name: Myocardial necrosis
Desc: Irreversible damage to heart tissue (myocardium) due to lack of oxygen after a heart attack (myocardial infarction).

Name: Periodic hypokalemic paresis
Desc: Episodes of muscle weakness associated with reduced levels of potassium in the blood.

Name: Episodic flaccid weakness
Desc: Recurrent episodes of muscle flaccidity, a type of paralysis in which a muscle becomes soft and yields to passive stretching.

Name: Late-onset proximal muscle weakness
Desc: Lack of strength of the proximal musculature occurring late in the clinical course.

Name: Periodic hyperkalemic paralysis
Desc: Episodes of muscle weakness associated with elevated levels of potassium in the blood.

Name: Abnormal synaptic transmission
Desc: An anomaly in the communication from a neuron to a target across a synapse. This is a four step process, comprising (i) synthesis and storage of neurotransmitters; (ii) neurotransmitter release; (iii) activation of postsynaptic receptors by the neurotransmitter; and (iv) inactivation of the neurotransmitter. Thus, this term is defined as an anomaly of neurotransmitter metabolic process.

Name: Paradoxical myotonia
Desc: A type of myotonia that worsens with repeated muscle contractions.

Name: Facial muscle hypertrophy
Desc: Hypertrophy of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

Name: Myotonia of the face
Desc: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the face.

Name: Cold-sensitive myotonia
Desc: An involuntary and painless delay in the relaxation of skeletal muscle following contraction or electrical stimulation that is induced by exposure to cold.

Name: Cold paresis
Desc: Increased muscle weakness upon exposure to cold temperatures.

Name: Glomerular deposits
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of protein in the glomerulus.

Name: Pregnancy exposure
Desc: Exposure of pregnant women to toxins from any source, such as environmental toxins or chemicals, that may potentially cause problems such as miscarriage, preterm delivery, low birth weight, and, in some cases, developmental delays in infants.

Name: Chronic irritative conjunctivitis
Desc: A chronic irritative conjunctivitis, which commonly presents with general irritation and redness of the eyes, with a burning, dry, or foreign-body sensation of the eyes.

Name: Abnormal nipple morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the nipple.

Name: Axillary and groin hyperpigmentation and hypopigmentation
Abnormal skin morphology of the palm
Desc: An abnormality of the skin of the palm, that is, the skin of the front of the hand.

Name: Crohn's disease
Desc: A chronic granulomatous inflammatory disease of the intestines that may affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus, causing a wide variety of symptoms. It primarily causes abdominal pain, diarrhea which may be bloody, vomiting, or weight loss, but may also cause complications outside of the gastrointestinal tract such as skin rashes, arthritis, inflammation of the eye, tiredness, and lack of concentration. Crohn's disease is thought to be an autoimmune disease, in which the body's immune system attacks the gastrointestinal tract, causing inflammation.

Name: Plantar telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located on the skin of sole of foot.

Name: Pigment deposition in the trabecular meshwork
Desc: Accumulation of abnormal amounts of pigment within the trabecular meshwork.

Name: Iris pigment dispersion
Desc: Shedding of the pigment granules that normally adhere to the back of the iris into the aqueous humor.

Name: Abnormality of the hypothenar eminence
Desc: An abnormality of the hypothenar eminence, i.e., of the muscles on the ulnar side of the palm of the hand (i.e., on the side of the little finger).

Name: Elevated lactate:pyruvate ratio
Desc: An abnormal increase in the molar ratio of lactate to pyruvate in the blood circulation.

Name: Malabsorption of Vitamin B12
Synonyms: Vitamin B12 deficiency caused by intestinal malabsorption

Name: Hypoplastic spleen
Desc: Underdevelopment of the spleen.

Name: Macronodular cirrhosis
Desc: A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of large regenerative nodules.

Name: Abnormal CSF lactate level
Desc: Abnormal concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Abnormal brain lactate level by MRS
Desc: A deviation from normal of the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Synonyms: Abnormal lactate level by magnetic resonance spectroscopy

Name: Punctate keratitis
Desc: A type of keratitis characterized by inflammation in pinpoint areas of the corneal epithelium.

Name: Abnormal blood gas level
Desc: An abnormality of the partial pressure of oxygen or carbon dioxide in the arterial blood.

Name: Meconium stained amniotic fluid
Desc: Amniotic fluid containing the earliest stools of a mammalian infant.

Name: Hyperoxemia
Desc: An abnormally high level of blood oxygen.

Name: Cardiac shunt
Desc: Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system.

Name: Recurrent thromboembolism
Desc: Repeated episodes of obstruction of blood flow due to an embolus, i.e., blood clot that has traveled from its point of origin within the blood stream.

Name: Dysfibrinogenemia
Desc: Qualitatively abnormal fibrinogen.

Name: Abnormality of von Willebrand factor
Desc: Decreased quantity or activity of von Willebrand factor. Von Willebrand factor mediates the adhesion of platelets to the collagen exposed on endothelial cell surfaces.

Name: Hypocapnia
Desc: Abnormally reduced blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level.
Synonyms: Reduced carbon dioxide in the blood

Name: Right atrial enlargement
Desc: Increase in size of the right atrium.

Name: Increased factor VIII activity
Desc: Increased activity of the coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.

Name: Atrophy/Degeneration involving the spinal cord
Synonyms: Atrophic and degenerative changes in the spinal cord

Name: Enlarged mesenteric lymph node
Desc: Increase in size of one or more mesenteric lymph nodes.

Name: Central opacification of the cornea
Desc: Reduced transparency of the central portion of the corneal stroma.

Name: Thinning of Descemet membrane
Desc: A reduction in the thickness of Descemet's membrane.

Name: Microtia, second degree
Desc: Median longitudinal length of the ear more than two standard deviations below the mean in the presence of some, but not all, parts of the normal ear.

Name: Bicuspid pulmonary valve
Desc: The presence of a bicuspid pulmonary valve.

Name: Abnormal pulmonary vein morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the structure of the pulmonary veins.

Name: Increased hepatocellular lipid droplets
Desc: An abnormal increase in the amount of intracellular lipid droplets in hepatocytes.

Name: Abnormality of vitamin metabolism
Desc: An anomaly in the metabolism of a vitamin.

Name: Decreased 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase level
Synonyms: Long chain 3 hydroxyacyl coA dehydrogenase deficiency
Medium and short-chain L-3-hydroxyacyl-coenzyme A dehydrogenase deficiency

Name: Abnormal circulating acetylcarnitine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of acylcarnitine, which is produced by reversible esterification of the 3-hydroxyl group of carnitine.

Name: Central fundal arteriolar microaneurysms
Desc: Microscopic aneurysms of the retinal arterioles near the central part of the fundus, visible as small round dark red dots on the retinal surface (not arising from visible vessels) that are by definition less than the diameter of the major optic veins as they cross the optic disc.

Name: Subretinal exudate
Desc: A type of retinal exudate located in the subretinal space between the sensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.

Name: Amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenia
Desc: Thrombocytopenia related to lack of or severe reduction in the count of megakaryocytes.

Name: Decreased hemoglobin concentration
Desc: An abnormal reduction below normal hemoglobin concentration in the circulation.

Name: Childhood-onset truncal obesity
Desc: Truncal obesity with onset during childhood, defined as between 2 and 10 years of age.

Name: Decreased level of plasminogen
Desc: A decreased level of Plasminogen

Name: Cervicitis
Desc: Inflammation of the uterine cervix.

Name: Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia
Desc: An opportunistic disease caused by invasion of unicellular fungus Pneumocystis jirovecii. Transmission of P. jirovecii cysts takes place through the airborne route, and usually, its presence in lungs is asymptomatic. However, people with impaired immunity, especially those with CD4+ T cell count below 200/microliter, are still at risk of the development of Pneumocystis pneumonia due to P. jirovecii invasion. Symptoms induced by this disease are not specific: progressive dyspnoea, non-productive cough, low-grade fever, arterial partial pressure of oxygen below 65 mmHg, and chest radiographs demonstrating bilateral, interstitial shadowing.

Name: Combined cystic and ground-glass pattern on pulmonary HRCT
Desc: Co-occurrence of the cystic pattern and the ground-glass pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography,

Name: Bloodstream infectious agent
Desc: The presence of an infectious agent in the blood circulation.

Name: Chondritis
Desc: Inflammation of cartilage.

Name: Chondritis of pinna
Desc: Inflammation of the cartilage of the external ear.

Name: Albuminuria
Desc: Increased concentration of albumin in the urine.

Name: Abnormal systemic arterial morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the systemic arterial tree, which consists of the aorta and other systemic arteries.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the systemic arterial tree

Name: Reduced renal corticomedullary differentiation
Desc: Reduced differentiation between renal cortex and medulla on diagnostic imaging.
Synonyms: Loss of definition of corticomedullary differentiation

Name: Biliary hyperplasia
Desc: Hyperplasia of the biliary tree, as manifested by increased size of bile ducts, dilated lumen, and histologically by an increased number of epithelial cells or hyperplasia.

Name: Hypoplastic sweat glands
Desc: Underdevelopment of the sweat glands.

Name: Abnormality of dermal melanosomes
Desc: An abnormality of the melanosomes, i.e., of the cellular organelles in which melanin pigments are synthesized and stored within melanocytes (the cells that produce pigment in the dermis).

Name: Orthokeratotic hyperkeratosis
Desc: A form of hyperkeratosis characterized by thickening of the cornified layer without retained nuclei.

Name: Localized hypoplasia of dental enamel
Desc: A localized form of developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.

Name: Hyperprostaglandinuria
Desc: An increased concentration of prostaglandin in the urine.

Name: Abnormal renal resorption
Desc: An abnormality of renal absorption.

Name: Triangular shaped distal phalanges of the hand
Synonyms: Triangular shaped outermost bone of the hand

Name: Fetal megacystis
Desc: Fetal megacystis is an abnormally enlarged bladder identified at any gestational age.

Name: Ileitis
Desc: Inflammation of the ileum.

Name: Cutaneous wound
Desc: A cutaneous wound is a defined as a disruption of normal anatomic structure and function of the skin that occured owing to an injury of the skin. Wound healing is a dynamic, interactive processinvolving soluble mediators, blood cells, extracellularmatrix, and parenchymal cells. Wound healing has three phases: inflammation, tissue formation, and tissue remodeling, that overlap in time.

Name: Retinal arterial occlusion
Desc: Blockage of the retinal artery, generally associated with interruption of blood flow and oxygen delivery to the retina.

Name: Colon perforation
Desc: A hole (perforation) in the wall of the colon.

Name: Abnormal pineal melatonin secretion
Desc: An anomaly in the amount or timing of melatonin secretion by the pineal gland. Note that melatonin is also synthesized by multiple tissues outside of the pineal gland.

Name: Abnormal circulating porphyrin concentration
Desc: An abnormality in the synthesis or catabolism of heme. Heme is composed of ferrous iron and protoporphyrin IX and is an essential molecule as the prosthetic group of hemeproteins such as hemoglobin, myoglobin, mitochondrial and microsomal cytochromes.

Name: Gastrointestinal eosinophilia
Desc: Eosinophilic infiltration of one or more gastrointestinal organs. Gastrointestinal eosinophilia is a broad term for abnormal eosinophil accumulation in the GI tract, involving many different disease identities. These diseases include primary eosinophil associated gastrointestinal diseases, gastrointestinal eosinophilia in HES and all gastrointestinal eosinophilic states associated with known causes. Each of these diseases has its unique features but there is no absolute boundary between them.

Name: Prominent umbilicus
Desc: Abnormally prominent umbilicus (belly button).

Name: Abnormality of the nasal tip
Desc: An abnormality of the nasal tip.

Name: Low-frequency sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects primarily the lower frequencies.

Name: Left ventricular diastolic dysfunction
Desc: Abnormal function of the left ventricule during left ventricular relaxation and filling.

Name: Progressive clavicular acroosteolysis
Desc: Progressive bone resorption in the distal part of the clavicle.

Name: Carotid artery occlusion
Desc: Complete obstruction of a carotid artery.

Name: Nocturnal lagophthalmos
Desc: The inability to close the eyelids during sleep.
Synonyms: Inability to close the eyelids at night

Name: Retinal nonattachment
Desc: Failure of attachment of the retina during development.

Name: Shortening of all metacarpals
Desc: Abnormal reduction in length of all metacarpal bones.

Name: Wind-swept deformity of the knees
Desc: The appearance of abnormal valgus deformity in one knee in association with varus deformity in the other.

Name: Limited hip extension
Desc: Limitation of the extension of the hip, i.e., decreased ability to straighten the hip joint and thereby increase the angle between torso and thigh; moving the thigh or top of the pelvis backward.

Name: Irregular carpal bones
Desc: Carpal bones with irregular or fragmented margins.

Name: Interstitial cardiac fibrosis
Desc: A type of myocardial fibrosis characterized by excessive diffuse collagen accumulation concentrated in interstitial spaces.

Name: Hyperautofluorescent macular lesion
Desc: Increased amount of autofluorescence in the macula as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

Name: Full-thickness macular hole
Desc: Full-thickness macular hole (FTMH) is defined as a foveal lesion with interruption of all retinal layers from the internal limiting membrane to the retinal pigment epithelium. Full-thickness macular hole is primary if caused by vitreous traction or secondary if directly the result of pathologic characteristics other than vitreomacular traction. Full-thickness macular hole is subclassified by size of the hole as determined by OCT and the presence or absence of vitreomacular traction.

Name: Foveal photoreceptor outer segment loss on macular OCT
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the fallopian tube
Desc: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.

Name: Testicular torsion
Desc: Testicular torsion is when the spermatic cord to a testicle twists, cutting off the blood supply. The most common symptom is acute testicular pain.

Name: Megaloblastic erythroid hyperplasia
Synonyms: Bone marrow biopsy shows megaloblastic erythroid hyperplasia

Name: Granulocytopenia
Desc: An abnormally reduced number of granulocytes in the blood.

Name: Periodic paralysis
Desc: Episodes of muscle weakness.

Name: Angioid streaks of the fundus
Desc: Irregular lines in the deep retina that are typically configured in a radiating fashion and emanate from the optic disc. Angioid streaks are crack-like dehiscences in abnormally thickened and calcified Bruch's membrane, resulting in atrophy of the overlying retinal pigment epithelium. They may be associated with a number of endocrine, metabolic, and connective tissue abnormalities but are frequently idiopathic.

Name: Testicular teratoma
Desc: The presence of a teratoma of the testis.

Name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanx of the 4th toe
Reduced red cell pyruvate kinase level
Desc: Decrease in the level of pyruvate kinase (PK) within erythrocytes. PK catalyzes the reaction: ATP + pyruvate = ADP + phosphoenolpyruvate.

Name: Increased pineal volume
Desc: An abnormal elevation in the quantity of three-dimensional space taken up by the pineal gland.

Name: Elevated levels of phytanic acid
Desc: An abnormal elevation of phytanic acid.

Name: Shortening of all phalanges of fingers
Desc: Abnormal reduction in length affecting all phalanges.

Name: Acute promyelocytic leukemia
Desc: A type of acute myeloid leukemia in which abnormal promyelocytes predominate.

Name: Congenital hypoplastic anemia
Desc: A type of hypoplastic anemia with congenital onset.

Name: Abnormal inflammatory response
Desc: Any anomaly of the inflammatory response, a response to injury or infection characterized by local vasodilation, extravasation of plasma into intercellular spaces and accumulation of white blood cells and macrophages.

Name: Focal hyperkinetic seizure
Desc: A focal seizure characterized at onset by predominantly proximal limb or axial muscles producing irregular sequential ballistic movements, such as pedaling, pelvic thrusting, thrashing, rocking movements.

Name: Incomplete cleft of the upper lip
Desc: A subtle unilateral cleft of the upper lip, which may appear as a small indentation.
Synonyms: Incomplete cleft of the upper lip
Notched cleft of the upper lip
Partial cleft of the upper lip

Name: Cardiac fibroma
Desc: A fibroma of the heart.

Name: Calcification of falx cerebri
Desc: The presence of calcium deposition in the falx cerebri.

Name: Clinodactyly of the 2nd toe
Desc: Bending or curvature of a second toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

Name: Moderate sensorineural hearing impairment
Desc: The presence of a moderate form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

Name: High-pitched cry
Desc: A type of crying in an abnormally high-pitched voice.

Name: Increased serum leptin
Desc: An increased concentration of leptin in the blood.

Name: Anticardiolipin IgG antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of circulating IgG autoantibodies to cardiolipin.

Name: Antimitochondrial antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against mitochondria.

Name: Elevated tissue non-specific alkaline phosphatase
Desc: An abnormally increased level of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.

Name: Abnormal circulating testosterone concentration
Desc: An anomalous concentration of testosterone in the blood.

Name: Abnormality of the pubic hair
Desc: Abnormality of the growth of the pubic hair. Pubic hair is part of the secondary sexual hair, which normally ensues during puberty.

Name: Reduced euglobulin clot lysis time
Desc: Abnormally decreased length of time required for an in vitro clot to dissolve in the absence of the normal plasmin inhibitors. This test is a clinical assay used to measure fibrinolysis. The euglobulin fraction of plasma is precipitated and used to form clot by addition of thrombin; after clot forms the rate of clot breakdown (fibrinolysis) can be monitored.

Name: Hypopyon
Desc: Presence of pus (appears as a white fluid) producing a fluid level in the inferior part of the anterior chamber.

Name: Retinal calcification
Desc: Deposition of calcium salts in the retina.

Name: Pineoblastoma
Desc: Pineoblastoma is a rare primitive neuroectodermal tumour (PNET) arising in the pineal gland. Pineoblastomas are classified as a WHO grade IV tumour and comprise one-fourth to one-half of pineal parenchymal tumours. Pineoblastoma is a highly cellular tumor originating in the pineal gland and containing small, poorly differentiated cells.

Name: Midclavicular hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the middle portion of the clavicle.
Synonyms: Underdeveloped middle portion of the collarbone

Name: Freckled genitalia
Desc: One or more brown punctate macules on the skin of the genitalia.

Name: Unicameral bone cyst
Desc: A benign fluid filled simple cyst of bone filled with serous fluid.

Name: Abnormality of the amniotic fluid
Desc: Abnormality of the amniotic fluid, which is the fluid contained in the amniotic sac surrounding the developing fetus.

Name: Pyridoxine-responsive sideroblastic anemia
Desc: A type of sideroblastic anemia that is alleviated by pyridoxine (vitamin B-6) treatment.

Name: Abnormal circulating glycine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of glycine in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal circulating threonine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of threonine in the blood circulation.

Name: Thyrotoxicosis with toxic single thyroid nodule
Absent tragus
Desc: Lack of convexity or prominence of the contour of the ridge between the bottom of the incisura and the confluence of the ascending helix and crus helix.

Name: Abnormal lymphocyte count
Desc: Any abnormality in the total number of lymphocytes in the blood.

Name: Decreased proportion of memory B cells
Desc: A reduction in the normal proportion of memory B cells (CD19+/CD27+) in circulation relative to the total number of B cells. Memory B cells develop from naive B cells. Upon antigen rechallenge, memory B cells rapidly expand and differentiate into plasma cells under the cognate control of memory Th cells (Phase IV).

Name: Reticulonodular pattern on pulmonary HRCT
Desc: Co-occurrence of reticular and micronodular patterns on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.

Name: Reduced hematocrit
Desc: A reduction below the normal ratio of the volume of red blood cells to the total volume of blood.

Name: Paucity of anterior horn motor neurons
Focal T2 hyperintense thalamic lesion
Desc: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the thalamus.

Name: Hyperintensity of MRI T2 signal of the spinal cord
Desc: A region of high intensity (brightness) observed upon magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scans of the spinal cord.

Name: Irregular respiration
Desc: Uneven rhythm of breathing.

Name: Abnormality of the internal capsule
Desc: An anomaly of the internal capsule, which is an area of white matter in the brain that separates the caudate nucleus and the thalamus from the putamen and the globus pallidus.

Name: Eyelid fasciculation
Desc: Tiny, repetitive muscle contractions in the eyelids, causing the appearance of twitching.

Name: Merkel cell skin cancer
Desc: A malignant cutaneous tumor of the elderly that is characterized by an aggressive course with regional nodal involvement, distant metastases and a high rate of recurrence. Most patients present with rapidly growing, painless, firm, non-tender, dome-shaped red, occasionally ulcerated skin nodules, which have a red or bluish color, measuring up to several centimeters, on predominantly sun-exposed areas of the body. The overlying skin is smooth and shiny, sometimes exhibiting ulcerative, acneiform or telangiectatic features.
Synonyms: Merkel cell cancer of the skin
Primary small cell carcinoma of the skin
Primary undifferentiated carcinoma of the skin

Name: Neoplasm of the outer ear
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the outer ear.

Name: Increased number of elastic fibers in the dermis
Desc: An elevated number of elastic fibers, that is of bundles of proteins and glycoproteins in the extracellular matrix in the reticular dermis. Elastic fibers can stretch and recoil back to their original length. This feature can be appreciated on histology with hematoxylin and eosin or other staining methods.
Synonyms: Increased number of elastic fibres in the dermis

Name: Abnormality of the periorbital region
Desc: An abnormality of the region situated around the orbit of the eye.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the region around the eye
Abnormality of the region around the eye socket

Name: Perifolliculitis
Desc: Inflammation surrounding hair follicles.

Name: Abnormal circulating tryptophan concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of tryptophan in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormality of endocrine pancreas physiology
Desc: A function abnormality of the endocrine pancreas.

Name: Impairment of galactose metabolism
Desc: An impairment of galactose metabolism.

Name: Neonatal death
Desc: Death within the first 28 days of life.

Name: Perioral eczema
Desc: A type of eczema that occurs in the lips and perioral area.

Name: Congenital lactic acidosis
Desc: A form of lactic acidemia with congenital onset.

Name: Abnormality of medullary pyramid morphology
Desc: A structural anomaly of the pyramid of the adult kidney, cone-shaped structures with a broad base adjacent to the renal cortex and the narrow apex that is termed papilla.

Name: Cerebellar gliosis
Desc: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the cerebellum.

Name: Elevated urinary delta-aminolevulinic acid
Desc: An increased concentration of 5-aminolevulinic acid (CHEBI:17549) in the urine.

Name: Increased urinary porphobilinogen
Desc: Increased concentration of porphobilinogen in the urine.

Name: Long hairs growing from helix of pinna
Synonyms: Long hairs growing from helix of ear

Name: Lip telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectasia (that is, the presence of small dilated superficial blood vessels) of the lips.

Name: Telangiectasia of the oral mucosa
Desc: Telangiectasia (that is, the presence of small dilated superficial blood vessels) of the oral mucosa.
Synonyms: Angioectasia of the oral mucous membrane
Spider veins of the oral mucosa
Telangiectasia of the oral mucous membrane

Name: Elevated circulating palmitoleylcarnitine concentration
Desc: An elevated level of propionylcarnitine in the circulation. Propionylcarnitine is present in high abundance in the urine of patients with Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (MUT) deficiency.

Name: Decreased adenosylcobalamin
Desc: Decreased concentration of adenosylcobalamin. Adenosylcobalamin is one of the active forms of vitamin B12.

Name: Decreased methylcobalamin
Desc: Decreased concentration of methylcobalamin. Methylcobalamin is a form of vitamin B12.

Name: Reduced factor IX activity
Desc: Decreased activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.

Name: Reduced thyroxin-binding globulin
Desc: An abnormally decreased amount of thyroxin-binding globulin (TBG) in blood. TBG is responsible for carrying the thyroid hormones thyroxine (T4) and 3,5,3'-triiodothyronine (T3) in the bloodstream.

Name: Hyperplastic labia majora
Desc: Overgrowth of the outer labia.

Name: Impaired antigen-specific response
Desc: An impaired immune response mediated by cells expressing specific receptors for antigen produced through a somatic diversification process, and allowing for an enhanced secondary response to subsequent exposures to the same antigen (immunological memory).

Name: Hypoglycinemia
Desc: An abnormally reduced concentration of glycine in the blood.

Name: Hypoplastic dermoepidermal hemidesmosomes
Desc: Underdeveloped hemidesmosomes at the dermoepidermal junction. Hemidesmosomes are the specialized junctional complexes, that contribute to the attachment of epithelial cells to the underlying basement membrane in stratified and other complex epithelia, such as the skin.

Name: Pyoderma
Desc: Any manifestation of a skin disease associated with the production of pus.

Name: Genital blistering
Desc: The presence of one or more bullae on the skin of the genital region, defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls.

Name: Chronic cutaneous wound
Desc: A cutaneous wound that has failed to proceed through the orderly and timely process to produce an atomic and functional integrity, or proceeded through the repair process without establishing a sustained anatomic and functional result.

Name: Abnormal circulating selenium concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal circulating concentration of selenium.

Name: Vaginal stricture
Desc: A narrowing of the vagina owing to scar formation.

Name: Pretibial blistering
Desc: A type of blistering that affects the skin of the tibial region.

Name: Partial albinism
Desc: Absence of melanin pigment in various areas, which is found at birth and is permanent. The lesions are known as leucoderma and are often found on the face, trunk, or limbs.
Synonyms: Congenital partial albinism on face, trunk, or limbs

Name: Broad distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Increased width of the distal phalanx of thumb.
Synonyms: Broad outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Osteoma cutis
Desc: The term osteoma refers to the anomalous presence of ossification (bone formation) in the interior of the dermis or epidermis. The dermal or subcutaneous bone formation presents as stony hard nodules. The osteomata appear as irregular, hardened small nodules that are well circumscribed and generally of the same color as the skin.

Name: Pituitary resistance to thyroid hormone
Desc: A condition in which the pituitary gland is partially resistant to thyroid hormone, so that it continues to secrete thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) until the blood level of thyroid hormone rises higher than normal.

Name: Choroid plexus calcification
Desc: The presence of calcium deposition in the choroid plexus.

Name: Broad 1st metacarpal
Desc: Increased width of the 1st metacarpal. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

Name: Hair shafts flattened at irregular intervals and twisted through 180 degrees about their axes
Cylindroma
Desc: A benign skin adnexal tumor of eccrine differentiation.

Name: Skin appendage neoplasm
Desc: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the hair follicles, sebaceous glands, or sweat glands.

Name: Trichoepithelioma
Desc: A benign hair follicle tumor whose tumor cells form rudimentary hair follicles but not actual hair shafts. A trichoepithelioma is usually less than one centimeter, firm, round, and shihy with yellow, pink, brown, or bluish color. They may occur multiply, usually on the face, and may gradually increase in number with age.

Name: Nodular changes affecting the eyelids
Desc: Nodular changes affecting the eyelids may have many different causes such as cystic lesions (chalaziae, hordeolae), lipogranulomas, melanomas, infectious diseases (Molluscum contagiosum) and many more.

Name: Skin-colored papule
Desc: A papule with the same color as the surrounding skin.

Name: Abnormality of the submandibular glands
Desc: Any abnormality of the submandibular glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth, superior to the digastric muscles.

Name: Abnormality of the sublingual glands
Desc: Any abnormality of the sublingual glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth anterior to the submandibular glands.

Name: Absent fifth fingernail
Desc: Absence of nail of little finger.

Name: Malalignment of the great toenail
Desc: A lateral deviation of the nail plate of the great toe along the longitudinal axis due to the lateral rotation of the nail matrix. The nail plate grows out in ridges.

Name: Small cerebellar cortex
Desc: Reduced size of the cerebellar cortex.

Name: Abnormal placental membrane morphology
Desc: Structural anomaly of the fetal membranes (also known as the amniochorionic or placental membranes), which comprise a vital intrauterine compartment, where they perform mechanical, immune, and endocrine functions to promote growth of the fetus and protection from environmental adversity. Amniochorionic membranes anatomically consist of a single layer of cuboidal amnion epithelial cells, chorionic trophoblasts, and scattered fibroblasts connected by a layer of type IV collagen-rich extracellular matrix.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
Ampulla of Vater carcinoma
Desc: A carcinoma originating in the ampulla of Vater (also known as the hepatopancreatic duct), which is formed by the union of the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct.

Name: Abnormal nasal mucosa morphology
Synonyms: Abnormality of mucous membrane of nose

Name: Enlarged lacrimal glands
Desc: Abnormally big lacrimal glands.

Name: Stiff elbow
Desc: A sensation of tightness in the elbow joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

Name: Finger swelling
Desc: Enlargement of the soft tissues of one or more fingers.

Name: Anti-topoisomerase I antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against topoisomerase I.

Name: Gastrointestinal telangiectasia
Desc: Telangiectasia affecting the gastrointestinal tract.
Synonyms: Small, enlarged blood vessels near skin

Name: Abnormal phalangeal joint morphology of the hand
Synonyms: Abnormality of phalangeal joints of the hand
Abnormality of the small joints of the hand

Name: Anti-centromere antibody positivity
Desc: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the centromeres or centromere components.

Name: Cortical tubers
Desc: Cortical tubers in the brain are hamartomatous lesions typically located at the gray-white matter interface, commonly in the frontal and parietal lobes. Cortical tubers are composed of abnormal glial and neural cells, and the size, number, and location vary among patients.

Name: Hypomelanotic macule
Desc: Hypomelanotic macules ("ash leaf spots") are white or lighter patches of skin that may appear anywhere on the body and are caused by a lack of melanin. White ash leaf-shaped macules are considered to be characteristic of tuberous sclerosis.

Name: Subependymal giant-cell astrocytoma
Desc: A demarcated, largely intraventricular tumor in the region of the foramen of Monro composed of spindle to large plump or ganglion-like cells with eosinophilic to amphophilic cytoplasm and somewhat pleomorphic nuclei with occasional prominent nucleoli. These tumors are almost always associated with tuberous sclerosis.

Name: Retinal astrocytic hamartoma
Desc: A glial tumor of the retinal nerve fiber layer arising from a retinal astrocyte.

Name: Bloody mucoid diarrhea
Desc: Passage of many stools containing blood and mucus.

Name: Increased urinary O-linked sialopeptides
Desc: Excretion of peptides conjugated to sialic acid in the urine.

Name: Urinary excretion of sialylated oligosaccharides
Desc: Excretion of oligosaccharides conjugated to sialic acid in the urine.

Name: Abnormality of male external genitalia
Desc: An abnormality of male external genitalia.

Name: Elevated 7-dehydrocholesterol
Desc: Elevated 7-dehydrocholesterol levels.

Name: Reduced antithrombin antigen
Desc: Reduced antithrombin antigen. A reduced level of antithrombin may lead to an increased risk of thrombus formation.

Name: Superficial thrombophlebitis
Desc: Inflammation of a superficial vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein).

Name: Retinal vein occlusion
Desc: Blockage of the retinal vein.

Name: Hepatic vein thrombosis
Desc: An obstruction in the veins of the liver caused by a blood clot (thrombosis).

Name: Sparse anterior scalp hair
Desc: Decreased number of head hairs per unit area on the anterior region of the scalp.
Synonyms: Sparse scalp hair at front of head
Thin scalp hair at front of head

Name: Cholesteatoma
Desc: Cholesteatoma is a benign but potentially destructive growth consisting of keratinizing epithelium located in the middle ear and/or mastoid process. In cholesteatoma, a skin cyst grows into the middle ear and mastoid. The cyst is not cancerous but can erode tissue and cause destruction of the ear.

Name: Pulmonary bleb
Desc: A bleb is a small gas-containing space within the visceral pleura or in the subpleural lung, not larger than 1 cm in diameter. CT findings show a bleb as a thin-walled cystic air space contiguous with the pleura.

Name: Edema of the upper limbs
Desc: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin of the arms.

Name: Trophic changes related to pain
Desc: Trophic changes is a term used to describe abnormalities in the area of pain that include primarily wasting away of the skin, tissues, or muscle, thinning of the bones, and changes in how the hair or nails grow, including thickening or thinning of hair or brittle nails.

Name: Gastrointestinal arteriovenous malformation
Desc: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Abnormality of the nasal cavity
Desc: Abnormality of the nasal cavity (the cavity includes and starts at the nares and reaches all the way through to the and includes the choanae, the posterior nasal apertures).

Name: Oral mucosa nodule
Desc: A palpable, solid lesion greater than 5mm in diameter. that is located in the mucosa of the mouth.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia affecting the anterior segment of the eye
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior segment of the eye.

Name: Abnormality of the humeral diaphysis
Desc: An anomaly of the humeral diaphysis.
Synonyms: Abnormality of shaft of long bone in upper arm

Name: Abnormality of the medullary cavity of the long bones
Desc: An abnormality of the medullary cavity (medulla, innermost part), which is the central cavity of bone shafts where red bone marrow and/or yellow bone marrow (adipose tissue) is stored.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the marrow cavity of the long bones

Name: Cleft vertebral arch
Desc: A discontinuity of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.

Name: Contracture of the distal interphalangeal joint of the fingers
Desc: Chronic loss of joint motion in one or more distal interphalangeal joints of the fingers.

Name: Large knee
Desc: Abnormally increased size of the knee joint.

Name: Nevus sebaceous
Desc: A congenital, hairless plaque consisting of overgrown epidermis, sebaceous glands, hair follicles, apocrine glands and connective tissue. They are a variant of epidermal naevi. Sebaceous naevi most often appear on the scalp, but they may also arise on the face, neck or forehead. At birth, a sevaceous nevus typically appears as a solitary, smooth, yellow-orange hairless patch. Sebaceous naevi become more pronounced around adolescence, often appearing bumpy, warty or scaly.

Name: Abnormal glomerular mesangium morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the mesangium, i.e., of the central part of the renal glomerulus between capillaries.

Name: Impaired ADP-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal platelet response to ADP as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ADP.

Name: Impaired epinephrine-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal response to epinephrine as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of epinephrine.

Name: Impaired arachidonic acid-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal response to arachidonic acid as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of arachidonic acid.

Name: Impaired thrombin-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal response to thrombin or thrombin mimetics as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of thrombin (or thrombin mimetics).

Name: Impaired thromboxane A2 agonist-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal response to thromboxane as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of thromboxane A2 receptor agonists.

Name: Impaired collagen-related peptide-induced platelet aggregation
Desc: Abnormal response to collagen-related peptide (CRP) as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of CRP.

Name: Thiamine-responsive megaloblastic anemia
Desc: A type of megaloblastic anemia (i.e., anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal) that improves upon the administration of thiamine.

Name: Shortening of all middle phalanges of the toes
Desc: Abnormal shortening of all middle phalanges of toes.
Synonyms: Shortening of all the middle bones of the toes

Name: Flared radial metaphysis
Desc: The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of the radius.

Name: Glenoid fossa hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the glenoid fossa, which is the cavity in the lateral part of the scapula which articulates with the head of the humerus.

Name: Abnormality of skull ossification
Desc: An abnormality of the process of ossification of the skull.
Synonyms: Abnormality of bone calcification of calvarium
Abnormality of bone calcification of cranium
Abnormality of bone calcification of skull
Abnormality of bone formation of calvarium
Abnormality of bone formation of cranium
Abnormality of bone mineralization of calvarium
Abnormality of bone mineralization of cranium
Abnormality of bone mineralization of skull

Name: Vertebral arch anomaly
Desc: A morphological abnormality of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.

Name: Metaphyseal enchondromatosis
Desc: An enchondroma is a benign growth of cartilage that develops within the medullary cavity of bone. Enchondromatosis refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas, and this term refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas within the medulla of metaphyseal bone. Radiographically an enchondroma presents a an oval, linear, or pyramidal osteolytic (radiolucent) lesion with well defined margins.

Name: Stillbirth
Desc: Death of the fetus in utero after at least 20 weeks of gestation.

Name: Galactosuria
Desc: Elevated concentration of galactose in the urine.

Name: Folate-dependent fragile site at Xq28
Desc: The presence of a folate sensitive fragile site at chromosome Xq28.

Name: Finger dactylitis
Desc: Fingers appear swollen and plump owing to inflammation of the complete finger.

Name: Toe dactylitis
Desc: Toes appear swollen and plump owing to inflammation of the complete toe.

Name: Generalized morning stiffness
Desc: A sensation of stiffness in the joints that occurs following waking up in the morning.

Name: Plasmacytoma
Desc: A discrete mass of neoplastic monoclonal plasma cells either in the bone marrow or in an extramedullary location.

Name: Jaw claudication
Desc: Pain in the jaw or ear induced by chewing or otherwise moving the jaw.

Name: Lattice corneal dystrophy
Desc: The presence of fine, branching linear opacities in Bowman's layer in the central area that may spread to the periphery in the clinical course. The deep corneal stroma may be involved but the process does not reach Descemet's membrane. Recurrent corneal erosion may occur. Histologic examination reveals amyloid deposits in the collagen fibers of the cornea.

Name: Absent toe
Desc: Aplasia of a toe. That is, absence of all phalanges of a non-hallux digit of the foot and the associated soft tissues.

Name: Central retinal artery occlusion
Desc: Blockage of the main artery in the retina. The typical presentation is one of profound monocular visual loss.

Name: Thigh hypertrophy
Desc: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the thighs.

Name: Increased alpha-globulin
Desc: An abnormally increased level of circulationg alpha-globulin. Alpha globulins are a group of serum proteins defined by their mobility on serum electrophoresis. The alpha1-protein fraction is comprised of alpha1-antitrypsin, thyroid-binding globulin, and transcortin. Ceruloplasmin, alpha2-macroglobulin, and haptoglobin contribute to the alpha2-protein band. The alpha2 component is increased as an acute-phase reactant.

Name: Low pulse pressure
Desc: Reduced amplitude of the pulse pressure (systolic blood pressure minus diastolic blood pressure).

Name: Abnormal circulating albumin concentration
Desc: Deviation from normal concentration of albumin in the blood.

Name: Multiple lineage myelodysplasia
Desc: Myelodysplasia with dysplastic changes in two or more of the myeloid lineages: erythroid, granulocytic, megakaryocytic.

Name: Single lineage myelodysplasia
Desc: Abnormality/dysplasia of a single myeloid cell (erythroid, granulocytic, or megakaryocytic).

Name: Megakaryocyte nucleus hypolobulation
Desc: The presence of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow whose nuclei are less lobulated than expected for the size of the nucleus.

Name: Abnormality of bone marrow stromal cells
Increased micromegakaryocyte count
Desc: The presence of abnormally high numbers of micromegakaryocytes in the bone marrow. Micromegakaryocytes are mononuclear diploid cells, with a nucleus similar in size to that of a myeloblast or promyelocyte with the cell being less than 30 micrometers in diameter.

Name: Leber optic atrophy
Desc: Degeneration of retinal ganglion cells and their axons.

Name: Acrobrachycephaly
Desc: An abnormality of head shape characterized by the presence of a short, wide head as well as a pointy or conical form of the top of the head owing to premature closure of the coronal and lambdoid sutures.

Name: Cervical C5/C6 vertebrae fusion
Desc: Fusion of the C5 and C6 cervical vertebrae.

Name: Morphological abnormality of the semicircular canal
Desc: An abnormality of the morphology of the semicircular canal.

Name: Acute megakaryocytic leukemia
Desc: A rare subtype of acute myeloid leukemia evolving from primitive megakaryoblasts.

Name: High urinary gonadotropin level
Desc: An elevated concentration of a gonadotropin hormone (stimulating hormone or luteinizing hormone) in the urine, consistent with the diagnosis of primary hypogonadism.

Name: Increased upper to lower segment ratio
Desc: Elevated ratio between the upper and the lower segment of the body, where the lower segment is defined as the length between the top of pubic symphysis to floor, and the upper segment is defined as the top of head to top of pubic symphysis.

Name: Enlargement of the distal femoral epiphysis
Desc: An abnormal enlargement of the distal epiphysis of the femur.
Synonyms: Enlargement of the outermost thighbone end part

Name: Irregular proximal tibial epiphyses
Desc: Anomaly of the contour of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia such that its normally smooth appearance is irregular.

Name: Neck pterygia
Desc: Pterygia affecting the neck.

Name: Splayed toes
Desc: Divergence of digits along the anteroposterior axis (in the plane of the sole).

Name: Gastrointestinal angiodysplasia
Desc: Dysplasia affecting the vasculature of the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Abnormal circulating methionine concentration
Desc: Any deviation from the normal concentration of methionine in the blood circulation.

Name: Abnormal circulating homocysteine concentration
Desc: An abnormality of a homocysteine metabolic process.

Name: Reduced factor VII activity
Desc: Reduced activity of coagulation factor VII. Factor VII is part of the extrinsic coagulation pathway, which is initiated at the site of injury in response to the release of tissue factor (fIII). Tissue factor and activated factor VII catalyze the activation of factor X.

Name: Elevated coagulation factor V activity
Desc: Increased activity of coagulation factor V, Factor V, which is activated to factor Va by means of minute amounts of thrombin (and inactivated by larger amounts of thrombin). Activated factor V (fVa) is a cofactor in the formation of the prothrombinase complex.

Name: Choroid hemorrhage
Desc: Hemorrhage from the vessels of the choroid.

Name: Truncal titubation
Desc: Tremor of the trunk in an anterior-posterior plane at 3-4 Hz.

Name: Bone spicule pigmentation of the retina
Desc: Pigment migration into the retina in a bone-spicule configuration (resembling the nucleated cells within the lacuna of bone).

Name: Hypomature dental enamel
Desc: A form of hypomineralization of enamel characterized by a chalky appearance of the enamel with orange, brown, or white color.

Name: Abnormality of permanent molar morphology
Desc: An abnormality of morphology of permanent molar.
Synonyms: Abnormality of shape of adult molar
Abnormality of shape of permanent molar

Name: Lower lip pit
