Desc: Depression located on the vermilion of the lower lip, usually paramedian.

Name: Elevated circulating catecholamine level
Desc: An abnormal increase in catecholamine concentration in the blood.

Name: Pancreatic islet cell adenoma
Desc: The presence of an adenoma of the pancreas with origin in a pancreatic B cell.

Name: Papillary cystadenoma of the epididymis
Desc: A cystadenoma, an epithelial tumor, that originates within the head of the epididymis.

Name: Endolymphatic sac tumor
Desc: A low-grade papillary epithelial neoplasm (adenocarcinoma) with a slow growth pattern. The endolymphatic duct emerges from the posterior wall of the saccule (of the inner ear) and ends in a blind pouch, the endolymphatic sac. Endolymphatic sac tumors (ELSTs) are known under different names in the literature (Heffner tumor, aggressive papillary middle ear tumor, and low-grade adenocarcinoma of endolymphatic sac origin).
Synonyms: Low-grade adenocarcinoma of endolymphatic sac origin

Name: Abnormality of the forearm
Desc: An abnormality of the lower arm.

Name: Subepidermal blistering with cleavage in the lamina lucida
Desc: The formation of bullae (blisters) with cleavage in the lamina lucida layer of the skin.
Synonyms: Subepidermal blistering with cleavage in the lamina lucida

Name: Microlissencephaly
Desc: Severe microcephaly and lissencephaly with granular surfaces with immature cortical plate, reduced in thickness, with focal polymicrogyria and immature small neurons with rare processes, intermingled with a considerable number of glial elements.

Name: Abnormality of lower-limb metaphyses
Synonyms: Abnormality of the wide portion of the lower-limb bone

Name: Upper limb metaphyseal widening
Desc: Increased width (breadth) of metaphyses of the arms.
Synonyms: Broad wide portion of upper limb bone
Wide/broad metaphyses of the upper limbs

Name: Beaded ribs
Desc: The presence of a row of multiple rounded expansions (beadlike prominences) at the junction of a rib and its cartilage.

Name: Vertebral hyperostosis
Desc: Excessive growth of the bones of the vertebral bodies.

Name: Sacroiliac joint synovitis
Desc: Inflammation of the synovial membrane of the sacroiliac joint.

Name: Diaminoaciduria
Desc: An increased urine level of any amino acid carrying two amino groups (Asparagine, glutamine and lysine, cystine, ornithine).

Name: Aplasia of the inner ear
Desc: Absence of the inner ear due to a developmental defect.

Name: Dysfunctional alternative complement pathway
Desc: An abnormality of the functioning of any aspect of the alternative complement pathway.

Name: Anuria
Desc: Absence of urine, clinically classified as below 50ml/day.

Name: Colonic stenosis
Desc: A narrowing of a segment of colon whereby bowel continuity is maintained.

Name: Abnormal mucociliary clearance
Desc: An anomaly in the system of mucociliary transport, which functions to transport the mucous layer lining the respiratory epithelium by ciliary nbeating.

Name: Reversible renal failure
Desc: Acute renal failure with resolution of manifestations.

Name: Disseminated viral infection
Desc: A viral infection that fails to be contained by the immune sytem and spreads throughout the body.

Name: Increased DLCO
Desc: Increased ability of the lungs to transfer gas from inspired air to the bloodstream as measured by the diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide (DLCO) test.

Name: Irregular septal thickening on pulmonary HRCT
Desc: Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with an irregular appearance of the interlobular septa. THis feature is often associated with distortion of lung architecture.

Name: Alkalosis
Desc: Depletion of acid or accumulation base in the body fluids.

Name: Abnormal capillary physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of the tiny blood vessels that connect arterioles with venules and whose walls act as semipermeable membranes that mediate the diffusion of fluids and gases between the blood circulation and body tissues.

Name: Abnormality of venous physiology
Desc: An anomaly of venous function.

Name: Absent ankle pulse
Desc: The pulsation of the posterior tibial artery behind the internal malleolus, or of the dorsalis pedis artery, cannot be detected on physical examination.

Name: Hyperglycorrhachia
Desc: Abnormally high glucose concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Name: Morphea
Desc: Isolated patches of hardened skin (scleroderma).

Name: Acral lentiginous melanoma
Desc: A type of cutaneous melanoma localized to the palm, sole, or beneath the nail (subungual melanoma). Acral lentiginous melanoma starts as a slowly-enlarging flat patch of discoloured skin and usually displays a size above 6 mm and often several centimetres or more in diameter upon diagnosis and variable pigmentation with a mixutre of colors including brown, and blue-grey, black and red. The surface of the lesion is initially smooth but later in the course may become thicker and irregular, and may ulcerate or bleed.

Name: Pruritis on hand
Desc: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the skin of the hand.

Name: Chronic myelomonocytic leukemia
Desc: A myelodysplastic/myeloproliferative neoplasm which is characterized by persistent monocytosis, absence of a Philadelphia chromosome and BCR/ABL fusion gene, fewer than 20 percent blasts in the bone marrow and blood, myelodysplasia, and absence of PDGFRA or PDGFRB rearrangement.

Name: Progressive loss of facial adipose tissue
Synonyms: Loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue from face, progressive
Progressive loss of facial subcutaneous adipose tissue
Progressive loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue from face

Name: Abnormality of skin adnexa morphology
Desc: An abnormality of the skin adnexa (skin appendages), which are specialized skin structures located within the dermis and focally within the subcutaneous fatty tissue, comprising three histologically distinct structures: (1) the pilosebaceous unit (hair follicle and sebaceous glands); (2) the eccrine sweat glands; and (3) the apocrine glands.

Name: Digital ulcer
Desc: An open sore on the surface of the skin of a finger or toe.

Name: Bounding pulse
Desc: Increased amplitude (strength) of the pulse.

Name: Hypertrophy of the upper limb
Desc: Abnormal increase in size of the upper limbs (due to an increase of the size of cells).

Name: Widely spaced primary teeth
Desc: Increased space between the primary teeth. Note this phenotype should be distinguished from increased space due purely to microdontia.

Name: Hypoplasia of the primary teeth
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the primary teeth.

Name: Increased blood pressure
Desc: Abnormal increase in blood pressure. An individual measurement of increased blood pressure does not necessarily imply hypertension. In practical terms, multiple measurements are recommended to diagnose the presence of hypertension.

Name: Clear cell renal cell carcinoma
Desc: A subtype of renal cell carcinoma thought to originate from mature renal tubular cells in the proximal tubule of the nehpron.

Name: Urethral diverticulum
Desc: The presence of a diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urethra.

Name: Abnormality of hair pigmentation
Desc: An abnormality of hair pigmentation (color).

Name: Chylous ascites
Desc: Extravasation of chyle into the peritoneal cavity.

Name: Functional abnormality of male internal genitalia
Nystagmus-induced head nodding
Desc: Head movements associated with nystagmus, that may represent an attempt to compensate for the involuntary eye movements and to improve vision.

Name: Kayser-Fleischer ring
Desc: Grey-green or brownish-pigmented ring in the deep epithelial layers at the outer border of the cornea.

Name: Abnormality of the internal auditory canal
Desc: An abnormality of the Internal acoustic meatus, i.e., of the canal in the petrous part of the temporal bone through which the cranial nerve VII and cranial nerve VIII traverse.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the internal acoustic meatus

Name: Pituitary dwarfism
Desc: A type of reduced stature with normal proportions related to dysfunction of the pituitary gland related to either an isolated defect in the secretion of growth hormone or to panhypopituitarism, i.e., a deficit of all the anterior pituitary hormones.

Name: Ectopic anterior pituitary gland
Desc: Abnormal anatomic location of the anterior pituitary gland.

Name: Adrenogenital syndrome
Desc: Adrenogenital syndrome is also known as congenital adrenal hyperplasia, which results from disorders of steroid hormone production in the adrenal glands leading to a deficiency of cortisol. The pituitary gland reacts by increased secretion of corticotropin, which in turn causes the adrenal glands to overproduce certain intermediary hormones which have testosterone-like effects.

Name: Congenital adrenal hyperplasia
Desc: A type of adrenal hyperplasia with congenital onset.

Name: Ectopic adrenal gland
Desc: Abnormal anatomical location of the adrenal gland.

Name: Hypervolemia
Desc: An increase in the amount of intravascular fluid, particularly in the volume of the circulating blood.

Name: Maternal virilization in pregnancy
Desc: Virilization (deepening of voice, facial hirsutism and scalp hair loss) with onset during pregnancy (usually towards the end of the first trimester) and regression several months post-partum.

Name: Adrenal medullary hypoplasia
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal medulla.

Name: Abnormality of hair growth rate
Desc: Hair whose growth rate deviates from the norm.
Synonyms: Abnormality of pace of hair growth
Abnormality of speed of hair growth

Name: Early onset of sexual maturation
Desc: An early onset of puberty, in this case early does not refer to precocious.

Name: Flat nasal alae
Desc: An abnormal degree of flatness of the Ala of nose, which can be defined as a reduced nasal elevation index (lateral depth of the nose from the tip of the nose to the insertion of the nasal ala in the cheek x 100 divided by the side-to-side breadth of the nasal alae).

Name: Absence of CD8-positive T cells
Desc: Lack of detectible CD8-positive T cells

Name: Euthyroid hyperthyroxinemia
Desc: An abnormality of thyroid physiology (HP:0002926) characterized by increased levels of thyroxine without evidence of clinical thyroid disease.

Name: Abnormal muscle physiology
Desc: A functional abnormality of a skeletal muscle.

Name: Thunderclap headache
Desc: Severe head pain with sudden onset, reaching its maximum intensity in less than one minute and lasting from one hour to ten days.

Name: Chronic lymphocytic meningitis
Desc: Meningitis that persists for more than 4 weeks, and lymphocytes are present in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Name: Lacrimal gland hypoplasia
Desc: Underdevelopment of the lacrimal gland.

Name: Hyperfibrinogenemia
Desc: Increased concentration of fibrinogen in the blood.

Name: Coronal hypospadias
Desc: A mild form of hypospadias in which the urethra opens just under the corona glandis.

Name: Abnormal respiratory motile cilium morphology
Desc: Abnormal arrangement of the structures of the motile cilium.

Name: Reduced catalase level
Desc: An abnormally decreased amount of catalase level.

Name: Aspartylglucosaminuria
Desc: Excretion of excess amounts of aspartylglucosamine in the urine.

Name: Abnormality of exocrine pancreas physiology
Desc: A functional anomaly of the acinar gland portion of the pancreas that secretes digestive enzymes.

Name: Bicoronal synostosis
Desc: Synostosis affecting the right and the left coronal suture.

Name: Deviation of the thumb
Desc: Displacement of the thumb from its normal position.

Name: Absent vertebral body mineralization
Desc: A lack of bone mineralization of the vertebral bodies.

Name: Delayed vertebral ossification
Desc: A decrease in the amount of mineralized bone in one or more vertebrae compared with that expected for a given developmental age.

Name: Ankle pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the ankle.

Name: Abnormality of upper limb epiphysis morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal shape of end part of upper limb long bones
Abnormality involving the epiphyses of the upper limbs
Epihyseal plate abnormality of the upper limbs

Name: Iliac crest serration
Desc: Irregularities of the iliac crest that produce the appearance of a lace border around it.

Name: Abnormal upper limb bone morphology
Synonyms: Abnormal morphology of bones of the upper limbs
Abnormal shape of bones of the upper limbs

Name: Abnormality of the humeral heads
Synonyms: Abnormal head of long bone in upper arm

Name: Sclerotic forearm bones
Synonyms: Increased bone density of forearm bones

Name: Abnormal calcification of the carpal bones
Synonyms: Abnormal calcification of the wrist bones

Name: Aplasia of the 5th finger
Desc: Absent 5th (little) finger.

Name: Aplasia of the 4th finger
Desc: Absent 4th finger.

Name: Duplication of phalanx of 3rd finger
Desc: This term applies if one or more of the phalanges of the 3rd finger are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.
Synonyms: Partial/complete duplication of phalanges of the 3rd finger

Name: Abnormality of the 3rd metacarpal
Desc: Any abnormality of the third metacarpal bone.
Synonyms: Abnormality of the 3rd long bone of hand

Name: Aplasia of metacarpal bones
Desc: Developmental defect associated with absence of one or more metacarpal bones.

Name: Curved toe phalanx
Desc: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more toe phalanges.

Name: Elbow pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the elbow.

Name: Abnormality of the trapezium
Desc: An anomaly of trapezium.

Name: Deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand
Desc: Displacement of the hand or of fingers of the hand from their normal position.
Synonyms: Displaced hand or fingers of the hand

Name: Proximal tibial and fibular fusion
Synonyms: Fusion of innermost shinbone and calf bone

Name: Aplasia of the 2nd metacarpal
Desc: Absence of the second long bone of the hand.

Name: Aplasia of the 4th metacarpal
Desc: Absence of the fourth long bone of the hand.

Name: Absent hallux
Desc: Aplasia of the hallux, that is, a development defect such that the big toe does not develop.

Name: Partial absence of foot
Desc: An incomplete absence of the foot, with no bony elements distal to the tarsals, but with preservation of some or all of the tarsals.

Name: Proximal femoral focal deficiency
Desc: Proximal femoral focal deficiency is a deformity manifested by hypoplasia of a variable portion of the femur with shortening of the entire limb.

Name: Hypoplastic acetabulae
Desc: Underdeveloped acetabulae.

Name: Disproportionate prominence of the femoral medial condyle
Calvarial osteosclerosis
Desc: An increase in bone density affecting the calvaria (roof of the skull).

Name: Stenosis of the medullary cavity of the long bones
Postnatal macrocephaly
Desc: The postnatal development of an abnormally large skull (macrocephaly).

Name: Abnormal circulating follicle-stimulating hormone concentration
Desc: An anomaly of the circulating level of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).

Name: Hypoplastic distal humeri
Desc: Underdevelopment of the distal portion of the humerus.

Name: Abnormality of the joint spaces of the elbow
Synonyms: Abnormality of the joint spaces of the elbow

Name: Pear-shaped vertebrae
Desc: Bulbous appearance of the anterior vertebral bodies, such that the vertebral bodies have the greatest vertical height anteriorly as well as bulbous anterior superior-inferior contours.

Name: Slender metacarpals
Desc: Decreased width of the metacarpal bones (that is, reduced diameter).

Name: Pseudoepiphyses of the 2nd finger
Desc: A secondary ossification center in the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

Name: Complete duplication of distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. On x-ray two separate bones appear side to side.
Synonyms: Complete duplication of outermost bone of the thumb

Name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
Desc: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
Synonyms: Speckled calcifications in the end part of the outermost thumb bone

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the 1st metacarpal
Desc: Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 1st metacarpal. In contrast to the metacarpals 2-5, the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5 (whereas the proximal phalanx of the thumb is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits).

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the hallux
Distal symphalangism of hands
Desc: The term distal symphalangism refers to a bony fusion of the distal and middle phalanges of the digits of the hand, in other words the distal interphalangeal joint (DIJ) is missing which can be seen either on x-rays or as an absence of the distal interphalangeal finger creases.
Synonyms: Symphalangism affecting the distal phalanges of the hand

Name: Type A2 brachydactyly
Synonyms: Short index fingers and second toes

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/aplastic middle phalanx of index finger

Name: Medially deviated second toe
Desc: Medial deviation of the second toe.

Name: Triangular epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
Synonyms: Triangular end part of the middle bone of the index finger

Name: Absent middle phalanx of 2nd finger
Desc: Absence of the middle phalanx of the index (2nd) finger.
Synonyms: Absent middle bone of index finger
Absent middle phalanx of index finger
Aplasia of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

Name: Short middle phalanx of the 5th toe
Desc: Developmental hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe.
Synonyms: Hypoplastic/small middle phalanx of the 5th toe
Short middle bone of little toe
Short middle bone of pinkie toe
Short middle bone of pinky toe
Short middle phalanx of the fifth toe

Name: 1-5 finger syndactyly
Desc: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to five (complete syndactyly of all fingers of the hand).

Name: Bifid clitoris
Desc: Two clitorides located side by side.

Name: Absent foot
Desc: The total absence of the foot, with no bony elements distal to the tibia or fibula.

Name: Facial wrinkling
Desc: Excessive wrinkling of the skin of the face.

Name: Agraphesthesia
Desc: Impaired ability to recognize letters or numbers drawn by an examiner's fingertip on the patient's skin (the patients eyes are closed or covered throughout this examination).

Name: Iris neovascularization
Desc: New growth of vessels on the surface of the iris.
Synonyms: New blood vessel formation in iris

Name: Abnormality of central retinal artery
Desc: An abnormality of a central retinal artery.

Name: Maintenance insomnia
Desc: Abnormal difficulty in staying asleep. Affected individuals tend to wake up at night and have difficulty returning to sleep.
Synonyms: Waking up several times during the night

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the hand
Desc: Absence or underdevelopment of the distal phalanges.
Synonyms: Absent/small outermost finger bone of the hand
Absent/underdeveloped outermost finger bone of the hand

Name: Diaphyseal sclerosis
Desc: An elevation in bone density in one or more diaphyses. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Synonyms: Increased bone density in shaft of long bone

Name: Cortical subperiosteal resorption of humeral metaphyses
Increased bone density with cystic changes
Abnormality of central motor conduction
Desc: Any anomaly of the conduction of motor nerve impulses in the central nervous system.

Name: Abnormality of the incus
Desc: An abnormality of the incus, an ossicle in the middle ear.

Name: Abnormality of the malleus
Desc: An abnormality of the malleus, an ossicle in the middle ear.

Name: Impaired visually enhanced vestibulo-ocular reflex
Desc: The vestibulo-ocular reflex is responsible for the stabilization of the retinal image during movement. The visual vestibular ocular reflex (VVOR) or visual enhanced VOR, maintains ocular stability during head motion by generating compensatory eye movement opposite to head movement, and is a major component of visual vestibular interaction. This feature is an impairment of this reflex, manifested as the combined impairment of the three compensatory eye movement reflexes, namely the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR), smooth pursuit (SP) and optokinetic reflex (OKR).

Name: Anterior predominant thick cortex pachygyria
Desc: Pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm and an anterior predominant severity gradient. The severety gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Anterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe over the frontal and temporal lobes.
Synonyms: Pachygyria with cortical thickness > 10 mm anterior predominant

Name: Posterior predominant thick cortex pachygyria
Desc: Pachygyria with cortical thickness above 10 mm with and a posterior predominant severety gradient. The severety gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Posterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.
Synonyms: Pachygyria with cortical thickness over 10 mm posterior predominant

Name: Spinocerebellar atrophy
Desc: Atrophy affecting the cerebellum and the spinocerebellar tracts of the spinal cord.

Name: Moderate albuminuria
Desc: The presence of moderately increased concentrations of albumin in the urine, defined as and albumin-creatinine ratio (ACR) of 30 to 299 mg/gm (3.4 to 34 mg/mmol).

Name: Partial absence of toe
Desc: The absence of a phalangeal segment of a toe or hallux.

Name: Abnormality of the posterior pituitary
Desc: An abnormality of the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.

Name: Rudimentary fibula
Desc: Absent or nearly absent fibula. (Does not include aplastic)

Name: Cochlear malformation
Desc: The presence of a malformed cochlea.

Name: Morphological abnormality of the vestibule of the inner ear
Desc: A morphological abnormality of the vestibule, the central part of the osseous labyrinth that is situated medial to the tympanic cavity, behind the cochlea, and in front of the semicircular canals.

Name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
Synonyms: Absent/small middle bone of the middle finger
Absent/underdeveloped middle bone of the middle finger

Name: Mild intrauterine growth retardation
Desc: Intrauterine growth retardation that is at least 2 standard deviations (SD) below average, but not as low as 3 SD, corrected for sex and gestational age.

Name: Hooded eyelid
Desc: Eyelid partly covered by skin when eyes are open.

Name: Severe hearing impairment
Desc: A severe form of hearing impairment.

Name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the hand
Desc: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the hand.

Name: Hypoplasia of the gallbladder
Desc: The presence of a hypoplastic gallbladder.

Name: Respiratory infections in early life
Desc: Increased susceptibility to respiratory infections in early life, as manifested by recurrent episodes of respiratory infections.

Name: C1-C2 vertebral abnormality
Desc: Any abnormality of the atlas and the axis.

Name: Abetalipoproteinemia
Desc: An absence of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Name: Chaddock reflex
Desc: A diagnostic reflex elicited by stimulation of the skin over the surface of the lateral malleolus of the foot. The Chaddock refelx is present if there is extension of one or more or all of the toes with or without fanning of them when the external inframalleolar skin is stimulated. The Chaddock sign, similar to the Babinski sign, is taken to be an indication of disease of the spinocortical (pyramidal) tract.

Name: Narrow joint spaces of the elbow
Synonyms: Narrow joint spaces of the elbow

Name: Abnormality of fibular epiphyses
Synonyms: Abnormality of the end part of the calf bone

Name: Posterior plagiocephaly
Desc: Asymmetry of the posterior part of the skull.

Name: Abnormality of the costochondral junction
Desc: Any anomaly of the costochondral junction. The costochondral junctions are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.

Name: Metaphyseal spurs
Desc: Bony outgrowths that extend laterally from the margin of the metaphysis.

Name: Absent glenoid fossa
Desc: Lack of development of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.

Name: Chin with H-shaped crease
Desc: H-shaped crease in the fat pad of the chin.

Name: Small proximal tibial epiphyses
Desc: Reduced size of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia.
Synonyms: Small end part of innermost shankbone
Small end part of innermost shinbone

Name: Anhedonia
Desc: Inability to experience pleasure activities usually found enjoyable.

Name: Sleep onset insomnia
Desc: Difficulty initiating sleep, that is, increased sleep onset latency.

Name: Unhappy demeanor
Desc: A conspicuously unhappy disposition characterized by negative assumptions, self-defeating talk, fear of failure, and negative ruminations about past events.

Name: Cuboidal metacarpal
Desc: Severely shortened metacarpal with a cuboidal appearance.
Synonyms: Short, cube shaped long bone of hand

Name: Fifth metacarpal with ulnar notch
Desc: Presence of an angular or V -shaped indentation on the ulnar side of the fifth metacarpal bone (i.e., on the sides towards the fifth finger).
Synonyms: Fifth metacarpal notched on ulnar side

Name: Right-to-left shunt
Desc: Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system from the right side of the heart to the left.

Name: Aortopulmonary window
Desc: A congenital anomaly with an abnormal connection between the aorta and the main pulmonary artery resulting in an aortopulmonary shunt.

Name: Abnormality of the pancreatic islet cells
Desc: An abnormality of the islet of Langerhans, i.e., of the regions of the pancreas that contain its endocrine cells. These are the alpha cells, which produce glucagon, the beta cells, which produce insulin and amylin, the delta cells, which produce somatostatin, the PP cells, which produce pancreatic polypeptide, and the epsilon cells, which produce ghrelin.

Name: Abnormal gastrointestinal motility
Desc: An anomaly of the muscular contractions that propel food though the gastrointestinal tract.

Name: Neoplasm of the endocrine system
Desc: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the endocrine system.

Name: Renal oncocytoma
Desc: A renal tumor originating from an oncocyte, which is an epithelial cell characterized by an excessive amount of mitochondria, resulting in an abundant acidophilic, granular cytoplasm.

Name: Increased pulmonary capillary wedge pressure
Desc: Pulmonary capillary wedge pressure (PCWP) above 15mmHg.

Name: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
Desc: Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of little finger.
Synonyms: Duplication of the outermost little finger bone
Duplication of the outermost pinkie finger bone
Duplication of the outermost pinky finger bone
Partial/complete duplication of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger

Name: Abnormality of upper limb joint
Synonyms: Abnormality of the joints of the upper limbs

Name: Irregular articular surfaces of the elbow joints
Large elbow
Desc: Abnormal increased size of the elbow joint.

Name: Palmomental reflex
Desc: A type of primitive reflex characterized by an involuntary contraction of the mentalis muscle of the chin caused by stimulation of the thenar eminence of the palm.

Name: Nevus anemicus
Desc: A congenital skin lesion characterized by irregular hypopigmented macules that coalesce to form plaques and occur particularly on the chest. It is generally present at birth or develops in the first days of life. It is more common in females. Diagnosis is confirmed by applying gentle friction to the lesion and the surrounding skin and checking that the erythema produced in the healthy skin does not appear in the hypopigmented lesion. This pale macule becomes more conspicuous when the lesion and its surroundings are rubbed. The margin of the naevus is ill-defined and consists of an archipelago of small anaemic spots.

Name: Cerebellar glioma
Desc: A glioma affecting the cerebellum.

Name: Brainstem glioma
Desc: A glioma affecting the brainstem.

Name: Narrowing of medullary canal
Desc: A reduction in diameter and volume of the central cavity of bone where red or yellow bone marrow is located.

Name: Abnormal cerebellar peduncle morphology
Desc: An anomaly of the cerebellar peduncles. The superior, middle, and inferior cerebellar peduncles emerge from the cerebellum. The superior cerebellar penduncles connect the cerebellum to the midbrain, the middle cerebellar peduncles connect the cerebellum to the pons, and the inferior cerebellar peduncle connects the medulla spinalis and medulla oblongata with the cerebellum.

Name: Periostosis
Desc: Abnormal deposition of periosteal bone.

Name: Morning glory anomaly
Desc: An abnormality of the optic nerve in which the optic nerve is large and funneled and displays a conical excavation of the optic disc. The optic disc appears dysplastic.

Name: Abnormal flash visual evoked potentials
Desc: Anomaly of the visual evoked potentials elicited by a flash stimulus, generally a flash of light subtending an angle of at least 20 degrees of the visual field and presented in a dimly lit room.

Name: Cerebellar Purkinje layer atrophy
Desc: Atrophy of the cerebellum affecting primarily the Purkinje cell layer.

Name: Bradyopsia
Desc: Difficulty in seeing moving objects.

Name: Transient hyperphenylalaninemia
Desc: A condition of not having consistently high levels of phenylalanine in the blood but of experiencing temporary hyperphenylalaninemia following ingestion of large quantities of phenylalanine (for instance, following an oral loading test with phenylalanine).

Name: Paresis of extensor muscles of the big toe
Abnormal erythroid lineage cell morphology
Desc: An anomaly of erythroid lineage cells, that is, of the erythropoietic cells in the lineage leading to and including erythrocytes.
Synonyms: Abnormality of cells of the erythroid lineage

Name: Bilateral perisylvian polymicrogyria
Desc: A type of perisylvian polymicrogyria that affects both sides of the brain.

Name: Perisylvian predominant thick cortex pachygyria
Desc: Pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm and a perisylvian predominant severity gradient. The severity gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Perisylvian predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.
Synonyms: Pachygyria with cortical thickness > 10 mm perisylvian predominant

Name: Progressive ptosis
Desc: A progressive form of ptosis.

Name: Chronic pancreatitis
Desc: A chronic form of pancreatitis.

Name: Abnormal muscle fiber myotilin
Desc: A deviation from normal in the expression of myotilin in muscle tissue. Myotilin is a 57kD cytoskeletal protein.

Name: Loss of ability to walk in first decade
Synonyms: Loss of ability to walk in first decade

Name: Abnormality of the musculature of the upper limbs
Decreased miniature endplate potentials
Desc: An abnormal reduction in the amplitude of the miniature endplate potentials, i.e. the postsynaptic response to transmitter released from an individual vesicle at the neuromuscular junction.

Name: Decreased size of nerve terminals
Desc: A reduction in the size of nerve terminals.

Name: Abnormal synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction
Desc: Any abnormality of the neuromuscular junction, which is the synapse between the motor end plate of a motor neuron and the skeletal muscle fibers.

Name: Prolonged miniature endplate currents
Desc: An abnormal prolongation of the miniature endplate potentials, i.e. the postsynaptic response to transmitter released from an individual vesicle at the neuromuscular junction.

Name: Abnormal Descemet membrane morphology
Desc: Abnormality of Descemet's membrane, which is the basement membrane of the corneal endothelium.

Name: Reduced number of corneal endothelial cells
Desc: A reduction in the number of corneal endothelial cells.

Name: Uveal ectropion
Desc: Presence of iris pigment epithelium on the anterior surface of the iris.

Name: Very low visual acuity
Desc: A reduction in visual acuity with best corrected visual acuity between 1.40 (20/500) and 1.89 logMAR (up to roughly 20/1590).

Name: Increased corneal curvature
Desc: An increase in the degree of curvature of the cornea compared to normal.

Name: Tonic pupil
Desc: An abnormality of the pupillary light reaction characterized by a marked slowing of the light reaction of usually just one pupil. The pupil tends to be relatively dilated, and there is reduced accommodation.

Name: Synotia
Desc: A congenital malformation characterized by the union or approximation of the ears in front of the neck, often accompanied by the absence or defective development of the lower jaw.

Name: Vitelliform-like macular lesions
Desc: Vitelliform maculopathy is a sharply demarcated lesion caused by the accumulation of material, often lipofuscin in the subretinal space underlying the macula.

Name: Dilatation of the bladder
Desc: The presence of a dilated urinary bladder.

Name: Systolic heart murmur
Desc: A heart murmur limited to systole, i.e., between the first and second heart sounds S1 and S2.

Name: Unroofed coronary sinus
Desc: Unroofed coronary sinus (CS) is a rare congenital cardiac anomaly in which there is partial (either focal or fenestrated) or complete absence of the roof of the CS, which results in a communication between the CS and the LA. Unroofed CS is the rarest type of atrial septal defect. It is often associated with persistent left superior vena cava (LSVC) and other forms of complex congenital heart disease, usually heterotaxia syndromes. The morphological types have been classified into 4 groups: Type I, completely unroofed with persistent LSVC; type II, completely unroofed without persistent LSVC; type III, partially unroofed mid portion; and type IV, partially unroofed terminal portion.

Name: Anomalous origin of the left common carotid artery from the main pulmonary artery
Desc: The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the main pulmonary artery.

Name: Abnormally loud pulmonic component of the second heart sound
Synonyms: Accentuation of the pulmonic component of the second heart sound

Name: Presyncope
Desc: Presyncope is a state of lightheadedness, muscular weakness, blurred vision, and feeling faint. Presyncope is most often cardiovascular in cause.

Name: Paradoxical splitting of the second heart sound
Desc: Normally, the aortic valve closure (A2) is followed by the pulmonic valve closure (P2) but the A2-P2 interval increases with inspiration and decreases with expiration. With paradoxical splitting, there is a delay in the closure of the aortic valve, so that A2 can follow P2; the individual components can be appreciated at the end of expiration and the interval narrows with inspiration (which is the oposite of the normal pattern).
Synonyms: Reversed splitting of the second heart sound

Name: Automatic atrial tachycardia
Desc: Chronic supraventricular tachycardia predominantly seen in childhood.

Name: Third heart sound
Desc: The third heart sound (S3) is related to rapid filling in diastole. S3 can be a normal finding in children and adolescents but suggests heart failure in older patients.

Name: Fixed splitting of the second heart sound
Desc: Lack of variation in the splitting between the two components of the second heart sound with respiration. Normally, the aortic valve closure (A2) is followed by the pulmonic valve closure (P2) but the A2-P2 interval increases with inspiration and decreases with expiration.

Name: Supracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
Desc: Type 1 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
Synonyms: Supracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connexion
Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection, supracardiac
Type 1 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

Name: Cardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
Desc: Type 2 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
Synonyms: Cardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connexion
Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection, intracardiac
Type 2 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

Name: Infracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
Desc: Type 3 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
Synonyms: Infracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connexion
Type 3 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

Name: Mixed total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
Desc: Type 4 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
Synonyms: Mixed total anomalous pulmonary venous connexion
Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection, mixed
Type 4 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

Name: Impaired ristocetin cofactor assay activity
Desc: Abnormal response to ristocetin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ristocetin to platelet-poor plasma.

Name: Large carpal bones
Desc: Increased size of carpal bones.

Name: Bridged palmar crease
Desc: A crease that connects the proximal and distal transverse palmar creases.

Name: Generalized muscle hypertrophy
Desc: Hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells in a generalized (not localized) distribution.
Synonyms: Generalised increase in muscle cell size
Generalized increase in muscle cell size

Name: Abnormal liver lobulation
Desc: Formation of abnormal lobules (small masses of tissue) in the liver.

Name: Hyperpigmentation of the fundus
Desc: Increased pigmentation of the fundus

Name: Hyperemesis gravidarum
Desc: Excessive vomiting in early pregnancy, leading to the loss of 5% or more of body weight.

Name: Abnormal isohemagglutinin level
Desc: An abnormal level of isohemagglutinin in the blood. An isohemagglutinin refers to the naturally occurring antibodies in the ABO blood group system (i.e., anti-A in a group B person, anti-B in a group A person, and anti-A, anti-B, and anti-A,B in a group O person).
Synonyms: Abnormal level of natural antibody to blood group agents
Abnormal natural antibody level to blood group antigens in blood (isohemagglutinin)

Name: Bronchiolitis obliterans
Desc: Inflammation and fibrosis of the bronchioles leading to partial or complete obstruction of these airways.

Name: Trophoblastic tumor
Desc: A gestational or non-gestational neoplasm composed of neoplastic trophoblastic cells [NCIT:C3422].

Name: Low maternal serum chorionic gonadotropin
Desc: An abnormally low concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

Name: Foot pain
Desc: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the foot.

Name: Thyroglossal cyst
Desc: An abnormality of the thyroid gland owing to the presence of a fibrous cyst resulting from the persistence of the thyroglossal duct.

Name: Enlarged epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Synonyms: Enlarged end part of the outermost hand bones

Name: Accessory scrotum
Desc: Additional scrotum, or part of a scrotum in an abnormal location.

Name: Overjet
Desc: An abnormal anteroposterior extension of the maxillary teeth beyond the plane of the mandibular teeth upon jaw closure.
Synonyms: Protrusion of upper teeth in front of lower teeth

Name: Absent mastoid
Desc: A developmental anomaly in which the mastoid process fails to form and is thus found to be congenitally absent.

Name: Gluten intolerance
Desc: A detrimental reaction to the presence of gluten in food, which may include abdominal pain, fatigue, headaches and paresthesia, or celiac disease.

Name: Cow milk allergy
Desc: Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against cow milk protein.
